<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS LOOK GOOD, BUT IT WON'T GET THEM FAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Seconds to play, Jason Williams running the fast
break, faking a pass to the right and whipping it around his back
to the left, Nick Anderson swooping in from the wing for a soaring
dunk. Fans oohing.
</P>
<P>
   Buzzer sounding. With the Sacramento Kings 117-107 losers to the
Lakers in Game 1 of Round 1 of the NBA playoffs at the Staples
Center on Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   That's the basketball Kings for you _ fleet, clever, highly
entertaining. And, in the end, irrelevant for purposes of
championship competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously this is the way the game is meant to be played, or
people wouldn't be watching us,'' backup center and forward Scot
Pollard had said before the game in a mild defense of his team's
reputation.
</P>
<P>
   But that's the point. Nobody said the Kings aren't worth
watching. They simply said you'd better look quick, because they
won't be around next week.
</P>
<P>
   So much for the fear that this five-game series will take 13
days under the ridiculously stretched-out scheduling mandated by
NBC executives. So much for the idea the Kings are a dangerous
playoff opponent for the Lakers, who won the regular-season series
3-1 but trailed at halftime in all four games.
</P>
<P>
   So much for NBA commissioner David Stern's preseason
proclamation that the Kings ``are clearly the prototype of the team
of the new millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   The league changed some rules over the summer with the idea of
loosening up offenses. Everybody fell in love with the Kings in the
50-game season of 1999, when newcomers Williams and Chris Webber
led the team to its first plus-.500 record in 13 years in
Sacramento, and it seemed as if it would be a nice idea if
everybody had as much fun as they did.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're kind of like the NBA's poster child for new rules or
for the way they'd like to see the game played
</P>
<P>
   up-tempo, open floor, not a lot of throw it in the post and
pound it, pound it, pound it,'' Brian Hill, then coach of the
Vancouver Grizzlies, said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings must think the new millennium begins next year. Their
further improvement in 2000 could be measured only with the aid of
a microscope. They went 44-38, were No.1 in scoring but No.27 in
defense, and got into the playoffs as the bottom seed in the
Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I expected out of the team this year was to
make the playoffs. We've met our expectations,'' Pollard told a
couple of reporters. ``It's you guys' fault'' for raising false
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll second that,'' guard Nick Anderson chimed in from the
next cubicle.
</P>
<P>
   I, for one, am no longer raising false expectations.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out the Kings are fun dates. Pretty to look at,
spontaneous, uninhibited. They'll dance all night.
</P>
<P>
   They're nothing to get serious about, though.
</P>
<P>
   Game 1 wasn't a blowout. The Kings led 42-41 before Chris
Webber's foul trouble began. They had closed to within 105-99 with
four minutes remaining. Yet there was never a doubt the Lakers were
going to win.
</P>
<P>
   The equation of springs past has been reversed. Now it's the
Lakers who are fundamentally sound, in perfect balance, can-do in
the clutch. It's the other team that's all style and no substance.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings came to downtown Los Angeles hoping to steal a game
and perhaps set the Lakers back on their heels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Realistically we're underdogs. We wanted to sneak in and get
one,'' said Webber, downcast after fouling out with 6:53 left in
the game. ``It's like when you're fighting
</P>
<P>
   you want to land the first punch and then run home to your
mom.''
</P>
<P>
   They're running home with a bloody lip _ hoping to return to the
Staples Center for Game 2 on Thursday night with a plan.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday their defensive lapses were on display for 18,997 fans.
Not to mention their rebounding lapses; they came up with less than
half of the Lakers' misses. Not to mention their lapses of cool; a
couple of the fouls on Webber, which dominated the Kings' postgame
discussion, were questionable, but the late-third-quarter offensive
foul he protested vehemently enough to draw a technical foul was
legit.
</P>
<P>
   And they have no answer for Shaquille O'Neal. But who does?
</P>
<P>
   There's only so much the Kings can do differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't change the way we play,'' Williams said stubbornly.
</P>
<P>
   But that's the point. They have only one way to go _ fast,
loose, thrilling _ and it'll get them only this far. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Kevin Modesti's column appears in the Daily News three days a week.
He can be reached at (818) 713-3616. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
