<HEADLINE>
RED SOX SUFFER 4TH STRAIGHT POSTPONEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The players knew. The umpires knew. The people in the
TV trucks knew. Even some ballpark ushers knew.
</P>
<P>
   Among the last ones to know that an Easter weekend of Red Sox
baseball would be a total washout were Fenway Park's paying
customers, who were not informed until 4:27 p.m. that Sunday's
doubleheader between the Sox and Cleveland Indians was postponed.
That was 3 hours 22 minutes after Game 1's scheduled first pitch,
almost 4 1/2 hours after the players on both sides OK'd a June 8
reschedule date in the event of a rainout, and close to an hour
after Indians pitcher Chuck Finley was told, he said, he wouldn't
be pitching against Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox spokesman Kevin Shea insisted that the decision to call
off the game was made only minutes before park announcer Ed
Brickley went on the PA system and, reading from a prepared
statement, told the fans still huddled in the steady rain that the
games had been called off and the weekend's three postponements had
been rescheduled. It was the only announcement fans heard all
afternoon regarding the status of the game.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fourth straight day the Sox couldn't play because of
rain. Thursday night's game in Detroit also was postponed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made every effort to play at least one game today,
especially in light of what happened all weekend,'' Shea said.
``People understood when they came here that the forecast wasn't
good, and unfortunately we weren't able to play.''
</P>
<P>
   The home team has the authority to call off a game until lineup
cards are exchanged. Then the authority shifts to the umpiring crew
chief, who in this case was Jim McKean. He was in consultation with
both clubs throughout the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason given for a delay in the announcement, according
to Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette, was that the teams were
waiting for the players association to approve the makeup dates.
Shea said it took four hours for the union to respond to the teams'
request. The Sox wanted fans to know what their options were, Shea
said, before they left the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Orza, the associate general counsel for the Major League
Players Association, acknowledged that he was unable to respond
immediately to the call from the Sox. ``I was having Easter dinner
with my mother in an Italian restaurant in the Bronx,'' Orza said.
``When they called me again in the car, they had an answer from us
within 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said they wanted to have all agreements in place before
people left the ballpark,'' Orza said. ``I'm not sure that need was
as profound as they suggested, but everything is now in place.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision to play June 8 requires both teams to give up an
off day to play a single game at 6:05 p.m. The Sox originally were
scheduled to have an off day between a three-game set in Miami
against the Marlins and a three-game series in Atlanta against the
Braves. The Indians, meanwhile, are scheduled to play the Brewers
in Milwaukee June 7, then play host to the Reds on the 9th.
</P>
<P>
   The scheduling of the June 8 game did not require the approval
of the union, Orza said. ``The players (on the teams) voted,'' Orza
said. ``It requires the waiver of a provision in the Basic
Agreement barring one-game stands.''
</P>
<P>
   Union permission was necessary, Orza said, for the back-to-back,
split-admission doubleheaders the teams will play Sept. 20 and 21
when the Indians return here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made the doubleheaders Wednesday and Thursday instead of
Tuesday and Wednesday,'' Orza said, ``because the Indians have a
game scheduled that Monday (in New York).''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Wakefield, the Red Sox player representative, said Duquette
informed the team of the schedule revisions at around noon Sunday,
and that the players OK'd the June 8 game informally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan said, `If we don't play, this is the scenario,' ''
Wakefield said. ``We agreed to it informally. It would be stupid to
play three doubleheaders in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   The crews manning the TV trucks outside the ballpark were
packing up equipment around 3:30, the same time Finley, the
Indians' scheduled Game 1 starting pitcher, said he was told the
game had been called off. One ballpark usher said that he heard
around 3 that the Sox already had decided to call the game off but
were waiting to hear back from the players union. The umpires were
out of uniform and gone almost immediately after the announcement
of the postponement.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coach Joe Kerrigan poured a drying agent on the bullpen
mound and reliever Derek Lowe already was throwing around 4, joined
20 minutes later by Martinez, whose appearance drew a cheer from
the remaining fans, many of whom believed he'd gone out to prepare
for his start. Instead, Martinez was in the bullpen for a side
session, knowing his next start wouldn't come until Tuesday night
in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Martinez is scheduled to pitch Monday night against the
Rangers, with Jeff Fassero due to pitch Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   All three games against the Indians were sellouts, according to
one club official, who estimated that each rainout cost the Sox at
least $1 million in revenue. However, with all three games
rescheduled as separate-admission events, the Sox should be able to
recoup that money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the rain, cloudy days and storms, especially when I'm
sleeping,'' Pedro said. ``I wish I could see through the glass
(window).
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's when I'm sleeping, not playing. I think it's
romantic, the rain. Rainy days are good to cuddle and stay at home.
Not to play ball.''
</P>
</TEXT>
