</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'NEAL, LAKERS TOO MUCH FOR KINGS IN GAME 1
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If it's a race to 15 wins, as the Lakers have
dubbed their championship pursuit, then Sunday's opening leg was
appropriately paced.
</P>
<P>
   They sprinted alongside the Sacramento Kings when necessary, and
then, with momentum as their ally, ran right over them. And between
baseline sprints, they clarified a few things, in case there were
doubts:
</P>
<P>
   Yes, they can play at the Kings' pace and not lose their heads
in the process (though they did lose a shoe).
</P>
<P>
   No, those little hiccup losses in Texas last week didn't mean a
darn thing.
</P>
<P>
   And yes, they in fact do have another gear reserved for the
playoffs, and it's faster than a speeding Jason Williams bullet
pass.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere after fifth gear came the turbo-Shaq.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal extended his MVP season into the postseason,
pummeling the Kings with 46 points, 17 rebounds and five blocked
shots to lead the Lakers to a 117-107 victory at Staples Center and
a 1-0 lead in the best-of-five first-round series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different season,'' O'Neal said, ``a different type of
focus. And we're on a mission here.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal's scoring total tied his career playoff high, and he set
new career marks for field goals attempted and made (21 for 33).
Kobe Bryant kicked in another 23 points, and the Lakers who fretted
and sweated through every game against Sacramento this season
relaxed through the last quarter of this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was an easier time tonight,'' said Glen Rice, who
added 18 points on 7-of-12 shooting. ``I don't think we played our
`A' game. I think we still have a lot more room to improve. Things
just happened to work out a little bit better than they have in the
previous games.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, they are ready to play at a breakneck pace that in the
past has meant breaking their own necks. Offense ruled as the
Lakers took a 65-55 halftime lead, and it wasn't until the third
quarter that they held the Kings under 40 percent shooting.
</P>
<P>
   But the defense eventually arrived, and the Lakers made 52 of 99
shots (52.5 percent) to maintain a consistent lead that never
dropped below six points in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal's domination of Vlade Divac (2 for 14, 10 points), the
fourth-quarter foul-out of Chris Webber (28 points) and the Lakers'
total domination of the boards (54 to 37) rendered the Kings
impotent.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the type of team that likes to run and shoot, and
whenever we get the opportunity to run and shoot, we also do
that,'' O'Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who has hurt the Lakers in the past, scored 20 points
but never got on enough of a roll to break down the defense.
Sacramento's next highest scorer was Tony Delk, whose 17 points
came mostly with the game out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   The victory only seemed in jeopardy for a short time ironically,
just !ital!after!off! Webber went to the bench with his sixth foul,
with 6:53 left to play. A Nick Anderson 3-pointer and five quick
points from Divac fueled a 10-0 run that got closed the gap to
105-99.
</P>
<P>
   But Bryant hit a 15-footer as the 24-second clock expired and
O'Neal did the rest. He stuffed a Divac layup at the other end,
then scored on a bank shot and a thunderous dunk off a Ron Harper
lob for a 111-99 cushion. For emphasis, O'Neal swatted Divac once
more, and the 18,997 at Staples Center began amusing themselves
with the wave and a few ``M-V-P'' chants.
</P>
<P>
   It was a charmed afternoon for the Lakers' mammoth leader. He
even split a double-team for a short bank shot while losing his
right shoe in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Best player in the universe,'' Harper said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he played a terrific game,'' coach Phil Jackson
said. ``I thought his mindset, his demeanor, the fact he didn't let
some bangs and bumps on his shot upset him. He obviously got fouled
a couple plays with no call. He played right through it, didn't let
it irritate him. I think he carried himself great today. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``The officials obviously demonstrated there won't be a lot of
fouls on Shaq, so he's just going to have to make his shots, rather
than getting bailed out by foul calls.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no sign of the banged-up Lakers team that last week
muddled through a pair of losses at Dallas and San Antonio to close
out the regular season. Apparently, three days off got them healed
and focused.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been waiting for this for almost two weeks,'' Derek
Fisher said. ``We didn't want to lose any games. But you really
could tell that there wasn't any sense of urgency or there wasn't
anything that kept the fire burning on the inside going on. So
we've been looking forward to today for awhile. This is only the
beginning. We can definitely play much better, and we'll continue
to get better as these playoffs go on.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
