<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION UNINSPIRED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The contrast could not have been much
greater between the two Kraft-owned teams in the MLS Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The dreariness of a rainy night at Foxboro Stadium magnified and
contributed to an uneven and uninspiring performance as the
Revolution tied the Chicago Fire, 1-1. Meanwhile, on a bright,
sunny afternoon in San Jose, Calif., the Earthquakes celebrated a
5-0 victory over Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Though geography and weather are often major determining factors
in the style of play and even the success of soccer teams, they
were not the greatest reasons for the differences between the
Earthquakes and Revolution. Though the difference in climate is
symbolic, the greater reasons for optimism and pessimism reside
within the makeup of the teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution once again seem bogged down in their own
limitations. There is little evidence this team is destined for
great things, though it should improve on last year's finish and is
currently among the leaders in the Eastern Division. But a better
context to evaluate the Revolution is in their overall standing _
ninth place in the MLS.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose, though, presents a young team with a lot of mobility
and dynamic figures such as Ronald Cerritos, Abdul Thompson Conteh,
and Mauricio Wright to provide points of reference. The five-goal
victory over Dallas seems a fluke, but it is the type of fluke the
Revolution never have been able to accomplish, and seem unlikely to
with the current team.
</P>
<P>
   More significantly, the Earthquakes project an image of a team
of the future. This is a process that began more than a year ago
under Brian Quinn. Lothar Osiander has replaced Quinn as coach but
seems to be following the spirit of the project.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution would like to replicate many elements of San
Jose's on-field plan. Coach Fernando Clavijo is an enthusiastic
promoter of young talent and wants to present a team that combines
aesthetics and pragmatism.
</P>
<P>
   Clavijo, though, might have missed his chance to make over the
Revolution in his image, to start the process that began in San
Jose before the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution midfield is a study in underachievement. Leonel
Alvarez and John Harkes essentially duplicate functions as
defensive midfielders. Mauricio Ramos is wasted on the outside.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution strikers are not producing, which is as much a
function of the midfield malfunctioning as their own limitations.
</P>
<P>
   Only the defense, perceived as a major weakness before the
season, has performed at a consistently competent level.
</P>
<P>
   William Sunsing could become a galvanizing force in attack. His
best position is on the outside of midfield, whether competing with
Imad Baba for the starting spot on the right or taking over the
left side. Either way, this would allow Ramos to move to the
center. But, should the Revolution remain in a 4-4-2 alignment,
Harkes then would be forced to move outside.
</P>
<P>
   Harkes is motivated by a possible recall to the US national team
as a holding midfielder. And, indeed, his experience and
personality qualify him for a central role. Harkes is an
accomplished and versatile player, but is it wise to base so much
of the strategy on him? The San Jose model would indicate the
opposite.
</P>
<P>
   After six games, the Revolution have earned six points, about on
par with past teams. As in the past, most Revolution players and
management are convinced they are close to blending a successful
team and require only persistence and time. But Clavijo and
director of operations Sunil Gulati will have to decide soon
whether they can convince fans and players there is hope for the
future, or if they should modify their plans.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, their attacking players aren't worrying opposing
defenses.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is this team capturing the attention of any but hard-core
fans. And this is an important consideration, since the Boston area
continues to prove its superior soccer interest. Despite the
miserable weather and the team's historic lack of success, a crowd
of 6,737 was perceived as disappointing. The Revolution never have
defeated an MLS opponent by five goals, and if they did, they
likely would draw significantly more than the 8,000 Silicon
Valley-ites who were in Spartan Stadium Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
