<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAME 1 WIN HAS NICE RING TO IT FOR LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Phil Jackson's best motivational tool Sunday
wasn't a book or a quote from Eastern philosophy but something far
more tangible, and really, really sparkly: a diamond-encrusted
piece of jewelry on his right hand.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since becoming Lakers coach last June,
Jackson wore a Chicago Bulls championship ring No.6, from 1998 in
front of his players. The message and the timing needed little
explanation as the Lakers prepared to open round one of the
playoffs against the Sacramento Kings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was gleaming, huh?'' Glen Rice said. ``One of the things he
told us is that he's going to wear his ring, to put it in our face
a little bit, so we can work just as hard, so we can get our ring
and put it back in his face. ... It said a lot. It's really what
it's all about. You go out and you work hard in games, and you try
and get to that point where you can also have a ring.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Harper, who won three championships under Jackson, also wore
his 1998 ring to Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want one of those,'' Kobe Bryant said. ``I think the focus
has always been there, but to see it live and direct, it's another
experience. ... He said he was going to wear it until somebody
knocks us out, or until we get him another one.''
</P>
<P>
   There was one other pregame wrinkle for the playoffs: Bob
Marley's ``Get up, Stand up'' played over the locker room speakers.
</P>
<P>
   NO PAIN: Derek Fisher played for the first time since going on
the injured list April 14, but he said the bone spur in his right
ankle didn't affect him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going to go for it,'' he said. ``I might last a week,
I might last two weeks. You don't know really what's going to
happen. I think I'm just going to go for it when I'm there, and
just play hard, try to provide some energy when I'm on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher scored just three points in 10 minutes, but his main
contribution came when he took a charge from Sacramento's Chris
Webber midway through the fourth quarter, causing him to foul out.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not running as well as I'd like to see him run,'' Jackson
said of Fisher, ``and I'm concerned about that, because this is a
series in which we have to have a quick guard, a small guard.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant's sprained right wrist was taped but also seemed to be a
non-issue as he hit 11 of 22 shots for 23 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get an injury, the concentration picks up, your focus
picks up,'' he said. ``I told (trainer Gary) Vitti, I didn't want
to do any treatment before the game because my wrist felt pretty
good.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
