<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-INDIANS-FINLEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINLEY RIDES OUT THE STORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He spent his off time in his Boston hotel room reading
``The Perfect Storm.''
</P>
<P>
   He spent his working time during the past two days watching a
less-than-perfect storm create havoc with his plans to face the Red
Sox' Pedro Martinez in what some viewed as a near perfect matchup
of pitching aces.
</P>
<P>
   For Chuck Finley, newly minted as one of the leaders of the
Cleveland Indians staff after a 14-year stint with the Angels ended
over the winter, Sunday was a hurry-up-and-wait end to a
hurry-up-and-wait weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Finley was to start against Martinez Saturday, but that game was
called off three hours before its 3:05 start, one that had been
pushed back two hours to try to dodge the rain that settled over
the region the past three days.
</P>
<P>
   No problem, said Finley. ``Part of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   He could wait a day. But when Finley woke up Sunday morning and
turned on the Weather Channel, he saw nothing but green radar
blotches hovering over Boston. ``I saw that and they said it was
just sitting there and I thought it might be a problem,'' said
Finley after waiting 3 hours 22 minutes for Sunday's doubleheader
to be postponed, wiping out the entire series.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Finley kept his game face on as long as possible. While
most of his teammates were in the visiting clubhouse, watching NBA
playoff games on television, Finley sat in the dugout, watching the
rain fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never really let up,'' said Finley. ``The field was
saturated, and it would have taken a while to get going even if the
rain had stopped.'
</P>
<P>
   Someone suggested the Indians and Sox _ who now must play
back-to-back day-night doubleheaders in September to make up for
two of the games washed out and a one-game pit stop in between
trips June 8 to make up the other _ might have been best served if
they had started in the light rain and tried to get at least five
innings and an official game into the books.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would have been tough,'' said Finley, who flew across the
country Sunday &UR;  &LR; night to Seattle and will pitch Monday night
against the Mariners. ``It would have been dangerous and they would
have had to change the ball on every pitch and after every hit. It
would have taken a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley and Charles Nagy, who was scheduled to start the second
game, both shrugged off the delay. ``You just make adjustments,''
said Nagy, who will have to wait until Tuesday night to pitch,
which means he will have waited a week between starts. ``It really
shouldn't have any effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley said the weekend was surreal. He never even began to warm
up, much less pitch. What was unusual was getting washed out two
days in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've missed a start, but never two days in a row, because of
weather,'' said Finley, who was even more intrigued by New England
weather after reading ``The Perfect Storm,'' the chronicling of the
deadly Halloween storm that killed fishermen off Gloucester,
prompting a best-selling book and a soon-to-be-released movie.
``It's just something you have to get used to. I don't think there
will be any problem (with too much rest).''
</P>
<P>
   For Finley, who sat in the dugout and watched replays of Red Sox
magic moments _ six times _ before he was told the game was
postponed, it was a weekend of reading and reflection rather than
accomplishment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-00 0020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
