<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 00:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5288 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     04-24 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARPER SETS TONE FOR LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On Easter Sunday, Ron Harper rose from the
debilitated if not the dead.
</P>
<P>
   Written off all year as too decrepit to run the floor with the
likes of Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant, the 36-year-old guard
put together a marvelous first quarter against Sacramento that set
into blurring motion the Lakers' 117-107 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Harper contributed five points, five rebounds and two assists in
the opening 12 minutes, as the Lakers raced to a six-point lead
over the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   He got his second basket of the quarter by rising like a
specter, seemingly materializing out of nowhere to heave home a
miss by O'Neal to lengthen the Lakers' lead to 34-26.
</P>
<P>
   Harper's tip-in acted on the sellout Staples Center crowd like a
double shot of espresso. About the only person in the building who
didn't pop a cornea when Harper took flight and the ball fell
through the hoop was Harper. In typically self-deprecating fashion,
he said, ``I closed my eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   An awesome game by an aw-shucks guy who sat out the last two
regular-season games with a bruised tailbone; how's that for a
Hollywood beginning?
</P>
<P>
   For sure, coach Phil Jackson couldn't have scripted it any
better. The fast start was precisely what a head doctor would have
ordered for a heavily favored team looking to shake some bad
playoff mojo.
</P>
<P>
   A stumble out of the gate would have reversed the momentum the
Lakers built en route to compiling the league's best regular-season
record (67-15). A shaky performance in front of a hyped-up home
crowd, and all of the sudden, people would have been looking back,
at the Lakers' second- and third-round playoff exits of the
previous two years, instead of ahead, to a possibly jubilant June.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first game is always the hardest, especially when you have
the home-court advantage,'' said O'Neal, who made it look pretty
easy, actually, collecting 46 points, 17 rebounds and five blocked
shots.
</P>
<P>
   The last of Harper's four assists set up one of O'Neal's more
spectacular putaways. After grabbing the rebound at the other end,
Harper lobbed an alley-oop pass that O'Neal threw down to put the
Lakers up, 111-99, with just over three minutes remaining.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to putting an exclamation point on the afternoon,
the play made a point: No matter how cushy their lead, the Lakers
weren't about to back off and give the Kings a bit of breathing
room.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 and 1999, the Lakers talked about doing such things. The
difference was they didn't have anyone like Harper to breathe life
into the words.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson lured Harper, whom he had coached in Chicago, out of
retirement so he could be the coach's alter ego on the floor.
Harper was a cog in three of Chicago's NBA title runs, so he knew
the drill.
</P>
<P>
   His Lakers' teammates know he knows the drill, which makes all
the difference. ``He has a couple of rings,'' O'Neal said of
Harper. ``So we're going to listen to what he has to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Harper overcame a speech impediment in his early 20s and hasn't
stopped talking since. His lips must get tired before his legs do
for all the work they get. On Sunday, Harper filled every break in
the action with chatter.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke to the officials during some lulls, politicking on
behalf of his teammate, O'Neal, whom Harper said, ``is getting
pulled on all the time'' by the Kings' Vlade Divac, Chris Webber
and Scot Pollard.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal shot 33 free throws, 17 more than than any King tried, so
one can assume Harper was heard.
</P>
<P>
   When he wasn't pleading with the officials, Harper was in his
teammates' faces. He told Kobe Bryant more than once to stop
hurrying the offense, and when Robert Horry committed a silly foul
on Webber in the waning minutes of the second quarter, Harper
harped to him, saving Jackson a little breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some players who tend to get overanxious,'' Harper
said, stressing the last word. ``Sometimes, they try to score too
soon. I've got guys who tend to shoot too fast. My job is to try to
calm them down.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the Kings had outrebounded the Lakers in their lone
victory in four regular-season meetings, Harper decided it was also
his job to go hard to the glass. He grabbed six offensive rebounds,
and with every one of them he effectively stalled the Kings'
patented fast break.
</P>
<P>
   Asked when was the last time he collected so many offensive
boards, Harper laughed. ``In the eighth grade,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When Harper was in the eighth grade, Kings point guard Jason
Williams was in the womb. Despite the lower mileage on his legs,
Williams, 23, had a heck of a time keeping up with ``Old Head,'' as
Bryant affectionately calls Harper.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has all the basketball skills,'' Harper said of Williams.
``I used my old head on him.'' The Lakers used to be like Williams,
who has more skill than he sometimes can manage. Harper's job, as
he sees it, is to show them the way.
</P>
<P>
   So far, so good. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Karen Crouse's column appears in the Daily News four days a week.
She can be reached at (818) 713-3619. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-00 0025EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000424.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 00:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5289 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-SHORTHAND-AZR &LR;      04-24 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHORTHAND-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY IS MAKING SHORTHAND OBSOLETE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY LAURA TRUJILLO  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Back before secretaries were administrative assistants, when
many still bought gifts for the boss' wife, Judy Pool took
shorthand.
</P>
<P>
   The squiggly lines and symbols, illegible to the men who
dictated the letters, filled her steno pads and her days. The job
required it.
</P>
<P>
   Now, few, if any, schools in the Valley offer shorthand, which
at one time allowed secretaries to take as many as 200 words of
dictation a minute. Community colleges offer something called
``Rapid Writing'' using abbreviations. But dictaphones, speed
typing and computers that recognize voices have taken the place of
the administrative art. And within 30 years, many predict the
method will be extinct.
</P>
<P>
   Vanishing shorthand reflects a major change in the fourth most
common job for women. This year, Secretaries' Week was renamed
Administrative Professionals' Week, another sign of the shift.
</P>
<P>
   Administrative Assistants, the chosen job title, now are taking
on more authority, as their rote duties are handed off to
receptionists and word processors.
</P>
<P>
   Probably fewer than 25 percent of administrative assistants know
shorthand, guesses Rick Stroud of the International Association of
Administrative Professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is a disappearing art,'' says Pool, 57, who runs the
Secretarial Pool in Scottsdale. ``It's lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Most colleges dropped their shorthand classes in the late 1980s,
more than 20 years after many high schools stopped offering the
courses.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the 1950s, almost every girl took shorthand in high
school, listening to the Gregg instructional record albums. The
still-popular Gregg's steno pads with the pink line dividing the
pages in half remind most women over 40 of practicing the lines
over and over.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Brown, 62, taught herself shorthand in the 1950s so she
could learn the lyrics of her favorite songs by the Four Tops,
Perry Como and Debbie Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   She used shorthand as a secretary and, later, taught it at
Lamson Junior College.
</P>
<P>
   As the job of secretary changed and technology evolved, her
class changed to ``Fast Writing.''
</P>
<P>
   It would cost $30-$40 to use shorthand for dictated letters now,
Brown guesses, for the time of writing the letter in shorthand,
then transcribing it into the computer and then rewriting it after
it's edited.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Now, the boss will just say, `Write a letter to so and so o
this or that,' and you compose it,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   The Administrative Professionals' Association says very few jobs
require shorthand and, although it can be useful, those looking for
a job don't really need it.
</P>
<P>
   Though Pool says she hears now and then of some bosses requiring
shorthand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old guys like it,'' said Pool, who had to wear white
gloves to work when she was a secretary in the 1960s. ``They
probably liked having the female in front of them, hanging on each
word.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown still uses shorthand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks so pretty,'' she says. She lapses back to Gregg when
``I don't want the person next to me to know what I'm writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``But secretaries have outgrown it,'' she says. ``It's sad, but
now we're not just here to please the boss, but to meet the
company's goals.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-00 0032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000424.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 00:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5290 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      04-24 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
  
 OLERUD KO's KC  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM CAPLE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ They placed their No. 1 starter on the disabled list
Friday night and added their No. 2 starter to the list Saturday
afternoon. It was such a painful weekend that one of their players
was knocked out of the game standing in the on-deck circle. There
were so many injuries that Jay Buhner, who missed half of Seattle's
games the past two seasons, said, ``I feel like an iron man.''
</P>
<P>
   But after applying all the bandages, reviewing all the X-rays
and filling out all the insurance forms, the Mariners not only
survived the weekend from hell, they swept three games from the
Royals and increased their lead to three games in the American
League West.
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Martinez returned from a strained quadricep to hit a
two-run home run into the upper deck, but it was Washington native
John Olerud who delivered Sunday's biggest hit. After Arthur Rhodes
allowed a game-tying home run in the top of the ninth, Olerud
slammed a three-run, walkoff homer in the bottom of the inning to
beat the Royals 8-5 and extend Kansas City's losing streak to nine
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you sweep a series it's good, but especially so after
getting banged up like that,'' starter Aaron Sele said. ``There's a
lot of satisfaction to this.''
</P>
<P>
   No kidding, given the way the series started out on Black
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Opening day starter Jamie Moyer went on the disabled list with a
shoulder strain before Friday's series opener, and then No. 2
starter Freddy Garcia limped onto the DL with what turned out to be
a hairline fracture of his right tibia. And then there was John
Mabry's pulled groin. The Mariners say Moyer will be out three
weeks; Garcia and Mabry could be out four to six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you've got some other guys that have some injuries who
have to tippy-toe around,'' Buhner said. ``But that's part of the
adjustments you have to make, part of the grind. And that's the
best part about playing 162 games _ you know you'll get those guys
back. Those are the challenges and you've got to pick guys up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners certainly did that over the weekend. Frankie
Rodriguez came through with four scoreless innings in relief of
Garcia on Friday, Brett Tomko came up from AAA Tacoma and won
Saturday's game in place of Moyer, and Olerud came through Sunday
after the bullpen faltered.
</P>
<P>
   Sele left with a 5-1 lead in the sixth, but Jose Paniagua and
Jose Mesa gave up three runs in the seventh inning and Rhodes,
filling for closer Kazu Sasaki, allowed a solo home run to Jermaine
Dye in the ninth to tie the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had the making of a game we let slip away,'' said Alex
Rodriguez, who set a club record by walking five times. ``We've had
games like that slip away in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Not this time. After Stan Javier and Rodriguez walked, Olerud
quickly fell behind reliever Ricky Bottalico 0-2 and also took a
1-2 slider that just missed the strike zone. He sent the next pitch
into the right-field seats for a game-ending home run and found his
teammates waiting for him at home plate.
</P>
<P>
   Olerud is hitting .404 and has reached base in 21 of his past 28
plate appearances. He was 2-for-4 with four RBIs and two runs
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think only John could lay off a pitch like that (1-2
pitch),'' Rodriguez said. ``Even the fastball he hit was a good
pitch, a fastball on the hands. But that's pretty much indicative
of the hitter he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``He makes it look way too easy. We're different hitters. I'm a
lot more aggressive than he is. With John, he gets behind 0-2 and
it's like he's taking a walk in the park, he is so cool and
collected. He might be the best hitter in the game. He's like Tony
Gwynn. You do learn discipline from him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a right-handed Edgar,'' Buhner said. ``You've got John
from the left and Edgar from the right, bam-bam. And A-Rod in front
of them and some rum-dum behind them. Three guys with hitting
titles, three guys with a pretty good idea of what they're doing up
there. And then some rum-dum like me.''
</P>
<P>
   Olerud said he couldn't remember the last time he hit a walkoff
home run in the state of Washington, if ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can remember hitting some in the run for the state
championship (at Interlake High School in 1986) but I don't know if
I hit one to end a game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After all that happened over the weekend, Olerud said the sweep
was a big lift.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bullpen has done a good job for us overall and it's always
nice to pick them up so they know they can count on us when they
struggle,'' Olerud said. ``Because there will be times when we need
them to pick us up.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Jim Caple can be reached at 206-448-8006
</P>
<P>
   or at jimcaple &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-00 0037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000424.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 00:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
