<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Monday, April 24.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LABOR-TRADE (Washington) _ The American labor movement, while
waging its biggest battle ever against trade liberalization, is
trying to fend off charges from many economists, business
executives and members of Congress that it has re-embraced
protectionism. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-AIDS (Irkutsk, Russia) _ Today a region which had hardly
heard of AIDS a year ago has recorded 5,000 new cases of HIV
infection and registered more than 8,500 drug addicts. Those are
the official statistics: The true figures could be as much as 10
times greater, officials say. Perhaps nowhere else in Russia have
HIV infections grown so explosively. Heroin has proven the deadly
catalyst in this epidemic. It has fueled a sharp rise in drug use
and encouraged the needle-sharing that helps the AIDS virus spread.
By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAM-TODAY (Thu Duc, Vietnam) _ ``For Vietnam, 1975 was the
year of national reunification geographically and 1976 was the year
of national reunification legislatively,'' said a Vietnamese
journalist in Hanoi. ``But for national reunification
psychologically it will take several decades more.'' By Seth
Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-SUICIDE (Bhilai, India) _ That most haunting of questions
_ ``Why?'' _ is one that researchers are grappling with in India as
suicide rates rise. While India's rates are below the international
average of 16 per 100,000 people, they have been on a steady upward
march to 10 per 100,000 people in 1997 from 6.3 in 1980, according
to India's National Crime Records Bureau and the World Health
Organization. Psychiatrists here say they are not sure why, though
they believe the accelerating pace of social and economic change is
behind the rising rates. By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   NKOREA-DEFECTOR (Seoul, South Korea) _ For Kim Eun Chol, a North
Korean defector, his long, arduous flight to freedom began three
years ago when he swam across the Amnokkang River and into China.
Barely a year into his new life, Kim says he is terribly unhappy in
this strange land of seemingly boundless freedom and a strong,
hi-tech market economy that has given South Koreans one of the
highest standards of living in Asia. His difficulties illustrate
the deep disparities that have developed between the two Koreas
since they went to war 50 years ago. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   PERU-TOURISTS (Cuzco, Peru) _ In the last seven years, since the
terrorist Shining Path insurrection began to wind down, Cuzco has
rapidly become one of South America's prime tourist destinations.
Quechua-speaking Indians, who pose for tourist cameras with llamas
decorated with pink ribbons tied to their ears, have begun to ask
for tips in smatterings of Italian, French and English. Visa and
American Express signs hang ubiquitously over Inca stonework.
Diesel exhaust belched from tourist buses now mixes with the
traditional Cuzco fragrance of burning eucalyptus. By Clifford
Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
