<P>
   CUBAN-BOY-NEWSPAPER (Miami) _ How the Miami Herald and its
Spanish-language sibling, El Nuevo Herald, have covered the Elian
Gonzalez story, in the face of pressure and tension in Miami. By
Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   TUFTS-EBAY (Medford, Mass.) _ A lesson in dot-com democracy, as
the founder of eBay guest lectures to the inaugural class of Tufts
University's College of Citizenship and Public Service. Tufts'
attempt to integrate civics themes in every aspect of its
curriculum _ powered by a $10 million gift from the eBay guy _ is
the boldest effort in a national trend of trying to promote civic
engagement among students. By Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-HEALTHCARE (Washington) _ In his campaign for the political
center and the issues that traditionally favor the Democrats, Gov.
George W. Bush has entered the health care wars _ promising a big
expansion of coverage without an accompanying expansion of
government. But many analysts say his approach has serious
shortcomings, and Democrats are only too willing to highlight them.
By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-IMAGE (Austin, Texas) _ Gov. George W. Bush is constantly
telling people, in one way or another, that he is a regular,
down-home kinda guy. Trendy television shows? Doesn't watch 'em.
Fancy-schmancy vacations? Doesn't take 'em. Literary novels?
Doesn't read 'em. Bush is hardly the first presidential candidate
to strive for a folksy touch. But in his case, several political
analysts said, that persona contains especially interesting
tensions and contradictions, because it is conspicuously at odds
with his surname, his pedigree and much of his personal history. By
Frank Bruni.
</P>
