</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-U.S.-JUICE (Undated) _ Nobody grows or squeezes more
oranges than Brazil, where some 400,000 workers rely on oranges for
their livelihoods. Since most of the 170 million people in Brazil
are not in the habit of drinking orange juice, all but 1 percent of
the juice gets exported. Much goes to the United States, where
Americans are the globe's biggest consumers of orange juice. In a
world of open borders, this pairing of abundant supply and growing
demand should come close to free trade nirvana. But Washington has
imposed heavy tariffs on orange juice from Brazil since 1987. By
Anthony DePalma with Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   CHIP-PHOTO (Grenoble, France) _ A new generation of chips could
soon lead to a new generation of ultra-low-cost, high-resolution
cameras, potentially adding digital photo capabilities to any
number of consumer-electronics products, like cell phones, portable
computers and personal digital assistants. By John Markoff.
</P>
