<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 01:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5294 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     04-24 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOWTIME IS BACK FOR LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ No one in the Los Angeles Lakers' locker room said
a single discouraging peep on Easter Sunday about their first round
playoff opponent, Sacramento. But sometimes words aren't necessary.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth quarter of a game they controlled and would win by
10, one could scan the Lakers bench and find A.C. Green sitting
with a green Beanie Baby on his head.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers respect the Kings and Chris Webber, but the Lakers of
the New Millennium now understand that what they do, how well they
execute Phil Jackson's game plan, comes before any hard-sell on the
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Showtime is clearly part of the Lakers' history, replaced now by
Jackson's methodical yet challenging approach. He has prepared his
team so well, invariably the same team that always looked
unprepared a year ago, that there's a sense of fait accompli in
what they do. That's a trait one usually finds in the DNA of most
championship teams, too. There wasn't a single moment Sunday when
anyone in the Staples crowd of 18,997 felt the Lakers were in any
real danger.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson still works hard, though, to keep his points fresh. His
early season comment about Kobe Bryant, that the young star needed
to play within the team, has turned Kobe into a complete player, a
transition Michael Jordan also had to make before becoming the
league's best player and winner of six NBA titles.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's unwavering support of Shaquille O'Neal from tipoff to
playoff has allowed the Man of Steel to fill his BMOC (Big Man On
Court) role without any of the leadership paranoia that accompanied
the team in the past. O'Neal, the son of a Marine, now plays drill
instructor to Jackson's captain. There's something to be said for a
well-defined chain of command.
</P>
<P>
   Think back to last week, too, when Jackson spliced scenes of
movies with a message into film sessions, or the day he put the
best team in the league through a sweaty three-hour pre-playoff
practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did the same things in Chicago,'' said Lakers guard Ron
Harper, who won three NBA titles as a member of Jackson's Bulls.
``He's in his mode now. He wants us to now play our best
basketball, to play with great intensity.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best time of every season, after the 82 games. The
best time.''
</P>
<P>
   This time of year has not been the best time for the Lakers, at
least not since 1991, their last visit to the NBA finals. Between
1992 and 1999, the Lakers missed the playoffs one season, were
eliminated in the first round three times, and swept out of the
playoffs the last two years, by Utah in the 1998 Western finals and
San Antonio in the second round last year. Total postseason record
the last eight years: A miserable 23-31.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is here for that very reason, to improve the postseason
marks, and he is unconcerned about style points.
</P>
<P>
   It's intriguing to note that while Shaq, Kobe and Glen Rice are
the Big Three, Jackson is getting great play from the supporting
cast. Harper had nine rebounds Sunday, six of them offensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I had six offensive rebounds was probably the
sixth grade,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Harper this season has had 36 games with six or more boards and
35 with four or more assists. A.C. Green, with six boards Sunday,
has had 60 games now with five or more rebounds. Robert Horry has
had five assists or more in 20 games since late February. And Brian
Shaw, a player G.M. Jerry West always wanted, has been an asset
cross the board.
</P>
<P>
   Once mesmerized by half-court teams, the Lakers now look to trap
opponents in their triangle offense. Unlike last year, when the
team's defense went to Charlotte with Eddie Jones, the Lakers this
year set an L.A. club record for fewest points allowed per game
(92.3) and held opponents to 41 percent from the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a team that likes to run and shoot, and when we have
the opportunity, so do we,'' said Shaq. ``But when they take shots
like that, there are a lot of long rebounds, and we win those
battles. He (Jackson) has prepared us well.''
</P>
<P>
   This includes advising O'Neal not to expect any favors by the
officias.
</P>
<P>
   ``The officials have demonstrated there won't be a lot of fouls
called against Shaq, so he has to make his shots,'' Jackson said.
``Everything about his mindset and demeanor was good. He played
through the non-calls and carried himself great.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, he carried himself with 46 points on 21 for 33 from the
field, plus 17 rebounds and five blocked shots. Fourteen more games
like that and the Lakers can win a title and earn rings.
</P>
<P>
   And they have all seen enough of those worn by Harper and
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've all seen the rings,'' said Harper, ``seen them enough
that they want to win one for themselves.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
