<P>
   &QL; 
SHORTHAND (undated) _ Back before secretaries were administrative
assistants, when many still bought gifts for the boss' wife, Judy
Pool took shorthand. The squiggly lines and symbols, illegible to
the men who dictated the letters, filled her steno pads and her
days. The job required it. Now, writing shorthand is a skill on the
brink of extinction. By LAURA TRUJILLO. Story will move in the
``A'' category.
</P>
<P>
   MENTAL (Phoenix) _ Record numbers of residents of Arizona's
Maricopa County _ frustrated at being refused state services _ are
going to court to prove they have a serious mental illness. But
even in court, advocates say, potential patients face a legal
system so lopsided that it requires them to prove their mental
illness. The appeals system requires that potential patients make
their case under rules more strict than state statutes that define
mental illness. Even then, the Arizona Department of Health
Services has the final say over whether they receive treatment. By
JODIE SNYDER. Story will move in the ``A'' category.
</P>
