<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-LeBRETON-RYAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RYAN'S HEART WOES HUMBLING FOR US ALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ As the TV commercial used to say, some
people think he's a superman.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, we did. Nolan Ryan proved it for five other-worldly
seasons while he wore a Rangers uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Double-bypass surgery? It can't be. Didn't Nolan just pitch last
week?
</P>
<P>
   Some of us still believe, you see, in both the Easter Bunny and
Nolan Ryan _ and not necessarily in that order. Nolan was timeless.
Nolan was tireless.
</P>
<P>
   He gave hope to all of the 40-something guys out there who, when
confronted with life's Robin Venturas, now had a role model to show
how to apply a headlock.
</P>
<P>
   The news from Austin is encouraging, as heart surgeries go. But
this is a living legend that we are talking about.
</P>
<P>
   Overweight, over-indulged, over-partied TV stars get heart
attacks. Ryan, on the other hand, is 53 and as fit as a saint.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, I'd be two years younger myself if I could have the
time I spent waiting for Nolan to conclude his obligatory
post-pitching workout before speaking to the media.
</P>
<P>
   His son Reese reported yesterday, with considerable relief,
``The doctors say he's got the heart of a 30-year-old. They were
real optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Right. They probably want him to pitch for the hospital softball
team.
</P>
<P>
   According to the family, Nolan and wife Ruth were walking around
the grounds yesterday morning at the new Round Rock ballpark _ home
of the latest Ryan family business enterprise, minor-league
baseball. When Nolan reported feeling shortness of breath and pains
in his chest, Ruth drove him to a nearby clinic, where he was
examined and sent to the Heart Hospital of Austin.
</P>
<P>
   An angiogram there disclosed a 90 percent blockage of one
artery, and doctors were summoned to perform the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   According to Reese Ryan, the medical people seem to think that
heredity might have finally caught up with the Rangers' superman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dad's mom, dad and grandfather all had heart attacks or
strokes before they were 55,'' Reese said.
</P>
<P>
   After the double bypass, surgeons pronounced the operation a
``complete success.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all feeling a lot better after seeing him,'' Reese
reported. ``There was a lot of stress there for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Nolan had been under a tight schedule, trying to open the
new ballpark and launch the Round Rock Express, the son said that
his dad had been enjoying himself and had even played a rare round
of golf last week.
</P>
<P>
   Heart disease, however, is a walking case of Craig Grebeck. He's
the little weasel, now with Toronto, that Nolan never could seem to
get out.
</P>
<P>
   America has spent billions on educating people about the dangers
of high cholesterol. We eat egg whites and drink caffeine-free
coffee. We smell the burger, but order the grilled chicken. We mix
in a salad. We dodge the neighborhood dogs on our daily jog.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan Ryan did all of that and a lot, lot more _ and he has
double-bypass surgery?
</P>
<P>
   Attention, Internet millionaires: Next time, don't buy the
basketball team for a toy. Give the $280 million to heart disease
research.
</P>
<P>
   The cruel irony to yesterday's news, of course, is that most of
America remembers Nolan Ryan for his endurance, his
indestructibility and his unfaltering spirit. It was no coincidence
that Ryan was a disarming pitch man for Advil pain relievers,
Duracell batteries and Nike.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan was featured once on one of Nike's ``Just Do It''
campaigns, and the slogan never had a more perfect fit.
</P>
<P>
   It read, in part, ``People who forgot to retire ... And never
got old ... People who realized it's easier to keep going, if you
never stop ... Just Do It.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan was 46 when he threw his last pitch for the Rangers. His
elbow finally failed him. The conditioning didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully, the doctors are right and Nolan _ with his
30-year-old-like heart _ will be back in the owner's box at Round
Rock in a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, we remain humbled that this could happen to a man who
looks like he could still down two Advils and pitch for the home
team.
</P>
<P>
   Tomorrow, just in case, I'm ordering the salad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-00 0136EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
