<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAKERS-COLOR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS FANS GET PLAYOFF FEVER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By DAVID R. BAKER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
 &UR;
<P>
   &LR;  LOS ANGELES _ It was enough to make Michael Miller of
Northridge shake his blue and gold Afro wig in disgust.
</P>
<P>
   Here were the Lakers, starting their first postseason at Staples
Center with a good chance to win it all, and Sunday's crowd looked
as if they came fresh from a tasteful brunch.
</P>
<P>
   Were Miller, 27, and his friends the only face painters? Where
was the rabid passion, the abandon, the men and women with ``L.A.''
scrawled across their body parts?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a town full of vanity,'' Miller sighed, his richly
hued face barely visible beneath the hair. ``They're here for
paparazzi purposes. They're here to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   No sooner had Miller decried the crowd's restraint, however,
than another batch of pigment-enhanced fans poured off the
escalator. ``Get in here!'' Miller yelled. ``Go Lakes!''
</P>
<P>
   They were slow to arrive and slow to warm up, but many Lakers
fans at Sunday's playoff opener did their best to dispel the
Staples Center crowd's lackluster rep. They screamed to drown out
the cell phone conversations going on in the good seats below. They
hurled abuse at the opposing players during free throws.
</P>
<P>
   And by the end of the game, they had an audience known more for
preening than for enthusiasm roaring at the team's blowout 117-107
win over the Sacramento Kings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the Lakers fans to step up,'' said Junior Villela, 25,
of Torrance. ``We gotta represent for L.A.''
</P>
<P>
   Mobilizing the crowd took work. Awkward silences dominated the
game's first half, with many in the audience shutting up completely
between Lakers baskets. Whole blocks of seats remained empty at the
start of play.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone was willing to show fashionably late.
</P>
<P>
   More than an hour before the game, Lawrence Balag stood munching
a burrito with his wife and son as the parking lot slowly filled
with Suburbans. They were the only tailgaters in sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Raiders fan by heart, so I'm used to tailgate parties,''
said Balag, 37.
</P>
<P>
   Like most at the game, he expected a win. The 1999-2000 Lakers
were strong and deep, and only the San Antonio Spurs, last year's
champion, could possibly derail them, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once they get past San Antonio, they'll win it all,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Garay of North Hills and his family stood ready in line
for the center's doors to open at 1:30 p.m. Decked in yellow, they
were bound for the center's nosebleed seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Down there's the millionaires,'' said Garay, 21. ``They don't
even watch the game. They just talk and talk and talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their distance from the actual game -- so high up even
Shaq looked small -- Garay vowed to make noise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, you'll hear me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the cheers that eventually swept the crowd all seemed to
emanate from the cheap seats. Ramon Andrade and ``Big Lou'' Ruiz of
Rosemead started early, waving a golden Lakers flag from the upper
balcony and trying to launch cheers while many fans were still
finding their seats.
</P>
<P>
   At first, it didn't work. No matter how loud Big Lou bellowed,
his chants hit the audience and disappeared like water into a
sponge. Decked in a Shaquille O'Neal jersey and a hat reading
``Nobody knows I'm a lesbian,'' he looked out of place in a sea of
tasteful sweaters and capris.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to get everyone into it,'' said Andrade, a season
ticket holder who takes complaints about the center's quiet crowd
very seriously. ``It's going to be loud. We're going to get this
crowd going.''
</P>
<P>
   It still didn't work. The audience clapped politely whenever a
Laker scored, then fell so silent that the basketball's bounce
could be heard in the top row.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll get into it, man. They're going to in the second
half,'' Andrade said.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't far off. With a few minutes left in the first half,
the Lakers started stretching out their lead, and the crowd
responded. The cheers continued between baskets. Cries of
``Defense!'' finally took on volume and strength.
</P>
<P>
   No one screamed louder than Villela and his crew from Torrance.
Eddie Lopez, 30, took the lead on chants, and the rest spread them
into the nearby sections. Such hard-core fans that several still
sported Raiders tattoos, it was the least they could do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here to pump up the Lakers fans,'' Villela said. ``When
was the last time we could win the playoffs? You've got to
represent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-00 0146EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
