<HEADER>
A5348 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-CUBA-BOY-REVIEW-NYT     04-24 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CUBA-BOY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CUSTODY BATTLES, CHILDREN GET UNEQUAL TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating)  (The Week in Review)  
 By SOMINI SENGUPTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the Elian Gonzalez case illustrates anything, other than the
peculiarly overheated state of Cuban-U.S. relations, it is that
courts run on adult time, with unhappy consequences for the
children they are trying to help.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, after a federal appellate court ruled that Elian
Gonzalez must remain in this country while his political asylum
request is aired, Attorney General Janet Reno said the boy had been
formally assigned to a ``kind of never-never land.''
</P>
<P>
   That is familiar territory for scores of American children whose
destinies remain uncertain, sometimes for months and years, as
their custody and child welfare cases wind through the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Look at this particular Cuban 6-year-old boy. He has suffered
the trauma of losing his mother, who drowned while attempting to
flee Cuba last November by boat. He has been transplanted to a new
place and surrounded by new people, one of whom, Elian's cousin
Marisleysis, has reportedly become a surrogate mother. He is not
attending school, where children his age are learning critical
lessons in how to socialize with peers.
</P>
<P>
   And he has now been forcibly taken from his Miami relatives and
delivered to his father. A court must still rule on the issue of
political asylum _ if Elian can leave the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The latest court postponement of Elian's fate only underscored
what experts see as the tension between two notions of time. There
is the deliberate, adult pace of the law, in which a day or a week
or a month may not seem terribly significant. And then there is the
highly compressed time of child development, in which bonds can be
made, or poisoned, in the same span of time.
</P>
<P>
   There are rules of civil society, which demand that the courts
allow all the parties in a case to be heard. There is also the
child's sense of time, as psychiatrists are fond of saying, in
which waiting in uncertainty can leave a child feeling insecure and
helpless.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the judicial system handles custody and child welfare
cases would shock child developmental experts as being almost
designed to insure that children will be ill-served by the
process,'' said Martin Guggenheim, a law professor at New York
University. ``Ordinarily, we are taught, `Don't rush through
decisions that are perceived to be at the expense of getting it
right.' Paradoxically, the failure to rush may ensure we can't get
it right. That's the rock and the hard place of law and custody
disputes.''
</P>
<P>
   In its ruling last Wednesday, the three-judge panel of the 11th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta did not render a verdict
on the issue of custody. But in stern language, the judges seemed
to scold the government for its handling of the boy's asylum
request. The Justice Department had asserted that only the boy's
father, and not his Miami relatives, was legally entitled to speak
or him, since a child could not comprehend the complexities of an
asylum claim. The judges, however, said that the Immigration and
Naturalization Service may not have properly considered ``the
child's separate and independent interests.''
</P>
<P>
   ``According to the record,'' they wrote, ``plaintiff, although a
young child, has expressed a wish that he not be returned to
Cuba.''
</P>
<P>
   But to what extent can a 6-year-old's opinion be considered in a
legal matter? Should children his age have a say in custody
disputes, let alone matters of political asylum?
</P>
<P>
   In child custody cases in New York City, children, usually at
age 11 or 12, are asked where they would like to live, said Joseph
M. Lauria, the administrative judge of the city's Family Court. But
children are also told by the judge and their own law guardian _
the advocate appointed to represent the child in court _ that the
decision is not theirs to make.
</P>
<P>
   In the Gonzalez case, it may be therapeutic for the boy to
express his feelings, but his opinions should not be accorded the
same weight as, say, a 14-year-old's, said Dr. Albert Solnit,
professor emeritus of psychology at Yale and the outgoing mental
health commissioner of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``He shouldn't be burdened with the responsibility of making
decisions that require an adult capacity, cognitively, emotionally
and socially,'' Solnit said. ``You would not expect a 6-year-old
child to be able to understand what is entailed in such a decision
_ how to trust his memory, how to deal with the severe trauma.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Elian waits in the United States while the courts hear
his case. Waiting, in fact, is the hallmark of the process. In New
York City's Family Court, children and their caretakers may wait
all day to see a judge. At that point, if, say, one attorney has
been unable to reach another, the case is adjourned.
</P>
<P>
   Lauria said it was common for a contested custody case to take
eight months to a year in Family Court. It can take up to a year
just to conclude whether a child had been abused or neglected, and
equally long to determine whether a drug-addicted parent is fit to
raise a child. There is increasing pressure on the city's Family
Court to speed up, but judges and lawyers concede that the very
character of American jurisprudence _ not to mention badly
overburdened courts _ makes it virtually impossible for cases to
move at a pace that suits a child's psychological need for swift
resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The legal system has a sense of thoughtful due process in
which all avenues should be explored,'' said Donald J. Cohen, a
child psychiatrist and director of the Yale Child Study Center.
``This can go on for years, this process for looking for a perfect
solution, while children lives don't stand still. A child's
custodial situation is treated in some ways as battles between
stockholders in a company, where lawyers on both sides argue in
court.''
</P>
<P>
   One need not have a degree in psychology to realize that for a
child, especially a young one, being unable to answer the basic
question, ``Who will take care of me?'' can leave him feeling
frightened and helpless. Psychiatrists say these feelings may lead
to adolescent depression and delinquent behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``The waiting game for a child is a painful one,'' said Michael
G. Kalogerakis, a clinical professor of psychiatry at the New York
University School of Medicine. ``If we are counseling healthy
parents about healthy children and the issue of time is on the
table, we would always say, `Don't postpone. Don't delay. Don't
keep a kid hanging.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-00 0856EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000424.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 08:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0497 &Cx1f; var-z
