<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 08:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5350 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-GUNS-HISTORY-REVIEW     04-24 1306
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-GUNS-HISTORY-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISARMING AMERICA'S GUN HERITAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating)  (The Week in Review)  
 By ANTHONY RAMIREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the rancorous national debate over gun control, both sides
assume that America's earliest experiences with guns shaped the
modern American character. Where they differ is on whether
Americans should embrace their frontier heritage and reliance on
guns, or resist it.
</P>
<P>
   This heritage is widely assumed but rarely examined, even in
history books. ``The prevalence of firearms and the high value
placed on the quick draw made a sure shot the test of manliness,''
wrote Daniel J. Boorstin in ``The Americans: The Democratic
Experience.'' ``From earliest colonial times, the needs of the
wilderness and the threat of Indians had put firearms in the
American household. The right to bear arms had been hallowed in the
Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a new book due this fall, another historian challenges
what he calls a modern myth and argues that gun ownership in the
frontier era was far from universal. In ``Arming America: The
Origins of a National Gun Culture'' (Knopf), Michael A. Bellesiles
(pronounced buh-LEEL) contends that only a relative few private
citizens actually owned firearms between 1765 and 1850. Fewer still
owned guns that worked, he says, and only an elite, typically
professional hunters and sportsmen, could reliably aim and fire a
weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no more than 10 percent of the total American population
owned guns at any time before 1850, according to a variety of
records cited by Bellesiles, an associate professor of history at
Emory University in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a federal report in 1803 found that fewer than a
quarter of white adult males owned guns. This census of militias _
emergency forces composed of citizens rather than professional
soldiers _ covered all 17 states and three territories. It
suggested that there were enough firearms for one in 20 Americans.
(By contrast, most estimates today, including the FBI's, suggest
that there are enough firearms for the entire population.)
</P>
<P>
   Average Americans in the pre-Civil War period considered guns,
especially rifles, an expensive luxury that cost a month's wages or
more. Members of Congress, in a lament that would last from the
Revolutionary War to the 1850s, continually deplored citizen
militias' indifference to acquiring, maintaining and using
firearms. What armed America, Bellesiles argues, was the Civil War
of 1861-65, the bloodiest conflict of the century.
</P>
<P>
   Bellesiles' research fills a vacuum, according to William
Hosley, a former curator of the Samuel Colt gun collection in
Hartford, Conn., and the author of ``Colt: The Making of an
American Legend'' (University of Massachusetts, 1996). The problem
with scholarship on gun ownership, Hosley said, is that ``there is
very little of it, and I've been looking for it for the last 10
years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more known about silver teapots than there is about
guns,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Bellesiles declined to speculate how his
findings affect the current debate over gun control. But Joshua
Sugarmann, executive director of the Violence Policy Center in
Washington, which favors gun control, says Bellesiles' book may
change the terms of the debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took it at face value that rifles and handguns were
omnipresent from colonial times onwards,'' he said. ``But if
America's gun culture is a recent development, then gun deaths
today, as the NRA argues, are not the price we pay for our heritage
_ because there is no such heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   Bellesiles has his critics. The National Rifle Association, the
strongest opponent of gun control, declined to comment on the book
but has criticized an earlier academic article on which his new
book is based as an attack on the right to bear arms.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Kottrol, a professor of law and history at George
Washington University who sympathizes with the NRA, asks, ``How
would the westward expansion of the United States, into Indian
territory, have been possible if the population was lightly
armed?''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Bellesiles' research doesn't square with other
contemporary narratives, such as travelers' diaries, newspaper
accounts and autobiographies, critics say. Clayton Cramer, a writer
who sympathizes with the NRA, said numerous 19th century accounts
mention an American gun culture.
</P>
<P>
   He cites, for example, Philip Gosse, an English naturalist
traveling in Alabama in the 1830s, who wrote, ``The long rifle is
familiar to every hand; skill in the use of it is the highest
accomplishment which a southern gentleman glories in; even the
children acquire an astonishing expertness in handling this deadly
weapon at a very early age.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Kleck, a criminology professor at Florida State University
in Tallahassee and the author of ``The Great American Gun Debate''
(Pacific Research Institute, 1997), said Bellesiles had
overinterpreted his evidence.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BC-R-GUNS-HISTORY-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: his evidence. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``At best, he could say at least 10 percent of the population
had guns but we have no real way of knowing how much higher that
could go,'' Kleck said, mainly because pre-Civil War record keeping
was so poor. Even in 1968, when recordkeeping of all kinds had
presumably improved, a federal commission had difficulty measuring
gun production because records were scant, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Kleck said, fathers in frontier America who handed
down their guns to their sons would do so when their children were
young. ``Gun use occurred in adolescence or young manhood so men
would not wait until they were near death to hand on their guns,''
he said. Probate records, Bellesiles' principal evidence, ``would
not reflect that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bellesiles did not set out to dismantle an American myth but
fell on the subject by chance. He based many of his conclusions on
a 10-year study of more than 11,000 probate records. Unlike
published wills, which sometimes reflected imagined notions of a
property holder's estate, probate records were inventories of
actual property after a death, from land to broken cups, used to
settle debts in what was known as ``the final reckoning.''
</P>
<P>
   After reviewing thousands of such records while researching a
paper on frontier law in 18th-century America, Bellesiles said he
had an epiphany in a Vermont courthouse in 1989. ``Where,'' he
asked himself, ``were the guns?''
</P>
<P>
   As for Kleck's criticism, Bellesiles said, the probate records
he examined appear to record every bequest and gift of value,
including those made during the life of the deceased. These gifts
were subtracted from an heir's portion of the estate, unless there
was a specific instruction to the contrary. ``I am curious to see
Kleck's historical analysis in detail,'' Bellesiles said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bellesiles' argument does not rest solely on probate
records. The rifles and muskets of the period rusted quickly and so
required careful maintenance, he said. In a typical report to
Congress, the secretary of war complained in 1838 that ``when
mustered, a majority of (the militia) are armed with walking canes,
fowling pieces, or unserviceable muskets.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, scattered records of gunsmiths seem to indicate little
demand for their wares, Bellesiles said. For example, the family
business of Eltweed Pomeroy of Windsor, Conn., the first known
gunsmith in Colonial America, produced no more than two dozen guns
a year between 1630 and 1849, he said. Other gunsmiths of the time
_ like Hugh Orr of Bridgewater, Mass., and William Henry of
Lancaster, Pa. _ stayed in business by branching out into other
kinds of ironworks like axes and scythes.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Bellesiles said, ``As a historian, I would be the
last one to say that mine was the final word.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-00 0858EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000424.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 08:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0499 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-GUNS-HISTORY-REVIEW     04-24 1306
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-GUNS-HISTORY-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISARMING AMERICA'S GUN HERITAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating)  (The Week in Review)  
 By ANTHONY RAMIREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
