<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 09:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5361 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-TEEPEN25-COLUMN-COX     04-24 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN25-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: A new era of custody politics
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even amid the general squalor of the Elian case, for those with
a political taste for such piquant delights there's a delicious
irony in the musings of the 11th Circuit Court of Appeals over the
question of whether a 6-year-old has independent standing to seek
U.S. political asylum.
</P>
<P>
   A three-judge panel barred Elian Gonzalez from going home to
Cuba with his father while the court puzzles over this unknown. The
judges noted that in writing ``any alien who is physically present
in the United States'' may seek refuge from political and other
abuses at home, Congress did not specifically bar children from the
privilege _ and hundreds of years of common law that assume such
age distinctions go hang.
</P>
<P>
   Thus looms the odd prospect of defecting toddlers testifying for
their emancipation from this and that tyranny. Millions of Chinese
kiddies are ready to go in, coach.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, the court sharply rebuked the Immigration and
Naturalization Service for not at least querying Elian before
lapsing to the commonplace legal assumption that parents and
children ordinarily belong together. This, mind you, from a
routinely conservative circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a decade ago, conservatives in general and Republicans
in particular were demonizing Hillary Clinton, wife of the
Democratic presidential nominee, for advocating limited legal
rights for children.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary, ``a dowdy feminazi,'' intended to rip children from the
bosom of the family and have them reared _ read: ``indoctrinated''
_ by the state. One commentator had her as the cackling wicked
witch of Oz, carrying off innocents.
</P>
<P>
   Republican National Committee Chairman Rich Bond said Hillary
had ``likened marriage and family to slavery.'' She believes, Bond
said, ``kids should sue their parents rather than helping with the
chores.''
</P>
<P>
   The air of the 1992 GOP convention in Houston was superheated
with fevered Hillary-bashing.
</P>
<P>
   The sources of this calculated hysteria were two academic
journal articles Hillary Clinton has written in 1973 and '79 for
the Harvard Education Review and the Yale Law Journal.
</P>
<P>
   They were carefully calibrated and thoughtful pieces. In them,
Hillary argued that children in some very limited circumstances
should have a legal right to seek their own interests in the courts
in contravention of their parents' wishes. One cited case: an
adolescent whose parents, for religious reasons, forbade the
surgical correction of a cleft palate.
</P>
<P>
   The author emphasized that she was not advocating any broad
legal estrangement of parents and children.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all but the most extreme cases,'' she wrote, ``such
questions should be resolved by the families, not the courts.''
</P>
<P>
   But here we are with a conservative court, to relief and cheers
from much the same quarters that pilloried Hillary, wondering if
children as young as six shouldn't have the legal right to, in
effect, divorce their parents over a supposed ideological
disagreement.
</P>
<P>
   What a difference a little politics makes.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is a columnist for Cox Newspapers. He writes from
Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
