<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 10:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5373 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l BC-PROM-LIMO-KANSAS-KAN &LR;      04-24 1379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROM-LIMO-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIMO COMPANIES SAY NO TO UNDERAGE DRINKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LISA GUTIERREZ and BRIAN MCTAVISH  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Every prom season the campaigns against
underage drinking abound: Don't drink on prom night. Don't drink
and drive on prom night.
</P>
<P>
   This year there's another message: Don't drink and ride.
</P>
<P>
   An increasingly popular way of getting to and from prom is a
cushy ride in a big ol' limo. But parents and limousine operators
are now being urged not to make it easy for kids to binge in the
backseat.
</P>
<P>
   Some kids who are lucky enough to be riding in such style,
however, don't seem to be getting the message. Or maybe they're
just not listening.
</P>
<P>
   Limousine companies hired to transport teens on their special
nights out continue to find underage passengers sneaking alcohol in
the limo, perhaps even more often than in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see kids bringing backpacks, overnight bags and large
purses into the car, that kind of gives you a clue,'' said Gregg D.
Shane, owner of Kool Nites Limousine Inc. in Blue Springs, Mo., a
suburb of Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't see the drugs with the kids ... it's alcohol.''
</P>
<P>
   Shane named an incident this year in which as many as eight
carry-on bags belonging to one group of prom-night passengers were
found to contain some form of alcohol, with several devoted
entirely to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That night some of the parents even helped their kids put
their belongings in the car,'' he said. ``That's not saying the
parents knew. I hate to say it, but the parents need to check their
kids' bags when they're going out the door.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if they do, the trend has motivated Shane to stop relying
on prom-night passengers to automatically comply with underage
drinking laws. He recently ordered warning stickers placed on his
company's contracts with customers. They say: ``Possession of
alcohol by a minor will constitute immediate cancellation of our
contracted services. Parents will be notified immediately. No
exceptions.''
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Shane said, ``our drivers are subject to arrest, can
go to jail, our cars can be towed, and we open ourselves up to
lawsuits by the parents. It's a can of worms.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the stickers were implemented, Shane said he's had to
terminate ``about three'' trips for alcohol-related reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The drivers watch for it, and they do check,'' said Teri
Mynatt, manager of Custom Limousine Inc. in Bonner Springs, Kan.,
also a suburb of Kansas City. ``If they are caught, the ride stops
and the parents are called ... because we tell parents we do not
contribute to the delinquency of a minor.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Rowlands' Shawnee Mission (Kan.) Limousine &AMP; Airport
Service also notifies customers in writing that chauffeurs are not
designated drivers for underage imbibers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general public is fine, but there are occasions when not
everybody is watching the store,'' Rowlands said. ``What we've
tried to do is be proactive. And, perhaps without exception, every
parent we've worked with has wholeheartedly embraced the policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhonda Seymour's daughter Ashlee, a senior at Park Hill South
High School, was taken to prom this year in a limousine with her
date and several other couples. Like many high-schoolers who
arrange for such high-toned transportation, Ashlee and her pals
pooled their money and paid for it themselves. Seymour never saw a
contract from a limousine company, but she doesn't think the
primary responsibility for kids' prom-night behavior lies with limo
operators.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first responsibility is with the parents,'' Seymour said.
``Then the teen-agers. Then I'd say the limo driver or whoever else
is involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Laws in Missouri and Kansas protect the welfare of minors and
punish anyone aiding and abetting a minor in committing a crime.
Those laws could be used to hold limousine drivers accountable for
underage drinking that occurs in their cars.
</P>
<P>
   But those laws have rarely been applied, say local authorities
who can't quote a single case where a limo driver has been charged
or prosecuted for a prom-related offense.
</P>
<P>
   One limousine driver, though, came close at last year's prom at
Lee's Summit (Mo.) High School.
</P>
<P>
   When school officials smelled alcohol on a group of students who
had just arrived by limousine, uniformed police on hand to help
with security detained the partyers and the limo driver, a first
for Lee's Summit police.
</P>
<P>
   The kids admitted they'd had a cooler of beer in the car, but
the driver told police he didn't know anything about it, said Sgt.
Chris Salva, supervisor of the juvenile investigations unit for the
Lee's Summit Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   Although the limo driver had committed no crime, he should have
been more aware of what was going on in the car, Salva said. ``We
educated him that it was not a smart thing to do with minors,'' he
said. ``We determined that he was not being the best adult figure,
but he did not participate in them purchasing'' the beer. The
driver was not charged.
</P>
<P>
   Salva says limousine companies that follow a ``don't ask, don't
tell'' policy about kids drinking in their cars need to change that
thinking. ``Some upscale limos have partitions that allow privacy
for adult passengers. But when they have children in there, that's
when they have to override those amenities and be more
responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Sneaking liquor into a limousine on prom night is no mission
impossible. Some students carry bags with a change of clothing for
later. Slip a bottle or two into the bag, or even into a small
cooler, and the driver may never know that his passengers are
partying.
</P>
<P>
   It happened in a limo that Brian Davis, a senior at Park Hill
High School, shared with several other prom couples two years ago.
``There was only drinking afterward in the limo,'' said Brian, 18.
``And there were only two or three in there who did.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's not the worst of it in Vicky Ward's view, because on
prom and graduation nights _ high-risk nights for underage drinking
_ some parents supply their kids with liquor or make accommodations
so that their children can drink, she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents say, `Well, you know, they're going to drink anyway.
At least they're not going to drive.' But they are condoning that
behavior,'' said Ward, prevention services director for Tri-County
Mental Health Services Inc. in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure many parents rent limos to make it a special night.
But there are others who do it to `keep them safe.' The problem is,
if you truly want them to be safe, condoning their drinking is not
the way to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Community surveys have found that ``by and large, underage
drinking was condoned,'' Ward said, including in hotel rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Tri-County Mental Health, school and law enforcement officials,
mostly in the Northland, have sent letters to hotels in a
five-county area asking them not to rent rooms to minors on prom
night.
</P>
<P>
   Local limousine companies received similar letters urging them
to clamp down on teens drinking in their cars. ``Because some young
people seek places to have parties, your awareness and commitment
can make the difference between safety and tragedy,'' the letters
said.
</P>
<P>
   John Fritz, assistant district attorney in Johnson County, Kan.,
said a legal argument could be made that if a limo driver did
nothing to stop teens from drinking in the car, he is aiding and
abetting a minor in the commission of a crime. It's the same state
statute that would apply to ``lookouts'' who help kids buy beer at
liquor stores.
</P>
<P>
   But Fritz has never come across such a case.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the problem can be handled by simply confiscating the
alcohol, as Gene Gamble, general manager of City Lights Limousine
in Kansas City, had to do last prom season.
</P>
<P>
   After Gamble picked up a group of prom-goers at a house near
Pleasant Hill in Cass County, a young man in the group asked for
the car to pull over only about a block away. He ran into a pasture
and returned with a cooler.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `What you got in there? Booze?' Gamble said. ``He
said, `Yeah.' I said, `OK, let's put it in the trunk.' I guess he
thought I would just let him in with it. They'll try things, but
most of them don't get away with it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
