<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5374 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l BC-ART-FARMER-KANSAS-KAN     04-24 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-FARMER-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAINTINGS OF FARMER GERALD MOORE CAPTURE A COUNTRYSIDE FROM
YESTERYEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KAREN UHLENHUTH  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MUNDEN, Kan. _ Gerald Moore tells a tale of two countrysides.
</P>
<P>
   There's the countryside of his acrylic paints and his
imagination, where small towns are vibrant, and the evening sky
radiates lavender behind a well-ordered farmstead.
</P>
<P>
   The other countryside, the one where Moore actually resides,
isn't quite so pastoral or benign. It's rural America in decline.
It's towns that have lost their young folk and their Main Streets,
and farmhouses gone vacant because it hardly pays a family anymore
to raise soybeans or hogs.
</P>
<P>
   Moore hovers in the middle, one dusty boot in each. He's the
fifth successive generation to farm the acreage his
great-great-grandfather homesteaded west of Washington, Kan., hard
against the Nebraska line. He's the first generation to paint it.
</P>
<P>
   An exhibit of about 15 of his paintings has toured Kansas for 15
months, stopping at banks and community centers and colleges. It's
at the Agricultural Hall of Fame &AMP; National Center in Bonner
Springs through Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Don Lambert, an arts promoter, organized the show after Moore's
art instructor introduced Lambert to the farmer's work. Lambert was
taken by the painter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not an art-jaded person,'' said Lambert, who was
instrumental in propelling another regional artist, the late
Elizabeth Layton of Wellsville, Kan., into the limelight. Layton
enrolled in her first and last art class at the age of 68 and
produced an extensive body of work the next 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Moore ``takes his cues not from ... whatever is hot in New York.
He paints the world around him, which is vanishing rural Kansas,''
Lambert said. ``That's one reason I like him so much.''
</P>
<P>
   That world has been transformed right before Moore's eyes. When
he was a child 40 years ago, his hometown of Munden had an
elementary and a high school, a pool hall, a bank, a grocery store,
beauty parlor, auto repair shop and a couple of gas stations. The
train from Chicago to Denver even stopped in Munden.
</P>
<P>
   Today the lone surviving establishments are a post office,
beauty parlor and bank, set amid a collection of blank-eyed
storefronts.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty years ago the countryside had a farmstead every
quarter-mile and a school every couple miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``A farmer could make a living off 80 or 160 acres,'' Moore
said. ``You wouldn't stand a chance of making a living off 160
acres today.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore and his father and sister together cultivate nearly 800
acres.
</P>
<P>
   In agriculture, as in other industries, staying viable
increasingly means getting big.
</P>
<P>
   Moore and his family quit raising hogs in recent years after the
industry became dominated by a half-dozen packers. Moore says the
small family farmer had no place to sell the animals.
</P>
<P>
   Moore has seen, and personally felt, the life being squeezed out
of the countryside. But you won't find a hint of that saga in his
bucolic tableaux.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'm trying to put that in the back of my head,'' he
said. He is ``not trying to make a statement,'' but aims instead to
depict the natural beauty and the small pleasures of his world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Colors, contrasts, the way light hits things,'' he said. ``I
think (people) miss those things. I never get tired of when the sun
is going down or coming up. I never get tired of the way the sun
makes shadows.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore, 51, seems more comfortable expressing the country's
poetical appeal in acrylic paints than in words. He quickly shifted
conversational gears to a safer, less emotional realm: what route
had his visitor taken to his remote homestead?
</P>
<P>
   His wife and three grown sons take little interest in his work,
Moore said. His first encouragement came from the owner of an art
supply store in the nearby town of Scandia, where he bought some
red paint about 15 years ago. He told the proprietor he was
painting his red Ford tractor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that's gonna stick to the tractor,'' she said of
the tube of acrylic he had selected. She suggested he might benefit
from some instruction. And indeed, he admits the tractor portrait
was ``really bad.''
</P>
<P>
   He registered for her basic painting class at Cloud County
Community College and, in short order, Moore had himself a mentor.
</P>
<P>
   Moore had drawn caricatures for years, but one winter in the
mid-1980s, when he was disabled with a back injury, he decided he'd
watched enough television. He unearthed an ancient set of paints
from the basement.
</P>
<P>
   His first subjects were tractors, barns, houses. He has since
moved on to scenes of small-town life, a crowd at a county fair,
kids throwing snowballs. His current project, at 10- by 3-feet, is
much larger than any earlier works. He's laboring on it in his
basement _ for both space and privacy reasons. Except for his
immediate family members, viewing of works in progress is strictly
prohibited.
</P>
<P>
   He has sold some of his paintings, mostly commissions arranged
beforehand. Painting won't supplant his farming income anytime
soon, but Moore finds other rewards in it.
</P>
<P>
   He's pleased when viewers ``walk away with the feeling, `I've
been here before.' If anything, that's what I want them to walk
away with, a sense of belonging.''
</P>
<P>
   He also aims to educate city-slickers about farmers and the
volatile universe in which they operate. It is marked by ``sunsets
and windstorms and rain and the elements ... and market forces,
things we don't have any control over,'' the painter said. ``We're
at the mercy of the markets and the weather.''
</P>
<P>
   Fellow farmers may relate to the challenging conditions under
which both they and Moore labor, but some of them can't quite
accept this farmer as artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well that's nice,'' some of them might allow. ``But shouldn't
he be out checking the calves?''
</P>
<P>
   For Moore, it's not one or the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice being recognized as an artist and a farmer.'' For
him, the two are inextricably entwined, especially in the twilight
when the sun's rays fall in gentle crossways slats, illuminating
every floating particle of dust.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all comes together for a couple minutes. I sometimes stop
the tractor, stare at it and think, `This is what I want to paint
next. How am I gonna do it?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
