<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Multi-tasking senators are representative
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ She keeps warning them. For two years
running, Florida Senate President Toni Jennings has scolded
senators for dinking around
</P>
<P>
   on their computers when they should be paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't worked.
</P>
<P>
   And that may not be so horrible. Bad things happen when the
Florida Senate focuses on its work. When focused, senators pass
transparently bad, defiantly unconstitutional and special-interest
payback legislation without hesitation. Best they keep themselves
busy with things that won't harm the environment or busy the
appellate courts. Like eBay and their stock holdings.
</P>
<P>
   This is supposed to be the more deliberative chamber, so slowing
the process by inattention is in keeping with their constitutional
purpose.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing about hearing the muted click of keyboards around
the chamber is that many offending computer operators are reading
their e-mail. Hearing from constituents. To a believer in
democracy, this is good. The Senate is ready to hand out tax breaks
instead of fixing roads, paying teachers or seeing that kids get
basic health care, but the majority of Floridians have other
priorities. I'd like to think a few of them are sharing these
feelings with legislators.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, a lot of the floor action this session had more to do with
surfing the Net and nervously consulting the Nasdaq index rather
than consulting the folks back home. That's OK, too.
</P>
<P>
   These people have a hard job. It's not easy to live through
three months of partisan rhetoric no sane person really believes
and legal minutiae that make your head hurt. They must sit through
agonizing meetings, stay awake against all odds, and brazen it out
while introducing lobbyist-written legislation that makes the same
amount of sense whether read left-to-right or right-to-left.
</P>
<P>
   Internet surfing on the floor reminds senators that there's a
bigger, saner and less harsh world out there. Maybe the exercise
makes them less mean.
</P>
<P>
   Proof: The Florida House does not allow computers on the floor
and it is altogether nastier, grouchier and more partisan than the
Senate. Coincidence?
</P>
<P>
   The Senate president is fighting a losing battle against
multi-tasking. It's not only happening on the Senate floor, it's
everywhere: in the classroom, in the workplace and especially on
the road.
</P>
<P>
   The pace of daily life is speeding to the point that people feel
guilty doing only one thing at time. Just look at the cars around
you. A quarter of the drivers are talking on the phone, perfecting
their grooming or looking for one particular song on a two-hour
tape.
</P>
<P>
   I have even watched people talk on cordless phones while
gardening. I have laughed at this as I walk the dog and talk into a
cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   My time waiting for kids' doctor appointments is no longer
devoted to last year's People Magazine and calming
prescription-drug pamphlets. No, it's devoted to a tiny hand-held
computer that holds more text than I can read in a day. I'm not
just cooling my heels in a waiting room. I'm multi-tasking. And
that marks me a certified busy, on-the-go, 21st century person.
</P>
<P>
   People look at me and think: ``There is a very on-the-go,
pressed for time, 21st century multi-tasking person. No wonder he
dresses like that.''
</P>
<P>
   We have moved from a culture that sees status in conspicuous
consumption and conspicuous leisure to a society that celebrates
the status of the person too busy to do only one thing well.
</P>
<P>
   If elected to the Florida Senate, I'm certain I, too, would
drift away from the debate over the third amended tax table in the
Tax Break for Companies that Force Their Employees to Pledge
Allegiance to the Flag Act. I would idly check plane fares to
Brazil in case I had to leave the country in a hurry or track the
plunging worth of my shares in
PocketProtectorDiscountWarehouse.com.
</P>
<P>
   And I'd be a better person for it.
</P>
<P>
   I could go on, but my phone and wristwatch are beeping
simultaneously while the incoming e-mail symbol flashes on my
computer. There are tasks to take on simultaneously and three is my
limit.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is a columnist for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
