<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    D.C. demonstrators didn't know they have same goals as IMF,
World Bank
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Now that America's latest protest movement has
chalked up a few quality practice sessions, the protesters are
stoked about their chances to disrupt the Republican and Democratic
presidential conventions this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Protest leaders point with pride to the 50,000 demonstrators who
got lots of ink and air time for their efforts to wreck the meeting
of the World Trade Organization in Seattle last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Battle in Seattle provided a nice warm-up for protests of
recent meetings of the International Monetary Fund and World Bank
in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters had a grand time baiting police officers,
clogging traffic, chanting slogans and acting morally outraged over
issues they likely did not understand.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few points of agreement among a panel of experts on a
public broadcasting news program discussing the anti-globalization
protests was the likelihood that only a handful of the protesters
understood the functions of the IMF or World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Had the protesters understood what the IMF and World Bank
attempt to accomplish, and if they were truly concerned about the
environment, world poverty, governmental corruption, health care
for impoverished children, access to education, clean water,
living-wage jobs, economic stability and world peace, then they
might be inclined to assist the efforts of IMF and World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the goals of these institutions. Certainly, the
leaders of the two organizations have occasionally blundered, but
their goals are praiseworthy. They have had far more successes than
failures.
</P>
<P>
   Both international organizations were founded at or toward the
end of World War II in an effort to prevent future world wars by
promoting international monetary stability, fostering economic
growth, boosting worldwide employment, fighting poverty, providing
resources to protect the environment, sharing knowledge, increasing
life expectancy and reducing infant mortality, to name a few of the
many laudable objectives.
</P>
<P>
   With a righteousness that only the bewildered can achieve, the
protesters railed against the IMF and World Bank for raping the
environment and holding the hobnailed jackboot of multinational
corporations on the throat of the world's poor to enrich wealthy
stockholders.
</P>
<P>
   That's drivel.
</P>
<P>
   While both organizations have made loans and decisions that have
backfired, their intent and their track records show remarkable
achievement on most endeavors. They deal with many of the world's
most intractable problems.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of the anti-globalization protests appears to be a
philosophical antipathy toward capitalism and free trade.
</P>
<P>
   That's why extreme conservatives join extreme liberals in
protest against the efforts of these international organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Despite history's clear and convincing evidence to the contrary,
many Americans still believe fascism or socialism will produce
heaven on earth.
</P>
<P>
   A Reuters news story by David Morgan tells how protest
organizers are planning to improve on the demonstrations in Seattle
and Washington, D.C., at this summer's presidential conventions in
Philadelphia and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the Unity 2000 coalition hopes to attract 100,000
protesters from more than 100 activist organizations to the
Republican convention in Philadelphia. Compare that to the 15,000
anti-war demonstrators who disrupted the 1968 Democratic convention
in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters can be credited with sharpening the focus and
improving the operations of the IMF, World Bank and World Trade
Organization. We can only hope that they will do the same for the
presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
