r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0425-CO     04-24 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0425-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A good argument is key to a long life
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Annie and Leonard, both octogenarians, live
to argue. This week it's about cemetery plots. Annie says she
doesn't give a hoot because she's not ready to ``move on.'' Leonard
says it's time to decide because they can't spend eternity in the
old Buick even though, according to him, that would be Annie's
final resting-place-of-choice since she's run the wheels off of it
for the last 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   It was a little before breakfast when I stopped in to ask for
the loan of Old Blue, Leonard's 23-year-old pickup with windows
that quit working in the winter of '84. Annie was cooking
breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have a seat,'' Leonard says nodding toward the table and
plunking an Ohio State mug full of the evil brew he calls coffee in
front of me. ``Whatcha'' doing up so early?''
</P>
<P>
   I tell him I'm in need of a load of manure for my flower beds, a
truck to haul it in, and maybe some help shoveling. He tells me it
looks like all I have is the notion and it's up to him to supply
the rest. I put on my blameless face.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll load up right after breakfast,'' he says, ``but right
now we're having a discussion and Annie is being bull-headed.''
</P>
<P>
   Annie explains, looking as exasperated as I've ever seen her
except the time the pressure cooker blew up and stuck beans all
over the ceiling. ``This old fool ran into Howie Sikeston at the
feed store and they got to talking about dying. Every time those
two get together, it means trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Annie turns back to the stove where she's frying a fat hunk of
bologna for Leonard's breakfast. He has the same thing every
morning _ bologna and fake eggs. Gave up the real ones about eight
years ago when the doc told him if he wanted to live to spend all
of his money he was going to have to quit eating anything and
everything that couldn't outrun him.
</P>
<P>
   Grudgingly, Leonard gave up nightly chocolate malts, peanut
brittle, and real eggs. But not the fried bologna. Annie tried to
take it away once and he refused to get out of bed that morning.
Said it just wasn't worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The price is right on two plots over in Union Cemetery but
this woman here,'' he waves a hand in Annie's direction, ``says
she's too young to talk about dying and anyway, she'd rather use
the money for a trip.
</P>
<P>
   Annie flips the bologna and slaps it a hard lick with the
spatula. ``We need a vacation more than we need a hole in the
ground,'' she says. ``What'd you rather see?'' she asks
rhetorically, ``The Grand Canyon or the underside of some danged
weeds?'' Leonard argues it's two plots for the price of one but
Annie says if it's not big enough to build a barn on she doesn't
want it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they're a bargain,'' Leonard says. ``Two for $300. They're
going so cheap because Howie's sister has made up her mind she's
not going to spend eternity in a cemetery full of Lutherans.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Truth is,'' Annie answers back, ``I've kind of made up my mind
to get buried on a mountain top in California. Only $265,000 for a
family of four. Saw it in the paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard's eyes roll back in his head. There's no more cemetery
talk. ``Let's go out and shovel,'' he says as he heads for the
door, ``it's getting too deep in here.''
</P>
<P>
   Annie grins at me behind his back. ``Now a trip to Branson won't
sound nearly so expensive to him,'' she whispers. ``He's so easy to
trick.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard hands me a shovel that fits my hand and chuckles,
``Well, guess I took her mind off the Grand Canyon with all that
cemetery talk. I'm going to offer her Branson instead. Whatta' you
think?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Truth?'' I ask. He nods. ``I'm thinking I want to be having as
much fun as you two when I'm 80.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard winks and we dig in.
</P>
<P>
   (Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(at)nwonline.net)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
