A5391 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-TECH-CENTERPIECE0425-     04-24 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-CENTERPIECE0425-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New Netscape 6 has many features average surfers could find
difficult to use.
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Netscape 6 is not fun.
</P>
<P>
   It's big, busy, flashy and can be just plain annoying. Netscape
took two years to dream up this mishmash of features, pull-down
menus, wacky toolbars and icons.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, Netscape was the market leader in Web browsers _
the Internet software that enables computer users to surf the Web.
Microsoft also makes Web surfing software called Internet Explorer
that comes on every computer that runs the Windows operating
system.
</P>
<P>
   The dueling browsers _ so named because people can use them to
``browse'' the World Wide Web _ led to the antitrust suit against
Microsoft. The Justice Department and 19 states claimed Microsoft
used unfair business practices to edge Netscape out of the market,
which it nearly did. Microsoft currently has around 65 percent of
the market to Netscape's 35 percent. Netscape is hoping its latest
browser will help it regain lost ground.
</P>
<P>
   But the way it looks right now, it's just going to drive users
away.
</P>
<P>
   If you want or expect all the features Netscape 6 offers, forget
the browser and just log on to America Online. The menu bars across
the top and the bottom bear a striking resemblance to AOL's version
5.0.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, America Online owns Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Chronicle said the browser looks more like a
souped-up version of the America Online software than a Web
browser, and that's right on the money. But other aspects of the
service like the pull-down menus look a lot like the Microsoft
Network, so there is something for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   So just when you got to thinking you were a Web surfing
superstar ordering everything from books to antique pottery on the
Web, Netscape 6 swoops in and changes everything.
</P>
<P>
   What you'll get out of Netscape 6 is exactly what you put into
it. Using Netscape 6 on a daily basis requires a lot of time, a lot
of effort and a lot of waiting, no matter how much broadband you
may have streaming into your home.
</P>
<P>
   However, if you have a lot of time and a lot of energy and don't
mind filling out forms, you'll love Netscape 6. If you don't mind
sitting at your computer playing games and reading magazines while
it tries to process the information you've just entered, this also
is a great program for you.
</P>
<P>
   However, if your Web browser needs are pretty much confined to
visiting a few favorite sites, and maybe engaging in a little bit
of electronic commerce along the way, stay far, far away from
Netscape 6 until the company _ or CNet or someone else you rely
upon for your software decisions _ says it's ready for prime time.
It's in a preview release now, which means it is still a work in
progress.
</P>
<P>
   It takes a hearty soul to install and then try to navigate
through Netscape 6, now available to download at
home.netscape.com/download/previewrelease.html.
</P>
<P>
   The installation process is pretty easy, and users can decide
what applications they want and don't want from the new browser.
Netscape 6 also takes up less space than current and previous
versions of Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   But after a week of fussing and struggling with Netscape 6, it's
safe to say more work needs to be done before ordinary non-geek
consumers can or even should be using it.
</P>
<P>
   This new browser bears no resemblance to any browser you've seen
before. (Rumors are rampant that Microsoft is working on a
similarly feature-filled browser that will be just as flashy and
just as hard to use. Memo to Microsoft: If you want to hang on to
your market lead, leave your Internet Explorer browser alone.)
</P>
<P>
   In its evaluation of the product, CNet said, ``Netscape 6 ain't
soup yet, but it's off to a good start.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a pretty charitable comment for a product that takes
hours to load and takes up one-quarter of the browser space with a
new feature called Sidebar. If you have the time and endurance, you
can customize Sidebar, a pane taking up about a quarter of the
browser window. Sidebar has special folders users can fill with
anything they'd like, including stock portfolios, weather reports,
movie listings or news updates from CNN and others. There are also
integrated versions of AOL's Instant Messenger and a built-in
version of Net2Phone, which lets you make phone calls over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Web veterans who bravely decide to download Netscape 6 will
notice that Sidebar is very similar to the ill-fated PointCast
service from the mid-'90s.
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, PointCast and its ``push technology'' were
hailed by Internet soothsayers as the next big thing. The idea of
requesting information and having it ``pushed'' to your desktop
practically bordered on the revolutionary.
</P>
<P>
   However, PointCast had many of the same problems Sidebar has.
For example, when Sidebar is updating information, the browser
grinds to a mind-numbing halt. Many companies eventually officially
prohibited employees from downloading PointCast onto their desktop
PCs because when PointCast was updating information on just one
computer, it could freeze up an entire office network.
</P>
<P>
   Even as I'm writing this, I can hear my poor little Pentium II
groaning under the strain of Sidebar as it struggles to update all
the information I've put into it. You know you've hit an all-time
low when you start feeling sorry for a computer.
</P>
<P>
   Sidebar also makes Netscape 6 one of the busiest pieces of
software available today. There's so much going on, so many menu
bars and pull-down menus, the actual Web browser seems like an
afterthought. Netscape 6 has a menu bar at the top of the screen
and a menu bar at the bottom of the screen. The familiar
``backward,'' ``forward'' and ``reload'' keys have been replaced
with a series of arrows that look more like international highway
signs than browser buttons. The ``stop'' button is just an ``X,''
which makes me lonesome for the cute little red stoplight that's
been calling a halt to loading pages all these years. I also miss
the little house icon Netscape used to send users back to their
chosen home page.
</P>
<P>
   AOL has stated that it wants Netscape 6 to be a browser that
will work on any platform: the PC, the cellular phone, the personal
digital assistant and even America Online.
</P>
<P>
   The new browser is part of the company's ``AOL Anywhere''
philosophy of providing AOL service regardless what appliance is
used to access the service. But with so many agendas and the sheer
volume of information, toolbars and links all crowded onto the
browser, it looks like a combination of the Microsoft Network,
America Online and even software from Internet service provider
EarthLink, which also offers a detachable ``sidecar'' service that
works with EarthLink's high-profile personal start page.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape 6 looks like a browser built by committee that wants to
be all things to all people and a product for all platforms.
</P>
<P>
   Still, analysts adore Netscape 6 and have high hopes for the
product in the long run. They may prove right, but from this user's
point of view, there's still a lot of work to be done.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
