<SLUG> BC-TECH-GAMER25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Star Trek game makes no gains on TV seriesBy Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ FOR THE DESKTOP
</P>
<P>
   The problem with episodic action/adventure television is that,
more often than not, it's so, well, formulaic. Likewise is this
digital incarnation of the Roddenberry world, Star Trek: Hidden
Evil ($30; www.acti-vision.com; PC). Taking up where the Next
Generation ``Insurrection'' movie left off, the Enterprise crew
continues to interact with the enigmatic Ba'ku people as they
uncover still more ``advanced technology'' from a long-dead
civilization. Gamers mainly control a Star Fleet ensign, an apt
adventurer who's a little slow on the uptake when it comes to
action. Genre-typical tasks and objectives _ explore, find, unlock,
clash with the enemy every now and again _ mire what is otherwise a
graphically splendid and technically efficient game. Voiceover work
from the likes of Patrick Stewart (Picard) and Brent Spiner (Data)
do well to offer an immersive Star Trekian interactive adventure.
Yet, all said and done, it's an episodic TV-caliber adventure, not
a virtual extravaganza on par with the blockbuster movies.
</P>
<P>
   This is not Wrebbit's first digital incarnation of perplexing
3-D jigsaw puzzles, but the QuickTime dependant Puzz3D CD The
Orient Express from the Twenties ($20; www.wrebbit.com; for the PC
or Mac) is its first blend of genuine jigsaw challenge with more
conventional computer based mind-benders. In and of itself, the
virtual 3-D build-a-train puzzle promises/threatens hours of
well-interfaced point and click, and drag and drop, puzzle play
with difficulty ranging from easy (150 simplistic pieces, a help
menu, some task automated) to ``Super Challenging'' (707 tiny
pieces, no help, no hints). Once completed, Orient Express becomes
an Agatha Christie-inspired virtual mystery, a graphic-intensive
point and click adventure in the tradition of ``Myst'' or
``Riven,'' replete with mini-games involving clue-riddled Mah Jong
tiles/ciphers, code conundrums, music sheet mysteries and more.
Innumerable FMV featurettes present characters and plot lines and
move the mystery along. A well-executed, long-term
mind-messer-upper for a paltry $20.
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE CONSOLE
</P>
<P>
   For fans of fighting games, the Sega Dreamcast's lineup since
its launch has been an cornucopia of riches. First came the
exquisite ``Soul Calibur,'' and now Tecmo's Dead or Alive 2 ($45,
www.tecmoinc.com), which is, in a word, gorgeous. The game is a
standard fighting game the way the Sistine Chapel has bunch of
squiggles on its ceiling. With great graphics, ultra smooth
game-play and some stellar modes like Tag Team fighting, Dead or
Alive 2 is stunning. The levels are interactive, so throwing an
opponent off a ledge can lead you to another, lower level to
continue a fight. Snow-covered vistas, beautiful gardens and ornate
arenas are just eye candy to the very fun game-play. If we have one
complaint, it's that the game doesn't have as many modes of play as
``Soul Calibur.'' But once you're swapping out players in Tag Team
mode, you won't care.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
