<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY0425-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delete key probably the best defense against junk e-mail
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There are times _ lots of them, really _ when I'm over
my head talking about some facet of technology. Things change so
fast and get so complicated that I end up spending a lot of my time
being mystified. But when it comes to junk e-mail, I'm on solid
ground.
</P>
<P>
   I once was a junk-mail king. I spent seven years writing for
mail-order catalogs and putting mailings together. So next time you
open your real-world mailbox and find envelopes telling you that
the ``Smith Family Is Already a Winner'' or that the secret to
consolidating all your credit card bills is inside, curse me.
</P>
<P>
   Junk e-mail is just the modern equivalent of all those mailings
that I worked on so diligently. Both are a major irritant for a lot
of people, and both are almost impossible to stop. I know that junk
e-mail _ spam as it's called _ is becoming an increasingly annoying
problem because I get so many e-mails asking how to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   There are all sorts of methods, and we'll sure touch on them
because sometimes it helps to at least try to stop an annoyance
rather than just feel helpless. But the bottom line is that, if you
have an e-mail account, you're going to get junk mail addressed to
you. And a high proportion of this mail will be offensive in some
way. They'll either insult your intelligence with stupid get-rich
offers, or they'll offend your sensibilities with X-rated offers
that are blatant, even in the e-mail itself.
</P>
<P>
   First, let's talk about what not to do. Most junk mail includes
instructions for being removed from future mailing lists. Don't
comply. While some legitimate mailers really will remove you, it's
impossible to know who is legitimate and who isn't. By replying,
you are actually making your e-mail address more valuable to the
e-mailer. It can then be sold as an address that has proven valid
and active. The exception to this rule is if you get an e-mail from
a brand-name company. Then you are probably safe in asking that
your name be removed.
</P>
<P>
   Next, don't give in to the temptation to write back and chew out
the mailer _ for the same reason you shouldn't ask to be removed
from the list. You'll just increase the chances of even more
e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Now, what can you do? Keep in mind my opinion that none of these
techniques will noticeably decrease the amount of junk mail you
get. That's a fact of life. But you can try to discourage specific
mailers. One good way to do that is to write and complain to the
folks at the Internet provider used by the mailer. There are Web
sites such as www.bankes.com/nslookup.htm that will let you look up
the administrators at a site. Just go to the site and follow the
directions to find the names, addresses and even telephone numbers
of the administrators. All that said, be warned that many junk mail
abusers use free and low-rent sites that frankly don't care whether
you're angry or not. But you can try.
</P>
<P>
   Some Internet providers also offer software filters that help
remove junk mail. For instance, if you have an EarthLink account,
you can use what that service calls the Spaminator. Other providers
also have similar features, designed to filter out junk mail. So,
write an e-mail to your provider and ask them.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail programs themselves _ Microsoft's Outlook and Eudora's
professional version, or its new free version _ sometimes offer
ways for you to filter the mail.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, you can do what I do. Just read the headers and press
the delete key and forget it. The best way to eliminate junk e-mail
is to avoid responding, avoid buying. That's a slower filter but
one that _ if enough people do it _ is guaranteed to solve the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
