r l BC-NETWATCH0425-COX     04-24 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH0425-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Microsoft workers unfazed by ruling
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Web, not the government, is the hot topic at the
sprawling Microsoft campus set against a backdrop of breathtaking
mountains in the Seattle suburb of Redmond.
</P>
<P>
   The buildings are filled with mostly young, mostly male
employees who pack the campus cafeteria at lunch hour to talk about
the intricacies of software programming, snowboarding and power
hiking.
</P>
<P>
   You don't hear much talk about Netscape or browser wars up in
Redmond anymore, or even what the judge in the Justice Department's
antitrust case might do to punish the company for illegal
anti-competitive practices. The talk, instead, is all about coming
up with more compelling start pages and developing technology
similar, but not too similar, to Amazon.com's one-click ordering
system. The last thing Microsoft needs is for legal history to
repeat itself.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft employees appear to be a middle-American, fairly
apolitical bunch, much more interested in programming and
delivering new products on time to consumers than the fact a judge
recently ruled the company they work for is a monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't seem to bother them that the company that signs their
checks and gives them their millionaire-making stock options has
been branded as a company that illegally bullied its rivals,
stifled software innovation and basically did a lot of
less-than-noble things to dominate the software and later the
Internet marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   While company founder Bill Gates does TV commercials and huddles
with advisers in both Washington state and Washington, D.C., it's
pretty much business as usual at the Microsoft campus. Employees
would rather talk about their work. When it comes to the Web, they
are doing some pretty fascinating work. Right now, Microsoft is
producing some of the best Web sites around. The company has built
a new search engine (search.msn.com) as good as any search engine
on the Web. Its travel and real estate spinoffs, Expedia
(www.expedia.com) and HomeAdvisor (www.homeadvisor.com), are two of
the best sites in their respective categories.
</P>
<P>
   Long before it was trendy, Microsoft's Web team decided it
couldn't care less about how users get access to the Web. They
couldn't care less whether you get to the Microsoft Network from
your computer, your cell phone, your Palm Pilot or even your
wristwatch. They just want you to log on from somewhere and go
straight to the Microsoft Network of sites.
</P>
<P>
   This is revolutionary thinking coming from a company whose
entire business and the legal debacle that followed was based on
dominating the personal desktop computer. Analysts aren't really
sure if Microsoft's strategy will pay off, but it won't be for lack
of enthusiasm or lack of commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has always been a company that needs to clearly define
an enemy to aim at. With the new emphasis on the Web rather than
software, the employees are now talking about Yahoo and Amazon.
They're interested in forming partnerships with companies that can
put good-quality content together with their whiz-bang technology
to make the Microsoft network of sites truly indispensable.
</P>
<P>
   But even with the deepest pockets in the industry, Microsoft is
still late to the party. As many analysts will tell you, when it
comes to the Web, if you are going to be late, you might as well
not show up at all.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, because of its sheer size and influence, has often
been able to break those rules. If it can overcome a late start
with sophisticated Web functions that run on multiple platforms,
the company might be able to overcome the obstacles that could trip
up other lesser players.
</P>
<P>
   Finding and building software for a brave new world no longer
chained to the desktop is far more interesting to Microsoft's rank
and file than a legal battle being fought 3,000 miles away in the
nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the Microsoft case, most employees seem to
think everything will be all right in the end, and the free sodas
in the break rooms will keep flowing. Most say they are more than
confident that Gates, Chief Executive Officer Steve Ballmer and as
many lawyers as Microsoft can buy will sort the whole mess out.
</P>
<P>
   What goes on in the boardroom and the courtroom doesn't make a
whole lot of difference to the people who actually make the
software that contributed to one of the most controversial
antitrust cases in history. That's their story, and every employee
seems to be sticking to it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
