<SLUG> BC-TECH-SAVVY0425-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    E-mail forwarding - a great way to go
 &HT;    By Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In a recent column we discussed whether your e-mail
address had to change when you switch ISPs. The answer was
something like, ``well, it depends.'' Some readers asked us to clue
y'all in on e-mail forwarding, another great way to go.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: With e-mail forwarding, you can have one e-mail address
for life. You can change ISPs umpteen times and your e-mail address
will stay the same.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: There are several e-mail forwarding services. Many are
free. Their gig is to route e-mail to your ISP account(s). Here are
a few some of our readers suggested: Bigfoot (www.bigfoot.com),
iName (www.iname.com) and akaMail (www.akamail.com).
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Interested? Go to an e-mail forwarding site. Pick your
new permanent e-mail address. Give the forwarding service your
current ISP e-mail address so they can forward mail to it. Then
give your permanent address to all your contacts. Any e-mail sent
to that address is automatically forwarded to your ISP e-mail
account, regardless of how many times you switch ISPs.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Basically, if I give Mom my Bigfoot e-mail address and
switch from AOL to EarthLink, she'll keep sending to Bigfoot.
Bigfoot kicks it along to my new ISP account.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: If you switch ISPs, go back to the forwarding service and
update your information. It's like filling out a change-of-address
form for the post office.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: You can get more than just e-mail forwarding. Some features
are rolled into your package, and others can be obtained for a fee.
In addition to basic forwarding, options include: autoresponders
that respond to e-mail while you're away; filtering, which allows
you to reject unwanted e-mail or forward it elsewhere; and
anti-spamming, which allows you to block nasty spammers.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: If you're one of those folks with your own Web site, one
of the coolest features is URL forwarding. It allows you to move
your Web site as often as you need to without having to inform
everyone of your new Web address. So, if I'm selling thingamajigs
on my Web page, my clients will never have to be inconvenienced
because I've switched Web-hosting services.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: For those who need to be reminded, your e-mail forwarding
service can help you remember holidays, birthdays and
anniversaries, too.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd write for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. E-mail questions to techsavvy(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
