<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-TOOLS0425-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The DOS world is hanging tough
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The truth is still out there.
</P>
<P>
   For the gentleman who is miffed because Windows no longer comes
with QBasic, two readers, Larry Logue and Jane Halstead, have good
news: You're wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The executable file and the help file are both in the Windows
98 delivery CD.''
</P>
<P>
   Find it by looking at this address on the CD (fill in the CD
drive letter for your own
computer):(backslash)tools(backslash)oldmsdos on the Windows 98
delivery CD. Simply copy both files to your hard drive, and you are
in business. It will run either in a DOS window or full screen.
</P>
<P>
   I also heard from readers with DOS printing problems, and one of
them is using one of the great old DOS programs, PFS: Professional
File. The PFS series was one of the high points of DOS software, as
far as I'm concerned.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, he finds that he can't print to modern printers,
and the ``current date'' function always produces the year
``1900.'' Well, the latter is what the Y2K thing was all about,
isn't it? Software Publishing Co., makers of the PFS series, was
sold and the series discontinued before the problem ever occurred
to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   As for printing, a reader reported he solved his DOS-to-modern
printer problem with a shareware program called Duplex. A cursory
search of a couple of shareware sites didn't turn it up, but it
shouldn't be too hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of printers, another reader kicked sand in my face for
``belittling'' people with dot-matrix printers. I don't belittle
people. I do assume they have a sense of humor, and tease them a
bit. After a couple of personal insults, he goes on to berate
inkjet printers because if not used regularly, the jets will clog.
</P>
<P>
   I found that out, too, and now I make sure to run a test page
through the printer every week if I'm not using it regularly. Seems
a lot easier than listening to a dot-matrix clacking away.
</P>
<P>
   Another fellow, however, writes to point out that impact
printers are still the only thing that will print multipage forms.
He's got me there.
</P>
<P>
   A reader in Denver says he used to run a huge spreadsheet under
DOS on a 386SX machine. Now he's got a new computer running
Windows, with four times the memory of his old one, and it can't
run the spreadsheet the 386 did. ``It is good for wasting time on
the Net, and fooling with pictures. Other than that, near as I can
tell, it's useless.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no arguing the fact that Windows itself eats up a huge
amount of resources. But there are at least two good reasons,
beyond Microsoft's machinations, that Windows has overshadowed DOS.
One of them matters to me, one doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   The one that matters to me is the ability to multitask. Running
several programs at once is a very valuable feature for me. More
important to the world in general, however, is the standardization
that Windows imposes.
</P>
<P>
   Business users, not personal users, are the folks who drive the
market, and for them Windows makes training employees far, far
easier.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, neither of those things matters to all the folks who've
been writing to me lately. I admire you, and I love hearing how
you're making things work out there in The Lost World.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
