</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A0425-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service AUSTIN, Texas _
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q:Where can I write to Lauren Hutton? Also, on Home and Garden
TV there is a program called ``The Designer's Landscape.'' The
host, Gary Alan, does excellent upgrades on people's yards. How are
those yards selected? Mine is in need of desperate help and I would
love to have him redo it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kay C.
</P>
<P>
   A: The stunning Hutton may be contacted in care of William
Morris Agency, 151 El Camino, Beverly Hills, Calif. 90212. Gary
Alan owns a landscaping contracting company and personally selects
a few jobs to air on the popular program out of the many paid jobs
he does. He charges $1,000 for a consultation plus travel and
accommodations. After the consultation, Alan can propose a
landscape restoration. To schedule a consultation, call Wade
Barlow, general manager, (800) 396-0611 Q: I am moving to
Georgetown from Arizona and am looking for hiking groups in the
area.
</P>
<P>
   _ R.D.
</P>
<P>
   A: Colorado River Walkers members are young, old and in-between,
married and single, fast walkers and stroll-along (my category).
Annual dues ($10) include the entire family. Call 495-6294 for a
membership package or visit www.onr.com/user/dbarber/crw. Happy
trails. Q: Please settle a bet about which actress plays opposite
Jason Alexander in the Visa Check Card commercial. He is going to
the movies with an actress I believe is Marisa Tomei as per their
``Seinfeld'' skits. My wife and others insist it is not her!
</P>
<P>
   _ C.H.
</P>
<P>
   A: Your wife wins. Brian Young of Untitled Entertainment
confirms that the actress is not Marisa Tomei, but Kari Wuhrer, who
plays Margaret Beckett on the television show ``Sliders.'' Q: I am
looking for a Special Olympics cap or T-shirt for a little boy. I
try to encourage him every time I see him struggling in his walker
or wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   _Verda H. A: Call Midwest Trophy, (800) 324-5996, the official
supplier of Special Olympics paraphernalia. You can order a T-shirt
for around $12 and a cap for $14 or request a catalog. Midwest also
makes Special Olympic trophies and medals.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are the beginning and ending years for the birth of baby
boomers? Also there are only five states left in the United States
that do not have a state income tax _Texas, Florida, New Hampshire
and Tennessee. What is the fifth?
</P>
<P>
   _W. C.
</P>
<P>
   A: Discourses on age disagree on the boomer definition.
Generally, the boom began with those born in 1946. Susan Mitchell
in ``The Official Guide to the Generations'' defined the baby
boomers as those born between 1946-1964. Alaska, Florida, Nevada,
Texas, Wyoming, Washington and South Dakota do not have a state
income tax, according to the folks at the Federation of Tax
Administrators (imagine how wild their conventions must be). New
Hampshire and Tennessee have a state income tax limited to dividend
and interest income. For specifics, visit www.taxadmin.org
</P>
<P>
   Q: Since I was little bitty, I have always wanted to sing on the
TV show ``Star Search.'' But before I even had a chance, it was
canceled. I heard auditions were being held for a new show entitled
``Star Search 2000.'' Do you have the contact?
</P>
<P>
   _ S.C.
</P>
<P>
   A: You are looking for ``Next Big Star'' _ Ed McMahon's latest
foray into the talent show biz. Information is online at
www.nextbigstar.com. Contestants submit audition tapes, which are
broadcast on the Internet. There are 13 categories in which to
compete. Contestants must be 15 years or older, except for a few
categories designated for kids (music, dance, cheerleader). This
session began April 15 and runs for 13 weeks. Voting is on the
Internet. The winner in each category will receive either a prize
of $10,000 or an item of equivalent value. Need more info, but no
access to the Internet? Write ``Next Big Star,'' LLC/Victory
Entertainment Corp., 1000 Universal Studios Plaza, Bldg. 22A, Suite
262, Orlando, Fla. 32819 Q: I am having a huge battle with a friend
about whether or not Fat Tire beer is all about mountain biking or
beach cruising. I firmly believe that this beer is all about
hanging out rather than the hardcore lifestyle associated with
mountain biking. Can you help?
</P>
<P>
   _ Sarah D.
</P>
<P>
   A: Fat Tire began with a loyal small-town following in Colorado,
says New Belgium Brewery spokeswoman Pam Schmidt, but now defies
demographic studies. Customers range from of-age college students
to of-a-certain-age retirees, from fly fishermen to hard-core
bikers. Some beer aficionados think the trendy Fat Tire is
overrated (guess value is in the stein of the quaffer). By the way,
New Belgium Brewery purports to be the only wind-powered brewery in
the United States.Contact Jane Greig, author of ``Thanks for
Asking,'' at P.O. Box 670, Austin, TX 78767; (512) 445-3697; e-mail
jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968. Due to the number of
inquiries, Jane cannot respond to every request.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
