<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5404 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-DRUGS-DISCLAIMERS0425     04-24 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUGS-DISCLAIMERS0425-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Disclaimers offer legal protection
 &HT;    By Brett Thurman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _
</P>
<P>
   Q: Recently I have noticed that in the ads for prescription
drugs the pharmaceutical companies run, they always include a list
of possible side effects in the legalese disclaimer at the end. I
saw one advertising something to help you with toenail fungus, and
the possible side effects included kidney problems and seizures!
Who in their right mind would trade their kidneys for nicer
toenails? What gives here?
</P>
<P>
   A: We at LegalEase deplore any and all legalese, and welcome
this opportunity to examine this new and sometimes amusing source
of same.
</P>
<P>
   First, however, you should know that reading the rest of this
column may satisfy your curiosity, but could lead to higher blood
pressure, pulling of hair and your dog getting kicked.
</P>
<P>
   There are two main reasons for these darkly cynical sources of
humor. First and foremost, there is a federal law that requires
possible side effects be mentioned in drug advertising. Not
surprisingly, the drug companies would probably play it safe and
put these disclaimers in even if the law did not require it. There
is a brave new world of potential liability just opening up as a
result of widespread direct advertising of drugs to the ultimate
consumer.
</P>
<P>
   The old liability rules _ back before patients got much
information directly from the drug companies _ were pretty clear.
The government would approve a drug. Drug companies dealt
exclusively with doctors, and doctors dealt exclusively with
patients.
</P>
<P>
   Patients could under certain circumstances sue the drug
companies. But there were a lot of protections available to the
drug companies as a result of the fact they got government approval
of the drug and then limited their dealings to the doctors who
prescribed the drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The drug companies recently discovered they could sell more of
their drugs if patients (and hypochondriacs) watching at home only
knew it was available and could then rush to their doctor to ``ask
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the good news. The bad news is that a variable in the
old relationships has changed. The drug companies are now
communicating with the consumer, and the consumer is now a
decision-maker in the drug-taking process.
</P>
<P>
   This change may or may not alter the old liability rules. It
takes a while for a significant number of medical conditions to
arise and work their way through the courts. Drug companies are
profitable enough that lucrative settlements often make more sense
than risking a trial that could create new and unfavorable law, so
most cases settle without a trial.
</P>
<P>
   But more and more, the drug companies anticipate, plaintiffs
will sue for complications allegedly caused by taking a drug that
was advertised. One of the things that will be mentioned at trial
is how the drug companies seduced the consumer into taking the drug
with their advertising. Not only did this drug company make an
unsafe product, it will be claimed, it also took out ads trying to
get people to ask for it from their doctors! That's two bad things,
not just one.
</P>
<P>
   These disclaimers would give the drug companies a better chance
to raise an affirmative defense of ``assumption of the risk.'' The
more specific the list of possible side effects, the better this
defense is.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
