<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5405 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN0425     04-24 1628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN0425-cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Color TV, in black and white
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ We're a nation racially divided _ except for
football fans. And, shall we say, mature viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently all couch potatoes, black and white, hunker down for
``Monday Night Football.'' We're a rainbow coalition that huddles
around the tube to start the work week watching grown men smash
helmets. It's a long-standing racial crossover unparalleled in TV
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Wants To Be a Millionaire'' might break that monopoly if
it sticks around long enough. At the time of the latest demographic
survey, however, the ABC game show was dubbed a special rather than
a series. While it ranked high among whites and blacks (despite the
low number of black contestants), it has not been evaluated for a
full season. Experts say it might crack the Top 20 in black
households but probably not the Top 10. And it appears to be
cooling off.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, black and white viewers tend to watch different
shows, a trend long demonstrated by Nielsen Media Research's annual
demographic survey. Only one show is a crossover hit in each
group's Top 10, and only six in the Top 20.
</P>
<P>
   But the latest report by New York ad agency BBDO finds a new
twist: Older viewers, regardless of race, seem to have similar
tastes. Teens used to watch the same shows, but now it's the
50-plus gang, the semi-geezers, who are coming together. Seven of
the Top 10 shows in older black households are in the Top 10 for
all old-viewer households. Among this racially diverse group's
favorites: football, news and drama. ``60 Minutes'' is the No. 1
show on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a lifestyle difference,'' says Doug Alligood,
senior vice president of BBDO and author of the yearly survey of
black viewing habits. ``An older black viewer may have more in
common with an older white person than he does with a young black
person. Older whites and blacks don't dig the music or humor of the
younger groups either.''
</P>
<P>
   That's been true for some time, so why are older black and white
viewers suddenly sharing favorite TV shows?
</P>
<P>
   ``The over-50 viewer has never been a demographic coveted by
advertisers, and that's become even more true this season,'' says
Tina Pieraccini, professor of communication studies at the State
University of New York in Oswego. ``By emphasizing teen
programming, there are so few shows left for over-50 viewers that
everybody in that age group is watching the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Alligood has analyzed racial demographics for two decades and
witnessed the various shifts in viewing patterns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black and white teens used to like many of the same
programs,'' he says. ``It used to be that teens crossed over
tremendously to Fox.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early '90s, a racially mixed teen audience watched ``21
Jump Street,'' ``In Living Color,'' ``Beverly Hills, 90210,''
``Living Single'' and ``Married ... With Children'' _ all on Fox.
The youth-oriented upstart network had decided to go after teens in
a big way to launch the network.
</P>
<P>
   But with the arrival of the UPN and WB networks, programmers
zoomed in even tighter on specific segments of the youth market,
changing program style to meet the needs of advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``As cable TV arrived and all the programmers started trying to
appeal to smaller segments of the audience, the audience
fragmented,'' Pieraccini says. ``It's too bad it's so fragmented
now, but it really has more to do with the structure of the
industry trying to meet the needs of advertisers than the consumers
themselves. It's an economic explanation with societal
ramifications.''
</P>
<P>
   The sitcoms popular among black teens now are the so-called
``black experience'' sitcoms like ``Moesha'' and ``Grown-Ups.''
They're all on UPN and the WB (not a single top black favorite is
on Fox), and they're not remotely popular with white teens. For
example, UPN's ``The Parkers'' is No. 1 among black teens and 122nd
among white teens. (The one teen crossover hit is UPN's wrestling,
but that's almost too scary to consider.)
</P>
<P>
   Older black viewers are even less taken with the black sitcoms
than white teens.
</P>
<P>
   ``UPN and the WB have sitcoms that are almost pure in their
style of black stand-up comedy,'' Alligood says. ``They probably
have a pinpointed appeal in the black community among younger
people.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, humor is so specific to a culture and age group that
none of the Top 20 crossover shows is a comedy. But it wasn't
always that way. NBC's mega-hit ``The Cosby Show'' (1984-92)
crossed all racial and generation lines. It was a huge hit among
kids, parents and grandparents, marrieds and singles, blacks and
whites.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing has come close to the broad appeal of ``The Cosby
Show,'' not even Bill Cosby himself. His current CBS sitcom,
``Cosby,'' never a major hit, is going off the air Friday due to
lackluster ratings. Although criticized by some blacks for not
being ``black enough,'' ``The Cosby Show'' single-handedly revived
the sagging sitcom genre and brought millions to the box.
</P>
<P>
   What was its appeal?
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Cosby stressed how much alike we are rather than how
different we are,'' Alligood says. ``Color had very little to do
with the situational humor in that show. There was a funny but
strict dad, a mother who was generally strict but also loving, and
brothers and sisters who teased the heck out of each other. There
were trappings that showed they were proud of who they were _
paintings by black artists, sweatshirts from black colleges. But
there was very little racial context.''
</P>
<P>
   These days the races are more likely to come together over
dramas than sitcoms. Both groups can more easily relate to the
stories, characters and emotions in dramas. As Alligood says,
there's a ``universality to drama, good vs. evil,'' that appeals to
everyone. It probably doesn't hurt that popular crossover dramas
like ``ER'' and ``The Practice'' have multiracial casts, but black
fans don't tune out when the black characters aren't featured one
week.
</P>
<P>
   But the differences between black and white viewers are striking
_ perhaps predictably so with the much-talked about lack of
diversity on last fall's new shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question the lack of diversity had some impact,''
Alligood says. ``We went from a lot of separation many years ago to
coming together to going apart again. There are so many more
choices it may have been inevitable, and the networks have made no
overt effort to lure the black audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Statistics can give a false impression. Alligood says there's
``a pattern but no proof positive that blacks are in a world unto
themselves'' when it comes to TV viewing. Certainly black viewers
are more willing to watch so-called white shows than vice versa.
For some reason, white viewers still have trouble relating to the
black experience when there isn't a white best friend, co-worker or
goofy family next door.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we shouldn't worry so much about our separate viewing
habits. Maybe we should celebrate the fact that there are shows
specifically geared to blacks, since for so long there were none
(with the exception of ``Amos 'n' Andy'') that featured people of
</P>
<P>
   color.
</P>
<P>
   It would be wonderful if another crossover hit like ``Cosby''
came along that could give us a shared pop-culture experience. But
maybe that's not necessary. Maybe we should just watch football,
game shows and the occasional drama together and wait until we're
all over 50 _ we'll all be watching the same things then anyway.
</P>
<P>
   WHO'S WATCHING WHAT
</P>
