<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Even amid the general squalor of the Elian case,
for those with a political taste for such piquant delights there's
a delicious irony in the musings of the 11th Circuit Court of
Appeals over the question of whether a 6-year-old has independent
standing to seek U.S. political asylum. (Teepen, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ LUFKIN, Texas _ From Elian to flag burning,
from capital punishment to Microsoft, from guns to chili, such are
the burning issues of the day. The readers write. (Murray, Cox News
Service) MOVED FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Annie and Leonard, both
octogenarians, live to argue. This week it's about cemetery plots.
Annie says she doesn't give a hoot because she's not ready to
``move on.'' Leonard says it's time to decide because they can't
spend eternity in the old Buick even though, according to him, that
would be Annie's final resting-place-of-choice since she's run the
wheels off of it for the last 14 years. (Schuett, Cox News Service)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ Washington demonstrators didn't
know they have same goals as IMF, World Bank. (Rowland Nethaway is
senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   LANE-COLUMN _ DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ If elected to the Florida
Senate, I'm certain I, too, would drift away from the debate over
the third amended tax table in the Tax Break for Companies that
Force Their Employees to Pledge Allegiance to the Flag Act. I would
idly check plane fares to Brazil in case I had to leave the country
in a hurry or track the plunging worth of my shares in
PocketProtector
</P>
<P>
   DiscountWarehouse.com. And I'd be a better person for it. (Lane,
Daytona Beach News-Journal) MOVED
</P>
