<P>
   LONG-LOST PHOTOS OF VIETNAM WAR -- AND ACCOMPANYING FEATURES --
AVAILABLE FOR PURCHASE FROM THE NEW YORK TIMES SYNDICATE.
</P>
<P>
   ----------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   April 30th marks the 25th anniversary of the Fall of Saigon, the
official end of the decade-long conflict known to Americans as the
Vietnam War. In the end, the war claimed an estimated 3 million
Vietnamese, military and civilian, in both the North and South, and
some 58,000 U.S. soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   To commemorate the end of the war, THE NEW YORK TIMES SYNDICATE
is offering an  &UR; EXCLUSIVE TEXT-AND-PHOTO PACKAGE &LR;  that conveys the
profound impact of this catastrophic period in world history.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THIS NEW VISUAL RECORD OF COMBAT &LR;  is being gathered by Doug
Niven and Chris Riley, two American researchers who have combed
through government archives to track the photographers who risked
their lives to take the images.
</P>
<P>
   (SEE PURCHASE INFORMATION BELOW DESCRIPTIONS.)
</P>
<P>
   PHOTOGRAPHS
</P>
<P>
   (VIETNAM1) _ In the swamps of South Vietnam in February 1970, a
wounded Communist guerrilla, Danh Sol Huol, was carried to a field
hospital during a period of heavy U.S. bombing. (Photo by Vo Anh
Khanh/American War Photo Project)
</P>
<P>
   (VIETNAM2) _ Under fire in Quang Tri province in 1972, a North
Vietnamese radio operator relayed information from the front during
battle with a South Vietnamese armored unit. (Photo by Doan Cong
Tinh/American War Photo Project)
</P>
<P>
   (VIETNAM3) _ In Cam Lo, Quang Tri province, in 1972, a North
Vietnamese army truck driver is cared for by a local supporter as
he rests through the daylight hours before returning to the Ho Chi
Minh Trail at night. (Photo by Hoang Kim Dang/American War Photo
Project)
</P>
<P>
   (VIETNAM4) _ In 1975, volunteers clear the ground for a North
Vietnamese military base outside Cu Chi near Saigon. (Photo by Mai
Nam/American War Photo Project)
</P>
<P>
   (VIETNAM5) _ On the last day of the war, April 30, 1975, a road
leading to Saigon was littered with boots and uniforms abandoned by
fleeing South Vietnamese soldiers. ``I was just happy,'' recalled
Duong Thanh Phong, the photographer. ``Happy.'' (Photo by Duong
Thanh Phong/American War Photo Project)
</P>
<P>
   ARTICLES:
</P>
<P>
   THE FALL OF SAIGON, 25 YEARS ON
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAM-ESSAY (Undated) _ Suddenly, it was the last day. For 30
years the tides of civil war had washed over Vietnam, but there had
always been a non-Communist south _ a broad, fertile region south
of the 17th Parallel that was home not only to ethnic southerners
but the million or so ethnic North Vietnamese who had fled the
North after France's colonial forces were defeated in 1954. Most
people in South Vietnam had counted since then on perpetual United
States support against Hanoi's forces. But it was not to be. By
Malcolm W. Browne. (775 words.)
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAM TODAY: FORGOTTEN IMAGES REVEAL THE WAR FROM THE
COMMUNIST SIDE
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAM-PHOTOGRAPHERS (Hanoi, Vietnam) _ Many thousands of
photographs survive from a corps of photographers who recorded the
war on the communist side, both in North and South Vietnam. But
these pictures are little known outside Vietnam. Now, decades
later, a selection of those photographs is being gathered by two
U.S. researchers, Doug Niven and Chris Riley. ``Some (of the
photos) are as good as the most famous photographers on the Western
side,'' Niven's said. ``But they've been in the shadow for 25
years.'' By Seth Mydans. (1,600 words.)
</P>
<P>
   (A shorter 925-word story has moved as
VIETNAM-PHOTOGRAPHERS-ABRIDGED.)
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAM TODAY: PEACETIME BATTLES
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAM-25YEARS (Ho Chi Minh City, Vietnam) _ It was 25 years
ago, on April 30, 1975, that the last fleeing helicopter lifted off
the roof of the U.S. Embassy and the first tanks of the victorious
North Vietnamese smashed through the gates of the presidential
palace a few blocks away. But in its way, a quarter of a century
later, the war is still being waged here, even though more than
half the population of 78 million was born after 1975. Ho Chi Minh
and the alluring faces of Western capitalism still confront each
other, emblems of communist Vietnam's celebrated past and of a more
complicated future it has not yet decided to embrace. By Seth
Mydans. (3,200 words.)
</P>
<P>
   (A shorter 1,300-word story has moved as
VIETNAM-25YEARS-ABRIDGED.)
</P>
