<HEADER>
A5434 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u a BC-VIETNAM-PHOTOGRAPHERS     04-24 1728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIETNAM-PHOTOGRAPHERS-1100&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIETNAM TODAY: FORGOTTEN IMAGES REVEAL THE WAR FROM THE COMMUNIST
SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEWS SERVICE clients. Nonsubscribers can
use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, see end of text. 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.2000 New York Times   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOI, Vietnam _ Bundled in two sweaters and a coat in his
chilly, tiny apartment, an old photographer described in sharp
detail his most cherished image of the war _ a young woman, bent
under her burden of supplies, laboring up a steep rock face on the
Ho Chi Minh trail.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody _ not even the photographer, Dinh Dang Dinh _ has ever
seen that picture. After three months on the trail in 1974, all his
film, 80 rolls of it, was destroyed in an attack by a U.S. F-4
Phantom jet.
</P>
<P>
   Streamers of exposed film fluttered from a treetop, said Dinh,
who is now 80. His first impulse was to photograph the destruction,
but that is another image that remains only in his memory. All his
cameras were destroyed in the attack as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't sleep for a month, it was so awful,'' he said.
``Sometimes I still can't sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Many thousands of other photographs do survive from a corps of
photographers who recorded the war on the communist side, both in
North and South Vietnam. But these pictures are as little known
outside Vietnam as the long-gone work of Dinh.
</P>
<P>
   Now, decades later, a selection of those photographs is being
gathered by two U.S. researchers who have dug through government
archives and tracked down a dozen of the aged photographers who
risked their lives to take them.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years after the fighting ended, something surprising
is emerging: a new visual record of the war whose images had once
seemed so familiar.
</P>
<P>
   They are pictures of battle and of daily life from the other
side _ of barefoot guerrillas attacking a tank, of an outdoor
operating theater in a swamp, of children studying in a bomb
shelter, of a young soldier smiling brilliantly at the camera
moments before he was killed in a bombing raid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've printed hundreds of these from the original negatives,''
said one of the researchers, Doug Niven, who is preparing a book
along with his associate, Chris Riley. The work is similar to a
previous project in which they produced a book of portraits of
victims of the Khmer Rouge in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys would just bring us plastic bags full of negatives,
and we'd just hold them up to a loop and go through them,'' Niven
said. ``Some of them are as good as the most famous photographers
on the Western side. But they've been in the shadows for 25
years.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent interviews here and in Ho Chi Minh City, the former
Saigon, seven of the photographers talked about their work,
recalling what they said were the most intense and rewarding years
of their lives. They photographed the war, they said, with the same
nationalist fervor as their comrades, the soldiers. They include:
</P>
<P>
   Doan Cong Tinh, 57, a tough combat photographer who spent more
than two years living under fire in Quang Tri, capturing some of
the most dramatic battlefield pictures from the northern side. He
said he had carried a firearm as well as his camera and used both
of them.
</P>
<P>
   Le Minh Truong, 70, who took up photography after he was wounded
fighting the French in the 1950s, then discovered beauty everywhere
he looked, in the flare of napalm or the contrails of U.S.
warplanes in the rubble of Hanoi or the silhouettes of jungle
fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Mai Nam, 69, whose picture of a U.S. bomber tumbling through the
sky, a parachute floating nearby, was reproduced as a postcard by
the government with the caption, ``Happy New Year 1967.'' When
peace came, he became a pioneer in photographing beauty pageants in
communist Vietnam, and his walls are now adorned by pictures, not
of war, but of beautiful women.
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen Dinh Uu, 82, who took his first pictures in 1948 when he
helped capture a unit of French soldiers and then turned their own
camera on them. ``Oh, I was so happy,'' he said, recalling the day
he first held a camera in his hands. ``We were more alive in
wartime, working in the border between life and death.''
</P>
<P>
   Lam Tan Tai, 65, a master of battlefield photo-processing, who
carried his chemicals with him, built little earthen darkrooms and
hung his negatives on the bushes to dry.
</P>
<P>
   And Duong Thanh Phong, 61, who spent the war documenting life in
the hidden tunnels of Cu Chi, just south of Saigon. Then, in the
greatest thrill of his life, he photographed the final day of the
war, April 30, 1975, as victorious guerrillas and their supporters
surged toward the South's capital with flags and guns and laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Those pictures of victory are a revealing counterpart to the
familiar scenes of terrified Vietnamese in Saigon fighting their
way onto evacuation helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   Today, most of these photographers are little known even in
their own country. Much of their wartime work has been uncollected
and unused since its original publication decades ago in Vietnamese
and some foreign communist newspapers. Some has never been
published, and some of the photographers have little left besides
the negatives they put aside for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   For these photographers, the ignorance is mutual: the work and
names of their Western counterparts is all but unknown to them.
</P>
<P>
   At his little house in Ho Chi Minh City, Tinh, the Quang Tri
photographer, pulled stacks of crumbling newspapers from under a
cupboard, pointing to his byline as he opened each one, murmuring
his name as if he, too, had been hidden from view all these years.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his pictures, crudely mounted with tape years ago, were
stuck together and would not come apart without tearing. Some were
blurred by yellow spots of mold.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has always been my dream to exhibit my pictures,'' he said.
``But as you know, the years after the war were very difficult here
and nobody had the money for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this is also because the government _ like the
photographers themselves _ viewed their work as part of the war
effort, a project that could be forgotten now that it had served
its purpose.
</P>
<P>
   In the interviews, the photographers acknowledged with pride
that their pictures were deliberately one-sided, that they were
fighting as hard with their cameras as the soldiers were with their
guns.
</P>
<P>
   And for the most part, their wartime propaganda _ often stunning
to look at _ is as genuinely descriptive of the conflict as were
some of the great U.S. pictures of battlefield horror or anti-war
protests.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most beautiful of these was shot by Uu: a file of
young soldiers heading for the front surrounded by adoring
schoolchildren. The smiles on both side are radiant and clearly
genuine, if, perhaps, not entirely spontaneous.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this picture the soldiers understood the purpose of my
work,'' said Uu. ``We were all soldiers together, and we had a
common determination to win against the Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Nam, who photographed the falling bomber, put it this way: ``I
never had any doubts about my work because I never set up any scene
for propaganda. What i took was reality, but it was just one side
of reality.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For example, he said: ``After a bombing raid we never showed the
dead bodies lying in the road. Instead we took pictures of people
rushing to fill the holes, to show that bombs are terrible but our
road to the front is still open.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no question that their work was dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some photographers were assigned to the front but they didn't
go,'' said Truong. ``Nine out of 10 people who went never came
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Tinh was perhaps the most enthusiastic of them all in covering
combat, sometimes rolling onto his back, he said, to fire his gun
at a circling helicopter. Some of his pictures are blurred because
he was photographing on the run as he joined in a charge on an
enemy position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked my assignment,'' he said. ``There were big battles in
that area with America, many famous places that have left an echo
in history, like Kon Tien and Khe Sanh.''
</P>
<P>
   One of his most striking pictures shows communist soldiers
raising their flag over a captured bunker, with the bodies of South
Vietnamese soldiers lying around it. Another shows a communist
soldier warily checking two badly wounded South Vietnamese troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three times I was completely covered by dirt from an exploding
shell,'' Tinh said. ``Two of my close friends died. I'm alive now
only by luck. I loved taking pictures like this.''
</P>
<P>
   But nothing could match the excitement of Phong, who hitched a
ride into Saigon on the last day of the war, leaving behind the Cu
Chi tunnels where he had lived for years under the endless thudding
of enemy bombs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were so thrilled,'' he said. ``It was such a happy day.
Everybody was on the streets laughing and singing.''
</P>
<P>
   He hitched a ride for the 30-mile trip to Saigon, stopping often
to photograph the fighters in black who milled about openly now,
their rifles in their hands.
</P>
<P>
   The most evocative shot from that ride shows a two-lane road
filled with hundreds of pairs of military boots, discarded by South
Vietnamese soldiers who ripped off their uniforms to try to mingle
with civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Phong said that he had also taken pictures of the fleeing
soldiers in their underwear but that he had thought them too
embarrassing to print.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just standing at the back of the car, shooting backwards
as we headed into the city,'' he said. ``The car was going voom,
voom, voom as we drove over the boots, like a boat going over
waves. I was just happy. Happy. It was fun driving over the boots,
bumping up and down.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
