   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RPI-PRESIDENT (Troy, N.Y.) _ In her first year on the job,
Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute President Shirley Ann Jackson has
amassed a Washington-style team of assistants and corporate perks
to accommodate what school officials are calling a high-octane
schedule of travel, speeches and corporate meetings. By ANDREW
BROWNSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   EARTH-DAY (undated) _ On the first Earth Day in 1970, the cherry
blossoms in the nation's capitol were blooming. But just 30 years
later, global warming has pushed the flowering season a week
earlier. In another 30 or 40 years, according to climate models,
cherry trees in Washington--along with the rest of the eastern
forests--could well be dying. By EBAN GOODSTIEN.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-CONDUCTOR (San Francisco) _ Few young conductors live up
to their advance notices, but reports on Alan Gilbert proved mostly
right. The young American musician made his San Francisco Symphony
debut at Davies Symphony Hall and scored high where you would least
expect it - in the Teutonic Romantic repertoire. By ALLAN ULRICH.
</P>
<P>
   SEX-PISTOLS (San Francisco) _ Even if you hate the Sex Pistols,
even if punk rock turns your stomach and you wouldn't dream of
piercing a body part, you might consider seeing ``The Filth and the
Fury,'' director Julien Temple's documentary on the seminal English
band. By CRAIG MARINE.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Contrary to a scandalous
rumor, the National Park Service has not authorized a secret
program to kill off the spectacular non-native fallow deer and axis
deer so popular with visitors at Point Reyes National Seashore. By
TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WONG-COLUMN (Piedmont, Calif.) _ Political ``empowerment'' has
become a Holy Grail for many Asian Americans. One group
aggressively pushing this envelope is the 80-20 Initiative, an
Asian American political action committee. It is the brainchild of
S.B. Woo, a physics professor at the University of Delaware who is
a former Democratic lieutenant governor in that small mid-Atlantic
state. By WILLIAM WONG.
</P>
<P>
   SF-STYLE (San Francisco) _ San Francisco has always been a
cosmopolitan city with different languages heard on every corner,
but it used to be that only tourists wore shorts and sport shirts
when shopping. Now we see few women in dresses or men in coats and
neckties; almost everyone is casually dressed, and most women wear
pants. White shoes are everywhere. The changes are probably for the
best, but San Francisco lacks a special quality it once had. By
MARIA KRENZ.
</P>
