<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-RETURN-OF-THE-WHO-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHOSE WHO?: A CLASSIC BAND EYES A NEW GENERATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Roger Daltrey, Pete Townshend, John
Entwistle and the late Keith Moon.) 
 By GARY GRAFF  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Back in 1965, the Who gave the world one of rock's most
indelible lyrics: ``Hope I die before I get old.''
 &HT;    Mostly they didn't, however, and after 35 years the sentiment
seems more facetious than rebellious.
 &HT;    The venerable British band, which staged a 1982 farewell tour
but has regrouped several times since, has reunited for a summer
tour that will start in June and, possibly, for a studio album that
would be its first in 18 years.
 &HT;    The impetus for the reunion was the release of two vintage
albums earlier this year: ``BBC Sessions,'' a collection of 1960s
and 1970s recordings, and ``The Blues to the Bush,'' a live album
from some 1999 shows that's available only via the Internet site
www.musicmaker.com.
 &HT;    In short, the Who may be getting old, but they're very much
alive.
 &HT;    ``I've always kind of laughed at people who say you're too old
to rock 'n' roll,'' says the 56-year-old Roger Daltrey, who sang
that line in ``My Generation.'' ``To me it's got nothing to do with
your age or any of that _ it's to do with the music and what the
music itself generates.''
 &HT;    That's certainly been true for Daltrey and his colleagues Pete
Townshend and John Entwistle, who remain very active. Daltrey, for
instance, has maintained a busy solo career as a performer,
recording artist and actor. Most recently he's fronted the British
Rock Symphony, which performs orchestral versions of classic rock
hits, and is producing director Brad Silberling's film biography of
the late Who drummer, Keith Moon.
 &HT;    Meanwhile, the 55-year-old Entwistle continues to lead his own
band, which has recorded music for the children's cartoon
``Van-pires.'' He also creates rock-themed lithographs and is
writing a memoir about the Who.
 &HT;    The 54-year-old Townshend, who has been the Who's main
songwriter, has overcome bouts with alcoholism and drug addiction
to complete a variety of projects, including the Broadway hit ``The
Who's Tommy'' (1989) and a 1996 stage version of ``Quadrophenia''
(1973).
 &HT;    Most recently, he's resurrected the band's abortive rock opera
``Lifehouse,'' begun in 1970, as a radio play, a stage production
and an album that's available in different configurations via his
Web site at www.eelpie.com.
 &HT;    So it's not as if the three are short of work. But there's a
lure to being the Who that they can't seem to shake, no matter how
many times they promise ``never again.''
 &HT;    ``We've gone up and down over the years,'' Daltrey says. ``It's
never really gone away, though. We enjoy our company. We enjoy the
camaraderie of the band now. Pete has come an awful long way in his
addiction program now _ he hasn't gotten all the old hangups he
used to. It's really great fun being back together.''
 &HT;    Entwistle agrees.
 &HT;    ``It's really natural, kind of like a sixth sense,'' he says.
``You turn your brain off and, as long as you don't think of what
you're playing, it just falls together very naturally.''
 &HT;    Nonetheless, Entwistle cautions that, while the band does plan
some exploratory recording sessions, there's no guarantee that an
album will result.
 &HT;    ``Obviously, if we don't like it, it won't come out,'' says the
bassist/songwriter, whose contributions to the Who canon include
``Boris the Spider,'' ``My Wife'' and ``Had Enough.'' ``We've
agreed to go into the studio and have a go at one. It's basically
`What's the Who going to be like in the year 2000?'
 &HT;    ``And if you like the result, then there'll be an album.''
 &HT;    Townshend also emphasizes the provisional nature of their
upcoming studio work.
 &HT;    ``We don't have a record deal,'' he says. ``Nothing is going to
get me into the studio with a bullying producer to spend six months
trying to wring something out of my soul which is not appropriate
to either the band or the rock-'n'-roll market.
 &HT;    ``I can't imagine ever going into the studio and doing what we
used to do, with a hard-knock producer and spending six months
perfecting something,'' Townshend adds. ``I don't think the climate
now is about that, not with people making records in their garages
or bedrooms.''
 &HT;    What the band should sound like now is still very much up in the
air. Entwistle says he's hoping for something that hits hard and
heavy, like the Who of the 1960s and 1970s.
 &HT;    ``I hope it's going to go back to `Who Are You' (1978), rather
than `Face Dances' (1981) and `It's Hard' (1982),'' he says. ``I
think the feeling is it's going to be a lot more uptempo, upfront.
 &HT;    ``I've said that before,'' Entwistle adds, ``and I usually end
up with the only rock-'n'-roll songs on the album. But hopefully it
can be different this time.''
 &HT;    Daltrey, who has three songs for the next Who project already
finished and plans to write with Townshend for the first time ever,
is confident that the group can rekindle the vital, deep-reaching,
empathetic musical craft of its heyday.
 &HT;    ``It's a very unique band,'' he says. ``You can hear the
influences, but it's not derivative. If you hear the Stones, they
are derivative of Chuck Berry and the early blues people. With the
Who, you can hear the influences of those people, but it's become
something totally, totally different, with the way Pete wrote his
songs and the structures.
 &HT;    ``And what he wrote about ... where everybody else was writing
about sex and `I'd like to screw you, baby' in various different
ways, Pete was more interested in the psychological problems of the
adolescent and the young man,'' Daltrey adds. ``And that, of
course, is timeless, because it doesn't change. There's just a new
generation that comes around with the same set of problems.''
 &HT;    It remains to be seen, of course, whether that new generation
wants to hear those problems explored by three men in their 50s.
Daltrey concedes that it's important for the band to move beyond
the nostalgic appeal of its classic tunes to address its fans'
current issues.
 &HT;    ``I've always been of the opinion that, if Pete could write
about the problems of adolescence, why can't he write about the
problems of middle age?'' Daltrey says.
 &HT;    ``Our audience hasn't gone away,'' he adds. ``They're still
going through the same things I am, that Pete is, all those little
insecurities and everything. No one is completely cleaned up and
knows where they're going, ever in their life.
 &HT;    ``I don't think so, anyway,'' he says with a laugh. ``They may
think they know where they're going, but they probably won't end up
there.''
 &HT;    Whether any of these new songs will be heard in the upcoming
tour is another question, however. After seeing other bands perform
new material live, Daltrey admits that he's a little reluctant to
chance it.
 &HT;    ``Half the audience gets up and goes to the bar or the toilet,''
he says. ``We don't want to ram new stuff down the throats of
people who don't particularly want to hear new stuff, because we
can't at the present time play enough of our old stuff.''
 &HT;    That may be the band's next argument, though, because Townshend
definitely wants to give his audience new music.
 &HT;    ``When you look at the Rolling Stones, the Who, the Kinks, you
want to know where they are going to go now,'' he says. ``You know
where they have been, you want to know what they are going to do
next.
 &HT;    ``You want to hear what we're doing today.''
 c.2000 Gary Graff  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Gary Graff is a Beverly Hills, Mich.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``BBC Sessions,'' consult the
MCA Records Web site at www.mcarecords.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http:www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
