w a BC-KIM-BASINGER-IN-I-DRE     04-24 1251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIM-BASINGER-IN-I-DREAMED-OF-AFRICA-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTO AFRICA: KIM BASINGER EXPLORES THE DARK CONTINENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Kim Basinger in a scene from ``I Dreamed
of Africa.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    She may have an Oscar to her credit, but Kim Basinger is as
insecure as ever.
 &HT;    ``I think we're all insecure,'' says Basinger, who earned her
Best Supporting Actress statuette as the Veronica Lake-like call
girl in ``L.A. Confidential'' (1997). ``We all have our
insecurities, whether we admit it or not. I'm still insecure from
time to time about certain things.
 &HT;    ``The Oscar, to me, was one of the greatest moments I'll ever
have in my life, professionally,'' Basinger admits. ``It gives you
credibility in the eyes of so many people, and they let you know
it.
 &HT;    ``It gave me confidence,'' she says. ``It gave me credibility.
It's nice to be welcomed in that way _ it absolutely gives you more
choices, and more people want to take chances on you.''
 &HT;    Settling in for an interview at New York's Regency Hotel,
Basinger shrugs.
 &HT;    ``It puts you in another place,'' she says. ``But as far as
making me less insecure, every project is the next project and each
one has its own emotional ride.''
 &HT;    Basinger's latest project is ``I Dreamed of Africa,'' which will
open nationwide on May 5. The actress stars in the based-on-fact
film as Kuki Gallmann, an Italian woman who traded a life of
European luxury for the wilds of Kenya.
 &HT;    In her memoir, also titled ``I Dreamed of Africa'' (Viking
Penguin, 1991), Gallmann recounts how she tragically lost her lover
and her son _ played in the film by Vincent Perez and Liam Aiken,
respectively _ but also how she gained strength by becoming a
protector of the land and the animals around her.
 &HT;    ``I read the book and I had a meeting with (producer) Stanley
Jaffe, and that was it,'' says Basinger, who's still gorgeous at 46
and retains more than a touch of her original Southern accent.
``The story had everything _ it had every element any actress could
ever ask for, and it touched me personally.
 &HT;    ``The book was so beautifully written I couldn't get through the
last part,'' she recalls. ``I knew where it was going, and I
couldn't get through it. Kuki is such a beautiful writer _ it was
like a diary.
 &HT;    ``By the last page I was so emotionally moved, and not just by
the tragedies that happened, but by her journey as a woman,'' the
actress says. ``To be able to cinematically fill those shoes, to be
able to play those scenes, it was a gift.''
 &HT;    Making the film, Basinger recalls, was a dream, albeit a dream
fraught with snakes, dust storms and the loss of most of the
luxuries of movie stardom. And it was a long dream, too, as
director Hugh Hudson led his cast and crew through six months of
location shooting in Italy, Kenya and South Africa.
 &HT;    ``I had to face a lot of fears, the biggest one being taking my
then-2-1/2-year-old daughter, Ireland, into the bush,'' says
Basinger, who was also accompanied by her husband, actor Alec
Baldwin. ``But it was an experience that changed me forever.
 &HT;    ``I worked seven days a week,'' she explains. ``On Sundays I was
riding horses or learning how to drive a jeep with my left hand.
 &HT;    ``As a person, to be cut off from what we think of as
civilization,'' Basinger says, ``to have very little electricity,
to have to have water flown in, to live in the bush with the Zulu
people and have my daughter pick up Zulu words ... I could never
sit here and verbally express the mystical, magical, spiritual,
wonderful time I had.
 &HT;    ``It was a time with my family,'' she adds. ``When we took off
from Johannesburg, my husband was holding my hand and I was holding
Ireland's hand. I was crying, he had tears in his eyes.
 &HT;    ``Ireland didn't want to leave at all,'' Basinger says. ``She
asks all the time, `When am I going back to Africa?'''
 &HT;    One of these days, Ireland may ask her mother another question,
one of a far more touchy nature. Early in Basinger's career, she
posed naked for Playboy. She later had several nude scenes opposite
Mickey Rourke in the erotically charged drama, ``Nine 1/2 Weeks''
(1986).
 &HT;    Basinger can't relish the question, but she doesn't dodge the
issue.
 &HT;    ``It's going to be a big question when she gets older,'' she
admits. ``At that time, I really don't know how I'll handle it.
 &HT;    ``But I know one thing: I'd never hide a thing from my
daughter,'' she says. ``I had a journey myself _ I had to go on it.
She will understand every step of the way why I did what I did at
the time and where I was at the time in my life. My daughter and I
don't keep anything from one another, and that's the way it will
be.
 &HT;    ``She understands that he is showing his boom-boom, meaning
(rear end) or that they have goobies, which are these,'' she adds,
pointing to her breasts.
 &HT;    ``We're in a rented house right now that's owned by a bachelor,
and he has a nude little drawing,'' she adds. ``So all of Ireland's
friends know that's the boom-boom and that's the whatever and that
you're not supposed to show those in public.
 &HT;    ``So, yes, it'll be a slight concern of mine, but she will know
me,'' the actress concludes. ``I don't think we'll ever come to
that place where she says, `Why did you do that?' I will have
informed her of why before she ever gets to that place where she
will ask me.''
 &HT;    A smile crosses Basinger's face.
 &HT;    ``Ireland's only 4,'' she adds. ``So we've got a little ways to
go.''
 &HT;    Moviegoers will next see Basinger in the supernatural thriller
``Bless the Child,'' a fall release that she describes as a cross
between ``Rosemary's Baby'' (1968) and ``Ghost'' (1990). Right now,
though, Basinger is spending time with Baldwin and their daughter
in East Hampton, N.Y., reading scripts and basking in her career
revival.
 &HT;    And, though she's well into her 40s in an industry which is
notoriously indifferent toward its aging leading ladies, Basinger
isn't complaining.
 &HT;    ``So far, so good, don't know about the future,'' she says,
reciting the words like a mantra. ``Really. So far, so good. I've
been very blessed and lucky to have been asked to do the last three
movies that I've done. And we just go on.''
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``I Dreamed of Africa,'' consult
the Sony Pictures Web site at www.spe.sony.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
