<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEVERLY-HILLS-90210-FINALE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CURTAIN FALLS ON `BEVERLY HILLS 90210' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Luke Perry, Jennie Garth, Tori Spelling,
Brian Austin Green, Ian Ziering and Lindsay Price in a scene from
the final episode of ``Beverly Hills 90210.'') 
 By KEVIN DICKSON  
 c.2000 TV Guide Canada  
 Not to be published in Canada before May 14. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Expectations were generally low when Fox launched ``Beverly
Hills 90210,'' way back on Oct. 4, 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the pilot episode, with privileged kids driving BMWs to
school while wearing Armani and talking on cell phones, wasn't
promising _ it looked like a mix of ``Eight Is Enough'' and
``Valley Of The Dolls.''
</P>
<P>
   Before long, however, things improved. Each of the six leads
developed a distinct persona, both onscreen and off, and the
storylines settled into deeper material such as drugs, sex and
general teen angst.
</P>
<P>
   All of a sudden, teens on television became a hot commodity, as
``90210'' became the first television phenomenon of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years later, it's time to say goodbye to ``90210.''
Continuously sliding ratings have ceased to justify the $2.2
million production cost of each episode, and although the series
still rates well among its target demographic ... well, let's face
it, the cast are getting a bit long in the tooth for a ``Dawson's
Creek'' world.
</P>
<P>
   Teaser trailers have revealed that the final episode, which will
air on May 17, features a wedding. Translation: Do you, Donna (Tori
Spelling), take this man, David (Brian Austin Greene), to be your
lawful wedded husband?
</P>
<P>
   There will also be some not-so-surprising returns _ paging
Gabrielle Carteris and Tiffani Amber Thiessen! _ since Fox plans to
send ``90210'' out on a happy, all-the-loose-ends-knotted note, a
la ``Melrose Place.''
</P>
<P>
   But we come not to bury ``90210,'' but to praise it. What kept
viewers tuning in for 10 seasons? It's easy to write it off as the
appeal of the show's likeable, good-looking leads, but its tangy
writing must not be overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, ``90210'' was created and run by Aaron Spelling, the
same man who devised such long-running tacky-television classics as
``The Mod Squad'' (1968-1973), ``The Love Boat'' (1977-1986),
``Fantasy Island'' (1978-1984) and ``Dynasty'' (1981-1989). And one
of the first laws of Spelling Entertainment is that, if you want
viewers to keep coming back, you'd better throw one hell of a bitch
into the mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned years ago,'' the producer says, ``that if you want
to keep things interesting, you put a cat in among the canaries.''
</P>
<P>
   On ``Melrose Place,'' that role fell to blonde-tressed Heather
Locklear. On ``90210,'' at least in the early years, it was up to
the wretched Brenda Walsh, played by Shannen Doherty, currently
starring on WB's witchy series ``Charmed.''
</P>
<P>
   Brenda was ostensibly the twin sister of Brandon _ a.k.a. Jason
Priestley, who was and is actually a bit prettier _ and almost all
the storylines for the first four seasons seemed to revolve around
Brenda, whether it was her on-again/off-again romance with the
rebellious Dylan (Luke Perry) or her madcap trip to France with
Donna and Kelly (Jennie Garth).
</P>
<P>
   Things got serious, too _ unlike the ``Dawson's Creek''
ensemble, the ``90210'' crowd were neither self-absorbed nor
completely sex-obsessed. They weren't as inaccessibly wordy _ in
fact, most of the time they spoke like real teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, all of their actions were accompanied by
repercussions, especially sex. The first-season episode in which
Brandon lost his virginity to a visiting ex-girlfriend stood out:
He ended up feeling guilty and confused, a stark contrast to the
elation that typically follows every television character's first
sexual experience.
</P>
<P>
   Today the cult of ``90210'' is global. The series airs in more
than 80 countries, and the Internet is cluttered with devoted fan
sites. In Japan, ``90210'' cultists have given the show and its
American Teen Dream a crazed reverence, with memorabilia trading
for incredible prices.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is common among all fans, though: They refer to the
show's golden age as ``the Brenda Years.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of ``90210's'' early success was due to Doherty's wild-girl
rampage through Hollywood. The media couldn't get enough of her
ever-escalating antics. Like the mallrat from hell, she left a
trail of broken windows, black eyes and ex-boyfriends in her wake,
and the show's ratings skyrocketed as viewers delighted in seeing
the offscreen bad girl being forced to play a slightly snippy
high-schooler on television.
</P>
<P>
   Many believe ``90210'' faltered after Doherty was
unceremoniously dumped in 1994 over what were delicately called
``creative differences.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The machine works a lot better now,'' co-star Ian Ziering said
at the time. ``The lunatic is no longer running the asylum.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans clamored for Doherty's return, but co-executive producer
Steve Wasserman vowed, ``She'll never come back.''
</P>
<P>
   She didn't, and many felt that the show was never the same.
Thiessen did her best, but never quite captured fans' attention the
way Doherty had, and each ensuing season was a little blander than
the last.
</P>
<P>
   There have certainly been some bright spots along the way,
however, most notably the touching episode last year, written by
Ziering, that dealt with Alzheimer's disease and earned an Emmy
nomination for guest star Milton Berle.
</P>
<P>
   Over the decade of its existence, many actors and actresses have
moved through the zip code, but few who left have been able to
replicate their success on the show.
</P>
<P>
   Perry left for a big-screen career, failed and returned to the
fold. Garth stuck to the small-screen, and found a niche as a
teen-set Jane Seymour in innumerable ``issue-oriented'' television
movies. Priestley has also made a few movies, but got more
attention from a 1999 drunk-driving incident.
</P>
<P>
   The ``90210'' yearbook contains two very surprising
developments, however. One is the emergence of Spelling as an
actress unafraid of quirky choices, one with a knack for zany
comedy. Her winning turn in the dark independent movie ``The House
of Yes'' (1997) was a wake-up call to her detractors, and her
self-effacing role in ``Trick'' (1999) earned some outright raves.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's that actress who played Steve Sanders' single-mom
love interest a few years back. Remember her? She went on to do an
obscure little indie film ... ``Boys Don't Cry'' (1999). Yes,
Hilary Swank is a ``90210'' alumnus, the first to land a Best
Actress Oscar after passing through the zip code.
</P>
<P>
   That should encourage some of those who are now preparing to be
thrust from the nest. With the last episode already in the can,
Spelling is shooting a pilot comedy for Fox. Thiessen is shooting
one as well, called ``The Peter Principle.'' The other cast members
are reading scripts, so count on seeing them all again, very soon.
</P>
<P>
   All told, it's time to draw the curtain on ``Beverly Hills
90210,'' if for no other reason than that the series has simply run
its course. The original show aspired to focus on the lives of
Hollywood teens as they edge into adulthood, and it's done so _ the
original cast members are now in their late 20s.
</P>
<P>
   The show's most substantial legacy is the flock of
teen-populated series that have sprung up in its footsteps. It's a
safe bet that ``Dawson's Creek,'' ``Party of Five,'' ``Popular''
and their like would never have existed if ``90210'' hadn't paved
the way.
</P>
<P>
   So ring the bell one more time _ for the class of 1990, school
is finally out.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Kevin Dickson is a Los Angeles-based writer for TV Guide
Canada.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Beverly Hills 90210,'' consult
the Fox Broadcasting Web site at www.fox.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
