<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 12:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5505 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-WONG-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-24 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WONG-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GROUP RALLIES ASIAN-AMERICAN VOTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WILLIAM WONG  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PIEDMONT, Calif. _ Political ``empowerment'' has become a Holy
Grail for many Asian-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   One group aggressively pushing this envelope is the 80-20
Initiative, an Asian-American political action committee. It is the
brainchild of S.B. Woo, a physics professor at the University of
Delaware who is a former Democratic lieutenant governor of
Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   Woo also ran unsuccessfully for the Democratic nomination for a
U.S. Senate seat in the state and wanted, but did not get, a
high-level appointment in the Clinton administration in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1998, he and about a dozen like-minded
Chinese-Americans (including former University of California at
Berkeley chancellor Chang-lin Tien), launched 80-20 largely as a
cyberspace movement to try to influence the two major parties'
presidential candidates this year. The goal is to deliver 80
percent of the Asian-American vote and contributions in California,
New York and New Jersey to the candidate who commits to the group's
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   As a practical matter, it is unlikely the group will meet that
goal given the highly diverse and internally contentious
Asian-American community.
</P>
<P>
   The group's agenda includes an implicit demand that an
Asian-American be appointed to the next presidential Cabinet (which
would be a first).
</P>
<P>
   Also wanted are other presidential appointments, as well as
congressional hearings on why highly educated and highly qualified
Asian-Americans aren't better represented in corporate management
and university faculties.
</P>
<P>
   According to Woo, the group began with an e-mail support list of
300. It now has 150,000, he said, and aims to have 2.5 million in
two years.
</P>
<P>
   On April 15, 80-20 held a fund-raising banquet attended by some
300 people at the glitzy Marriott Hotel in downtown San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The group billed the occasion as ``historic'' because it raised
$100,000, an amount the group called a record for Asian-American
political fund-raisers in San Francisco. Other political observers
aren't so sure that amount is a record. In any event, $100,000,
while a tidy sum, won't excite fund-raising professionals in the
two major parties who regularly see millions of dollars raised at
events in Hollywood, New York, and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, some in the crowd called the movement important
because it is a concerted attempt to galvanize the nascent
political yearnings of Asian-Americans who have heretofore not been
politically engaged.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the strength of 80-20 appears to be immigrant
Chinese-American, middle-aged academics and scientists who are
fluent in Mandarin, which is only one segment of the multifaceted
Asian-American community.
</P>
<P>
   As 80-20 has grown, it has upset Asian-American activists in
both major parties. Just before the California primary election in
March, 80-20 called for a boycott of the Republican Party because
two of its candidates at the time, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas and
Sen. John McCain of Arizona, did not respond to the group's demand
to sign its declaration, while the two Democratic candidates, Vice
President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, had.
Shortly before its San Francisco fund-raiser, however, the group
rescinded its call for a GOP boycott.
</P>
<P>
   Even though 80-20 urged its supporters to work for either Gore
or Bradley during the primary season, some Asian-American
Democratic loyalists have questioned what 80-20 will do with the
$250,000 it has raised thus far. Woo said the group intends to
spend the money on voter registration drives, get-out-the-vote
efforts and hiring staff.
</P>
<P>
   The next big step for the group is its endorsement process this
summer. A committee made up of one-third Democrats, one-third
Republicans and one-third independents will decide which
presidential candidate to endorse based on deeds between January
1999 and this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The party that has done the most for us will get our
endorsement,'' Woo said.
</P>
<P>
   Although many other Asian-American political groups are active
throughout the nation, 80-20 sometimes gives the impression it is
the only such game in town. And it has managed to garner unusual
attention because of Woo's drive and a persistent e-mail campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, the group exemplifies a hunger that continues
to go unfed by the mainstream political system.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (William Wong is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is wongink(at)earthlink.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
