<HEADER>
A5511 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-NEW-AMERICA-ELIAN-FAT     04-24 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-ELIAN-FATE-SPURS-SELF-EXAMINATION-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELIAN GONZALEZ'S FATE SPURS SELF-EXAMINATION  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement
with New York Times Syndicate. For purchase information, see end of
text. 
 &HT;    
 By AMY WU 
 &HT;    The uncertainty of Elian Gonzalez's fate has spurred massive
protests in Little Havana. The raucous scene, described by some as
``an out-of-control banana republic,'' has also caused many
Cuban-Americans to question their national allegiance and identity.
 &HT;    Recent press reports reveal that Cuban-American police officers
at the scene are confused about their cultural identity. They feel
pressured by the crowds, who want the officers to sympathize with
their pleas to let Elian remain in America because they share
similar roots. On the other hand, some officers want to distance
themselves from this battle. One cop, quoted in The Wall Street
Journal, said, ``I'm first and foremost an American.''
 &HT;    The custody battle that has divided the Cuban-American community
has reminded me of my own mixed feelings about my Chinese ancestry
and American identity.
 &HT;    Recently, I found myself walking along crowded Canal Street in
New York City's Chinatown. It was familiar territory, since I had
walked the same path as a teen _ only then I did it unwillingly.
 &HT;    As a teen-ager, my family's weekly ritual was to take an
hour-long drive to Chinatown. Back then, I protested the ritual
because I was ashamed of being surrounded by people who clearly
looked very similar to me but, to my mind, were in another world.
 &HT;    The Chinese who occupied the open markets, mom-and-pop stores
and laundromats of Chinatown were new immigrants. Their clothes
were worn, and they spoke in a foul-sounding dialect called
Cantonese.
 &HT;    I distanced myself from them by refusing to speak Chinese and
reveal the existence of my Chinese name. In short, I distanced
myself from anything ``Asian.''
 &HT;    My father had a cousin from China who became a waiter at one of
Chinatown's restaurants. I remember ignoring him and feeling
ashamed whenever we all stopped to chat.
 &HT;    Much like today's Cuban-American police officers, I thought to
myself, ``I am an American first and foremost.''
 &HT;    But my strong feelings about, and memories of, New York City's
Chinatown began to change when, at 21, I sought a promising
journalism career in Hong Kong and had to stroll through that
city's streets, which eerily mirrored those of New York's Asian
district.
 &HT;    In Hong Kong, I was thrown into a world where everyone looked
like me, and I held the false belief that I would fit in simply
because all of us shared similar features and names.
 &HT;    The sales ladies spoke to me in Cantonese, as did the bus
drivers and bank tellers, and they all froze in disbelief when I
answered them in English.
 &HT;    In contrast to my childhood thoughts, I now felt a strong desire
to belong. I wanted to soak in their dialect, eat their foods,
understand the humor in their jokes, watch their TV sitcoms.
 &HT;    In short, I wanted to binge on the culture and ``become
Chinese.''
 &HT;    Unfortunately, I found myself caught between cultures and
confused about wanting to assimilate and disassimilate.
 &HT;    A Chinese-American friend who had lived in Hong Kong for four
years told me there are no in-betweens. I had to choose to either
be a local or a foreigner.
 &HT;    During my time in Hong Kong, I learned that gaining an identity
was not as simple as slipping a new outfit over an old one.
Relearning the language and eating the native foods wasn't enough.
Like any foreign culture, the Chinese people have a unique state of
mind and follow a different set of principles.
 &HT;    For example, as a woman born and raised in the United States, I
believe in being independent and in the importance of my career.
Going dutch on dates is the norm in America (at least in the
beginning). In Hong Kong _ and, frankly, in most of Asia _ that is
simply foolish. In Hong Kong, well-educated women dream of
secretarial positions at big companies, where they will hopefully
marry the boss. During my stay, I neither shared their beliefs nor
understood the intricacies of their jokes.
 &HT;    Over time, I found comfort in accepting the fact that complete
assimilation is a myth, and it was something I no longer desired. I
also learned that distancing oneself from one's roots is tragic.
 &HT;    I recently returned to New York City's Chinatown and walked the
same streets I despised as a teen. I saw those same people who once
repulsed me. This time around, however, I felt at ease. The street
peddlers and new immigrants were still working, but I no longer
felt the need to completely associate with, or disassociate from,
them. I realized I could maintain my sense of self _ be a proud
Chinese-American _ and still learn about my culture from them.
 &HT;    I decided I would speak the language and eat the food safely,
and that I would not look down or reject these people with whom I
shared similar roots _ but little else. I did not have to hate them
for who they are or hate myself for who I am.
 &HT;    It is OK to be confused about your identity, but you should
never amputate yourself from your roots.
 &HT;    If anything positive is to come from little Elian's fate, it may
be that first-generation and second-generation hyphenated-Americans
will re-examine who they are and how they see themselves living in
hyphenated-America.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Amy Wu is a free-lance writer who spent three years as a
journalist in Hong Kong.)
 &HT;    -----
 c. 2000 Amy Wu 
