<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 12:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5529 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-ZIMBABWE-DEAL-BOS &LR;      04-24 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-DEAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAL REPORTED FOR HALT TO ZIMBABWE VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG _ President Thabo Mbeki, handling his first
regional crisis, has brokered a deal with President Robert Mugabe
of Zimbabwe to end the violent invasions of white-owned farms and
bail out that country's hobbling economy, a senior South African
official said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, according to the official, Britain and the
United States have agreed to fund a structured land-reform program;
the International Monetary Fund would restore frozen relations with
Mugabe and prop up Zimbabwe's cash-strapped state-owned electricity
and fuel companies; and South Africa will seek to restore foreign
investors' confidence in its neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   In return, according to regional officials, Mugabe agreed to end
the two-month campaign against commercial farmers and take steps to
hold free and fair parliamentary elections due within four months.
Meeting with regional counterparts on Friday at Victoria Falls, in
Zimbabwe's northwestern corner, Mugabe indicated that police would
begin removing his supporters, many veterans of the liberation
wars, from the farms this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have is the beginning of an African engagement, of the
search for an African solution to an African problem within the
rule of law,'' Peter Hain, Britain's Foreign Office minister, told
BBC radio Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   US and British confirmation of their participation in Mbeki's
deal could not be obtained. But a Zimbabwean delegation was
expected to fly to London this week to seal the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Already caught in its worst economic crisis in at least a
decade, with critical shortages of fuel and foreign exchange,
Zimbabwe has been brought to the brink of anarchy in the past two
months as angry veterans, encouraged by Mugabe, seized commercial
farms owned by whites. Land is the country's most emotional issue.
</P>
<P>
   White-owned farms were the primary battlegrounds of the
liberation war against white-minority-ruled Rhodesia in the 1970s.
Since independence in 1980, however, most of the best agricultural
land has remained in white hands.
</P>
<P>
   The deal to end the invasions marked a significant diplomatic
milestone for Mbeki, who faced in Zimbabwe his first urgent
regional crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwe is South Africa's leading trading partner, and the
violence, which has claimed the lives of two white farmers and at
least four blacks, has made South African investors jittery. With
inflation and unemployment at 50 percent, and the critical tobacco
crop in jeopardy, financial analysts worried that Zimbabwe's crisis
is weakening South Africa's rand. The currency reached a two-year
low against the US dollar on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Criticized by opponents at home, Mbeki remained curiously silent
on Zimbabwe until late last week, opting to pursue a ``softly,
softly'' diplomatic approach. In the two weeks prior to the
Victoria Falls summit, Mbeki personally called President Clinton,
British Prime Minister Tony Blair, EU leader Romano Prodi, and IMF
officials to broker the plan, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president would not have done all this if he didn't
realize the impact of Zimbabwe's situation on South Africa,'' said
Parks Mankahlana, Mbeki's spokesman. ``You can't begin to imagine
what would happen to the region if Zimbabwe fell apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Meeting at Victoria Falls, the regional leaders _ Mbeki,
President Sam Nujoma of Namibia, and Mozambican President Joaquim
Chissano _ warned Mugabe privately that the farm invasions, which
were twice ruled illegal by Zimbabwe's High Court, could
destabilize the region. But publicly they called Mugabe a
``champion of the rule of law'' as they emerged from the talks.
</P>
<P>
   The accolades, however, weren't all show. Behind the deal, one
South African official said, lie fierce loyalties forged among the
region's liberation movements during decades of struggle against
repressive white regimes. The ruling parties in Namibia, Zimbabwe,
South Africa, and Mozambique are all former freedom organizations.
None of them want Mugabe to fall, even though polls indicate that a
majority of Zimbabweans want change.
</P>
<P>
   Tapping popular economic frustrations, a new opposition group,
the Movement for Democratic Change, or MDC, has grown at remarkable
speed throughout Zimbabwe. In one measure of its strength, it
orchestrated the vote against the draft constitution in February.
The MDC's manifesto includes a wide range of economic and political
reforms, including land redistribution.
</P>
<P>
   But its leader, former trade union chief Morgan Tsvangirai, has
angered Mbeki's South Africa, the official said. In his mid-40s and
without liberation credentials, Tsvangirai has obtained funding and
support from white South African businessmen and opposition
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how bad things get in Zimbabwe, Thabo Mbeki is able
to look at Mugabe and have a starting point: Comrade Bob,'' the
official said. ``Under Tsvangirai, Zimbabwe would be run by foreign
commercial interests. To be honest, we don't take him seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   The upcoming elections for parliament do not directly affect
Mugabe, whose current term ends in 2002. But Tsvangirai said that
if his party obtains enough legislative seats, it will be able
under the constitution to start impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate question, however, was whether the invasions would
be stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Veterans of the liberation war started invading white-owned
farms in late February, shortly after voters rejected Mugabe's
draft constitution in a nationwide referendum. Earlier this month,
the president pushed a constitutional amendment through parliament
enabling the government to seize land without compensation. The
bill used the same language contained in the rejected constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Although the veterans have clamored for land for 20 years, the
invasions have been more about politics than a yearning to grow
soybeans, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Shocked by defeat at the ballot box and facing his first serious
challenger in 20 years, Mugabe paid the war veterans $500,000 to
wage attacks against the white farming community. Most of the
estimated 10,000 squatters occupying some 600 farms are unemployed
women and youths. Victims of violence on the farms, including
laborers and owners alike, claim their assailants beat them into
pledging allegiance to Mugabe's ruling party.
</P>
<P>
   War veterans and government supporters invaded at least two more
farms over the weekend, and veterans leader Chenjerai Hunzvi
reiterated that his followers would neither vacate nor allow
elections until a land-reform program was in place. In addition to
the farms already seized, he said, the veterans demanded another
841 farms.
</P>
<P>
   When he came into power, Mugabe promised to put 162,000 black
families on new land within a decade. The government has purchased
about 8.65 million acres of land from whites, but 20 years later,
it has resettled only 70,000 families. Much of the land remains
idle. In the meantime, about 1.2 million acres have gone to
Mugabe's government and business cronies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
