<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CAT'S PAWS PUT WRITING ON PAUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   An item in last Thursday's New York Times reported that a
computer company is marketing a software utility ``that offers to
keep unintentional cat computing to a minimum.''
</P>
<P>
   But does a cat ever do anything unintentionally?
</P>
<P>
   The $20 software, by BitBoost Systems, is called PawSense.
According to the item, if the device detects ``catlike typing'' it
will block input from the keys to prevent unwanted commands or
deletions to your computer and files. It can also be programmed to
emit a loud noise to scare the cat away.
</P>
<P>
   PawSense is able to distinguish cat typing from bad human typing
by analyzing recognizable key combinations pressed by cat paws,
patterns determined with the help of several tester cats.
</P>
<P>
   This piece of new technology is fine as far as it goes, but what
cat people really need is some innovation that would discourage
cats from placing themselves on us or between us and our computers,
typewriters, notebooks, pads of paper, etc.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally someone asks, ``Do you work at home?'' and I
answer, ``No. I can't.''
</P>
<P>
   I can't work at home because no matter where I try to write, or
what I try to write on, my cat Killer manages to get between me and
the work. He seems to be getting more persistent as he ages. I used
to try to shoo him away, or pick him up and put him elsewhere. It
was useless. Now I look at him, so frail and yet still so feisty,
and I haven't got the heart to try to move him. He'll just come
right back, and I know the effort must take a lot out of him.
</P>
<P>
   Killer gets between me and whatever I'm reading, too. He reminds
me of a ``Mother Goose and Grimm'' comic strip that had Ms. Goose
trying to read a newspaper over the head of her dog, Grimm. Pet
owners, the caption said, have to learn to read between the ears.
</P>
<P>
   I tell myself that cats don't understand reading and writing,
but perhaps they do, in a way. Killer sees me focused on reading
instead of on him and does me the favor of placing himself between
me and the paper. He knows instinctively that he's more worthy of
my attention. What's the news of the world, what's anything for
that matter, compared with the purr of a happy cat?
</P>
<P>
   I remember reading that Virginia Woolf kept a Manx cat. Perhaps
that's why she was unable to finish a novel until she was nearly 30
years old. I imagine the cat sprawling before her on the paper,
batting at her pen, preventing her from writing.
</P>
<P>
   The cat problem has probably vexed many well-known writers.
Would Jane Austen have written more novels if the Austen family
hadn't kept cats?
</P>
<P>
   It's not clear whether James Joyce lived with a cat, but parts
of his work shows signs of possible feline interference. Some
particularly difficult passages of ``Finnegans Wake'' could be the
result of Joyce attempting to write over, or maybe even through, a
cat.
</P>
<P>
   ``One cat just leads to another,'' said Ernest Hemingway,
perhaps literature's most passionate cat lover. He surrounded
himself with cats. Maybe that's why he wrote such short sentences.
The famous Hemingway style may well have been the result of his
efforts to cope with his cats.
</P>
<P>
   How many profound thoughts have gone unrecorded, how much great
literature has never seen the light of day, how much pleasure have
readers been denied because one writer or another couldn't get past
a cat? On the other hand, the world may have been spared a lot of
junk and nonsense through the efforts of persistent cats. I'll keep
that in mind the next time Killer comes between me and whatever I'm
trying to write.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Diane White is a Boston Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
