<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-REAL-ESTATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUILDING BOOM: REAL ESTATE SITES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Real estate Web sites give a new meaning to the phrase ``home
page.''
</P>
<P>
   You can search the Internet for a home anywhere _ from Maine to
California _ by price range or number of bedrooms or style. You can
view pictures, or even take a virtual tour. And you can find out
what comparable homes in your neighborhood have sold for, or what
your boss paid for his new abode.
</P>
<P>
   One of the newest Web sites, Domania.com, lets you find
comparable sales, estimate the value of the house you already own,
and calculate approximate property taxes on the home you're
interested in purchasing.
</P>
<P>
   Formerly known as HomePriceCheck.com, Boston-based Domania.com
went online this month with financial backing from CMGI Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to consider ourselves a complement to the realtor. All
parties benefit when you have an educated consumer,'' said Owen
Eagan, communications manager for Domania.com.
</P>
<P>
   And for people who already own a home, he said, the Web site
``allows consumers to manage their most prized and valuable asset.
They can keep track of their home's value over time.''
</P>
<P>
   Other sites, such as VirtualRelocation.com and
realestate.Yahoo.com, let you check out schools and compare cities,
based on economic and quality-of-life factors.
</P>
<P>
   Some specialize in houses being sold by owners, while one site
bills itself as the leading online real estate brokerage. All
promise to save you on commissions.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Web addresses reviewed offer links to mortgage
companies, or calculators to figure out how much house you can
afford and whether it makes sense to pay points for a loan with a
slightly lower interest rate.
</P>
<P>
   There are so many real estate sites that a Massachusetts firm
that rates Web sites limits its latest reviews to 22 sites that
offer at least 10,000 home listings nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez Advisors (www.Gomez.com) scores the online home-buying
sites on such factors as ease of use and on-site resources. It also
allows users to compare sites, based on whether they are old hands
at buying homes or new to the real estate market.
</P>
<P>
   But when making any kind of a purchase over the Internet _
especially one as major as a house _ a buyer must beware.
</P>
<P>
   Some real estate sites offer a link to only one or two
affiliated mortgage companies, which may not necessarily offer the
best interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   And some of the sites' claims _ that they offer hundreds of
thousands or, in one case, more than a million listings _ may be
inflated, according to a study last year by Clareity Consulting, a
real estate consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a review of some real estate sites on the Internet:
</P>
<P>
   --www.Domania.com _ With what it calls the ``largest free online
bank of home sales comparables,'' this site promises to ``provide
all the tools and information you need to save time and money in
the real estate game.''
</P>
<P>
   You can check sales prices from as recently as two months ago
and estimate the current value of a home you own or project its
future value, based on sales data in your ZIP code.
</P>
<P>
   An outgrowth of INPHO, a company that provided real estate
information over the phone, Domania.com remains an information
service, Eagan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're designed by homeowners for homeowners,'' he said.
``We're not a transaction-related site,'' like those put up by real
estate brokers or mortgage lenders. You'll find no listings of
homes for sale _ just data to make your real estate decision an
informed one.
</P>
<P>
   Domania.com also provides data to Yahoo, America Online,
zipRealty.com, and other Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   --realestate.Yahoo.com _ You can search its ads nationwide for a
home based on location, price, type of residence (single-family or
condo, for example), and number of bedrooms and baths.
</P>
<P>
   You can compare cities, based on cost of living, median family
income, average home purchase price, and crime rates.
</P>
<P>
   And there's a fun tool: You can compare salaries and the cost of
living in different cities. For example, you can learn how much
more you would need to earn in New York to buy what you can buy
with a $50,000 salary in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The site also allows you to find a child-care provider, research
schools, hunt for a mortgage, and calculate whether to rent or buy.
</P>
<P>
   --www.Realtor.com _ Earning the highest overall score from
Gomez.com, this National Association of Realtors site boasts more
than 1.3 million listings. You can look for a mobile home in Maine
or a town house in Florida, by price range, square footage, and
other factors.
</P>
<P>
   One neat feature: Each listing estimates your monthly mortgage
payment, based on 20 percent down and the average 30-year fixed
mortgage rate (7.96 percent during this review).
</P>
<P>
   This site has the most listings by far, according to Gomez.com.
But last year, Clareity Consulting found that Realtor.com's 1.3
million figure overstated the number of listings by nearly 100,000,
according to Realty Times, a trade publication. Realtor.com didn't
dispute that finding, explaining that market conditions and the
winter weather at the time of the consultant's study accounted for
the deviation.
</P>
<P>
   --www.zipRealty.com _ Newly targeting the Boston area, this
Berkeley, Calif.-based company says it's the world's first online
real estate brokerage.
</P>
<P>
   Sellers and buyers who register have access to online agents, an
``escrow tracker,'' and loan, insurance, and home-inspection
options. Because of its lower overhead, the company promises cash
back at the close of escrow, up to $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   But because the site was just launched in Boston, on April 2,
its online calculator's finding that an average three-bedroom,
two-bath house in the Boston area is selling for $695,744 may have
been skewed. That result was based on only 45 homes.
</P>
<P>
   --www.owners.com and www.ForSaleByOwner.com _ These nationwide
sites target do-it-yourself sellers and adventurous home buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Owners.com offers three marketing deals: a free one-month trial
listing, with one picture; a $99 three-month basic package, with
five pictures and a customized yard sign; and a $289 three-month
deluxe package, with a virtual tour taken by a professional
photographer and an open-house kit.
</P>
<P>
   ForSaleByOwner.com offers two deals: a $39.95 monthly rate with
up to six pictures, or a $99 flat rate for a six-month listing with
up to six pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Both sites also offer calculators, access to mortgage services,
and other features.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-00 1248EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000424.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 12:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5540 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-ISSUES-BOS &LR;      04-24 1563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ISSUES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`QUALITY TV' REQUIRES A QUANTITY OF TISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What is it about these ``quality TV'' dramas that makes root
canals seem like a better way of spending time? Why was I not
addicted, like people I respect, when there were new episodes of
shows as disparate, but highly regarded, as ``The X-Files,''
``ER,'' ``NYPD Blue,'' ``Once and Again,'' and the two ``Law &AMP;
Order'' programs?
</P>
<P>
   The fog finally lifted when the latest of these quality shows,
``Wonderland'' hit the airwaves for two segments before being
canned. This was the program that incurred the wrath of mental
health professionals for its stark depiction of the population they
treat. As you might expect, the subject matter ranged from
schizophrenia to depression and suicide.
</P>
<P>
   But isn't that true of all these shows? Doesn't everyone on the
above-mentioned programs look as if he or she is one teardrop away
from taking the big plunge? Even sex, of which there's plen-
</P>
<P>
   ty, is marked by a maximum amount of anxiety or even desperation
and a minimum amount of joy. The world that's presented on these
shows is, with rare moments of light, an utterly mirthless one,
which is represented not only by the script writing, but an often
laughably morose style of acting; soft-focus cinematography (``Once
and Again''); and shaky _ i.e., gritty _ and frenetic hand-held
camerawork (``ER,'' ``NYPD Blue'').
</P>
<P>
   The issue is not that these shows explore the dark side of life.
That has been one of the roles of art since there have been artists
_ and these shows aspire to art as much as entertainment. The
problem is that they have become so predictably mannered and
superficial in that exploration. Characters often have good reasons
to be down in the dumps but on these shows everybody looks as if
his wife has been gunned down by a psychopath or his sister has
been abducted by aliens.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of weeks ago I taped episodes of ``Once and Again'' and
``NYPD Blue'' for vidoegraphic evidence of must-weep TV. You could
freeze-frame either show at random and see Sela Ward, her daughter,
and ex-husband in tears or on the verge. When you add in the
black-and-white psychotherapy sessions and W. G. Snuffy Walden's
new-age musical noodlings, you have enough ennui for an Antonioni
festival. On ``NYPD Blue,'' Rick Schroder constantly had his head
in his hands; Dennis Franz looked as if the Metamucil hadn't kicked
in for weeks; and the various female officers _ don't ask about
their biological clocks.
</P>
<P>
   If ``The Sopranos'' is marked by the normalness of the mobsters'
abnormal lives, these shows are marked by the extraordinariness of
these ordinary lives. Thus nurses, prosecuting attorneys, and wives
of policemen are dashed off to the next world if the actors'
contracts aren't renewed; even when police officers die, such as
Jimmy Smits's Bobby Simone, it's as likely to be from disease as
violence.
</P>
<P>
   The proof of a television show's worth is usually in the
writing, and the writing in some television programs is often as
good as just about anything you'll find in the movies or the
theater _ ``The Sopranos,'' ``The West Wing'' and ``Buffy the
Vampire Slayer'' are probably the top three.
</P>
<P>
   What each of them has that the others don't, for starters, is a
decent sense of humor. From Shakespeare to Beckett and beyond,
dramatists have recognized the importance of comedy to carry a
tragedy. What would ``King Lear'' be without his fool? When
``Waiting for Godot'' isn't funny, it isn't very good. Only the
Scandinavians like Ibsen and Bergman seem able to do without comic
relief of some kind.
</P>
<P>
   As Schroder's character said to a fellow cop _ whose harassment
of a drunk was about to lead to a fatal beating _ ``You know, we
lose our senses of humor, what and where are we? We're dead on our
feet. We're dead as doornails.'' That's a pretty good one-paragraph
description of all these shows.
</P>
<P>
   The Marshall Herskovitz-Ed Zwick school _ ``thirtysomething''
along with ``Once and Again'' _ is more humor-impaired than Al
Gore. The Steven Bochco school, which includes his ``NYPD Blue''
collaborator David Milch, does have a sense of humor, though its
darkness and faux working-class crassness grows increasingly
tiresome. After Schroder broke down in officer Kim Delaney's arms,
he apologized: ``I got your hair full of snot.''
</P>
<P>
   Glib one-liners are the stock in trade on ``Law &AMP; Order'' as
well as ``NYPD Blue,'' and what an equally glum cast of characters,
from Jerry Orbach and his terminally hangdog expression to Sam
Waterston, whose picture is in the dictionary next to
self-righteousness, to Steven Hill, who looks as if he's never
gotten over losing the ``Mission Impossible'' lead to Peter Graves.
And these guys are party animals next to Mariska Hargitay, who
looks as if someone is constantly holding smelling salts under her
nose, and her self-satirical crew on ``Law &AMP; Order: Special Victims
Unit.''
</P>
<P>
   At least with ``The X-Files,'' the tongue is often in the cheek
of the writers as they give David Duchovny and Gillian Anderson one
more reason to think that there's something to all these conspiracy
theories, as when the Cigarette Smoking Man fixed it so that the
Buffalo Bills would never win a Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   And ``ER''? Anthony Edwards _ what an actor _ has a range of
exhausted expressions that go from self-disgust to world-weary pity
as he attends to the grim politics at his hospital or his father's
bed-wetting at his apartment. The ``ER'' writers' idea of comic
relief is having Noah Wyle tell a scam artist trying to collect on
disability that he really is sick, with a case of leukemia that's
probably fatal. It was a mistaken diagnosis. Har-de-har-har. It
turns out a much nicer guy was going to die. Natch.
</P>
<P>
   All these shows have a pretense of profundity. Thus when we see
Schroder break down in tears we're supposed to think what a
multidimensional character he's playing. Or Waterston's decision to
prosecute a man who killed his wife despite the fact he has
Alzheimer's is supposed to show how law must prevail if we're going
to have order. What they're really doing, though, is substituting
one form of one-dimensionality for another. Compare the power of
Tom Cruise breaking down in ``Magnolia'' with Schroder and the
``Once and Again'' weepers to see how smart, developed writing can
be far more powerful than wearing one's sensitivity on one's
sleeve.
</P>
<P>
   It may seem unfair to compare programs in a medium that is by
and large a medium meant to entertain people and sell hamburgers to
independent films or nonprofit theater, but the best of dramatic
television, at least since ``Hill Street Blues'' and ``St.
Elsewhere'' and probably before, can stack up against less
commercial artistic fare. What seems to be at work here, after all,
isn't that these shows are after ratings but that they are taking
themselves too seriously. Either because the writers are suffering
from an inferiority complex or because they truly are inferior,
they think that piling gloom upon doom adds up to something more
significant than television that is purely entertainment. When
television _ or any writing _ tries too hard to be art, the result
is often pretentiousness.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, there is wonderful dramatic programming on television.
You don't even have to go outside the genre for examples. David E.
Kelley is the one writer who knows how to balance a script between
lows and highs, comedy and tragedy, all the while creating
multidimensional characters. That has been true of his writing
since taking the place of Bochco, his mentor, as head of ``L.A.
Law,'' to ``The Practice'' and ``Ally McBeal.'' There's a sense
lately that he, too, has gone over the edge, but you couldn't prove
it by the first episode of the retooled ``Chicago Hope.'' James
Garner stepped in as the head of the HMO that bought the hospital
with the kind of performance that's rarely allowed on these more
smug shows _ part ``Maverick'' antihero and part capitalist
uberpig. Taking a page from George Bernard Shaw and ``Major
Barbara,'' Kelley gave the villain the best lines of the show,
which brought the whole script up to ``The West Wing'' territory.
When an experimental operation that he authorized (for perhaps the
wrong reasons) goes awry, there's even more at stake than the lives
of the characters and the careers of the doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ``ER'' doctors have their share of bureaucrats to deal with as
well, but it's usually easy to tell the good characters from the
bad, the good ones having graduated from Waterston's acting classes
in moral indignation and the bad ones wearing the ``I am a
scumbag'' signs around their necks.
</P>
<P>
   Bad politics as well as bad drama can result from thinking that
there's depth to such shallowness, from ``X-Files'' conspiracy
theories on the right (Waco) and the left (Fells Acres and other
day-care prosecutions) to a general feeling that all our
institutions are broken and all it would take is a straight-talking
Sipowicz (Jesse Ventura) to fix them.
</P>
<P>
   But let's not lose our sense of humor along with the characters
on these shows. With ``West Wing,'' ``Buffy,'' and ``Chicago
Hope,'' there's no reason to despair. And if all else fails,
remember: There is less than a year left until another season of
``The Sopranos.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
