<HEADER>
A5541 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-24 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PARK SERVICE TAMES NON-NATIVE DEER POPULATION AT POINT REYES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TOM STIENSTRA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Contrary to a scandalous rumor, the National
Park Service has not authorized a secret program to kill off the
spectacular non-native fallow deer and axis deer so popular with
visitors at Point Reyes National Seashore.
</P>
<P>
   What the Park Service is doing, explained park superintendent
Don Neubacher, is ``continuing a culling program'' to stabilize the
non-native deer populations stable at about 700 animals and keep
them from overrunning native blacktail deer.
</P>
<P>
   To achieve that, park rangers have shot an average of 100 fallow
and axis deer per year over the past 26 years, he said, a total of
2,600 deer. The program was first authorized after considerable
debate in the mid-1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eradication isn't the goal,'' Neubacher said. ``We want to
control their numbers so they don't continue to spread and they
don't outcompete native blacktail deer.'' He called the controlled
hunts a management device, ``one of the tools in the toolbox.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a report circulating, men wearing camouflage with
rifles and high-power scopes have been systematically trying to
eliminate the non-native deer species at the national park. No way,
Neubacher said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last shooting was last winter and we have no plan to do it
further this year,'' Neubacher said. ``All the shooting is
conducted by rangers in uniform in times and areas so it is
non-intrusive, very controlled.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, rangers often pick winter mornings on
weekdays in areas receiving no hiking use.
</P>
<P>
   The fallow deer and axis deer fascinate many visitors who see
them at Point Reyes, most commonly spotted in the Limantour and
Muddy Hollow areas of the park. The fallow deer are larger than
blacktail, often with odd antler configurations, with about 20
percent of the fallow deer colored pure white.
</P>
<P>
   The axis deer are nearly as dramatic, colored with spots as if
giant fawns of blacktails. Both species were introduced in the
1930s by a Sonoma County dentist who was fascinated with exotics.
</P>
<P>
   Since the wildfire of October 1995, the high amount of sprouting
grasses, wildflowers, bushes and trees has provided an abundant
food supply on the west slopes of Inverness Ridge, especially with
so many wet years that have followed. Despite the culling program,
it is likely there are actually more deer than ever of all species,
not less.
</P>
<P>
   The management goal, Neubacher said, is for the Point Reyes herd
to support 350 fallow deer, 350 axis deer and 1,500 blacktail. In
addition, 27 tule elk were recently transplanted to the Limantour
area from the herd at Pierce Ranch near Tomales Point (that herd
numbers about 500 after starting with an original transplant of 10
from Grizzly Island near Fairfield).
</P>
<P>
   Because of apparent population expansions in the past five years
since the wildfire, Neubacher said a new management plan is likely
because of the land's higher carrying capacity from so much food
being available.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing a response to the fire, that the productivity of
the land is higher,'' Neubacher said. ``So what we're doing now is
bringing in more people and getting a new census done before there
is any more shooting, to update the management plan.''
</P>
<P>
   He welcomed the public to comment by writing him at:
Superintendent, Point Reyes National Seashore, Point Reyes, CA
94956.
</P>
<P>
   This ongoing story is significant because within many park
departments and wildlife agencies is a cult-like sect that advances
the opinion that all non-native species should be wiped out,
regardless of their benefits, as if it were a cleansing of the
land. They almost never recognize that the biggest non-native
species of them all are people, and that they are among them.
</P>
<P>
   Many non-native species are widespread and add rich texture to
the California landscape, including pheasant, wild turkey, chukar,
Rocky Mountain elk, fallow deer, largemouth bass, striped bass,
brown trout and many others. It is true, on the other hand, that
the introduction of some non-native species can be extremely
harmful, especially plant species.
</P>
<P>
   The best example is the proliferation of ice plant, once planted
routinely by the military and the Department of Transportation. At
Fort Funston in San Francisco, ice plant has been removed and
replaced with native plants, inspiring the recent return of
burrowing owls and swallows for the first time in many years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
