<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMEDY-ROCKWELL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONEYMOON BECOMES A JOKE TO MULTIMILLIONAIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Maybe Rick Rockwell could have cut his losses and
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, like other celebrities born out of personal scandal, he
could have sold his story. Or made a weight-loss commercial. Or
gotten his own radio talk show.
</P>
<P>
   But Rockwell, also known as the multimillionaire who got married
on TV in front of 23 million viewers, pledging devotion to a
stranger who dumped him 36 hours later in one of the most frenzied
tabloid stories of the year, is not just any
real-estate-mogul-turned-television-groom.
</P>
<P>
   He's also a comedian.
</P>
<P>
   And if his life is going to be a national joke, he wants to be
the one telling it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty weird, aren't I?'' he said, strolling out on stage at
the DC Improv Comedy Club last Thursday night, dressed in a black
turtleneck and brown trousers.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd giggled. It seemed everyone in the full house had been
thinking that very thing.
</P>
<P>
   Nine weeks earlier, Rockwell was transformed into a favorite
subject on late-night comedy through a succession of humiliating
headlines (he had a restraining order from an old girlfriend! He
had a toilet in his backyard! He wasn't really a multimillionaire
at all!). He was the butt of serious criticism, too, as feminists
questioned what kind of man would go on national television to
essentially buy a wife.
</P>
<P>
   But on this particular night last week, people seemed ready to
take Rockwell's side. Or at least hear his self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   Rockwell calls it the ``Annulment Tour.'' At times, ``Rockwell's
Revenge'' seems more appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   One punch: ``Who the hell marries someone named Darva Conger?
It's not even a real name.''
</P>
<P>
   And another: ``Darva Conger? I married Lorena Bobbitt, for
Chrissakes. She just snipped me verbally.''
</P>
<P>
   And another: ``So what do you think? Is my wife going to pose in
one of those girly magazines? Of course she is. I don't have a
problem with that, either. Call me old-fashioned. I'd like to see
my wife naked.''
</P>
<P>
   And another: ``Fifty choices, I pick an ice cube,'' he said,
sipping a drink as he shook his head, thinking back on the other 49
bride candidates. He lifted his glass and gave a sarcastic toast:
``To my wife's health.''
</P>
<P>
   For months, he has been the quiet one. When his two-day bride,
Conger, hit the talk-show circuit after their tense honeymoon to
explain how horrified she was by what she'd done, public opinion
swung her way. She described Rockwell as presumptuous, trying to
hold her hand on their honeymoon. She conveyed her nausea at that
first, public kiss.
</P>
<P>
   Rockwell didn't say much then. He did little, in fact, but make
unwitting appearances on tabloid shows.
</P>
<P>
   Before the wedding, of course, Rockwell had wanted to be in the
public eye. He was a comedian, not exactly struggling, but not even
close to being a household name. Then he turned to real estate,
where he made the multimillions qualifying him for the show.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Rockwell denies he used Fox's ``Who Wants to Marry a
Multi-Millionaire?'' to garner publicity for his comedy career.
</P>
<P>
   He even denies the ordeal buoyed his act.
</P>
<P>
   ``The audience response was always the same,'' he said, somewhat
defensively, when asked about it after the show.
</P>
<P>
   But there is little arguing with the fact that the Darva Conger
affair makes for some good standup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you plan on ever talking to Darva?'' one man shouted from
the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, that's the irony. Most husbands, when they want to
tune their wives out, turn on the TV,'' Rockwell shot back.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed confident, his eyes bulging slightly the way they did
on that fateful television night. His hair was slightly grayer. He
appeared to have a better tan.
</P>
<P>
   He joked about picking up single ladies in the audience. About
his religion. About the e-mails he gets.
</P>
<P>
   He read aloud from a few. ``You're a good-looking, honest guy
who Larva should have been honored to marry,'' he read, chuckling.
``Darva the Larva,'' he repeated, chuckling some more.
</P>
<P>
   The audience cheered him on. One woman taunted him, and he
reminded her about his restraining order, to even louder roars. He
seemed so natural in the role of jilted husband, so confident, as
if he had planned it all along, several patrons thought.
</P>
<P>
   Some women even thought he was cute. Funnier in person.
Definitely worth 17 bucks.
</P>
<P>
   But still a mystery, said Stephan Marmai, 31, an analyst at
Fidelity Investments in Boston who happened to be in town and ``had
to'' see the show. ``I just don't know why he did it,'' Marmai
said. Which is perhaps what made the whole affair so funny all
along.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
