<SLUG> BC-MONEY-TRAUSCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIP AND NEW? YOU? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN TRAUSCH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Are you old economy?
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people are, but don't want to admit it. That's why the
business world is so tense _ thousands of old-economy people trying
to pass as hot, hip and new, even as they experience vertigo
staring at the flying purple logo on the company Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, sure, they can flash their Palm Pilots, carry their cell
phones into the bathroom, and know how to turn ``IPO'' into a verb,
as in ``That son of a gun Herb just IPO'd another one!'' But at
least once a day, wham _ in flies a thought straight out of 1955.
</P>
<P>
   And the thought might be this: (itals)I wish the boss wouldn't
stare at his computer screen and read his messages when he's
allegedly having a conversation with me.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   This is a classic old-economy neurosis, stemming from a fear of
multitasking managers and rooted in the belief that people who are
attempting to communicate face to face should be looking at each
other.
</P>
<P>
   The antiquated thinking can be cured with therapy, but first a
person must recognize the problem. The following psychological quiz
is designed to help people focus on the warning signs of O.E.S.
(Old Economy Syndrome), and to move out of denial and into
recovery.
</P>
<P>
   1. Watching the current roller coaster markets, do you secretly
root for the blue chips? Alone in the car, listening to a business
report, have you ever slapped a fist on the dashboard and shouted,
``Come on toasters and soap!''
</P>
<P>
   2. When the Nasdaq tanks, do you ever high-five a graying
coworker and utter the phrase ``Dot-coms must die''?
</P>
<P>
   3. Do you think Fast Company is a humor magazine? Do you carry
one around to try to look cool while keeping a Reader's Digest
stuffed inside?
</P>
<P>
   4. Whenever you see the ad for the online freelance job bank
FreeAgent.com _ boasting that it is ``Saving the world from the
company picnic. One person at a time'' _ do you want to run a sack
race? Have you ever gone out to the parking lot and actually tried
to run one?
</P>
<P>
   5. Do you think your software is out to get you? Have you tried
to appease the technology gods by promising to add memory to the
hard drive if they let you finish the project without crashing?
</P>
<P>
   6. Are you haunted by the lyrics to an old Bob Dylan song
because in this revolution 40 years later you're identifying with
Mr. Jones?
</P>
<P>
   7. Have you ever worn a suit to lunch with dot-com
entrepreneurs? Did you ask them for a tour of the factory?
</P>
<P>
   8. Have you worked at the same company for more than five years,
and did you think becoming vested in the pension plan was a really
big deal?
</P>
<P>
   9. When the Democratic Leadership Council invited high-tech
gurus to come out from behind their computers and talk public
policy at a 4/1/00 conference in Boston, did you think it was an
April Fools' joke?
</P>
<P>
   10. The following week, when the Nasdaq dropped nearly 600
points as the White House held its New Economy conference, did you
figure the powers of the universe were making a statement about
politics, the market, or both?
</P>
<P>
   11. Would you rather drive than click? Do you have to go to the
store to ``feel the goods'' because that's what your mother did? Do
you believe online grocery delivery services would stick you with
the speckled bananas?
</P>
<P>
   12. Have you ever entertained theories that the Internet may
have been invented by space aliens? Have you seen them at work?
</P>
<P>
   Answering ``yes'' to six or more questions indicates you need a
support group. Finding one won't be easy, though. Perhaps an
anonymous note on the company bulletin board, naming an offsite
meeting place, would be the least threatening way to bring people
together. Promising to hold a sack race might help. Members could
wear the sacks over their heads until they become comfortable
admitting who they are _ human beings in transition. Never easy.
Always an adventure. Laughing helps.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Susan Trausch is a member of the Globe staff. She can be reached
by e-mail at trausch(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
