<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 12:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5546 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CATHOLIC-CONVERTS-ART     04-24 1540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATHOLIC-CONVERTS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 CATHOLICISM SEES SURGE IN ADULT CONVERSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the sun falls and an Easter vigil fire burns outside their
churches, they are escorted inside by candlelight.
</P>
<P>
   Standing by the baptismal font, they first renounce Satan, and
then embrace Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   Donning a dark robe representing the power of darkness, they are
immersed in water; donning a white robe representing a life of
faith, they are anointed in perfumed olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   And now, Catholics at last, they receive for the first time the
wafer and wine that the church believes has become the body and
blood of Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   This ritual, performed in churches around the world on the night
before Easter, is the final step in an ancient conversion rite that
is enjoying an astonishing revival after 1,500 years of dormancy.
</P>
<P>
   Data being collected by the National Conference of Catholic
Bishops indicate the Catholic Church in the United States this year
is experiencing a significant, if somewhat mysterious, surge in the
number of adults joining the church.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, the number of adults being baptized as Catholics is
up by as much as 10 percent this year, and the number of Catholic
adults who were baptized as infants but who are just now receiving
First Communion and being confirmed is rising slightly faster.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, the numbers are even more dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,000 Greater Boston residents went to the Cathedral of
the Holy Cross a month ago to sign the Book of Election _ the
penultimate ritual in the Rite of Christian Initiation as Adults,
the yearlong preparation program to become a Catholic. That is up
from 600 people last year, and 150 in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The increase in the number of Protestants converting to
Catholicism and in lapsed Catholics completing their religious
training is welcome news to an American church that is battling
declining numbers of men and women joining religious orders and
declining attendance at Mass. In Boston, Mass attendance has risen
slightly during the past two years, but archdiocesan officials
still estimate that only one-third of Catholics regularly attend
worship services.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic officials attribute the growth in conversions, as well
as the increasing return to the church of those who dropped out
after being baptized, to a variety of changes in how the church
interacts with non-Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   But those joining the church generally cite different reasons,
such as an interfaith marriage, the birth of children, a
life-changing tragedy, or a spiritual quest.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's Cardinal Bernard F. Law says he is delighted by the
phenomenon, which he, as well as other church officials, also
attributes to renewed church energy associated with this Jubilee
Year, in which Christianity is celebrating its 2,000th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   Other Catholic clergy and scholars say the surge of new
Catholics is the result of a little-noticed overhaul in how adults
are trained to become Catholics. The traditional process, in which
an individual is trained by a priest, has been replaced by group
sessions that are less insistent on the rote memorization of dogma,
focusing more on group discussions, participatory ritual, and
building community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's misconception is that they give you a bunch of
books and you memorize these prayers, but it's not like that at
all,'' said Jason R. Swartz, 26, of Winthrop, the child of a
Catholic mother and a Jewish father who will be baptized as a
Catholic. ``There's an understanding that this is a journey, that
everybody's at a different place on the journey at different times,
and you'll pick it up along the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan M. Rummel, who leads the Rite of Christian Initiation for
Adults program at St. Richard in Danvers, puts it bluntly: ``We
don't teach them rules and regulations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually a child comes into a faith community because it's the
tradition of their family,'' Rummel said. ``The adults have come
consciously searching for something, and ultimately what that turns
out to be is a relationship with God. So it's a process of
self-discovery.''
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for the increase, according to some Catholic
officials, is a more inviting church posture toward people with
messy marital histories and people who were baptized as
Protestants. These attitudinal changes are a byproduct of a renewed
effort at US evangelization by the church, which has long been
better known for its international missionary work.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to be part of something that's vibrant and
alive,'' said the Rev. John E. Hurley, director of evangelization
for the National Conference of Catholic Bishops. ``The parishes
that have a tremendous increase in numbers usually are very
evangelizing and reconciling communities of faith that are very
contagious.''
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenon can be seen at parishes around Boston, which are
enjoying record numbers of new communicants _ people who never
before were baptized as Christians, who were baptized as
Protestants but have decided to become Catholics, or who were
baptized as Catholics but were never confirmed or received First
Communion, steps required to regularly receive Communion in a
Catholic church.
</P>
<P>
   ``Communion is the main thing that makes people come to the
Catholic Church,'' said Michelle Akinyele, 20, of Lawrence, one of
several people interviewed who said they felt left out at church
because they could not receive Communion. ``Having the body of
Christ is the best thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Most new Catholics have some Christian heritage and are not
coming from non-Christian faiths.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to church, but I didn't feel like I was part of it _ I
didn't know why they did certain things, like blessing themselves
when they went in, and I wanted to learn more,'' said Faith S.
Hocter, 40, of Middleton, who grew up in a Congregationalist church
but began attending a Catholic church after marrying a Catholic and
raising their son Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, understanding it more . . . I feel comfortable, as though
this is where I should have been,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The churches that have the highest numbers of new Catholics seem
to share two characteristics, according to interviews with
participants and church officials. The successful programs are
generally run by charismatic priests, nuns, or laypeople who help
guide participants through the year, and the programs are willing
to work with participants who are divorced, who are single parents,
who do not speak English, or who begin the process despite
misgivings about some aspects of church policy.
</P>
<P>
   In language that might surprise some, people becoming Catholics
as adults use such words as ``relaxed'' and ``open'' to describe
the church.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``What I like most about the Catholic Church is that it is very
open-minded,'' said Niurka Ruiz, 21, of Lawrence. ``I remember
going to some other churches that were not Catholic and they tried
to inculcate, to force you to join, and I didn't like it. And the
Catholic Church is definitely not like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people are drawn to the church by dramatic personal
experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Welch, 40, of Lawrence, came to the church while trying to
cope with the death of his 18-year-old son in a car accident last
fall. Although Welch was raised Presbyterian, his son was Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my son died, I went to all these meetings of parents who
lost children. I went to a psychiatrist, but the only thing that
helped me was church,'' he said. ``The more I pray, the closer it
makes me feel to my son.''
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenon is arguably part of a broader national pattern of
faith-seeking by Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a movement of people who are in midlife, searching
for meaning, and returning to church,'' said Robin M. Jensen,
associate professor of the history of Christianity at Andover
Newton Theological School in Newton.
</P>
<P>
   And many of the new Catholics use the language of seekers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something was missing in my life,'' said Kathleen Haley, 23,
of Lawrence, who was baptized as a Catholic but never went to
church as a child. She is now going through the Rite of Christian
Initiation in order to be confirmed and receive First Communion.
``I wouldn't be happy if I didn't come to church. It makes me
complete.''
</P>
<P>
   From the year 215 through the 5th century, people interested in
becoming Christians had to undergo three years of rigorous
preparation before baptism, and in 1972 the Vatican required that
the modern rite of adult baptism be revised to resemble the ancient
process. The new rite, adopted in the United States in 1988, is
only now catching on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically I thought it would be a paper drill _ I would fill
out some papers, go to some classes, and boom, you're a Catholic,''
said Kevin R. Babcock, 39, of Beverly. ``Thankfully, it wound up
being a lot more than that. I can't say I'm going out and preaching
on street corners or anything, but it made me examine my life and
how I'd been living, and church is now an important part of my
life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
