<HEADLINE>
DECREASE RISK AS TIME TO USE COLLEGE SAVINGS NEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I have held onto Windsor II after its steep decline until it
has just about returned to the price at which I bought it. I would
like to exchange some or all of it for another Vanguard fund. What
is your suggestion? I just bought the Total Stock Market Index
fund. Should I be in Index 500 or Index Growth?
</P>
<P>
   D.C., Cambridge, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. This portfolio is much too aggressive for its
short-to-intermediate-term time frame. Presumably your grandchild
will need to begin drawing on the funds in about six to seven
years, so I would favor a much more cautious approach.
</P>
<P>
   I can understand your impatience with Windsor II, but I wouldn't
quit on it now; this is a fund with a long and proven track record,
and I fear that if you sell now you may eventually find you jumped
ship just as the value investments that dominate its portfolio were
returning to favor. With a portfolio dominated by durable goods
manufacturers, utilities, financials, and energy stocks, this
should be a solid foul-weather fund, and foul weather is precisely
what I see on the market horizon. I suggest you look not to its
1999 loss of 5.8 percent, nor its 0.8 percent year-to-date loss in
2000, but rather to its five-year record of 17.31 percent average
annual gains and its 10-year record of 14.31 percent average gains.
Its portfolio P/E ratio of 23.3 is also comforting to me.
</P>
<P>
   You could also take comfort in looking at a comparison of the
results of Windsor II and its large-cap value peers during the last
couple of years _ with Windsor II consistently running ahead of its
peer group until early this year, and currently running a bit ahead
of the pack in this currently unpopular market sector.
</P>
<P>
   As you probably know, Vanguard Health Care fund is also a
longtime favorite of mine but not for a portfolio such as this. I
suggest you sell half of that position, putting the proceeds into
Vanguard Balanced Index. And I would sell all of the Total Stock
Market Index fund, putting the proceeds there in Vanguard GNMA
fund.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I would allocate future contributions along similar
lines, not only putting the new money in funds such as the Balanced
and GNMA offerings, but also slowly decreasing the stock market
risk as your granchild nears the first year of college. I'd begin
at about the time your grandchild is a freshman in high school,
slowly liquidating the Windsor II and Health Care positions so that
by the time college looms, the entire portfolio would be on the
fixed-income side, most of that in CDs, short-term bonds, and money
market positions. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I expect to net $50,000 from the sale of my home this year.
Of this, $20,000 will be used as the down payment on a condo and
$5,000 will go into an emergency savings account. As for the
remaining $25,000, what do you advise? I have been considering
either putting it into a fixed-income fund, the proceeds of which
would go to pay premiums on a long-term health care policy, or
adding the money to my portfolio. If I take the latter course,
should I add to my current portfolio or add to my holdings by
betting into a combination of risky high-tech funds balanced by
some conservative blue chips?
</P>
<P>
   K.C., Shrewsbury, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I'm far from an expert on this, but my visceral feeling is
that unless you have, or expect you might soon have, some unusual
health situation, you would be better off in the long run if you
added that $25,000 to your investments rather than putting it in
fixed-income holdings that would pay premiums on a health-care
policy.
</P>
<P>
   If you agree with that thinking, I would advise that you pursue
a combination of the two alternatives you propose. I would add to
the current portfolio by increasing the stake in the ICM/Isabelle
Small-Cap Value fund by about $5,000. This is an intriguing little
fund, begun only in March 1998 with only $19 million in assets. But
it produced a gain of 49.5 percent in 1999, and so far this year it
has a 9.68 percent gain. These are especially spectacular numbers
when you consider the unpopular market segment _ small-cap value
stocks _ in which it has been operating.
</P>
<P>
   It also is fairly risky, so a bigger position here might fill
your apparent appetite for something dicey. Its portfolio is
concentrated into only 44 stocks, with those concentrated in small
industrial and durable stocks.
</P>
<P>
   If you go along with that suggestion, you would have a little
more than 30 percent of your fund portfolio in issues with
above-average risk _ Isabelle and Vanguard Health Care. That's
enough. At that point, I would seek to build a more traditional
core portfolio, dividing the remaining $20,000 evenly between
Vanguard Mid-Cap Index fund and Vanguard Index 500. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am contributing 10 percent of my salary to my company's
401(k) fund. I would like to know which funds among the 10
available in the plan would give the maximum growth.
</P>
<P>
   V.A., San Diego &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Questions like that can be answered only in hindsight. But it
appears to me that you have your portfolio pretty well out of
balance with your current allocations. More than 70 percent of your
holdings are in the small-cap and mid-cap arenas, and while these
market sectors have been doing fairly well lately, most investors
prefer to have their portfolio dominated by the large-cap stocks.
Besides the three funds that you are now using, your 401(k) offers
three other stock funds _ Prices International Stock fund, its
Equity Index fund, and its Equity-Income fund. (You are correct to
ignore the three fixed-income funds and the balanced fund; at your
age you want to be entirely in stock funds for maximum long-term
growth.)
</P>
<P>
   If I were allocating a long-term portfolio with these choices I
would go with 40 percent in the Equity-Index fund, which simply
tracks the results of the Standard and Poor's 500 Index. I would
then put another 10 percent in Price's Equity-Income fund, which
holds a portfolio of large-cap value-oriented stocks, and is the
only fund offered that will give you participation in the value end
of the large-cap market. I would then cut the holdings in New
Horizons, a small-cap fund, and in Mid-Cap Growth fund to 20
percent each. I would then fill out the allocation by putting the
final 10 percent in Price's International Stock fund. That last
move increases your exposure to international equity markets from
the current 7.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   What do I have against the Spectrum Growth fund? Nothing,
really. It is a fund that puts its assets in shares of eight
different Price stock funds, with the International Stock fund at
the head of the list, closely followed by New Horizons. It's a
solid fund, but it's easier to track the performance of different
segments of your portfolio if your holdings are in specific market
funds rather than jumbled together in a single offering. Funds such
as this are basically designed for people who just want a single
fund that will touch all the bases. Since you can select your own
variety through the 401(k) allocation, that's the course I would
take. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Money Musings: Reading the notice of the annual meeting of a
mutual fund can be about as instructive and exciting as most
boilerplate is, and maybe even worse. But occasionally, you can
find a nugget.
</P>
<P>
   I use the Alger family of funds as a source for investing odd
bits of money that stumble in. From time to time I have been
alternating between investments in the Small-Cap, Mid-Cap Growth
and Capital Appreciation funds.
</P>
<P>
   The Alger fund family was established by a father, and his son
came into the business later and is now the manager of record of
the funds. When I looked into the notice for the annual meeting,
part of that boilerplate detailed where the Algers had put their
own money: They had fairly small holdings in each of the funds and
big concentrations in both the Small-Cap and Mid-Cap Growth
entries.
</P>
<P>
   What better insider information do you need? This approach won't
work with mammoth fund families such as Fidelity and Vanguard, but
if you use a small fund family, taking a few moments to go through
the meeting notice can be informative.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box 2378,
Boston, MA 02107. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
