u a BC-SLAVE-GENETICS-ART-BO     04-24 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLAVE-GENETICS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DNA READINGS TO PUT US BLACKS ON AFRICA'S MAP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
888-346-9867 or 888-603-1036.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Promising to reconnect a bond broken by the horrors of the
trans-Atlantic slave trade, a team of geneticists plans to offer a
DNA test this summer that would allow African-Americans to pinpoint
their roots on the African continent.
</P>
<P>
   By using a blood test that matches DNA sequences to samples
taken from native African populations, scientists at Howard
University say, they could, for example, link a black man from
Roxbury to the mountains of Ghana's Ashanti region, where his kin
walked centuries ago.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say the test, which could cost up to $300, could
easily spark the kind of movement that followed Alex Haley's book
and television miniseries ``Roots'' in the 1970s, when thousands of
blacks set across the Atlantic, hoping to reclaim their lost
culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't mean anything to know that some of my people came
from Africa, but if I can pinpoint a culture, a religion, and
language, then it can strengthen my sense of identity and
relationship with Africa,'' said Richard Newman of Harvard
University's W.E.B. DuBois Institute for African-American Research.
</P>
<P>
   But as members of a new generation search the past for a sense
of identity, they might not find what they expect, warn historians,
educators, and genealogists. Some African-Americans will discover
the branches of their family tree lead not to a bend in the Niger
River, but to England and Germany. DNA tests, Howard University
geneticists say, have already revealed that about 30 percent of
African-American men descended from a European on their father's
side _ largely the legacy, they say, of raped women slaves.
</P>
<P>
   Others, predicted genealogist Tony Burroughs, will flock to
Africa searching for similar sounding last names and family
resemblances only to discover that they have nothing in common with
the people there but the color of their skin. Burroughs recalled
many blacks went to Africa after ``Roots,'' but came back feeling
confused and ultimately, unfulfilled.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way we have roots, blood, and regional ties in Africa,
but in other ways it's still a foreign country,'' said Burroughs,
an African-American.
</P>
<P>
   ``The years that have passed since we have been off the African
shores have been difficult on both sides of the ocean, and there
has been little attempt to bridge those gaps.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick Kittles, the 34-year-old geneticist at Howard University in
Washington who initiated the study, has been the main researcher.
He insists that while the test will offer only a glimmer of the
past, even a hint of their African roots is more than most
African-Americans have ever hoped for. The slave trade erased
family histories, and, before the discovery of DNA, nobody imagined
that the stories could be written anew.
</P>
<P>
   ``To a lot of blacks, knowing a little bit of the story is
important, he said. ``This will definitely contribute a lot to
understanding the history of African-Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard University will be able to do two versions of the test,
Kittles said. The first looks at mitochondrial DNA, which is handed
down, unchanged, from mother to child. The other uses the male, or
Y, chromosome, which is passed on from father to son unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers can then compare the test subject with a database of
more than 2,000 samples they have assembled from about 40
populations across Western Africa, where the trans-Atlantic slave
trade originated. Small, distinctive mutations in the DNA of each
of these populations serve as fingerprints, allowing researchers to
make the match.
</P>
<P>
   Kittles has also collected a separate database with Native
American, Asian, and European DNA to cross-reference genes that
cannot be traced to Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Such a test makes no attempt to tell a full family story; it
tells where only one line of the family tree came from, researchers
say.
</P>
<P>
   Burroughs said the DNA results may give people a ``false sense
of security.'' People may head to Nigeria because the DNA results
say they may have roots in that country, but there are many people
there who have a different genetic makeup, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another pitfall is that researchers have extracted genetic
fingerprints from only a limited number of African populations. If
an African population has scattered since the slave trade, or if
researchers have not yet isolated a population's DNA, then the test
will not lead anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Kittles said the researchers are collecting additional DNA
samples so they can expand the database and identify more African
populations. He also said they do not know when the test will be
available to the public, but they hope to have it ready this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Despite limitations of the test, Kittles said he is already
getting calls from across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think African-Americans will be receptive to this. Right
from the start there has always been a spiritual link to Africa,
though there was never any physical link,'' said Manisha Sinha,
assistant professor of Afro-American studies and history at the
University of Massachusetts at Amherst.
</P>
<P>
   Kittles said the idea for the test came to him when he was a
graduate student.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, Kittles was tracing the origin of skeletal
remains found in a lost burial ground in Manhattan. As he worked to
compare DNA sequences in the bones with African populations _ to
establish that the bones were those of enslaved African _ he
realized he could use the same method to find the origins of living
African descendants.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are from Europe, you know where your relatives probably
came from, and if you are Native American, you know what tribe you
are from, but if you are black and want to go to Africa, where do
you go?'' asked Sam Ford, 46, one of the subjects whom Howard has
used to refine the test.
</P>
<P>
   He said he has always been told that he looks Nigerian, but had
no way of knowing the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are like an adoptive child trying to find out where your
family came from,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Months after Ford took the test, Kittles sat him in front of his
computer and explained that a pattern on his Y chromosome linked
him to people from the area of Ibadan, a city in southwestern
Nigeria. Ford's ancestors on his father's side are probably
Yorubas, one of the largest tribes in Nigeria. Mitochondrial DNA
showed that ancestors on his mother's side were probably from an
area that includes modern-day Somalia and Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least now there is some place for me to go,'' said Ford,
who plans to travel to Nigeria soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
