graphics with BUSH-EDUCATION and SLAVE-GENETICS are being
transmitted to NYT Photo Service subscribers.  
 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, please contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta
 &LR; at the Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of
graphics or photos please call  &UR; 888-346-9867  &LR; or  &UR; 888-603-1036 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHEMICALS (Shchuchye, Russia) _ Distrust runs deep over a
Russian-American plan to destroy one of the world's largest and
deadliest chemical weapons stockplies. By David Filipox. 1690
words. PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS (p) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-EDUCATION (Houston) _ George W. Bush is widely praised in
Texas for his advocacy of education issues. But his record shows
that while Bush deserves credit for boosting education spending and
for pressing for reforms, some of the successes he cites can't be
traced to his efforts. By Michael Kranish. (2 takes) GRAPHIC: 25
picas x 12 inches: ``Behind the rhetoric.''
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-GORE (Undated) _ After a month in which George Bush has
neatly staked out the ideological middle ground while Al Gore has
enraged Democrats by pandering on Elian, it may be time to
reevaluate who is stronger. By Scot Lehigh. 1400 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CANCER-SCAM (Woburn, Mass.) _ In the early 1990s, a
Massachusetts warehouse held a promising cancer drug that was
shipped to Mexico, the Bahamas and the United States. Now criminal
charges have been filed against two officials of the company making
LK-200, accusing them of defrauding investors and deceiving
patients. By Richard Saltus. 1760 words. (a and f coding)
</P>
<P>
   SLAVE-GENETICS (Undated) _ Promising to reforge a bond broken by
the horrors of the trans-Atlantic slave trade, geneticists plan to
launch DNA testing to help African Americans to pinpoint their
roots on the African continent. By Tatsha Robertson. 1145 words.
GRAPHIC: 25 picas x 4 inches, ``Roots.''
</P>
<P>
   CATHOLIC-CONVERTS (Undated) _ The number of adults converting to
Catholicism this year is at a record high. Officials are somewhat
at a loss to explain it, but theories include a new emphasis on
domestic evangelization, a reinvigoration of church life, a new
openness to solving problems by Catholic officials, and a more
welcoming attitude to other Christians. By Michael Paulson. 1575
words. &UR;  &LR; PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   HARVARD-WEB (Cambridge, Mass.) _ In the wake of the Arthur
Miller debacle over Internet courses, Harvard is toughening up
regulations governing what its professors can and can't do on the
World Wide Web. By David Abel. 1300 words.
</P>
