<HEADER>
A5561 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-24 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PROSPECTS FOR JEANNE SHAHEEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; WASHINGTON _ It was a remark delivered so calmly it was almost
offhand. But New Hampshire's Governor Jeanne Shaheen was talking
about far more than the campaign for governor this year, at least
by implication. And that implication is full of national meaning
because it directly affects Al Gore's options in choosing his
running mate against George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   What she said was that she would be announcing her plans about
seeking reelection this fall to a third term as governor in a few
weeks or so _ about a month before the June filing deadline. Down
here for some fund-raising, a little shoulder-rubbing with the Gore
family, and an opportunity to show off before the Democratic
Governors' Association's monthly
come-see-a-real-live-Democratic-governor forum, she had also said
she probably would be running.
</P>
<P>
   The implication is that the governor's likelihood of being
Gore's running mate, of even being part of the mix down the stretch
toward the Democratic National Convention in August, has taken a
tumble down to longest of long shots. And from watching and
listening to her here and up in Boston this month, it seems clear
that this is her choice about her life.
</P>
<P>
   After seeing a dozen of these running-mate decisions evolve over
the years, you learn to put conditional words in all your
sentences. Surprise and last-minute lurches are the norm.
</P>
<P>
   But because of the political calendar, what Shaheen has said
appears pretty clear. From Gore's perspective _ and I believe the
country's as well _ this is more than unfortunate. The political
calendar, a pesky reality check sometimes, has in effect made it
difficult to the point of impossible for him to consider a female
Democratic politician for Vice President.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Dianne Feinstein, whom Walter Mondale almost picked as
his running mate in 1984 when she was mayor of San Francisco, is
not only also up for reelection this year; she has already been
through her primary and raised gobs of money for her race. She gets
mentioned as a running mate all the time (though from what I hear,
it was Jeanne Shaheen the Gore campaign was eyeing all along) _ but
picking Feinstein in August would be disruptive in the extreme.
</P>
<P>
   And the job title of Lieutenant Governor Kathleen Kennedy
Townsend of Maryland, Robert Kennedy's first-born, says it all. She
is considered a certain candidate to succeed Parris Glendenning two
years hence; were she to win, she would immediately be a factor in
presidential politics. But to skip a rung on the career ladder
doesn't make sense for her or for Gore, who will be emphasizing the
word ``experience'' straight through to November.
</P>
<P>
   The only other female name who shares Gore's core beliefs as a
New Democrat that I've heard _ Laura Tyson _ symbolizes how long a
female long shot has become. Tyson is top-drawer, an architect of
the Clinton's administration's successful economic policies in his
first term and now the highly thought-of dean of the University of
California's business school. But for now that's a notion, not even
a viable possibility.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year, it was Jeanne Shaheen who was in Gore's
sights, precisely because her gender was an added, not the sole,
benefit. In fact, her boosters for veep are said to have included
the campaign's chief kibbitzer, President Clinton himself.
</P>
<P>
   Alliance politics, like gender, was also involved, but that,
too, was an extra dimension. The fact is, it was was more than
Shaheen's endorsement that helped Gore beat Bill Bradley in New
Hampshire's pivotal primary on Feb. 1. It was also more than the
fact her husband and one of the state party's legendary operatives,
Billy Shaheen, was running the Gore operation months before she
went public.
</P>
<P>
   The real key was that the concept of the primary that came from
the governor's operation _ that the fulcrum for the primary would
be the economy, state and national, and that Gore needed to make it
clear that he would fight for working families and not merely come
up with policy ideas _ carred the day.
</P>
<P>
   But what would have made Shaheen a certain short-listee is her
status and record as a successful New Democrat. Her strength in
creating a vital center in New Hampshire has been visible in her
landslide majorities and in the quiet support for her patient,
consensus-building emphasis on governance over quixotic, swaggering
partisanship.
</P>
<P>
   The wisdom of Shaheen's approach becaomes more evident every
month. Already the state share of education has jumped from a dime
on the dollar to more than half. An advisory commission will tell
the state with authority what its options are and what their
economic impact would be and Shaheen will run for reelection on a
proposal of her own.
</P>
<P>
   My money's on the guv. But before this becomes purely a state
matter, it's worth noting that the judgment of national party
leaders, including Clinton and Gore, was that her character and
record had prepared her for national office. They were right.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-00 1309EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
