<DOCNO> NYT20000424.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5562 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-SEX-PISTOLS-HNS &LR;      04-24 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEX-PISTOLS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE BRITISH GROUP THAT HELPED CHANGE THE WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CRAIG MARINE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Even if you hate the Sex Pistols, even if punk
rock turns your stomach and you wouldn't pierce a body part for all
the stock options in the Silicon Valley, you might consider seeing
``The Filth and the Fury,'' director Julien Temple's documentary on
the seminal English band.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Sex Pistols changed your life, whether you know it
or not. Once the Sex Pistols roared through the public
consciousness like a runaway freight train destined for the
inevitable nasty ending, the world could never return to its former
bloated, passive ways.
</P>
<P>
   Try this on for size: all of you jokers who made hundreds of
thousands of dollars on stocks this year should send the Sex
Pistols a thank you note, at least the ones that are still alive.
(As for those of you who hung on a tad too long and lost the farm,
well . . . blame disco.)
</P>
<P>
   The easiest way to explain this far-from-radical premise is with
a bit of historical comparison. Here we are back in the 1400s, and
since there were no BMW engines to hone to absolute, minute
perfection, Johann Gutenberg turned his inbred anal tendencies
toward another time-consuming task.
</P>
<P>
   Gutenberg is credited with being the first European to print
with movable type. Wait, don't turn to the comics yet. Johann
rocked his world because movable type meant you could print things
on the cheap. Previously, if you wanted to print a book, every page
had to be carved out of wood _ it was cheaper to write books out by
hand.
</P>
<P>
   So Gutenberg has his type, starts churning out Bibles, and the
next thing you know, everyone is reading their own Bibles, which
means they are making their own interpretations of God's word,
which means the Church has a significant loss of influence among
the populace, since the clergy can no longer hand down
proclamations based upon exclusive knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Bingo _ a less docile populace, a massive questioning of
established authority and the next thing you know, Lou Reed is
going to play for the Pope on May Day 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward from the 15th century to the bloated 1970s:
Emerson, Lake and Palmer are actually selling records and filling
stadiums with tedious re-arrangements of classical riffs the public
is too ignorant to recognize. The world of rock music is, on the
whole, dominated by overproduced, soulless arena bands. Kansas,
Styx _ it's too painful to remember.
</P>
<P>
   Out of England comes this incredibly angry sound, the apparent
humor in the lyrics not enough to mask the raw rage at a political
system with a boot on the throat of the common man. Musically, it's
three chords cranked to 10 on the amplifier and a singer who loses
whatever melody a song might contain in his need to shout out his
message at the top of his lungs.
</P>
<P>
   Visually, the Pistols proudly display their refusal to join the
mainstream _ it appears they consider a bath or a washing machine a
political compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Rebellion is back in rock 'n' roll. And, as with Gutenberg's
contribution, the Sex Pistols once again get people to begin
questioning authority. The '60s were passive. Buffalo Springfield's
``For What it's Worth,'' passed for revolutionary music, even
though its central message, ``Something's happening here, what it
is ain't exactly clear,'' is inherently foggy.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the Pistols have no confusion whatsoever: ``Don't
know what I want, but I know how to get it.''
</P>
<P>
   This message, combined with the fact that as musicians they bit
the big tamale, was all it took. The sheep shook off whatever it is
that sheep would shake off when they stopped being sheep.
</P>
<P>
   Instantly, people started doing, instead of watching. Who says
they have to be good to form a band? Who cares? Do it anyway.
</P>
<P>
   And therein lies the revolution. Everywhere, people began taking
risks. The pervasive attitude became one of action. This
infiltrated society as a whole, as revolutions tend to do, and next
thing you know, every geek with a pocket protector is starting a
company, Apple (founded in 1976, the same year the Pistols started
rocking Britain) takes off, and kaboom! NASDAQ goes through the
roof, you're driving a Saab (badly, with a cell phone) and
listening to crap on your CD player.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Filth and the Fury'' is great at setting the band within
its era, even if it spends a little too much time on the whinefest
over whether manager Malcolm McLaren or Johnny Rotten deserves more
credit for the band's impact.
</P>
<P>
   Rotten, real name John Lydon, with his legit working-class
credentials lending credibility to his role as the group's chief
lyricist, always has a way of keeping things in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Malcolm was a wanker who knew how to stir up a load of s. and
had zero idea on how to deal with things once they came down,''
Rotten said in a recent interview. ``He thought all press was good
press, when all that did was make it impossible for us to ever be
heard. I liked infusing our songs with humor _ it's a British
working-class way of dealing with abject poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the anger and refusal to ignore the obvious misery anymore
was also real. I was never able to spend any time on that part of
what we were saying, because if we did any interviews at all, they
were inevitably confrontational from the start. And I was never one
to take any guff from anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Take his word for it. After all, he did change your world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
