<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5573 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CUBA-BOY-BOS &LR;      04-24 1537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-BOY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIAMI RELATIVES OF ELIAN GONZALEZ TAKE BATTLE TO WASHINGTON
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Irate Republicans joined Elian Gonzalez's Miami
relatives Sunday in accusing federal authorities of lying, breaking
the law, and collaborating with Cuban President Fidel Castro, as an
already divisive controversy began expanding into a wider and more
vituperative dispute.
</P>
<P>
   US officials adamantly denied every allegation and suggested
that Elian's relatives were the ones distorting the truth. The
officials insisted that, after months of unrewarded patience and
fruitless negotiations, they'd been left with no choice but to send
armed Immigration and Naturalization Service agents to gain custody
of the 6-year-old boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened Sunday was not the rule of law. . . It was an
abuse of power, and it was a violent abuse of power,'' said
Republican Senator Bob Smith of New Hampshire. He sponsored a news
conference on Capitol Hill at which anguished members of the
Florida branch of the Gonzalez family and their supporters called
Attorney General Janet Reno a liar, portrayed President Clinton as
a draft-dodging flag-burner, and questioned whether the government
had altered photographs to make it appear that Elian was happy to
be reunited with his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``An enforcement action like this is a frightening event,'' INS
Commissioner Doris Meissner acknowledged on CBS's ``Face the
Nation.'' But she added, ``This was a last resort.'' Deputy
Attorney General Eric Holder, appearing on NBC's ``Meet the
Press,'' said every effort was made to reach an agreement with the
Miami relatives but ``they would agree to nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Advocates on all sides of the issue flooded the television news
programs on Easter, alternately leveling angry accusations and
defending themselves, as Elian and his father spent a second quiet
day together in guest quarters at Andrews Air Force Base outside
Washington, D.C. As they had a day earlier, the Miami family tried
to enter the air force base Sunday to see the boy or arrange a
meeting with the father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, but they were again
denied entry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally they have some time together, some space together,
some privacy together, some silence around them so that the circus
atmosphere and that environment down in Miami (are) no longer
inflicted upon this boy,'' said Gregory Craig, the father's
attorney, on NBC's ``Meet the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of Elian's forced removal from his great-uncle's
home, months of debate about whether he should remain in this
country were rapidly supplanted by scathing personal attacks _
mainly by GOP members of Congress, but also by some Democrats _
against Reno and Clinton. The critics contended that US officials
had not bargained in good faith to peacefully transfer the child to
his father, and that the INS had used excessive force.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders asked for congressional investigations of the
matter, regardless of what happens in the courts or between the
Gonzalez family in Florida and Juan Miguel Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a frightening event, that American citizens now can
expect that the executive branch on their own can decide on whether
to raid a home,'' said the third-ranking leader in the House, GOP
whip Tom DeLay of Texas. DeLay, who said he was ``sickened'' by the
raid, implied that the INS had broken the law because he said it
hadn't gotten a court order for the raid.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department and INS officials explicitly denied that
allegation. The officials cited several agency and judicial
authorizations, and said they had obtained a search warrant as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Several senior Republican leaders lambasted the Clinton
administration for Elian's seizure, and some _ along with members
of the Miami family _ asserted that Reno and the president, perhaps
operating through Craig, were deliberately taking sides with
Castro.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Republicans who spoke out were majority leader Trent
Lott of Mississippi, Judiciary Committee chairman Orrin Hatch of
Utah, and the party's presumptive presidential nominee, Texas
Governor George W. Bush. Lott said that when he learned of the
armed operation in Little Havana, ``my first thought was that this
could only happen in Castro's Cuba.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Bob Graham of Florida, a Democrat sometimes mentioned as
a possible vice presidential prospect, said Clinton had promised
him personally that Elian would not be taken in the nighttime.
Graham said on ABC's ``This Week'' that he didn't know whether the
president had been aware that subordinates were breaking that
commitment, but Graham clearly sounded upset by the government's
actions _ especially by what he described as the ``excessive
force'' employed to take the boy and by the ``insensitivity'' of
carrying out the operation during Easter weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Even as bad reviews like those seemed likely to extend the
drama's life on the political stage, lawyers for Elian's Miami
relatives indicated that his treatment may also generate additional
and potentially lengthy legal battles.
</P>
<P>
   The attorneys said they would not only fight during already
scheduled judicial proceedings to keep the boy in the United
States, but also were considering filing suit against the federal
government for the aggressive way in which the child was taken.
</P>
<P>
   Several supporters of the Miami relatives said the federal
authorities didn't abide by legal procedures for such a raid, such
as knocking first and identifying themselves clearly. US officials
strongly denied that, maintaining that every aspect of the
operation had gone by the book.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most damning accusations were that the agents pointed
their rifles at people in the house and threatened to shoot them if
they didn't cooperate, and that the pictures distributed Saturday
of Elian smiling broadly next to his father had somehow been
altered. The critics also continued to deride the government's
explanation for an armed assault _ that it had received reports
that people in or outside the house may have had weapons _ saying
there was no evidence to support that.
</P>
<P>
   Meissner, among others, categorically rejected the assertions
about the pointed rifles and the phony photographs, and said the
INS would have been derelict to send unarmed forces into a
potentially explosive situation.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reality, the vastly differing pictures painted by
the two sides demonstrated just how far apart they remain about
virtually every aspect of the controversy. As many people continued
to suggest Sunday that Elian would benefit if his feuding family
members could get together to smooth the transition for him, the
degree of rancor between the two sides made it difficult to see how
that could happen anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Miguel Gonzalez, who was described as angry and upset with
his Miami relatives, refused to meet with them or to permit them to
see his son. And his cousin, Marisleysis Gonzalez, who continues to
depict herself as Elian's surrogate mother, lashed out at Juan
Miguel during the family's news conference on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Donato Dalrymple, the fisherman who rescued Elian from the sea
five months ago _ and who, in the photo that has come to define the
raid in Little Miami, is seen clutching the boy as an INS agent
points his rifle in their direction _ offered a scathing
description of Clinton during the same news conference. Saying his
own father had fought in World War II and Korea, Dalrymple added,
sobbing: ``You, Mr. President, burned the flag.''
</P>
<P>
   Other family members and one of their attorneys also spoke at
the event. But Marisleysis, clearly angry and distraught, dominated
it with an angry description of what she said had happened Saturday
morning and with personal attacks on the people she deemed
responsible.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing Reno and apparently alluding to the fact that the
attorney general has never been married, the 21-year-old woman
said, ``You still don't know what being a mother is.''
</P>
<P>
   Marisleysis Gonzalez, who said an INS agent had held a rifle to
her chest and threated to kill her, wept as she maintained that
``Elian cannot be without me'' and pleaded for public condemnation
of Saturday's action.
</P>
<P>
   At least in the raid's immediate aftermath, however, most
Americans appeared to support the government. A poll conducted
Saturday and released Sunday by Cable News Network and the Gallup
Organization showed that respondents approved of Elian's physical
removal from his relatives' home by 57 to 37 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-nine percent said that the boy should return to Cuba with
his father, while 27 percent replied that he should remain with his
relatives in this country. And 54 percent said the government had
done all it could to resolve the dispute without using force,
compared to 30 percent who disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   While all those statistics presumably pleased US officials, one
other result indicated critics may win some support: Just 36
percent said federal authorities used the right amount of force to
get Elian, while 40 percent answered ``too much.'' The telephone
survey of 613 adults had a margin of error of plus or minus 4
percentage points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-00 1314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
