<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5580 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-YOYO-MA-BOS &LR;      04-24 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-YOYO-MA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MA TAKES A NEW `APPALACHIAN JOURNEY' FOR YOUNG AUDIENCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every record Yo-Yo Ma makes is a bestseller, but some of them
sell better than others. One of his greatest hits is ``Appalachia
Waltz,'' which Sony Classical released five years ago. Now the
cellist has followed it up with a sequel, joining fiddler Mark
O'Connor and bassist Edgar Meyer again for ``Appalachian Journey.''
</P>
<P>
   The first live performance of ``Appalachia Waltz'' was at a
benefit concert for Young Audiences of Massachusetts in 1995 _ the
concert took place prior to the recording sessions. Now Ma,
O'Connor, and Meyer perform ``Appalachian Journey'' at another
benefit for Young Audiences _ the 11th benefit in Cambridge, Mass.
he has played for the organization since 1988, and, for the time
being, the last.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent phone conversation, Ma said, ``In terms of
regularity, this will be my last Young Audiences benefit for a
while, but in terms of my heart, Young Audiences will always be
there. Over the last dozen years Young Audiences has grown so much
_ when I started playing these benefits, the budget was about
$300,000, but now, this year, it is up to $1 million. Young
Audiences programs reach 50,000 kids every year, in 600 schools in
every part of the state; the organization puts on more than 2,400
music, dance, and theater programs a year. There were only 900
programs when I started.''
</P>
<P>
   Ma first heard of Young Audiences when he was a student at
Harvard and living in Leverett House. Later Ma's wife, Jill Horner,
joined the board of Young Audiences. ``She's been the person who
has led the effort in terms of my participation,'' he explains.
</P>
<P>
   Ma has always tried to do something unsual for the benefit
concert. He has appeared in recitals with pianists Judith Gordon
and Peter Serkin. He has played with vocalist Bobby McFerrin;
violinists Pamela Frank, Joseph Swenson, Lynn Chang, and Lucy
Stoltzman; the Amaryllis String Quartet and members of the Orion
String Quartet; clarinetist Richard Stoltzman; and the New
York-Buenos Aires Connection in a collaboration on a tango program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a kind of history of my seminal friendships,'' Ma
says of these concerts. ``For example, I admired Peter Serkin for
years and years but never dared to talk to him, there on his own
mountain, so our Young Audiences benefit was our first concert
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Ma sounds particularly happy to be rounding things off with Mark
O'Connor and Edgar Meyer again. ``I remember after our last concert
of the `Appalachia Waltz' tour _ it was at Cornell University in
Ithaca, New York _ and we all absolutely felt we would like to try
to do something else together. So here we are again. The way Mark
talks about it, he says, when we first got together we were three
voices, and now there are four voices _ we've added the voice of
the group. We feel secure enough about working together to have the
nerve to invite some of our other friends to participate, so James
Taylor and Alison Krauss appear on the album with us.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a special focus to the album, a family focus. ``James
wrote a piece called `Benjamin' for his son, which we all loved. So
Mark wrote a piece for Emily, my daughter, and Edgar wrote a piece
for his son George, and then Alison wrote a slumber song. There's a
subtheme of family on the album which is completely appropriate for
Young Audiences. Family is what all of us believe in.''
</P>
<P>
   Ma's own children are growing up _ his son Nicholas is 16 (``Can
you believe it?'') and Emily is 14, and both are away at school.
``We've found the right place for each of them for their particular
interests and characters,'' Ma says, ``and it all seems to be
working. But it's so sad to be getting towards the time when they
will be leaving home for good.''
</P>
<P>
   Ma's other projects include his collaboration with the composer
Bright Sheng to explore the music of the ``Silk Road,'' the
historic trade route than ran between the Roman Empire and China.
``Tanglewood has been very generous in providing us with space, and
at the end of June and the beginning of July we will have a lot of
composers from Mongolia, Central Asia _ all the way west to
Lebanon. We have commissioned about 16 pieces and the composers are
coming. We will rehearse the music that has come in and see where
we're going to go with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ma has completed a second baroque album with Ton
Koopman, and he would very much like to record the ``Goldberg''
variations by contemporary composers that he played at his Symphony
Hall concert earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, even a superstar like Ma has been affected by the
crisis in the record industry. ``Now all the companies are global,
which in some ways is more effective, and in other ways less
effective. I've always thought it would be great to be able to do
more things locally, to inform people about the wonderful things
that happen right here, but I've never gotten a positive answer.
`It won't work,' I'm always told, but I'm still very up for ideas
on how to do things that should be done locally. It would be
wonderful to show that something like this could work. Obviously
some things you do nationally and internationally, that's the
nature of the beast, but it would be better if we could do other
things in other ways, so that the music could speak the way it
should, so it can find its own right level.''
</P>
<P>
   Ma is very conscious of his dual life as an international artist
and a local resident. He loves traveling (``I am doing what I
believe in, and I love being a guest in other communities; somehow
it works'') but he also loves community and community building.
``I've been talking with the stage director Peter Sellars a lot
lately about what he's doing in Adelaide, Australia, and I'm
learning a lot about what it takes to build community from those
conversations. What I admire about Peter is that he talks things
through, and then he goes and does it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ma has supported Young Audiences through benefits that raise
money for its activities. But he has also worked more directly and
actively with young people. ``I'm really proud of the little bit I
did with `Mr. Rogers' and `Sesame Street.' Kids see a five-minute
thing in a world that belongs to them; you are a guest in their
world. But somehow it connects. They bug their parents about
playing an instrument until their parents relent _ often the
parents have no idea where this is coming from. And then the kids
will go through hoops to get to a concert and then line up
afterwards for an autograph because they want another kind of
connection with this world. Music has touched their special,
personal world in a private, direct, and fascinating way.''
</P>
<P>
   As Ma ends this string of benefit concerts, Horner is leaving
the board of Young Audiences. ``They have a fabulous person running
the organization now in Harold Berman,'' Ma says, ``and under his
leadership it has grown tremendously. They're in great shape, so
this seems a good moment to hand things over. That's what it's all
about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
