<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5581 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-PISTOLS-BOS &LR;      04-24 1476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-PISTOLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESHOOTING THE SEX PISTOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How many filmmakers get to revisit their past by doing a second
movie about the same subject?
</P>
<P>
   British director Julien Temple, 45, didn't plan it this way.
Twenty-one years ago, he directed the Sex Pistols
pseudo-documentary ``The Great Rock 'n' Roll Swindle,'' a project
shepherded by the band's former manager Malcolm McLaren and made
without the active participation of the band members, who had split
up the previous year. Temple is back now with ``The Filth and the
Fury,'' a Pistols documentary told from the surviving members'
point of view, with singer Johnny Rotten (ne John Lydon) and
guitarist Steve Jones serving as prime narrators.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a sudden, kind-of, `My God, we've got to make
another film about the Sex Pistols!''' says Temple, though he
admits ``it is a strange thing to do. You're not really meantto
film that same subject again. Other people are supposed to do the
remake. But, in some ways, what you're not meant to do is often the
best thing to do, as it turns out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Filth and The Fury'' is a trip through the time tunnel, a
quick jolt back to 1976-77, when punk rock raged in England and the
Sex Pistols were its most notorious purveyors, the wiliest of
antagonists as devil-may-care court jesters. Plus _ and this is at
the root of it all _ they wrote snarling, hook-packed songs that
captured the ethos of desperation and disillusionment among British
working-class youth at the time. They seized the day; they seized
the zeitgest.
</P>
<P>
   Why go back?
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly wasn't banging on doors trying to get the film
made,'' says Temple. ``It was a chance meeting with John Lydon at a
restaurant in LA that opened the way for me working with him again.
This was back in the early '90s.''
</P>
<P>
   They rebonded, agreed to do the documentary. Lydon, who hates
McLaren (and won a lawsuit against him in the '90s, regaining Sex
Pistols rights and royalties), loathed ``Swindle,'' just as he
detested Alex Cox's ``Sid &AMP; Nancy.'' He believed the latter film
glorified Vicious's drug abuse and the former was a conceit of
McLaren's massive ego and self-serving imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Temple has a different twist. `` `The Great Rock 'n' Roll
Swindle' was a very deliberate and provocative film,'' he says,
from his home in Somerset, England. ``It was designed to annoy and
confuse the fans who had become total idol worshippers of the Sex
Pistols in the way people had worshipped Rod Stewart in the early
'70s.'' The film presented the Pistols as a McLaren creation with
him as a master puppeteer cagily staging one uproar after another,
the better of which to play into the pliable media's hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The `Swindle,' '' says Temple, was ``something to deflate the
aura of pop stardom . . . unlike most pop films commissioned by
bands, `A Hard Day's Night' or whatever, where they're basically
selling lovable teddy bears. With all the mythologizing that's gone
on about the Pistols, in some circles it's been taken as a kind of
literal, truthful presentation of the situation, which it was never
meant to be. This is a truer film, but it doesn't replace the other
film. It complements it.''
</P>
<P>
   Temple realized there were many reels of unseen live footage
housed in a huge London film warehouse called the Vault. He
excavated them, he says; they weren't on a shelf but ``in a corner
on the floor, film canisters spilling film out.'' Somehow, this is
metaphorically appropriate. Initially, he wasn't sure what kind of
footage he needed to make the documentary, but then he realized he
had more than he needed, including scenes shot on the streets of
London. Temple weaves the band and its music into the tapestry of
'70s social upheaval, in a country with high unemployment among
youth about to celebrate its Silver Jubilee. In capturing that mood
and presenting the Sex Pistols as reflective of it, Temple sees the
film as ``not really a documentary, as it is more an architect's
film.'' It's not, he says, a broad look at punk _ its history, its
competing bands and fractious relationships. ``It's produced by
(the Pistols) and made by myself and it's very much from within.
The text is not trying to be a kind of `objective' TV-style
documentary where you get all the opposing guys and a lot of
talking heads who agree to differ, and you somehow make things
reach `the truth.' ''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Rotten says he participated in the film because
the production company, England's FilmFour, ``gave us the freedom
to tell the Sex Pistols story as it really was. It's the band's
chance to set the record straight. We don't praise ourselves or wax
lyrical about our influence. We just tell the truth. For the last
20 years, people have exaggerated and blown up the Sex Pistols into
something they never were. I think the truth is far more shocking
and more interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With their first two singles, ``Anarchy in the UK'' and ``God
Save the Queen,'' the Pistols showed they possessed an aura of
nihilism. ``Your future dream is a sharpie's scheme!'' railed
Rotten in ``Anachy in the UK.'' But what was _ and still is _
misunderstood is their humor, their celebration of life in all its
squalor. ``The Filth and the Fury'' brings that to the mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the nihilism is really a weapon to point out such
things,'' says Temple. ``You can't remove the politics and the
attitudes and ideas that came from that band from the music. If the
music had been no good, it wouldn't have worked at all.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a productive, dysfunctional marriage _ bassist-songwriter
Glen Matlock's melodic craftsmanship, Jones's rudimentary guitar
skills but ferocious attack, Cook's rock-ribbed solidity, and
Rotten's lyrical genius, scabrous vocal style, and electifying
stage presence. All in all, the Pistols were provocative and
volatile, and all this comes across on screen.
</P>
<P>
   What is rather shadowy are the Pistols themselves _ that is, the
fortysomething former Pistols. They are shot in silhouette. ``It
was to spare the world any more wrinkly old rock stars in
armchairs,'' says the director. ``I can't think of a more boring
and overcooked image, the old rock star reminiscing about the good
old days. I also had some kind of Witness Protection Program idea
in there. But most importantly, I think by removing another kind of
mediation, you can take the audience there more directly.'' And
that allows, at some level, for the band to remain forever young.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Matlock was sacked, Vicious, a good friend of Rotten's,
joined the band despite his inability to play bass. He was given
his moniker as an ironic jest. (The man born John Simon Ritchie was
weedy and weak.) But the ante for outrage was upped. Vicious, for
instance, would sport a T-shirt bearing a swastika. ``It was the
pure element of shock,'' worn to get a rise, not to promote Nazism,
says Temple.
</P>
<P>
   For all of Vicious's notoriety, says Temple, ``I think if people
met Sid, they'd be very fond of him. He was a very engaging
character, a real presence. He was young and pushing it to the
edge, but he was a far more witty, funny, intelligent guy'' than
people think.
</P>
<P>
   But Temple uses an infamous interview clip from the Sex
Pistols-on-tour movie, ``D.O.A.,'' that features a drugged Vicious
nodding out and his sycophantic girlfriend Nancy Spungen (whom
Vicious was later accused of murdering) poking and taunting him.
``When he became a junkie, he became a huge junkie,'' says Temple.
``It's not a happy thing to witness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about this film is it's about people who went
through this kind of media chemotherapy, and only three of them
(Rotten, Jones, Cook) got out and the three that got out are still
very scarred by it. I think it probably has defined every minute of
the rest of their lives.'' Temple says he puts the number at three
because Matlock was booted midway through and essentially ``backed
out.'' (Matlock did, however, join the Pistols on a 1996 reunion
tour.)
</P>
<P>
   Temple has not been inactive between Pistols documentaries. He
has directed music videos and British TV projects. In feature
films, he helmed 1985's ``Absolute Beginners'' and ``Earth Girls
Are Easy'' in 1988, a comedy starring then-unknowns Jim Carrey and
Geena Davis. His ``Vigo,'' a love story inspired by the '20s French
film director Jean Vigo, is awaiting US distribution. For the BBC
he is wrapping up ``Pandemonium,' a film starring Robert Carlyle
(``Trainspotting,'' ``Angela's Ashes''), based on the friendship
between 18th-century poets Samuel Taylor Coleridge and William
Wordsworth. A period piece. Sound a bit high-brow? Temple laughs.
No, he says, the relationship between the two was just as
contentious as anything between the Sex Pistols.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
