<HEADER>
A5585 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS &LR;      04-24 0477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
 
!!! 1/2 ``Croupier'' An absorbing, unpredictable little minefield
of a crime movie from Britain. Clive Owens's slightly sinister
croupier wants to just cut the cards and stay cool, but is drawn
into the expectations of a couple of women he meets while dodging
his con-man dad. (Unrated) 
 
!!! ``East Is East'' Om Puri sputters entertainingly as a Pakistani
dad trying to keep the lid on his seven kids in a Manchester
suburb. Unable to see that they're just replicating his own
youthful rebellion, he's left wondering why they insist on eating
skillets of pork and chasing English girls at discos instead of
hanging out at the mosque. (R) 
 
!!! 1/2 ``The Filth and the Fury'' Director Julien Temple's second
Sex Pistols rockumentary is presented from the band's point of
view, not from the manipulative manager's, as was 1980's ``The
Great Rock 'n' Roll Swindle.'' Temple links the social upheavel of
England in 1976-77 to the Pistols' vitriolic and nihilistic punk
rock; he also depicts the joy of sticking it to the establishment,
be it media, government, or the music biz. Temple captures the buzz
of a time before rage was codified _ and the music mattered.
(Unrated) (Jim Sullivan) 
 
!!! 1/2 ``Love &AMP; Basketball'' A breakthrough film about a woman
basketball player and a breakout performance by Sanaa Lathen as a
spirited player who wonders why she can't shoot for the same career
as her neighbor and love interest, Omar Epps. Both are warm and
appealing and you root for them to make it work in this film that
attaches as much importance to hearts as to hoops. (PG-13) 
 
!! ``Me Myself I'' A lightweight vehicle driven to watchability by
Australia's Rachel Griffiths in a dual role when her career woman
worried about missing the personal-fulfillment boat finds herself
plunked into the marriage she regretted not having entered into 13
years ago. (R) 
 
! 1/2 ``Gossip'' James Marsden, Lena Headey, and Norman Reedus play
college roommates who spark a nasty rumor as an academic exercise,
with disastrous results. Yet another
jaded-20-somethings-behaving-badly film with a contrived plot and
hunks and dolls masquerading as characters, ``Gossip'' offers
nothing more than the average daytime soap opera except its
pretensions. (R) (Loren King) 
 
!! 1/2 ``U-571'' A slick action-packed throwback to World War II
submarine thrillers that comes up short on character definition and
relies inordinately on the Germans' bad aim. They never hit the
endangered sub with their torpedoes or depth charges, while we
never miss. But the film's technical experts, many of whom worked
on ``Das Boot,'' are in great form, and Jonathan Mostow's
jackhammer pacing keeps us from dwelling on the flaws. (PG-13) 
 

