<HEADER>
A5589 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-BELLOW-BOS &LR;      04-24 1200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-BELLOW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RAVELSTEIN' IS LESS A NOVEL THAN A PORTRAIT OF FRIENDSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
RAVELSTEIN 
By Saul Bellow 
Viking Penguin. 233 pp. $24.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saul Bellow's crankish, indomitable wit has never bothered to
wear much camouflage in his fiction. Most of his protagonists are
antiheroes whose alienation is part of their survival package: Cast
out by the piety of former wives or the idiocies of mainstream
(often gentile) culture, they savor their triumphs not in spite of
their disaffection, but because of it. Born of modernity and
eternally suffering within it, Bellow's dangling man would scarcely
know what to do with his feet on terra firma.
</P>
<P>
   Bellow's long and vast affection for the social theorist Allan
Bloom, who died in 1992 at age 62, fits well within this model of
discontent. Colleagues at the University of Chicago, the novelist
and the political philosopher were finely matched _ each in his own
way breathtakingly intelligent and wickedly unruly in a cerebral
street fight. Though Bloom was younger than Bellow by two decades,
he played mentor to his elder when it came to ancient Greece,
contemporary politics, or the mating rites of shared acquaintances.
He urged Bellow to train his intellectual sights on biography;
Bellow, in turn, urged Bloom to popularize his round-table
teachings. The result was Bloom's 1987 bestseller, ``The Closing of
the American Mind,'' which sought to pinpoint an intellectual
crisis in American culture without ever getting winded. For sheer
Renaissance-man chutzpah, it is little wonder that either fellow so
admired the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ravelstein'' is Bellow's fictionalized homage to Bloom and to
their friendship; it is also being touted as the first full-fledged
novel Bellow has given us in more than a decade. But ``Ravelstein''
is hardly a novel, at least in the sense that Bellow himself has
defined the form over the past half-century. It is instead a
loosely woven portrait, sometimes pleasant and sometimes
irritating, of an intellectual wild man whom Bellow loved. The
names have been changed _ the dying professor is Abe Ravelstein;
the author-biographer telling his story is a writer called Chick _
which I suppose qualifies the work as a roman a clef. That, of
course, is often a Frenchified way of labeling gossip as
literature, which Bloom would be the first to point out.
</P>
<P>
   The character of Ravelstein, a man huge in size and appetite, is
someone whose charms and eccentricities are certainly worthy of
record: At a colossal 6 feet 6 inches, he dresses in $5,000 suits,
shaves his immense head, brings adoring students over to his
art-drenched apartment to partake of pizza and the Chicago Bulls or
Maria Callas. HIV-positive and entering the realm of physical
decline, he falls prey to one infection after another, then brings
his great bulk back into fighting position and flies off to France.
He chain-smokes in front of his doctors, fusses over buying a new
$80,000 BMW for his partner, Nikki, operates a phone system of
command central through which Paris, New York, and Washington,
D.C., check in several times a day. (Most of these calls are from
Ravelstein's former students, who are now running the world.
Reporting in on the Gulf War or myriad shenanigans on Capitol Hill,
they're more likely to quote Machiavelli or Shakespeare than they
are Deep Throat.)
</P>
<P>
   He loves rumors as well as Platonic truths, in other words, and
his immense presence _ his mind, his attitudes, his hubris _ has
clearly dazzled the friend who seeks to deliver Ravelstein beyond
the grave. ``There were two people in Paris who knew him
intimately,'' Chick tells us, ``And three on this side of the
Atlantic. I was one of them.'' And so he must play Boswell to
Ravelstein's Johnson: Ravelstein has asked him to tell his story
after he is gone. (The professor's expressed altruistic motives,
which range from providing Chick with an intellectual purpose to
liberating him from the abyss, seem less clear than Ravelstein's
wish to be remembered.) In fulfilling his duties, Chick has
wandered through the fields of memory where both men walked: the
rigorous intellectual debates they shared (about God, Jewishness, a
moral life); the oddball neighbors and friends and even enemies
they had in common. And for all his cool analytic powers,
Ravelstein also emerges as a man whose intuition is precise in
matters of the heart. He sees through the pastoral glaze of
hypocrisy coating Chick's marriage to a chaos physicist, Vela, long
before Chick himself is ready to give up those illusions. When
Chick marries the kinder, younger Rosamund, one of Ravelstein's
former students, the professor is begrudging only because he didn't
have the sense to see it coming.
</P>
<P>
   By simple force of its unfettered devotion, many elements of
``Ravelstein'' are touching, and Bellow's raw intelligence is
always worth following through many a thicket and bramble. But the
unfortunate fact of this book is that much of the thundering beauty
of Bellow's voice is missing. In assuming the ironic-acolyte
position of Chick to Ravelstein, he has eclipsed his own narrative
skills and authorial presence, delivering instead a story that is
too often rambling, repetitive, and, God help us, dull.
</P>
<P>
   Things perk up considerably when the ramblings revert back to
the narrator's story. After Ravelstein's death, Chick and Rosamund
decide to leave behind their mournful Chicago neighborhood for a
new chapter of life in New England. Relocated from Midwest to East,
they head to Saint Martin for vacation, where Chick ingests a cigua
toxin from infected fish that nearly kills him. The last portion of
``Ravelstein'' (which also mirrors Bellow's life) follows this
frightening, sometimes hallucinatory journey through illness and
airports and the ICU. Hovering throughout is that Bellovian
consciousness that sees the jokes in religious belief and the
spiritual essence of humor; alongside him is the character of
Rosamund, who _ saintly and sensible at once _ nearly manages to
steal the show from the two men this book is purportedly about.
</P>
<P>
   This is hardly the first time Bellow has infused fiction with
facts from his own life; one of his great novels, ``Humboldt's
Gifts,'' is drawn from the life of the poet Delmore Schwartz. But
there he usurped a piece of real life and transformed it; in
``Ravelstein,'' the symphonic possibility that ought to govern the
story within is rarely in sight. At one moment, Chick explains
something about himself to Rosamund _ about how he struggled with
the problem of grasping a particularly unpleasant truth about
someone he knew.
</P>
<P>
   ``You didn't know where to begin?'' she asks him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I had a Jewish life to lead in the American language,''
he tells her, ``and that's not a language that's helpful with dark
thoughts.''
</P>
<P>
   Those brief words are pure Bellow: confident, laconic, and
elegant, hinting at something of great dimension. However heartfelt
and elegiac, ``Ravelstein'' may recall such Bellovian depths, but
rarely ventures there itself.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Gail Caldwell is chief book critic of The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
