<HEADER>
A5592 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-DUMB-BOS &LR;      04-24 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-DUMB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS ACCOUNT OF DAY TRADING HITS BULL'S-EYE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
DUMB MONEY: Adventures of A Day Trader. 
By Joey Anuff and Gary Wolf. 
Random House. 219 pp. $23.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joey Anuff was already a card-carrying member of the Internet
community when the revelation hit him. ``Thousands of unremarkable
people have already become ultra-rich. Last year I finally woke up
to the big question: Why not me?''
</P>
<P>
   And with that, Anuff began his career as a day trader. ``Dumb
Money,'' is a short, generally enjoyable account of his experience,
written with Gary Wolf. Anuff didn't get ultra-rich. He was only
modestly successful. But he is an ideal guide for a journey through
the world of day trading. He is smart, funny, cynical, and doesn't
take anything too seriously, including himself.
</P>
<P>
   Day trading, we quickly learn, has little in common with
investing. Day traders frequently have no information about the
companies in which they invest. Anuff got annual reports in the
mail and never opened them. Why do research on a company you may
own for a few minutes?
</P>
<P>
   The key in this field is speed. You want to jump into a stock on
its way up or down _ it doesn't matter which _ and then jump out
again before the direction changes. It comes as no surprise to find
out that video-game players and airline pilots do well in this
business.
</P>
<P>
   There is some method to the madness. Like other shrewd
investors, Anuff quickly recognizes that Wall Street often
overreacts to news, especially bad news. If Company A reports
disappointing earnings, Wall Street may punish the stock
unmercifully, then have a change of heart and correct its mistake.
A skillful trader can anticipate that pattern and make some money .
</P>
<P>
   Experience also teaches Anuff that when positive news gets
reported on CNBC, the all-day business television network, the
stock in question gets a brief bounce. A good trader can buy the
stock when the news first gets reported over the wires, wait for
CNBC to announce it, and make a buck or two before the momentum
fades. ``My goal is to beat the crowd by a few seconds,'' writes
Anuff.
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by a few good trades and a successful investment in eBay,
the online auction house, Anuff begins to think he has the right
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   The feeling doesn't last long. The second half of the book is a
tale of disillusionment that reads like a love affair gone sour.
Anuff, wearing his journalist's hat, goes out to meet some of the
superstars of the day-trading world, people whose legendary skills
are celebrated on a variety of cyber-bulletin boards.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these heroes are quite impressive, but Anuff becomes
suspicious when he learns that most of them actually earn their
living teaching other people how to become day traders. He writes
of Anthony, one of the stars: ``Anthony has discovered that the
best business in the bull market is helping other people get into
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Anuff's bubble deflates even further when he reads the history
of some of the great debacles in investment history like the Great
Crash of 1929 or the South Sea Bubble. The lessons of history are
irrefutable: In good times even dummies can make money; in bad
times, even smart investors get wiped out.
</P>
<P>
   ``A circus chimp could have doubled his money buying the stocks
I was playing,'' Anuff ruefully concludes.
</P>
<P>
   Even Anuff's one great coup _ his investment in eBay _ turns out
not to have anything to do with day trading at all. Like Fidelity's
Peter Lynch, who advised investors to buy what they know, Anuff
buys eBay stock because he uses the site and recognizes that it has
great potential. A smart investor could have had the same insight
about the automobile or Wal-Mart. The Internet generation didn't
invent intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dumb Money'' has a few slow spots. Day trading involves a lot
of technology, and Anuff tells you more than you want to know about
the mechanics of the business. At times, you may feel that you are
plowing through an owner's manual.
</P>
<P>
   At its best, however, the book nicely captures the intensity _
and ultimately the insanity _ of day trading. ``Dumb Money'' should
be required reading for anyone contemplating a career in this
field. Like those grisly prison movies they show to juvenile
delinquents, it should have the effect of scaring off those who
think day trading represents a risk-free, effort-free path to
success.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to stop dreaming about getting rich. Just don't
assume you are going to get there as a day trader.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
