<HEADER>
A5614 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-CANCER-SCAM-BOS &LR;      04-24 1639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-SCAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRAUD CHARGED IN CANCER CURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WOBURN, Mass. _ The nondescript warehouse is a sports supply
store now, but it was in the front lines in the mid-1990s for a
bizarre chapter in the war against cancer, a place where federal
investigators say life-saving research mingled freely with consumer
fraud.
</P>
<P>
   From here, the fledgling Private Biologicals Corp. shipped a
promising new cancer drug called LK-200 to doctors and patients in
Mexico, the Bahamas, and the United States. Independent researchers
were excited about LK-200's prospects because in some cases it
shrank tumors by boosting the body's own defenses without causing
severe toxic reactions.
</P>
<P>
   But the career of LK-200 ended abruptly in 1995 when federal
agents raided the plant in a small industrial park and shut it
down. Private Biologicals ran an elaborate scam to rip off
investors, they contended, through a company run by a phony doctor
and employing an offshore address to evade federal regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Now, five years later, US Attorney Donald K. Stern has filed
criminal charges against two men in connection with Private
Biologicals. Thomas R. Theodore of Sandwich allegedly defrauded
investors of $2 million and misled doctors and patients by
illegally distributing a drug that was not approved for human use
in the United States and was made in an unsanitary, unlicensed
facility.
</P>
<P>
   A second man, Thomas M. Rodgers Jr. of Atlanta, faces
misdemeanor charges in connection with the drug manufacturing and
distribution.
</P>
<P>
   But even as the two defendants face fines or imprisonment for
their roles in promoting LK-200, the flashes of anticancer potency
the drug once showed continue to nag scientists.
</P>
<P>
   ``To this day, I am convinced there is something in there,''
says Dr. Charles Dinarello, a former New England Medical Center
researcher who studied LK-200, which he got from the company.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, Theodore allegedly misled investors by
saying that LK-200 was produced by a ``highly secret and
proprietary'' process. In fact, the substance, which is derived
from the fluid surrounding human white blood cells grown in the
laboratory, was easy to produce, said the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Dinarello and Dr. James Mier, a cancer researcher at Beth Israel
Deaconess Medical Center who previously studied CT scans of
patients from Mexico treated with LK-200, say they thought Private
Biologicals was trying to develop the drug legally. Unknown to
them, Mier said, the company was sending the drug to the Bahamas _
where it could be legally used _ and then back to the United States
_ where the drug's use was illegal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what they wanted to do,'' Mier said recently, ``was
set up a small bunch of clinics in Mexico and the Bahamas and
compete for the alternative medicine market. And they would have
succeeded'' had they not flouted the Food and Drug Administration's
rigorous drug development regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The misbegotten plan is a striking example of how the demand for
cancer drugs by desperate patients can lure unscrupulous
entrepreneurs into taking shortcuts, avoiding the long and costly
drug approval process. Though the FDA's reviews have many critics,
the risk of skirting them is that sick people will put their hopes
in useless or dangerous cures.
</P>
<P>
   It's still unclear whether the partners at one time planned a
legitimate business. But either way, LK-200 seemed doomed to fail,
according to Ralph Moss, a New York consultant on alternative
medicines. They were treating too many patients not to draw
regulators' attention, yet they were too small to do the research
necessary for FDA approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people were skating on thin ice,'' Moss said.
</P>
<P>
   The origins of LK-200, say people knowledgeable about the field,
date to work done in the 1970s and 1980s by Ben Papermaster, an
immunologist at the University of Missouri. In animal and human
experiments, Papermaster reported that the fluid from human white
blood cells grown in his laboratory caused an inflammation-like
response when given to patients, and in a few cases shrank tumors.
</P>
<P>
   It was apparently under Papermaster's direction that human
experiments were conducted in Mexico, with some success. When the
FDA crackdown came in 1995, colon cancer patient Sara Stone-Alston
of Seattle wrote to Moss defending LK-200. ``It had no side effects
and kept my tumor under control and even seemed to shrink it,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   How Private Biologicals, Rodgers, and Theodore became involved
in producing LK-200 is hazy. There appears to have been
disagreement between Private Biologicals and Papermaster, who left
after a short stint as a consultant. He died in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   By 1992, Rodgers, an Atlanta businessman, was chairman of the
board and majority stockholder. Meanwhile, Theodore, who had been
convicted of mail fraud in 1987 and stripped of his license by the
Massachusetts Board of Registration in Medicine, was in charge of
the Woburn plant, according to federal officials.
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers's attorney, Nick Littlefield, downplayed the charges
against his client, stressing that Rodgers is cooperating with the
government in the case. Unlike Theodore, Rodgers was not charged
with fraud or misleading investors, Littlefield said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is charged with . . . technical regulatory misdemeanor
offenses that don't even require specific intent or knowledge,''
said Littlefield, of the law firm Foley, Hoag and Eliot. ``We look
forward to getting the matter resolved promptly.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators portray Theodore as the scientific front
man, falsely presenting himself as a doctor, and illegally using
the mails and Federal Express to ship LK-200 and tout its benefits.
The board said that Theodore did not possess a degree from an
approved medical school, and didn't even have an undergraduate
degree.
</P>
<P>
   Theodore's attorney, John Noonan, said that his client was just
a consultant to Private Biologicals and wasn't on the premises of
the Woburn plant during the times of his alleged criminal
activities. He said that the plant was set up ``by the best minds
in the business,'' including several physicians.
</P>
<P>
   Noonan also said that Theodore has a degree from a medical
school in Santo Domingo, Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding problems for defendants Theodore and Rodgers, a
report on the Internet wrongly linked LK-200 to Dr. Stanislaw
Burzynski, a controversial physician in Texas who has long battled
the federal government over cancer drugs he has developed called
``antineoplastons.'' The Globe reported this erroneous connection
in an earlier article.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, before the 1995 raid, LK-200 had a reputation that was good
enough to attract the attention of serious researchers.
</P>
<P>
   The two physicians at New England Medical Center, Dinarello and
Mier, became interested in the substance in the 1990s after hearing
about the dramatic results in some patients in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Dinarello, an infectious disease specialist who left NEMC in
1995, said he was intrigued by LK-200 because of what it was, a
mixture of immune system chemicals known individually as having
important roles in inflammation, infection, and cancer. In
addition, he said, he saw some photographs of patients treated for
skin cancers with LK-200.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I sat in a room with you and showed you pictures of these
patients'' before and after treatment, ``you'd be impressed,'' he
said. Dinarello, comparing LK-200 to supposedly anticancer
substances found in natural plants, said, ``This drug had a
portfolio far more interesting than some bug juice from the
Amazon.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, a small delegation from the federal Office of
Alternative Medicine visited a clinic in Monterrey, Mexico, where
results of LK-200 in some patients were presented.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Adrienne Fugh-Berman, a physician formerly with the federal
office, recalled that the drug ``looked really promising'' and she
wrote a report to that effect. Shortly afterward, she left the
office, which has been reconstituted as the National Center for
Complementary and Alternative Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Mier and Dinarello said that shortly before the Woburn plant was
closed down, the company had brought in consultants, one of them
reportedly a former FDA employee, to tell them what kind of
research data they would need to apply for an Investigational New
Drug permit from the FDA. The permit allows a new drug to be tested
in patients for safety, and then for effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   According to Mier, Theodore was dismissed from the company after
some of his alleged misrepresentations were discovered. Of Rodgers,
Mier said, ``I think he was duped. I don't think he was
malicious.''
</P>
<P>
   The collapse of Private Biologicals cast a cloud over research
into LK-200, but, remarkably, a Vienna, Va., company has picked up
on a similar concept.
</P>
<P>
   Cel-Sci Corp. is testing a product called MultiKine, which, like
LK-200, is described as a mixture of lymphokines and cytokines that
stimulate immune responses. Eyal Talor, vice president of research,
said MultiKine is a patented preparation that is similar to LK-200
but is extracted from whole blood.
</P>
<P>
   MultiKine is being tested in several foreign countries,
including Israel, under the new drug permit. The drug has been
injected into patients prior to surgery to remove head and neck
cancers. He said there have been a number of encouraging responses
and that testing will also be done in the United States in the near
future.
</P>
<P>
   Cel-Sci spokeswoman Daryl Strahl criticized the FDA's ``outdated
rules'' for drug approvals, but she said her company has no
intention of taking any shortcuts. Potential treatments, she said,
have to be studied in scientifically sound and lengthy trials ``to
find out what happens next.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
