<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5622 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SF-STYLE-HNS &LR;      04-24 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-STYLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BYGONE DAYS OF SHOPPING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIE WAGNER KRENZ  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Back then it was special to go shopping in
downtown San Francisco. My earliest memories were of those
wonderful Saturdays when Mother dressed me in a little coat with
matching hat, white gloves, and black patent Mary Janes (shined
with a dab of salad oil).
</P>
<P>
   Although we sometimes drove, it was easier and more fun to take
the streetcar. It was airy and comfortable and groaned along at
consistent speeds.
</P>
<P>
   The motorman wore a visored cap and tapped a bell on the floor
with his foot. The conductor stood on the back platform and kept a
wary eye for neighborhood boys who tried to steal rides on the
cowcatcher.
</P>
<P>
   We'd trek to various stores, then have lunch _ which was often
chicken a la king in a pastry shell. Best of all was an ice cream
soda at Haas' Candy Store, Goldberg Bowen or the Golden Pheasant.
</P>
<P>
   Time passed and I became a teen-ager, then an adult, and Mother
and I shopped throughout the years. Neither of us would have
dreamed of going downtown without hat, gloves, heels and stockings.
We even wore scarves of glassy-eyed furry creatures, and no one
accosted us for our lack of sensitivity. The greatest sartorial
gaffe would have been to wear white shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Service was excellent at a multitude of fine stores, now gone:
I. Magnin, Joseph Magnin, H. Liebes, Ransohoff, Livingstons, Maison
Mendesolle, the White House, the City of Paris, etc.
</P>
<P>
   Purchasing gloves was a major operation. A well-groomed
salesperson would position our elbows on a small pillow and smooth
numerous pairs on our waiting fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Selecting hosiery was almost as complicated. A salesperson with
beautiful hands opened box after box to find just the right color.
</P>
<P>
   It would never have occurred to us to carry home that package,
small as it was. Everything was delivered without charge. During
the war years, Mother and I had only one pair of nylons between us,
and we had to make do with those ugly rayon things that took
forever to dry. Panty hose had yet to be invented.
</P>
<P>
   The nicer stores were not cluttered with racks and stacks of
clothes. We waited on little settees as the saleslady brought
garments for our inspection, then brought more to replace the
rejects.
</P>
<P>
   We had many favorite places for lunch _ some more elegant than
others _ Old Poodle Dog, Normandy Lane, El Prado, Bardelli, Blum's,
the St. Francis. An all-time favorite was Townsend's on Geary for
creamed spinach.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes we would drive downtown. When it was time to go home,
we walked to the Union Square underground garage and gave the
attendant our ticket. We sat comfortably on padded benches until he
brought up our car and helped us inside.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco has always been a cosmopolitan city with different
languages heard on every corner, but it used to be that only
tourists wore shorts and sport shirts when shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Now we see few women in dresses or men in coats and neckties;
almost everyone is casually dressed, and most women wear pants.
White shoes are everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The changes are probably for the best, but San Francisco lacks a
special quality it once had. Although the streets are much the
same, I miss the people who once walked there _ especially the lady
who walked with me.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Marie Krenz, who grew up in San Francisco, is a retired teacher
working on a mystery novel.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
