   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INFLATION BEAR CHASES AMERICA'S `GOLDILOCKS' ECONOMY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `GOLDILOCKS'-MAULED-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   America's famous ``new economy'' promised rapid growth without
inflation. Yet its inflation rate is now the highest of any big
rich economy. No wonder share prices tumbled when the latest
figures were published on April 14. Those who have, over the past
few years, made much of America's Goldilocks economy (neither too
hot, nor too cold) should have remembered that the tale ends with
Goldilocks being chased away by the bears. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (825 words) &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MIAMI'S CUBAN-AMERICANS ARE PLAYING INTO CASTRO'S HANDS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FIDEL'S-PAWNS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the Elian Gonzalez soap opera drags on daily, Miami's Cuban
exiles are increasingly, utterly immovable on one point: they will
not deal with Cuba while Fidel Castro is in power. He is the devil,
and six-year-old Elian their saint. How misguided they are. The
Economist yields to nobody when it comes to contempt for Castro,
but to use Elian for propaganda purposes, as the exiles now are, is
exactly the tactic Castro would choose. He is getting enormous
mileage out of this case. It shows, even better than the trade
embargo can, how vindictive and inhumane the United States can be. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (975 words) &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OH, PLEASE DON'T LET MUGABE PROVE THE RACISTS RIGHT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AFRICA-DOMINO-EFFECT-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Is the western world's concern about the deteriorating turn of
events in Zimbabwe just a reflection of the fact that some of the
people being beaten and shot there are white? Frankly, yes. There
is no other honest answer. Yet outsiders are right to be concerned
about Zimbabwe, not least because what happens there will have a
profound effect upon what happens in other parts of Africa, and
therefore upon all Africans, black and white. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (1,050 words) &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GROW UP, BRAZIL. YOU'RE TOO OLD FOR AN INFERIORITY COMPLEX &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BRAZIL-500YEARS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the Americas celebrated, or mourned, their
``discovery'' by Europeans back in 1992, the quincentenary of
Columbus's landfall. But that meant little to Brazil. Its discovery
by the Portuguese came eight years later, on April 22, 1500, and by
accident, when a fleet bound for India was blown off course.
Brazilians mark that event this weekend, amid much soul-searching
about what makes them unique. After 500 years, it is now high time
for South America's giant to shake off its lingering inferiority
complex. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (700 words) &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; USA &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ECO-PROPHET AL GORE: THE ENVIRONMENT'S HEROIC HYPOCRITE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOW-GREEN-IS-GORE?-ECONOMIST-700&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the issues on which Al Gore expects to trounce George W.
Bush this election year is the environment. Understandably so. The
vice president's reputation as somebody who cares deeply, really
deeply, about the planet is well known. On the evidence of his 1992
book-manifesto, ``Earth in the Balance,'' whose second edition
arrives in bookstores this weekend to coincide with ``Earth Day
2000,'' Gore is, in fact, a hypocrite of heroic proportions. His
description of the environmental ``crisis,'' and his way of
thinking about it, could not be more extreme. Is Gore's expounded
hot air contributing to global warming? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors...TIMELY for `Earth Day 2000') &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Note 350-word optional trim; 1,100 words uncut) &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 'TWIXT LITTLE ROCK AND A HARD PLACE: THE CLINTONS AND
ARKANSAS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LOVEHATE-ARK-CLINTONS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In most states a retiring president is treated like a returning
hero, the ultimate ``local boy made good.'' But not in Arkansas,
and not Bill Clinton. While the rest of America turns its attention
to George W. Bush and Al Gore, Arkansas is still riveted by a man
it can't quite work out whether to hail or sue. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors...ARKANSAS Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (975 words) &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A NEW BOOM FOR 'OL MAN RIVER, THE MISSISSIPPI &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `MICHI-SIPI'-RIVER-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For too long many people who live in the cities and towns that
flank the mighty Mississippi have forgotten that a river as grand
and nearly as long as the Nile flows beside them. But not for much
longer. The Mississippi is enjoying a new boom, and a new
appreciation of what the Algonquin Indians called michi-sipi, the
Big Water. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Twin Cities, Minn., Iowa, Mississippi River States) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (900 words) &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NO CAPITOL PUNISHMENT FOR `SPANK THE BANK' PROTESTERS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `SPANK-THE-BANK'-DC-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was not a replay of riotous Seattle, but neither was it a
damp squib. Some 10,000 protesters descended on Washington, D.C.,
last weekend, intent on shutting down the spring meetings of the
International Monetary Fund and the World Bank on April 16 and 17.
Despite a few photographs of students being clobbered, the police
were widely praised for doing a good job of containment. As D.C.
Police Chief Charles Ramsey, seen chatting with demonstrators,
said, ``They're just kids with a cause. God bless 'em. That's what
America is all about.'' &QL;
</P>
