<HEADLINE>
INFLATION BEAR CHASES AMERICA'S `GOLDILOCKS' ECONOMY    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 825-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)     
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)     
 From the Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   America's famous ``new economy'' promised rapid growth without
inflation. Yet its inflation rate is now the highest of any big
rich economy. No wonder share prices tumbled when the latest
figures were published on April 14.
</P>
<P>
   A prudent central bank increases interest rates at the first
sign of overheating, before inflation actually takes off. So far
the Federal Reserve has been too lax, and that now makes its task
doubly difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the jump in consumer-price inflation _ to 3.7 percent in
