<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5676 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-`SPANK-THE-BANK'-DC-E     04-24 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-`SPANK-THE-BANK'-DC-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO CAPITOL PUNISHMENT FOR `SPANK THE BANK' PROTESTERS    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 575-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)     
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)     
 From the Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It was not Seattle, but neither was it a damp
squib.
</P>
<P>
   Some 10,000 protesters descended on Washington last weekend,
intent on shutting down the spring meetings of the IMF and the
World Bank on April 16 and 17.
</P>
<P>
   Just as in Seattle, the aim was to use ``nonviolent civil
disobedience'' to stop the meetings from taking place. In other
words: block roads by forming human chains, and stop anyone getting
through.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters failed to shut down the meetings of the Fund and
the Bank, but they did paralyze large parts of downtown Washington
and cause the delegates much inconvenience.
</P>
<P>
   The police sealed off a huge 90-block area around the Bank and
Fund buildings. By the eve of the meetings hundreds of policemen
were on guard in full riot gear.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the staff of the Bank and the Fund spent the night in
their offices, with videos and inflatable mattresses. Others were
told to report for work at 5 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates were driven to the meetings from their hotels in
police-escorted buses soon after dawn. Those who tried later
(including Laurent Fabius, the French finance minister) failed to
make it past the human chains.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone naive enough to wander among the demonstrators in a suit
was likely to be treated to an impromptu lecture on the evils of
global capitalism. Most of the time, the mood was festive.
</P>
<P>
   There were plenty of placards (``Imperialist Monetary Fiend,''
``Indigenous Manipulation Fund,'' ``Spank the Bank''). Huge banners
spanned the streets (``IMF/World Bank: start shakin'; today's pig
is tomorrow's bacon'').
</P>
<P>
   Bare-breasted women demanded the end of corporate rule;
makeshift bands of drummers banged empty water bottles on plastic
buckets; three young women from Vermont, in bright red evening
dresses, pranced around quoting from the ``Communist Manifesto,'' a
book whose message they felt was ``pretty accurate for right now.''
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to find any protesters with a coherent explanation
of why they were there. The usual responses were mumbled slogans
saying that the World Bank and the IMF oppressed the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the demonstrators seemed to be students, many inspired
by recent teach-ins on the evils of the IMF at their college
campuses. Several admitted that they had not heard of these
organizations two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Some were even younger: a group of 14-year-olds from a suburban
Washington high school claimed they were there to protest against
the World Bank's ``corrupt'' loan system.
</P>
<P>
   There was a sinister element. Groups of black-masked anarchists
_ similar to those who smashed windows in Seattle _ roamed around
looking for trouble. But by Seattle standards it was all fairly
peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   The police arrested around 1,300 people, including 600 the day
before the main protest started and another 400 who were
``voluntarily arrested'' after they crossed a police line.
</P>
<P>
   There was virtually no vandalism (a few cars got smashed); and
some pepper spray was used. Despite a few photographs of students
being clobbered, the police were widely praised for doing a good
job.
</P>
<P>
   Their boss, Charles Ramsey, became something of a media star as
he walked around chatting with demonstrators. ``They're just kids
with a cause,'' he said at one of the many press briefings. ``God
bless 'em. That's what America is all about.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
