<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIMARYCOLOR-COLUMN-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIMARY COLOR: QUIRKY MOMENTS ON THIS WEEK'S CAMPAIGN TRAIL    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary, Political, Humor Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 425-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)     
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)     
 From the Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)     
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; VOTERS OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``People who pray will probably vote all right, too.'' (Jerry
Falwell, a TV preacher, launching an initiative to register 10
million churchgoers as voters, Associated Press, April 15) &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INDEPENDENT OF THE WEEK (1): &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him quite strongly he would have a chance to win.''
(Minnesota's Governor Jesse Ventura, urging John McCain to run for
president as an independent.) &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INDEPENDENT OF THE WEEK (2): &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a mediocre high-school and college wrestler, and I used
to wear a feather boa around the Senate sometimes.'' (McCain on his
resemblance to Ventura, Associated Press, April 17) &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LAWSUIT OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush has been named as defendant in a lawsuit against
the Texas Funeral Service Commission. Its former executive
director, Eliza May, claims she was fired by the state for
repeatedly reporting violations by Service Corporation
International, the world's largest funeral company. SCI, which is
based in Houston, gave money to Bush's 1998 gubernatorial campaign.
(Salon, April 18) &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INCENTIVE OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be like a bunch of investors in your industry saying,
Well, let's get rid of the team that made `American Beauty' and get
the ones that made `Howard the Duck.''' (Al Gore on why you
shouldn't vote Republican. He was addressing a $25,000-a-head
dinner, organized by Jeffrey Katzenberg _ the mogul behind ``Howard
the Duck.'' Washington Post, April 17) &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CANDIDATE 2004: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Newt Gingrich, former speaker of the House, declared that
Hillary Rodham Clinton would beat Rudy Giuliani in the battle for
New York's Senate seat and, if Gore loses the presidency this year,
she would head the Democratic ticket in 2004. &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IT'S BEEN DOWNHILL SINCE...: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When Gore was bored with his thesis, (I) found him sitting at
his desk teaching himself how to play `Dixie' on the touch-tone
phone.'' (Actor Tommy Lee Jones on his Harvard roommate, Harvard
Crimson, April 17) &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; VICE PRESIDENT OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He will be pro-life, he will agree with me by and large... He
or she will agree with me by and large on almost all issues.'' (Pat
Buchanan on choosing his vice president, National Journal Hotline,
April 18) &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; REDUCED CIRCUMSTANCES: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Bushes earned $1.3 million in 1999 and paid federal taxes of
$514,000. In 1998 their income was $18.4 million, and they paid
$3.8 million. &QL;
</P>
