<SLUG> BC-HIV-CARIBBEAN-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUN, SURF AND DEATH: AIDS DECIMATES CARIBBEAN COUNTRIES    
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 600-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)     
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)     
 From the Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT OF SPAIN _ Africa apart, nowhere in the world suffers more
from AIDS than the countries of the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Some 2 percent of their population, or half a million people,
are infected with HIV (the virus which causes the disease).
</P>
<P>
   Though this is a much lower rate than in several African
countries, the impact is broad, growing, and potentially
devastating to what are already some of the most vulnerable
countries in the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   Some places are worse hit than others. In Haiti, the incidence
of the disease is similar to that in sub-Saharan Africa: 12 percent
of Haitians in urban areas are infected, and 5 percent of those in
the countryside.
</P>
<P>
   At the main hospital in Kingstown, the capital of St. Vincent, a
study last year found nearly 40 percent of young men's deaths were
linked to AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   In the Dominican Republic, Guyana and the Bahamas, routine
testing of pregnant women and blood donors (groups not especially
at risk) shows a prevalence of well over 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The deadly effects of these figures will become fully clear only
in coming decades. AIDS is already the largest single cause of
death among young men (aged 15-44) in the English-speaking
Caribbean; within 20 years, it is expected to account for
three-quarters of all such deaths, according to the U.N.
</P>
<P>
   The number of orphans in the Caribbean, now 83,000, is likely to
rocket.
</P>
<P>
   According to an estimate by the World Bank, the disease has
already cost the Caribbean region some 6 percent of its potential
wealth, because of lost workers, increased dependency on those who
do work, higher medical spending and reduced savings.
</P>
<P>
   Public awareness and understanding of AIDS has been slow in
coming. Health campaigns have faced big obstacles in efforts to
change sexual practices (a billboard in Guyana used to advise men
to ``wear a fresh condom every time'').
</P>
<P>
   At first, treatment of those who admitted they had the disease
could be rudimentary and cruel. Some AIDS sufferers were allowed to
die in the streets; some hospital staff refused to touch corpses of
victims; and in Barbados an infected man was even stoned to death.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, better drugs and education have improved matters,
but problems remain. Peggy McEvoy, who heads UNAIDS in the
Caribbean, says the region is particularly vulnerable because its
people are young, and many are sexually active from an early age.
</P>
<P>
   But the strong influences of churches, whether Catholic or
evangelical Protestant, has led to public reluctance to discuss sex
or encourage the use of condoms.
</P>
<P>
   The one exception to this bleak regional picture, as in many
other health matters, is Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its historical intolerance of homosexuality, Fidel
Castro's regime has set up an effective screening and reporting
system for AIDS. As a result, the infection rate in Cuba has been
kept remarkably low, at just 0.02 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, too, some efforts are being made to tackle the
disease. A plan backed by all the region's governments aims to
boost public-health education.
</P>
<P>
   Good screening programs in the Bahamas have helped to slow the
infection rate, and drug treatments there and in Barbados that help
to prevent pregnant mothers passing the disease to their children
have been copied elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But too often politicians are not leading. ``In some countries,
during election years there is a deafening silence on the issue for
fear of clashes with the church,'' says McEvoy. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
