<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5693 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-SUIT-500&AMP;AD     04-24 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-SUIT-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. GOVERNMENT MAY PROPOSE DIVISION OF MICROSOFT 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed) 
 By STEVE LOHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After months of considering an array of possible remedies in the
Microsoft antitrust case, the U.S. government intends to propose
breaking the company in two, sources familiar with the plan said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, they said, would involve forcing Microsoft to spin off
its Office software _ which includes word processing, spreadsheet,
database and presentation programs _ from the company's industry
standard Windows operating system business.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, they say, the government intends to propose a
series of conduct remedies likely to remain in effect for two to
three years. These would include mandating that Microsoft publish
the prices it charges PC manufacturers for Windows, a step intended
to prevent Microsoft from rewarding its industry friends with lower
prices while punishing manufacturers that distribute software that
competes with Microsoft with higher prices.
</P>
<P>
   The government proposal, they say, would also prohibit Microsoft
from entering into exclusive contracts. Microsoft could include new
features in its Windows operating system, but it would be required
to offer an ``unbundled'' version of Windows without current
features like its Internet browser or new features like
voice-recognition software, which Microsoft has said it plans to
add to Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Broadly, the government proposal is intended to prevent
Microsoft from using the market power of its monopoly in the
personal computer operating system business to unfairly defend its
dominance or to extend it into new software markets.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal also seeks to change the incentives in Microsoft's
biggest businesses, according to people familiar with the
government plan. For example, they say, an independent Office
company would be more likely to make sure its applications programs
like Word and Excel run on operating systems that compete with
Windows, including Linux, a version of Unix that is distributed
free on the Internet. Microsoft already makes Office for Apple's
Macintosh operating system. Yet according to testimony at the
trial, the government alleged that Microsoft threatened to stop
making a Macintosh version of Office unless Apple made Microsoft's
Internet Explorer its main browsing software instead of Netscape's
competing browser.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's stock price fell sharply in morning trading Monday.
It was down more than $12 a share at 1 p.m. EST, to about $66 a
share. But the main reason for that drop was the disappointing
financial results Microsoft announced after the close of the market
last Thursday. With stock markets closed on Good Friday, Monday was
the first day the market could react to those results.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Microsoft reported solid quarterly earnings but its
revenue growth disappointed Wall Street analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Monday morning, Wall Street's most influential Microsoft analyst
dropped the company from his ``recommended for purchase'' list _ on
which Microsoft had been included since March 1996. Richard
Sherlund, an analyst at Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co., mentioned Microsoft's
market trends instead of the government antitrust case as the
reason for his move.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``There is an increasing risk,'' Sherlund wrote, ``that
Microsoft might atrophy on the PC platform as IBM did on the
mainframe platform, while robust growth shifts to hand-held and
wireless devices.''
</P>
<P>
   For Microsoft shareholders, the breakup that the government
intends to recommend this week _ possibly as early as Tuesday _
might well prove rewarding. The Microsoft Office share of the
market for so-called productivity applications is even higher than
the 85 percent of the market that Windows holds in the PC operating
system market.
</P>
<P>
   Many Wall Street analysts have said the value of the two
``monopoly'' franchises might well be far higher than the stock
market value of the combined company. That, they note, is what
happened after the government broke up Standard Oil in 1914.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-00 1359EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
