<SLUG> BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Monday, April 24, 2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Editors &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file the following for Tuesday. If
you have questions, please call Chuck Lewis or Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-PRIMARIES (Washington) _ California's primary system that
allows voters to choose candidates without regard to party
affiliation comes under heavy fire at the Supreme Court, where the
justices question the law's constitutionality and its impact on
fair elections. If the court strikes down the law, Washington state
and Alaska could be forced to change the way they conduct their
primaries. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-POVERTY (Washington) _ Rep. Tony Hall, D-Ohio, urges the
United Nations to allow a freer flow of food and medicine into
Iraq. Hall, who recently returned from a trip to Iraq, said U.N.
economic sanctions have hurt millions of civilians there. By AUSTIN
ZALKIN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) - The saga of little Elian Gonzalez is
heart-rending human drama, but it is easy to lose sight of the
central issue here because of the many political and emotional
distractions. The irresponsible Miami relatives had no legal right
to custody of Elian. This is not about Castro, or communism, or
President Clinton or the timing of the armed raid. It is about
family values and parental authority, reuniting a separated father
and son. BY MARIANNE MEANS
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
