<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YANKS-CENTRALASIA-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENTRAL ASIA AND AMERICA: WOOED _ BUT NOT WOWED    
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 775-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)     
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)     
 From the Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASTANA _ The election victory last month of Russia's new
president, Vladimir Putin, was hailed by the presidents of the
ex-Soviet Central Asian republics. But in private they are anxious
to see what policies Putin will have in store for Russia's former
colonies.
</P>
<P>
   The American government, however, has wasted no time in
asserting its interests in the oil-rich region by dispatching a
series of senior government officials.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the CIA, George Tennet, and the FBI's director,
Louis Freeh, both visited the region immediately after the Russian
election.
</P>
<P>
   Hot on their heels came Madeleine Albright, the secretary of
state, who travelled to the capitals of Kazakhstan, Kirgizstan and
Uzbekistan this week.
</P>
<P>
   Her mission was to discuss regional security and democracy with
the three countries' authoritarian presidents. Each was offered $3
million to assist in dealing with an increasing cross-border flow
of weapons, drugs and terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   But along with the carrot came the stick: Mrs. Albright
admonished the presidents for the manifest shortcomings of recent
elections in all three countries, for persecuting political
opponents and, in Uzbekistan, for using the threat of Islamic
fundamentalism and terrorism to repress the Muslim population.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Central Asian presidents were evidently flattered
by such a high-level American charm offensive, it may not have the
desired result.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia is our God-given neighbor,'' says Nursultan Nazarbaev,
Kazakhstan's president. He would like to establish a political and
economic partnership with Russia, but also enjoy close relations
with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Russia matters, not least because a third of the country's
population is Russian.
</P>
<P>
   Kirgizstan, one of the smaller countries in Central Asia, also
has little choice about where to look for friends. Last autumn,
hundreds of Islamic militants invaded southern Kirgizstan, taking
four Japanese geologists hostage.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities were caught unprepared and Kirgizstan's
president, Askar Akaev, asked Russia for help. After two months,
the hostages were released and the kidnappers escaped to
Tajikistan.
</P>
<P>
   Only days before Mrs. Albright's arrival in Kirgizstan, Russia's
spokesman on Chechnya, Sergei Yastrzhembsky, had met Akaev in the
capital, Bishkek, and Uzbekistan's president, Islam Karimov, in the
Uzbek capital, Tashkent.
</P>
<P>
   They discussed joint measures to combat terrorism and religious
extremism. Yastrzhembsky believes that there is a connection
between the rebels in Chechnya, the incursion in Kirgizstan and
terrorist bombings in Uzbekistan in February last year.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Albright's argument that democracy is the best defense
against extremism probably fell on deaf ears in Uzbekistan. Karimov
has antagonized many of his citizens by muzzling any form of
opposition, arresting thousands after last year's bomb blasts, in
which he himself narrowly escaped death.
</P>
<P>
   Many people think his iron rule is at least partly responsible
for the extremism he is now struggling against. Russia says it is
ready to help and will do so without making demands for democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The one issue on which America's dogged efforts to influence
Central Asia's leaders may pay off is oil.
</P>
<P>
   The American government is determined to decrease Central Asia's
dependence on Russia's pipelines for transporting oil to
international markets.
</P>
<P>
   Nazarbaev, who would like to see several pipelines built so that
Kazakhstan can be as independent as possible, has reiterated his
commitment to a 1,730-km (1,075-mile) oil pipeline to run from
Azerbaijan's capital Baku on the Caspian Sea to the Turkish port of
Ceyhan on the Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
   Construction is due to start next year, but the pipeline will be
economic only if Kazakhstan commits 20 million tons of oil a year
to the project. Recently, its officials have seemed to be backing
away from any such commitment, perhaps because they think
Kazakhstan will not be able to produce enough oil, at least before
2004.
</P>
<P>
   If the United States cannot stop Russia from resuming a leading
role in Central Asia, the Americans hope they can at least prevent
a reunification with Russia of some of the former Soviet republics.
They may not succeed even in this aim.
</P>
<P>
   When Putin became Russia's acting president at the end of last
year, Slavic organizations in Kazakhstan and Kirgizstan called for
referendums on joining the Russia-Belarus Union. Though there is
little support for this among the non-Slav population, many people
feel that their future would be safer under Russian protection.
</P>
<P>
   Independence is attractive, but the countries of Central Asia,
with small populations in relation to their size, feel vulnerable
to Islamic ambitions from Afghanistan. China, too, a giant
neighbor, is historically distrusted by Central Asians.
</P>
<P>
   The United States may be a friend, but it is far away. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
