<HEADLINE>
25 YEARS AGO, PHNOM PENH FELL _ AND I ALONE SURVIVED    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (RESENDING from April 21)   (This personal 775-word ``separate-buy'' commentary is from the
International Herald Tribune.)     
 (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders _ and readers'
horizons _ the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald Tribune.
  
 (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.)     
 (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, her e-mail
address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)     
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``k'' commentary news and ``a'' general news files.)     
 By SICHAN SIV  
 c.2000 International Herald Tribune  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Twenty-five years ago, on April 17, 1975, I was in
Phnom Penh. It was a city that had been under siege for months, a
place of fear and desperation.
</P>
<P>
   Khmer Rouge rockets rained down daily, bringing random death,
injury and destruction. The population had been swollen to 3
million, mainly by people fleeing the war-torn countryside.
</P>
<P>
   We were warned that Phnom Penh's defenses could not hold out
much longer. I remember hearing a Voice of America radio broadcast
in which President Gerald Ford warned Congress in a somber tone
that the situation in both Cambodia and South Vietnam had reached a
critical phase.
</P>
<P>
   ``The options before us are few and time is very short,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   I was working as a Cambodian staff member of the American aid
agency CARE. I had my chance to leave Phnom Penh. In the early
morning of April 12, a U.S. Embassy official told me that I had to
get to the embassy within an hour if I wanted to be evacuated from
Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
   The American staff of CARE had gone, leaving the management of
its multimillion dollar program in our hands. My mind was on the
plight of more than 3,000 refugee families in the provincial town
of Kampong Speu.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Khmer Rouge tightened their noose around Phnom Penh,
we had been able to arrange trucks to carry food and medical
supplies to these refugees. Now the road had been cut and I was
preoccupied with a meeting that morning to finalize an airlift of
supplies instead.
</P>
<P>
   When the meeting ended, I suddenly realized that I was running
late for the rendezvous at the U.S. Embassy. I arrived just in time
to see the last of the evacuation helicopters taking off. There was
no other way out. I was trapped, like everyone else in Phnom Penh.
</P>
<P>
   People prayed that the Cambodian New Year that started the
following day would turn a fresh page in Cambodia's recently
tormented history. We knew that the war would soon be over. But we
did not know whether its end would bring peace or more death and
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   On April 17, Khmer Rouge soldiers clad in black pajamas and
carrying AK-47 assault rifles walked into the city. Many were just
teenagers. People thought that between Cambodians we could work
things out.
</P>
<P>
   I went to one of the city's main hotels, where the Red Cross had
set up a neutral zone. I spent the day helping its staff in the
emergency room in one of the bungalows. Later that afternoon the
Khmer Rouge ordered the entire city emptied.
</P>
<P>
   Our family group of 16 left that night along with thousands of
others. Imagine 3 million people trying to get out of the city.
Among the forced evacuees were huge numbers of women, children,
elderly and infirm _ even thousands of hospital patients, many
seriously ill or maimed.
</P>
<P>
   This forced march was desperately slow. It took us 10 days to
get to Tonle Bati, usually reached from Phnom Penh in an hour. This
was just the beginning of the Killing Fields.
</P>
<P>
   On April 30, Saigon, the capital of South Vietnam, also fell to
the communists.
</P>
<P>
   The next 10 months were a time of unimaginable horror in
Cambodia. I managed to survive by disguising my identity and slowly
working my way westwards towards the border with Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1976, I crossed into Thailand, joining other
Cambodians in refugee camps there. Later, I was taken to America.
But of the 16 members of my family, I was the only one to make it
to Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   Have Cambodia and Vietnam learned any lessons from this terrible
period?
</P>
<P>
   Despite the alliance between the Khmer Rouge and the Vietnamese
communists during the years of the war in Indochina, both countries
underwent internal purges and fought against each other. The
conflict resulted in a 10-year occupation of Cambodia by Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Cambodia and Vietnam have mended their relations.
Both are now members of ASEAN, the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations, and espouse market economics. Both have relative stability
and considerable economic potential.
</P>
<P>
   But Vietnam's communist rule and its inability to end corruption
and bureaucratic red tape scare away many investors. Cambodia, too,
has governance problems. Yet even its less-than-fair elections have
awakened the population to the importance of having their voices
heard.
</P>
<P>
   Both Cambodia and Vietnam must accept the bright light of
accountability and transparency before they can enjoy the full
benefits of democratic prosperity _ and be sure that the dark
period of their recent history is never repeated. &QL;   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Sichan Siv was deputy assistant to the president
and deputy assistant secretary of state in the George Bush
administration.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
