<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WWTBAM IS A SOFTWARE HIT, TOO  
</HEADLINE>
   By LONNIE BROWN   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's the best-selling game software for the past few months?
Before giving your final answer, do you want to use one of your
three lifelines?
</P>
<P>
   Who Wants To Be A Millionaire CD-ROM (Windows; about $15-$20) is
as big a hit on the computer monitor as it has been on television
screens. It's dominated the top of the software best-seller list
since its debut late last year.
</P>
<P>
   It's such a hit, in fact, that the distributor, Disney
Interactive, has announced that a sequel, WWTBAM 2nd Edition, will
be out sometime next month. For fans of this hot trivia show, the
first version has enough going for it to recommend the second
version sight unseen.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the CD version is hosted by Regis Philbin. Yes, there is
the same ``fastest finger'' round where contestants seek to put
four items in the right sequence in the fastest time in order to
play the game. (Up to 26 players can compete in the round to see
who gets to take the first shot at the prize.) Yes, players can get
lifelines. Yes, it is the same 15-question format leading to a top
prize.
</P>
<P>
   No, you do not get a check for $1 million from Regis if you make
it to the top of the CD's game ladder.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the questions are just as interesting as the ones on
television: What type of animal is a humuhumunukunukuapuaa? A.
turtle; B. bird; C. fish; D. monkey. (Answer at the end of the
column.)
</P>
<P>
   The game moves along quickly. The stage setting and music have
been transported to the computer monitor so that the show becomes
interactive with the home player.
</P>
<P>
   Philbin will provide one-sided chatter during the game
including, of course, his ``Final answer?'' trademark. He'll also
make some deflating comments when players bomb out on low rounds
and ask if players want to change their minds.
</P>
<P>
   Each question also must be answered within a set amount of time.
That's mainly to provide equal competition if several people are
playing separate rounds for a high score. If you don't have enough
time and want to cheat, pressing the escape key pauses the program.
</P>
<P>
   Another cheat: Typing in no name when starting a game will
result in the name ``Kathy Lee'' being displayed and easier
questions being used; typing ``John Carpenter'' will trigger a
harder set of questions.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter, you may recall, was the first contestant to ever
reach the seven-figure goal, including all contestants on the
original British telecasts. He's also the one who used his lifeline
to call his father, not to ask for help on the final question, but
to say, ``Dad, I'm about to win the million dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   The three lifelines have been transposed from the television
show to the computer with minimum degradation. The 50/50 is easy
enough to do: The computer simply takes away two wrong answers.
Since the home player doesn't have an audience to ask, game
designers conducted an online poll prior to publishing the CD in
which visitors to a Web site were asked to select their answers to
the questions. The graphs show up on screen when a player uses that
lifeline.
</P>
<P>
   Use the Phone-a-Friend lifeline and Regis will place the call.
Philbin and a prerecorded voice will make small talk, and then the
prerecorded ``friend'' will give the answer to the question.
Sometimes, the friend is dead wrong.
</P>
<P>
   You can also play Millionaire online at the ABC Web site:
www.abc.com. You'll need Flash 4 loaded on your computer and have
to endure some advertising to get to the game site. Once there, you
might find that ``today's featured game'' or previous games may not
be currently available because of heavy traffic on the site.
</P>
<P>
   As for the answer to the question earlier in the column, the
humuhumunukunukuapuaa is a fish _ the state fish of Hawaii, in
fact. It's pronounced WHO-moo-WHO-moo-NEW-coo-NEW-coo-AH-poo-AH-ah.
The first part of the word means ``fit pieces together'' because
the fish is colored in sections that look like puzzle pieces. The
second part of the name means ``snout like a pig.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's my final answer.
</P>
<P>
   (Lonnie Brown is associate editor of The Ledger in Lakeland,
Fla. He can be reached by e-mail at LonnieB001(AT)aol.com. The
Ledger is a member of the New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
