<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RPI-PRESIDENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COLLEGE PRESIDENT RETAINS TRAPPINGS OF FEDERAL OFFICE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ANDREW BROWNSTEIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROY, N.Y. _ In her first year on the job, Rensselaer
Polytechnic Institute President Shirley Ann Jackson has amassed a
Washington-style team of assistants and corporate perks to
accommodate what school officials are calling a high-octane
schedule of travel, speeches and corporate meetings.
</P>
<P>
   New positions created by Jackson include a chief of staff, a
speech writer who once worked for FBI Director Louis Freeh and two
``personal security specialists,'' who also share duties as
Jackson's driver.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, formerly the head of the U.S. Nuclear Regulatory
Commission, called herself the ``Energizer Bunny'' upon landing the
RPI job in December 1998. To trustees and faculty, the support
staff is necessary to help her fulfill her promise of shoring up
the school's international reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the school had been run for the past 10 to 15 years the way
it is now, we may not have needed Shirley Ann Jackson,'' said
Warren Bruggeman, a retired vice president of the General Electric
Co. and RPI trustee. ``Her job is to enhance the image of the
university. If she can do that by being with influential people,
God bless her.''
</P>
<P>
   As the former head of a federal agency and the first black woman
to lead a major research university, Jackson also is in high-demand
to appear for speeches and academic panels.
</P>
<P>
   Her combination of ingredients and breadth of commitments are
rare, but so far, faculty members are not complaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get used to a president that's not here all the
time,'' said Michael Hanna, president of the faculty senate.
``That's a real change. We need her to be the external face of the
university, and you can't do that by staying in Troy.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was head of the NRC from 1995 to 1999, and aspects of
the team she has formed at RPI resemble her Washington support
staff.
</P>
<P>
   Security is one example. Two veteran cops take turns setting up
protection for Jackson and prominent visitors to the campus.
</P>
<P>
   Officials added that as a former high-profile Washington
official, Jackson must continue to stay on guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, a woman alone driving in Washington, D.C., Chicago or
Troy is faced with dangers you and I are not,'' said RPI spokesman
Bruce Adams. ``The fact is, she happens to be on the go an awful
lot. You don't want your president walking three blocks to get a
car.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson declined to be interviewed for this article.
</P>
<P>
   Other new RPI officials help free up Jackson's schedule for
speeches and fund-raising engagements. Robin Sparks, a former
assistant to the FBI director and Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif.,
is Jackson's full-time speech writer. And Cynthia McIntyre, a
former professor of physics at George Mason University in Virginia,
serves as her chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   Accommodations for Jackson also extend to the personal front.
The RPI president was recently able to bring her husband home after
six months of a long-distance relationship. Morris Washington, a
photonics expert from Lucent Technologies Labs in New Jersey,
became assistant director of RPI's Center for Integrated
Electronics and Electronics Manufacturing in January.
</P>
<P>
   It's been nine months since Jackson started her job at RPI _
perhaps too short a time to tell if RPI's investment is paying off.
But so far, so good, faculty say.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, Jackson jump-started a strategic plan designed
to put RPI on the map in information technology and biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
   Another part of her ``ambassadorship'' for the school extends to
the business world. Since she came to RPI, she has been invited to
sit on four corporate boards, including FedEx Corp. That alone
would be an ambitious load for a university president, but she is
also a lifetime trustee of the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology, and sits on the Council on Competitiveness and the
Government-University-Industry Research Roundtable of the National
Academies.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Charles Vest, president of the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology, sits on two corporate boards.
</P>
<P>
   Board positions can be lucrative, but RPI officials would not
say if Jackson gets paid for those posts. The potential earnings
come in addition to Jackson's regular salary, which officials would
not release. Pipes, her predecessor, made $288,000 in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
