</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Nasdaq stocks tumble in early trading,
dragged down by shares of Microsoft, which open 15 percent lower.
At 11:10 a.m., the Nasdaq composite index is down 5.70 percent, the
Dow Jones industrial average is down 0.15 percent and the S&AMP;P 500
is down 1.09 percent. Treasury prices are slightly higher, except
for the 30-year bond. European stock markets were closed Monday.
The Nikkei closed up 1.25 percent. The Hong Kong market was closed.
By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-TV (Mexico City) _ Not even his own father was sure that
Emilio Azcarraga Jean could run Grupo Televisa, the broadcasting
giant that has loomed large over Mexican life for half a century.
When his father, Emilio Azcarraga Milmo, died in April 1997, he had
not tapped his 29-year-old son to succeed him as chairman. What he
did bequeath to his son was a bloated and stumbling company, debts
estimated at $1.3 billion and a tangled estate that generated a
struggle among the heirs. Now, just three years later, the junior
Azcarraga is the undisputed leader of Televisa. And he has righted
Televisa largely by departing from the autocratic and freewheeling
ways of his father, imposing costs controls and running the company
as a ``directed democracy.'' By Julia Preston.
</P>
<P>
   LUCENT-APPOINT (Undated) _ Lucent Technologies names Deborah
Hopkins of Boeing chief financial officer, replacing Donald
Peterson. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-AUTOS (London) _ Two of Britain's biggest auto plants
may be closed. Prime Minister Tony Blair has talked with Jacques
Nasser, Ford's chief executive, about the fate of Ford's plant in
Dagenham, east of London, the biggest British auto plant. A rival
bid for Rover, meanwhile, has collapsed, leaving the fate of the
plant in Longbridge, outside Birmingham, up in the air. By Alan
Cowell.
</P>
