<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 14:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5777 &Cx1f; sci-z
u v BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-     04-24 1432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following  &UR; Science
Times &LR;  stories for papers of Tuesday, April 25:
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DROUGHT (Undated) _ Tornadoes, hurricanes and floods are the
stuff of television drama; they make people sit up and take notice.
Not so with drought. It is a far more subtle weather catastrophe
and consequently commands little awe or respect. But in an average
year drought is responsible for about as much economic damage as
floods and hurricanes combined. Nor is it a rare phenomenon.
Instead, it is a persistent and permanent feature of weather and
climate, severely affecting some part of the United States almost
every year. By William K. Stevens. (2200 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FERRET-BRAINS (Undated) _ Scientists at MIT have
reconfigured newborn ferret brains so that the animals' eyes are
hooked up to brain regions where hearing normally develops. The
surprising result is that the ferrets see the world with brain
tissue that was only thought capable of hearing sounds. The
findings contradict popular theories on how animal brains develop
specialized regions for seeing, hearing, sensing touch and, in
humans, generating language and emotional states. By Sandra
Blakeslee. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MEDICAL-REPORTS (Undated) _ Commentary: Two recent studies
have debunked long-held assumptions about preventive medicine:
benefits of postmenopausal estrogen in preventing heart disease and
of high-fiber diets in preventing colon cancer. Now, some
scientists and other experts are warning caution in describing
medical findings, unless results are pinned down by randomized,
double-blind, long-studies that show definitive results. By Gina
Kolata. (950 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-TRILOBITE-EXTINCTION (Undated) _ A quarter billion years
ago, some 90 percent of all animal species, including the
trilobites, the three-lobed predators of the sea, suddenly
disappeared in the worst of all mass extinctions. The killer's
identity has long been a mystery. But now scientists in Australia
have unearthed evidence that the culprit could have been a speeding
rock from outer space that slammed into the planet, carved out a
huge crater some 75 miles wide, and blasted millions of tons of
rock and dust into the sky, blotting out the sun. By William J.
Broad. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ASEXUAL-CROPS (Undated) _ A small but growing number of
scientists are pursuing what they call the holy grail of
agriculture, which promises a ``revolution'' in world food
production. The goal is a plant that will reproduce asexually, so
that its seeds will grow into exact genetic copies, or clones, of
the parent. This process occurs naturally in hundreds of plants,
but the world's major food grains do not reproduce asexually. If
they could, some scientists say, it would greatly simplify crop
breeding: a high-yielding corn, wheat or rice plant could reproduce
itself unchanged for generations. By Andrew Pollack. (1635 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MATH-PROBLEM (Undated) _ Mathematicians are competing to
prove Goldbach's conjecture, a beautiful conjecture about how
numbers fit together, a guess about the infinite. In 1742 a
little-known mathematician named Christian Goldbach wrote a letter
to Leonhard Euler in which he speculated that every even number
greater than two can be expressed as the sum of two prime numbers.
For many mathematicians, the techniques invented and principles
illuminated by pursuing the proof of a hard problem are the real
rewards. But a $1 million prize doesn't hurt either. By Bruce
Schechter. (1170 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT2.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SPIN (Undated) _ A spinning disk has inspired a British
scientist to delve into the underlying mathematics, and now he has
devised a model to explain how the rolling speed can accelerate
even as the disc is losing energy. By Kenneth Chang. (850 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT3.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BIO-PROSPECTING (Undated) _ In a decision that could give a
boost to ``bio-prospecting'' in national parks, a federal judge has
upheld a precedent-setting agreement in which a biotechnology
company will pay Yellowstone National Park for the right to search
its geysers and hot springs for commercially valuable microbes. By
Andrew Pollack. (680 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT4.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ News and notes on science: Items on new
shatterproof pods with potential to increase canola oil yields, a
report on dying trees in and near the Brazilian rain forests, and
.... By Henry Fountain.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DEPRESSION-DRUGS (Undated) _ Psychiatrists and other experts
on depression have widely differing views on the value of Prozac
and other drugs used to treat depression. Critics of the drugs say
they do little more than a placebo; others insist the drugs work.
And maybe both are right: the drugs now available to treat
depression are effective, but not effective enough. By Erica Goode.
(820 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DIFFICULT-PATIENTS (Undated) _ When doctors encounter
difficult patients sometimes they have few choices: generally they
can't just fire them like their bookkeeping staff. Usually only the
most egregious misbehavior: threats, violence, total noncompliance
qualify for dismissal of patients under AMA guidelines, which spill
over into the courtroom. But in some cases, it's just bad
chemistry. By Sandeep Jauhar, M.D. (1325 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NURSE-PRACTITIONERS (Undated) _ Nurse practitioners were the
focus of a study published in January in The Journal of the
American Medical Association, which found no significant
differences in the quality of care received by patients randomly
assigned to either doctors or nurse practitioners. Patients see
advantages in the nurses, who often have much more time to spend
with them and can work on prevention issues. By Tina Kelley. (1860
words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT1.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HELTH (Undated) _ Personal Health: Some doctors are
getting more personal in taking medical histories, and this is a
positive sign. But still other questions need to be asked about
healthful habits like exercise, diet and stress. By Jane E. Brody.
(1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FITNESS-TECH (Undated) _ A technology wave has hit exercise
equipment, and manufacturers have begun flooding the market with
gadgets for fitness buffs. Many of these exercise innovations were
unveiled at a recent sporting goods trade show. Along with the
retooled pedometer, manufacturers rolled out a talking heart
monitor; GetFit.com, a personalized, exercise Web site; iFit.com,
fitness equipment controlled digitally through a Web site; and a
Palm Pilot that keeps track of exercise programs and records to
name several. By Linda Villarosa. (1120 words)
</P>
<P>
   VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ News and notes on health and fitness:
</P>
<P>
   _ Baby ducklings and chicks can give children salmonella, the
CDC is warning consumers. (230 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT5.
</P>
<P>
   _ People who suffer from social anxiety disorder, a common
psychiatric ailment, realize that they have a problem but often
fail to seek treatment because of embarrassment or lack of
resources, a new study has found. (300 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ A new study shows that smaller hospitals are unclogging heart
arteries almost as well as large medical centers. Still, there
seems to be little effort to change guidelines for which centers
should perform the procedure. (325 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Researchers at Stanford report in a study that they found
little correlation between the tears commonly found in people's
vertebral discs and the amount of pain reported. The findings were
reported at a recent meeting of the International Society for the
Study of the Lumbar Spine by Dr. Eugene Carragee. (260 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Brain research provides possible explanations for antisocial
aspects of autism: people with the condition often do not recognize
people's faces. (190 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ A science question answered: How are
expiration dates for medicines determined? Are expiration dates
simply inducements to repurchase? By C. Claiborne Ray. (300 words)
</P>
