<P>
   Entertainment and culture stories from The N.Y. Times News
Service for Tuesday, April 25:
</P>
<P>
   LITERARY-OFFSPRING (Undated) _ Gautama Chopra freely admits that
his last name helped sell both his books. His first agent was a
friend of his father, the best-selling New Age guru Deepak Chopra.
His first publisher, Amber-Allen, was also the original publisher
of his father's blockbuster, ``The Seven Spiritual Laws of
Success.'' Gautama, 24, is not the only young writer capitalizing
on a literary lineage these days. There are Rice, Jong, Heller,
Updike, Bellow, Theroux, Styron and McPhee (make that three McPhee)
children writing, not to mention two Cheever siblings. All were
born with the most valuable asset a writer can have: access. By
Karen Angel. (1800 words)
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI-FRESCO-DISPUTE (Miami) _ In 1984, the artist David Novros
found a public space for one of his huge fresco murals in the old
federal courthouse here. But today he is trying to save his
``Frescoes in the Courtyard'' from destruction by the government in
a dispute that is pitting the artist and his supporters against
historic preservationists who want to restore the old courthouse to
its original condition. By Mireya Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   TEETH-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``White Teeth'' by the young
British writer Zadie Smith, is not one of your typical small,
semi-autobiographical first novels. It's a big, splashy, populous
production reminiscent of books by Dickens and Salman Rushdie with
a nod to indie movies like ``My Beautiful Laundrette,'' a novel
that's not afraid to tackle large, unwieldy themes. Reviewed by
Michiko Kakutani.
</P>
