<P>
   OHIO'S SUMMER POTTERY SHOW DRAWS COLLECTORS FROM ALL OVER
</P>
<P>
   ANTIQUES-POTTERY-TRAVEL-LIFEBEAT _ Summer gives pottery
collectors an opportunity to comb yard sales, sidewalk art
exhibitions and open-air flea markets for American art pottery. The
motherlode, however, can be found in Zanesville, Ohio, drawing
collectors from all over the country. For more than 20 years, fans
have come to this quiet river town to visit pottery-making
exhibitions, attend conventions and purchase pottery during a
week-long festival, which this year takes place from July 9 to July
16.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos of pottery show and pottery closeups are
available in JPEG format by calling William Gonzalez at
212-499-3355.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CAN MARRIAGE SKILLS BE TAUGHT? SOME EDUCATORS TRY
</P>
<P>
   MARRIAGE-LIFEBEAT _ In the United States, the divorce rate
exceeds the birth rate, the death rate, the inflation rate, the
prime rate and the unemployment rate combined. Concerned by the
fallout she saw amongst her own students, high school teacher
Charlene Kamper devised a three-week course called ``Connections:
Relationships and Marriage'' that is now used in 400 high schools
in 32 states and is just one of several such courses available. But
many experts believe that marital problems can neither be avoided
nor solved. Kamper agrees that she can't teach 18-year-olds about
marriage but adds, ``the lessons they learn here will give them a
much better chance of handling the lessons marriage has for them.''
</P>
<P>
   CAN NEWBORNS HEAR? DETECT PROBLEMS EARLY
</P>
<P>
   CHILDCARE-HEALTH-HEARING-LIFEBEAT _ Only half of babies born in
the United States have their hearing tested, yet three out of every
1,000 have serious problems. An equal number struggle with moderate
hearing loss. Unaddressed deafness can lead to learning and
socialization problems. However, babies as young as 4 weeks can be
fitted with hearing aids, and most children with hearing loss
develop normal speech and language if they get hearing aids early.
</P>
<P>
   AFTER 40, DROPPING TESTOSTERONE LEVELS MAY AFFECT HEALTH
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-TESTOSTERONE-LIFEBEAT _ Testosterone levels in men often
decrease by 1 percent a year after age 40; by age 70, many men
produce only a third of what they once produced. Some research
indicates that men with higher levels of testosterone may be less
vulnerable to high blood pressure, heart attacks, frequent colds,
obesity, depression and osteoporosis. Although it isn't widely
known, testosterone-replacement therapy is available though it
isn't advisable for everyone. However, men should be aware of the
warning signs of low testosterone and head to a doctor if they
occur.
</P>
