<HEADLINE>
OHIO'S SUMMER POTTERY SHOW DRAWS COLLECTORS FROM ALL OVER
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text. 
 (ART ADV: Photos of pottery show and pottery closeups are available
in JPEG format by calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 (tlk) 
 &HT;    From ``Country Living'' magazine.
 &HT;    
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc. 
<TEXT>
 &UR; World rights &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   Save antiques-mall crawls and Internet surfing for a rainy day:
Summer gives pottery collectors an opportunity to enjoy the great
outdoors as they comb yard sales, sidewalk art exhibitions and
open-air flea markets for American art pottery. The motherlode,
however, can be found in Zanesville, Ohio, drawing collectors from
all over the country.
</P>
<P>
   Every July, colorful glazed vases, mixing bowls, umbrella stands
and jardinieres are the attraction in this quiet river town which
has a population of 28,000. For more than 20 years, fans have
convened here to visit pottery-making exhibitions, attend
conventions and purchase pottery during a week-long festival known
locally as ``Pottery Week.'' This year, it takes place from July 9
to July 16.
</P>
<P>
   One of nature's most valuable gifts to Zanesville came in the
form of the rich deposits of high-quality Tionesta clay that
spawned southeastern Ohio's thriving pottery industry. Another was
the river access that made long-distance shipping of locally made
goods possible.
</P>
<P>
   The first pottery makers in the region were farmers who made
household necessities in tiny kiln-equipped sheds. But 22
commercial potteries already operated in Muskingum County by 1840.
When the Industrial Revolution brought coal and, later,
electric-powered potter's wheels and kilns into use, area
entrepreneurs with a taste for a little friendly or
fierce-competition wasted no time in combining the region's natural
resources.
</P>
<P>
   Their ingenuity enabled their factories to turn out the large
quantities of ceramic crocks, churns, mixing bowls, garden
ornaments, and ``fancy-glazed'' art pottery that would eventually
earn Zanesville the moniker ``Pottery Capital of the World.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1872, Muskingum County resident Sam Weller outfitted a log
cabin in Fultonham with a potter's wheel and a brick beehive-shaped
kiln. When business boomed, he built a new factory in Zanesville on
the banks of the Muskingum River. His factory was followed by many
more _ dozens of which went on to become household names among
collectors of 20th-century ceramics. Roseville, J.B. Owens, McCoy,
Watt, American Encaustic Tiling, Hull, Shawnee, Brush and the
still-thriving Robinson Ransbottom were among the potteries
headquartered in the county in the first half of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the Second World War, outmoded production
techniques, competition from inexpensive imports and the rising
popularity of unbreakable metal and plastic tableware and storage
pieces forced many of the once-booming businesses to close their
kilns for good. Utilitarian products became collectors' items.
</P>
<P>
   Large quantities of the wares remain in Muskingum County,
awaiting rediscovery by eagle-eyed ceramics lovers who know a
treasure when they spot one.
</P>
<P>
   During the past 20 years, a revived appreciation of southeastern
Ohio's pottery heritage has given rise to a new generation of local
potteries, including Hartstone, Inc. and Fioriware Art Pottery, as
well as a number of museums, galleries, and education centers
dedicated to preserving and celebrating the region's rich pottery
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Every July, as families across America gather for fun-filled
reunions and outdoor amusements, folks in Muskingum County host a
party of their own: a weeklong tribute to the natural resources and
innovative artisans and entrepreneurs that put Zanesville and its
environs on the map of pottery enthusiasts around the world.
</P>
<P>
   For information about Pottery Week, contact the
Zanesville-Muskingum County Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau at (800)
743-2303 or log onto its Web site at www.zanesville-ohio.com
----------------------------
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LIFEBEAT
and other features. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives: &LR;  --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ
in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax, 47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex,
282-942. --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382. &QL;
