<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5819 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-MARRIAGE-LIFEBEAT-180     04-24 2015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARRIAGE-LIFEBEAT-1806-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN MARRIAGE SKILLS BE TAUGHT? SOME EDUCATORS TRY
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text. 
 (tlk) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lee Green writes for ``Spirit'' magazine.
 &UR; By LEE GREEN &QL; 
 &UR; c.2000 by Lee Green. &QL; 
 &UR; World rights &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Few things send the average human into a glazed stupor faster
than the sight of charts and graphs, but the graph Mrs. Kamper has
drawn on the front board has an entire classroom of high school
students transfixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' Mrs. Kamper pronounces as she points to the diagram,
``is normal.''
</P>
<P>
   The subject at the moment in Room 443 at Redlands High School,
east of Los Angeles, is marital passion, and the graph represents
what typically happens to it over time. It looks like a stock that
probably should have been sold years ago: strong at first, then a
dip.
</P>
<P>
   ``The passion levels off,'' Mrs. Kamper says. ``Lots of people
assume that if the energy lessens, something must be wrong. They
say, 'Well, the magic is gone. This isn't working: They don't
realize this is the natural pattern.''
</P>
<P>
   The room is silent as the 17- and 18-year-old juniors and
seniors try to figure out if this natural pattern could possibly
apply to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you base your marriage on this [here, Mrs. Kamper points to
the graph's apex, the enchanted early days, when passion flows like
cheap Bordeaux], you're going to be sadly disappointed with this.''
Here, she indicates the flattened norm, also known variously as the
unvarnished truth, the way it is, the human condition _ in a word,
reality.
</P>
<P>
   Today's lesson ranges from intimacy to commitment to love's many
guises. Empty love, romantic love, fantasy love, companion love.
Tomorrow, all 28 students in the class and every student in Mrs.
Kamper's other five psychology classes will do something high
school students should never do: Get married. Random draws will
assign them jobs, incomes, children, and, just to give the exercise
authenticity, a marriage crisis. It's all part of a three-week
program called ``Connections: Relationships and Marriage.''
Charlene Kamper designed the curriculum herself when she couldn't
find a high school approach to the subject that suited her.
</P>
<P>
   ``For three weeks I don't have any absences,'' says the
51-year-old teacher, an apparent affirmation of her contention that
kids are hungry for relationship guidance.
</P>
<P>
   That view came to Kamper piecemeal.
</P>
<P>
   As an elementary school teacher she encountered an alarming
number of children with behavioral problems, their family lives
strained or fractured. When she switched to junior high, or middle
school, students opened up to her about their family and
relationship frustrations. Her recurring thought, she recalls, was,
Why can't we teach some skills in high school instead of waiting
until the marriage is on the rocks?
</P>
<P>
   That was, and is, a legitimate question in a society where the
divorce rate exceeds the birth rate, the death rate, the inflation
rate, the prime rate and the unemployment rate combined.
</P>
<P>
   Kamper moved to Redlands High in 1992 and introduced what would
soon be called ``Connections'' to her psychology classes. Word
spread, and eight years later the 15-lesson course is part of the
curriculum at more than 400 high schools in 32 states and eight
other countries (Belgium, France, Germany, Norway, Australia, South
Africa, Egypt and Russia).
</P>
<P>
   High schools have dabbled in family skills for a long time, but
``Connections'' probes relationships and marriage more deeply and
creatively than previous courses. Guided by teachers trained in the
program and a 52-page workbook, students take the Keirsey-Bates
personality assessment test and explore how well they know
themselves and how others see them.
</P>
<P>
   They look at how their families communicate, study communication
skills that foster relationships, and think about what they want _
and what they don't want _ in a partner. Through role-playing they
get at least a taste of marital stressors and learn techniques for
dealing with conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly it's a crash course in a big subject, but you have to
start somewhere. If 10 seasoned adults sat in on ``Connections,''
two would lament having had to learn this stuff the hard way, and
the other eight, if they were wise, would take notes. Kamper knows
the terrain, having been happily married herself for 31 years and
possessing a master's degree in family studies and training in
marriage and family counseling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of anything you guys do in life,'' she tells her students,
``marriage will be among the hardest.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid growing concern over divorce, which has become as much an
American institution as baseball, ``Connections'' isn't the only
relationship tutorial to find its way into high school classrooms
in the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   In conjunction with the American Bar Association, Philadelphia
divorce lawyer Lynne Gold-Bikin has created ``Partners,'' a program
of 10 videotapes of a fictional couple fighting over issues spouses
frequently fight about. Sometimes the conflicts escalate and get
ugly, other times they go well and are resolved. Students learn
techniques for resolution and practice them in class with a
partner.
</P>
<P>
   Another program emphasizing communication and conflict
resolution skills is ``Building Relationships,'' designed by
Minnesota family psychologist David H. Olson.
</P>
<P>
   Introduced just last year, the curriculum already has been
adopted by high schools in 10 states. Olson's Twin Cities company,
Life Innovations, also owns PREPARE, a 195-question compatibility
test for adult couples on the brink of marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are willing to be more honest on a questionnaire than
they are with their partner,'' Olson claims. But a little insight
can be dangerous. According to Olson's research, about a fourth of
those who take PREPARE test out as ``conflicted,'' a designation
that gives them an 80 percent chance of divorce. The social
scientist takes satisfaction in having spared a million couples
that fate. More than 10 percent of those who take the test break
off their engagements.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Time columnist Amy Dickinson struck just the right
irony in noting that her local bookstore ``has a shelf of
relationship books that is longer than most relationships.''
Harville Hendrix, John Bradshaw, Maggie Scarf, Laura Schlessinger,
Joy Browne, Barbara DeAngelis, John Gray ... Multitudes have read
them all and plenty of others, attended workshops and logged pricey
hours in therapy, yet the divorce rate just hangs in there at
midfield, more reliable than the lunar cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Since all that reading and counseling seem to have no effect
other than a redistribution of wealth, and given, moreover, that
second marriages fail at a slightly higher rate than do first
marriages, perhaps we should begin to question whether partnering
can be learned _ in high school or at any age.
</P>
<P>
   Having empirically analyzed 2,000 married couples over more than
two decades, University of Washington researcher John Gottman,
author of the 1994 book ``Why Marriages Succeed Or Fail,'' has
concluded that most couples wage the same battles over and over for
the life of their marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you pick somebody to marry, you automatically have chosen
your set of unresolvable relationship problems,'' he says. ``You'll
never solve them.''
</P>
<P>
   As a culture, we can't even seem to solve the most fundamental
and recurrent problem: selection error. No matter how fervently the
sages counsel against marrying our parents, marrying our fantasies,
marrying strangers, marrying personality disorders, we keep looking
for love in all the wrong faces. Sex drive and emotional need
override intellect and judgment _ so much for all those books _ and
by the time we come to our senses, we find ourselves in a wedlock
headlock, more inmate than soulmate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I could randomly pair up people and they'd have better
relationships than the ones they choose on their own,'' says Olson.
</P>
<P>
   One of Gottman's observations is that the divorce stats, as
troubling as they are, don't tell the full story, that in fact
three-quarters of all married couples have ``crummy
relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our culture sets a very high standard for what a marriage
should be,'' says Olson, ``but then it doesn't provide any good
ways to help people develop and maintain those relationships over
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is, well, unpleasant. ``Conflict in a relationship
occurs when reality collides with our expectations,'' says clinical
psychologist Peter T. Pearson, a consulting associate professor at
Stanford University and co-founder of a Menlo Park, Calif., shrink
tank called The Couples Institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where it starts.'' At this point, we do the logical,
sensible, obvious thing. ``Most people get into trouble because
they set goals for their partner,'' Pearson says. ``It comes under
the heading of 'nothing's impossible for the other person.'''
</P>
<P>
   Psychology author Jo Coudert tackled this theme 35 years ago in
her graceful book of wisdom, ``Advice From A Failure'': ``If you
are among the angry, with the best will in the world you located
the source of the trouble in someone else and said, 'If I can just
get him to change, then I will be able to behave as I should.'''
</P>
<P>
   This is the road more traveled, a paradox because it doesn't
lead anywhere anyone would want to be.
</P>
<P>
   Kamper's class is popular with students, but can she leaven
their expectations and alter their destiny or will three-fourths of
them end up in crummy relationships?
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things you can teach them,'' says David Schnarch, a
therapist and author of a book (``Passionate Marriage: Sex, Love,
and Intimacy in Emotionally Committed Relationships'') that shuns
traditional approaches, ``is that a three-week course won't help
them avoid the problems, because the problems are not to be
avoided.''
</P>
<P>
   Schnarch says that we have it all backward.
</P>
<P>
   ``The struggles of marriage are not caused by ignorance,'' he
explains. ``They're not caused by the absence of caring or a lack
of communication. They are part of a very difficult but natural,
inevitable process that has driven the evolution of the human race.
By going through the struggles we become capable of having a better
marriage. When you see it that way, your difficulties are much
easier to tolerate, and even in the midst of the worst of it,
you're more likely to stay resilient and stick in there and let the
thing move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   However much truth that view may contain, it could only be seen
as hopeful and alluring to someone looking at marriage from the
inside. What do we say to high school students looking at marriage
with uncertain anticipation from the outside?
</P>
<P>
   ``What we can teach kids,'' Schnarch says, ``is that marriage
will teach them things that there's no way they can learn now. They
can't learn them ahead of time because marriage itself is the
lesson.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't teach an 18-year-old about marriage,'' Kamper agrees.
``Only marriage can do that. But the lessons they learn here will
give them a much better chance of handling the lessons marriage has
for them.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
