<HEADER>
A5831 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r t BC-23TRAVEL-BRUNCH-LADN &LR;      04-24 0440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-23TRAVEL-BRUNCH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FEAST FIT FOR ROYALTY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by LANG) 
(Eds: For use with Montecito main) 
By ERIC NOLAND 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTECITO _ The hotel Sunday brunch has evolved a bit since its
decadent origins in the 1970s. While the spreads are every bit as
dizzying as they were then, the selections in many cases are
broader, healthier and fresher, with chef attendants on hand to
cook many items to order.
</P>
<P>
   The trend is exemplified at the Four Seasons Biltmore in
Montecito. It has developed as a popular indulgence for travelers _
not only those on weekend getaways to Santa Barbara, but also for
day-trippers.
</P>
<P>
   The setting, to begin with, is hard to beat: views of the ocean
from two patios and the sun-washed indoor dining area, which is
topped by a massive retractable skylight.
</P>
<P>
   And the food is superb.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Sunday, there were no fewer than six chef attendants
on hand to produce made-to-order items: omelets, waffles, carved
meats, sauteed mushrooms, espresso drinks, crepes and blintzes. The
mushroom station is particularly intriguing. It featured three
different types of mushrooms _ shiitake, oyster, fist-sized
portobello _ cooked in front of you in a garlic-rich saute.
</P>
<P>
   As for diversity, the brunch included a table devoted entirely
to Asian cuisine: dim sum, sushi, won tons. Another offered a
generous array of salads and low-fat items.
</P>
<P>
   There was even a station just for kids. On a table that was
knee-high to an adult, it offered French toast wedges, peanut
butter-and-jelly sandwiches _ with the crusts trimmed off, of
course _ chicken wings and French fries. (On a brunch visit a few
years ago, I couldn't resist a harmless regression: I waited until
the coast was clear, then loaded up a plate here.)
</P>
<P>
   Other highlights of the brunch: smoked trout, mackerel and
salmon; an assortment of pates; an 8-foot rowboat filled with
crushed ice and topped with boiled shrimp and oysters on the half
shell; an enormous filet of roasted, seasoned salmon at the carving
table; fresh-squeezed orange juice poured freely at the table
(along with a serviceable champagne); and, at the dessert table, a
sinfully delicious bread pudding made with bananas, pecans and rum.
</P>
<P>
   During our brunch, a steel-drum musician provided a backdrop of
1950s calypso music, plunking out such tunes as ``Jamaica
Farewell.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday brunch at the Four Seasons Biltmore in Montecito is
served from 10 a.m. to 1:30 p.m. and costs $39.95 for adults, $16
for children ages 4 to 12 (age 3 and under free). Reservations are
strongly recommended. Phone: (805) 565-8237.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
