<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE WAR OVER ELIAN CONTINUES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The saga of little Elian Gonzalez is a
heart-rending human drama, with so many political and emotional
distractions it is easy to lose sight of the central issue.
</P>
<P>
   This is not about Fidel Castro, or communism, or President
Clinton or the degree of force involved in the armed raid on the
Miami house where Elian was held.
</P>
<P>
   This saga was not about Attorney General Janet Reno's tactics or
the Cuban-American politics that dominate south Florida and
periodically intimidate the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   We will certainly hear a great deal about those issues in the
coming months, as a Republican Congress that loves to second-guess
the administration investigates the episode.
</P>
<P>
   But what was really going on was something else. It is less
about what happened than why it happened, although Clinton's
critics would like to make this into a political blunder useful in
the 2000 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   At bottom, this drama was about family values, parental
authority and respect for the rule of law. It was about reuniting a
father and son who were kept apart by distant relatives who had no
legal right to custody of the boy. It was about the right of a
father to choose where his family will live, even if it is under a
dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno had patiently negotiated with the
relatives for five months, even going personally to Miami at one
point to demonstrate her sincerity. But the relatives persistently
stalled; finally, a responsible government must stop talking and
act in the face of continued defiance.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department had every right to enforce the father's
legal custody. Despite the terrifying spectacle of the pre-dawn
raid, no shots were fired, no one was injured.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami relatives have behaved irrationally throughout, a
reality proving that Reno was correct to give up on them. They
hinted they had weapons in the house. They exploited Elian
shamelessly, refusing to let his father speak to him on the phone
and issuing videotape on which Elian said he didn't want to go to
Cuba. Increasingly, they seemed controlled by radical anti-Castro
activists.
</P>
<P>
   After the raid, they claimed the federal agents had cursed at
them and threatened their lives, a far-fetched accusation for which
there is no evidence. They claimed the first picture of a happy
Elian reunited with his father was doctored. They claimed Elian had
been drugged. They rushed to Washington, making a public show of
appearing at the gates of Andrews Air Force base and demanding to
see Elian immediately, waving as a prop an Easter basket. Their
demands were harsh and totally inappropriate. For all their
complaints, they were able to behave that way because this is a
free country.
</P>
<P>
   The relatives gave an inflammatory press conference with New
Hampshire Sen. Bob Smith, a conservative publicity hound running
who briefly and unsuccessfully sought the Republican presidential
nomination last year on an anti-abortion platform.
</P>
<P>
   Smith accused the Justice Department of ``abuse of power.''
</P>
<P>
   Marisleysis Gonzalez, Elian's cousin, called the president a
liar. Miami family members indicate they will sue the government,
for something or other.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the case will drag on for some time. Elian must stay in
America until a three-judge federal appeals court panel can decide
whether as a 6-year-old Elian is mature enough to merit a political
asylum hearing with the Immigration and Naturalization Service. The
INS argues that Elian is too young to seek asylum for himself and
that his father as his legal guardian must act in Elian's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   The decision at the May 11 hearing, no matter which way it goes,
can be appealed to the full 12-member court or directly to the
Supreme Court. Heaven knows how long all that might take.
</P>
<P>
   The politics won't end right away, either. The raid does not
seem to be upsetting most American voters. A majority of 57 percent
told a CNN/Gallup poll that they approved of the federal agents'
actions. And 57 percent said it was in Elian's best interest to
live with his father in Cuba rather than with the relatives in
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   But in the Cuban-American community it is very big. This
probably kills Vice President Al Gore's effort to give Texas Gov.
George W. Bush a real race in Florida. Gore is the big loser here;
his mealy-mouthed position has always looked like pandering and now
it seems a certifiable waste of time. He repeated his view that the
boy's case should have been handled through a family court, a
meaningless dodge. But he said nothing about his view of Elian's
reunion with his father.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, by contrast, condemned ``the terror of middle of-the-night
raids,'' empathizing with immigrants accustomed to a history of
harsh government repression. It may not work well elsewhere, where
such terror is only imagined, but it is likely to work with the
agitated anti-Castro Cuban-American community in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
