<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5838 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-BIO-PROSPECTING-N     04-24 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BIO-PROSPECTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARK'S DEAL TO CHARGE FOR RESEARCH UPHELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888 603-1036 or 888
346-9867.)  
 (Science Times)  
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a decision that could give a boost to ``bioprospecting'' in
national parks, a federal judge has upheld a precedent-setting
agreement in which a biotechnology company will pay Yellowstone
National Park for the right to search its geysers and hot springs
for commercially valuable microbes.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Royce C. Lamberth of federal district court in Washington,
recently dismissed a lawsuit charging that the agreement violated
rules prohibiting the ``sale or commercial use'' of natural
resources of the national parks.
</P>
<P>
   The Yellowstone agreement with the Diversa Corp. was announced
in 1997 as the prototype for a policy by the National Park Service
to be paid for drugs or chemicals derived from the national park
resources. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The policy reflects a change in thinking in many nations. In the
past, scientists who took samples of plants, animals or microbes
were generally free to exploit discoveries without compensating the
country that was the source of the material.
</P>
<P>
   But many nations, realizing the potential value of such genetic
resources to the biotechnology industry, are demanding pay for such
bioprospecting. And, proponents hope the compensation will help pay
for the conservation efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The suit against the park service was filed by some
biotechnology critics and environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   In dismissing the suit on April 12, Lamberth agreed with the
park service's interpretation that Diversa would be profiting from
discoveries involving the microbes, not from the sale of actual
specimens, which would not become the company's property.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also said the agreement was consistent with the
conservation mandate of the park service, in part because the money
from Diversa would help pay for conservation programs. He noted
that Yellowstone issues 250 to 300 research permits a year and that
the only difference in this case was that Yellowstone could share
some of the benefits arising from that research.
</P>
<P>
   Diversa, of San Diego, agreed to pay the park service about
$100,000 over five years plus royalties of 0.5 percent to 10
percent on sales of any commercial products they derived.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the ruling, the agreement remains suspended by a ruling
Lamberth made a year ago in the same lawsuit. At that time he said
that the park service's agreement with Diversa represented a
``dramatic change'' in national policy and therefore required an
environmental impact assessment.
</P>
<P>
   That assessment, which will look at the policy as a whole, could
take several years to complete. But once it is complete, the
project, and perhaps others, should now be able to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   John Varley, director of Yellowstone's Center for Resources,
called the Diversa agreement ``good for science, good for parks and
good for the citizens of our country.''
</P>
<P>
   But Beth Burrows, president of the Edmonds Institute, the lead
plaintiff, said the latest ruling would be appealed. She said the
park service had sold what belonged to the public to a private
company for ``way too little.''
</P>
<P>
   In seeking profit-sharing, Yellowstone wants to avoid a repeat
of what happened in the 1960s, when a microbe discovered in a hot
spring at Yellowstone yielded a heat-resistant enzyme that is now
instrumental in the polymerase chain reaction, a technique for
replicating DNA that is widely used in science, medicine and
fingerprinting.
</P>
<P>
   The inventor won a Nobel Prize, and patents related to the
enzyme now bring in an estimated $100 million a year to
Hoffmann-LaRoche, the drug company. Yellowstone has received
nothing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
