<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TAXPAYERS WIN ANOTHER ROUND 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Since someone trying to raise shrimp in West
Texas probably needs all the help he can get, it was understandable
that Bart Reid would turn to a government loan program.
</P>
<P>
   Reid got the loan guarantee for his company, Permian Sea Shrimp
&AMP; Seafood of Imperial City. But he also got what he didn't want _
public disclosure of his business records.
</P>
<P>
   His experience prompted a court fight over privacy rights vs.
the taxpayers' right to know how their money is being spent _ or,
in the case of a loan guarantee, how it may be spent if the loan
goes bad.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to an Austin judge who overlooked the Constitution, Reid
and his bank won the first round. Thanks to a second judge, the
taxpayers won the second. But the overriding conflict isn't over.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, it will worsen as businesses continue to seek the
taxpayers' help and _ in this age of increasing privatization of
public services _ realize new profits from government contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Raising shrimp in land-locked West Texas _ Pecos County, to be
more precise _ may not be as improbable as it seems, thanks to
aquifers with water as saline as the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   But it was risky enough for the First National Bank of Monahans
to ask that the state help guarantee a $360,000 loan to Reid's
company. The guarantee was made through a Texas Department of
Agriculture program designed to encourage innovative business
ventures for whom conventional financing is difficult.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal, Reid provided the state with information
about his company, including financial data and names of clients.
And he also signed an agreement that the information could be made
public, which was only proper because Texas taxpayers could be
called upon to bail out the company if it defaulted.
</P>
<P>
   But when The Associated Press, acting under the state's Public
Information Act, obtained copies of Reid's loan documents from the
agricultural agency to help prepare a story on the loan guarantee
program, the businessman and his banker objected and went to court.
</P>
<P>
   Reid said he hadn't realized how much of his company's
information would be made public and said the material released to
the AP included trade secrets that could help competitors.
</P>
<P>
   State District Judge Margaret Cooper of Austin, ignoring clear
constitutional precedent, granted Reid and his lender a restraining
order earlier this month, temporarily prohibiting the AP from
publishing a story based on the documents that the news
organization had legally obtained.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's order amounted to an unconstitutional act of prior
restraint, and, fortunately, it was lifted eight days later by a
second Austin judge, Suzanne Covington.
</P>
<P>
   The AP then published its story by reporter Chris Williams,
which made clear the importance of requiring participants in the
agricultural loan program to share their financial data with the
public.
</P>
<P>
   The program, according to a state audit that the AP also
obtained, has a $7.8 million deficit. And 22 of the 83 loans
guaranteed under the program from 1993 to 1996 had defaulted,
meaning tax dollars may eventually be required to repay them.
</P>
<P>
   No loans guaranteed after 1996 have gone bad, and Reid's loan is
current, although his company was still in the red last year, the
AP reported.
</P>
<P>
   With hard work and good fortune, Reid may be successful. Texas
taxpayers should certainly hope so, since they may lose some money
if he fails.
</P>
<P>
   And as long as taxpayers are potentially on the hook should Reid
default on his loan, they have every right to know what shape his
company was in when he got the loan guarantee. Openness helps keep
everyone accountable, including officials who approved Reid's
application.
</P>
<P>
   There will always be conflict between the confidentiality that
cloaks most business dealings and the openness that is supposed to
characterize government. And loan guarantees are only part of the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Open government issues also have been growing in Texas in the
rush to privatize a host of public services _ from printing
documents to running prisons. Some companies are eager to profit
from taxpayers but less willing to share information.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses that dislike scrutiny should avoid the public trough.
But many won't, as long as they can find a way to restrict what the
public can learn about public-private endeavors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
