<DOCNO> NYT20000424.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5841 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT &LR;      04-24 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHATTERPROOF CROPS
</P>
<P>
   Consumers of a certain age will no doubt remember when Prell
shampoo switched from glass bottles (the kind they dropped pearls
into in those memorable TV commercials) to unbreakable plastic
squeeze tubes. Suddenly, bathrooms everywhere were safer places.
</P>
<P>
   Now, several decades later, there is an effort under way to make
some agricultural plants shatterproof as well. The goal is not to
make fields safer for farmers, of course, but to increase crop
yields.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists at the University of California at San Diego have
identified genes in a plant that are responsible for the shattering
of the seed pod, which allows seeds to disperse. The scientists,
reporting in the journal Nature, found the genes in that old
laboratory standby, arabidopsis, a weed that is a member of the
mustard family, but the findings could have implications for
related crops like canola, the source of canola oil.
</P>
<P>
   The seed pod of arabidopsis consists of two elongated
half-shells separated by a thin structure called a replum. The
genes, affect a narrow band of cells where the half-shells meet the
replum. At a late stage in development, these cells begin to
separate. Eventually the half-shells detach, and the seeds fall
out. In mutant strains of arabidopsis that lacked these genes, the
researchers discovered, seed pods did not shatter.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers suspect that identical genes are found in
canola. Because oil accumulates in canola seeds relatively late in
development, farmers usually wait until the crop matures before
harvesting it. This can mean that much of the crop _ up to 50
percent in some cases _ is lost to pod shatter. So by developing
shatterproof varieties, yields of canola oil may be greatly
increased.
</P>
<P>
   AMAZON'S VANISHING TREES
</P>
<P>
   There is a divide-and-conquer chain of events being played out
in the central Amazon. Humans divide up the rain forest by
clear-cutting, and nature conquers by killing off a
disproportionately large number of big trees in the remaining
forest.
</P>
<P>
   That is the conclusion of a study of 350 square miles of rain
forest near Manaus, Brazil, by scientists with the National
Institute for Amazonian Research. The researchers, who wrote about
their work in Nature, kept track of more than 64,000 trees with
trunks more than four inches in diameter for about two decades.
Some of the trees were in plots of land within continuous areas of
rain forest, while others were in fragments of forest up to 100
acres in size.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers found that many more trees died near the edges
of forest fragments than within continuous forests, and that a far
higher proportion of the dead trees near edges were more than 24
inches in trunk diameter. Since trees of that size make up
something like one-quarter of the above-ground biomass in the
Amazon, the study results are a cause for concern.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists suggest three reasons why large trees in
fragmented areas are dying at a faster rate. First, thick,
inflexible trunks may be more susceptible to uprooting in windy
conditions, which are worse near the edge of forests. Second, old
trees are more susceptible to infestation by lianas and other
parasitic vines, which are more prevalent near edges. And third,
taller trees get more sun and are therefore more likely to be
affected by drier edge conditions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-00 1559EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000424.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 16:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5842 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-YOUNG-CONDUCTOR-HNS &LR;      04-24 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-CONDUCTOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     YOUNG CONDUCTOR ENJOYS STELLAR DEBUT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ALLAN ULRICH  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Few young conductors live up to their advance
notices, but reports on Alan Gilbert proved mostly right last week,
when the young American musician made his San Francisco Symphony
debut at Davies Symphony Hall and scored high where you would least
expect it _ in the Teutonic Romantic repertoire.
</P>
<P>
   Any conductor for whom Robert Schumann's Symphony No. 2 in C
Major, Op. 61, is a calling card is someone worth watching.
Gilbert's debut performance Thursday duplicated the fine reports
that came out of New York last winter when Gilbert led the work
with the Orchestra of St. Luke's. On this side of the continent, he
found the thread that connects these four movements (which in
lesser hands can sound awfully meandering and diffuse) and wove a
ravishingly lyrical tapestry. He is one to watch.
</P>
<P>
   New York-born, Curtis and Juilliard-trained, Gilbert recently
assumed a position as chief conductor and artistic adviser to the
Royal Stockholm Philharmonic in Sweden. It's impossible to believe
that his future activities won't be concentrated stateside. For the
San Francisco Symphony, he offered sane musicianship, a jittery
podium style in which almost every entry was cued and uncommon
respect for dynamics. Most listeners would not rate the C Major
Symphony the best of Schumann's four, but the case for it has
rarely been made so cogently.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert's entire debut program verged on the unorthodox. He
opened with the Symphony premiere of Jay Alan Yim's ``Rough Magic''
_ you have to have a bit of razzle-dazzle _ and accompanied the
orchestra's principal cello Michael Grebanier in Shostakovich's
Cello Concerto No. 2, Op. 126.
</P>
<P>
   What impressed most in the Schumann was its proportion. Gilbert
divided his violins in the 18th-century manner, encouraged only
moderate vibrato and proposed decisive cadences. Perhaps the sound
of the orchestra missed the lustrousness to which we have become
accustomed this season, but responsiveness counts as much as
sonority.
</P>
<P>
   If this is a work the Romantic excess of which needs taming,
some of that wildness should occasionally seep through the
restraints. Gilbert launched into the opening sostenuto at such a
daringly slow tempo that the symphony's brass found themselves
seriously extended. They held on, barely. But, then the sweep
through the Allegro was robust, assertive and abundant in often
concealed detail.
</P>
<P>
   The Scherzo looks back to Mendelssohn in its busy figurations
and is as mercurial as Schumann ever gets. Here, Gilbert guided the
strings without serious mishap, abridging some of the conventional
rests in an impulsive dash to the double bar line. The Adagio
remains the composer's most heartfelt and here the conductor let it
flow, keeping the textures light and the articulation clean,
sustaining a pulse, scarcely regearing for transitions. Excellent
contributions here from the winds, notably principal clarinet David
Breeden.
</P>
<P>
   The effect was magical and the dash through the finale, its
final statement in the home key, impressed deeply. This should take
care of the Schumann Second Symphony for a while.
</P>
<P>
   The last word on the Shostakovich Concerto, however, was not
pronounced in the San Francisco Symphony performance on Thursday.
Finished in 1966 and premiered by Mstislav Rostropovich, the piece
betrays the composer's fingerprints everywhere _ in the slow,
soulful ``Largo'' and in the burlesque elements of the Allegretto.
Here, a Russian street song is transformed to the point of parody.
The final movement, with its trading of fanfares between brass and
soloist, offers episodes of innovation before a recapitulation.
</P>
<P>
   Shostakovich cannot resist, at the end, the ironic jabs (from
the percussion) that, along with a certain mournfulness, mark his
final period. Yet, the piece wanders too much for its own sake,
missing the acerbic economy of the earlier concerto in E-flat.
</P>
<P>
   What the later concerto retains are the Olympian demands made
upon the soloist, who is rarely silent throughout and whose primacy
is rarely challenged by the lightly scored orchestra. Grebanier
introduced this work to the San Francisco Symphony in 1985 and he
has mastered much of it since then.
</P>
<P>
   The lyrical writing drew a tensile line from the soloist
Thursday, a bit edgy, but phrased with melancholic expansiveness.
Where Shostakovich demands a more fiery response, Grebanier
remained dutiful and merely human. Double stops were not clean,
pitch was unreliable, tone was rough, dynamics were slighted.
</P>
<P>
   If you were interested in mere sound, ``Rough Magic'' furnished
a full 16 minutes of it. Premiered in 1997 by the Chicago Symphony,
this percussive essay is basically one long chord progression. It's
also noisy, unrelenting and entirely unrelated to its
Shakespeare-derived title. Gilbert and an augmented percussion
section gave it their all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-00 1601EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000424.0229 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5844 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT     04-24 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT WAFFLES ON FOURTH AMENDMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.)  
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c.2000 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This term, the U.S. Supreme Court heard appeals in three cases
that involve the Fourth Amendment. Amazingly, what's left of the
Fourth Amendment came out unscathed in two out of the three court
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   This may indicate a tiny change of heart among the court's more
conservative justices. It's too little, too late _ in the past two
decades, the high court has hacked most of the essential
protections out of the Fourth Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   The Fourth Amendment once guaranteed: ``The right of the people
to be secure in their persons, houses, papers, and effects, against
unreasonable searches and seizures shall not be violated, and no
warrants shall issue but upon probable cause, supported by oath or
affirmation, and particularly describing the place to be searched,
and the persons or things to be seized.'' However, the words
``secure,'' ``warrants,'' ``probable cause,'' and ``particularly
describing'' in the amendment's proscription against government
intrusion have been shredded into mere confetti by the court.
</P>
<P>
   The high court allows random drug testing of groups of people _
with no probable cause and no particular person as a target.
``Reasonable suspicion'' has replaced ``probable cause'' as a
criteria for many police searches and seizures. The court allows
law enforcement officials to seize and keep citizens' property
based upon so-called reasonable suspicion, even when no criminal
charges have been made.
</P>
<P>
   The best recent news for the Fourth Amendment comes from the
case, Bond vs. United States, decided April 17, in which the high
court reversed the ruling by the Fifth Circuit U.S. Court of
Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Bond was a passenger on a Greyhound bus traveling from
California to Arkansas. The bus stopped at a border patrol
checkpoint in Texas and a border patrol agent boarded the bus to
check the immigration status of the passengers.
</P>
<P>
   According to court documents, the agent worked his way to the
back of the bus and was satisfied that the passengers were lawfully
in the country. He began walking back to the front of the bus, but
along the way, he squeezed the soft luggage which passengers had
placed in the overhead racks.
</P>
<P>
   When he squeezed the green canvas bag belonging to Bond, he felt
a brick-like object in it and asked Bond if it was his bag. Bond
admitted that it was. The border agent asked if he could inspect
it, and Bond agreed to allow the agent to open his bag. The agent
found a brick of methamphetamine wrapped in duct tape and rolled in
a pair of pants.
</P>
<P>
   Bond was found guilty of possession and sent to prison. He
appealed on the grounds that the agent's manipulation of his canvas
bag was an illegal search in violation of the Fourth Amendment. The
court of appeals upheld his conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William Rehnquist wrote the 7-2 decision for the
Supreme Court. He asked two pivotal questions. Did Bond, by his
conduct, exhibit an actual expectation of privacy in regard to the
contents of his luggage? And was Bond's expectation of privacy
``one that society is prepared to recognize as reasonable''?
</P>
<P>
   The court answered ``yes'' to both questions. The bag was opaque
and Bond had placed it directly above his seat. Passengers may
expect bus employees to move their bags but not prod them in an
exploratory manner.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, the court ruled, the border agent in his ``physical
manipulation'' of Bond's bag ``violated the Fourth Amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   This ruling seems to pull back from the high court's previous
decisions that allow police to sift through garbage bags on public
streets, to use aircraft to look into a fenced backyard of a home,
and to use dogs to sniff for drugs hidden inside luggage. This
clash with prior decisions caused Justices Stephen Breyer and
Antonin Scalia to dissent.
</P>
<P>
   On March 28, in the case, Florida vs. J.L., a unanimous Supreme
Court ruled that an anonymous tip, which lacks any indication of
being reliable, cannot be used as the sole reason to justify a
police officer stopping and frisking a person for a gun.
</P>
<P>
   This ruling comports with previous rulings of the court but
clarifies the limits of anonymous tips. The high court also denied
the Justice Department's request for an exception to the
stop-and-frisk law when it involves firearms. Pat-downs cannot be
conducted simply on the whim of a police officer. There must be
reasonable suspicion, says the court.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 12, a 5-4 Supreme Court decided the case, Illinois vs.
Wardlow, in which it ruled that law enforcement officials can stop
and frisk a person who flees a high crime area when the police
arrive.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist wrote for the majority: ``Headlong flight _ wherever
it occurs _ is the consummate act of evasion: it is not necessarily
indicative of wrongdoing, but it is certainly suggestive of such.''
And triggers the notion of ``reasonable suspicion,'' according to
the court. Therefore, the stop-and-frisk does not violate the
Fourth Amendment, wrote Rehnquist, because the ``stop is a ...
minimal intrusion, simply allowing the officer to briefly
investigate further.''
</P>
<P>
   The four dissenting justices found Rehnquist's expansive notion
of ``reasonable suspicion'' unreasonable.
</P>
<P>
   The very wording of the Wardlow ruling indicates just how much
has been eliminated from the protections supposedly guaranteed by
the Fourth Amendment. The court now claims that a stop-and-frisk is
merely a ``minimal intrusion.''
</P>
<P>
   I doubt whether the framers of our Constitution would have
considered it that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-00 1610EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
