<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5848 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-SPIN-ART-NYT &LR;      04-24 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SPIN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS LINING UP TO EXPLAIN THE MATH OF A SIMPLE TOY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo has moved as NYT3 to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.)  
 (Science Times)  
 By KENNETH CHANG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spin a quarter.
</P>
<P>
   As the spin slows, the coin begins to topple, and the spinning
transforms into a new dynamic: the coin rolls around along its rim
in a circular motion. As the coin topples farther, it rolls around
faster and faster, emitting a whir of rising pitch. Then, with a
final shudder, the quarter lies still.
</P>
<P>
   Fascinated by this phenomenon, a San Diego engineer several
years ago created a toy that extends the circular rolling to
seemingly gravity-defying lengths of time. That toy, in turn,
inspired a British scientist to delve into the underlying
mathematics, and now he has devised a model to explain how the
rolling speed can accelerate even as the disc is losing energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a paradox,'' said Dr. H. Keith Moffatt, director of the
Isaac Newton Institute for Mathematical Sciences in Cambridge,
England. ``To explain that sort of behavior with mathematics is
very interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Moffatt, who reported his work in the current issue of the
journal Nature, said he was paging through a mail order catalog a
couple of years ago looking for toys for his grandchildren when an
item called ``Euler's disc'' caught his eye. Named after 18th
century Swiss mathematician Leonhard Euler, the toy consists of
just two pieces: a 14-ounce chrome-plated steel disc and a
circular, slightly concave platform. ``I sent for it,'' Moffatt
said. ``It's an interesting and instructive toy.''
</P>
<P>
   The operating instructions were simple: spin disc on platform.
Watch.
</P>
<P>
   Moffatt observed that the disc itself was not rotating very
fast. What was rotating was the point of contact where the disc met
the surface. The phenomenon is similar to what happens when
baseball fans do the ``wave'' _ the pattern of rising and falling
arms circles the stadium, but the fans themselves remain
stationary. Similarly, the rim of the disc is rising and falling at
a quickening pace, but the disc is almost stationary when looked at
from above.
</P>
<P>
   In a vacuum, a perfectly rigid disc on an absolutely hard
surface would roll forever. In the real world, air resistance slows
the disc, toppling it over.
</P>
<P>
   Moffatt, who usually directs his mathematical inquiries in the
field of fluid mechanics, became intrigued at how the disc
continued its pirouette for more than a minute and a half, compared
with the few seconds of rattling around of a coin.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with an equation Euler first wrote down more than two
centuries ago to describe the motion of spinning objects, Moffatt
calculated that heavier discs rolled longer and that the rolling
speed increased as the disc approached the surface.
</P>
<P>
   In the final one one-hundredth of a second before the disc comes
to a rest, the theory fails _ the calculations suggest the disc
would reach an infinite rolling speed, which, as a practical
matter, is impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``What breaks down in this system is that the disc stops rolling
and begins slipping,'' Moffatt said. Still, for scientists, knowing
when a theory does not work is as important as knowing when it does
work. In this case, the calculations assume the disc is rolling
without slipping. The prediction of an infinite rolling speed
suggests this assumption does not hold in the final fraction of
second.
</P>
<P>
   The scientific attention naturally pleased the toy's inventor,
Joseph Bendik of San Diego. ``That's a very nice thing,'' Bendik
said of Moffatt's paper.
</P>
<P>
   While a material sciences engineer at Hughes Aircraft in the
mid-1980s, Bendik started playing around with some metal discs,
noticing that on hard surfaces, the discs rolled around longer.
``About 40 to 45 seconds, the brain thinks, `Wow, what's making
that thing go for such a long time?''' Bendik said.
</P>
<P>
   Through experimentation, Bendik figured out the same
relationship between rolling time and disc weight calculated by
Moffatt. With aesthetic improvements _ a holographic sticker and a
mirrored platform _ the toy found a commercial home at Tangent Toy
of San Diego in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Moffatt was not the only scientist intrigued by Euler's disc.
After reading an article about the toy, Dr. David O. Harris, a
professor of chemistry at the University of California at Santa
Barbara, wrote Bendik a note pointing out that the disc's motion
resembled the dynamics of some ring-shaped molecules.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said he admired Moffatt's calculations but, as an
experimentalist, he wanted to put them to the test.
</P>
<P>
   ``The obvious question is, has anyone put one of these discs in
a vacuum chamber?'' he said. ``If I can find a vacuum system big
enough, I'll do it, and then I'll write a paper and put it in
Nature that either confirms it or doesn't. That's what science is
all about, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, he found a colleague down the hall with a
suitable chamber. ``It's not profound,'' Harris said of his
projected experiment, but it is interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Now, all he needed was to buy the toy.
</P>
</TEXT>
