<HEADLINE>
15 RUSSIAN TROOPS KILLED IN AMBUSH BY CHECHEN REBELS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By PATRICK E. TYLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Just days after Aslan Maskhadov, the leader of the
secessionist southern region of Chechnya, was reported to have
ordered guerrilla commanders to suspend combat operations so that
peace talks might take hold, a rebel force attacked a Russian
military convoy on Sunday, Russian officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said that as many as 15 Russian soldiers were
killed. A Chechen rebel spokesman, Movladi Udugov, contended that
80 Russian troops had died and an armored column of 23 tanks and
armored vehicles had been destroyed in the attack near the village
of Serzhen-Yurt, 16 miles from the bombed out regional capital,
Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   The attack was organized by a Chechen guerrilla leader, Shamil
Basayev, whose forces placed 15 anti-tank mines in the convoy's
path, the rebels said. A two-hour firefight ensued, and Russian
warplanes and helicopters were summoned to rescue the unit and
evacuate the dead and wounded.
</P>
<P>
   A Chechen spokesman said the Russians bombed the nearby village
of Serzhen-Yurt in retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   Russian military officials initially said only five soldiers had
died, but Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev acknowledged Monday that
15 soldiers died and six were wounded. He said six vehicles were
destroyed, most of them fuel tankers. Russian troops said they had
killed 20 Chechen rebels and captured 14.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Gennady Troshev, commander of the Russian forces in
Chechnya, said at a news conference in Khankala: ``The commanders
cannot be reproached for this. The servicemen acted in full
accordance with the rules, and the fighters were properly
repulsed.'' A group of 80 to 100 rebels led by an Arab had
assaulted the convoy along its entire length and from both sides,
he said. He gave the Russian death toll as 13.
</P>
<P>
   The attack followed accusations that incompetence had led to a
rebel ambush a month ago in which 36 Russians died. And it ended a
weekend of recriminations over Maskhadov's peace initiative, which
was reported Friday in an interview published by the newspaper
Kommersant. In that interview, Maskhadov said the relative calm on
the battlefield in recent weeks ``is directly attributed to my
order to suspend the hostilities.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This order is an element of the peaceful resolution plan I
suggested,'' he continued. ``Moreover, I have given my consent to
unconditional liberation of all Russian prisoners. All field
commanders have been ordered to free all prisoners and hostages
they may be holding.''
</P>
<P>
   The interview raised hopes that a peace effort might be in the
formative stages and that Maskhadov might have the support of
powerful field commanders, like Baseyev, to begin serious political
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Baseyev was quoted by Chechen spokesmen as saying,
``We are observing the orders'' of Maskhadov, ``but if the
aggressors attack, we are forced to defend ourselves.'' Baseyev
also claimed that as many as 15,000 Russian troops were in the
Vedeno gorge area, attacking mountain villages and killing dozens
of civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Then, later that day, Maskhadov amended his remarks. In an
interview with the U.S.-funded Radio Liberty, he said the
Kommersant correspondents who had interviewed him ``did not
understand me properly.'' He said he would only call a cease fire
if both sides agreed to stop fighting and political negotiations
began. ``So, on a unilateral cease fire, there was nothing on
that,'' Maskhadov said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   He said Chechen leaders are willing to submit to the peace plan
put forward by the Political Assembly of the Council of Europe,
which calls on both sides to enter a cease fire and undertake
political negotiations without preconditions while releasing all
hostages. He denied that Chechen rebels would be ready to release
prisoners of war without preconditions, as Kommersant had quoted
him as saying.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   What was most apparent by the end of the weekend was that the
war was still on, with large-scale movements of Russian troops into
the gorges south of Grozny. The apparent strategy is to try to trap
rebels, who have demonstrated a capability to carry out hit-and-run
attacks in areas ostensibly under the control of Russian forces.
</P>
<P>
   It was also apparent from weekend statements by Russian
officials that they do not believe Maskhadov has the political or
military strength to control rebel commanders like Baseyev and
that, in any case, the Russia president-elect, Vladimir Putin, and
his senior military advisers remain determined to achieve a
military victory over the major rebel groups still opposing them in
Chechnya.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Also Monday, Ruslan Aushev, the leader of Ingushetia, a region
that borders on Chechnya, estimated that 15,000 to 17,000 rebels
are still active in Chechnya _ more than acknowledged by Russian
military commanders. Aushev, in an interview with Russian
television, said he believed that Maskhadov had been serious in his
effort to initiate peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maskhadov took one more step toward beginning a dialogue,'' by
making the statements attributed to him in Kommersant, he said .
``I understand that if the federal authorities began to support
this dialogue, Maskhadov would give the order to stop combat
operations.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``This process must be mutual.''
</P>
</TEXT>
