<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WACO TRIAL JUROR STILL FOLLOWING 1994 CASE
 &HT;    680&AMP;add. With COURT-WACO.
 &HT;    By TOMMY WITHERSPOON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It has been six years since the Branch Davidian
criminal trial in San Antonio, but Sarah Bain just can't seem to
get it out of her system.
</P>
<P>
   The self-styled ``skeptical patriot'' served as presiding juror
at the 1994 trial of 11 Branch Davidians charged with killing
federal agents during a shootout at Mount Carmel outside Waco on
Feb. 28, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Bain has been openly critical of U.S. District Judge Walter S.
Smith Jr. for sentencing six of the sect members to 40-year prison
terms, even after the jury found them not guilty of murder
conspiracy charges. One defendant is not appealing his sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Bain disagreed with the lengthy sentences and said it was not
the jury's intent to see the Branch Davidians in prison for so
long. She has strong feelings about the sentences, which she said
``absolutely shocked'' her, and does not hesitate to share those
thoughts with anyone.
</P>
<P>
   So it was not too surprising that Bain, now 53 and retired after
teaching high school Spanish for 17 years in New Braunfels, was in
Washington on Monday for oral arguments in the Branch Davidian
appeal before the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am here hoping to see the turnaround of what I consider to
be some really unjust sentences that the court handed down in 1994
following the trial there in San Antonio,'' Bain said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, the jury made that really severe error on the
federal firearms charge, and when we were made aware of that
mistake and the judge told us that would have to be thrown out,
most of us thought, 'Well, good,' because we almost felt trapped
the way it was worded and having to find them guilty on that
count,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After the jury acquitted the Davidians on murder conspiracy
charges, the judge set aside the convictions for using firearms
during a violent crime. He said that the weapons convictions were
not consistent with the murder conspiracy acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   However, government prosecutors argued that inconsistent
verdicts are valid and convinced Smith to reinstate the weapons
charges. The judge later found that the Davidians used ``enhanced''
weapons, such as machine guns and grenades, and agreed with the
government that five of the Davidians deserved 30-year terms on the
gun counts instead of five years.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court agreed to decide if the government should be
required to allege in indictments what type of weapons defendants
use and whether that issue must be presented to juries.
</P>
<P>
   It was not in the Branch Davidian case, and Bain said that was
unfair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am most anxious to see if there isn't some possibility that
those sentences can be taken back down to the minimum instead of
augmented to the maximum,'' she said. ``I think maybe the severity
of the sentences and the fact that the severe sentences are based
on what I consider a jury error is really keeping me involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Bain and a friend from San Antonio were about the only ones not
associated with a party to the litigation or the media to show up
for the Supreme Court session. There were no protests by Davidian
sympathizers, no marches by militia groups who have attended April
19 memorial services at Mount Carmel for those who died in the 1993
fire.
</P>
<P>
   As Bain spoke outside the Supreme Court building, her words were
drowned out by anti-abortion and gay rights groups. The court will
address those hot-button issues later this week, and they seemed to
take some of the spotlight from the controversial Davidian case.
</P>
<P>
   Bain, who has a Spanish and education degree from Baylor
University, said she has attended five of the seven memorial
services at Mount Carmel, hoping to bring her involvement with the
case to a close. It didn't work, she said, adding that she has been
disappointed by some of the ``fringe groups'' who have attended
recent services.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to be in an area where the United States flag is
flying upside down, even though I understand that all that means is
a nation in distress,'' Bain said. ``It is really not unpatriotic,
but it seems unpatriotic to me, and I am a patriot. A skeptical
patriot, but I'm a patriot.''
</P>
<P>
   Bain said the ``intensity'' of the six-week criminal trial in
her hometown seared the case into her psyche.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up until the time of trial, I had no more of an idea about the
Branch Davidians than what was on the 6 o'clock news, and I was
getting tired of that. So I was really not that involved. But
goodness gracious, that trial was so intense and we had to keep it
all bottled up. We weren't to talk to anyone about it, and I
definitely tried to abide by the court's request that we not talk
to other people. So it was all bottled up for 40 days. It was
really just the intensity of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bain, who retired in 1996, is building a new home in San
Antonio. She said after it is finished, she hopes to work as a
volunteer with disabled children and horses in equestrian therapy
sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe that somehow will take my mind off all of this,'' she
said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
