<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AND FITNESS NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAZARDS: That Cuddly Duckling Can Make You Ill
</P>
<P>
   Salmonella is most commonly associated with eating contaminated
food, but federal health officials are now noting other sources:
baby chicks and ducklings.
</P>
<P>
   A recent report from the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention warns that merely handling the young birds _ as children
sometimes do, especially around Easter _ can transmit the disease,
which causes diarrhea, vomiting and fever and can be especially
dangerous to children.
</P>
<P>
   The report noted two outbreaks last year among people who had
handled baby birds. In Michigan, 21 people were infected, three of
whom were hospitalized. In some cases, young birds were kept in
homes, and one boy kept the birds in his bedroom and even in his
jacket.
</P>
<P>
   The outbreak in Missouri infected 40 people. Again, three were
hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   The disease is spread from animals when people touch infected
feces and then touch their mouths. Other animals, especially
reptiles, also pose a threat.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials urged that people wash their hands carefully
after handling fowl and said the animals might not be appropriate
pets for children.
</P>
<P>
   MENTAL HEALTH: Few Seek Help for Extreme Social Fears
</P>
<P>
   People with social anxiety disorder, a common psychiatric
ailment, realize they have a problem but often fail to seek
treatment because of embarrassment or lack of resources, a study
has found.
</P>
<P>
   The study, in The American Journal of Psychiatry, said more
should be done to build public awareness of the treatments and to
educate health care professionals.
</P>
<P>
   People with the disorder often fear speaking with strangers,
dealing with those in authority or being scrutinized by others in
social situations like classes. Sufferers blush, sweat, shake and
even have trouble breathing in such cases. Though numbers vary
widely, some experts say millions of Americans are affected.
</P>
<P>
   The study was based on a survey done in 1996 as part of an
annual event that includes free evaluations around the country.
(The next screening is May 3; information is at
www.freedomfromfear.org.) Researchers reviewed survey data from 130
people who showed symptoms of social anxiety disorder to see why so
many had not sought treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The reason cited in 39 percent of the cases was lack of
knowledge about where to go. About 24 percent said they could not
afford care, while 20 percent said they feared what other people
would think. Only 8 percent said they did not believe they had the
disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mark Olfson of Columbia University, the lead author of the
study, acknowledged that people with mental problems often failed
to seek treatment. But he said the peculiar nature of this illness
might make it even harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that people with social anxiety disorder are often
ashamed of their symptoms and therefore inhibited or embarrassed to
discuss them,'' Olfson said.
</P>
<P>
   RISKS AND REMEDIES: When Small Hospitals Fix Big Blockages
</P>
<P>
   Major medical organizations often frown on smaller hospitals
that perform elective angioplasty, saying that the procedure to
unclog arteries and reduce the risk of heart attacks is so delicate
it should be done only at institutions where it is performed
regularly.
</P>
<P>
   But a new study suggests benefits to loosening that policy to
allow patients in rural areas better access to the treatment. The
guidelines are not binding, but they can influence state
regulations governing what procedures hospitals can perform.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in Circulation, the American Heart Association journal,
researchers said they had studied angioplasty results in California
for 14 years and found that the mortality rates between low- and
high-volume hospitals had become much closer.
</P>
<P>
   From 1984 to 1987, hospitals that performed fewer than 200
angioplasties a year had a mortality rate of 2.5 percent, almost
twice as high as the 1.3 percent rate of hospitals that performed
400 or more. But from 1993 to 1996, the mortality rate for
high-volume hospitals remained the same, while for smaller ones it
dropped to 1.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it seems unlikely that the two major groups behind
the recommendations _ the American Heart Association and the
American College of Cardiology _ will ease their policies any time
soon. Instead, the groups, which now suggest that elective
angioplasties be limited to hospitals that perform at least 200 a
year, are considering raising that minimum to as many as 600.
</P>
<P>
   Even the author of the study, Dr. Vivian Ho, a health-management
professor at Washington University in St. Louis, is not pushing the
point. ``I don't think I'm at this moment ready to say they should
change the guidelines to a lower standard,'' Ho said.
</P>
<P>
   Sidney Smith, a former president of the heart association,
defended the guidelines. He said the study had merit but called it
limited because of its focus on deaths instead of later heart
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   PATTERNS: Of Suffering, Coping and Damaged Disks
</P>
<P>
   By some estimates, as many as 30,000 back operations a year are
performed in the United States to remove damaged discs and fuse the
spine back together to reduce a patient's lower back pain.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, a new study argues, doctors would be better off
shifting their focus to their patients' state of mind.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at Stanford said they found little correlation
between the tears commonly found in people's vertebral discs and
their level of pain. The findings were reported by Dr. Eugene
Carragee at a recent meeting of the International Society for the
Study of the Lumbar Spine.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors look for tears with MRI scans and a procedure called a
discograph, involving injected dye. If the dye leaks out, it can be
seen in X-rays, and it often causes pain. When the tears and leaks
are found, surgery is often performed.
</P>
<P>
   But the Stanford researchers found that many people had torn
discs but suffered little or no pain. A more useful diagnostic
tool, they said, was a psychological test administered to the 96
patients studied. The people with poor coping skills (as well as
those with workers compensation claims or lawsuits related to their
back pain) were more likely to report symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Before recommending surgery, doctors should make sure they
understand their patients' mental states, the researchers said.
Psychological treatment, an exercise program or even simple
reassurance may be more appropriate, they said.
</P>
<P>
   BEHAVIOR: Exploring Antisocial Aspects of Autism
</P>
<P>
   One of the classic symptoms of autism is difficulty recognizing
people's faces, one reason, perhaps, why people with autism show so
little interest in other people.
</P>
<P>
   Now, researchers at Yale say they may have a better
understanding of the problem, as a result of brain scans.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that people with autism and Asperger's syndrome,
a related condition, perceive faces not as most people do _ as
billboards that display dozens of characteristics including age,
sex and even mood _ but as mere objects.
</P>
<P>
   In the study, people with autism and Asperger's were shown
pictures of faces while in an MRI machine. Their brains showed
little activity in the fusiform gyrus area, that part of the
cerebral cortex that processes faces. Instead, an adjacent region
that processes objects became active.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers could not say whether the brain pattern showed
the cause of autism or simply what happened to the brain after
years of poor socialization. But they said it helped make a case
for intervening early in the lives of children with Asperger's,
while their brains are still malleable.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
