<DOCNO> NYT20000424.0239 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5861 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-ARCHER-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      04-24 1743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCHER-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS HEALTH CHIEF'S GAFFE ISN'T HIS FIRST 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas' health chief apologized profusely last
week for his comments on Hispanic attitudes toward teen pregnancy,
but he has made similar statements about out-of-wedlock births of
blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Health Commissioner Dr. William Reynolds ``Reyn'' Archer
III, who has enjoyed the backing of Republican presidential
candidate Gov. George W. Bush, asked two years ago why, in an era
of civil rights and desegregation, social conditions for blacks
seemed to have worsened.
</P>
<P>
   He cited statistics that 70 percent of black babies were born
out of wedlock, while in 1965 only 15 percent were.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to figure out why it is when blacks were more
segregated and had less opportunity that they did better on
cultural measures than they do in that sense today,'' Archer said
at a conference for Texas schoolteachers and other educators on
March 12, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the meeting, Archer tried to explain his
comment to reporters. Although trained as an
obstetrician-gynecologist, he said, he thinks like an
anthropologist, and has noticed that people in a culture tend to do
what's in the group's best interest.
</P>
<P>
   In speaking of value systems within the black community, he said
that he had noticed that blacks are loyal to one another and that
he's observed cultures where loyalty is more important than
honesty.  &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; He said that could explain why a mostly black jury thought O.J.
Simpson was innocent while most white people did not, or why blacks
might be loyal to Jesse Jackson even if they didn't agree with him.
He also said that ``Anglos'' were uninvited guests, perhaps, in
their attempts to help the black community. And he expressed the
view that blacks ``don't buy'' such cultural and legal institutions
as marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Archer, who concedes he often speaks in academic terms, said he
sometimes makes ``awkward comments'' in his efforts to build
connections among cultures. He said he believes in diversity and he
sincerely tries to reach out and understand others.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we try to build bridges to different communities, people
have to look deeper than words, and they have to look at the
intentions of the person. If individual words are not understood
contextually, we all lose,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he still asks the question about conditions among blacks
in a post-segregation society, but he said he was mistaken to call
these ``cultural'' conditions. He said he ``absolutely'' did not
mean to imply that blacks are not honest.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that he has no idea what he was thinking when he
made his comment about whether blacks ``buy'' marriage and other
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say those are just completely awkward statements,''
Archer said.
</P>
<P>
   The health chief, who is the son of retiring House Ways and
Means Chairman Bill Archer of Texas, was in the national spotlight
in recent weeks. In an interview with The New York Times about
Bush's health care policies, he said Texas has a high rate of teen
pregnancy because Hispanics do not believe that ``getting pregnant
is a bad thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were to go to a Hispanic community and say, `Well, we
need to get you into family planning,' they say, `No, I want to be
pregnant,''' he told the Times.
</P>
<P>
   Following an immediate written apology about the Hispanic
comments last week, Archer issued a public one and several private
ones to black and Hispanic Texas lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made statements that created the wrong impression about the
Hispanic community,'' Archer told members of a legislative
committee Wednesday, ``and want to just deeply apologize to those
I've offended.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charlie Gonzalez, D-Texas, and Hispanic activists in Austin
have called for Bush to ask Archer to resign, but Bush has said
that an apology is sufficient. Also, the state's two Hispanic
legislative caucuses have sent letters of concern to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign headquarters referred questions about Archer's
record to the governor's office, which issued a statement late
Friday saying teen pregnancy is a problem in all segments of
society.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Archer believes we need to work together to understand the
complex reasons for the rise in out-of-wedlock births in every
community,'' it said. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``Governor Bush hopes that parents from all backgrounds and all
walks of life will encourage their children to make responsible
decisions and choose the happiest and healthiest decision, which is
to abstain from sex until they are married to their lifelong
spouse.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some black and Hispanic state legislators say they
are willing to forgive Archer for the Hispanic remarks. But many
lawmakers who happen to be Democratic are not ready to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``The jury is still out on Commissioner Archer,'' said Sen.
Rodney Ellis, D-Houston, who met with Archer on Wednesday to
discuss health care problems in Texas, as well as a comment Archer
made about blacks in a speech posted on the health department's Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   In that speech to health professionals, Archer had wondered why
blacks die younger than Anglos or Hispanics, then answered:
``Culture seems to be more a driver than health care.'' Ellis
called the comments ``strange,'' and Archer apologized.
</P>
<P>
   Just an hour before their talk, Ellis had told members of the
Senate Hispanic Caucus that the health commissioner's gaffe about
Hispanics wasn't the first controversial public statement he has
made.
</P>
<P>
   The state senator was referring to articles in the Houston
Chronicle and Washington Post about controversial comments Archer
had made on women, men and family planning issues while working in
President Bush's administratio7f
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Opposed to premarital sex and abortion, Archer once said that it
was a bad idea to give women birth control pills. He also had said
that as a doctor counseling pregnant women he tried to make them
``bend to my will'' or sent them on their way.
</P>
<P>
   Family planning professionals mounted an unsuccessful campaign
to derail his appointment as Texas health commissioner in 1997, a
time when Texas led the country in teen pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bush was aware of Archer's previous comments but approved
his appointment anyway, calling him a ``compassionate man'' who
would do ``a fine job.''
</P>
<P>
   One health board member said Archer's assurances had convinced
her that he ``had changed a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Another board member said he didn't think Archer was qualified
to oversee a $6.4 billion budget, 6,000 employees and nearly 100
programs affecting millions of Texans.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Garnet Coleman, a Houston Democrat who is vice
chairman of the House Public Health Committee, said he immediately
remembered Archer's 1998 comments about blacks when the Hispanic
comments were published.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman, along with Gary Bledsoe, president of the Texas chapter
of the NAACP, were asked by the Houston Chronicle in 1998 if they
had any comment on Archer's statement to the teachers' group about
blacks and his follow-up comments to the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Neither expressed outrage at the time. Coleman, noting that
Archer was new at his job, said he was willing to give him the
benefit of the doubt. Bledsoe said the comments ``smack of cultural
supremacy'' and seemed insensitive, but he, too, wanted to give
Archer the benefit of doubt.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle did not publish a story at the time because
editors found his remarks confusing, and the two black officials,
Coleman and Bledsoe, had not reacted strongly. Coleman said he
thought Archer's intentions were good.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Archer's comments appeared contradictory. He had also
told the teachers: ``This is about winning the hearts and minds of
all communities. It is not about forcing people to be good. I
believe that fundamentally, whether you're Hispanic, Asian, white
or black, you want the same things for your children.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman said he now finds Archer's comments more disturbing in
light of his recent remarks about Hispanics and his health policy
philosophies.
</P>
<P>
   Archer describes his philosophy as a holistic approach to
medicine and public health. He said he thinks immediate health
needs should be met, along with a search for causes _ even if they
are culturally rooted.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the budget is only so large and many immediate needs
are not met. In fact, legislators worried last year that Archer had
a plan to close some school health clinics.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman, Ellis and others object to the priority they think
Archer places on the preventive side of public health, especially
when it encompasses cultural issues.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Archer wants to discover whether conflicting
dynamics of love and alienation might be ``root causes'' of risky
behaviors _ smoking, excessive drinking and irresponsible sex _
that can imperil health.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question arises once you've given someone the benefit of
the doubt, if they repeat those errors over and over again,
immediately you have to wonder if that's a point of view,'' Coleman
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a pure policy and philosophical standpoint, this is
something that cannot be accepted by anybody. According to Reyn
Archer, it's not even accepted by him. It speaks for itself,''
Coleman said of the most recent comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he's been disingenuous about wanting to
understand other cultures,'' Coleman said. ``I think where he has
made an error is in thinking that he understands those cultures
better than people who are in them. It's another form of
patronizing. I really do believe Reyn is out of step with the
people that he serves and that he's somewhat out of step with other
policy makers in state government.''
</P>
<P>
   At the governor's mansion, meanwhile, Austin-area marchers
hoisting signs with such slogans as ``Adios Archer'' said they
can't forgive racially charged rhetoric from officials Bush
appoints.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters also said that Archer seems blind to the state's
poor health care record, with its high rates of uninsured working
poor and children and high rates of tuberculosis and HIV infection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just can't continue to use these stereotypes as an excuse
for this state's awful health care record,'' said protest organizer
Gina Hinojosa, an attorney. ``We're not going to tolerate being
scapegoats.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
 &QL; 
$$$
</P>
