<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5867 &Cx1f; tth-z
r f BC-AIRBUS-BOEING-SPI &LR;      04-24 1436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRBUS-BOEING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRBUS AIMS FOR 60 PERCENT OF JET MARKET; BOEING SCOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Airbus Industrie no longer wants to be Boeing's equal.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh off its first-ever pasting of Boeing in new jetliner
orders last year, the European manufacturer is aiming higher _ much
higher.
</P>
<P>
   A top executive said Airbus is gunning for 60 percent share of
the commercial market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boeing will probably stabilize at around 40 percent,'' John
Leahy, Airbus senior vice president for commercial operations, told
the industry magazine Flight International.
</P>
<P>
   He said Airbus would draw the line at 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you will see Airbus having 80 percent,'' Leahy
was quoted as saying. ``We don't think we need to be producing that
much.''
</P>
<P>
   His words did not go down well at Boeing, which in recent months
has taken steps to turn the rising Airbus tide.
</P>
<P>
   ``In his dreams,'' Boeing commercial spokesman Randy Harrison
fired back when asked about Leahy's comments.
</P>
<P>
   Some industry analysts agree. They believe Airbus will find it
difficult to sustain even 50 percent market share without the A3XX
super jumbo. Airbus must have the 550-seater to break the 30-year
monopoly Boeing has enjoyed with the 747, they argue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will Airbus be able to get to 60 percent and stay there? I
doubt it. They have a long ways to go,'' said Bill Fiala of Edward
Jones. ``But it is possible as long as they are willing to be
aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Airbus, a consortium of four aerospace companies from France,
Germany Spain and Great Britain, has said it expects to get
supervisory board approval to begin offering the A3XX for sale in
June, which could lead to a possible launch by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Emirates Airlines is expected Monday, at an event scheduled in
Cairo, Egypt, to be the first carrier to public announce it will
buy the A3XX if Airbus builds it.
</P>
<P>
   Even without the A3XX, an Airbus spokeswoman said the consortium
is not just blowing smoke in saying it can win 60 percent of the
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Airbus has long held the goal of a sustainable 50 percent
market share,'' Mary Anne Greczyn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we have seen more and more customers turn to us for the
first time, and repeat orders. So it is certainly not unreasonable
to set our sights higher. Airbus would not have gotten anywhere in
the last 30 years without aiming high.''
</P>
<P>
   It's still very early, with several important campaigns still to
be won or lost, but so far this year Boeing is leading Airbus in
the order battle.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has 126 firm orders to 59 for Airbus, according to the
latest figures posted on their respective Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The gap could soon tighten. Airbus is reported to be close to
completing a deal with International Lease Finance Corp. for about
50 widebody and narrowbody jets.
</P>
<P>
   When Boeing reported first quarter earnings last week, Chairman
Phil Condit told analysts he was pleased with the rebound in
Boeing's orders this year. He said the solid order book after three
months reflected the economic recovery in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Asian airlines are key customers for Boeing widebody jets such
as the 747 and 777, and the economic downturn in that part of the
world contributed to Boeing's somewhat lackluster order totals _
measured against what Airbus did _ in 1999, according to analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Asia doesn't do much, advantage Airbus,'' said Joe
Campbell, chief aerospace analyst for Lehman Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor that hurt Boeing last year was that it was coming
off two of its worst years ever in 1997 and 1998, when its jetliner
production system was in chaos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boeing screwed up its deliveries, it screwed up its
earnings,'' said Paul Nisbet of JAS Research. ``Those things do not
help sales. Boeing is turning things around. The dip they got in
sales (in 1999) will be a temporary one. Airbus people are having
wonderful dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   Until last year, Airbus barely beat Boeing in 1994 orders,
though they essentially tied when cancellations are factored in. It
was such a poor sales year for both, however, that industry
analysts dismiss the results.
</P>
<P>
   But 1999 wasn't even close.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus had 476 firm orders to 332 for Boeing. The Airbus number
represented about 59 percent of the commercial market for jetliners
with more than 100 seats.
</P>
<P>
   (Boeing's Web site lists 391 orders in 1999, but some of those
were placed the two previous years. They were from customers who
did not want to be identified. To be consistent with Airbus, Boeing
decided late last year to list orders from unnamed customers, but
it put all those orders in its 1999 totals.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Airbus has every reason to be proud. It was a heck of an
achievement,'' said Richard Aboulafia, senior aerospace and defense
analyst with the Teal Group.
</P>
<P>
   Can Airbus hang on to the crown of market leader that it won
last year?
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, the answer is no, analysts believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Airbus does not have the product family to command 60 percent
of the market,'' said Peter Jacobs, aerospace analyst with the
Ragen MacKenzie group in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only area where Airbus is truly competitive with Boeing is
in the narrow-body segment of the market,'' Jacobs said.
</P>
<P>
   There, the Airbus A320 has more than held its own against
Boeing's next generation 737, and was responsible in large part of
the Airbus victory in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But Boeing still commands the upper end of the market with its
widebody offerings, Jacobs said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Airbus will be more competitive if it goes ahead with
development of the super jumbo,'' Jacobs said. ``But Airbus would
still be at a disadvantage in the 300- to 400-passenger market.
Boeing's 777 has proven to be more successful than the Airbus A330
or A340.''
</P>
<P>
   In a recent report on the world jet transport market, Aboulafia
noted that even though Airbus scored a tiny victory over Boeing in
the 1994 order battle, it was ``annihilated'' in 1993 and in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   `` ... There are good reasons to believe that 1999 was not a sea
change in the Boeing-Airbus battle,'' he wrote. ``Deliveries, the
widebody battle and the overall product line balance all remain
positives for Boeing.''
</P>
<P>
   Aboulafia, in his report, forecast that Boeing, not Airbus, will
continue to get about 60 percent of the market, in terms of value,
over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   But that could change if the Airbus A3XX is launched and is
successful, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boeing has every reason to fear that Airbus will do even
better in the future,'' Aboulafia said.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing executives don't like to talk about the order war with
Airbus, saying the more important measure to judge success is by
looking at deliveries _ when most of the money changes hands from
the customer to the manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Boeing delivered a record 620 planes to 297 for
Airbus.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Boeing plans to deliver 490 jets. Airbus has said it
will deliver 307 jets this year.
</P>
<P>
   But Airbus' output is heading up. Production of the A320 at
Airbus headquarters in Toulouse, France, is set to increase from
seven planes a month to 15. A second production site in Hamburg,
Germany, also is increasing production of the other members of the
A320 family.
</P>
<P>
   And Airbus is ramping up production of its widebody planes.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the 307 delivery figure for this year could go
higher, said Greczyn, the Airbus spokeswoman. The increased
production rates could see Airbus delivering as many as 450 planes
within a couple years.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Boeing executives may talk publicly about how
deliveries are more important than orders, the Airbus victory last
year got the company's attention at the highest levels. Boeing
reorganized its commercial operations earlier this year to improve
customer relations. Boeing Commercial President Alan Mulally says
this will be the ``year of the customer.''
</P>
<P>
   The move came after several important Boeing customers defected
to Airbus. Some airlines executives have said privately that Airbus
has done the better sales and marketing job over the last couple
years.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing is clearly set on making sure last's year resounding
Airbus order victory does not become a trend, said analyst Jacobs.
</P>
<P>
   While Jacobs does not believe Airbus can attain the 60 percent
market share envisioned by Leahy anytime soon, Airbus does have the
potential to eventually de-throne Boeing as the dominate airplane
manufacturer, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next 10 to 20 years could belong to either,'' he said.
``There is plenty of time for a substantial shift in the market
place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
