<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-EDITORIAL-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FATE OF SIX-YEAR-OLD HAS THE POWER TO MOVE NATIONS    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Editorial)   (This ``separate-buy'' editorial is from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper
in London.)     
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)     
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)     
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)     
 By THE EDITORIAL BOARD OF THE INDEPENDENT  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was the picture that went around the world, which will be
remembered long after most people have forgotten what the dispute
over Elian Gonzalez was about.
</P>
<P>
   Except that it was about the elemental question of how to
enforce the rule of law in matters as sensitive and untidy as the
custody of a six-year-old child.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, we would not have done it like that, most Britons
would say. The aim of reuniting Elian with his father was clearly
right, but to have used a squad of masked men (and a
Spanish-speaking woman with a blanket) to achieve it, brandishing
machine-guns within inches of the terrified child's face, that
would not happen here.
</P>
<P>
   Before we are too smug, however, we should pause. How should it
have been done?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps an unarmed constable should have dismounted his bicycle,
knocked on the door and asked for the boy, sternly but politely.
Not that he could have reached the door through the hundreds of
anti-Castro Cuban exiles.
</P>
<P>
   No, it was the prominence of the guns which was most offensive
to European sensibilities: the use of surprise, speed and minimal
force would have been needed in any case.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, the guns up front were unnecessary. But this was
America. Who was to say that not one of Elian's self-appointed
custodians would be armed, and would not, in the emotional and
ideological heat of the moment, start shooting?
</P>
<P>
   Not George W. Bush, anyway, first out of the hypocritical blocks
to criticize the action as ``defying the values of America.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican candidate for the presidency opposes gun control
and is not well placed to argue that law enforcement agencies
should use only truncheons and whistles on delicate missions.
</P>
<P>
   In the broader scheme, the mission was successful. The U.S.
courts can now assess the claim made on Elian's behalf for refugee
status without the distraction of his being held illegally by his
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   The claim must stand little chance of success, however, even if
the courts allow Elian to apply for asylum against his father's
wishes.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers would have to show that the boy had a well-founded fear
of persecution if he returned to Cuba, whereas the truth is that he
can only have a well-founded fear of canonization.
</P>
<P>
   Fidel Castro has already proclaimed the action of the U.S.
authorities to be a victory for the Cuban nation.
</P>
<P>
   Therein lies the longer-term significance of Saturday's snatch.
It is clear that Presidents Clinton and Castro are working
together, against the Cuban-exile political bloc in Florida, which
exerts such a disproportionate and malign influence on U.S. policy.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution of the impasse was only made possible by the
arrival in Washington earlier this month of Elian's father, by
arrangement with the Castro regime.
</P>
<P>
   This changed the story from one of the boy orphaned in a heroic
escape from wicked communist tyrant to another narrative equally
familiar to an American audience, that of the father-son bond.
</P>
<P>
   It also holds out the hope that the ending of this story could
be one of reconciliation on a larger stage.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton, freed from the need to grub for votes among the
virulent leaders of Miami's anti-Castro Cubans, could use the Elian
affair to normalize relations with Havana.
</P>
<P>
   And if Elian's too-eventful life could contribute to the ending
of America's counterproductive isolation of Cuba, the shock he
endured at five o'clock last Saturday morning may have heralded a
larger accomplishment. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this editorial from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-00 1651EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000424.0246 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5870 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-EARTH-DAY-HNS &LR;      04-24 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARTH-DAY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ENVIRONMENTAL LAWS WON'T CRIPPLE NATION'S ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By EBAN GOODSTEIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ On the first Earth Day in 1970, the cherry
blossoms in the nation's capital were blooming. But just 30 years
later, global warming has pushed the flowering season a week
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In another 30 or 40 years, according to climate models, cherry
trees in Washington, along with the rest of the Eastern forests,
could well be dying.
</P>
<P>
   Neither this simple warning sign, nor the deadly heat wave that
hit the East Coast last summer, nor the joint call for action from
the heads of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration
and Britain's Meteorological Office, have moved the U.S. Senate any
closer to ratifying the Kyoto global warming treaty. The senators,
apparently, are still misled by dire warnings about damage to our
economy.
</P>
<P>
   From past battles over clean air, snail darters and spotted
owls, to the looming crisis created by greenhouse gas emissions,
``jobs versus the environment'' has been the pivotal political
issue challenging our national clean-up effort. And after a 25-year
media barrage, many Americans, including senators, share three
related _ and false _ perceptions about jobs and the environment.
They mistakenly believe that environmental protection creates
economy-wide slowdowns, boosting unemployment; that it has led to
large numbers of plant shutdowns and layoffs in the manufacturing
sector; and that it has forced many U.S. companies to flee to
developing countries with lax environmental regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all economists who have studied the issue agree that
these three propositions are false. At the economy-wide level, in
reality, there has simply been no trade-off between jobs and the
environment.
</P>
<P>
   From 1990 to 1999, for example, U.S. corporations, consumers,
and governments boosted their spending on environmental protection
from around $138 to $219 billion, or from 2.1 to 2.8 percent of the
GDP.
</P>
<P>
   Over the same period of time that environmental spending grew so
dramatically, the U.S. economy added a whopping 16 million new
jobs. Even at the local level, regulation-induced plant closings
and layoffs are very rare.
</P>
<P>
   Study after study has found that layoffs in the manufacturing
sector resulting from environmental regulation have averaged one to
three thousand jobs per year nationwide since the late 1970s. To
put these numbers in perspective, around two million people are
laid off in the U.S. every year for non-environmental reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, despite what one hears in the news media, few companies
are fleeing industrial countries like the United States to take
advantage of lax environmental regulations in poor countries. Why?
For most industries, environmental costs are on order of only 1 to
2 percent of total business costs. Moreover, much pollution control
technology is now embedded in modern plant designs; that is,
pollution control increasingly reflects fundamental process changes
rather than end-of-the-pipe filters. This means that an oil
refinery or chemical plant built by a multinational corporation in
Seattle will in fact look reasonably similar to one built in South
China.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing new or controversial about this information,
which clearly needs to be more widely understood. As the stalemate
in the Senate starkly illustrates, jobs versus the environment
myths now threaten to scuttle international efforts to tackle
global warming.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer's heat wave was just the tip of the bad news on the
climate change front over the last 12 months. For example,
Britain's Hadley Center, an important research organization,
predicted major forest diebacks in the mid-latitudes, including the
southern and eastern United States, beginning in a few decades;
Australian researchers concluded that global warming could
eliminate all reefs from most of the world by the year 2100, and
kill the Great Barrier Reef within 30 years. From retreating
glaciers to a worldwide wave of extreme weather measured in
unprecedented insurance claims, the grim evidence for global
warming continues to mount.
</P>
<P>
   But the good news is that we can take action to stop our
disruption of the global climate, and at relatively low cost. In
the early 1970s, when the first round of environmental regulation
was introduced, we really did not know what the employment impacts
of environmental protection spending were going to be. At that
time, the jobs-versus-environment debate was legitimate. But since
then, repeated predictions of massive layoffs have simply not been
borne out.
</P>
<P>
   There is no reason to think that the global warming case will be
dramatically different. Consistent with past experience, greenhouse
gas control will likely lead to nationwide layoffs averaging on the
order of a few thousand per year.
</P>
<P>
   Comprehensive adjustment assistance for workers who do lose
their jobs is something that we can easily afford. What we can no
longer afford is to be paralyzed by the myth of a jobs-environment
trade-off. Cherry blossoms are not all we have to lose.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Eban Goodstein is an associate professor of economics at Lewis
and Clark College in Portland, Ore., a research associate at the
Economic Policy Institute in Washington, D.C., and the author of
``The Trade-off Myth: Fiction and Fact About Jobs and the
Environment.'' He can be reached at the Department of Economics,
Lewis and Clark College, Portland, OR 97219.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
