<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5877 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-BONFIRE-PROBE-HNS &LR;      04-24 1741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONFIRE-PROBE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS A&AMP;M CHIEF'S JOB CALLED SECURE DESPITE BONFIRE TRAGEDY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN WILLIAMS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a special commission studying the deadly collapse of the
Texas A&AMP;M Bonfire nears the end of its job, university President
Ray Bowen does not appear in jeopardy of losing his position.
</P>
<P>
   Despite comments by Bowen earlier this year in which he hinted
at a resignation, top officials say they do not expect, nor do they
want, Bowen to go.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the debate is the issue of responsibility for a
disaster on university grounds involving an activity almost
exclusively overseen by students. Also an issue is a close-knit,
military-style culture that at times may make those associated with
the school blind to problems. The special commission is studying
the A&AMP;M culture as part of a sweeping examination of the collapse
in a $1.67 million report scheduled for release May 2.
</P>
<P>
   In anticipation of the commission's report, an A&AMP;M graduate has
written an account of the Bonfire disaster that blames school
officials for ignoring warning signs.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Bowen should take responsibility for the Nov. 18
accident that killed 12 and injured 27, said Irwin A. Tang, author
of ``The Texas Aggie Bonfire: Tradition &AMP; Tragedy at Texas A&AMP;M.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that we can all see that he is responsible, that the
administrators below him are responsible,'' said Tang, who
graduated in 1992. ``In other countries and places in the world,
someone would have resigned on the day of the accident.''
</P>
<P>
   In January, two newspapers reported that Bowen would resign if
the commission found that the accident was caused by poor
leadership from his administration.
</P>
<P>
   But an A&AMP;M spokesman, the head of the school's Faculty Senate
and two university regents, including board Chairman Donald E.
Powell, now say Bowen's intentions were misinterpreted.
</P>
<P>
   They agreed that Bowen has said he would step down if asked by
the board of regents. But, Powell said, there has been no
discussion of that.
</P>
<P>
   Appointed to the position in 1994, Bowen is pushing the school
into a new era in which it is trying to become one of the nation's
Top 10 state universities by 2020.
</P>
<P>
   Now is not the time to force him out, most say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer is no,'' said regent Robert H. Allen. ``He
certainly hasn't said that, we certainly have not said that.
Wherever the quote came from, it was a misquote or
misinterpretation.''
</P>
<P>
   Tang said Bowen's hesitance to assume responsibility may be for
fear of lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason, no one has stood up and taken responsibility
for the accident,'' the author said. ``That probably has something
to do with protecting the university from lawsuits.''
</P>
<P>
   No lawsuits have been filed to date, and several parents of
those who died have expressed no such intentions.
</P>
<P>
   However, if the school is sued, it will have what is expected to
be the best research into the Bonfire collapse.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, chaired by Houston businessman Leo Linbeck Jr.,
hired five consulting firms expert in examining the aftermath of
calamities and in finding their causes.
</P>
<P>
   Among the many problems being investigated is a sloping terrain
that resulted in the first of four ascending levels of the Bonfire
stack being built at an angle. In addition, the experts are trying
to determine whether a crane that hit the stack days earlier caused
it to eventually fall. Or whether cables should have been used as
they were in the past to keep the lower tiers secure. Or whether
the center pole was brittle.
</P>
<P>
   But in addition to examining the design and materials used in
this and other Bonfires, the report is expected to determine
whether school policies were violated and what role that may have
played in the collapse, Linbeck said.
</P>
<P>
   There will not be a placing of blame but rather a detailed
analysis of the factors that caused the woodpile to collapse,
Linbeck said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be an exhaustive assessment as to the contributing
and causal factors of the collapse, but nothing short of or beyond
that,'' Linbeck said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that effort includes looking at the culture of Bonfire,
a tradition since 1909 when Aggies built a huge tower of wood and
burned it shortly before their annual football game with the
University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Tang said there is plenty to investigate that could hold the
university responsible for the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Suggestions to improve Bonfire safety were either ignored or
overlooked during more than a decade of warnings from school
faculty, Tang said.
</P>
<P>
   Already, details that have come out since the disaster show that
these university rules were broken:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Bonfire violated the 55-foot height limit and was already
59 feet tall when it collapsed. When complete, it would have been
about 70 feet tall.
</P>
<P>
   _ Alcohol, which is banned, was found in the blood of two
victims. In addition, police reports indicate that many empty beer
cans were found around the collapsed Bonfire and that officers
smelled alcohol on the breath of some workers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Only professional operators are allowed to handle a crane that
helps stack the logs. However, a 24-year-old student was operating
a crane when the Bonfire collapsed, though authorities do not
believe that the crane played any role in the collapse. It is
unclear, however, whether a student or professional was operating
the crane that smacked the Bonfire days before.
</P>
<P>
   Tang, however, is more critical of a bigger picture than just
broken rules.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Bonfire collapse is a result of Aggie Spirit, a
defining term of the culture at the school. While Tang's book
repeatedly lauds that esprit de corps, he says that at times it
acts as a stumbling block to recognizing or solving problems.
</P>
<P>
   And with Bonfire, one of the biggest of Aggie traditions, he
said the culture began a ``slow devolution.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It became more and more a student activity. That's because the
university allowed it to,'' Tang said. ``They didn't wish to
allocate the resources to monitor a tradition that was growing more
and more out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   At one time, freshmen were prohibited from the log stack above
the first level, a sign of both honor for older students and
recognition that it was dangerous work requiring special skills.
That rule, however, fell by the wayside. Many freshmen were on the
stack when it fell in November, including one who had only one
night of experience on the project before the collapse.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1990s, a tradition once supervised by the commander
of the Corps of Cadets was left largely to students and a school
adviser, Rusty Thompson, who is not an engineer.
</P>
<P>
   With that change came alterations in the way the stack was
built, Tang said. The changes were passed down from Aggie to Aggie
with no blueprint of the massive structure.
</P>
<P>
   A log stack that leaned toward the middle like a teepee in the
1950s and 1960s had evolved into something that looked like a
wedding cake. That decreased stability, Tang said.
</P>
<P>
   Previous methods of stabilizing the stack, such as cables and
interlocking logs, were not employed in the 1999 Bonfire, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In his book, Tang said that Bowen, an engineer, should have
recognized the slide.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how embarrassing or sobering the various Bonfire
crises Bowen saw, he never ordered a thorough evaluation and
overhauling of any part of the Bonfire building process or stack
design,'' Tang wrote in his book.
</P>
<P>
   Bowen has declined to comment until the special commission comes
back with a report.
</P>
<P>
   But in a January story by The Eagle of Bryan-College Station,
Bowen said he would take all responsibility for the Bonfire
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, the buck stops here,'' he was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
   The story went on to say that Bowen said he would resign if it
was determined the accident was a product of poor leadership on his
administration's part.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would do that on a variety of issues,'' Bowen said in the
Jan. 12 article. ``If, for example, there was a serious financial
situation that led back to my indifference, I would take the
responsibility. How can I say to someone, `I want you out of this
job' when I am at the top of that command? I have to set the
standard.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day, A&AMP;M's chief spokeswoman, Cindy Lawson, confirmed
that Bowen would resign if asked or if a failure of university
leadership over the Bonfire was found to have been a factor, the
Austin American-Statesman reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the ultimate leader, he feels he would be responsible,''
Lawson told the newspaper. ``And that is not out of character for
him. Honesty and integrity are paramount to him. Taking
responsibility goes with that, and doing what is right is part of
the cost of responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   School spokesman Lane Stephenson said The Eagle misquoted Bowen
about any intentions to resign. Stephenson would not comment on the
remarks subsequently made by Lawson. Lawson did not return phone
calls from the Houston Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely is a big enough issue for resignation to be
considered,'' said Faculty Senate Speaker Thomas Wehrly. ``That
doesn't answer whether or not he should.''
</P>
<P>
   Wehrly said Bowen is responsible for the biggest turnaround in
the school in decades. A committee that Bowen formed in 1997 to
study the school's future produced a far-reaching set of strategies
called Vision 2020. It challenges the school to become one of the
nation's top state universities by that year.
</P>
<P>
   For a school that has worked hard to grow from a regional
university into a major institution of national standing during the
past few decades, Bowen's new challenge is inspiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Bowen seems to have the goal of moving us forward into the
next rank of universities,'' Wehrly said. ``No one is asking that
Dr. Bowen step down over Bonfire.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, those close to the president say he has been greatly
affected by the tragedy and say he has expressed remorse for not
recognizing the problem before it occurred.
</P>
<P>
   And the future of Bonfire lies directly on his shoulders, where
the buck still stops. Once the commission's report is made, Bowen
is expected to decide whether Bonfire continues as is, is changed
or is halted.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's felt a deep sense of loss, as we all have,'' said board
Chairman Powell. ``The loss has weighed on his shoulders very
heavily.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
