<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HEAT25-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   HEAT: NO MORE SPLIT DECISIONS
</P>
<P>
   Miami fully aware 1-1 starts were its undoing against Knicks
twice
</P>
<P>
   By Ethan J. Skolnick
</P>
<P>
   c. 200 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Double or nothing.
</P>
<P>
   That's the proposition facing the Miami Heat as they prepare for
Tuesday's rematch against the Detroit Pistons. Each of the past two
seasons, the Heat won only one of the opening two games at home,
then dropped both series to the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know that (Saturday's) game doesn't mean anything if we
don't take care of business Tuesday night,'' P.J. Brown said
Sunday, before he left to boil Easter eggs for his kids. The Heat
had a relatively short practice on the holiday, and Pat Riley led a
more intense one Monday. He realizes the Heat won't repeat their
comfortable 10-point victory if they don't address shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   Prominent among those is defending harder on the perimeter.
Riley counted 48 drives to the basket by the Pistons on Saturday,
and that was with Grant Hill noticeably hobbled. ``That's high,''
Riley said. Hill and Jerry Stackhouse combined for 20 free throw
attempts. Stackhouse led the league in that category, mostly
because of his quick first step.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were attacking (Saturday) night, so we're very aware that
their game is attack, run, attack, run,'' Riley said. ``They were
just getting by us. We want to get up and into them. We gave them
too much room and we got soft.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Riley, if the Heat _ particularly Jamal Mashburn,
Bruce Bowen and Dan Majerle _ can challenge the Pistons' slashers
farther out on the floor, ``it gives your help a little more time
to get there.'' Alonzo Mourning provided nine blocks' worth of
assistance Saturday, but he can't be counted on to save every
defensive stand. The center said as much after the victory.
</P>
<P>
   That victory was enabled primarily by the passionate play of
Mashburn, and Riley wants him shooting 20 times per game. Saturday,
he took 17 shots, making 10, and added seven free throws. ``He
ain't going to be out there without having the ball in his hands,''
Riley said. ``There ain't going to any of these, well, 'I didn't
get it for eight minutes.' He's going to have it a lot. If they are
taking it out of Zo's hands, then we want it in Mash's hands.''
</P>
<P>
   And they will take it out of Zo's hands, by denying him touches
through deception if not force. Each team has accused the other of
playing illegal defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's anybody who has their defense leaning toward
Alonzo, it's them,'' Riley said. ``I made the point a week ago, and
they still are.''
</P>
<P>
   Mourning is trying to work around it. His unselfishness and
savvy decision-making Saturday foiled the Pistons' best and worst
intentions. Told that Pistons coach George Irvine accused him of
striking his own illegal defensive poses, Mourning replied:
``That's his opinion, man. Believe me, they play illegal too. I
think there's been a lack of consistency on calls the whole year,
because referees are trying to adapt to these new rules. If that's
the excuse he uses, then fine, I'm sorry. I can't do anything about
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor about the past two years either. Yet Riley says the players
are aware of history. ``We've lost either the first or the second
game,'' Riley said. ``Detroit's going to forget about this (first
game), because they have one more opportunity to do what it is they
want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Though his players ``left everything they had out there on the
floor,'' Riley didn't want all this rest for them. ``I'd rather
play (Monday) night, it's just more natural,'' Riley said Sunday.
``Having two or three days between games allows a player to become
a person. In the playoffs, you don't want your players to be
people.''
</P>
<P>
   People subject to distractions, caused by family, friends,
hobbies. ``He knows this is a long, tough journey, and we need the
edge in every department,'' said Mourning, who plans to avoid Jet
Skiing, and partying, and hanging out late during the playoffs.
However long they go. They may go longer if the Heat take Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we're in dire need of a win, we've always seemed to step
up,'' Brown said. ``When things are going good, and flowing very
well, we don't seem to handle success that well. It seems to hurt
us more than help us.''
</P>
<P>
   But they are in dire need of a win, aren't they?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
