<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5881 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-TRILOBITE-EXTINCT     04-24 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-TRILOBITE-EXTINCTION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWFOUND CRATER COULD EXPLAIN WORST MASS EXTINCTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: NYT Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 (The Science Times)  
 By WILLIAM J. BROAD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A quarter billion years ago, some 90 percent of all animal
species, including the trilobites, the three-lobed predators of the
sea, suddenly disappeared in the worst of all mass extinctions.
</P>
<P>
   The killer's identity has long been a mystery. But now
scientists in Australia have unearthed evidence that the culprit
could have been a speeding rock from outer space that slammed into
the planet, carved out a crater some 75 miles wide, and blasted
millions of tons of rock and dust into the sky, blotting out the
sun.
</P>
<P>
   A team of four scientists at the Geological Survey of Western
Australia and the Australian National University, led by Arthur
Mory, announced the discovery in the April 15 issue of Earth and
Planetary Science Letters, published by Elsevier. The structure, at
least 75 miles wide and hidden from sight by hundreds of feet of
dirt and rock, is in Western Australia near an arm of the Indian
Ocean known as Shark Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tantalizing,'' Michael Rampino, an earth scientist at New
York University, said of the discovery. ``It's clearly a big
crater. But the age is up for grabs, so a link to extinction
remains to be proven.''
</P>
<P>
   The exact dating of the cosmic scar is uncertain, the
discoverers said. But clues suggest its age is roughly between the
early Jurassic and early Permian periods, or 200 and 280 million
years ago. That distant era, they noted, contained two mass
extinctions _ one at the end of the Triassic some 214 million years
ago, and one at the end of the Permian 247 million years ago.
</P>
<P>
   That upheaval saw the disappearance of not only trilobites but
hundreds of other marine invertebrates, insects and early reptiles.
Their demise was a turning point in earth history that made way for
the rise of dinosaurs and widened the niches available for the
mammal-like reptiles, which became ancestors of the human race.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian blow probably accounts for ``one of the two major
extinctions,'' the crater discoverers wrote, ``given the likely
environmental consequences of an impact of this magnitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Named Woodleigh after a station in the Australian outback, the
new crater is the largest ever discovered on the Australian
geological plate. Globally, it is the fourth largest. The only
bigger ones are Vredefort in South Africa (about 185 miles wide),
Sudbury in Canada (about 155 miles wide) and Chicxulub in Mexico
(about 110 miles wide). In all, scientists have now found some 150
or so impact craters.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian find was inspired by the scientific detective
work that tied the Chicxulub crater (pronounced cheek-soo-LOOB) to
the most famous of all mass extinctions. That die-off, 65 million
years ago, at the end of the Cretaceous period, killed the
dinosaurs, the marine shellfish called ammonites and many other
groups of animals.
</P>
<P>
   The main dinosaur sleuth was Dr. Walter Alvarez, a geologist at
the University of California at Berkeley. In 1980, he and his
colleagues reported that they had found unusually large amounts of
iridium in geological strata laid down when the dinosaurs died out
and proposed that the rare metal had come from a giant asteroid
that struck the Earth. Iridium, a precious metal belonging to the
platinum group of elements, is more abundant in meteorites than in
terrestrial rocks.
</P>
<P>
   The Alvarez theory won wide attention. And in 1990, after long
hunts, geologists announced that they had found a candidate crater
in Mexico, buried deep under the Yucatan Peninsula. The Chicxulub
crater was big enough to account for the dinosaur extinctions, and
its age was exactly right. Many scientists sought similar
accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian team found an intriguing sample of rock from the
Woodleigh region that a company in 1981 had pulled up from a depth
of 620 feet. The quartz in this rock was fractured or ``shocked''
in a way that suggested that it had been subject to sudden extreme
heat and pressure. In March 1999, the team went back to the site
and took 25 core samples from depths ranging from 620 to more than
1,000 feet down.
</P>
<P>
   Study of the samples with light and electron microscopes
revealed multiple signatures of shocked quartz, as well as glassy
areas that implied a history of fiery melts.
</P>
<P>
   The team also obtained government gravity maps of the region,
and in March 1999 took their own gravity readings as well,
according to the Earth and Planetary Science article. The maps
revealed a buried, multiring structure some 75 miles wide _ the
bull's-eye of a cosmic scar.
</P>
<P>
   The team used an ultraviolet laser to try to date the rocks
through mineral analysis, but that effort failed. A minimum age of
200 million years was obtained from geologic deposits that filled
in the Woodleigh crater and a maximum age of 280 million from
fossils at its base. In addition, the region yielded radiochemical
signs of high heats occurring somewhere from 250 to 280 million
years ago _ about the time of the great dying at the end of the
Permian.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Boyle, a geochemist at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology and an editor at Earth and Planetary Science Letters, in
an interview called the Australian findings ``very interesting''
and predicted other researchers will aid the attempt to pin down
the crater's date.
</P>
<P>
   In the years prior to the Australian find, scientists who
pondered the cause of the Permian extinction had suggested a change
in the composition of the earth's atmosphere, volcanoes in Siberia
and the lowering of global sea levels. Clues have been sparse
because the events occurred so long ago. In particular, little
remains of the period's fossil record.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists say a mix of factors may have contributed to the
Permian event, with the Australian object providing the killer
punch.
</P>
<P>
   Rampino at New York University noted that scientists had
identified a 25-mile-wide crater in Brazil that also seemed the
right age for the Permian extinction.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, he said, it was caused by a pair of cosmic killers, or
possibly a barrage of them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-00 1705EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
