<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5885 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT25-COX     04-24 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BREAKUP TALK PUTS PRESSURE ON MICROSOFT TO SETTLE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Microsoft Corp., assailed by the courts and
hammered by the stock market, came under renewed pressure Monday to
try to settle its antitrust battle with the government.
</P>
<P>
   The company's renewed need to act was fueled by a spate of
reports that the Justice Department and 19 states have reversed
course and now intend to seek a remedy that would split up the
software giant along product lines.
</P>
<P>
   While denouncing the notion of a breakup, Microsoft spokesman
Jim Cullinan still held the door open to a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in Microsoft's interest, we believe, to try to put this
issue behind us as quickly possible,'' Cullinan said. ``But we're
only going to do so in a way that protects our ability to continue
to innovate products.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing in the trial record or in this case that
would justify such an extreme and radical remedy. This would be bad
for Microsoft, consumers and the entire industry,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps an even more urgent reason to settle the case is to stem
the sharp sell-off of its shares. On Monday, Microsoft stock, once
the darling of Wall Street investors, fell to its lowest level in
some 17 months, closing at $66.38, a drop of nearly 16 percent on
the day.
</P>
<P>
   The more than $150 billion in shareholder value that has been
wiped off Microsoft's books since January impedes the company's
ability to make acquisitions and offer attractive stock options to
prospective key employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the short term, these (breakup) reports are not meant so
much to put pressure on Microsoft but instead to gauge reaction in
the industry,'' said Jonathan Zuck, who has followed the case
closely from a pro-Microsoft perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Added Zuck, executive director of the 6,000-member Association
for Competitive Technology: ``If it's a trial balloon, it will a
lead balloon.''
</P>
<P>
   Such radical steps were never at issue earlier this year when
Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates and other top company officials
sought to forge a negotiated settlement to the landmark case, with
the aid of Richard Posner, a federal appeals judge based in
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   After those talks faltered, U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson, who instigated them, found Microsoft guilty as charged and
gave the government until the end of April to produce a proposed
set of remedies as a means of lifting the company's monopoly hold
over the personal computer industry.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the government may eventually decide to propose, the
law grants Jackson full freedom of action to impose whatever sort
of relief he deems appropriate, including the option of a fine that
could be in the many billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   There was further uncertainty over whether the Justice
Department and the state attorneys general could agree on a unified
remedy plan. Some states, notably New York and Connecticut, were
known to be taking a hard line while others, notably Ohio and Iowa,
favored a more nuanced approach.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Joel Klein, the chief antitrust official at Justice,
was still seeking to reach a compromise on the prosecution bench in
advance of Jackson's April 28 deadline.
</P>
<P>
   What is certain is an appeal of Jackson's ruling. Microsoft
could also appeal any interim and immediate steps in the way of
relief, if sought by the government and approved by the judge, that
alters the way Microsoft does business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not sure if I were the government I would want to go down
that (interim) road,'' an official who has helped prosecute the
case cautioned privately. ``Having an unfriendly court of appeals
focusing on relief _ which is probably most controversial aspect of
anything Jackson might do _ may prove to be poor tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The dynamic changes after the final relief proposal is out on
the table,'' this official added. ``Microsoft is under pressure not
only because of the relief that Jackson might impose but also
because what the stock market has done to its stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``So they might say: 'Let's have another go at this.' But that's
not the underlying purpose (of the breakup reports). A lot of work
has gone into this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose if you wanted to take a sort of off-the-wall view,
maybe they (the government) are trying to negotiate in print. Maybe
they're leaking these really harsh remedies in the hope that
Microsoft, still at this last minute, might come up with a
settlement,'' said Greg Valliere, an economist for Schwab
Washington Research Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought there would be something a little gentler,'' he
added. ``This is very harsh.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.microsoft.com/presspass
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
