<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5895 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-PORTMAN-FEATURE-LADN &LR;      04-24 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PORTMAN-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE THE ART IS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Natalie Portman is at the age where her life and her acting career
can't help but intersect. She's never been part of the ``Dawson's
Creek'' pack; audiences haven't seen the 18-year-old-actress in a
teen romance or a self-referential slasher flick. That leaves
coming-of-age stories (along with the latest ``Star Wars''
trilogy), and with ``Anywhere but Here'' and her latest movie,
``Where the Heart Is,'' Portman is proving to be quite adept at
playing young women who face pivotal transition points in their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parallels are pretty obvious,'' Portman says. ``I just
left home for college this year, and I'm deciding how to define
myself in new situations. It's exciting and scary, too. All the
ingredients of good drama, in other words.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Where the Heart Is,'' Portman plays Novalee Nation, a very
pregnant 17-year-old who must fend for herself after her no-account
musician boyfriend abandons her at an Oklahoma Wal-Mart en route to
California. Novalee takes up residence inside the Wal-Mart,
sleeping in the camping gear aisles and judiciously snacking in the
grocery section. After the baby is born, she meets a host of
eccentric locals who take her in and become the family she has
never known.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's `The Wizard of Oz,' really,'' Portman says of the movie,
which was adapted from Billie Lett's novel, the latest selection
from Oprah Winfrey's book club to be made into a movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning there's this young girl, and she's lost and
looking for home,'' Portman continues, ``and along the way toward
home, she meets all these wonderfully odd characters who become her
family and become her home.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie, which co-stars Ashley Judd as Novalee's surrogate big
sister and Stockard Channing as the mother figure, marks the
feature directorial debut of Matt Williams. Williams made his mark
in television, helping create ``Roseanne'' and ``Home
Improvement,'' as well as serving as a writer and producer of ``The
Cosby Show'' for three seasons. For him, ``Where the Heart Is'' is
a natural extension of those shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been celebrating the American family my whole career; I
just didn't realize it until I started directing this movie,''
Williams says. ``My own family fell apart when my parents got a
divorce. I was 15 years old and had grown up in this (Norman)
Rockwell-like environment in the Midwest, and I thought, 'Oh my
gosh, this is what life is,' only to see it torn apart. I suddenly
became the adult.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I didn't realize this for years, but it influenced
everything I wrote because all the families stayed together. Dan
and Roseanne stayed together for the kids. Pat and Tim stayed
together for the kids. They'd fight and argue, but ultimately they
survived. And I realized I had been patching up my family and
making it survive all these years through the TV shows and plays I
was directing. None of my families fell apart.''
</P>
<P>
   The family Williams gives us in the movie is an odd, diverse
bunch, related not by blood but out of need and a shared longing
for community. The villains in the film (and the book) are people
who refuse to recognize families that go beyond the traditional,
husband-wife-children construct.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are those people that say a family is only 'this,'''
Williams says. ``You certainly see that today with regard to gay
couples who want to adopt kids. We have to be tolerant enough and
open enough to realize that we have to redefine our concepts of
family. If a child is nurtured and loved, that's going to be a
happy child no matter who the parents are.''
</P>
<P>
   Portman, too, appreciated the film's non-judgmental tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good-natured and well-meaning without being embarrassed
about it, and you don't find that in most movies today,'' Portman
says. ``Most movies would say, 'Oh, look at this dysfunctional
family and how screwed up everyone gets because of it.' And this
movie shows how you can transcend what life hands you.''
</P>
<P>
   Portman herself had to transcend one story element that the
movie handed her _ a love scene, her first ever on film. Throughout
her career, the young actress has balked at doing anything remotely
sexual. She refused to consider her last film, ``Anywhere but
Here,'' until Wayne Wang rewrote a love scene to her
specifications.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's very firm on that point,'' Wang says.
</P>
<P>
   But she caved _ a bit _ for ``Where the Heart Is'' because the
scene was so essential to the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had just turned 18 and was very concerned,'' Williams
says. ``How would you feel if you were asked to take off your
clothes and simulate making love with 50 people watching and a
camera rolling? It's tough, and at 18, it's even tougher. We did it
as tastefully as we could and still suggested the tenderness of the
relationship. It wasn't a hard-core bump and grind; it was about
people connecting emotionally and spiritually.''
</P>
<P>
   And Portman still hated every moment of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the best possible situation. I liked Matt, and I was
really good friends with James (Frain, the actor), and we were both
completely dressed under the covers and we didn't have to do
anything explicit ... just kissing and stuff,'' Portman says. ``And
I was still so uncomfortable. I just felt so weird being told to
kiss someone that I didn't want to kiss. I almost felt whorish,
being told what to do in a sexual way.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams says Portman got through it by being a pro and
surrendering to the moment and her character. Upon hearing this,
Portman says she must have had her director pretty fooled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't just let go,'' she says. ``I think it would be even
harder if I had a boyfriend. I was thinking, 'I hope to get married
someday, and then how would I feel?' It would probably be worse.''
</P>
<P>
   But Portman seems resigned to losing a battle or two while
growing up on screen. After she finishes her freshman year of
college in May, she'll be heading to Australia for the summer to
shoot the second episode in the new `Star Wars'' series. Then
she'll return to her Ivy League school for another year _ after
which she'll take a sabbatical, since she's already a year ahead in
her studies. Although she professes an interest in psychology, she
doesn't seem interested in giving up her movie career any time
soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still a pretty fun job,'' Portman says with a smile. ``I
mean, I don't get pampered as much as when I was younger. It's more
work, more of a job, because people know you and expect you can do
things. But of all the jobs you can do, it's a pretty great one,
don't you think?'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-00 1723EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000424.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5897 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-ARIZONA-REPUBLIC &LR;      04-24 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARIZONA-REPUBLIC </SLUG>
  
 BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    NEW &AMP; NOTABLE (a) 
 &HT;    (Duplication warning: Also moving in ``L'' category) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By ANNE STEPHENSON (a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule book reviews.
</P>
<P>
   The World's Shortest Stories of Love and Death
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Edited by Steve Moss and John M. Daniel
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Running, $7.95)
</P>
<P>
   We flatter ourselves to think we know something about writing
tight, but we are pikers compared with these people. Granted, there
was self-interest involved. They were embroiled in a contest
sponsored by the San Luis Obispo newspaper (beginitalic)New
Times(enditalic), which invited readers to submit stories using
plot, setting and character in fewer than 55 words. First prize
included a certificate and a T-shirt. If (beginitalic)New Times
(enditalic)hasn't upped the ante since then, it doesn't deserve
readers like these. Most of the stories are long (relatively
speaking) on dialogue, humor and creative implication, and short on
everything else. It sounds easy, but try it. Here is ``The Britches
of Madison County,'' in which author Bill Crown one-ups Robert
James Waller in 37 words: ``Francesca came out on the porch and
welcomed them home, her husband, their son, and daughter. But her
skirt was hung up in the waist of her drawers. The old man got hip
and he shot her.''
</P>
<P>
   Orchid Fever
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eric Hansen
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Pantheon, $23)
</P>
<P>
   Please do not shy away from this book because its subject is
orchids and you don't know anything about them. Hansen didn't know
anything about them either, until he was hired to guide two orchid
fanatics into the wilds of Borneo in search of the holy grail of
orchids, the Latin name of which we refuse to repeat here. Hansen
hired some Borneo natives to provide sherpalike assistance on this
journey, and these simple, jungle-savvy men provide lots of laughs
as they react to the orchid zealots' reasons for sloshing up a
muddy Borneo river with a stockpile of equipment that includes a
camouflaged cardboard toilet. This trip was the author's
introduction to the world of orchids and orchid lovers, which was
far more complex, seductive, competitive and pricey than he ever
imagined. Read all about it in this captivating and often funny
book. (Hansen appeared briefly in a recent (beginitalic)60 Minutes
(enditalic)story about the orchid world. As is almost always the
case when media overlap, the book is better.)
</P>
<P>
   Shrink Your Handicap
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Phil Lee and Jeff Warne
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Hyperion, $23.95)
</P>
<P>
   You can read this as a means to improve your golf game, or you
can read it for laughs. New &AMP; Notable has no golf game to speak of,
but in search of good suggestions for Father's Day, we read gamely
on, stifling our guffaws. Lee, a psychiatrist, and Warne, a golf
instructor, join forces to explain the mystery of why you play
better when no one is watching. The villain is the dreaded panic
attack syndrome. As Lee says, ``There are specific swing weaknesses
that are magnets for the chemicals of anxiety. Even the tiniest
amount of anxiety produces chemicals that will feast on certain
specific weaknesses in the swing.'' Their solutions include a
pre-shot routine that involves entering a light trance, developing
``Insight-Oriented Defenses'' to fight the nasty chemicals and
``uninstalling'' the ``Blame Game,'' or the urge to be angry over
bad shots. They take this very, very seriously, but we could not.
Disguised as psychobabble, even common sense sounds like hooey.
</P>
<P>
   Left for Dead
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beck Weathers
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Villard, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   The survival of Dallas pathologist Beck Weathers was just about
the only good news to come out of the storm on Mount Everest that
killed nine people in 1996. Left for dead by other climbers, he
suddenly, miraculously stood up and walked through the squall to
the nearest camp. Fellow climber Jon Krakauer ((beginitalic)Into
Thin Air(enditalic)) comes off well in this version of the day's
events. Anatoli Boukreev, the guide who climbed without oxygen and
so was unable to help his clients descend before the storm hit,
does not. Neither does George W. Bush, who would not help Weathers'
family get him home from Nepal. Less interesting sections about
Weathers' youth and relationship with his wife and family are
followed by sobering descriptions of his recuperation (he lost both
hands and his nose to frostbite). Best of all, he tells of the
daring Nepalese pilot who flew alone, perilously higher than his
helicopter was meant to go, and brought Weathers off of Mount
Everest alive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-00 1724EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000424.0261 </DOCNO>
