<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5910 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-FITNESS-TECH-NYT &LR;      04-24 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-FITNESS-TECH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GADGETS GALORE FOR FITNESS BUFFS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mass.)  (The Science Times) 
 By LINDA VILLAROSA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Quan Phu, the fitness manager of 24-Hour Fitness, a health club
in Huntington Beach, Calif., likes to be precise about his
workouts. For instance, he knows that his run to Sunset Beach is
five miles and 7,610 steps, thanks to the new pedometer he wears
snapped to his waistband.
</P>
<P>
   But this is not the old-style pedometer: The model he uses does
more than simply measure footfalls. It also computes calories
burned and average speed, records data for the current and previous
week and contains fitness programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pedometer helps me set goals rather than playing a
guessing game,'' said Phu, 24, who added that he was aiming to get
in the best shape of his life.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, fitness enthusiasts were the ultimate low-techies.
Real athletes did not need equipment, they just did it. But a
technology wave has hit exercise equipment, and manufacturers have
begun flooding the market with gadgets for fitness buffs.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these exercise innovations were unveiled at the recent
Super Show, the sporting goods industry's annual trade show. Along
with the retooled pedometer, manufacturers rolled out a talking
heart monitor; GetFit.com, a personalized, exercise Web site;
iFit.com, fitness equipment controlled digitally through a Web
site; and a Palm Pilot that keeps track of exercise programs and
records, among others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Far and away there was more technology in the equipment than
I've ever seen before,'' said Mike May, director of communications
for the Sporting Goods Manufacturers Association, the organization
that owns the Super Show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Access to the computer chip has transformed what fitness
companies can put out there,'' May said. ``It is one of the biggest
selling points of new exercise products.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the sporting goods manufacturers and other organizations
have no sales figures specifically for high-tech fitness equipment,
these gadgets seem to be catching on with exercisers, many of whom
are getting in shape with specific goals in mind like training for
an event, losing weight or lowering blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fitness is best done in a goal-oriented way, and computers and
other equipment help make it more accurate and more convenient,''
said Keli Roberts, owner of Real Fitness Inc., a personal training
business in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   She uses a Palm Pilot to record her clients' exercise records
and then downloads the information into her computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can track their progress accurately and look at their
progression to see if the program is working,'' she said. ``These
kinds of records are also important in terms of injury
prevention.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet has given fitness a technological boost. While the
spin on the Internet used to be that it was a barrier to exercise,
keeping people chained to their computers, that attitude has
changed.
</P>
<P>
   New fitness Web sites have emerged and some people are getting
their workout regiments by e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is a great innovation and can be the incentive
for getting people off the couch,'' said Ken Germano, the executive
director of the American Council on Exercise, a fitness watchdog
organization in San Diego. ``It is also ideal for those who travel.
They can stay connected with a fitness professional through a
laptop.''
</P>
<P>
   Fitness sites offer a variety of features: GetFit.com
(www.getfit.com), for example, offers customized workouts based on
the user's schedule, goals, fitness level and available exercise
equipment. In one area of the site, a user can click on a specific
body part and a videotaped demonstration of the exercise will be
streamed into the computer.
</P>
<P>
   Several months ago, Dick Norton, 55, who describes himself as
heavily into computers, bought an Internet-compatible treadmill and
hooked it up to his home computer.
</P>
<P>
   When he is ready to exercise, he logs on to iFit.com
(www.iFit.com). The Web site streams a 30-minute workout video,
which he follows on the computer screen in a kind of online
one-on-one exercise class. His treadmill receives digital cues to
vary the speed and incline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had treadmills in the past, but they're boring,'' said
Norton, a manager for the U.S. Treasury Department in Burbank,
Calif. His favorite workout takes him on a virtual hike in Hawaii,
the incline on his treadmill increasing as the terrain in the video
moves uphill.
</P>
<P>
   However, some experts question the safety of these workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people feel more comfortable over the Internet than they
do in the gym, but those kinds of beginners are the very people who
need some kind of human interface first to avoid getting injured,''
Germano said. ``The critical eye of the trainer is missing online.
And I'm very concerned about exercise equipment operated by the
computer. This is a potentially dangerous situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Norton insists that he still has control of the treadmill
and he can override the computer's adjustments in speed and
incline, Germano remains wary: ``Yes, we're moving to long-distance
learning. But what about long-distance liability?''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, the personal trainer, adds: ``I caution people about
the promise of online training in general. With fitness, it's not
only what you do but how you do it. So starting an exercise program
without some kind of monitoring and measuring of fitness,
flexibility and strength, can be dangerous, especially for someone
just beginning or someone with a medical problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some of the innovations can be very useful and safe _
especially to some subgroups of exercisers. Pam Fernandes, a tandem
bike racer who lost her eyesight to complications of diabetes
nearly 20 years ago, uses a talking heart-rate monitor to measure
her exercise intensity. Otherwise she would have to rely on her
biking partner to read the numbers to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``This device tells me what my heart rate is every 30 seconds so
I know if my workout is intense enough,'' said Fernandes, 38, who
lives in Needham, Mass., and holds a number of tandem records among
racers who are blind. ``Using it has bumped up my training
significantly.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the benefits fitness technology affords her, Fernandes
believes that it can help only so much. ``When it comes down to it,
especially in competition, it's your mind and body that win a race.
When you're exercising, that's really all there is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
