<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5919 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER25-COX     04-24 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Blanket consideration of blanket primaries
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Supreme Court justices vigorously questioned Monday the
legitimacy of state ``blanket primary'' systems that lets voters
cast their ballot for any candidate regardless of party
affiliation. The state of California defended the primary system,
arguing that a primary election ``belongs to the voters,'' not to
the various political parties. Lawyers for four political parties
argued that the system is ``a wholesale assault'' on the parties'
ability ``to choose a standard-bearer who best represents'' their
views. Justice Sandra Day O'Connor seemed to agree, calling the
system ``tremendously intrusive'' on the rights of political
parties. The high court's decision, expected by late June, likely
will determine the future of blanket primaries in Louisiana and
Washington state as well _ along with various open-primary systems
used in about half the states.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN CASH CHASE NEVER STOPS
</P>
<P>
   For the first time this political season, President Clinton, Al
Gore and Hillary Rodham Clinton were appearing side by side at a
fund-raising party. The Democratic National Committee, which doles
out campaign cash to Democratic candidates nationwide, hopes to
raise $2 million at Monday's event in New York. Tony Bennett is the
featured entertainment, with political jokes and introductions by
comic Jon Stewart. This event, combined with one in Hollywood a
week ago, were adding an estimated $4 million to party coffers. On
Wednesday, George W. Bush is headlining a black-tie gala in
Washington for the Republican National Committee. It's expected to
bring in at least $15 million _ a record one-day haul.
</P>
<P>
   RECORDS ARE MADE TO BE BROKEN
</P>
<P>
   In a campaign that's been making history since Hillary Rodham
Clinton announced her candidacy in New York, she and Rudy Giuliani
are on a pace to shatter the record for the most expensive U.S.
Senate race in history. California set the bar in 1994 when Sen.
Dianne Feinstein and then-Rep. Michael Huffington spent $43.3
million; New Yorkers Alfonse D'Amato and Charles Schumer spent
$40.9 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Giuliani have raked in more than $32 million so far,
federal campaign finance records show, and the election is still
seven months away. ``We were saying early on, $50 million, but I
think that's going to be low,'' said Larry Makinson, head of the
nonpartisan Center for Responsive Politics, which studies campaigns
and their financing.
</P>
<P>
   RAISING MONEY FROM NEW YORKERS
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton has gotten a higher percentage of her
itemized Senate campaign donations from New Yorkers this year than
rival Rudy Giuliani, according to a report Monday. The Albany Times
Union analyzed campaign finance reports filed during the first
three months of this year and found Clinton received 51 percent of
her itemized donations of $200 or more from New Yorkers. Giuliani
received 31 percent of those donations from New Yorkers. Giuliani
campaign manager Bruce Teitelbaum called the analysis fundamentally
flawed. He said the mayor was concentrating on direct-mail appeals
this year that tended to focus on non-New Yorkers. He noted that a
Center for Responsive Politics analysis of last year's fund-raising
found Clinton's out-of-state fund-raising outstripping Giuliani's
56 percent to 44 percent.
</P>
<P>
   THE SOUTH COMES OF AGE
</P>
<P>
   The South has offered up favorite sons Al Gore of Tennessee and
George W. Bush of Texas to lead the rest of the country for the
next four years. It's only the second time since 1808 that both
major party presidential candidates have hailed from states that
were part of the Confederacy. The other time was only two elections
ago, in 1992, when the elder George Bush of Texas took on Bill
Clinton of Arkansas. But aspersions were cast in 1992 on the elder
Bush's Southern roots. Although he has lived in Texas since the
late 1940s, he was born in Massachusetts and grew up in
Connecticut. To have an all-Southern matchup in two of the last
three election cycles after such a long drought, experts say,
illustrates that the South is more important politically and less
isolated culturally than it used to be. Before 1992, an all-South
matchup hadn't happened since James Madison of Virginia defeated
Charles Pinckney of South Carolina in 1808. And that was well
before the North-South mindset.
</P>
<P>
   BIG ELECTION WINNERS: LOCAL TV STATIONS
</P>
<P>
   This year's South Carolina presidential primary was great news
for George W. Bush _ and it wasn't too bad for WIS-TV in Columbia,
S.C., either. The NBC affiliate earned $426,000 in political
advertising revenue during the first quarter of the year. It more
than doubled what John Cottingham, the station's general manager,
had budgeted, and easily eclipsed the $234,399 the station took in
during the same period four years earlier. This promises to be a
lucrative year for many stations across the country. The Television
Bureau of Advertising predicts politicians will spend $600 million
on TV ads during 2000, up from $400 million in 1996. The trend is
toward more ads being bought locally, instead of nationally. In the
last few presidential elections, ad dollars have shifted from the
national networks to local stations in key areas.
</P>
<P>
   INTO THE GOP VEEP MIX
</P>
<P>
   ``Friends of George W. Bush are promoting Rep. John Kasich as
the veep twin for'' George W. Bush, says U.S. News &AMP; World Report.
Kasich promoters are said to be nearing 1,000 petition signatures
backing him. Elizabeth Dole, meanwhile, has joined the board of
computer maker Gateway. Dole backers say it shows that she's
familiar with Silicon Valley and that she could be Bush's tech
link. Finally, according to U.S. News, conservatives are pushing
Oklahoma Gov. Frank Keating, who gets kudos for his handling of the
Oklahoma City bombing tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   AH, HOW QUICKLY THEY FORGET
</P>
<P>
   Now that George W. Bush and Al Gore have wrapped up their
parties' presidential nominations, it appears voters are forgetting
what they knew about the candidates. After February's New Hampshire
primary, according to a poll by the Joan Shorestein Center on the
Press, Politics and Public Policy, 24 percent of voters knew that
Bush is opposed to mandatory gun registration. Now that percentage
has fallen to 13 percent. The number of people who knew Gore
opposes using tax dollars to help parents pay for private or
parochial schools fell from 19 percent to 12 percent. The poll has
a 3 percentage point margin or error. ``A shorter, non-interrupted
campaign would be from the public's perspective a more informative
campaign,'' said Thomas Patterson of Harvard's John F. Kennedy
School of Government, co-director of the Vanishing Voter Project.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from Cox staff and wire reports.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
