<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5920 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR &LR;      04-24 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET'S GO OUT ON A LIMB AND MAKE YOU A `REALITY TV' STAR  
</HEADLINE>
   By DARYL LEASE   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Call me crazy, but I think our culture has reached a point where
you and I could sweet-talk a network executive into producing a TV
show in which you do nothing but ordinary stuff like floss your
teeth, sort your sock drawer and schlep down your driveway to get
your newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   We'd both get mind-numbingly rich, and you wouldn't even have to
take off your clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reality TV,'' as such fare is known, is the latest thing.
Every few days, the folks who run TV announce plans for yet another
show featuring real people in really dumb or really dangerous
situations.
</P>
<P>
   You may have read about ``Survivor,'' one such show that's set
to debut on CBS at the end of May. Sixteen people have been dumped
on a remote island off the coast of Borneo. They're videotaped
nonstop as they try to get along by spearing fish, nibbling on bugs
and roasting rats over an open fire.
</P>
<P>
   Every few nights, the group gathers and casts a secret ballot to
send the weakest or most obnoxious person home. The 13-week series
is supposed to result in one survivor, who will walk, or maybe
crawl, away with $1 million. (I hope there won't be any product
tie-ins for this. I'd hate to order my daughter a ``Survivor''
Happy Meal at Chez Mac's and find a toy rat-on-a-spit inside.)
</P>
<P>
   Reality-based programs are big in Europe, which is steadily
sending them our way, apparently to make up for centuries of giving
us really great art.
</P>
<P>
   One show, called ``Big Brother,'' has been a hit in several
countries. Ten people are crammed into a house outfitted with TV
cameras _ there's no privacy, hence the name _ and every week,
viewers vote out the weakest or most obnoxious. The last occupant
gets $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   In another show, ``Chains,'' four guys are chained at the legs
and ankles to a woman for five days. One day at a time, she unlocks
a fellow and sends him home. On Day 5, she claims her, uh, prize _
a date with the last guy and a box of cash.
</P>
<P>
   Other Euro-hits include ``The Bus'' (people ride on one for four
months) and ``In the Money'' (people do weird stuff like sit on an
egg and squawk like a chicken).
</P>
<P>
   ``My explanation is that our everyday life has become very
boring and nondramatic,'' Jens Jessen, an editor of a German
newsweekly, tells The New York Times. ``People are missing the real
life in their lives, so they want a substitute life.''
</P>
<P>
   There are, blessedly, some standards. Mike Darnell, a U.S.
producer of such shows, was planning one a while ago that was
called ``The World's Most Embarrassing Throw-up Moments.''
</P>
<P>
   He chose not to do it, although not for the reason you might
imagine, i.e. it's disgusting. According to The New York Times, he
scrapped the idea because he didn't have actual footage. Paying
actors to pretend to spew wasn't authentic enough.
</P>
<P>
   A few years back, I had the dubious honor of sitting in an
emergency room with a crowd of tired, ailing, cranky people
watching _ in blinking, open-mouthed incomprehension _ a show
created by Darnell called ``When Animals Attack.''
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to ignore. The volume was cranked up, apparently in
compliance with an insurance company edict that emergency-room TVs
be set at ear-piecing levels so that people won't lollygag and
drive up claims.
</P>
<P>
   The premise of the show was pretty simple: Clip after clip of
people getting their limbs ripped off or otherwise mauled by wild
animals.
</P>
<P>
   The first few incidents were unnerving. Those of us who were
able to hold our heads up glanced around the waiting room to see if
any of our fellow sufferers had an affliction similar to what we
were watching.
</P>
<P>
   When we determined they didn't, our eyes returned guiltlessly to
the TV for more. I didn't stick around long, but I suspect that
people eventually stopped flinching altogether and started saying,
``Shush'' to the nurse when she called their names.
</P>
<P>
   That's the beauty of reality TV, I reckon. No matter how grim
your reality may be, there's some schmuck or schmuckette on the
picture tube who's meeting an even grimmer fate _ and probably
isn't even earning royalties for it.
</P>
<P>
   So, give me a call, and we'll begin work on your very own
reality show.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, do you happen to have a cat with a really nasty
disposition? Maybe we can work that into a few action scenes.
</P>
<P>
   (Daryl Lease is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. Contact him at daryl.lease(AT)herald-trib.com.The
Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
