<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5924 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-BRAZIL-ANNIVERSARY-(T     04-24 1199
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-ANNIVERSARY-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NOTING PORTUGAL'S DISCOVERY OF BRAZIL, SOME SEE AN UGLY SIDE TO
HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ It was envisioned as a feel-good
patriotic festival like the American Bicentennial. But the
Brazilian government should have known its plans to mark the 500th
anniversary of the country's discovery by the Portuguese were
doomed when an irate Indian chief marched into Congress earlier
this month, drew his bow and arrow and threatened to kill the
Senate president.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, the yearlong commemoration got off to a bumpy start
Saturday, when military police used tear gas, night sticks and
rubber bullets to disperse 2,000 Indian-led demonstrators taking
part in a ``march of the excluded'' in Porto Seguro, focal point of
the official celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   More than 140 people were arrested and at least a dozen injured
in the clash. And Monday the director of the government's Indian
affairs bureau resigned in protest over the government's stance in
the whole affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened today was the same thing that took place when
Pedro Alvares Cabral arrived here,'' Nailton Pataxo, a leader of
the Ha Ha Hae tribe, said Saturday. ``He came, looted everything
and used violence against indigenous peoples.'' Pataxo's tribe has
been demanding the government return traditional lands now occupied
by ranchers.
</P>
<P>
   Cabral was the leader of the flotilla that on April 22, 1500,
sighted land in what is today the northern state of Bahia. The
first landing party went ashore the next day, led by a Polish Jew
who was the expedition's interpreter and whose languages included
Arabic and Hindi. On April 26, the rest of the crew disembarked at
the site now known as Santa Cruz Cabralia to erect a cross and
offer thanks in the first Roman Catholic Mass on Brazilian soil.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of Brazil's 300,000 Indians have vowed to ``resist'' the
commemorations of those and other events scheduled for coming days,
and they are not the only ones complaining. Black groups have also
been marching to protest what they say is the marginal role to
which Afro-Brazilians have been relegated. And the Movement of the
Landless, a leftist peasant group, is marking the anniversary with
a campaign to occupy 500 ranches and farms it contends are lying
idle.
</P>
<P>
   As the self-styled ``country of the future,'' bursting with
outsized dreams and ambitions, Brazil is not in the habit of
scrutinizing its past. ``Every 15 years, Brazilians forget
everything that happened in the past 15 years,'' is how a political
satirist, Ivan Lessa, once put it.
</P>
<P>
   The 500th anniversary, however, has forced a process of
self-examination, and many Brazilians do not particularly seem to
like what they see. ``I am ashamed of Brazil,'' the country's most
famous personage, the soccer player Pele, said in a newspaper
interview this month, denouncing what he called ``the diversion of
government funds, thievery and dishonest politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the country has largely bounced back from the crisis that
threatened to sink the economy last year, glaring problems remain _
such as urban violence and the concentration of income and land
ownership in relatively few hands.
</P>
<P>
   The result is an identity crisis. ``Brazil is marking 500 years
without knowing what it is,'' said a banner headline that ran in
the daily Jornal do Brasil over the weekend, echoing what many
Brazilians are saying.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, over the past year, the best-seller lists here have been
dominated by books that cast a critical look at Brazilian society
and history. Ranging from biographies of Emperor Pedro II and other
leading historical figures to trenchant analyses of social
inequalities, such works have been snatched up in record numbers by
a public that in the past has not shown much of a commitment to
buying books.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Brazilians want to know why things have not turned out
well, why Brazil hasn't worked,'' said Eduardo Bueno, the author of
three recent books on early Brazilian history that have sold more
than 500,000 copies. ``Life is complicated, money is scarce, a
feeling of citizenship is lacking, and people sense that the answer
lies in history, that perhaps things went wrong from the very
beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   That, however, is not the tone that the minister of tourism and
sports, Rafael Greca de Macedo, sought to impart when he wrested
control of the celebration away from the more intellectual types at
the Ministry of Foreign Affairs last year. His goal, he has said,
was a series of events that would be ``attractive, cheap and have
popular appeal,'' thereby helping the country's 170 million people
build a positive self-image.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't view history with a perspective of remorse,'' Greca
said recently at a news conference here for foreign reporters about
the anniversary celebration. He described Brazil as ``a land of
ethnic peace,'' praising its remarkable cultural and racial
diversity and arguing that Indians have cause to be grateful for
``their inclusion in Brazilian society.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there have been complaints that the $20 million Greca has
spent, some of it on concerts and the construction of a soccer
museum, should have gone elsewhere. ``Brazil would be much better
off if the president had applied the money consumed in this insipid
commemoration to building 500 schools and 500 hospitals,'' Artur
Xexeo wrote in his column in Jornal do Brasil on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the mother country on the other side of the Atlantic, a
similar divide has emerged. Although President Jorge Sampaio of
Portugal, who is here for this week's commemorations, has dismissed
complaints about the colonial period by arguing that ``we are
responsible only for our own time,'' Portuguese intellectuals have
taken a more negative view.
</P>
<P>
   ``The discovery was not a dialogue of cultures, nor an encounter
of peoples,'' Jose Saramago, the novelist who won the Nobel Prize
for Literature in 1998, wrote recently. ``It was violence,
depredation and conquest.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking a cue from such declarations, the Roman Catholic Church
here is about to issue an unprecedented mea culpa. At a weeklong
conference scheduled to begin Wednesday, the country's more than
300 bishops are to sign a statement asking forgiveness of Indians
and blacks for sins the church committed against them during the
colonial period.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Many times the church's envoys were more allies of the
conquistadors than the Gospel,'' Msgr. Marcelo Carvalheira, head of
the committee that is drawing up the statement, said in explaining
the need for the document. ``The philosophy was conquer first and
then catechize.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   With the national mood so somber and contentious, President
Fernando Henrique Cardoso has shown signs of increasing
exasperation. ``The 500th Anniversary festivities shouldn't be an
invitation to a wake,'' he said last week. In the face of the
protests, however, the president's itinerary in Bahia has been
reduced, and he is no longer scheduled to attend Wednesday's
commemorative Mass.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
