<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5929 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-ALTERNATIVE-MED-COX     04-24 1611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALTERNATIVE-MED-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Patients demanding doctors' help for nontraditional treatments
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For Felecia Dawson the problem was simultaneously
familiar and brand new.
</P>
<P>
   The fine-boned 40-year-old was experiencing the early symptoms
of menopause and contemplating the questions that the midlife
milestone presents to most women:
</P>
<P>
   Should she take hormone replacement therapy?
</P>
<P>
   Would herbs and nutritional supplements be an adequate
replacement?
</P>
<P>
   Could a plant-based diet cushion the stress ahead?
</P>
<P>
   The questions had more resonance than usual, because Dawson has
heard them asked so frequently. She is a doctor, an
obstetrician-gynecologist on the medical staff of Crawford Long
Hospital. Each week, patients ask for her help in exploring their
options.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am getting a lot more patients who are well-read, who don't
want to take estrogen, who want to know what their alternatives
are,'' said Dawson, who wears her long hair swept up in a regal
head wrap. ``Most doctors are hearing that these days, because our
patients are asking for it. But only some of us embrace it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dawson's parallel experiences, as a patient and as a doctor, sum
up a profound recent shift in health care. Consumer interest in
untraditional medicine is not a new phenomenon; what is new is
consumers' unwillingness to continue the exploration on their own.
Instead, they are insisting that doctors become knowledgeable about
alternatives too, so that they can offer advice and guidance when
patients need it.
</P>
<P>
   To a surprising degree, the medical establishment is responding.
The response springs from a mix of moral and market imperatives:
Consumers have proven they will do this with or without their
doctors, and physicians would prefer to be involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel like we must do this,'' said Dr. R. Paul Crank, Jr.,
director of medical affairs for DeKalb Medical Center, which has
opened a program combining conventional medicine and alternatives.
``It is not an optional thing. Our community is out there
experimenting with anything they can find. ''
</P>
<P>
   It has been seven years since a national survey by Harvard
Medical School researchers, published in the New England Journal of
Medicine, first disclosed that up to one in three adults used
alternative therapies. The trend has only increased since.
</P>
<P>
   In an update, released recently in the Journal of the American
Medical Association, the same researchers have found that 42
percent of U.S. adults now make use of unconventional practices
that are largely not taught in medical schools, such as
acupuncture, herbs, chiropractic and meditation. In 1997, the
researchers found, American adults made 60 percent more visits to
alternative medicine providers than they did to doctors. The total
amount that health-care consumers spent that year on alternative
care, without hope of reimbursement, was $27 billion _ the same
amount that consumers spent, in the same year, to see their
physicians.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers show Americans' eagerness for health care that is
more holistic, individual and self-directed. But they also point to
some troubling trends: Two-thirds of those who use alternative
therapies are still not talking to their doctors about it, the
Harvard researchers found. And as a result, 15 million adults are
believed to be taking both prescription drugs and natural remedies
without medical supervision, unwittingly risking dangerous
cross-reactions.
</P>
<P>
   The patients who do disclose their use of alternatives are
forcing a new kind of collaboration into their encounters with
doctors and nurses.
</P>
<P>
   ``My patients would come in and say, `I am trying this herb,
what do you think about it?''' Dawson said. ``And I wouldn't be
able to say I knew very much about it. But I was open to learning
with them.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to both patients' demands and doctors' need to
anticipate them, an industry has sprung up. Several peer-reviewed
journals devoted to alternative medicine have begun publishing, as
well as at least two newsletters focused on its business aspects.
Companies that market medical databases and patient-education
booklets have created companion products that supply information on
unconventional practices.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, continuing-education courses that acquaint health
professionals with the basics of alternative medicine are offered
during most months of the year in most parts of the country. One of
the most respected such courses, a weeklong symposium hosted by
Harvard Medical School each March, this year drew more than 500
participants, more than 200 of them physicians.
</P>
<P>
   Dawson was one of the attendees. So were a plastic surgeon from
Duluth, Ga., an internist from Decatur,Ga., an insurance executive
from Atlanta and the chief executive officers of DeKalb and
Gwinnett Medical Centers.
</P>
<P>
   The range of specialties suggests how complementary medicine is
becoming woven into mainstream health care. For Dawson, a
willingness to combine traditional and alternative methods has
produced a holistically oriented practice where nurses wear purple,
a fountain bubbles next to her computer, and patients seeking
advice for fibroid tumors are as likely to hear about exercise and
soy products as surgical procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sort of tailor things to the patient,'' she said. ``There
are patients who are very much into drugs and surgery and not
really open to alternatives, and then there are people who don't
want traditional anything. I have patients who want any way to
avoid the knife _ and then I have 55-year-old ladies who come in
with a long list of the drugs they are taking, and that is the only
thing they know.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jeffrey Zwiren, co-owner of Duluth's Prima Center for
Plastic Surgery, began educating himself on alternatives 10 years
ago when he realized how many of his patients had begun to take
them. His interest quickened last fall, after the American Society
of Anesthesiologists published a warning that common herbs
including kava, gingko, garlic and St. John's wort were interacting
negatively with sedatives or increasing blood loss in surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Now he counsels clients intensively on nutrition, and recommends
pineapple extract and homeopathic arnica to reduce bruising after
surgery. But he also won't operate unless patients have avoided
certain herbal products for at least two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``When patients see I am interested, they tell me a lot of the
things they are doing,'' Zwiren said. ``Most of them are amazed I
would ask.''
</P>
<P>
   DeKalb Medical Center hopes that soon each of its doctors will
ask patients about alternatives _ and that all of its patients will
feel comfortable enough to volunteer their experiences. The Decatur
institution has made a wholesale commitment to what it dubs
``integrative medicine.'' It has sent medical personnel and
adminstrators for training, created its own in-house continuing
medical education courses, held open meetings for the community,
and hired new staff with expertise in herbs, bodywork and
relaxation therapies.
</P>
<P>
   The effort is based in the medical facility's 15-year-old
Wellness Center, which now houses the new program in integrative
medicine. There is also an Integrative Medicine Advisory Committee,
headed by Dr. Eldred Taylor, and a proposal on the books to
consider making integrative medicine a full-fledged hospital
department, analogous to cardiology or pediatrics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to go out on a limb,'' said Taylor, an
ob/gyn. ``We're actually trying to be very conservative, paying
attention to what the National Institutes of Health says can be
substantiated. But when you have places like Sloan-Kettering and
Stanford and Harvard leading the way, it is not that hard to follow
along.''
</P>
<P>
   To enter the DeKalb program, modeled on one created by
alternative-medical celebrity Andrew Weil at the University of
Arizona, patients fill out a lengthy questionnaire. A team of
staff, headed by Taylor, reviews the information and suggests a
program of treatment. It is presented to the patient at a second
conference; to ensure collaboration, the patient can accept or
reject any recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   Though the program has been welcomed by patients, it may prove
not to be a major money-maker, said Jack Gerlach, DeKalb's CEO.
Insurance companies reimburse for alternative treatments only under
certain conditions, and DeKalb shares the cash that patients pay
for services with its practitioners in a 60-40 split.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is the suspicion that because hospitals can't collect on
hospital bills anymore, we have found a whole new revenue source,''
he said. ``That is not the reason we are doing this. Frankly, I'm
not sure the revenue is there.''
</P>
<P>
   The hospital has cast the new effort as a means of tying
together its Wellness Center and its medical staff, and of ensuring
that its health-care providers are alert to the whole range of
things that patients might be doing. Some of the doctors have been
dubious, Gerlach admitted, but the response from patients has
compensated for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We keep hearing from the community that they are glad a
hospital has gotten into this business,'' said Holly Wolfe, a nurse
who directs the Wellness Center. ``They didn't know where to go or
how to choose. But they trust that, in a hospital-based program, we
will have made sure this is safe and we will deliver it with high
standards.''
</P>
<P>
   O N T H E W E B : National Center for Complementary and
Alternative Medicine: altmed.od.nih.gov/
</P>
<P>
   M.A.J. McKenna writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
