<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    O debut shows power of Oprah
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Never underestimate the power of Oprah. The million-copy
launching of TV talk show host Oprah Winfrey's new magazine, O
($2.95), is a resounding success. It debuted Wednesday and was sold
out at a number of metro Atlanta outlets by the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got 200 copies for all of our stores,'' says Chapter 11's
Brian Lapidus, ``and they're all gone.''
</P>
<P>
   The story was the same at Joe Muggs on Peachtree Road, where
customers snapped up 250 copies in four hours Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were buying them four and five at a time,'' says
manager Awet Gebrehiwot. ``It was amazing.'' In comparison, she
adds, the only other magazine that sold nearly as well recently was
George magazine after John F. Kennedy Jr. died.
</P>
<P>
   Gebrehiwot admits she was skeptical about the content of O, the
Oprah Magazine, when it arrived. ``But when I had time to read it,
I was really impressed.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A tale of two covers: As expected, Time ($3.50) and Newsweek
($3.50) offer saturation coverage of the Elian Gonzalez raid in
Miami and the Cuban boy's reunion with his father. What's
interesting is the choice of pictures for the covers. Time has a
smiling photo of Elian reunited with his father, with a smaller
inset of the menacing looking armed federal agent confronting Elian
and Donato Dalrymple, his fisherman-rescuer, as they hide in a
closet at Lazaro Gonzalez's home. Newsweek opted for a cover photo
of a female agent carrying the terrified child out the door. An
unfortunate red-eye effect from the flash creates a demonic
appearance. A much smaller picture of a smiling Elian with his
father is inset.
</P>
<P>
   In both magazines, child psychology experts agree that Elian
needs to spend some time with his father _ without disruptions.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Date destinations: Tired of the same old dinner-and-a-movie
dates? Check out the May issue of Atlanta ($3.50) for 40
suggestions for romantic outings. Recommendations range from climbs
up Stone Mountain and Amicalola Falls to relatively inexpensive
meals by chefs-in-training at the Art Institute of Atlanta's School
of Culinary Arts. Other articles of interest include Candice Dyer's
outing with a pack of bloodhounds and Scott Freeman's tribute to
Andruw Jones' athletic artistry in center field.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Coming attractions: Summer's just around the corner, and
Hollywood is hoping it'll be a hot one at the box office.
Entertainment Weekly ($3.50) previews 135 of the new movies coming
soon to a theater near you and predicts that the winners will
include ``Battlefield Earth'' with John Travolta, ``X-Men'' with
Patrick Stewart and Halle Berry, ``Gladiator'' with Russell Crowe,
``Mission: Impossible 2'' starring Tom Cruise and ``The Perfect
Storm'' with George Clooney.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Vietnam revisited: People ($2.99) examines the fallout from
the Vietnam War 25 years after the fall of Saigon and updates what
happened to some of the people involved. Sen. John McCain talks
about his experience as a prisoner of war and notes that, although
he has made his peace with Vietnam, ``There are Vietnamese whom I
will never be able to forgive for their cruelty to me.'' Meanwhile,
Georgia native Chuck Searcy has devoted his life to helping
disabled Vietnamese children through his Vietnam Veterans of
America Foundation. ``I needed to mend not a physical injury but a
psychological wound _ the pain over what we had done in Vietnam,''
Searcy says.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Quick reads: Author Philip Caputo ventures into Kenya's Tsavo
National Park for a safari on foot to photograph lions and write
about his experiences for National Geographic Adventure ($3.95) .
Tsavo means ``place of slaughter,'' Caputo notes, and the name is
fitting: A century ago, two lions killed and ate 140 people in the
area. Working as a team, the animals sneaked into camps at night
and snatched the men from their tents. ... After destroying most of
its competition, Maxim ($3.99) is fatter than ever, with 216 pages
of glossy ads and glossy photo spreads of glossy women. One
interesting feature is a guide to fantasy camps where you can shoot
hoops with Michael Jordan or go hunting with Ted Nugent.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
