<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5933 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MIAMI-FRESCO-DISPUTE-     04-24 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIAMI-FRESCO-DISPUTE-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFF THE WALL: CONCRETE TROUBLES IMPERIL ABSTRACT MURAL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Fla., N.Y., Texas)  By MIREYA NAVARRO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ In 1984, artist David Novros found a public space for
one of his huge fresco murals in the old federal courthouse here.
With a $52,000 commission from the General Services Administration,
he spent five months painting about 6,300 square feet of walls and
arched ceilings in the two stories around an interior patio.
</P>
<P>
   It is by far the largest of Novros' works, one in which he tried
to depict in abstract shapes and light-to-dark colors the balancing
required in dispensing justice. But today he is trying to save his
``Frescoes in the Courtyard'' from destruction by the GSA in a
dispute that pits the artist and his supporters against historic
preservationists who want to restore the old courthouse to its
original condition.
</P>
<P>
   Novros, 58, an abstract painter in New York whose career started
in the late 1960s, got the government commission in Miami under
General Services' Art in Architecture program, which allocates 1
percent of a building's budget to art. GSA officials now say that
someone at the agency erred in commissioning the mural _ and in
allowing Novros to retouch it in 1987 _ without first subjecting it
to review under the National Historic Preservation Act. The old
courthouse building at the David W. Dyer Federal Building and U.S.
Courthouse complex in downtown Miami is on the National Register of
Historic Places.
</P>
<P>
   Both the deteriorating building and the mural are in need of
restoration. But Robert A. Peck, commissioner of the public
buildings service for the agency, said that preservation advisers
had told him that the mural would not pass the historical review
required in order to have it restored.
</P>
<P>
   So officials plan to restore the building and destroy the mural
sometime this year, either by removing the plaster or painting over
the mural.
</P>
<P>
   In letters to Novros and his supporters, Carolyn A. Dortch, a
GSA regional administrator, said that restoring the mural ``would
involve further alterations to the character-defining features and
spaces of the building'' that would be strongly opposed by historic
preservationists.
</P>
<P>
   Peck said in a telephone interview: ``This is not about somebody
that doesn't like David Novros' work; that's not it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not Rudy Giuliani taking offense,'' he said, referring to
a dispute last year between New York City's mayor and the Brooklyn
Museum of Art over a painting in its ``Sensation'' show. ``I happen
to like his work.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone likes the mural, and the artist, who has
created many works using a fresco technique that dates back to the
early Renaissance, contends that the decision has more to do with
political pressure than with historic preservation. As he enlists
support from art institutions, his opponents, among them local
lawyers and judges, argue that ``Frescoes in the Courtyard'' is at
odds with the architecture of the courthouse, which was built in
1933 in the Mediterranean revival style.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frescoes in the Courtyard'' was controversial from the start.
In an October 1984 article, which Novros keeps, The National
Enquirer wrote about it under the headline ``Painting, Painting on
the Wall _ Ugliest Tax Waste of Them All!'' It quoted courthouse
employees who complained that the modern work clashed with its
historical setting.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the mural's foes include U.S. District Judge Lenore C.
Nesbitt, who is overseeing the courthouse restoration. In a
telephone interview, Nesbitt said the mural's ``foreboding'' colors
clashed with the serenity of the courtyard and that the piece
itself was not in keeping with the building's ``original style and
beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   She and other critics want to replace Novros' reds, blues and
blacks with what they say is a more historically accurate color:
solid cocoa beige.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not on a vendetta,'' she said. ``We're on a program to
restore the courtyard, and the frescoes are inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   But Novros calls the planned destruction ``governmental
vandalism'' and a breach of his First Amendment rights. He has
declined a GSA offer for a new commission in another courthouse
building in the same complex. Agency officials have in turn
rejected the artist's suggestion that the frescoes be coated with a
varnishlike membrane to protect them before they are painted over.
The paint could later be removed with a solvent without damage to
the mural.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Novros said he would far prefer to have the painting
restored and ``respected.'' ``If they're not going to do that, I'd
like them to say publicly why they're doing this,'' he said. ``The
dispute is really between the government and the general public. We
can't get a public hearing on the issue. They want it destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   Novros has drawn support from a variety of institutions. Peter
Boswell, senior curator at the Miami Art Museum, called the artwork
``a very good match with the building'' and worth saving. ``It's a
good piece,'' Boswell said. ``He was very faithful to the tradition
of building ornament as it goes back to the Renaissance and
beyond.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter, Agnes Gund, president of the Museum of Modern Art
in New York, has offered to help rally support to save the mural.
Chief Federal Judge Charles P. Sifton &UR;  &LR; of the Eastern district of
New York wrote to the GSA calling the mural's ``magnificent.''
Sifton asked that the decision be reconsidered, saying that it
could have a ``devastating impact'' on the art program for
courthouses around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Spring, director of the Miami-Dade County Department of
Cultural Affairs, is trying to mediate. He said that while some
wanted the building restored to its original condition, others were
concerned ``about what that says about the community _ removing an
artwork from a public place by a well-respected artist.''
</P>
<P>
   Court officials have so far ignored his proposal to hold a
public meeting on the issue and provide, at the county's expense, a
fine arts conservator who would help find a way to save the fresco.
Spring said he was now looking for a film crew to ``at least ensure
some record of what David's work in that courtyard was.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Novros' murals can be seen in other parts of the country,
including one in Houston, which remains at the Museum of Fine Arts.
He recently had a solo show of abstractions made of large sheets of
copper at the Earl McGrath gallery in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Novros, who lives in SoHo with his wife, Joanna Pousette-Dart,
also a painter, and their 15-year-old son, Jason, describes wall
painting as an important alternative for artists. It ``doesn't
belong to anybody,'' he said. ``It doesn't cost anything to look at
it. It's a true democratic expression. That's why I love it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Miami space, he said, ``fit perfectly my ambitions of
expressing my ideas in public places with natural light.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to make something that was about justice as a kind of
balance, trying to come to some kind of equilibrium,'' he went on.
``I wanted people to have a feel for the complexity of making
decisions, of establishing morality and ethics in relationship with
justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Peck, the GSA commissioner, said that there were advocates of
the mural even within his agency. But, while difficult, his
decision is final, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I accept all the arguments, but we have to make a decision
about what to do with the courtyard,'' he said. ``The mural is a
modernist mural, and in both style and color it's not compatible
with the courtyard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
