<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5939 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-DIFFICULT-PATIENT     04-24 0436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-DIFFICULT-PATIENTS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: doctor's office?  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I recently helped care for a young woman in the hospital who had
been troubled for years with abdominal pain and a psychologically
abusive boyfriend. She had been in and out of hospitals, undergoing
X-rays, ultrasounds, CAT scans and so forth, all of which revealed
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   She was angry and afraid, and frequently came to the emergency
room demanding hospitalization and painkillers. Doctors who cared
for her in various hospitals had grown weary of her constant
complaints and started giving her morphine. Then she became
addicted, and no one cared about her enough to ensure that she got
the psychiatric help she sorely needed _ including, in retrospect,
me. It was easier to abdicate responsibility than to deal with her.
</P>
<P>
   She was the quintessentially difficult patient. After a while,
hers was a room we avoided. Her needs were bottomless, her pain
unremitting. In the constant buzz that is ward life for a resident,
time seemed better spent on other patients.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing seemed to be physically wrong with her, at least not
anything to explain the severity of her pain. Yet she relentlessly
demanded morphine. Try as we did, it was hard setting limits. A
tough approach alienated her. A conciliatory approach simply got
her more drugs.
</P>
<P>
   But one person, her internist, knew how to handle her. Though
the internist had been her doctor for only a few months, she had
developed an effective style with this patient. She was not afraid
to be strict: If the patient yelled, sometimes she yelled back _ or
she was kind, as the moment required. Though unconventional, she
grasped her patient's psychology like no one else, and she truly
cared for her. She eventually managed to discharge the patient
without morphine.
</P>
<P>
   I asked the internist about her approach to difficult patients.
She had several in her practice, she said. Like any doctor, she did
not seek them out, she said. But, she added, they are not hard to
treat, once you figure out what is bothering them.
</P>
<P>
   She understands this intuitively, and that is part of the reason
she is so effective. Some doctors know that patients do not always
come right out and say what is troubling them. Sometimes they hedge
or obfuscate, and often the key to treating them is to look a
little deeper. But exactly why one doctor can relate to a difficult
patient, and another can alienate her, is a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Another reminder, perhaps, that medicine is a field of
specialties. Some doctors are better at treating certain diseases;
some at treating certain patients.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
