<DOCNO> NYT20000424.0294 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5944 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-NURSE-PRACTIONERS     04-24 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-NURSE-PRACTIONERS-1600(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRACTITIONERS OFFER EXTRA ATTENTION FOR PATIENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 By TINA KELLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Eileen Cafasso's conversation with her patient was
expansive, touching on his taste for turnip paste, his number of
daily bananas, his self-diagnosed addiction to cheese. There was
time for him to ask about a particular blood pressure drug he had
read about, and for her to ask how he had spent his holidays.
</P>
<P>
   There was no watching of wristwatches.
</P>
<P>
   Godel, 79, who works in the mail room at Chase Manhattan Bank,
started seeing Cafasso, a nurse practitioner, a year and a half
ago, when he grew dissatisfied with the care he was getting from
his doctor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other one was giving me the bum's rush,'' said Godel, who
lives in Brooklyn. ``He was a heart specialist with too large a
work load. There was no way in the world they could they take care
of their patients.''
</P>
<P>
   Nurse practitioners are able to prescribe medicine and, in some
states, admit patients to the hospital. They pride themselves on
their ability to spend more time with patients, focusing on illness
prevention. For example, Cafasso, 34, spends about an hour with her
patients on their first visit to the Columbia Advanced Practice
Nurse Associates in Manhattan, which includes two other nurse
practitioners. Their practice has 500 patients, and Cafasso usually
sees 8 to 10 a day. By comparison, some doctors see 20 or more.
</P>
<P>
   The nurses' practice was the focus of a study published in
January in The Journal of the American Medical Association. The
study found no significant differences in the quality of care
received by patients randomly assigned either to doctors or nurse
practitioners.
</P>
<P>
   Patients who used emergency rooms for their health care and had
no regular doctors were offered care for a year from doctors or
nurses affiliated with Columbia University. The researchers
measured the patients' satisfaction with their care, their health,
(using physiologic test results for those with diabetes and asthma)
and their use of emergency rooms and other medical services.
</P>
<P>
   Although the quality of care was essentially the same, there
were three statistically significant differences between the
groups. Hypertensive patients treated by nurse practitioners saw
greater reductions in diastolic blood pressure than patients in the
doctor group. People treated by nurses were more likely to stick
with their provider's care than those treated by doctors; those
treated by doctors were more satisfied with their technical skill,
personal manner and, notably, time spent with the patient. But
while these differences were measurable, none were considered
likely to affect a patient's health.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mary O. Mundinger, dean of the Columbia nursing school and
the study's lead author, said the research had profound
implications. ``For those looking to get primary care from a nurse
practitioner, they can feel increasingly safe and confident in
doing so, as a result of this study,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The position of nurse practitioner was created in the mid-1960s
by a physician and nurse at the University of Colorado, working to
improve public health nursing. A nurse practitioner is now
generally required to have a master's degree in nursing, which
usually is a two-year program. Practitioners receive training in
topics like those taught to medical residents in primary care,
including taking medical histories and doing physical exams.
</P>
<P>
   At first they worked mostly with poor and rural patients, but
their skills were easily transferred to primary care, and they are
now increasingly seen in hospitals and in independent practices.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent afternoon, Cafasso treated people who welcomed the
time she was able to spend with them, talking about what ailed them
and how they could get and stay healthier. Kerry Hillard, 24, of
Manhattan, an editor with Baby Talk magazine, had a nasty cold in
the midst of her deadlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting, we don't realize the impact stress has on
our health,'' Cafasso told her. ``We don't really sleep or eat as
well, and we're more susceptible to colds.''
</P>
<P>
   Hillard has referred people to the practice. ``Here it seems
they are much more concerned with other aspects of your life: work,
nutrition, exercise and prevention,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Cafasso, an assistant professor at the Columbia School of
Nursing, where she received a master's of science, likes such
encounters because she can make more accurate diagnoses when she
understands what is going on in a patient's life.
</P>
<P>
   If, for example, someone comes in and says she is going through
a divorce, Cafasso says she tries to find out more. ``I'll ask how
are they coping with it, what kind of support system do they
have,'' she said. ``Clinically, it can tell you a lot.'' By
learning about a patient's coping mechanisms, she can assess how
rigidly the person may comply with particular health regimens.
</P>
<P>
   Cafasso, married with an infant daughter, followed her mother
into nursing. After 10 years, she got the extra training to be a
nurse practitioner, saying she wanted more decision-making power.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I could really give more to my patients by going on for
my advanced degree,'' she said. Her patients get, on average, 15
minutes longer with her than they would with a physician, based on
the American Medical Association's measures of average lengths of
doctor visits. ``We try to work with the patient individually to
get them to have a healthier life,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But there are those in medicine who are suspicious of the
finding that nurse practitioners can be as effective as physicians.
In an editorial accompanying the results of the Columbia study, Dr.
Harold C. Sox of the Dartmouth-Hitchcock Medical Center in Hanover,
N.H., criticized it for being too short and for working primarily
with Hispanic women in their 40's, a group not representative of
the population. (Women in their 40s are, on average, healthier than
the general population, and Hispanic women tend to have less
trouble with their pregnancies than others, though far higher rates
of diabetes and asthma.)
</P>
<P>
   Sox speculated that nurse practitioners might not fare as well
with more complicated cases, when they had to admit patients to a
hospital, care for them while there, and make appropriate choices
about drugs, which physicians spend many years learning, under
heavy supervision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we have a study that really tests independent nurse
practitioners' ability to do some of these things for which they
haven't had as much training as physicians,'' Sox said in a phone
interview, ``we shouldn't make the claim that they're
interchangeable.''
</P>
<P>
   But in defending her research, Mundinger pointed out that it
would be difficult to conduct a careful, randomized study on the
general population, because few people are willing to be randomly
assigned to a doctor or nurse. ``Those of us who are lucky enough
to have commercial insurance for health care have a strong
preference to choose our own provider,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The question, of course, comes down to dollars, and how the
study will be used by insurers, hospitals and private practices
hoping to cut costs. In his editorial about the study, Sox
cautioned, ``Its evidence that nurse practitioners and primary care
physicians could be interchangeable is far from convincing, but the
marketplace is not given to fine judgments.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, nurse practitioners appear to be cost effective, earning
about half to two-thirds of what primary care physicians earn.
Nurse practitioners in New York City are usually paid $80,000 to
$100,000 a year; statewide they receive, on average, $60,000.
</P>
<P>
   Sox noted that the primary care nurse practitioner work force is
projected to increase from 55,000 to 106,500, between 1995 and
2005, while the number of primary care physicians is expected to
increase by about 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Columbia study, taken in the context of cost control and
the growth of the nurse practitioner work force, is likely to mean
more competition for general internists and family physicians,''
Sox wrote. That, he added, is good for the patient, but bad for
doctors who invested a great deal of energy in their training but
could not keep ``busy enough to sustain their skills and earn a
reasonable living.''
</P>
<P>
   Mundinger said she hoped the study would provoke debate on how
public finances are allocated to medical education. Most money, she
said, now goes to train doctors. And Cafasso noted that some
physicians who had worked closely with nurse practitioners saw how
patients benefited from the additional emphasis on health promotion
and disease prevention.
</P>
<P>
   In practice, nurse practitioners must work well with doctors,
consulting them when patients' problems are beyond nurses'
expertise. For example, when Cafasso was concerned about Godel's
health, she referred him to a new cardiologist.
</P>
<P>
   Recently she discussed the results of his stress test with him
and told him that his cardiologist believed he might benefit from
an angiogram. When Godel cringed, she tried to reassure him. ``I
would never order you to do something you don't want,'' she
recalled telling him, then reminding him of the tightness he had
felt in his neck, a possible indication of risk for a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Cafasso said her meeting with Godel illustrated what she
enjoyed most about her job. ``I think the ability to spend that
extra time with patients,'' she said, ``somehow gets across to
patients that you understand their concerns.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
