<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Tuesday, April 25 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-SUIT (Washington) _ The Justice Department intends to
ask a federal judge this week to break the Microsoft Corp. into two
separate and competitive companies as a means to restore
competition in the software industry, according to officials who
are familiar with the government's deliberations. One company would
hold the Windows operating-system business, and the other would
have the Office suite of software programs and other businesses. It
is not at all clear that the trial judge, Thomas Penfield Jackson,
a Reagan appointee, would accept this breakup idea. He ultimately
assigns the remedy. And because the breakup proposal will almost
certainly be stayed pending appealed, the government plans to ask
for several temporary remedies that would modify Microsoft's
behavior during the interim. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY-FORCE (Washington) _ On the continuing debate about
the degree of force used in the government's raid to transfer
custody of Elian Gonzalez from his relatives in Miami to his father
in Washington. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds.: an early version of this story has moved; the
1stLd-Writethru is scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   MISSING-LAPTOP (Washington) _ An angry Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright on Monday announced new security measures
arising from the recent disappearance of a laptop computer
containing information of extreme sensitivity. The laptop, holding
files related to weapons proliferation, some of it gleaned by
satellite, disappeared more than two months ago from a State
Department conference room. Whether it was stolen or simple lost
has not been determined. The Federal Bureau of Investigation has
been conducting an exhaustive search. By Jane Perlez. (700 words)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-U.S.-ARMS (Moscow) _ A decade after the collapse of
Communism appeared to make superpower arms controls routine, the
old disputes over missile defenses have suddenly returned to the
forefront of United States-Russian relations. And though experts
think new rules of the nuclear game are technically feasible, the
issue has been caught up in American election politics and Russian
suspicions. By Michael R. Gordon. (1300 words)
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-POLITICS (Tehran, Iran) _ Two months after their triumph in
parliamentary elections, reformers are caught up in a war of nerves
with Iran's conservatives. The hardliners have closed newspapers,
jailed writers and annulled some election results, making the most
concentrated crackdown on dissent since the 1979 revolution. By
Susan Sachs. (1500 words)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-FUERTH (Washington) _ There is only one member of Vice
President Al Gore's staff close enough to call him Al. It is Leon
Sigmund Fuerth, Gore's longest-serving aide, who has acted as his
elder consigliere on national security matters for two decades.
Although he has exercised enormous influence over Gore, shaping his
interventionist views and stiffening his spine against world
dictators, the one-time career foreign service officer labors
largely in the shadows, preferring to remain, as he once said,
``nameless, faceless, odorless.'' But as Gore increasingly
contrasts his foreign policy experience with that of George W.
Bush, Fuerth may be drawn into the limelight, an uncomfortable
position for a man who never developed an ear for politics. By
Elaine Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
