<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5963 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-LUCENT-APPOINT-ART-NY     04-24 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUCENT-APPOINT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUCENT NAMES FORMER BOEING EXECUTIVE AS CHIEF FINANCIAL OFFICER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT9 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Still working to shore up its financial credibility
on Wall Street, Lucent Technologies named Deborah Hopkins, a senior
executive with the Boeing Co., as its chief financial officer
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins, 45, had been Boeing's chief financial officer since she
joined the aerospace giant in November 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Debby is a dynamic leader with a proven track record of
success,'' Richard McGinn, Lucent's chairman, said in a statement.
``Her experience, ability and enthusiasm will make her an immediate
and significant asset.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucent, North America's No. 1 maker of communications equipment,
suffered its first serious stumble in January, when the company
announced that its quarterly financial results would fail to meet
analysts' expectations. After splitting from AT&AMP;T in 1996, Lucent
had enjoyed a charmed financial existence, with its shares soaring
seemingly without end.
</P>
<P>
   But underlying the strength of the stock were some weaknesses.
Perhaps most important, Lucent had underestimated demand for new
optical communications systems, which transmit digital information
using pulses of light.
</P>
<P>
   That miscalculation allowed Nortel Networks of Canada, Lucent's
rival for decades, to assume some of Lucent's cachet. Based on the
companies' price-to-earning ratios, investors appear to believe
that Nortel is poised to grow significantly faster than Lucent.
</P>
<P>
   Donald K. Peterson, a former Nortel executive, had been Lucent's
chief financial officer since the company first offered shares to
the public in 1996. In March, less than two months after Lucent's
earnings warning, the company said that Peterson would step down to
run the company's weakest division. That unit, which makes
communications systems for corporate offices, is set to be spun
off.
</P>
<P>
   To replace Peterson, McGinn selected Hopkins, who joined Boeing
when that company was suffering in 1998. Two weeks after Hopkins
moved to Boeing from General Motors, Boeing said its forthcoming
financial results would fail to meet expectations and that it would
cut 48,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts blamed antiquated internal financial systems for
Boeing's woes, and Hopkins' reputation flourished as she modernized
Boeing's financial operation.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins replaced just about every senior executive in Boeing's
finance department and established more rigorous financial controls
for Boeing's operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think her legacy at Boeing, having been there only a little
more than a year, is the implementation of a disciplined set of
financial goals and objectives that all managers can operate
toward,'' said Byron K. Callan, who follows Boeing for Merrill
Lynch. ``If this move had happened six months ago, I would have
been a lot more concerned about it. But a lot of the infrastructure
is in place.''
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins' relationship with the financial community while at
Boeing was mixed, but in the end she appeared to emerge with
widespread respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Analysts all loved her at first because it was a change and
was refreshing,'' one Wall Street analyst said on the condition of
anonymity. ``And then people got irked at what they saw as her
highhandedness. Now, the world's come around again and people
realize that some of that change was hard, but she was an effective
catalyst.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, in the long run Boeing's stock did not appear to
respond. Trading at $42.125 just before her appointment at Boeing,
the company's shares closed Monday at $37.875, down $2.1875. One
analyst said the slide in Boeing's shares Monday could be
attributed to dismay over Hopkins' departure. Lucent's shares
closed at $60.625 Monday, down $2.375.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Monday, Hopkins said that one issue she intended
to address quickly was the potentially adverse effect of Lucent's
multibillion-dollar lending program for customers, some of whom
lack cash to buy Lucent's products. Some analysts have expressed
concern about the lending's effects on Lucent's balance sheet.
</P>
<P>
   She added that investors should have no fear that she will leave
Lucent after less than 18 months, as she did Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a daughter that is just entering high school,'' said
Hopkins, who will move from Washington State, near Boeing's
headquarters, to New Jersey, near Lucent's. ``And I have made a
sworn promise that she is able to go to the same high school for
four years in a row.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
