<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5972 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-SCOTUS-PRIMARIES-HNS &LR;      04-24 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-PRIMARIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COURT SKEPTICAL ABOUT CALIFORNIA PRIMARY SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: Filed in ``w'' and ``p'' categories.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ California's free-for-all primary election system
that allows voters to choose candidates without regard to party
affiliation came under fire Monday at the U.S. Supreme Court, where
justices questioned the law's constitutionality and its impact on
fair elections.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Sandra Day O'Connor called the California system
``tremendously intrusive'' on the rights of political parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very essence of the party's right is to define its own
message and decide its own candidates,'' O'Connor said.
</P>
<P>
   The California system allows any primary election voter _
whether registered as a Democrat, a Republican, a third-party
member or an independent _ to vote for the nomination of any
candidate from any party for any race.Justice Antonin Scalia
complained that the California system allows ``people with little
or no association with a party'' to decide that party's candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it hard to see why a state should take away a party's
right to elect whom it wants to elect,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If the court strikes down the law, California _ along with
Washington state, Alaska and Louisiana which have similar systems _
could be forced to change the way they conduct their primaries. The
court's decision is expected by late June.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, California voters passed Proposition 198, giving the
state a so-called ``blanket'' primary, which allows voters to cast
ballots in a primary to select any candidate, regardless of the
voters' political registration.California adopted the
single-ballot, blanket form of primary to give the state's 1.6
million independent voters their first opportunity to vote in what
had been a ``closed'' primary limited to party members.
</P>
<P>
   Washington state has used the blanket primary since 1935. Alaska
has had it in most elections since 1947. Louisiana has a variation.
The blanket primary gives voters more choices than the ``open''
primary used in 20 states. In an open primary, a voter can request
a party's primary election ballot at the polls without previously
registering in that party. The voter then is limited to voting only
in the primary that the voter selected. Thirteen states use closed
primaries where only registered party members can obtain their
party's ballot. Primaries in 13 other states are ``semi-closed,''
limiting participation to a party's members and to independents.The
state's Democratic, Republican, Libertarian and Peace &AMP; Freedom
parties challenged the California blanket primary system. They
argued that the system violates their First Amendment right of
``freedom of association.'' The national Democratic and Republican
parties filed briefs supporting that contention. In 1997, a federal
district court ruled that the blanket primary was constitutional.
U.S. District Judge David Levi said that while the system was an
``intrusion on a party's traditional right to select its own
candidates,'' the burden on the parties was not enough of a
``significant burden'' to justify striking down the law.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals affirmed, thinking
so highly of Levi's ruling that is simply adopted his opinion ``as
the opinion of our court.''
</P>
<P>
   In his arguments before the U.S. Supreme Court, George Waters, a
Sacramento, Calif., lawyer representing the four political parties,
said California's system is ``a wholesale assault'' on the parties'
ability ``to choose a standard bearer who best represents their
ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want people affiliated with a party to choose their
own candidates,'' he told the court.
</P>
<P>
   But Thomas Gede, special assistant attorney general for
California, defended the state's primary system, arguing that a
primary election ``belongs to the voters,'' not to the various
political parties. He also noted that the blanket system is what
``the voters want,'' referring to the fact that the system was
imposed by a voter referendum.
</P>
<P>
   Among the supporters of the blanket primary system are Sen. John
McCain, R-Ariz., and California Gov. Gray Davis, a Democrat, both
of whom broke with their parties in filing friend-of-the-court
briefs defending Proposition 198. They argued that the blanket
primary helps mavericks and moderates win nominations against
hard-core partisans by attracting ``crossover'' and independent
voters.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who relied heavily on Democrats and independents in his
unsuccessful bid for the Republican presidential nomination this
year, finished third in California's presidential primary behind
Democratic candidate Al Gore and Republican George W. Bush.Gede
told the high court that polls showed the blanket system had
``re-energized voters.'' He said voter turnout for last month's
presidential primary in California was 52 percent, the highest in a
presidential year since 1980.
</P>
<P>
   While conceding that the blanket primary infringes ``to a
degree'' on a party's right to association, Cede argued that the
state has an ``over-riding interest'' to enhance the ``democratic
nature of the election process.''
</P>
<P>
   Gede scarcely finished his opening statement before being hit by
a barrage of critical questions and comments from the justices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is it up to the voters to tell the parties who they should
elect?'' asked Justice Anthony M. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Justice David Souter chipped in: ``Under your system, the
unaffiliated voters will change the message of a party they don't
belong to.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist joined the ranks of the
skeptical justices.
</P>
<P>
   ``You say your system helps elect candidates that hold views
closer to the majority of voters,'' he said. ``But what if a party
believes that the majority is wrong and that over time, their
party's unpopular message will finally be accepted? You want to get
rid of these types of parties.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL; (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-00 1844EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
