A5981 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-MEXICO25-COX     04-24 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MEXICO25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush promises more free trade during bridge dedication in Mexico
 &HT;    By Dave Harmon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NUEVO LAREDO, Tamaulipas _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush spent a
couple hours out of the country Monday, hopping into Mexico to cut
the ribbon on a new international bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the likely GOP presidential nominee whose foreign policy
credentials have been questioned during his campaign, was in
friendly territory as he and Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo
dedicated the World Trade Bridge connecting Laredo and Nuevo
Laredo.
</P>
<P>
   The bridge, which carries only commercial traffic, opened April
15. It is the fourth bridge connecting the two cities.
</P>
<P>
   Standing before hundreds of cheering Mexicans under a loading
dock canopy, Bush used the event to promise to push free trade if
elected president.
</P>
<P>
   Since the North American Free Trade Agreement passed in 1994,
trade between the United States and Mexico has reached $200 billion
dollars a year, and half of all exports to Mexico passed through
Texas, Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we must build on the successes of NAFTA,'' Bush said. ``As
president, I will work to create a entire hemisphere of free
trade.''
</P>
<P>
   If elected, Bush said, he would ask Congress for fast-track
authority to negotiate new trade agreements, and he promised the
crowd he would not treat Mexico and Latin America as afterthoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past there have been walls and divides between Mexico
and the United States,'' he said. ``Today one more barrier has
fallen away, one more divide has been bridged.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's brief foray into Mexico on Monday marked his first trip
out of the country since clinching the GOP presidential nomination.
Earlier in the campaign, Bush talked about the possibility of
making major foreign trips, perhaps throughout South and Central
America as well as overseas.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, however, Bush campaign officials have said no
such trips are planned, though they are still a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Zedillo met privately for about 30 minutes after the
dedication. Neither was available for comment after their session.
</P>
<P>
   During the ceremony, Zedillo praised Bush, who has been popular
in Mexico for his ``deep appreciation for Mexico and our culture.''
He said the new bridge will help create jobs and speed up commerce
in the traffic-choked sister cities.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican president, a lame duck whose six-year term ends at
the end of this year, also urged both governments to continue
working to combat violence and smuggling on the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want a border without drug traffickers and people
traffickers, `` Zedillo said. ``(The border) can be much better.''
</P>
<P>
   For residents of both cities, the new bridge over the Rio Grande
already has relieved the infamous miles-long lines that used to
pile up at the two bridges connecting the downtowns.
</P>
<P>
   All commercial traffic now crosses at the World Trade Bridge or
the Solidarity bridge, both located miles upriver from the city
centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been wonderful,'' said Laredo Mayor Betty Flores. ``I
have gotten so many calls from people thanking me because they got
their two (downtown) bridges back.''
</P>
<P>
   With the 18 wheelers no longer clogging downtown, Flores said
the city plans to accelerate its downtown revitalization effort.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
