<HEADER>
A5982 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-LITERARY-OFFSPRING-10     04-24 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LITERARY-OFFSPRING-1080(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG AUTHORS FIND THEIR PARENTS' FAME A BOOM AND A BANE 
</HEADLINE>
  (NYT Photo 7 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KAREN ANGEL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gautama Chopra freely admits that his last name helped sell his
novel. His first agent was a friend of his father, the best-selling
New Age guru Deepak Chopra. His publisher, Amber-Allen, was the
publisher of his father's blockbuster ``The Seven Spiritual Laws of
Success.''
</P>
<P>
   His father even wrote the foreword to the novel, ``Child of the
Dawn,'' about a teen-ager's spiritual awakening. The book generated
reams of publicity; booksellers and curious fans of his father
snapped it up.
</P>
<P>
   Gautama Chopra, 24, is not the only young writer capitalizing on
a literary lineage. There are Jong, Heller, Updike, Bellow,
Theroux, Styron, Rice and McPhee (make that three McPhee) children
writing, not to mention two Cheever offspring. All were born with
the most valuable asset a writer can have: access.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a marketplace that's very interested in new voices and
that acknowledges pedigree,'' said Suzanne Gluck, an agent at
International Creative Management. ``When you talk to editors about
a first book by a Katie Roiphe or a Susan Merrell,'' Gluck added,
referring to the daughters of the novelist Anne Roiphe and the
best-selling author on relationships, Maggie Scarf, ``there's
greater interest because they do feel the talent is handed down.''
</P>
<P>
   The children of baby-boomer writers are coming of age. Just as
the music and film industries are seeing a burst of activity from
stars' progeny, books are being written by young people with
familiar names and, in some cases, derivative styles. They have
been emboldened by their parents' successes, and they can expect
more lucrative rewards than ever before from such sources as film
rights and foreign and electronic editions.
</P>
<P>
   ``These days advances are higher, and there tends to be a lot
more money in publishing, particularly if you hit it big, if you
turn out to be the next David Guterson,'' said Ted Solotaroff, a
prominent editor for 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   As consolidation in the industry puts extra pressure on the
bottom line, editors are looking for a sure thing. A last name
associated with best-sellerdom creates a powerful brand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Agents know they have a better chance of selling a mediocre
book by a person with a recognizable name than selling a very good
book by a person who's unknown,'' said Adam Bellow, 42, the son of
Saul, who is writing a book about nepotism for Doubleday that is
scheduled for publication next year. ``Publishers themselves know
an established name translates into sales. Frank McCourt published
a best seller. Then Malachy McCourt published a best seller. His
book wouldn't have been a best seller if Frank's hadn't been. He
probably wouldn't even have gotten it published.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good name used to mean that you had breeding and education.
A good name in our society means you can sell it.''
</P>
<P>
   The brand effect particularly comes into play when the writer's
relative adopts the same genre _ in the case of the McCourts, the
memoir; with the Chopras, spirituality. Carol Higgins Clark,
daughter of suspense diva Mary, writes mysteries; in fact, Carol
just brought the Higgins Clark brand under one roof with an
estimated $2 million contract with her mother's publisher, Simon &AMP;
Schuster. Eliza Minot, sister of Susan, writes family-oriented
novels for Knopf, too. And brother George Minot is working on his
first novel for Knopf, also about family.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of sales success, books by writers' relatives cover the
gamut. ``A Monk Swimming'' by Malachy McCourt (Hyperion, 1998) has
sold 330,000 copies, a small fraction of the 10 million copies of
Frank's ``Angela's Ashes'' in print, but not bad considering the
lukewarm reviews ``Monk'' received. All four of Carol Higgins
Clark's books have hit the New York Times best-seller list. Brian
Herbert jointly wrote a prequel to the sci-fi classic ``Dune'' by
his late father, Frank, titled ``Dune: House Atreides''
(Spectra/Bantam, which rocketed onto best-seller lists last fall
and has 200,000 copies in print. (Sales figures were unavailable
from the publisher.)
</P>
<P>
   Others have garnered respectable if not stellar sales. Gautama
Chopra's novel has sold 35,000 copies since 1998. In a strong
showing for a first novel, Eliza Minot's ``Tiny One'' (Knopf) is
nearing sales of 20,000 copies since its publication in November.
``Hullabaloo in the Guava Orchard'' (Atlantic Monthly Press, 1998)
by Kiran Desai, daughter of the writer Anita Desai, has also done
well, selling 27,000 copies. ``My Father, Dancing'' (Knopf, August
1999), short stories by Bliss Broyard, daughter of Anatole Broyard,
a book critic for The New York Times and an editor at The Times
Book Review who died in 1990, has sold more than 20,000 copies.
This probably figured into Little, Brown's decision to pay a
six-figure advance for her forthcoming memoir, ``Mixed Blood.'' But
a first novel published at the same time, ``A Stranger in the
Earth'' (Harcourt Brace by Marcel Theroux, son of Paul, has sold
only 8,000 copies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot more sons and daughters of literati writing
now, and I'm sick to death of it,'' said Ivan Solotaroff, 43, who
is writing a book about executioners for HarperCollins, where his
father, Ted, worked 10 years ago when it was Harper &AMP; Row. ``I
think people should go get a life instead of dining out on their
heritage. My first impression is, `How original _ you wrote a
book.' That's what people are thinking of me, and it puts a lot
more pressure on what I write.''
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenon may be especially appropriate in an era in which
everything is defined by its relationship to something else. ``A
Density of Souls,'' the first novel of Christopher Rice, 21, son of
Anne, is described by his editor at Talk Miramax Books, Jonathan
Burnham, ``as `Dawson's Creek' crossed with Donna Tartt,'' the
novelist. ``Normal Girl,'' the first novel of Molly Jong-Fast, 21,
due out in June, is described as ``a `Less Than Zero' from the
female point of view,'' by her editor, Pamela Cannon, at Villard
Books.
</P>
<P>
   It is no surprise that Rice would end up at a synergy factory
like Talk Miramax, which is printing 75,000 copies of his book for
its August release, sending him on a 20-city tour and conducting a
national advertising campaign for the book. It is extraordinary
support for a first novel, and a flag to booksellers that they had
better stock up on it. Even if his book flops, Rice will have
another chance because he has a two-book contract with Talk
Miramax, which is also not the norm for a novice.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Publishers do not overtly use parentage to promote books (except
for mentioning it in catalogs) because that would undermine the
idea that a work stands on its own. But a priceless last name still
sounds all the right chords of recognition in advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   Like Gautama Chopra, most children of writers mine their
connections on the path to publication. Rice presented his
manuscript to his mother. ``I told her, `Mom, I think I've written
a book,' and she said, `Oh, my God.' Then she said, `I have to send
it to everybody I know.''' Everybody included her agent, Lynn
Nesbit, who is now Christopher's agent too.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually some second-generation writers find that their family
background can be as troublesome as it is advantageous. ``You get a
lot of publicity, but most of it's bad,'' said Jong-Fast, the
daughter of Erica Jong. Reviewers compare their work to that of
their parents, usually unfavorably. The children struggle to
establish a literary identity, a subject Martin Amis, son of
Kingsley, touches on in his forthcoming memoir from Talk Miramax.
And they inherit their parents' enemies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be people gunning for her just because she's my
daughter,'' Erica Jong said. ``The access is there, but the
criticism is unduly harsh.'' Paul Solotaroff, another of Ted's
sons, is working on his first novel, a sex comedy. ``My father was
a tough editor and a tough critic,'' said Paul, 44, ``and there are
a number of people out there who have long memories.''
</P>
<P>
   The psychological hurdles are myriad. The relentless comparison
faced by Andre Dubus III, 40, namesake of his father, Andre Dubus,
the short-story writer who died last year, often made him feel like
``Elvis Jr.,'' said the author of ``House of Sand and Fog'' (W.W.
Norton, 1999). ``People would see a story by Andre Dubus _ it
probably got my manuscript to the top editor before it got
rejected.''
</P>
<P>
   All three of the younger Dubus' books, including ``House of Sand
and Fog,'' a National Book Award nominee that has sold 120,000
copies, made the rounds for more than a year before finding
publishers. ``I got nothing but no's for 10 years,'' said Dubus,
who still depends on carpentry for half his income.
</P>
<P>
   The going has not been so smooth for David Updike, either. The
son of John Updike, he had a short-story collection, ``Out on the
Marsh,'' published by David R. Godine 10 years ago, but it sold
only about 3,000 copies. He has also written six children's books
and collaborated with his father on a seventh. For several years,
his agent has been shopping around three more books. ``It's a
little distracting if you're struggling at something to be related
to someone who's so successful,'' said David, 43. ``But the
alternative of not doing it would be untrue to myself.''
</P>
<P>
   That struggle causes many children of authors to fight the urge
to write as long as possible. Determined not to follow in his
father's footsteps, Dubus recalled: ``I said I was going to be a
pipe fitter like Pappy, my grandfather. But I felt a calling. I
felt this weird, wispy pull.''
</P>
<P>
   Writing also seems the surest way into their parents' hearts.
Katie Roiphe, 31, is working on her first novel for Dial Books. It
is a 19th-century romance tentatively titled ``Still She Haunts
Me.'' ``Sometimes I think my work could be reduced to one of those
pictures you give to your parents to paste on the refrigerator as a
kid,'' said Roiphe.
</P>
<P>
   In Adam Bellow's book, tentatively titled ``In Praise of
Nepotism,'' he asks: ``Am I an opportunist trading on my father's
name, or am I a chip off the old block who is emulating his father
and thereby seeking his approval? The answer is both.''
</P>
<P>
   As a former editorial director of the Free Press, Adam built his
literary reputation around nonfiction. He spent his 20's writing
short stories, but turned down offers of publication to escape the
inevitable comparisons to his father, a Nobel laureate. But his
father will always be the most important editor in his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave him the first 50 pages to read,'' Adam said, referring
to his book. ``After he read them, I threw them away. They were
awful. He was very nice about it. He said, `You're a very good
writer and your ideas are very interesting, and I just have one
reservation.' I knew there was a problem, and he put his finger on
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-00 1853EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
