<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5984 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-IRAQ-POVERTY-HNS &LR;      04-24 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-POVERTY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CONGRESSMAN URGES AID FOR IRAQI CIVILIANS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AUSTIN ZALKIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A congressman who recently toured hospitals, health
clinics and schools in Iraq on Monday urged the United Nations to
ease sanctions so that more food and medicine can flow into the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tony P. Hall, D-Ohio, said the United Nations should do
everything it can ``to alleviate the suffering of the innocent
people who are not the intended targets of sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of malnourished children'' in Iraq, he said.
``I've seen malnourished children in many lands and I know what I'm
looking at.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1991 Gulf War, the United Nations has maintained
sanctions against Iraq as a way to compel President Saddam Hussein
to comply with post-war agreements to destroy weapons of mass
destruction. Since 1996, however, the United Nations has
periodically allowed Iraq to sell limited amounts of oil to buy
food and medical supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Hall told a news conference that the sanctions have created
problems with the Iraqi economy and population that did not exist
in the 1970s and 1980s. He said the national unemployment rate
stands somewhere between 50 and 65 percent, and illnesses such as
polio and cholera pose major threats to public health.
</P>
<P>
   He said at least a quarter of Iraq's children under age seven
are malnourished and that infant mortality rates are among the
highest in the world. He charged that Iraqi children are not
getting help in part because of holdups of supply deliveries that
result from the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   The Ohio congressman, who also has undertaken independent
humanitarian missions to North Korea and Ethiopia, traveled to Iraq
April 16-20 to determine whether reports of Iraqi hardship were
correct.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is ample evidence to show that Iraq is facing serious
humanitarian problems,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said items such refrigerators are needed in Iraq to store
vaccines for polio. However, the United States and allies like
Britain are reluctant to send these items into Iraq, fearing they
may be used to bolster the nation's military operations rather than
help civilians.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James Rubin told a news conference
Monday that the United States had been working to lift ``any
unnecessary holds'' on humanitarian supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as allowing dual purpose goods in, we've tended to err
on the cautious side given Saddam Hussein's track record of using
dual-purpose goods to produce chemical weapons,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said Iraq should be prevented from developing chemical and
biological weapons, but added that loosened regulations are needed
to help civilians.
</P>
<P>
   He also faulted the Iraqi government for refusing to allow
humanitarian workers from other nations into the country, and he
accused Hussein's regime of being uncooperative with the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   (Austin Zalkin can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at
dart(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
