<P>
   FOR TUESDAY AMs
</P>
<P>
   Business Day Front Page (coded ``f'' unless otherwise noted): &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Top lede)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-SPLIT (Undated) _ What the world would look like under
the Justice Department's breakup plan for Microsoft. The plan would
break the company into two entities of roughly comparable size,
both with high-margin businesses. It would avoid fracturing the
industry-standard operating system, while creating a separate
company with a theoretical incentive to write software for other
systems. But given the huge advantage of incumbency that each
business would retain, some questioned Monday whether the result
would simply be two monopolies instead of one.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   (Center display)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-TV (Mexico City) _ Not even his own father was sure that
Emilio Azcarraga Jean could run Grupo Televisa SA, the world's
biggest Spanish-language broadcast conglomerate. When his father,
Emilio Azcarraga Milmo, died in April 1997, he had not tapped his
29-year-old son to succeed him as chairman of the empire but had
instead handed that post to another young executive. But now, just
three years later, the junior Azcarraga is the chairman, president
and undisputed leader of Televisa. He survived one internal power
showdown after another, refinanced his debts and consolidated
financial control of the $9 billion corporation. He retired nearly
an entire generation of management chosen by his father, including
46 vice presidents, and revolutionized the operating culture by
imposing cost controls and laying off 6,000 of the company's 20,000
employees.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved.)
</P>
<P>
   (Right Center)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Since it first sold shares to
the public 14 years ago, Microsoft has become something more than a
software company. As it turned in steady increases in profit and
revenues quarter after quarter, year after year, Microsoft
convinced an entire generation of investors that there was no price
too rich to pay for a leading technology company. But no more. For
the first time in more than a decade, investors have had to
confront the reality that even Microsoft sometimes misses its mark.
And they are not happy. By Alex Berenson.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   (Bottom)
</P>
<P>
   LUCENT-APPOINT (Undated) _ Still working to shore up its
financial credibility on Wall Street, Lucent Technologies on Monday
named Deborah C. Hopkins, a senior executive with Boeing Co., as
its chief financial officer. Hopkins, 45, had been Boeing's chief
financial officer since she joined the aerospace giant in November
1998. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT 9 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
