<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6000 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0425-COX     04-24 1791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0425-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AS ACCUSATIONS FLY, CONGRESS PREPARES FOR HEARINGS ON ELIAN RAID
 &HT;    (650&AMP;ADDS)
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert joined a growing
chorus of Republican criticism Monday over the use of force in last
weekend's pre-dawn raid on the home of Elian Gonzalez's Miami
relatives, calling on a House panel to hold hearings on the
incident.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno and Clinton administration
officials, meanwhile, went on the offensive, blaming the Miami
relatives for forcing the confrontation and suggesting that a
congressional probe would be a political ploy aimed at diverting
attention from more pressing national issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did what we had to do,'' Reno said on NBC's Today Show. ``I
have no regrets whatsoever. I tried my level best to make sure that
we avoided this situation.''
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said President Clinton was
``convinced that the operation ... was the right thing to do and
was the only alternative remaining to us to reunite the boy with
his father.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno is scheduled to meet Tuesday with Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott, and about a dozen senators who have criticized the
raid, in a Capitol room normally used for national security
briefings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to politicize this,'' said Lott spokesman John
Czwartacki. ``We don't want to have a three-ring circus on the
Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   Czwartacki said no decision had been made whether the Senate
also would convene hearings on the raid, but Senate Judiciary
Committee Chairman Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, said he was considering it.
Czwartacki also said no decision had been made on whether to
consider bills that would confer either U.S. citizenship or
permanent residency status on the boy.
</P>
<P>
   House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., said as
per Hastert's request, a ``preliminary inquiry'' would begin soon
and ``will focus on whether the use of such force was necessary or
appropriate under all of the circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   For the third day in a row, the Miami relatives were turned away
at the gate of Andrews Air Force Base. Elian and his father,
step-mother and half-brother have been living on the base since
Saturday, but there were continuing reports that they might
relocate to the Wye River Plantation on Maryland's Eastern Shore _
the site of the Middle East peace talks in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, Cuban-American leaders called for a strike Tuesday to
demonstrate opposition to the raid. About 60 women dressed in black
held a protest outside the federal courthouse displaying copies of
the picture taken Saturday morning of an armed federal agent
confronting Elian in the arms of one of the fishermen who rescued
him last Thanksgiving Day.
</P>
<P>
   On the legal front, the U.S. Justice Department attempted to
file its arguments with the 11th Circuit Court of Appeals in
Atlanta, which has scheduled a hearing for the week of May 11 on
the issue of who can speak for the boy on the question of political
asylum. The legal brief was too long, so the government asked for
more time to file its arguments.
</P>
<P>
   The Immigration and Naturalization Service ruled in January that
only the boy's father can speak for him on such issues. Elian's
father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, has promised to remain in the United
States until the appeals process is completed, but has repeatedly
said he wants to return with the boy to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Elian lived with his Miami relatives from late November _ after
he was found floating in the Atlantic Ocean following the death of
his mother and nine others whose boat sank fleeing Cuba _ until
federal agents raided the home shortly after 5 a.m. (EST) Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Controversy continued Monday over not only the conduct of the
raid but whether it was necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Podhurst, a friend of Reno's for 30 years who was
negotiating a transfer of Elian on the telephone with her when the
raid began, reiterated his claim that an agreement was imminent
that would have prevented the raid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe a deal was within minutes or an hour away,''
Podhurst said on NBC's Today Show. When the raid began, ``I was
shocked, I was disappointed, I couldn't believe what I was looking
at it on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Later Monday, Podhurst called Reno ``a extraordinarily strong
woman'' who made a different decision than the one he would have
made.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, who said she trusted Podhurst ``with my life,'' said the
negotiations collapsed over the family's repeated insistence that
they meet with Juan Miguel in South Florida _ after previously
promising to meet with him anywhere _ and their refusal to agree to
release Elian to his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just kept getting mixed signals ... from a family that had
given us hope and then pulled it back, said they would comply with
the law and then said on several occasions that we would have to
take the child by force,'' Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart, asked about Democratic Florida Sen. Bob Graham's claim
that Clinton had promised him the raid would not be conducted at
night, said Clinton had merely been expressing his hopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the president said to Sen. Graham ... was that we didn't
want to do this, we thought there was a better way,'' Lockhart
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart also disputed Graham's claim that Gregory Craig, the
attorney for Juan Miguel Gonzalez, had veto power over attempts to
negotiate an agreement on custody of Elian.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans continued to criticize the use of force , however.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert, in calling for the Judiciary Committee hearings, said
he was ``appalled by the Clinton-Gore administration's decision to
use force in Miami to wrest Elian Gonzalez from his American
relatives. In doing so, our government has invaded the home of
American citizens who deserve the protection of our laws and a
certain respect for their rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. J.C. Watts, R-Okla., the third-ranking GOP House member,
said ``it's hard to imagine how (the administration) made this
child's safety a top priority when the Clinton-Gore administration
orders armed strangers wearing masks and guns to break into his
Miami house and whisk him away in the middle of the night.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Reno, Rep. Bill McCollum, chairman of the House
Judiciary subcommittee on crime, asked for answers within 24 hours
to a series of questions regarding the reasons for the raid and its
conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one overriding concern each of us has expressed throughout
this case is that the psychological well-being of Elian Gonzalez be
paramount,'' McCollum said. ``How can you possibly reconcile that
goal with the reality of the boy waking up to an armed invader in
his home pointing assault weapons and screaming obscenities at him
and his loved ones?''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said the public ``should not be surprised that the
first reaction from Capitol Hill is ... personal attacks on the
attorney general, personal attacks on the president, and then an
announcement of extensive investigative hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they make the choice that this is what they want to
dominate the next weeks and months, and not issues like
prescription drugs and minimum wage and patients' bill of rights,
that's the choice they make,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said Clinton was briefed on the general details of the
raid before it began and he concurred in its execution. Lockhart
blamed the Miami relatives for the action.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this could have been avoided; none of this had to happen.
This happened because the family did not respect the legal
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Responding to several tearful news conferences by the Miami
relatives' since the raid, Lockhart said ``no matter how loudly
they yell, no matter how impassioned their arguments are, when it
came down to the very simple issue of would the Miami relatives
respect the decision that the father had custody of the boy, the
answer was always 'no.'''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Several administration officials defended the extent of force
used in conducting the raid.
</P>
<P>
   Bo Cooper, INS general counsel, said ``there is a big difference
between a show of force and a use of force.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that there had been reports that some demonstrators
outside the house might have weapons _ and uncertainty whether
anyone inside the house was armed _ Cooper said ``you can't bet in
a situation like this. You have to be ready for any eventuality.''
</P>
<P>
   The heavy display of force and the timing of the raid before
dawn _ when there were relatively few protestors outside the house
_ were planned to minimize the risk of serious injuries, he said.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   A hearing on the Miami raid would add another probe to a series
of congressional inquiries of the Clinton administration.
Currently, the House Judiciary Committee is investigating the
Justice Department's handling of the Branch Davidian case in Waco,
Texas in 1993, allegations of campaign finance violations by the
Clinton-Gore campaign in 1996 and the transfer of nuclear secrets
to the Chinese government in the late 1990s. These investigations
follow the Clinton impeachment hearings and effort to remove him
from office in 1998 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Political analyst Charles Cook said Republicans could be in
danger of looking like they are obsessed with politically motivated
investigations that have little resonance with the general public.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (Texas Gov. George W.) Bush is handling it right and
(House Majority Leader Tom) DeLay is handling it wrong,'' Cook
said, noting that DeLay has been outspoken in demanding an
investigation while Bush has been only mildly critical of the raid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst thing the Republicans could do is have this
investigation,'' Cook said, noting that voters most opposed to the
raid are Cuban-Americans and conservatives and neither group are
swing voters. ``They're going down the road they went with
impeachment. They're so consumed with placating their base, they
forget that is not what swing voters are interested in.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry J. Sabato, director of the University of Virginia's Center
for Government Studies, said that if Republicans continue focusing
on the raid for too long ``the really silent majority that favored
the action might become aroused. If this is still going on in a
week or two, I'd say they're making their typical political
miscalculations.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   Immigration and Naturalization Service: http://www.ins.usdoj.gov
</P>
<P>
   Miami relatives: http://libertyforelian.org
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
