<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MEXICAN PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES GEAR UP FOR DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SUSANA HAYWARD  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Although it is not exactly an American style
democratic face-off, aspirants to the Mexican presidency will meet
in a live television debate Tuesday night for the second time in
the country's history.
</P>
<P>
   The encounter, the first one since 1994, could make or break two
of the main contenders in a close presidential campaign that,
analysts say, is the first time an opponent could unseat the
candidate of the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party. The
party, known as the PRI, has been in power for 71 years, making it
the longest-ruling political party in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The debate will give us a chance to see the real level of the
campaign,'' said Erick Fernandez, a political analyst at the
Universidad Iberoamericana in Mexico City. ``Even though the format
will not allow an exchange of ideas like they do in democratic
societies, there will be a solidifying of political positions.''
</P>
<P>
   The 90-minute exchange begins in the evening rush hour, when
most Mexicans are not home or are just leaving work. There will be
no questions from the media, and the occasion will only provide
revolving opportunities for each candidate to speak for a total of
14 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   A second debate with only the three top contenders for the July
2 election is scheduled for late May.
</P>
<P>
   The race is a tight one between veteran Francisco Labastida, an
economist who has served in important cabinet posts of several PRI
administrations, and Vicente Fox, a former Coca-Cola executive and
ex-governor of the state of Guanajuato state with the center-right
National Action Party, or PAN.
</P>
<P>
   Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, the first elected mayor of Mexico City and
a three-time presidential candidate, has been running a distant
third in the polls. But a good showing in the debate could bring
Cardenas' numbers up at a time when even some important backers of
his leftist-center Democratic Revolutionary Party have urged him to
drop from the race.
</P>
<P>
   A new poll in the Mexico City daily Reforma published Monday
gave Labastida 47 percentage points, compared with 39 percent for
Fox and 12 percent for Cardenas. The numbers have remained steady
since January, although internal polls by Fox's party has him ahead
by up to 15 points.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign has been marred by personal insults on both sides.
Fox, who stands well over six feet tall, once joked that Labastida
was a ``shrimp'' because he reportedly needs a stool for the debate
podium.
</P>
<P>
   With a deep voice and trademark cowboy boots, Fox, 57, has
lately not even been addressed Labastida by name, referring to him
instead as ``more of the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Labastida was last in a debate in November, when he faced
competitors in a PRI primary where he stood his ground against
strong opponents, who saw him as the party favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's strategy during the debate will be to attack the 71 years
of PRI rule and to emphasize Labastida stands for ``more of the
same,'' meaning PRI corruption and fraud in a country of 100
million that remains mired in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will present the precise and failed results of 70 years of
PRI rule,'' Fox said in a radio interview Monday. ``There will be
zero personal attacks and I will focus on my proposals for
Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   Labastida, also 57, said he would spotlight his vast political
experience and policy plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I will be playing a tennis game,'' Labastida,
who last headed the powerful Secretary of the Interior, said in a
morning radio show Monday. ``I will concentrate on . . . the
economy, society, how to generate more jobs, raise salaries.''
</P>
</TEXT>
