<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6010 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-IRAN-POLITICS-2TAKES(     04-24 1590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-POLITICS-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAN REFORMISTS SUFFER ANOTHER SETBACK AS 12 NEWSPAPERS ARE
BANNED 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran _ Two months after their triumph in parliamentary
elections, reformers are caught up in a war of nerves with Iran's
conservatives. The hard-liners have closed newspapers, jailed
writers and annulled some election results, making the most
concentrated crackdown on dissent since the 1979 revolution.
</P>
<P>
   After the Tehran courts delivered the latest blow late Sunday,
ordering eight dailies and four weeklies to stop publishing
immediately, reform leaders appealed for calm. ``We ask the Iranian
nation to keep calm and to be patient and careful about any action
that could lead to any kind of violence in society,'' pleaded one
of the few surviving reformist newspapers, Sobh-e-Emrouz, in its
Monday morning edition.
</P>
<P>
   All the banned newspapers have supported President Mohammad
Khatami, whose calls for reform of the judiciary and for open
political debate have won him vast public support but also fierce
enemies in the clerical establishment.
</P>
<P>
   The attack on the reform movement began shortly after elections
on Feb. 18, when pro-Khatami candidates won nearly 70 percent of
parliamentary seats. The reformers appeared poised to solidify
their victory, and control of the parliament, in a second round of
voting that was expected to take place last month.
</P>
<P>
   But the conservative Council of Guardians, an untouchable group
that has final say over all legislation and many other matters, has
methodically undercut the first-round results.
</P>
<P>
   The council voided the results in 10 provincial constituencies,
saying some victors had not campaigned fairly, and announced that
it will re-examine the ballots in Tehran. Most of the voided races
had been won by Khatami supporters.
</P>
<P>
   No date has yet been set for new elections, raising fears that
the hard-liners will not release their grip on power, by
disregarding the vote entirely. The new parliament is supposed to
take office on May 28.
</P>
<P>
   After the first round, many of the reformers who are now being
hounded were exuberant about their triumph and were predicting the
start of an era of more openness and social freedom.
</P>
<P>
   But the more cautious among them also warned that conservative
forces would not passively relinquish their power over the daily
lives of Iranians and over government institutions like the courts.
</P>
<P>
   They now say they are not surprised at the moves to harass the
reformers through their newspapers. Many conservatives blame their
poor showing at the polls on the feisty press that has blossomed
since Khatami's election in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this was predictable,'' said Abdollah Ramezanzadeh, a
close associate of Khatami and governor of Kurdistan Province.
``And we're expecting things to get a little worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Many reformers said they are afraid that Khatami's opponents
will try to set off a backlash that would provide an excuse for
greater repression.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   They point to events in Tehran last summer, when university
students who protested the closing of a liberal newspaper were
attacked by vigilantes, sparking riots that Khatami was able to
check only with difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   ``In today's circumstances, the reformers will be the ones to
suffer from any chaos in society,'' said Emadeddin Baghi, an editor
of one of the 12 banned newspapers, Fath. ``So it's important for
us to step back for the moment and stay calm.''
</P>
<P>
   Baghi, 39, will soon face his own test of nerves. He has been
summoned to appear in a Tehran court next Monday to answer charges
that he insulted Islamic values in articles he wrote. He said he
expects to be convicted and sent to prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take a few days,'' he said of his trial, ``but the
result is already clear in my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   If he is convicted, Baghi would join two other Fath editors,
Akbar Ganji and Mashallah Shamsolvaezin, in prison, as well as the
publisher of Neshat newspaper, Latif Safari. The three were jailed
in the past few weeks after being accused of defaming Islam or the
Iranian Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Even Khatami's brother, Mohammad Reza Khatami, has been summoned
to court on charges of violating press guidelines at the newspaper
he helps run.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The first blow struck at the reformers after the elections came
when Saeed Hajjarian, a strategist for the movement and close ally
of Khatami, was gunned down in a Tehran street. He survived, and
the assassination attempt was widely blamed on extremist groups
within the security forces.
</P>
<P>
   The accusations apparently angered Iran's supreme leader,
Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, who immediately denounced as un-Islamic
those who would besmirch the name of the security forces.
</P>
<P>
   His remarks set off an escalating series of assaults, verbal and
judicial, on the reformers. The parliament, now dominated by
hard-liners, recently approved a restrictive press law, as well as
legislation that removes institutions like the judiciary and
military from parliamentary monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, 140 members signed a petition that called a group of
reform activists traitors for attending a conference in Berlin.
Many of those people who attended the conference have been summoned
for questioning.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   More strident attacks have come from other quarters. Hard-line
clerics have publicly called for the killing of some reformers and
accused the reform press of destroying the values of the
revolution. The Islamic Revolutionary Guards Corps, a militia that
does not answer to the president, threatened to unleash what it
called ``Islamic violence'' against reformers.
</P>
<P>
   Khamenei, who controls the militias, courts and state media,
stepped in to cool matters, cautioning against ``illegal action''
to silence the reform movement. But he, too, has accused the
movement of fomenting unrest by trying to link the security
agencies to the killings of dissidents in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Although the attacks have clearly shaken the reformers,
Khatami's confidantes said they see some positive aspects to the
crackdown. And they said the public's hunger for change cannot be
ignored or discounted for long.
</P>
<P>
   As an example, they said the order to close the newspapers was
ostensibly based on Iranian law, although through a rarely used
1957 statute that permits the government to arrest people or
suspend an activity in order to prevent a possible crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before Mr. Khatami's election in 1997, they would just go to
an editor and say, close,'' said Ramezanzadeh, a confidant of the
president's. ``This time they closed the papers according to the
law, even though the law is questionable.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the Council of Guardians has even issued explanations _
vague, but still explanations _ for voiding some of the recent
parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a Third World country , yet our opponents have
dealt with us very calmly compared to what happens in the countries
around us,'' he added. ``The reform movement has actually forced
the opposition to play by the same rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the operative attitude is one of restraint. Journalists
and lawyers associated with the reformers said they would not react
to the ban on their newspapers in the same way they once did, by
simply reopening a few days later with the same staff but a
different name.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't do that,'' said Ali Hekmat, the only one of Fath's
editors to have so far escaped prosecution. ``This time our
opponents are more agitated and more angry. We only have one more
month before the new parliament should start work. Any kind of
action that would provoke our opponents would not be good.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   u ixxnt22 nt26 nt06 nt11 nt33 &QL; 
uixx &QL; 
 &UR; BC-IRAN-POLITICS-2NDTAKES-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; TEHRAN, Iran: be good.'' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A small group of university students, however, held a rally
Monday to protest the newspaper closures and said it will hold
another protest outside the offices of Fath on Tuesday, despite
entreaties from journalists not to provoke the police.
</P>
<P>
   At Tehran University, where last summer's demonstrations
dissolved into clashes with hard-line vigilantes, the mood was more
restrained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people have come to the same conclusion that it's better
to have peace and calm,'' said Rahim Bahrami, an art student.
``Everything is happening because of the new parliament, and the
extremists are trying to prevent as many reformers as possible from
taking office.''
</P>
<P>
   At a newsstand on Vanak Square, one of the busiest intersections
of Tehran, crowds milled in front of the slim choice of newspapers
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those papers all reported the reality of what's happening
here,'' said a woman in a black chador, or cloak, who gave her name
as Khavar. ``I don't believe much is really hidden in our country.
Even without the media, we can see. But I am worried. This is the
future of our country, and whatever happens, they are punishing us,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Another disappointed newspaper buyer, who also would give only
his first name, Mehrade, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knows what will happen,'' he said. ``There's a crisis
and it could be anything.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he did not expect Khatami to do much to overturn the
newspaper closings or the trials of his supporters. ``He can't
perform magic,'' Mehrade said. ``You have to be able to move your
hands to perform. He can move, but very slowly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
