<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-MARKET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT REPORT PUTS MARKET IN DOWN MODE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The technology bear market growled again Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The tech-dominated Nasdaq Composite index sank 161.50 points, or
4.4 percent, in reaction to twin blows to Microsoft Corp., the
world's largest software maker and a major component of the index.
</P>
<P>
   The company reported late Thursday _ after the markets had
closed for the Easter weekend _ that its sales last quarter rose
less than expected, as sales of personal computers have slowed.
</P>
<P>
   Several news organizations also reported Monday that the US
Justice Department has proposed that Microsoft spin off some of its
software operations to comply with court rulings that the company
violated federal antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   While New Economy stocks slumped, the Dow Jones industrial
average, a proxy for the Old Economy, rose, though by only 62.05
points, to a closing level of 10,906.10.
</P>
<P>
   The government's antitrust case against Microsoft has driven the
stock price of the world's biggest software company down 45 percent
from its high last December. Microsoft lost $12.3125 a share
Monday, falling to $66.625 in its its biggest one-day drop ever.
</P>
<P>
   But, a dramatic slide in Microsoft's stock in the midst of its
dispute with the US government may cause more damage to small
technology stocks in the Nasdaq index than it does to Microsoft
itself, which analysts said is big and resilient and would probably
rebound.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq index, which hit a high of 5048.62 on March 10, is
closing in on the 3000 mark, ``and that would still be a lofty
valuation,'' said Mark Lapman, chief executive for Independence
Investment Associates in Boston. ``We have a ways to go.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Lapman added, if Nasdaq does fall to the lows he predicts,
``Microsoft itself is probably close to a bottom here.''
</P>
<P>
   A resumption Monday of the slump in technology stocks, after a
respite last week, brought the index's closing level to 3482.48.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the day, Monday's losses looked far worse. A round
of buying late in the afternoon pared what had been an 8 percent
Nasdaq decline at its worst point in midafternoon, though not
before Microsoft's drop spread to other big computer companies,
including Cisco Systems Inc., Sun Microsystems Inc., and Dell
Computer Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Reports that sales of PCs slowed at the beginning of this year
added to the downward pressure on stocks of personal computer and
related hardware companies. Cisco, the top maker of
computer-networking equipment, fell $1.7985 to close at $63.4375.
Dell, the biggest US seller of personal computers, lost $2.1875 to
$47.75. And Sun, which makes computers that power Internet sites,
dipped by 12.5 cents to $87.625.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft is such a big provider to the PC industry, if
they're indicating there's some kind of slowing in demand for PCs,
it's got to'' hurt other software makers and semiconductor
companies, said Ned Riley of State Street Global Advisors, a
division of State Street Corp.
</P>
<P>
   A plan reportedly being proposed by the Justice Department would
require Microsoft to separate its Windows operating system and some
software applications from the rest of its business. Goldman, Sachs
&AMP; Co. cut its Microsoft rating to ``market outperform'' from
``recommended list,'' and a Lehman Brothers Inc. analyst reduced
his 12-month price target on the stock to 85 from 130.
</P>
<P>
   But the damage to small, startup tech companies may be far more
enduring, notably for Internet companies with disappointing news
that coincided with revelations about Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo, for example, fell $9.25 to $113.875 after Barron's
reported the top Web-navigation company could see advertising
revenue diminish if Internet startups lose their venture capital
streams. A small company that manages Internet Web sites, Exodus
Communications Inc., plunged $25.1985 to $82.50, in response to its
disclosure late Thursday that it had lost 32 cents a share in the
first quarter, 7 cents more than analysts expected. (The stock
market was closed on Friday for the Easter holiday.)
</P>
<P>
   While Nasdaq sagged, many Dow stocks picked up, despite a slump
in Microsoft, which is one of the biggest stocks in a 30-stock Dow
index.
</P>
<P>
   American Express, Merck, McDonald's Corp., DuPont Co., Dow
Chemical Co., General Dynamics, Home Depot, Sunoco Inc., and
Johnson &AMP; Johnson _ all these companies and others posted gains
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are value buyers coming back into the market and picking
up bargains,'' Lapman said. For these buyers, he said, the ``big
old ugly stocks'' have ``attractive valuations.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dow has declined 5 percent since January, and Nasdaq has
tumbled 14 percent this year in what is shaping up _ at least in
the early months _ as the worst time for stock market investors in
a decade.
</P>
</TEXT>
