<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MEXICO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT BRIDGE DEDICATION IN MEXICO, BUSH PROMISES MORE FREE TRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NUEVO LAREDO, Mexico _ Eager to remind voters that he is not a
foreign policy novice, Gov. George W. Bush went campaigning in
Mexico Monday. Foreign soil may be an unusual place to win votes,
but Bush seemed more in search of respect.
</P>
<P>
   It was a short trip, about 400 yards across the Rio Grande into
the Mexican scrub desert just west of this border city, and Bush
did not stay long, about two hours.
</P>
<P>
   But he managed to dedicate the eight-lane, $128 million World
Trade Bridge and share a stage, and compliments, with President
Ernesto Zedillo of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past there have been walls of divide between Mexico and
the United States,'' Bush said to a crowd of a few thousand people,
mostly Mexicans. ``We must, we must be committed to raise the
bridges of trade and friendship and freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, the international stage, even one within eyesight of
Texas, offered a chance to burnish his foreign policy credential
after some stumbles during the Republican primaries. For months,
Bush has boasted about his experience in dealing with Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, at a ceremony following a ribbon cutting on the bridge,
Zedillo credited Bush with understanding Mexican culture and
working as Texas governor to improve relations between Mexico and
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great friend of Mexico,'' Zedillo said.
</P>
<P>
   The growing closeness between officials in Mexico and Texas is
largely attributable to the North American Free Trade Agreement,
which has made Los Dos Laredos _ as the border cities of Laredo and
Nuevo Laredo call themselves _ a choke point for 1.3 million truck
crossings last year. The World Trade Bridge is the fourth
international bridge in the Laredo area. In promising to
aggressively push for free trade in this hemisphere, Bush, who has
assiduously courted Hispanic voters, said he would tear down trade
barriers from Alaska to ``the tip of Cape Horn.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all trade flowing across the Rio Grande is legal, and Bush
did not mention the huge volume of drugs and illegal immigrants
crossing daily.Nor did he mention the pollution from both sides of
the river that has prompted environmentalists to rank the Rio
Grande as one of the 10 most endangered rivers in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the theme was international friendship, and the Bush
campaign sent along a film crew to capture the governor and Zedillo
standing side-by-side.
</P>
<P>
   In arranging this international photo opportunity, Bush nearly
got mired in some tricky local politics. The bridge actually opened
on April 15, in a ceremony hosted by Mayor Betty Flores of Laredo,
a Democrat and friend of President Clinton. Citing a scheduling
conflict, Bush declined to attend that gathering, as did Zedillo
after originally indicating that he would. Flores said she was
``disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   How disappointed was she? The Bush campaign learned last week
when the mayor initially declined to allow the governor's motorcade
to cross the new bridge for the ceremony in Mexico. Flores said the
international permit for the bridge specifically allowed commercial
traffic only except for emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   She suggested the governor's entourage use one of the other
bridges or simply walk across. Or, she said, maybe he could just
drive a truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could ride in a big rig,'' she said in a telephone
interview on Friday. ``Think about it. The Teamsters will love
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But a weekend of telephone calls, including calls from Texas
officials to the State Department, broke the impasse, and on
Monday, the governor's car drove across the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Flores, who said she had not initially been invited to speak,
did so, and made certain to thank the politician that Bush hopes to
replace, President Clinton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-00 1927EDT &QL; 
