<SLUG> BC-GE-ONLINE-BANKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GE TO OFFER ONLINE BANKING ON ITS FINANCIAL WEB SITE 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   General Electric, which has been aggressively expanding the list
of products and services that it sells on the World Wide Web, plans
to announce Tuesday that it will offer online banking on its
consumer-oriented financial Web site.
</P>
<P>
   GE will team up with the online bank CompuBank to offer the
service on the GE Financial Network at www.gefn.com. It will be the
first financial service not home grown that GE will offer on the
Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize that partnering with people is the best way to get
speed to market with a full range of products and services,'' said
William C. Goings, senior vice president for e-business at GE
Financial Assurance, the company's consumer financial services arm.
</P>
<P>
   GE, based in Fairfield, Conn., began the banking service without
fanfare earlier this month, and consumers who stumbled across it on
the Web site have been able to open accounts, although Goings would
not say how many had done so.
</P>
<P>
   Goings said GE would announce another partnership soon, with
Netstock.com, to let consumers buy stock online in small lots. That
site, which will be called Netstockdirect, is not yet operational,
but GE has flagged its imminent arrival on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The new banking service will allow consumers to set up checking,
savings and money market accounts on the Web and to pay their bills
through electronic transfers. But they will also be able to write
regular checks against those accounts and gain access to them
through automated teller machines. And they will be able to earn
frequent flier miles for opening new accounts and handling banking
transactions online.
</P>
<P>
   GE Financial Network already offers insurance, mutual funds,
credit cards, home mortgages and other financial services.
CompuBank, which has been operating for about 18 months, offers
banking services to both consumers and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   CompuBank will retain any fees involved in the banking
transactions and will control the assets in the consumer accounts.
GE Financial Assurance has also made a small equity investment in
CompuBank. But Frank S. Goldberg, CompuBank's chairman, sounded
most excited about what the partnership could do for his fledgling
company's reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being chosen as GE's partner is like getting the Good
Housekeeping Seal of Approval,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-00 1931EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
