<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ISTANBUL-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISTANBUL INAUGURATES A NEW PORTAL TO THE GATEWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, April 30)  
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ A glittering new international terminal has
opened at Ataturk International Airport, finally giving visitors a
modern gateway to this many-splendored city. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Istanbul's old international terminal was intimate, and those
who used it regularly appreciated the speed with which they could
sometimes negotiate their way past the various control points. For
most passengers, however, it was a highly unsuitable point of entry
to Turkey. It was dark, crowded and often plagued by long lines. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The new terminal, built in 22 months at a cost of $306 million,
could not be more different. It is four times the size of the old
one, bright and airy with tall ceilings and broad corridors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a few cramped booths selling duty-free items, there
are dozens of shops, ranging from a toy store to a gallery that
specializes in reproductions of old maps and prints. Among the many
places to eat is one with stir-fried Chinese dishes to order. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Passengers used to have to take a shuttle bus between the
terminal and the parking area, but no longer. A covered garage
adjoining the terminal has space for more than 7,000 cars. The
garage is said to be the biggest of its kind in Europe, and the
terminal is the third biggest building in Turkey.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although President Suleyman Demirel officially opened the
terminal in January, it is not complete. Workers are still drilling
and patching in several places. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With an annual capacity of 14 million passengers, the terminal
is to be expanded to 20 million within a few years. It has been
built with modern techniques designed to make it resistant to
earthquakes.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of the 160 check-in desks, 64 belong to Turkish Airlines, which
has become a comfortable and generally efficient carrier,
especially on international routes. Baggage conveyers can handle
10,000 pieces of luggage an hour. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Until the new terminal opened, most arriving planes were forced
to park on the tarmac, and passengers were bused to passport
control or transit lounges. Now fewer people are experiencing that
inconvenience. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With 64 passport control booths and 34 X-ray machines, the
terminal should be able to offer no-wait service to most
passengers. But these posts are sometimes unmanned, so lines
persist. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are other quirks, some of which may be resolved as
administrators recognize them. Signs in the main concourse are
inadequate, and some check-in counters are difficult to find. At
the information desk, multilingual receptionists are cheerful and
eager to help, but even they do not yet know where to direct some
passengers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The main departure concourse is more than half a mile long and
is served by a single moving sidewalk. Since the sidewalk moves in
only one direction, passengers who want to go the ``wrong'' way
must walk. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the airport managers declined to answer
questions about this apparent design flaw. It may be difficult to
correct, but other start-up problems should be easier to resolve.
Shops in the departure area offer a rich selection of modern and
historic postcards, for example, but there is no place to buy
stamps. Public telephones along the departure concourse accept only
prepaid cards, but no cards are for sale. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Several passengers have also complained about surly treatment
from security agents who run the X-ray machines, which can put an
unpleasant end to a vacation.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By any standard, however, Istanbul has taken a giant step toward
accommodating international air passengers. The old terminal was
something of an embarrassment, certainly inadequate to serve as the
main gateway to a country that is now among the world's top 20
tourist destinations. The new one is an apt symbol of Turkey's
campaign to reach European levels of efficiency. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
