<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-DAVIDIANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES QUESTION FIREARMS SENTENCES IN DAVIDIAN CASE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Optional ending included) 
 
By STEVE LASH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Several skeptical Supreme Court justices grilled a
federal prosecutor Monday on whether a Waco judge improperly
extended the prison sentences of four men convicted of killing four
lawmen during a 1993 raid on the Branch Davidian compound in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The justices appeared more sympathetic toward a defense lawyer
who argued that U.S. District Judge Walter Smith of Waco was wrong
to apply a firearms law to beef up the killers' prison terms.
</P>
<P>
   Smith tacked 30 years onto the Davidians' 10-year sentences
after concluding that the four men had used automatic weapons to
slay four Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms agents at the
sect's compound near Waco.
</P>
<P>
   The botched raid led to a 51-day standoff that ended with a fire
in which Branch Davidian leader David Koresh and about 80 followers
were killed.
</P>
<P>
   The Davidians' lawyer, Stephen Halbrook of Fairfax, Va., argued
that the enhanced sentences were inappropriate because the kind of
weapons used by the defendants had not been determined by the jury.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law allows a judge to add up to 30 years to a killer's
sentence if an automatic weapon or bomb is used in a slaying.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Attorney General James Robinson argued that Congress
wanted judges to have the authority to determine what type of
weapon was used when deciding punishment.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1994, Renos Avraam, Brad Branch, Jaime Castillo and
Kevin Whitecliff were convicted of voluntary manslaughter and
firearms possession in the shooting deaths of BATF agents Conway
LeBleu, Todd McKeehan, Robert Williams and Steven Willis.
</P>
<P>
   A fifth defendant, Graeme Craddock, was convicted of possessing
a destructive device and sentenced to 10 years. Smith added 10
years to Craddock's sentence after concluding that he had possessed
an automatic weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors had asked the jury to consider charges of murder and
conspiracy to commit murder against the Davidians. The panel was
not asked to decide what kind of weapons were used, and some jurors
later said they were troubled when Smith tacked on the firearms
sentences.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were absolutely shocked at the severity of the judge's
augmentation of what we thought was going to be a slap on the wrist
of the defendants,'' said jury forewoman Sarah Bain, a San Antonio
resident who attended Monday's Supreme Court arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justice Antonin Scalia,
who generally side with prosecutors, pressed Robinson, the
government lawyer, on the increased prison terms and his argument
that juries do not have to be consulted on the question of weapons
used in a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist said allowing a judge to decide what kind of weapons
were used after the jury had determined guilt was akin to the tail
wagging the dog.
</P>
<P>
   Scalia, picking up the canine metaphor, said a judge would have
to have ``a long tail'' to resolve a factual dispute that is best
left to a jury and could add 30 years to a sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``That (result) doesn't seem strange to you?'' Scalia asked
Robinson, who heads the Justice Department's criminal division.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Robinson said that federal judges have historically
had the authority to increase sentences based on their own
conclusion as to the ``dangerousness'' of the weapon used.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Justice Stephen G. Breyer was unconvinced. He said the type of
firearm used appears to be an element of the crime and must be
answered by the jury, leaving it to the judge to then impose
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty hard to see ... why this (issue of gun type)
suddenly becomes a sentencing factor'' only for the judge to
determine, Breyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the justices did not appear to challenge Halbrook's
claim that juries _ not judges _ must determine what type of gun
was used, they questioned why he was not arguing that Smith's
decision was unconstitutional because it amounts to an unfair
trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it a strange argument you're making,'' Scalia said.
</P>
<P>
   If the high court rules in the killers' favor, their prison
terms would be reduced to 15 years, based on the initial 10-year
sentence and five-year enhancement judges are permitted to impose
if any type of firearm was used. Craddock's sentenced would be
reduced to 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   The justices are expected to render a decision by early July.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, an independent inquiry is underway into what role, if
any, the Federal Bureau of Investigation played in starting the
fire that engulfed the warren of buildings at the Davidian compound
on April 19, 1993. The fire broke out as the FBI flooded the
compound with tear gas in an effort to end the siege.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Davidians who survived the fire and the relatives
of those who were killed have sued the federal government, alleging
that officials should be held liable for the deaths.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
