<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-MIAMI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBAN EXILES PROMISE WORK STOPPAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ This seaside city of 2.2 million people was full of life
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, if the Cuban-American exile community has its way,
Miami will look all but dead, stricken by a massive, one-day work
stoppage to protest the US government's armed seizure of 6-year-old
Elian Gonzalez from the home of his relatives in Little Havana.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're calling it Dead Tuesday,'' said Ramon Saul Sanchez, the
leader of a Cuban-American exile group, the Democracy Movement.
</P>
<P>
   The title could prove apt, in a city with 800,000 Cuban
Americans who for decades have demonstrated extraordinary unity in
their contempt for any US action they view as favorable to Cuban
President Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   Half the city's work force is Cuban-American. A massive strike,
even for a day, could cause multimillion-dollar havoc in the
tourist-oriented economy here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to send a strong message that we want an investigation
of the outrageous act of violence committed by federal
authorities,'' said Sanchez, his head still wrapped in bandages
from injuries he received while trying to block Immigration and
Naturalization agents who stormed the Little Havana home.
</P>
<P>
   City and county officials, whose political fortunes largely
hinge on support from the Cuban-American community, did not oppose
the proposed stoppage other than to appeal for police, fire and
medical workers to report for work.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you consider the other options, it's probably the best of
all ideas,'' said Miami-Dade Mayor Alex Penelas of the planned
stoppage. ``A lot of people in our community feel indignant and
betrayed by what happened, and they want to express themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Scores of businesses, including the 25-store Sedona supermarket
chain, announced Monday they would not open Tuesdaday. Solidarity
with the shutdown was overwhelming in Little Havana.
</P>
<P>
   ``The community is in peril,'' said Maria Versace, who manages a
car dealership in the community. ``We have to show our support.''
</P>
<P>
   Other businesses may have no choice, depending both on the
willingness of workers to show up and their ability to do so if
protesters block streets. A number of major thoroughfares have been
blocked during the Elian saga, including access roads to Miami
International Airport, one of the nation's busiest.
</P>
<P>
   Police were on full alert and appealed for calm. They arrested
more than 350 protesters in the first 24 hours after Elian was
seized.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've already been enough of an international incident,'' said
Miami Police Lieutenant William Schwartz. ``Let's not make it
worse.''
</P>
<P>
   In a related protest, more than 60 members of Mothers Against
Repression marched silently outside the federal courthouse in Miami
Monday. Dressed in black, they showed copies of the picture of a
federal marshal pointing a submachine gun toward Elian during the
seizure.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, two prominent anti-Castro radio hosts in Miami were
organizing a caravan to drive to Washington this week to protest
Elian's removal from his Miami relatives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
