<SLUG> BC-UN-ALBRIGHT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US WILL OK NUCLEAR TEST BAN PACT, ALBRIGHT TELLS UN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE LAURIA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ America's European allies, praising Russia for
its recent nuclear disarmament moves, Monday criticized the United
States for failing to ratify the nuclear test ban treaty and for
continuing to develop an anti-missile defence system that UN
Secretary General Kofi Annan warned could lead to a new arms race.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright, speaking on the
opening day of the UN's month-long Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty
review conference, rejected criticism of the missile defence system
and predicted that the United States would ratify the test ban
treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal's UN Ambassador Antonio Monteiro, speaking for the
European Union, welcomed Russia's ratification last Friday of the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty and called on the United States to do
likewise ``so as to stimulate others to follow the same path.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We deeply regret, in this connection, the upset to the
ratification process in the US,'' Monteiro said. ``The EU strongly
supports the early entry into force of the CTBT through
ratification without delay and without conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration suffered an embarassing defeat last
year when the Senate voted down ratification of the test ban.
</P>
<P>
   Albright, while predicting that the United States would
eventually ratify the treaty, told reporters later she did not
expect another Senate vote before a new Congress and a new
administration were elected in November.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said Clinton has appointed General John Shalikashvili,
former chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to advise the
administration on ``how best to respond to senators' concerns about
the CTBT so we can build support for its eventual ratification.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Meanwhile,'' Albright said, ``we have made it clear that the
United States will not resume testing _ and are urging other
nations to do the same and to sign and ratify the treaty.''
</P>
<P>
   The Europeans also voiced opposition to US proposals to modify
the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty, a move that would allow the
Pentagon to deploy the anti-missile defense system on US soil.
</P>
<P>
   ``We reaffirm the importance of the ABM treaty as one of the
pillars of strategic stability,'' Monteiro said. ``The EU wishes to
see that treaty preserved.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia has refused to agree to a modification of the ABM treaty
to allow the anti-missile system, but specialists say Moscow may be
amenable to a deal if the United States agrees to a lower threshold
of nuclear weapons stocks in planned Start III talks.
</P>
<P>
   Annan warned, however, that the ``growing pressure to deploy
national missile defenses is jeopardizing the ABM Treaty and could
well lead to a new arms race.''
</P>
<P>
   But Albright strongly defended the administration's intentions.
``If the Clinton administration were bent on sabotaging the ABM
Treaty and strategic arms control, we have surely gone about it in
a strange way,'' she said. ``In the open, with care, and in
consultation not only with Congress, but after extensive
discussions with our allies and other countries, Russia and China
emphatically included.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The world has changed dramatically in the almost three decades
since the ABM Treaty was signed,'' Albright said. ``That treaty has
been amended before, and there is no good reason it cannot be
amended again to reflect new threats from third countries outside
the strategic deterrence regime.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright told reporters the missile defense system is intended
for future threats from North Korea and Iran. ``We are talking
about a system capable of defending against at most a few tens of
incoming missiles. It is not intended to degrade Russia's
deterrent. Nor will it have that result,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There doesn't need to be a confrontation'' on this issue with
Russia, she said, which simply doesn't ``agree on the nature of the
threat'' posed to American soil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-00 1944EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
