<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ANCIENT-SKULL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CONTROVERSY OVER OCCUPANT OF ANCIENT TOMB 
</HEADLINE>
   (Science Times)  
 By KENNETH CHANG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who is buried in King Philip's tomb?
</P>
<P>
   That's not a trick question, at least not to archaeologists
studying a royal burial site in northern Greece.
</P>
<P>
   Almost since the tomb near the town of Vergina was opened 23
years ago, scholars have argued about whose bones lay within: was
he King Philip II of Macedonia _ the father of Alexander the Great
_ or King Philip III Arrhidaeus, Alexander's half-brother, who
assumed the throne after Alexander's death? The tomb's occupant
could not be Alexander, who was buried in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   According to a study by a Greek historian, the bones themselves
provide the answer: Arrhidaeus, the half-brother. Dr. Antonis
Bartsiokas, director of the Anaximandrian Institute of Human
Evolution in Voula, Greece, and an assistant professor of history
and ethnology at the Democritus University of Thrace, reported his
findings in the current issue of the journal Science.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a confirmation using the bones as evidence,'' Dr. Eugene
Borza, professor emeritus of ancient history at Pennsylvania State
University, said of the Science paper.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the rulers of Macedonia, an ancient kingdom in northern
Greece, died young and violently. Philip II was stabbed to death in
336 B.C. during a celebration just before he was to set off to
conquer Persia. Philip III Arrhidaeus was also killed, in 317 B.C.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1984 examination of the bones in King Philip's tomb, a team
of British researchers had contended that a bump above the skull's
right eye socket was the healed-over wound from an arrow that
sliced into King Philip II's head in 354 B.C. Philip II survived
and ruled for another 18 years before he was assassinated.
</P>
<P>
   Examining life-size photographs of the bones, Bartsiokas has
concluded that the alleged wound is merely the ``supraorbital
notch,'' a normal feature of the eye socket where a bundle of
nerves and blood vessels pass through. Most people can feel the
notch beneath their eyebrows.
</P>
<P>
   A crack below the eye socket, which the British researchers had
interpreted as a healed bone scar, probably formed during
cremation, according to Bartsiokas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw there was no evidence of an eye injury,'' Bartsiokas
said.
</P>
<P>
   The surprisingly good condition of the bones _ almost the whole
skeleton remained after the cremation _ offers further clues to
their identity, Bartsiokas said. Usually, the burning heat of
cremation shrinks the collagen protein at the center of bones,
causing them to warp and fracture.
</P>
<P>
   According to historical records, however, six months passed
between Arrhidaeus' death and his cremation. During that six-month
gap, Bartsiokas argues, the collagen began to break down,
minimizing the amount of warping and fracturing that would occur
during cremation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the only skeleton that we know of a Macedonian king who
was not cremated immediately after his death,'' Bartsiokas said.
``The historical, the anthropological and the archaeological
evidence in this case all coincide.''
</P>
<P>
   Other researchers have come to the same conclusion from other
evidence, arguing that some of the pottery found in the tomb comes
from a generation after Philip II.
</P>
<P>
   If true, some of the artifacts within the tomb, including a
helmet and a ceremonial shield, could be those of Alexander the
Great, who conquered most of the Mediterranean region during his
13-year reign.
</P>
<P>
   The British researchers, however, remain certain the bones are
those of Alexander's father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Bartsiokas has been selective in the use of
evidence,'' said Dr. Jonathan H. Musgrave, senior lecturer in
anatomy at the University of Bristol in England and one of the
authors of the 1984 paper identifying the remains as Philip II.
</P>
<P>
   Musgrave conceded that evidence for the supposed eye wound was
``fairly weak,'' but said that was only part of the Philip II
argument.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the face remains twisted, as if it had sustained a
major wound. ``I personally believe you can see major signs of
asymmetry away from the area that he is talking about,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Musgrave also cited signs of hasty construction of the tomb's
main chamber, which would be expected in the turmoil after Philip
II's assassination. The six-month gap between death and burial of
Philip III Arrhidaeus would have provided plenty of time for the
building of the tomb, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
