A6066 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-MEXICO-DEBATE-BOS &LR;      04-24 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-DEBATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBATE HIGHLIGHTS RUNUP TO MEXICAN PRESIDENTIAL VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Vicente Fox calls Francisco Labastida ``Mr.
More-of-the-Same.'' Labastida refers to Fox as a vulgar rancher.
</P>
<P>
   For months, Mexico's two leading presidential candidates have
been tossing barbs at each other through newspaper stories, radio
interviews, and television soundbites. Tuesday night they'll
confront each other in person when they share the stage in a
nationally broadcast debate.
</P>
<P>
   With only ten weeks left in what has become the tightest
presidential race in decades, the debate could be key in deciding
who carries the momentum into the campaign's homestretch.
</P>
<P>
   All six of Mexico's presidential hopefuls will take part in the
90-minute debate, the first among this year's candidates and only
the second in Mexican history, but voters and analysts will likely
be looking closest at the two front-runners, who are locked in a
virtual tie in most major opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, 57, a former Coca-Cola executive and governor of Guanajuato
state, has become the opposition's best hope of knocking out the
ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party after 71 years in power.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate of a coalition between the conservative National
Action Party and the environmentalist Ecology Party, the boot-shod
Fox has appealed to many residents with a tart-tongued style that
evokes shades of Jessie Ventura, Ross Perot and George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   He has pegged Labastida, the ruling party candidate, as a
continuation of the government's technocratic policies that have
simultaneously brought economic growth and more poverty. But Fox's
routine seems to distract voters as much as it attracts them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admire his ability to stand up and speak frankly about the
way things are in Mexico,'' said Antonio Mendez Gallardo, a
33-year-old Mexico City accountant who considers himself an
undecided voter. ``But he has to balance that image with a more
refined approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Labastida is a longtime PRI insider who has served as governor
of Sinaloa state and, more recently, as President Ernesto Zedillo's
agriculture secretary and interior minister. In contrast to Fox,
Labastida has been more bland, except for the times he has tried to
take on Fox's jibes.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the 57-year-old economist has offered broad proposals
to improve Mexico's stagnant education system, to fight crime, and
to reform its inefficient farming sector.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing far behind Fox and Labastida in distant third is former
Mexico City Mayor Cuauhtemoc Cardenas. The son of a former
president from the 1930s whom many consider to be a Mexican hero
for nationalizing the country's oil industry, Cardenas, who is
making his third presidential bid representing a left-leaning
coalition, has been shadowed in recent weeks by rumors that he
might withdraw from the race to help Fox's opposition candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely not,'' Cardenas recently told a group of American
journalists. ``We have opposite proposals and it would be illogical
for us to make an alliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Most observers don't know what to expect from the debate. The
rules, which were negotiated by each campaign, are so rigid that
direct exchange between candidates is forbidden.
</P>
<P>
   But no one is dismissing the possibility of a repeat of 1994,
when, in Mexico's only other presidential debate, Diego Fernandez
de Cevallos, the PAN candidate, broadsided Zedillo and Cardenas
with an array of direct confrontations and impassioned speeches.
Fernandez's performance momentarily boosted his campaign into first
place, only to lose the election to Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year's debate format is the result of what happened in
1994,'' said Sergio Aguayo Quesada, a political professor at the
Colegio de Mexico. ``(Fernandez) took advantage of a flexible
format. It might happen this year, but it'll be harder to pull
off.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as the debate goes, Aguayo and others agree that Fox has
the most to win and that Labastida probably has the most to lose.
Analysts say the winner could gain as much as 3 to 4 points among
undecided voters. Another debate _ among only the top three
contenders _ will be held before the July 2 elections.
</P>
<P>
   This year's campaign has been perhaps the most democratic in
terms of press coverage. A survey released last month by the
independent Federal Elections Institute found that opposition
candidates received the greatest amount of coverage from the
country's two main television networks. The study also found,
however, that opposition parties also received a greater proportion
of negative coverage compared to the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   Although Mexicans everywhere, it seems, argue that it's time for
a change in governing party, they still seem to be worried about
the economic and political uncertainty it could create.
</P>
<P>
   A national poll published Monday by the Mexico City daily
Reforma showed that 50 percent of those interviewed think that a
PRI loss could cause economic instability, while 58 percent think
it could cause political upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether he thought Mexican voters were ready to end
the PRI's monopoly on the presidency, 24-year-old Miguel Antonio
Rivas shook his head and waved his hand dismissively.
</P>
<P>
   ``People always say they want something different,'' said Rivas,
a part-time college student and musician. ``But deep down I think
they're scared of something new. This is a country of traditions,
not of experiments.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
