<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES ENTER DEBATE ON BLANKET PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Wash., Alaska, La.)   By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court wrestled Monday with a civics
question of constitutional dimension and major practical
implications: Do the political parties or the electorate as a whole
control the nominating process?
</P>
<P>
   At issue was California's so-called blanket primary, in which
voters of all party affiliations receive the same ballot on which
they can make any set of choices, without regard to party. A voter
can select a favorite Democratic candidate for the gubernatorial
nomination, for example, while choosing among Republicans for a
state assembly nomination and among Libertarian Party options for a
local race.
</P>
<P>
   The system was adopted as a voter initiative, Proposition 198,
in 1996 over the official opposition of the political parties in
California but with support at the polls from a majority of
Democratic, Republican, and independent voters.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic, Republican, Libertarian, and Peace and Freedom
parties tried unsuccessfully in the lower federal courts to block
Proposition 198, which the parties' lawyer described to the
justices on Monday as ``a wholesale assault on a political party's
First Amendment right to choose the standard-bearer who best
represents the party's ideology.''
</P>
<P>
   The constitutional question is whether the parties have a right
under the First Amendment protection for freedom of association to
exclude nonmembers from their nominating process.
</P>
<P>
   One goal of the initiative's supporters was to produce more
centrist candidates by diluting the ability of party regulars to
control the nomination. George Waters, the parties' lawyer, argued
that the state could not constitutionally pursue that goal by
``commandeering the political parties as a vehicle to blend the
political ideologies together.''
</P>
<P>
   But a lawyer for California, defending the blanket primary,
described Proposition 198 as a great success, increasing voter
turnout by giving all voters, regardless of party registration, an
incentive to participate in the nominating process.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just civics,'' Thomas F. Gede, a special assistant state
attorney general, told the justices. ``The more people you have
voting, the more representative the candidates will be.'' He said
the parties should welcome, rather than fight, the opportunity for
enhanced success by appealing to a broader range of voters.
</P>
<P>
   The justices challenged many of Gede's assertions and, by their
questions, appeared sympathetic to the parties' position. But as
Gede stressed at the end of his argument, a decision striking the
blanket primary on the ground that it interfered with the parties'
autonomy would inevitably cast constitutional doubt on the much
more common open primary that is used in about half the states.
</P>
<P>
   Under that system, voters can request a party's primary ballot,
even if they are not enrolled in that party; their choices are then
limited to the contestants for that party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   To accept the principle of ``total party autonomy'' would be to
jeopardize that system, Gede said, as well as a system in some
states that permits same-day registration as entry for voting in a
primary.
</P>
<P>
   Under the court's precedents, states can insist that parties use
primaries to nominate candidates. But states do not necessarily
have the last word. In a 1986 decision, Tashjian vs. Republican
Party of Connecticut, the court ruled that Connecticut could not
enforce its closed primary law against the state's Republican
Party, which wanted to open its primary to independents as a way of
broadening its base.
</P>
<P>
   There was considerable discussion over how to apply the
Connecticut decision for the case Monday, California Democratic
Party vs. Jones, No. 99-401. Waters, the parties' lawyer, said the
1986 decision stood for the principle of ``party sovereignty,''
under which ``parties have the right to structure their own
rules.'' While the Connecticut Republicans chose openness, he said,
the California parties had an equally valid right to oppose the
blanket primary.
</P>
<P>
   Gede, arguing for California, said the Connecticut decision was
not directly relevant; rather than the Legislature imposing a rule
on the parties, he said, Proposition 198 was a direct reflection of
the will of California's voters. ``The voters acted in their own
First Amendment interest,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, the only member of the court to
have held elective office _ she was majority leader of the Arizona
state Senate before becoming a judge _ was openly skeptical of the
state's arguments. When Gede began describing broad participation
in primary elections as the ``first cut'' in the electoral process,
she interrupted.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is precisely the point at which the associational
interest is at its zenith,'' O'Connor said. She demanded of Gede
whether he recognized that the parties had ``any associational
right.'' When he said he did, O'Connor persisted: ``What would
remain after your so-called balancing test of a party's right at
all?''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Antonin Scalia was hostile to the state's position,
characterizing it as ``tyranny of the majority'' and ``democracy
carried to extremes.'' A small, ideology-based party might have no
interest in the mainstream, he said, and yet risked having its
nomination process taken over by voters who did not share its
views.
</P>
<P>
   Waters, the parties' lawyer, said the state's brief experience
under Proposition 198 demonstrated the risk to small parties. In
three primary races in 1998, he said, candidates running as
Libertarians attracted more than twice as many votes as there were
registered Libertarians in the districts.
</P>
<P>
   The weakest part of Waters' argument was his effort to reassure
the justices that they could strike down the blanket primary
without casting a constitutional cloud over the more common open
primaries. Only Washington and Alaska share California's blanket
primary, with Louisiana using some features of it, while 23 states
have open primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Waters said that in an open primary, voters engage in an ``act
of affiliation,'' however brief, by requesting a particular party's
ballot. But Justice David H. Souter objected that such an
affiliation was a ``pretty empty formality,'' rather than a
constitutional distinction.
</P>
</TEXT>
