<SLUG> BC-WINE-LABELS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL HEARINGS TO CONSIDER HEALTH LABELS ON WINE 
</HEADLINE>
   By TIM TESCONI   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ Federal hearings, which start Tuesday in
Washington, are rekindling the debate over the health benefits of
wine while addressing whether health labels of any kind should be
allowed on bottles of chardonnay and cabernet sauvignon.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents want to ban the health labels, claiming they are
misleading and have the potential to cause alcohol abuse. The wine
industry says it wants to preserve the labels because they direct
consumers to valuable information that could help them live longer,
healthier lives.
</P>
<P>
   George Hacker of the Center for Science in the Public Interest
said the health labels, approved in 1999 after three years of study
by a federal agency, are subtle promotional messages that may lead
consumers to believe that the government endorses drinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Health claims for alcoholic beverages on labels or in
advertising should simply not be allowed, no matter how well
supported those claims may be,'' said Hacker, director of alcohol
policies at the Washington, D.C.-based consumer information group.
</P>
<P>
   He concedes that there may be some benefits from moderate
alcohol consumption for some people but said that does not mean
that people should be advised to drink for their health.
</P>
<P>
   Hacker is among more than 20 speakers on both sides of the issue
who will testify at hearings being held by the Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearms to determine if the ``negative consequences of
alcohol consumption or abuse'' disqualify wine, beer and spirits
from carrying any health-related statements.
</P>
<P>
   The hearings are Tuesday and Wednesday in Washington and May 23
and 24 in San Francisco. Hearings scheduled for Atlanta, Chicago
and Dallas were canceled because so few signed up to testify.
</P>
<P>
   Of the more than 800 wineries in California, only 17 use the
labels. Most wineries don't bother with the labels for several
reasons, including the cost, lack of space on the bottle and the
bureaucratic hassle of getting the labels approved by the Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms.
</P>
<P>
   The wine industry insists that the labels under review make no
specific health claims. Instead, industry leaders say, the labels
are educational messages directing consumers to seek sound
scientific knowledge on alcohol consumption, including the
government's own dietary guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat of Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-00 2001EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000424.0363 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6078 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-AIRLINE-DELAYS-BOS &LR;      04-24 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-DELAYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RADAR TROUBLES IN BOSTON RIPPLE THROUGH AIRLINE SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As FAA technicians worked to install, test and operate a
replacement radar antenna for Logan International Airport, airline
operations centers struggled to keep problems in Boston from
swamping the schedule throughout the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The schedule began to return to normal with the replacement
antenna of the airport surveillance radar operating by late Monday.
But for two-and-a-half days passengers endured monumental delays
and saw flights to and from Boston canceled by the dozen to keep
the ripple effect of delayed in Boston from becoming delayed
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Without the cancellations _ more than 200 flights were lost on
each of Saturday and Sunday and at least 174 were wiped off the
schedule _ delays would have stretched to as much as 11 hours,
airline officials said.
</P>
<P>
   And in an effort to keep the skies over Boston from resembling
an expressway at rush hour, the FAA's Air Traffic Control System
Command Center, located in a Virginia suburb of Washington D.C.,
acted as the national traffic cop throughout the radar outage.
</P>
<P>
   By instituting what they call a ``Traffic Management Program''
and airline passengers call a major pain _ because of the delays
they cause around the country as Boston-bound planes sit on tarmacs
_ the FAA kept planes coming to Boston at a number that would not
overload the system. But the average ground hold on flights into
Boston was 110 minutes and the maximum ground hold was 279 minutes,
the FAA said.
</P>
<P>
   Airline schedules are incredibly complicated, and one plane
often has several different cities and crews in one day. A flight
from Chicago to Boston may then depart to Miami or Europe, rather
than head back to Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Because of that complexity, the collapse of the approach radar
early Saturday morning ``had far-reaching effects thoughout the
National Airspace System,'' said John White, deputy manager of the
FAA's command center.
</P>
<P>
   Personnel in airline operations centers worked to maintain
schedules by rapidly adjusting crew and aicraft destinations.
</P>
<P>
   At United Air Lines, one person was assigned to rewriting
schedules so aircraft and crews stayed together, which limited some
disruptions, said Mark Hussey, station manager in Boston for
United.
</P>
<P>
   And airlines relied heavily on airports in Providence, R.I. and
Manchester, N.H. to keep the system functioning.
</P>
<P>
   United, for example, chartered four buses that ran between Logan
and Manchester when it diverted about one third of its short haul
narrow body flights to Chicago and Washington's Dulles
International Airport. ``Because of the heavy loads into Manchester
we sent employees _ mechancis, ground support, customer service _
up there to meet our greater flight schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Delta Air Lines chartered buses to take passengers to
Providence. Reservations agents also called passengers to alert
them of the change in rescheduling its Boston-Orlando schedule with
six flights out of Providence, said Rick Danner, Delta's regional
director for airport customer service.
</P>
<P>
   On other routes, Delta used larger aircraft. For example, on the
Boston-Atlanta route, Delta canceled a flight, but used an L-1011
rather than a Boeing 767 on another flight to pick up an additional
80 seats. And Boeing 737s were replaced with Boeing 767s.
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines canceled eight of its 14 regularly scheduled
flights to Boston from Chicago's O'Hare Airport and several more
from its hub in Dallas. A spokeswoman said that enabled the airline
to move aircraft to other cities to contain damage to the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   US Airways canceled a dozen flights and moved some flights to
Manchester, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   White said the FAA's traffic management program, which is
computerized, does not differentiate between aircraft types, only
the number of operations.
</P>
<P>
   And the FAA gives airlines the opporunity to decide which
aircraft should use the departure times it is given in the traffic
management program. For example, if an airline is given a departure
time of 2 p.m. under the program, it could cancel a 12 p.m. flight
and combine the canceled flight with a later one and still use the
2 p.m. slot.
</P>
<P>
   In good weather, Boston can handle about 60 incoming flights an
hour. The command center pulled that back to 18 an hour, because
the back-up radar (a combination of coverage from three distant
radars) required approaching planes to be spaced farther apart.
</P>
<P>
   And when the radar was repaired, ground holds on flights to
Boston from all domestic cities expect Denver and the West Coast
were still in place because a northwest wind restricted the number
of runways aviailable. The FAA estimated the average ground hold
was 59 minutes and the maximum ground hold was 270 minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
