<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-RADAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS PUZZLED BY FAILURE OF CRITICAL LOGAN RADAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD HIGGINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A permanent new radar antenna was up and running Monday
at Logan International Airport, but officials remained confounded
why the one it replaced toppled suddenly on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The failure plunged the nation's ninth-busiest airport into
three days of delays and scrubbed flights that held up air traffic
across the nation. More than 140 flights were cancelled Monday
alone before the new radar unit was operating.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration, which operates Logan's
radar facility on Governors Island, said it is not certain that
Saturday's moderate winds caused the freak problem and was
investigating other possibilities, including a technical
malfunction and metal fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   The 36-foot-wide, 17-foot-high orange antenna, which swivels to
plot the location of aircraft, fell over in winds of 46 mph, less
than half of the 85-knot or 98 mph winds it waS proven to withstand
in tests, according to FAA officials.
</P>
<P>
   It was also lasted less than half of its projected 20-year
lifespan.
</P>
<P>
   Arlene Salac, chief spokesperson for the FAA's New England
regional office, said that of 143 identical radars around the
nation _ all of which are 10 years old or younger _ Logan's was the
only one to fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very good, reliable piece of equipment, and we've never
had this problem before, so we have no reason to believe that it's
a systemic problem,'' she said. ``We're treating it as an
anomaly.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at an FAA logistics center in Oklahoma began their
investigation into why the radar antenna, which is called an ASR-9,
toppled.
</P>
<P>
   ASR-9 stands for the ninth version of Airport Surveillance
Radar. It employs moving-target-detector technology developed at
the MIT Lincoln Laboratory and was developed by the Westinghouse
Electric Corporation.
</P>
<P>
   An identical antenna, flown to Boston from the FAA facility in
Oklahoma on Sunday, was installed, tested and put into operation,
immediately boosting the number of flights per hour from 26 to 38
and later to about 44 flights per hour, according to a Massport
official.
</P>
<P>
   The disabled, disc-shaped antenna, which dangled down the side
of the 20-foot-tall tower that supports it, was flown back to
Oklahoma for the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Salac, the FAA spokesperson, said the agency was looking into
the possibility that the failure was caused by a ``microburst,'' a
short, very intense windstorm, which can be as small as one or two
miles in radius and can contain hurricane-force winds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have reports of microburst activity in the region
Saturday, but we simply don't know if that was the cause,'' she
said. ``This post-mortem will be thorough and could take several
weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Massport spokesman Phil Orlandella said that the radar failure
was not an implication of the entire, $8 million surveillance
system, which can track weather conditions and airplanes within an
8-mile radius of Logan.
</P>
<P>
   Although Massport owns the land on Governors Island where it
sits, the FAA owns and operates the radar equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Orlandella also said there is no problem using an identical
model to replace the broken equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the antenna, the thing that goes around, and it's
just one part of the facility,'' said Orlandella. ``They're not
changing anything else, like the computers or software.''
</P>
<P>
   Orlandella also said that there was no reason to doubt the
reliability of the new ASR-9 unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're good, they work and they've proven effective, so we
are confident about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The new unit was operational at 2:03 p.m., and the flight
arrival rate was increased at 2:50 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``We watched the switchover,'' Robert Bartanowicz, regional
administator for FAA New England, said at a news conference at
Logan. ``It was totally seemless, no interruptions.
</P>
<P>
   Airport officials initially thought that it would take three to
five days to replace the radar and restore normal service at the
airport, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did this in approximately 58 hours, so this certainly puts
us ahead of our most aggressive estimate of 72 hours. So we came in
well ahead of schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Salac said that the FAA would not begin automatic inspections of
other ASR-9 units at airports nationwide, unless the examination of
the damaged Logan unit raises broader concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ASR-9 is considered 99.6 percent reliable,'' she said.
``This is that .4 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Globe correspondent Rachael Mullin contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
