<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT IS MAIN CULPRIT IN NASDAQ DROP 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MICROSOFT-MARKETPLACE, MICROSOFT-SUIT) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks had another rocky session Monday, as
aftershocks from a violently negative reaction among investors to
Microsoft's most recent earnings report reverberated through the
Nasdaq stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, which reported results from its third fiscal quarter
after the market closed on Thursday, was battered, falling 12 5/16,
or 15.6 percent, to 66 5/8. It was the biggest loss in the software
giant's share price since Oct. 26, 1987, a week after the stock
market crashed.
</P>
<P>
   The slide was a huge contributor to the 161.40-point, or 4.4
percent, decline in the Nasdaq composite index, which closed at
3,482.48. A late rally in many Nasdaq shares pulled the index off
its lows for the session. Still, Microsoft was responsible for more
than 41 points of the Nasdaq's drop.
</P>
<P>
   Investors moved into other sectors of the market as they exited
Microsoft and other technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average managed to rise, even though
Microsoft is a component of the blue chip index. The Dow closed at
10,906.10, up 62.05 points, or 0.6 percent. Gains in financial
stocks like American Express, which reported strong earnings,
General Electric and J.P. Morgan outweighed weakness in Microsoft
and Hewlett-Packard.
</P>
<P>
   Rising prices for drug, chemical and consumer stocks helped to
limit losses in the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, which closed
at 1,429.86, down 4.68 points, or 0.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the Russell 2000 index of small company stocks was battered.
The Russell, which has been dominated by the performance of a
relatively small group of technology and biotechnology stocks, fell
13.30 points Monday, or 2.8 percent, to 468.54.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in the midst of the decline in technology over the last
six weeks or so, I don't think investors have reconciled the fact
they were overweight technology at the expense of everything
else,'' said Jonathan Oleksy, head of block trading at Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter. ``We are seeing genuine interest in sectors
like drugs, chemicals, banks and utilities. Technology will still
ultimately command a large weighting of a person's portfolio. But
by the time you wring out this excess ownership more of this
rotational activity will have gone on.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Nasdaq market now down 31 percent from its peak on
March 10 and 14.4 percent for the year, some analysts said they
were beginning to look for signs that technology stocks are forming
a bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Nasdaq market is now just about as oversold relative to
its two-month moving average as it was back in 1987,'' said Laszlo
Birinyi, who heads his own stock market research firm in Greenwich,
Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are getting close to a level where I may actually do a
little buying myself, in Microsoft and in technology in general,''
said William Meehan, chief market analyst at Cantor Fitzgerald.
``If you are underweight technology, I would put some cash to work
if the Nasdaq composite got to 3,250.''
</P>
<P>
   There is little question that Microsoft's stock has been harshly
treated: So far this year, the stock is down 43 percent. Among
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 companies, the decline has dropped Microsoft
into fourth place in terms of market capitalization. It now trails
General Electric, Cisco Systems and Intel.
</P>
<P>
   And it has put a major crimp in the carrying value of Bill
Gates' holdings. Based on the most recent data on Microsoft
shareholders, the decline in the stock since the start of the year
has wiped out nearly $40 billion in paper assets from Gates'
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft was far and away the most actively traded issue
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 157 million Microsoft shares changed hands, the
third-highest ever for a U.S. stock. Trading in Microsoft was about
three times as heavy as in the next most active issue Monday, Cisco
Systems. Cisco fell 1 5/8, to 63 1/2. The stock traded as low as 59
1/4.
</P>
<P>
   On the whole, however, traders said business was fairly quiet.
European markets were closed in observance of Easter Monday. Among
Dow stocks, American Express rose 7, to 150, after it reported
first-quarter earnings that beat Wall Street's forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   Merck, which also reported solid earnings, gained 2 3/16, to 71
15/16. And McDonald's rose 3 3/16, to 39.
</P>
<P>
   Big chemical companies like DuPont and Dow Chemical gained.
DuPont rose 1 3/4, to 56. And Dow Chemical was up 3 5/8, to 109.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Microsoft, Exodus Communications was the biggest
loser on the Nasdaq market. Late Thursday the manager of Internet
sites reported a loss that was wider than expected. On Monday the
stock was hammered, falling 25 3/16, to 82 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we didn't see this terrific rotation that is going on, I
would be much more worried,'' said David Williams, manager of the
$1.2 billion Excelsior Value and Restructuring fund at U.S. Trust
Co. ``As long as the rotation continues, the market can probably
move higher.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
