<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6086 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-24 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: ABC HITS (MELTING) ICEBERG 
</HEADLINE>
   By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The time has come to put in a good word for Leonardo DiCaprio.
</P>
<P>
   The controversial White House interview between the star of
``Titanic'' and President Clinton finally aired last weekend, as
part of an ABC Earth Day special. ``Just by changing the lighting
in this building we lowered our electric bills by $100,000 a
year,'' the Leader of the World's Only Surviving Superpower said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow,'' replied the Most Famous Actor on the Planet.
</P>
<P>
   Later DiCaprio managed to elicit the revelation that
environmental concerns were just as important to the president as
education or health care. Those were pretty much the high points.
More than 17 minutes of the 20-minute interview wound up on the
cutting-room floor, allegedly because ABC felt it was too
amateurish. Politics has not always been kind to DiCaprio, the
movie star John McCain always enjoyed referring to as ``that
androgynous wimp.''
</P>
<P>
   As an interviewer, DiCaprio is no Tim Russert, or even the guy
who used to ask taste testers whether they prefer Coke to Pepsi.
However, the network could have made a worse decision than
assigning a 25-year-old actor to talk global warming with the
president. For instance, it could have given the job to any of the
people responsible for the rest of the show.
</P>
<P>
   Let's begin with a brief recap of ``Planet Earth 2000,'' since
the ratings suggest that you did not get a chance to watch it
yourself. In fact, the odds were better that you spent the holiday
weekend being abducted by a UFO.
</P>
<P>
   The high point probably came when the ABC correspondent,
Christopher Cuomo, delivered a paean to the ancient hunting
traditions of the local Eskimos while his subjects buzzed around on
snowmobiles, waving high-powered rifles. The actual topic of the
segment was thinning ice near the North Pole. But if you waited for
Cuomo to point out that melting of the polar ice cap had a
potential effect on anything but the Eskimos' ability to keep their
recreational vehicles from falling into the water, you'd still be
on the couch.
</P>
<P>
   The program's resistance to providing context, or making any
sort of compelling point, was actually sort of fascinating. A
segment on Julia Butterfly Hill, the woman who spent two years
living in a tree to save it from the loggers, managed to tell her
whole story without once giving any inkling of why cutting down
redwoods is undesirable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were targeting a younger audience,'' said Phyllis McGraddy,
an ABC vice president. ``The point of that woman was to bring them
to asking: `Well, why was she in that tree?'''
</P>
<P>
   The point of never giving them the answer was somewhat more
oblique.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bothers me that nobody seems to be giving us credit for
even trying,'' McGraddy added. ``Whether we failed miserably, well,
that's a different debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Interesting kids in global warming is such a fine goal that you
could overlook DiCaprio, not to mention the E.R.-like camera work,
the MTV-type soundtrack and the Foxian way that everything wound up
being illustrated by another picture of a hurricane. But out of
fear of offending or boring its target audience, ABC also made
global warming apolitical, devoid of villains. Even the lumber
company that wanted to cut down Hill's tree seemed nice.
</P>
<P>
   The White House, possibly hoping to drive ABC nuts, has released
a transcript of the 20 minutes of actor-president conversation that
got cut, and it turns out that there was one person involved in the
project who had a more, ah, global vision of global warming.
DiCaprio wanted to know how the United States could get developing
countries to cut pollution when ``we're responsible for a quarter
of the greenhouse gases that go into the atmosphere.'' He also
asked about requiring automobile manufacturers to make cars
cleaner.
</P>
<P>
   The president's answers were, to use the metaphors of the
moment, rather windy and unelectrifying. Even worse, from the
producers' point of view, they were delivered from a chair. The
network had counted on a walking tour of the energy-efficient White
House, and the producers apparently lost interest in DiCaprio's
scoop when they found out the president wanted the interview to be
stationary. ``It was supposed to be an hour of everything moving,
not sitting down,'' said McGraddy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
