<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6088 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MOTOROLA-AD-COLUMN-NY     04-24 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTOROLA-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTOROLA HOPES MYA WILL LINK THE REAL WORLD WITH THE VIRTUAL ONE
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ As the symbol of the new 24-hour talking Internet,
Motorola nominates a virtual woman named Mya, a long-legged blonde,
clad in a shimmering silver business suit and sporting punky hair
and a ubiquitous telephone headset.
</P>
<P>
   Her animated figure is showcased in a new 60-second television
spot created for Motorola Inc., the cellular telephone and
semiconductor giant that is now trying to sell software and
Internet services and jazz up its image.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the service will not be available to consumers until
summer, Motorola rushed the spot out for the Academy Awards, hoping
the hippest of hip would associate Motorola with an Internet
service that will allow people to call into a voice-activated
``cyberassistant'' who will read e-mail messages, stock quotes,
sports scores and weather forecasts directly from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless communications experts say the Motorola offering _
which would be sold to consumers through cellular phone carriers
and other intermediaries _ is among the first of many
voice-activated Internet operations to come, and that technology
companies are increasingly going to turn to virtual humans to sell
those products.
</P>
<P>
   Already, there is an online question and answer service called
Ask Jeeves. In London, a company has created Ananova, a
green-haired cyberanchor billed as the world's first virtual
newscaster, that began broadcasting from the Web site
www.ananova.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``Online companies are trying to personalize a service that is
inherently impersonal,'' said Joseph Laszlo, a wireless data
analyst at Jupiter Communications. ``In the consumers' mind, if
they think of this person who's trying to help them, this kind of
marketing may help out.''
</P>
<P>
   Mya is a computer-generated being who companies hope will link
the real world to the virtual one, and marketers hope will be
attractive enough to catch the attention of consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't a Web browser, this is someone who can speak to
you,'' said Geoffrey Frost, the vice president for consumer
communications at Motorola, which is based in Schaumburg, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers, however, will have to wait until at least June to
subscribe to the service, which gets its news from Reuters and its
weather from Accuweather, two companies that use Motorola's
technology to convert data to voice and voice to data.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola plans to spend more than $10 million to start the
service and recast its traditionally stodgy image with provocative
advertising from its agency, McCann-Erickson Worldwide Advertising,
part of the McCann-Erickson World Group unit of the Interpublic
Group of Cos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Motorola really wanted to put a stake in the ground in the
post-PC world,'' said Jonathan Cranin, a creative director at
McCann-Erickson. ``And the talking Internet seemed to be the
coolest thing going.''
</P>
<P>
   Motorola did not invent the idea of a 24-hour talking Internet
service, but it is an early developer, and the first company to
start a major marketing push in the United States. Motorola's
telecommunications partners in the venture have not been announced.
</P>
<P>
   In the spot that appeared during the Academy Awards ceremony,
Mya is portrayed as the sexy celebrity everyone is talking about:
Her portrait is on the cover of USA Today, Wired and InStyle
magazine. She has a guest appearance on a late-night talk show.
Hugh Hefner, lounging in a limo with two women, asks Mya to read
his e-mail messages.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the segment, a cyberlimo arrives at what looks
like the Academy Awards. Mya steps out and with bulbs flashing,
confesses, ``Yes, I read the Web to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Motorola and McCann-Erickson came up with the idea of creating
an animated character to symbolize the new Internet service, which
is called myosphere.
</P>
<P>
   To create the character, McCann hired Digital Domain, the
animation studio in Venice, Calif., that was founded by James
Cameron, the director of ``Titanic,'' and the producers of
``Terminator.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Raimondi, the visual effects supervisor at Digital Domain,
said the company began by casting a real-life actress as Mya and
then photographed and filmed her body in painstaking detail. A
three-dimensional image of the actress was created and then scanned
into a computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the first shot we showed them, she looked too real,''
Raimondi said. ``We had to pull her back. That's why her clothes
are shiny.''
</P>
<P>
   For Mya's angelic voice, the company hired Gabrielle Carteris,
the former ``Beverly Hills 90210'' actress.
</P>
<P>
   Digital Domain may spawn other cyberassistants, male and female,
perhaps even giving consumers the option of finding a voice that
suits their fancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may give you your choice of personalities,'' Frost at
Motorola said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
