<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6090 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GORE-FUERTH-ART-2TAKE     04-24 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-FUERTH-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIGMUND FUERTH: GORE'S FOREIGN POLICY MENTOR, THE ONLY AIDE TO CALL
HIM AL
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT13 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ELAINE SCIOLINO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There is only one member of Vice President Gore's
staff close enough to call him Al.
</P>
<P>
   It is Leon Sigmund Fuerth, Gore's longest-serving aide, who has
acted as his elder adviser on national security matters for two
decades. The two men know each other so well that, like an old
married couple, they can communicate through a grimace or a glance.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship goes back to 1980, when Fuerth, a staff member
on Capitol Hill, tutored the young congressman from Tennessee nine
years his junior several hours a week for more than a year on the
arcana of arms control. Since then Fuerth has exercised influence
over Gore, whose worldview blends a belief in a strong defense, the
elevation of issues like illness and the environment to the top of
the national security agenda and a moralistic impulse to punish
dictators.
</P>
<P>
   Fuerth has often stiffened his boss' spine, including pressing
early to use strikes to constrain Serbian forces from ethnic
cleansing in Bosnia and Kosovo and taking an uncompromising line
against Iraq, Iran and North Korea, which Fuerth has referred to
privately as ``giant zits on various parts of the body.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all his his influence, including membership in the
cabinet-level Principals' Committee that advises the president on
foreign policy, the onetime foreign service officer labors largely
in the shadows. He rarely gives speeches or interviews. He has
written no great tomes. He likes to work alone. At one point he
announced at a press briefing that his goal was to remain
``nameless, faceless and odorless''; at another he told aides that
his ideas ``belong to the vice president.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore praises that approach as positively quaint and has hinted
that he may name Fuerth as national security adviser in a Gore
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a keen intellect, a strong character, absolute
integrity and excellent instincts,'' Gore said in a telephone
interview. ``There is a certain quaintness to his insistence on
taking as little credit for anything he can possibly push off to
others, quaintness in the sense not that it is odd. In fact, I wish
it were more common. In today's world that quality is all too
rare.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Time magazine's prediction last year that Fuerth was
``a cinch'' to be national security adviser in a Gore
administration, Gore at first stuck to his rule not to discuss
potential advisers. But then he added, ``If I were to break that
rule for anybody, it would be for Leon.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly quaintness is not a word that springs to mind in
describing former national security advisers Henry A. Kissinger or
Zbigniew Brzezinski. And when asked what Fuerth would be like in
the job he once held, Kissinger replied, ``I'm afraid I don't know
the man.''
</P>
<P>
   Advisers to Gov. George W. Bush have already begun to criticize
the vice president and his top national security aide by
criticizing the performance of the Clinton administration. ``A
hallmark of the Clinton-Gore foreign policy has been ad hockery and
case-by-case actions lacking in strategy,'' said Robert Zoellick,
an undersecretary of state in the Bush administration. So despite
Fuerth's passion for anonymity, he inevitably will be drawn into
the spotlight in a presidential campaign in which Gore is
increasingly contrasting his foreign policy experience with that of
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   And that could be uncomfortable for Fuerth, 61, who has spent
his entire career inside government and who has never had to
develop an ear for politics. By contrast, Sandy Berger, President
Clinton's national security adviser, knows how to shape foreign
policy to fit politics.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie H. Gelb, the president of the Council on Foreign
Relations who has known Berger and Fuerth for years, said that
Berger ``came to the job as a political pro and had to master the
foreign policy part of it.'' ``Leon,'' he added, ``came to the
White House as a foreign policy expert and he now has to master the
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in their relationship, Gore created a division of labor
that he and Fuerth insist suits them fine. He told Fuerth to
provide the best advice on what was good for the country and to
``leave the politics to me.''
</P>
<P>
   But that division means that Fuerth can sometimes be out of the
political loop. In an interview on March 30, for example, Fuerth
was asked how his boss would resolve the case of Elian Gonzalez.
``The administration's position and the vice president's position
consistently are to navigate where the boy's best interests are,''
Fuerth said. ``And in our system, the courts are the best place to
get this task done.''
</P>
<P>
   At almost the same time, Gore was proposing a legislative
solution that could have allowed the boy to remain in the United
States. By Fuerth's own admission, he was unaware that Gore had
decided to change course that day.
</P>
<P>
   And there can be a downside to avoiding politics. It was Fuerth
who told Gore that the now celebrated fund-raising luncheon at a
Buddhist temple in 1996 posed no problem from a foreign policy
standpoint, instead of looking at it from a larger legal and
ethical perspective. (The National Security Council, by contrast,
warned that Gore should proceed with ``great, great caution.'')
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Fuerth was blamed for the politically embarrassing
incident during vice president's trip to China in 1997 in which he
inadvertently shared a Champagne toast with Prime Minister Li Peng,
who had orchestrated the Tiananmen massacre. Fuerth said that the
toast was never supposed to happen, but that the Chinese broke
their promises.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   While Gore at times has devised idealistic solutions for solving
global problems, Fuerth tends to takes a darker view, a view that
stems from a deeply rooted belief that the world is a dangerous
place. As a young man, Fuerth said he was so terrified by the 1960
classic ``On Thermonuclear War'' by Herman Kahn that he was
reluctant to start a family.
</P>
<P>
   Fuerth's vacuum-cleaner mind and his tenacity when he is
convinced he is right can make him a formidable opponent in making
decisions. ``Contrarian'' is often used to describe him.
</P>
<P>
   But he can also sound downright eloquent when discussing issues
about which he and Gore feel passionately, like the AIDS epidemic
in sub-Sahara Africa. ``If you get something which can burn out the
heart of a generation, what is the difference if they're dying of
disease or war?'' he said. ``They're dying! And people will not
flourish, people will not live out their lives or make their full
contributions. Societies will be destabilized. A generation of
orphans will be created. So if you need an analogy to warfare, it's
the consequences of war without the explosion.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore depends heavily on Fuerth, who has developed a system of
passing hand-written, humor-laced, policy-filled notes during
meetings, meals and even receiving lines. The note-passing became
so disruptive during the president's cabinet meetings that protocol
was abandoned and Fuerth was given a permanent seat at the vice
president's immediate right.
</P>
<P>
   For meetings with foreign officials, Gore gets the benefit of
Fuerth's detailed knowledge in thick briefing books and then
distilled on a stack of note cards.
</P>
<P>
   Some years ago, when an aide urged Gore to dispense with the
cards, the vice president was said to reply that he did not want to
hurt Fuerth's feelings. Gore now says that if he ever said such a
thing, it was in jest and that in fact, he does need the cards.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Gore, Fuerth did not grow up privileged. His father, who
drove an ice cream truck, died of coronary thrombosis when Leon, an
only child, was 8; his widowed mother went to work in a dry
cleaning shop.
</P>
<P>
   After majoring in English at New York University, Fuerth entered
the Air Force as a second lieutenant. Back at the university, he
began a doctorate in Russian history, but joined the foreign
service when his wife, Lynn, had their first of two sets of twin
girls and he needed a paying job.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven years later, he went to work for the House Permanent
Select Committee on Intelligence. When Gore moved to the Senate, he
took Fuerth with him.
</P>
<P>
   Gore describes Fuerth as a cross between ``a rabbi and a
stand-up comic.'' But many outsiders don't see his lighter side.
His gruffness earned him the nickname Metternich on the Hill years
ago and Darth Vader more recently in the corridors of the State
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Some people insist that too much work and too little staff
account for his irritability; others say it stems from deep
shyness. Said Toby T. Gati, who came to respect Fuerth when she was
the National Security Council's Russia expert: ``He's not a mother
figure. He's not a father figure. He's a patriarch.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of Fuerth's image problem is his body language. He has a
habit of casting his glance downward, staring at his tightly folded
hands. The posture is so much a part of his persona that Gore did a
parody of it at a party to celebrate Fuerth's 60th birthday a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   After Fuerth suffered a mild heart attack in March 1999, he
drastically changed his habits, shedding 45 pounds and embracing a
tough exercise regimen. At his 60th birthday party a few weeks
later, Gore had this advice for him: ``We all want to say, `Relax!'
''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he is trying to do that, even reaching out more to a
class of people with whom he never felt comfortable: the Washington
press corps. ``Part of his problem is that he has a linear way of
doing things,'' said Michael McCurry, the former White House press
secretary. ``I once had a conversation with him in which I said,
`You have to learn the language and culture of dealing with the
press.' I might as well have been dealing with a foreign
government.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Fuerth's colleagues in the administration speculate that
he may be better suited in the job of, say, CIA director or
secretary of defense than of national security adviser, which has
typically required extensive public diplomacy and the ability to
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   But Fuerth has something that no other national security expert
does: an intimate relationship with Gore. And Gore may just want to
keep the man he calls ``a great friend'' close to his side, doing
what he has always done: keeping him informed, passing him notes,
feeding him ideas, making him laugh and always, always giving him
the credit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
