<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6092 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-BOS &LR;      04-24 1247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADMINISTRATION RESPONDS TO GOP ATTACK ON CUBAN BOY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration fired back Monday at
critics of the raid to take custody of Elian Gonzalez, blasting
prominent Republicans for making ``wildly inaccurate'' statements
about the operation and blaming the boy's relatives for having
forced the government's hand.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno, who was described as having cried
after negotiations ended shortly before federal agents seized
Elian, said she had ``bent over backwards'' to achieve a peaceful
resolution to the custody dispute. Asked on NBC's ``Today'' show if
she had any second thoughts about having ordered a military-style
incursion before dawn Saturday, Reno replied: ``I have no regrets
whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   GOP leaders have been scathing in their criticism of the
administration's decision to forcibly remove Elian from his
great-uncle's home, and Monday they announced the start of an
investigation into the affair.
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee chairman, Representative Henry
Hyde of Illinois, said he was beginning a ``preliminary inquiry''
into the tactics used by armed Immigration and Naturalization
Service agents in Miami. Hyde said House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert
of Illinois had requested the probe, which will lead to full
committee hearings if GOP officials decide they're warranted.
</P>
<P>
   At the request of Senate majority leader Trent Lott of
Mississippi, Reno is also scheduled to discuss the issue Tuesday
morning with a group of Republican lawmakers on Capitol Hill. In
addition, the chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee, Senator
Orin Hatch of Utah, sent the attorney general a letter asking for
the supporting documents the government used Friday afternoon to
obtain a search warrant for the INS raid.
</P>
<P>
   The boy spent a third day in seclusion Monday with his father,
Juan Miguel Gonzalez, his stepmother and 6-month-old step-brother
in guest quarters at Andrews Air Force base in suburban Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Notwithstanding the activity by Republican leaders, they were
far less vocal in their attacks on the administration Monday,
perhaps because the controversy had entered a new phase, or maybe
because opinion polls showed Americans clearly in favor of the
operation that returned Elian to his father.
</P>
<P>
   In the hours after the 6-year-old boy's seizure, Lott had issued
a statement saying he thought ``that this could only happen in
Castro's Cuba.'' Representative Lincoln Diaz-Balart, a Florida
Republican, said Saturday night that a Band-Aid on Elian's arm in
photos of him with his father indicated the government had begun
``drugging'' him as part of a process of ``brainwashing.''
</P>
<P>
   Several high-ranking Republicans followed with their own
assessments Sunday, the sharpest offered by the House majority
whip, Representative Tom DeLay of Texas. Saying he was ``sickened''
and ``ashamed'' by the INS action, DeLay essentially accused the
Clinton administration of having kidnapped the child by acting
without a search warrant.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart Monday mentioned DeLay in his
angry response to what he depicted as a partisan effort by the GOP
to use the Elian drama for ``some perceived political gain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a number of Republicans who have come out and just
made what I have to view as wild statements, wildly inaccurate,''
Lockhart said. He said DeLay knew it wasn't true when he contended
that the government lacked a search warrant and that Elian's father
had abused his son.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart delivered equally harsh comments about the boy's Miami
relatives, with whom he lived since he was rescued off the Florida
coast five months ago until US agents snatched him Saturday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important piece of information here is all of this
could have been avoided,'' said President Clinton's spokesman.
``This happened because the family did not respect the legal
process here that dictated the father should be reunited with the
young boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``That lack of respect and the unwillingness to go along with
what the court said and what the INS said led to no other
alternative,'' Lockhart added. Repeating the government's
explanation that authorities had been told there might be guns in
the Miami home or in the crowd outside, he suggested that the
administrationn would have received even more criticism if the INS
agents had gone in unarmed and violence had ensued.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart took particular aim at claims by Elian's cousin
Marisleysis Gonzalez that photos of the boy looking happy with his
father had been altered. The spokesman called that notion
``absolutely absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department implied Monday that Marisleysis, who has
lambasted the federal government for its use of force, may have
provided some of the impetus for the decision to use weapons in
raiding her home.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman, Carole Florman, said the 21-year-old woman had
told a department official _ presumably during a phone call, but
Florman did not elaborate _ there were ``more than just guns'' in
the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``The person who heard it was very alarmed and took that ... as
a possibility of guns and as a threatening statement,'' said
Florman. ``Her remarks certainly added to the concerns that we were
sending law enforcement personnel into a possibly volatile
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno, on Monday's television interview, reiterated her
reluctance to order aggressive action to remove Elian from his home
in Miami, where the attorney general lived most of her life and
made her legal career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to avoid it with all my heart and soul,'' she said.
``But once having determined that we should go forward with it, it
should be done in the best, most professional way possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder described Reno as so upset
after ordering Elian's removal at gunpoint that he had to close the
door of the room in which they were negotiating by telephone with
mediators in Miami. Holder said he then ``held the attorney general
in my arms, and she wept.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Podhurst, a Miami lawyer and longtime friend of Reno's who
was acting as an intermediary with the Gonzalez family Saturday
night, gave a similar account during a news conference in Florida
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Podhurst said the attorney general sounded very sad and near
tears during the last moments of negotiations over the telephone.
While he praised his old friend for her strength and courage, he
continued to insist for a third day that the talks had been
extremely close to a breakthrough when Reno broke them off and
ordered the INS assault.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry that it worked out wrong,'' he said. He added that
Reno had shown ``extraordinary courage'' in remaining on the line
rather than just hanging up once she knew what she was going to do.
</P>
<P>
   The president of the University of Miami, Edward ``Tad'' Foote,
who also had acted as an intermediary, said he was ``disappointed
and dismayed'' that Reno had cut off the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Reno indicated Monday that she had ended the discussions for
several reasons: The Miami relatives had given their consent to
previous agreements and reneged; they seemed intransigent on the
key point of turning Elian over to his father immediately; and if
she had negotiated later into the morning, the optimum conditions
for a raid would have passed and the law-enforcement personnel
would have called it off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
