<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6093 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-CLINTON-POLITICS-(TRI     04-24 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-POLITICS-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ATTENDS FUND-RAISER FOR CONGRESSMAN WHO VOTED TO IMPEACH
HIM 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ President Clinton attends at least one fund-raiser a
week. He is used to the hors d'oeuvres, the banter, the elegant
surroundings. But his visit to a swank Fifth Avenue home on Monday,
where spicy lamb turnovers were on the menu and Central Park was
visible outside, represented a new experience even for him.
</P>
<P>
   It was Clinton's first campaign appearance for a congressman who
had voted to impeach him.
</P>
<P>
   As one would expect, Clinton did not once bring up the fact that
Rep. Michael Forbes of Long Island had less than two years ago
voted in favor of all four articles of impeachment against him.
Forbes, as well, failed to recount that he had once issued a press
release urging Clinton to resign. Their remarks instead ignored
that ugly episode entirely and stuck to typical fund-raising
chatter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is somebody I've grown to have great affection
for,'' said Forbes, who collected $500,000 in campaign money with
Clinton's aid. ``He loves this country clearly. Every day, he wakes
up to see what he can do as a leader to make this country better.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, who switched parties last year, was a Republican back
when he voted to oust Clinton from office. And Clinton's support
for him reinforces a reality of this post-impeachment White House:
the president, despite expectations to the contrary, is not holding
grudges as he rushes in the final months of his presidency to leave
a legacy that has nothing to do with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has reached out to other impeachment stalwarts. He has
invited Rep. Henry Hyde, who led the impeachment effort as chairman
of the House Judiciary Committee, to the Oval Office to discuss gun
control. At a recent East Room gathering on gun control
legislation, packed among a host of Democratic lawmakers, was none
other than Rep. James Rogan, a Republican of California and
outspoken supporter of returning Clinton to private life.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has even reached out, to some degree, to Rep. Tom DeLay,
the tough talking majority whip who helped stir up the impeachment
storm. DeLay is the chief Republican lawmaker charged with rounding
up votes for Clinton's effort to extend permanent normal trade
relations to China.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Clinton considers impeachment not unlike the defeat
of his health care overhaul or the rejection of the comprehensive
test ban treaty. It was a political act, in his view, pushed by his
political opponents that gained so much momentum that others
followed along.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton recently said he considers impeachment ``one of the
major chapters in my defeat of the revolution Mr. Gingrich led,
that would have taken this country in a very different direction
than it's going today, and also would have changed the Constitution
forever, in a way that would have been very destructive to the
American people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the president has decided not to waste any energy on
personal animosity,'' said Joe Lockhart, the White House press
secretary.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has never had a problem compartmentalizing his political
life. He delivered a State of the Union address when the Lewinsky
scandal was first breaking and acted as though all was well. A year
later, in the heat of impeachment, he spoke to the assembled
lawmakers without a word about the fact that his job was on the
line. Nowadays, aides to Clinton say impeachment still riles him
but not to the point where it clouds his political judgment.
</P>
<P>
   As the election nears, the Clinton White House has once again
grown accustomed to criticism from Republican congressional
leaders. In recent days, there has been a loud chorus of
condemnation from Republicans over the administration's handling of
the Elian Gonzalez case.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Since the not guilty verdicts rang out in the Senate chamber on
Feb. 12, 1999, Clinton has engaged in a vigorous, coast-to-coast
campaign to help House and Senate Democrats win back the majority.
That includes a one-time Republican such as Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   But despite suggestions from aides in the weeks after
impeachment that Clinton would launch a payback effort for those
who tried to remove him, Clinton's campaign stops have not had the
air of a personal vendetta.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to get legislative accomplishments, he needs to
cooperate with those who tried to tar and feather him,'' said Norm
J. Ornstein, a congressional analyst with the American Enterprise
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 278 members of the House and Senate attempted to oust
Clinton. The president would accomplish nothing if he shunned them
all. And some of those lawmakers who tried to remove him now find
him an occasional ally.
</P>
<P>
   The very same Forbes who was praising the president over lamb
turnovers once issued an urgent fund-raising appeal that labeled
Clinton a lawbreaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in my heart, the president committed the crimes of
perjury and obstruction of justice,'' Forbes wrote. ``This was not
about a ``Monica Lewinsky affair,' it was about using the power of
the presidency to obstruct our judicial system and to prevent the
truth from being told in a sexual harassment/civil rights
lawsuit.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Republican Campaign Committee, still bitter that
Forbes jumped ship, is aggressively backing the candidacy of Felix
Grucci, a businessman. A spokesman for the national Republican
group, Carl Forti, said Forbes divergent impeachment views
represent his ``lack of backbone.''
</P>
<P>
   But others see the divergent views as nothing more than
run-of-the-mill politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the real world, people are less likely to forgive someone
who has attempted to disgrace them, but this is politics and in
politics you sometimes try to secure a job for someone who tried to
remove you from yours,'' said Marshall Wittman, a congressional
analyst with the Heritage Foundation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
