u s BC-BBN-METS-DODGERS-NYT &LR;      04-24 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-DODGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS' BULLPEN PUTS UP ZEROES FROM START TO FINISH 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If you want to see six hearts leap at the same time,
Turk Wendell said, watch the reaction when the phone rings in a
bullpen where the relief pitchers don't know their roles. Six guys
think it may be their turn. Four or five, inevitably, will be
disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching in relief _ especially for the Mets _ is so physically
demanding that Wendell, who worked in 80 games last year, runs five
to eight miles a day to condition himself. If pitchers don't know
when they'll be used, the mental obstacles can be overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way to have a good bullpen _ every guy needs to
know their roles,'' said Wendell, who got six crucial outs in the
late innings of the Mets' 1-0 victory over the Los Angeles Dodgers
on Monday. ``When you don't know your role, you have to deal with
that uncertainty.''
</P>
<P>
   Mets pitchers were brilliant on Monday, working nine innings
with the score tied. A single by Matt Franco in the bottom of the
ninth brought in the only run and extended the Mets' winning streak
to eight games.
</P>
<P>
   Each pitcher in the Mets' bullpen knows precisely who does what.
Pat Mahomes understands that when a starting pitcher goes down to a
minor injury, he will be the first choice to fill in. The
right-handed Mahomes did it earlier this month, when Al Leiter
missed a turn, and he did it again on Monday, when Rick Reed's
bruised left hand kept him from starting.
</P>
<P>
   Mahomes gave a strong effort, allowing only two singles and
lasting until there were two outs in the sixth inning. Then, with a
man on third and the left-handed batter Shawn Green coming up, Mets
Manager Bobby Valentine called for the left-hander Dennis Cook.
</P>
<P>
   That was Cook's situation _ lefty on lefty _ and he got Green to
pop out, ending the threat. When Cook encountered trouble in the
seventh, it was Wendell who worked out of it, using a slider he
didn't think was very sharp to strike out Adrian Beltre and get
Devon White to pop out.
</P>
<P>
   After Wendell shut down the Dodgers in the eighth, the closer
Armando Benitez _ pitching the ninth inning of a tie game at home,
as expected _ fell behind each batter he faced but worked another
scoreless inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone did the exact job we wanted them to do,'' Valentine
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mahomes recognized that he was taking the place of a pitcher who
has been very successful so far. Reed _ who now seems likely to
start Wednesday against Cincinnati _ has the second-best earned run
average in baseball, and Mahomes did a fair imitation. ``Not as
many innings,'' he said, ``but I was able to put a zero on the
board.''
</P>
<P>
   Mahomes worked his slider and cutter off his fastballs, and
whenever he needed to make a pitch, Dodgers catcher Todd Hundley
said, he made it.
</P>
<P>
   Mahomes looked best against Green, striking him out on a
fastball in the second and a cutter that fooled Green badly in the
fourth. The cut fastball, Mahomes said, is the biggest reason his
career has blossomed the last two years after seven seasons spent
meandering through the majors, the minors and the Japanese league.
</P>
<P>
   ``Left-handers always killed me,'' Mahomes said. ``Now I have
another weapon against left-handers, instead of just a slow
curveball and changeup. The cutter looks like a fastball and gets
them out front a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Mahomes has learned the importance of accepting his role. After
Minnesota traded him to Boston in 1996, Mahomes expected to be a
closer. When his role became something different, he sulked and
wound up taking work in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   But Mahomes has a sharp focus now, Valentine has noticed, and he
watches the start of games from the dugout, preparing himself for
possibly pitching later. Long relief and spot starting is the least
glamorous job on a staff, but Valentine called Mahomes his ``staff
saver.'' Mahomes won't complain about how he is used.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to pitch in the major leagues,'' he said, ``you've
got to do whatever they tell you to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had 18 hits on Sunday, but Mahomes doubted they would
duplicate the output against the Dodgers starter Darren Dreifort,
who baffled the Mets earlier this year despite performing in a
loss. Mahomes was right: Dreifort allowed five hits and three walks
in six innings, but the Mets could not score.
</P>
<P>
   Facing the Dodgers reliever Terry Adams in the ninth, Robin
Ventura led off with a double and Melvin Mora pinch-ran. After a
walk, Jay Payton chopped a ball in the hole between shortstop and
third. Beltre, the third baseman, moved for it, but retreated when
shortstop Kevin Elster gathered the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to turn a double play, Elster tossed awkwardly to Beltre,
as if flipping an option pass, and Beltre's foot came off third
base as Mora slid in. Beltre's tag of Mora's hip was too late,
Umpire Gerry Davis ruled, prompting an argument that got Dodgers
Manager Davey Johnson ejected.
</P>
<P>
   Mora thought Beltre was afraid of being spiked.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know why he took his foot off the base,'' Mora said of
Beltre. ``Maybe if he did, it would have been a different story,
because he wouldn't have been scared of being cut. He didn't want
to get hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   The bases were loaded, and after Elster threw home on a grounder
by Rey Ordonez for the first out, Franco's bouncer skimmed Adams'
glove, and Jon Nunnally raced home with the winning run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would give myself an error, because that ball was hit right
at me,'' Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   It went for a hit, one of eight for the Mets in a game in which
their pitching did best. These days, the Mets are making everything
count.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just like the fact that we're not wasting our good pitching
and we're not wasting our good hitting,'' Valentine said. ``That's
the sign of a good team.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
