<HEADER>
A6097 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-TWINS-NYT &LR;      04-24 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TWINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS ADDS ANOTHER PIECE TO HIS PUZZLE OF INCONSISTENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The dissection of Roger Clemens continued Monday as
one of the greatest pitchers of this era had another performance
that added more confusion to his perplexing 14 months with the
Yankees. Clemens was inconsistent, then he was dominating and then
he was unreliable at the most inopportune time.
</P>
<P>
   Then Clemens discussed an aggravating 7-3 loss to the Minnesota
Twins as if he were analyzing his golf game. He actually mentioned
that the wind affected his pitches during a dreadful three-run
first inning and he said that he was not too disappointed about two
pitches that produced the tie-breaking run in the seventh because
they were solid pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens is a proud pitcher, a five-time Cy Young Award winner
who believes that he should be perfect. Not just in every start,
but for every pitch. Clemens was almost perfect over five powerful
innings, but the first and the last inning he worked doomed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I need better results,'' he said. ``But it's coming
down to one or two pitches to getting things turned around.''
</P>
<P>
   The dissection of Clemens (1-5) will continue because both he
and David Cone need to be consistent for the Yankees to be an
intimidating team. Joe Torre stressed how lucky the Yankees were to
enter the day with the best record in the major leagues because
their starters other than Orlando Hernandez are 2-6 with a 6.17
earned run average.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fortunate to be 12-6 because we're not doing it right
yet,'' said Torre. ``I think we're in a very fortunate position to
have won 12 of 18 games and have the manager say that we're going
to play better than we're playing. I think that's a good sign.
Hopefully, it happens quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, who was bruised for five earned runs in six and two
thirds innings, is the reason the Yankees looked so listless while
losing for the third time in their last four games.
</P>
<P>
   He started the contest with two quick strikes on Todd Walker,
presumably unaffected by the wind at that point. But then he
uncorked seven straight balls and eight in nine pitches to put
Twins on first and second. Matt Lawton singled to load the bases
and Ron Coomers' squibber to first delivered the first run.
</P>
<P>
   After a strikeout, Clemens needed to retire Butch Huskey to
emerge with a 1-0 deficit in the first. Huskey had one hit in nine
at bats off Clemens in his career, but, once again, Clemens fell
behind in the count and threw a 2-1 split-finger fastball that did
not dive and he said acted more like a ``slow fastball.'' Huskey
ripped it between third and shortstop to put the Twins ahead, 3-0.
Some of the 35,693 fans at Yankee Stadium booed, the first of three
different times Clemens received such treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt too good to be in that predicament early,'' said
Clemens. ``Like I said, I still had the chance to get out of it
fairly unscathed. But they were able to get that key hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre was mystified. He would never admit it, but Clemens seems
to puzzle him more than other pitchers. Torre praised Clemens'
repertory, which produced nine strikeouts, and said that type of
repertory will be ``fine'' all year. Still, Torre could not explain
how the future Hall of Famer could pump two strikes to open a game
and then walk two batters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't have an answer,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   From the second through the sixth, Clemens rebounded to retire
14 of 17 batters. Tino Martinez had a run-scoring single in the
first and the Yankees added two more in the sixth after left
fielder Jacque Jones lost a ball in the sun that fueled the rally.
Martinez had a run-scoring single and Shane Spencer had a sacrifice
fly off Eric Milton to even the score, 3-3.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens should have barreled to the mound a new man. That ugly
first had been erased. But Clemens faltered again, unable to
contain a team he had stifled for five straight innings. Clemens
left his last start with a stiff back, but the back did not bother
him Monday. Inconsistency did.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, a second-year player with 109 major league hits, stroked
a double to right center off a 1-1 slider. Matt LeCroy, a rookie
with nine major league hits, slapped a 1-0 fastball down the third
base line to give the Twins a 4-3 lead. So, five pitches after the
Yankees had saved Clemens, he was rattled by Jones and LeCroy, two
players most Yankees fans had never heard of until they purchased
scorecards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made good pitches there,'' insisted Clemens. ``I made the
pitches that I wanted to make. Give them credit. They hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens was giving credit to two unknown hitters who probably
collected his baseball cards at some point in their lives. It was a
nice gesture, but it did not sound like something one of the
greatest pitchers of his era should say. Then Clemens pulled on his
jacket and trudged away, the confusion following right behind him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
