<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-AUTOS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD PLANT IN BRITAIN MAY BE CLOSED 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Adds sentence to end of 8th graf, `Helmut Panke ... $3
million a day.') 
 By ALAN COWELL with KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ With Britain's troubled auto industry facing severe
cutbacks and job losses, Prime Minister Tony Blair and other
government officials have held talks with Ford Motor Co. as it
contemplates closing a plant near London.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials said Monday that Blair met recently with
Jacques A. Nasser, the Ford chief executive, and that he and other
officials were in contact with Ford over an internal review of its
European operations, expected to be concluded in mid-May.
</P>
<P>
   James Vella, a Ford spokesman, said: ``The review is continuing,
and no decision has been made'' about closing entirely the plant at
Dagenham, which employs some 4,500 workers producing the Ford
Fiesta compact. Ford announced in February that one shift would be
discontinued, eliminating 1,500 jobs, this summer.
</P>
<P>
   But auto industry executives have been saying for over a month
that Dagenham is likely to be closed when the review is finished.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of another auto industry cutback carries huge
political freight after the government was apparently surprised by
the decision of BMW AG last month to sell its loss-making Rover
Group British subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   BMW of Germany agreed to sell Rover's profitable Land Rover
sport utility vehicle division to Ford. It provoked an uproar with
a separate move to sell Rover's sprawling Longbridge car plant near
Birmingham to Alchemy Partners, a British venture-capital firm that
wants to produce only limited numbers of rebranded MG niche models
and cut thousands of jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, a consortium led by John Towers, a former
Rover chief executive, approached BMW with a $1.3 billion
counterbid intended to maintain mass car production with fewer job
losses among Longbridge's 9,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
   The British government, which said it had no prior knowledge of
BMW's plans to sell Rover, supported the counterbid. But in a
further setback for the government, executives close to the
negotiations said Monday that the Towers-led consortium was
scrambling to meet a BMW deadline to guarantee financing. Helmut
Panke, BMW's chief financial officer, said in an interview last
week that Rover was losing about $3 million a day.
</P>
<P>
   The government's discomfort over the Rover sale has deepened
with the debate over the possible closing of the Dagenham plant,
one of three major Ford plants in Britain. The opposition
Conservatives have already criticized the government for failing to
secure jobs or keep track of developments in the auto industry.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Blair denied that his meeting with Nasser had
been inspired specifically by the prospect of Dagenham's closing.
But she acknowledged that both the prime minister and the
Department of Trade Industry were ``in dialogue'' with Ford over
its review of European operations.
</P>
<P>
   British newspapers reported that Blair had also telephoned Nick
Scheele, the chairman of Ford's European division, who met last
week with labor union officials representing Ford's British work
force.
</P>
<P>
   The labor unions have threatened to call strikes at other Ford
plants in Britain if Dagenham is closed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ford has made steady inroads into the British auto industry in
recent years, buying such prestige marques as Jaguar and Aston
Martin before it acquired the Land Rover division from BMW.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Ford ranks as the top carmaker in Britain, with 12
percent of the market, but its sales fell 3.7 percent last year to
just under 390,000 cars.
</P>
<P>
   Across Europe, moreover, it has been losing market share
steadily. Subcompact rivals like the Volkswagen Polo and Peugeot
206 have outshone the Fiesta, while Ford also failed to anticipate
the shift of the region's market toward more diesel engines and
toward very small minivans like the Renault Scenic.
</P>
<P>
   That has left it with surplus production capacity. A study by
PricewaterhouseCoopers said Ford's European assembly plants run at
72 percent of capacity, compared with 83 percent for General
Motors. In Europe, Ford operates nine major assembly plants
including modernized sites at Cologne, Germany, and at Valencia,
Spain. But the Dagenham plant has had longstanding problems.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has already announced that one of the two shifts at
Dagenham will be eliminated as production of the Ford Focus is
moved to a factory in Cologne.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has singled out Dagenham for three reasons. The strength of
the pound against the single European currency, the euro, Ford
executives say, has made it much more expensive to produce cars in
Britain for export to the rest of Europe _ a reason also cited by
BMW as a cause of its huge losses at Rover, and by the French
carmaker PSA Peugeot Citroen as a threat to its plant in the
British Midlands.
</P>
<P>
   The union at Dagenham, moreover, has resisted labor-saving
production changes that other European unions have been willing to
accept, industry executives say, so the factory has very low
productivity. And the mostly white, unionized workers at Dagenham
have fiercely resisted the hiring of Asian and black workers, in a
dispute that Ford fears could be deeply embarrassing and damaging
to its global reputation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
