<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6101 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-ELIAN-US-HNS &LR;      04-24 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-US-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP LEADERS CALL FOR CONGRESSIONAL INVESTIGATION OF RAID 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican leaders announced the start of a
congressional inquiry Monday into the pre-dawn raid that led to
Elian Gonzalez's reunion with his father, as the White House
angrily accused critics of making ``wild'' and inaccurate
statements about the case.
</P>
<P>
   As the rhetoric heated up, the 6-year-old Cuban boy remained in
seclusion with his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, at Andrews Air
Force Base outside Washington. Elian's Miami relatives continued to
seek a meeting with the boy to assure themselves of his well-being.
</P>
<P>
   One of their attorneys said they would seek a court order in
hopes of forcing Gonzalez to allow them to see the boy.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Cuban-Americans upset over the handling of the case
called for a general strike that would turn Miami into a ``dead
city'' Tuesday, leading dozens of businesses to announce plans to
close.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno said Monday that she had ``no
regrets whatsoever'' about ordering the raid Saturday by federal
agents on the home of the Miami relatives, where Elian has been
staying for nearly five months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm satisfied with the result,'' she said on NBC's ``Today''
program. She said she ``bent over backward'' trying to accommodate
the demands of the boy's Miami relatives. But in the end, she said,
they would not agree to give up total physical custody of the boy
to his father, despite her offer to place them all in the same
compound together to help ensure a smooth transition for Elian.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton felt the raid was ``the right thing to do and
was the only alternative remaining,'' said presidential spokesman
Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this could have been avoided,'' he said. ``None of this
had to happen. This happened because the family did not respect the
legal process here that dictated the father should be reunited with
the young boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno planned to meet Tuesday with Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott, R-Miss., and other lawmakers to hear their complaints about
how the raid was carried out. But aides said Reno would not back
down from her view that the relatives had given her no choice but
to enforce an order issued by the Justice Department nearly two
weeks ago revoking their temporary custody of Elian.
</P>
<P>
   Armed federal agents battered down the door of the relatives'
home early Saturday and snatched the boy in a 3-minute operation
that brought cries of outrage in some circles.
</P>
<P>
   While lawmakers were eager to speak with Reno face-to-face, it
was unlikely that the meeting would quell the call for a
congressional investigation of the raid from Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., announced
that he had ordered his staff to begin a preliminary inquiry into
the tactics used to remove Elian from the home where he had been
staying since he was rescued at sea nearly five months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said the inquiry would focus on ``whether the use of force
was necessary or appropriate under all of the circumstances.'' Hyde
added that information gathered during the course of the inquiry
would determine whether public hearings should be held.
</P>
<P>
   The talk of investigations brought an angry response from the
White House, where Lockhart accused Republicans of ``playing
politics'' with the plight of a 6-year-old boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the American public should not be surprised that
the first reaction from Capitol Hill is ... personal attacks on the
attorney general, personal attacks on the president, and then an
announcement of extensive investigative hearings,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart also took issue specifically with comments made by
House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, who characterized as
illegal the Saturday raid on the Miami home of the Lazaro Gonzalez
family. DeLay said Sunday that the Justice Department had not
sought a court order beforehand authorizing them to take action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom DeLay went on television ... and said that there was no
warrant in this case ... It's factually not true and easily
knowable _ if you're not trying to play politics,'' Lockhart said
</P>
<P>
   DeLay spokesman Jonathon Baron dismissed Lockhart's comments as
``political rhetoric'' aimed at taking the focus off ``an
inexcusable action'' against Elian's Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was absolutely no reason to conduct an armed raid on
this family ... To use armed force against this child and his
family to return a child to communist repression is inexcusable,''
Baron said.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart also characterized as ``absurd'' charges by the boy's
Miami relatives that photographs of him laughing and playing
happily with his father had been ``doctored.'' They have also
asserted that Elian has been ``drugged'' since being taken by
federal authorities in order to prepare him for ``brainwashing'' by
the government of Cuban President Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said Elian ``is living now in a vastly different
environment than he lived in over the last few months. He is with
his father. He is not part of a media circus. He is not being
subjected to the constant attention that must have been so
difficult to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, a group of citizens involved in the last-minute
negotiations, including attorney Aaron Podhurst, a close Reno
friend, criticized the government's gun-wielding seizure of Elian,
saying it believed a negotiated compromise on the transfer of the
boy was at hand.
</P>
<P>
   Podhurst told reporters Reno was on the phone negotiating with
him when the raid took place. Although he thought most of the
issues had been resolved, he said Reno saw it differently.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he refused to join in with others who denounced her
actions, saying that while he disagrees with her decision to send
in armed agents to seize the boy, he still considers her ``a close
friend'' and an ``extraordinarily strong woman'' who believes in
the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
   Associate Deputy Attorney General James Castello said that while
Podhurst and others involved in the 11th-hour negotiations may have
felt that a deal was at hand, ``the fact was that we were not
getting agreement from the family'' on the key demand that physical
custody of the boy would have to be transferred ``immediately ...
and fully'' to his father.
</P>
<P>
   Although Republicans leaders continued to express outrage at the
use of force to reunite Elian with his father, several public
opinion polls indicated that a majority of Americans support the
government's actions even if they disagree with the tactics used in
carrying it out.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
