<SLUG> BC-WIS-ALCOHOL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WISCONSIN IS NO.1 FOR ADULTS CONSUMING ALCOHOL AND BINGE DRINKING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JANESVILLE, Wis. _ Shooting pool as the jukebox played a Beatles
song in a neighborhood tavern, Karl Sorenson put his stick aside
for a moment and grabbed his beer for a deep swallow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to drink,'' said Sorenson, a 36-year-old guitar teacher
with the big-shouldered frame of a construction worker. ``This
one's number five, I think, or is it six?''
</P>
<P>
   For Sorenson, the night was still young. For all of the warnings
about the perils of drinking, Wisconsin is still a place where
drinking beer is regarded as an honored pastime. And Milwaukee,
long the beer capital of America, was home of the Miller, Schlitz
and Pabst breweries, among others. Today, Miller is the last large
brewery in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   In a ranking of states, Wisconsin, where the legal drinking age
is 21, leads the nation in the percentage of adults who drink
alcohol, according to a study at the Centers for Disease Control
and Prevention in Atlanta. The survey found that Wisconsin led all
states in the percentage of adults who said they have had five or
more drinks in a single sitting in the last month, what the authors
of the study called binge drinking.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers in Wisconsin, acknowledging that some of its residents
are drinking too much, last month passed provisions that increase
penalties for drunken driving.
</P>
<P>
   Notable among the civic leaders who testified in favor of
stiffer penalties was John Bowlin, the president and chief
executive officer of Miller Brewing Co., based in Milwaukee.
Bowlin, who is said to be the first brewery chief executive ever to
deliver antidrinking testimony in the Wisconsin Capitol, said there
were ``those who abuse our product and must be targeted.''
</P>
<P>
   The results of the drinking survey came as no surprise to most
Wisconsin residents. The state led the nation in drinking in the
last study, which was conducted in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy Bawden, a lecturer at the University of Wisconsin who
has written about the history of breweries in the Midwest, said
visitors are often surprised by the number of watering holes here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who drives through Wisconsin for the first time says,
`Man, there's a lot of taverns here,''' Bawden said.
</P>
<P>
   Bawden and other scholars say the beer-drinking tradition traces
largely to the German heritage of Wisconsin, a state that claims a
bigger percentage of German-Americans than any other.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every town with a sizable German population had a brewery
early this century. Among German immigrants, Bawden said, beer was
considered something of a temperance drink.
</P>
<P>
   ``Germans were disgusted by the American taverns, which were
filled with men standing around drinking whiskey,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In these German-American communities, he said, beer was
considered a relatively tame refreshment that was available at
virtually every gathering.
</P>
<P>
   To this day, people often drink beer at church-sponsored fish
fries during Lent. And many families in towns leave Mass on Sunday
to sit in a tavern, where neighbors catch up on the week's news and
people play cribbage.
</P>
<P>
   At the University of Wisconsin in Madison, the Rathskeller Bar
in the Memorial Union serves beer to 21-year-old students. Through
the 1970s, even some dormitories had beer bars.
</P>
<P>
   According to the survey, Massachusetts was the state with the
highest percentage of drinkers after Wisconsin. Utah led among the
teetotalers, with only 28 percent of adults saying they sometimes
drink alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the study found rates of drinking to be lower in the
South, a region where churches typically inveigh against alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   To Sorenson, there was no deep mystery about why people drink.
``It's fun,'' he said. ``In Wisconsin, it gets boring, especially
when it's cold.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides that, he said people in the Upper Midwest tended to be
reserved, even stoic, and a few drinks tend to let down there
guard. ``You have a few drinks, you can get a little crazy, and
it's OK,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sorenson acknowledged that he often likes to have more than just
a few drinks. He said he can easily handle a 12-pack of beer.
</P>
<P>
   Becky Kunkel, the bartender at Briggs Tavern in this small
Wisconsin city, said there was an explanation for the ability of
Wisconsin residents to drink large amounts of alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ``We start young,'' she said. ``You go to a graduation in
Wisconsin, there's beer. You go to a sporting event, there's beer.
You go to just about anything in Wisconsin, there's beer.''
</P>
<P>
   For Dawn Johnson, 42, who shared a game of pool with Sorenson,
drinking was a recreation, much like snowmobiling or collecting
stamps.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just something you do to pass the time,'' said Johnson,
who drank a couple of beers, and then knocked back a shot of
tequila.
</P>
<P>
   But alcohol does not always mean fun and games, as Johnson said
she knows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen some pretty bad things that had to do with
alcohol,'' said Johnson, as her smile vanished. ``Not nice at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   She was asked if she had ever considered quitting drinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' she said with a wry smile, ``only about every other
day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
