<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6104 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CLINTON-EMAIL-NYT &LR;      04-24 0310
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EMAIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARCHIVES SUBPOENAED IN WHITE HOUSE E-MAIL INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
   By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Robert W. Ray, the independent counsel
investigating President Clinton, has issued a grand-jury subpoena
to the National Archives seeking help in determining whether the
White House deliberately withheld thousands of e-mail messages from
law-enforcement authorities and Congress, government officials said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the archives, which counsel the executive
branch on record-keeping, said that the subpoena arrived last
Tuesday and that officials were in the process of complying.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have received a grand-jury subpoena from the office of the
independent counsel pertaining to the record-keeping practices of
the executive office of the president,'' said the spokeswoman,
Susan Cooper, a senior archives official.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper declined to elaborate, and the independent counsel's
office had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   Ray's office, as well as the Justice Department, has been
looking into whether the White House deliberately concealed e-mail
messages in response to numerous subpoenas from congressional
committees and the independent counsel. The messages were sought in
connection with several topics, including Clinton's relationship
with Monica Lewinsky and the White House's response to the
investigation of many of its fund-raising efforts.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials have denied any effort to avoid compliance
with subpoenas. They say the problem was caused by malfunctioning
computer systems that failed to store all electronic messages
written to presidential aides from outside the White House.
</P>
<P>
   But investigators are also looking into accusations that White
House officials threatened employees of a government contractor if
they disclosed that the messages were missing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
