<HEADLINE>
COUNTING ON THE CUBANS AND THE MEDIA
</HEADLINE>
  
 
 c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Center for Media and Public Affairs, calling the  &UR; Elian &LR; 
 &UR; Gonzalez  &LR; saga ``a People magazine story with a real political edge
to it,'' counted 273 major network stories on Gonzales from
November 25 through April 13.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison, the 1997 car crash that killed  &UR; Princess Diana &LR; 
has been reported in 200 stories; the crash of JFK Jr.'s plane has
been reported in 161.
</P>
<P>
   The top celebrity story since counters started counting is
 &UR; O.J. Simpson &LR;  and the murders of  &UR; Nicole Simpson &LR;  and  &UR; Ronald &LR; 
 &UR; Goldman &LR; , which was the subject of 431 stories from June 12, 1994,
until the end of that year. Since much has happened in the Gonzalez
case since the center's count was taken, it's possible his story
will surpass the killings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; WEDDING BELLS &QL;  &LR; 
_Picking up on the ``most embarrassing moment'' features _
do-it-yourself candid camera _ springing up everywhere in the
magazine world, the latest issue of Mademoiselle asked readers to
describe ``Wedding Hells.''
</P>
<P>
   One bride's new mother-in-law took guests outside to get stoned,
while guests inside got into a fistfight. ``At one point,'' writes
the bride, ``we were the only couple dancing, and no one was
watching us.'' At another wedding, the bride and groom got lost on
the way to the reception and the groom, says the bride, ``refused
to stop to ask for directions.''
</P>
<P>
   And if you think those incidents were bad, imagine the tough
luck of another: ``My photographer died days before the wedding.''
The assistant filled in, ``but the photos were pretty horrible.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _Many Ozians report that the bumper sticker described here
Monday, April 24, about the falling house was a reference to
Dorothy's house falling on the Wicked Witch of the East in ``The
Wizard of Oz.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ ``(Herb) Caen is described by the San Francisco Office as a &LR; 
 &UR; liar, no good, and a gossip monger, who constantly ridicules the &LR; 
 &UR; United States Government. ... He thrives on secondhand &LR; 
 &UR; information written to suit his own personal distorted sense of &LR; 
 &UR; humor. He thinks he is a master of wit and very funny. In fact, &LR; 
 &UR; he is a no-good, loud-mouthed individual. ... Herb Caen is a &LR; 
 &UR; nitwit columnist.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   From  &UR; Herb Caen &LR; 's FBI file, as revealed in APBnews.com.
</P>
