<HEADER>
A6107 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-POLITICS-NY     04-24 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PANEL TO BEGIN INQUIRY ON SEIZURE OF CUBAN BOY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See alsoCUBAN-BOY, CUBAN-BOY-MIAMI, CUBAN-BOY-FORCE) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Henry Hyde, chairman of the House Judiciary
Committee and chief manager of the impeachment trial of President
Clinton, announced on Monday that his staff would begin a
preliminary investigation into the administration's tactics in
seizing Elian Gonzalez by force.
</P>
<P>
   ``The inquiry will focus on whether the use of such force was
necessary or appropriate under all of the circumstances,'' Hyde
said in a statement released by his office.
</P>
<P>
   While Republican leaders here and around the country continued
on Monday to criticize the raid in Miami on Saturday, most
Democrats rallied around the president, and some were even
relishing the prospect of another congressional investigation. In
the past, every time Republicans have investigated the president,
their popularity has fallen in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   That did not seem to daunt the Republicans in Congress. Sen.
Trent Lott of Mississippi, the Republican leader, summoned Attorney
General Janet Reno to a meeting in the Capitol on Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   And the chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee, Sen. Orrin
Hatch, R-Utah, wrote Reno requesting all documents related to the
application for a search warrant allowing federal agents to raid
the house in Miami where Elian was staying with relatives.
</P>
<P>
   The boy remained with his father on Monday at Andrews Air Force
Base outside of Washington. There was talk about moving the family
to Wye Plantation, a government conference center on the Eastern
Shore of Maryland, but no decision was made.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas went before a television camera and
said he hoped the administration could convince the boy's father,
Juan Miguel Gonzalez, to defect and raise his family in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said: ``Certainly the picture that most of America saw _
that I saw _ of the boy being seized by a marshal who had an
automatic weapon is not what America is about. And I would've hoped
that they could have resolved this through mediation.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore has said nothing in public about the
matter since he issued a brief statement on Saturday that ``this
issue should have been handled through a family court.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said he had ordered the preliminary inquiry at the request
of House Speaker Dennis Hastert. He said a decision on whether to
hold full-scale hearings would depend on the information developed
by his staff.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats seemed delighted by the idea of a Republican
investigation. ``Part of me says, `Please don't throw me in this
briar patch,''' said Sen. Christopher Dodd of Connecticut, a former
general chairman of the Democratic Party. ``Letting the Republicans
run with this is the best thing that could happen to Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   Geoffrey Garin, a Democratic pollster and strategist, said:
``This is the Republicans making the same mistake over again.
There's a very strong likelihood that the public will see this as
just another round of partisan investigations that don't amount to
very much and are completely tangential to what the people care
about, to what's important.''
</P>
<P>
   A CBS News poll conducted Sunday night found that most Americans
believe federal agents were only doing what was necessary to
enforce the law.
</P>
<P>
   Told of Hyde's inquiry, Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Calif., cracked,
``I hope this doesn't preclude Chairman Burton from also doing his
own investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Waxman was referring to Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., who is chairman
of the Government Reform Committee and who has held a series of
highly partisan hearings involving the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Burton called the raid in Miami reckless and added,
``The American people have a right to feel safe and secure in their
own homes.''
</P>
<P>
   A few Democrats also expressed regret. ``When I heard about it,
I was stunned and upset,'' said Sen. Joseph Lieberman of
Connecticut. ``The most important factor should have been to save
the child from one more trauma in his life and to keep the
negotiations going.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Torricelli of New Jersey, chairman of the Democratic
Senatorial Campaign Committee, said he had not yet heard evidence
that it was necessary to have agents in riot gear with automatic
weapons. But Torricelli, who was himself involved last week in the
negotiations to resolve the situation, said he had concluded and
advised the Justice Department that a peaceful settlement was not
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, interviewed on the ``Today'' show on NBC, said, ``I tried
my level best to make sure we avoided this situation. I'm satisfied
with the result.''
</P>
<P>
   So are most Democratic politicians. ``The fact of the matter is,
they were successful,'' said Waxman. ``No one was hurt, no one was
injured and the boy was united with his father.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-00 2041EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
