<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: BASEBALL'S RICHEST AND POOREST 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Four teams played baseball here yesterday. Three of
the teams have the largest payrolls in Major League Baseball based
on average value of all contracts, and the fourth ranks No. 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a blue-collar kind of guy,'' Tom Kelly, manager of the No.
30 Minnesota Twins, said in the visiting clubhouse at Yankee
Stadium before his financially overmatched team played the No. 1
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   But this is what the blue-collar Kelly has to deal with:
</P>
<P>
   Double his team's 2000 payroll of $16.5 million, also No. 30,
and it will not reach the combined Yankees salaries of Bernie
Williams, David Cone and Derek Jeter ($34,357,143). The combined
salaries of the Mets' Mike Piazza and Robin Ventura ($20 million)
exceed the Twins' entire payroll. Kevin Brown alone will earn
nearly as much with Los Angeles this season ($15.7 million) as the
entire Minnesota roster.
</P>
<P>
   How do his players deal with games against teams with salaries
like these?
</P>
<P>
   ``What you fear is your team will be intimidated by one of those
teams,'' Kelly said, ``but I don't think that will be the problem.
I don't think this bunch gets intimidated. I hope I don't have to
eat my words.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly's dinner Monday night was more savory. No. 30 Twins 7, No.
1 Yankees 3.
</P>
<P>
   At Shea Stadium, the No. 3 Mets played host to the No. 2 Dodgers
in a makeup game that was snowed out a couple of weeks ago. The
Dodgers had to stop here en route from Cincinnati to Atlanta and
play the game because they do not play a second series here this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like it, but there's nothing you can do about it,''
said Davey Johnson, the Dodgers' manager, who did not see the only
run of the game because he was ejected moments before the Mets
scored it.
</P>
<P>
   This is Johnson's second season with the Dodgers. The first was
a disaster. The team with an $87.8 million payroll, second only to
the Yankees, finished with a losing record. ``Maybe it was a shock
to you, but it wasn't a shock to me,'' Johnson said. ``When I came
in, the team had basically been put together. There were a lot of
things that didn't fit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' poor performance, coupled with Bobby Valentine's
uncertain status with the Mets, has prompted speculation, at least
on New York talk shows, that through the influence of his good
friend Tommy Lasorda, the Dodgers' senior vice president, Valentine
could wind up in Los Angeles next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could care less about that,'' Johnson said when asked if he
had heard that one. ``I'm not even commenting on that. I don't know
anything about that. Nor do I care. I have my job to do. I don't
try to figure out what's going to happen a year from now, six
months from now, six days from now. There's a challenge here that
I'd like to be able to finish.''
</P>
<P>
   And anyway, he added, this year's team has ``more of the
ingredients for a successful team.'' The Dodgers displayed some of
those ingredients during the weekend in Cincinnati, pummeling the
Reds by a composite three-game score of 36 to 7. But Pat Mahomes,
an emergency starter, and three Mets relief pitchers shut off the
Dodgers' run spigot.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Twins, Mahomes, one of the lowest-paid Mets at
$750,000, was not intimidated by the higher-paid hitters he faced.
Twice he struck out Shawn Green, at $14 million a year the
second-highest paid player in baseball, and three times he retired
Gary Sheffield, a $9 million player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw some balls where I really wanted to throw them,'' said
Mahomes, who explained that he couldn't do that when he pitched for
the Twins in the early years of his career. ``When I was over
there, I was young. I threw the ball 96, 97 miles an hour. I'd just
rear back and throw it. Now I tend to locate the ball a lot better.
I didn't know how to pitch when I was there. Now I know how to
pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   What's the difference between playing for the Twins and playing
for the Mets? ``Obviously, big market, small market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to figures sent to clubs last week by the labor
relations department in the commissioner's office, the Yankees have
a $98.8 million payroll based on the annual average value of
contracts, the Dodgers $97.7 million and the Mets $92.1 million.
They are the only teams at $90 million or higher. The Twins are
last at $18.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``On paper why even play the game?'' Jacque Jones, one of the
young Twins, said after their conquest of the Yankees. ``But that's
why you play the game. On paper we're supposedly the worst team in
the league, but we don't think so. It doesn't matter what's written
or what anyone else thinks as long as we believe.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-00 2042EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000424.0387 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
