r f BC-BIOSCOPE-COLUMN-SFCHR     04-24 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOSCOPE-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BIOSCOPE: HEARINGS ON STEM CELL RESEARCH THE START OF LONG DEBATE  &HT;     By TOM ABATE 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Congress will enter one of biotechnology's
ethical minefields this week, when a Senate committee considers
whether the government should fund stem cell research.
</P>
<P>
   Stem cells produce other types of specialized cells. The human
embryo contains the most potent stem cells. They can make every
nerve, bone and fiber in you or me.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, scientists have begun trying to control stem
cells to make them grow specific tissue, such as nerve cells to
repair a severed spinal cord.
</P>
<P>
   But the prospect of turning human embryos into spare parts
factories touched a nerve in Congress, which several years ago
banned federal funding for such research. That ban did nothing to
stop private firms like Menlo Park's Geron Corp. from paying for
their own stem cell experiments.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Pennsylvania Sen. Arlen Specter will hold hearings
on a bill to restore federal funding for stem cell research. His
star witness will be actor Christopher Reeve, paralyzed in a riding
accident, and now a candidate for the sort of therapy that might
one day come from stem cell experiments.
</P>
<P>
   So long as stem cells come from embryos it's difficult to
separate that discussion from the abortion debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think you can be consistently pro-choice and still have
a problem with producing human embryos for experimental purposes,''
says Stuart Newman, a cell biologist at New York Medical College in
Valhalla, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Newman is a member of the Council for Responsible Genetics, a
scientific watchdog group that says the debate over federal funding
misses the point: Whether it is public or private dollars that
finance the experiment, the real ethical concern is how embryos are
obtained.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, embryos for stem cell experiments would be leftovers
from in-vitro fertilization, Newman said. He fears that, in the
absence of federal laws, embryos will become items of trade,
produced to order for stem cell experiments.
</P>
<P>
   Specter's bill would prevent federally funded stem cell
researchers from knowingly buying embryos that are sold for
profit-making purposes. Newman said those same sorts of rules
should also be enforced on private labs.
</P>
<P>
   The Biotechnology Industry Organization isn't anxious for
additional regulation of the private firms it represents. It says
the U.S. Food &AMP; Drug Administration supervises privately funded
experiments. BIO doesn't want private firms to be regulated by
other ethical oversight bodies that Congress might set up, so long
as the private firms don't take public bucks.
</P>
<P>
   The politics of this issue are complex enough so that nothing is
likely to happen to change the status quo in an election year. But
the issue of how we control the traffic in human parts is not going
away.
</P>
<P>
   NEW MONEY: This week, several veteran financiers will formally
announce the creation of a $250 million health care fund called
Versant Ventures. Its nine principals include Ross Jaffe, formerly
of Brentwood Capital, and Sam Colella and Beckie Robertson, who
hailed from Institutional Venture Partners.
</P>
<P>
   Colella said when Versant _ the word means experienced,
practiced, conversant _ started raising money last fall, biotech
was a contrarian play. ``It was prior to the big boom,'' he said.
``VCs were leaving health care and life sciences.''
</P>
<P>
   Biotech stocks have since soared and retreated, but despite the
short-term fluctuations, the partners think they're in the right
place at the right time. ``There's a dearth of investment funding
in early stage health care,'' Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
   Jaffe said Versant plans to do 10 to 15 deals a year, in four
broad areas: medical devices, biotech, medical services and
e-health.
</P>
<P>
   Their Web site already lists five deals, and when this reporter
joined them for a conference call, he interrupted a discussion of
how to respond to a sixth potential deal.
</P>
<P>
   GENOME ENVY?: My sharp-eyed colleague, science writer David
Perlman, spotted a curious advertisement in the Puritan's Pride
vitamin catalog, for RNA and DNA tablets ``which nutritionists are
excited about.''
</P>
<P>
   I asked Larry Sasich, a pharmacist with Ralph Nader's Public
Citizen Health Research Group, whether he was excited about RNA and
DNA pills.
</P>
<P>
   Although it was a long-distance call, I could imagine him
shaking his head in disgust. Sasich wasn't aware of any condition
that would require supplemental amounts of RNA or DNA. Every cell
of any food imaginable contains DNA. Every time we take a bite, we
get a mouthful of DNA.
</P>
<P>
   ``This just seems to be aimed at the most gullible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A call to the nutritionist at Puritan's Pride went unreturned.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Tom Abate at abate(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-00 2042EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000424.0388 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6111 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-ORPHANAGE-SPINOFF-SFC     04-24 1622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORPHANAGE-SPINOFF-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 INDUSTRIAL LIGHT AND MAGIC ALUMS START DIGITAL REVOLUTION  &HT;     By KELLY ZITO 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ After years of watching their names roll by in
the credits of films like ``Jurassic Park'' and ``Star Wars:
Episode I _ The Phantom Menace,'' Scott Stewart, Stuart Maschwitz
and Jonathan Rothbart last year left Industrial Light and Magic,
George Lucas' special-effects powerhouse, to form the Orphanage.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not exactly what you might think.
</P>
<P>
   Like the dozens of Lucasfilm spin-offs that dot the Bay Area,
the Orphanage does visual effects work for larger companies. But
this Gen X trio doesn't want to become a de facto contractor for
Hollywood bigwigs. Ultimately, they want to compete with the
bigwigs on both the big and little screens, as more companies like
DreamWorks SKG make forays onto the Web.
</P>
<P>
   With a business model that relies on special-effects jobs, Web
content and digital video _ an increasingly important facet of the
film industry _ they just might become one of the few
visual-effects firms to successfully move into producing feature
films.
</P>
<P>
   ``That crossover is just starting to happen,'' said Mark
Fishkin, executive director of the Film Institute of Northern
California in Mill Valley. ``When you look at the mingling of
Internet, technology and the people involved in the creative arena,
you're getting people who look at the industry in new ways.''
</P>
<P>
   With more directors shooting films using bits and bytes instead
of staggeringly expensive film stock (``Star Wars: Episode II''
will be shot digitally), people and companies with digital
movie-making expertise are in demand.
</P>
<P>
   Pair that with the vast maw for quality entertainment on the
Internet, and companies like the Orphanage that straddle art and
technology are seeing more venues for their work, Fishkin said.
</P>
<P>
   Take San Francisco's Shockwave.com. The entertainment site
recently signed ``Batman'' director Tim Burton and ``South Park''
creators Matt Stone and Trey Parker to create separate animated
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at these Internet cinema companies, they need good
material; they need a `Sopranos,' '' Stewart said. ``We want to be
the company that creates that.'' That approach to the Web, their
digital filmmaking chops and the fact that they can whip up a
visual-effects shot of a helicopter blowing up an entire floor of a
San Francisco hotel, has already helped the Orphanage land some
relatively high-profile deals in the indie film world _ an arena
better known for filmmakers who max out 14 credit cards in order to
finance their dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the Orphanage signed a $20 million deal to
co-produce a dozen or so feature-length, low-budget films with New
York's GreeneStreet Films, producer of 1998's ``Illuminata.''
</P>
<P>
   On its own, the Orphanage has produced four shorts _ shot on
digital video rather than traditional film _ and worked on two
films that were shown at this year's Sundance Film Festival. They
provided post-production for ``G,'' a film chronicling a camera's
30,000-foot descent from a plane without a parachute, and produced
their own digital documentary on the making of ``G,'' titled
``Falling.''
</P>
<P>
   Its films may not break the box office tally of ``Titanic,'' but
the Orphanage is one of the companies breaking the mold for the
traditional visual-effects firm. Others include Alameda, Calif.'s
Manex Entertainment, the special-effects house that recently won an
Oscar for ``The Matrix.'' In addition to creating the illusion of a
gravity-defying Keanu Reeves, the company produces its own films
and rents out its soundstages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the profit margins are so minimal and the competition
is so tough in visual-effects work, many companies are taking their
technical expertise and their storytelling ability and looking to
develop their own content,'' said Tom Atkin, executive director of
the Visual Effects Society in Santa Monica, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The Orphanage principals obviously like to tout their digital
video abilities. But they also have a healthy respect for the
artistic.
</P>
<P>
   One of their favorite topics is ``What We Talk About When We
Talk About Love'' a 10-minute drama based on a Raymond Carver short
story. Produced by the Orphanage and directed by Stewart, it
chronicles a conversation between two couples about the thin line
between love and obsession.
</P>
<P>
   The three don't eschew spacecraft or explosions, but they think
many movies are bloated, special-effects vehicles devoid of strong
plot and characters.
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason why they left ILM.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt like being part of a giant machine,'' Maschwitz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Films like the ones that inspired us as kids didn't seem to be
coming through the door anymore,'' Stewart added.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, and a nod toward the ``Dickensian notion of
self-invention,'' Stewart and Rothbart invested several thousand
dollars of their own money, named their new venture ``The
Orphanage'' (Maschwitz joined later) and set up shop in the
International School in San Francisco, where dance troupes happily
thump around overhead, and an elevator man ferries people from
floor to floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted it to be a place for the disenfranchised, for
artists or filmmakers who want to create but who don't want to work
for the man anymore,'' Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   Another founding principal of the company: immersion in all
things technological. And that doesn't mean just crafting digital
space pods, but using computers to do everything film-related.
</P>
<P>
   The computer language of zeros and ones is largely expected to
explode in popularity as a film medium, in part because celluloid
is much more expensive than hard drive space.
</P>
<P>
   However, despite improving technology and cheaper digital
cameras, relatively few mainstream filmmakers have made the leap
because much of the other digital infrastructure isn't in place
yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The convergence of digital production, distribution and
exhibition isn't really there yet,'' Fishkin said. ``But it is
changing quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Stewart, indie circle heavyweights like Richard
Linklater, the auteur behind ``Slacker'' and ``Dazed and
Confused,'' regularly call them with questions about how to work
with digital video (they're working on a project now with
Linklater).
</P>
<P>
   That kind of buzz garnered the attention of GreeneStreet Films.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expertise we have in terms of producing low-budget films
complemented the expertise they have in the effects area, and we
liked the fact that they can make their films more exciting with
special effects without dramatic increase in costs,'' said Chris
Uetwiller, head of production at GreeneStreet's digital film
division.
</P>
<P>
   Because independent filmmakers are often working with budgets in
the tens of thousands rather than tens of millions, special-effects
work is frequently out of the question, according to Fishkin.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Orphanage can create (special effects) for a fraction
of the cost, that's a huge benefit for independent filmmakers,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   And that translates directly into the product itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can make a film for less money, you can stay truer to
yourself because the risks aren't so great,'' Fishkin said. ``And
it doesn't have to appeal to the lowest common denominator'' to
recoup its costs.
</P>
<P>
   One of the ways the Orphanage adds special effects inexpensively
is the fact that they don't invest a ton of money in gear, says
Maschwitz.
</P>
<P>
   While at ILM, Maschwitz and Stewart were members of the Rebel
Mac Unit, a small faction of artists who used off-the-shelf
software and hardware.
</P>
<P>
   They've brought that same sensibility to the Orphanage, where
they made the 20-minute ``Last Birthday Card,'' an action/comedy
about competing hit men in San Francisco (which featured the
helicopter shot) for about $6,000. If made by traditional means,
the film would have cost several hundred thousand dollars, they
estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, Maschwitz and Rothbart hope to bring that
cost-consciousness to both GreeneStreet Films and for-hire
special-effects work, which will largely help pay the bills,
including the rent on their new, 1,200-square-foot offices in the
Presidio, which they hope will house 10 staffers by the end of May.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Orphanage principals wouldn't discuss the company's
finances, they did say they made a slim profit last year and expect
to widen that margin this year.
</P>
<P>
   For companies like the Orphanage, ``there's no hard formula,''
says Atkin. ``Some will sign deals with big companies, just like
the dot-com companies, and there will be others that fall through
the cracks.''
</P>
<P>
   Some ILM alums, like Scott Ross, one of the co-founders of
Digital Domain in Southern California, have enjoyed incredible
success. Others, like Richard Edlund, haven't. His Boss Film
Studios went belly up in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Orphanage founders take an optimistic view of their future,
pointing to other Bay Area companies that have managed to combine
technology with an independent streak born of operating outside the
Hollywood system.
</P>
<P>
   Pixar Animation Studios, the Lucasfilm spin-off behind the
successful ``Toy Story'' and ``A Bug's Life'' movies, is one of
their favorite role models.
</P>
<P>
   Pixar once performed visual-effects work for others, then
focused on shorts and has now shifted almost totally to making
their own animated films under an agreement with Disney.
</P>
<P>
   Like Pixar, the Orphanage's founders want to make films whose
stunning visuals are second only to clever, smart stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make movies my parents want to see,'' Stewart said,
``instead of, `Well, the dinosaurs looked cool.' ''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kelly Zito at  &LR; kzito(AT)sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
