<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH21-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 TECH21: JUDGE SHOULD FORCE MICROSOFT TO PUBLISH CODE FOR WINDOWS  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Breaking Microsoft or imposing restrictions on
its business practices might be effective ways to prevent Gates &AMP;
Co. from expanding their monopoly into new areas, but they won't do
anything to reduce the overwhelming dominance of Windows in PC
operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   Even splitting the company into multiple ``Baby Bills,'' each
with the right to market all of the current company's products,
won't do that. Competition of that sort might result in lower
prices, but it wouldn't create any new alternatives to Windows or
bolster the chances of existing alternatives such as Linux or BeOS.
On the contrary, lower prices for Windows would actually make it
all the more difficult for challengers to gain any ground.
</P>
<P>
   Some would argue that this is a lost cause _ that Windows is so
firmly established as the OS standard that nothing the judge could
do would really reopen the desktop market.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, but I think it's worth a try. It seems to me that one
relatively simple step would go a long way in this direction: Make
Microsoft publish, or at least license on reasonable terms, the
Windows application programming interfaces (APIs), together with
all the supporting code libraries that are needed to make Windows
applications run, to current or future developers of alternative
operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   After all, as the good judge argued so convincingly in his
``findings of fact'' last fall, the key to Microsoft's power is
``the applications barrier to entry.'' Few users choose Windows
because it manages hardware so efficiently, and even fewer, I'm
sure, because it's so stable and reliable. People need it because
it's required for most of the applications they want to run.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the case of IBM's OS/2. Technically, it was far
superior to the Windows versions available at the time, but it
couldn't run Windows 95 applications, and that killed it.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, most people don't pick Windows at all _ they get it
simply because it's what comes with a PC. But any PC-maker
contemplating switching to an alternative would have to face the
fact that such a move would instantly cost it most of its
customers, because its machines would no longer run the programs
they want and need.
</P>
<P>
   Now suppose Microsoft had to disclose the code and technical
information Windows applications require, and to keep doing so as
it developed new versions. Linux distributors, Be and anyone else
who wanted to play _ maybe even IBM again _ could incorporate that
code into their systems, making it possible for customers to run
off-the-shelf (and off-the-Web) Windows applications in these
alternative environments, without rebooting, adding emulation
software or any other special burdens.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, this wouldn't trigger any large-scale abandonment of
Windows; if nothing else, inertia would prevent that. But other OS
developers would at least have a chance to demonstrate the merits
of their products without asking customers to give up all the
applications they depend on.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, that might lead to some real competition to Windows _
and isn't that what the case was supposed to be about in the first
place?
</P>
<P>
   STAYING IN SYNC: If you deal with two PCs _ a desktop and a
notebook, or a work machine and one at home _ you probably know
already that keeping your calendar, contacts and other critical
information in sync is a challenge. It's even tougher if you work
on multiple platforms _ a PC at work, say, and an iMac at home. And
with the proliferation of ``post-PC'' digital devices _ cell
phones, PDAs, information appliances and what have you _ the
problem is only getting worse.
</P>
<P>
   That's why I was delighted to come across the Web site of a San
Jose, Calif., startup called FusionOne. Its whole business plan is
based on solving the synchronization problem, and it has attracted
some impressive partners. Early financing came from 3Com and Nokia,
among others. Hewlett-Packard, EMC and a long list of well-known
venture-capital groups recently joined them in a third round of
funding worth $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   The free service is in beta testing, but it's open to anyone and
it seems to work fine, though slowly at times. When you first sign
up, you specify what kinds of information you want it to sync _ it
can handle files and folders as well as calendar and contact
information. The data is then copied to FusionOne's servers (run by
Sun Microsystems) in 128-bit encrypted form, which the company says
it couldn't read even if it wanted to. As you enter new data,
within the categories you've set, the changes are automatically
sent to the server whenever you're online.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the only desktop operating system FusionOne's
synchronization software runs on is Windows (95, 98 and NT), but
Mac and Linux versions are in the works. But your data is available
on the Web from any browser on any platform.
</P>
<P>
   The system also works with Palm devices and, via Outlook for
Windows, Windows CE. As for phones, the only formats that currently
support wireless synching are WAP and GSM, which aren't yet widely
used in this country. But with a cable and software developed by an
Estonian company FusionOne recently acquired, it'll be able to
transfer data to and from 150 types of phones, including analog as
well as digital models.
</P>
<P>
   FusionOne doesn't have this market to itself. Puma Technology, a
longtime leader in desktop synchronization, has announced, but not
yet launched, a Web site called Intellisync.com. Motorola's
StarFish subsidiary and others are also contenders. ``Internet
desktop'' sites like Visto.com and Desktop.com offer some of the
same capabilities. And an industry consortium, which includes
FusionOne, is developing a new standard, called SyncML, that may
someday make it easier for others to get in the game.
</P>
<P>
   But FusionOne is up and running already, and it's filling a real
need. Check it out _  &LR; www.fusionone.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   LOCKDOWN FOLLOW-UP: Like most 1.0 releases, last week's first
run of this column didn't go exactly as planned. The main problem:
I wrote too much for the space available, and some useful
information ended up on the newsroom floor.
</P>
<P>
   So this week, I want to go back to the subject of software
firewalls, programs that can protect your computer from hackers and
other uninvited guests. First, a bit more about the ShieldsUp Web
site ( &LR; grc.com/x/ &LR;   &LR; ne.dll?bh0bkyd2 &LR; ), cited last week as an
excellent resource. Run by Steve Gibson, a well-known PC
programming wiz, it offers lots of clearly presented information on
security problems and solutions.
</P>
<P>
   But what really makes it special is software built right into
the page that quickly tests your PC for security vulnerabilities.
Just click on the Test My Shields! and Probe My Ports! buttons, and
in a minute or two you'll see the results.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson also offers detailed assessments of a number of software
firewalls ( &LR; grc.com/su-firewalls.htm &LR; ).) Although he used to be
partial to BlackICE, the program I wrote about last week, he and
other users who've posted reports at his site have found some flaws
in it.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he now recommends another program, ZoneAlarm 2.1 from
San Francisco's Zone Labs. Among other merits, it comes at a great
price: It's free for personal and nonprofit use and just $19.95 for
business use. You can download a copy at  &LR; www.zonelabs.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   None of these programs runs on the Mac, but I know of two others
that do: OpenDoor Networks' DoorStop
( &LR; www2.opendoor.com/doorstop/ &LR; ) and Intego's NetBarrier. DoorStop
is available in several versions, but the ``Personal Edition'' is
$59; NetBarrier is $74.95. OpenDoor, which is headed by a former
Apple networking guru, also provides a useful white paper about Mac
Internet security issues at  &LR; www2.opendoor.com/doorstop &LR; 
 &LR; /macOSsecurity.html &LR; . And you can find out still more about the
problem at a site called SecureMac ( &LR; www.securemac.com &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at  &LR; hnorr &LR; (AT)s &LR; fgate.com &LR; .
</P>
