<HEADER>
A6116 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     04-24 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 Copyright 2000 Chronicle Publishing Company 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANOTHER DAY OLDER AND DEEPER IN DEBT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In a responsible effort to stay financially afloat, the
 &UR; Duchess of York &LR;  hawks goods and services for firms that come up
with enough dough. What else is a mother to do to keep her
daughters out of the poorhouse?
</P>
<P>
   All the same, Personals resists becoming an advertisement, too.
So:
</P>
<P>
   Sarah, the Duchess of York, national spokeswoman for some china
company or other, will be at some department store or other in the
East Bay on May 11.
</P>
<P>
   - One of the recent accomplishments of  &UR; Linda Tripp &LR; , reports
the Washington Monthly, is organizing the mailing of Department of
Defense Military Funeral Honors kits to funeral directors. Tripp
works for the government's Defense Manpower Data Center, which pays
her $98,744 a year.
</P>
<P>
   - Shopping in Washington, D.C., Personals spy  &UR; Emma Kahn  &LR; saw
 &UR; Rick Rockwell &LR; , has-been celebrity of the moment, step up to the
supermarket cash register. ``Ain't you that millionaire?'' the
clerk asked him, as other shoppers speculated on the chances of
finding a millionaire at the Safeway.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Garen  &LR; and  &UR; Shari Staglin &LR;  of the Napa Valley, who own
vineyards and wine labels but do not make wine, told Civilization
magazine about their many sidelines:
</P>
<P>
   They rented their spread as a set for ``The Parent Trap''; they
stage an annual classical musical concert to raise money for mental
illness research; they host lunches for ``CEOs and other corporate
brass''; and they help raise money for  &UR; Robert &LR; 
 &UR; Mondavi &LR; 's planned wine and food center in Napa. ``Wine is about
all these things,'' Garen told the magazine. ``When you say you
have had dinner with Garen and Shari, and talked about `The Parent
Trap,' you have had a whole reinforcing experience. ... We've got a
lot of lifestyle here.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLORA AND FAUNA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Garden Design magazine reveals that two years ago, when San
Francisco's Strybing Arboretum created a new garden, chains
securing rare plants were buried underground.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could grow 500 varieties of orchids here out of doors,''
horticulture manager  &UR; Don Mahoney  &LR; told the magazine. ``But if I
put out an orchid in bloom, it's gone in 24 hours.''
</P>
<P>
   The arboretum decided not to replant a bonsai nursery, says the
story, when all 40 of its plants were stolen, in the third burglary
in as many years.
</P>
<P>
   - Don't try this on public transportation: Natural Health
magazine says that some people believe that urinating on your feet
may cure athlete's foot, but others insist ``you need to soak your
feet in a basin of urine for several days.''
</P>
<P>
   - At demonstrations against the International Monetary Fund in
Washington last week, filmmaker  &UR; Michael Moore &LR;  announced that he
is running a potted plant, a ficus, against Rep. - After Personals'
reports of Peanuts, the missing Richmond District parrot who
imitates pagers and telephones, a Redwood City woman called to say
the bird had been outside her window last week, keeping her up all
night with repeated ``telephone rings.'' Further trackings should
be reported here.
</P>
