<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6117 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-LOS-ANGELES-AR     04-24 1272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-LOS-ANGELES-ART-$ADV30-2600(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE ART-FILLED DAYS IN LOS ANGELES WIN OVER AN INVETERATE NEW
YORKER
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(For release on Sunday, April 30) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In theory I can drive, and I have a license to prove it; in real
life my motor skills are pretty much limited to walking. By nature
I am a vampire, not crazy about daylight, much less direct rays of
the sun. These are just two of the reasons I had never warmed up to
Los Angeles.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I was wrong, of course, as I learned in January when a business
trip took me to California. On a day when the wind chill in New
York was 17 degrees below zero, I was having lunch by the pool at
the elegant Ritz-Carlton Hotel in Pasadena, surrounded by palm
trees and calm. Another afternoon I sneaked away to the nearby
Norton Simon Museum, filled with van Goghs and Cezannes. I returned
to New York thinking of all the art I had never seen on the other
coast. And so I went back to Los Angeles this month for a long
weekend of art gazing. The trip would not be a hunt for history's
greatest paintings but an immersion in a different cultural
experience.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Could I get around by taxi? (Yes, easily though not cheaply.)
Would I find works that I loved? (Yes, especially when I wasn't
looking for them.) Most pressing, in the land of cars and sun,
could I banish a devilish voice that kept whispering in my ear,
like some reject from an old Woody Allen movie, ``Why did you leave
New York?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In three crammed days I discovered that art viewing around Los
Angeles has its own relaxed indoor-outdoor atmosphere. At the
extravagant Huntington Library, Museum and Botanical Gardens,
visitors wander through acres of gardens, stopping in when they
choose at the four exhibition buildings. Meandering in and out also
describes a visit to the Getty Center, with its multilevel complex
of Richard Meier buildings, Robert Irwin-designed garden and
spectacular hilltop views. That indoor-outdoor pattern was one of
the trip's revelations and delights.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Friday's rocky start proved that serendipity shapes any quick
trip. I headed to downtown Los Angeles and the Geffen Contemporary,
the larger of the Museum of Contemporary Art's two locations. Signs
in the window said ``Closed for Installation.'' Closed for two
weeks. The online listings I had consulted, most usefully, hadn't
mentioned this; the efficient concierge at my hotel, the Peninsula
Beverly Hills, hadn't been aware of it.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My luck changed when the taxi drove on to MOCA's main building,
many blocks away. There I found a show by one of my favorite video
artists, Tony Oursler, known for haunting installations that
question the way television and video rule our lives. Ragdoll-like
figures have faces and ranting voices projected by video onto their
cloth heads; one lies under a flowered sofa that looks as if it was
salvaged from the set of Roseanne's old sitcom. Seen so near
Hollywood, these mischievous installations seemed like subversive
agents in the land of show biz. (Still, the New Yorker's voice in
my ear pointed out how many labels acknowledged Metro Pictures, a
Chelsea gallery I can walk to.)  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A smaller selection of works from the permanent collection
included a room of Mark Rothkos, a room of Franz Klines, and
several Robert Rauschenberg combines worth lingering over. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After lunch in MOCA's pleasant courtyard restaurant, Patinette
(with fresh salads and sandwiches), I headed for Santa Monica and
Bergamot Station, a trendy complex of galleries lined up in two
long, low industrial buildings that used to be storage sheds. There
were some standouts among the two dozen galleries, including
Patricia Faure and Patricia Correia. But galleries are always hit
or miss. Especially for a weekend tourist, Bergamot is primarily
about its mall-like, something-for-everyone experience, with
corrugated metal buildings, asphalt parking lot, and works that run
from mediocre to cutting-edge lined up side by side.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That night I met an old friend for dinner at Mimosa, a French
bistro in West Hollywood with photographs and mirrors lining the
walls, and comfy banquettes. Its version of country cooking is
refreshingly light (a delicious tomato tart). When I mentioned that
on my January trip I had liked Los Angeles for the first time, my
friend said, ``That's because you were in Pasadena.'' Oh. One
reason I'm a bad driver is that I'm really bad at geography.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday I saw the difference. The landscape on the way to
San Marino and the Huntington changed as the city limits and its
high-rise bank buildings were left behind, and a greener view of
hills appeared. (The $60 cab fare was the steepest of the weekend;
most fares around town were in the $15 to $20 range.)  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I spent the better part of the day at the Huntington, the
highlight of the trip. Formerly the home of the 19th-century
railroad mogul Henry Huntington, the estate represents the upside
of robber baron wealth. In glorious 80-degree weather, I wandered
on a path that led to the Camellia Garden, which looked like a
scene from ``Alice in Wonderland,'' with pink, white and red
camellias. The red Captain Rawes, a placard said, was named for the
English sea captain who carried it to England from China in 1820.
</P>
<P>
   The most elaborate of the 15 gardens may be the Japanese, with
its fish pond, bonsai, bamboo trees and model teahouse. The
Shakespeare garden includes plants and flowers named in the works.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As I strolled aimlessly along these elegant paths, one led to
``The Art of Bloomsbury'' in the newly opened Boone gallery, once
Henry Huntington's garage. It is a jewel of an exhibition, brought
over from the Tate in London. Though the Bloomsbury group was
instrumental in introducing Post-Impressionism to England, its
mystique owes more to its Bohemian love affairs and literary
biography. The exhibition's surprises include the lucid greens in
Duncan Grant's ``Self-Portrait in a Turban'' from 1910 (according
to Virginia Woolf, the year ``human nature changed''). There is
Vanessa Bell's mordant, brightly colored portrait of Lytton
Strachey, and Grant's pensive view of the pregnant Bell. She was
carrying his child; he was gay; no wonder she looks sad. I found
Bell's ``Studland Beach'' to be an exhilarating discovery, a
mysterious, evocative painting with wide swaths of midnight blue
and sand colors, and figures with their backs to the viewer.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The main building, the neo-Classical Huntington Gallery (once
the mansion where Henry lived with his wife, Arabella), holds a
feast of tapestries, decorative arts and portraits by Gainsborough,
Reynolds and Romney. The central gallery is a long, dramatic room
under a skylight, with 20 full-length 18th-century portraits. The
most famous, Gainsborough's ``Blue Boy'' and Sir Thomas Lawrence's
``Pinkie,'' stare at each other from opposite walls. But the others
are just as resonant, including Reynolds' `` Siddons as the Tragic
Muse.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The smaller, Scott Gallery holds American decorative arts,
paintings and sculpture from the 18th through the 20th century, and
the library's rare books include a Gutenberg Bible and a 1410
illuminated manuscript of Chaucer's ``Canterbury Tales.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After such an immersion in history, it made sense to repair,
like a proper gentlewoman, to the Rose Garden Tearoom, a small
building with a view of the rose arbor, serving a full English tea.
(Don't try this without a reservation.) (MORE)
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of the afternoon, there would be time to dash to
the Norton Simon, not far away, and sprint through. But because I
had been there so recently I headed back to Beverly Hills and the
galleries near my hotel. The Peninsula has a traditional, country
club atmosphere, with furniture of dark, polished wood. But the
armoire in the good-sized room hid a VCR and television, and the
hotel's service and location were ideal. A vase of roses appeared
shortly after I arrived. Housekeepers seemed to come every five
minutes (actually three times a day). And I soon found a favorite
spot, sitting under an umbrella in the Roof Garden, the peaceful
rooftop restaurant by the pool and spa.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I had been greeted with the information that the hotel offers
free limousine service within Beverly Hills and the adjacent
Century City, but I never needed it. The Peninsula is just a few
blocks from Rodeo Drive and Wilshire Boulevard's shopping district,
and I played the New Yorker by walking. Turning onto Rodeo, I was
instantly drawn into the Martin Lawrence gallery, displaying
Picasso's Vollard Suite, with its whimsical etchings of artists'
studios and mythological creatures. There was little time left to
visit the other galleries that dot the neighborhood.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At dinner that night in the hotel restaurant, the Belvedere
(very Peninsula, staid but good), I read a small book I had picked
up at the Huntington: ``A Lady's Guide to Perfect Gentility,''
published in 1856. ``Be careful,'' the guide warned, ``how you
indulge in sarcasm. If you are constitutionally inclined to this,
you will find that there is no point in your character which needs
to be more faithfully guarded.'' Why did this passage make me
pause? Could it be I was easing into California? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While I was preparing for the trip, nothing had elicited such
violently different responses as the question, ``Should I go to the
Getty?'' I'd heard that it was too crowded and no longer crowded,
that the architecture had to be seen and could be skipped. Ruth
Bachofner, owner of one of the most inviting Bergamot galleries,
had decided things when she said, ``You have to go; it's the
contemporary Acropolis.'' It is; it is also slightly Disney.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The experience begins with a ride on the tram, as they call it,
a train that carries all visitors from the entry level up a hill to
the main buildings. There, smiling employees in blue vests point
you in the right direction. They didn't sing ``It's a Small
World,'' but I was ready. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet when I entered the courtyard surrounded by gleaming Meier
buildings, this became an experience I wouldn't have missed. I
looked down on the city from several angles, and at the garden with
its huge spiral of flowers. Descending, I walked among its stones
and across bridges, over water running downhill over rocks. It was
surprisingly soothing.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And there was a charming exhibition of a new acquisition,
``Carmontelle's Transparency: An 18th-Century Motion Picture.''
Carmontelle, who designed the Parc Monceau in Paris, was also
commissioned by the Duc d'Orleans to produce portraits and
theatrical performances. His ``transparency'' is a delicate
watercolor and gouache on a scroll of translucent paper about 12
feet long. Called ``Figures Walking in a Parkland,'' it includes
scenes of boats, figures on horseback, men and women gathered under
trees. Walking by the scroll from left to right, you can imagine a
boat passing behind a hill as the river bends. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But that's not how it was meant to be viewed. The scroll was
placed in an illuminated box with handles, then rolled from one
side to the other; each backlighted scene passed through the frame
like a graceful comic strip set in motion. A reproduction in an
illuminated box lets you scroll through as Carmontelle did.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I found one work to adore in the collection (more than I hope
for in most museums). Munch's ``Starry Night'' (1893) is a
near-abstract, deep-blue painting of a coastline. The day before, I
had noticed that the wall label for Bell's ``Studland Beach''
mentioned Munch's influence on that work; here, with good fortune I
could never have planned, was the breathtaking evidence.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Getty had not been crowded when I arrived at 11 on Sunday
morning, after an easy 15-minute ride from the hotel. And though it
was filling up when I left at 1, it was not uncomfortably jammed.
Too bad my next stop was.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ''Pharaohs of the Sun: Akhenaten, Nefertiti, Tutankhamen'' at
the Los Angeles County Museum of Art, downtown, is the kind of
blockbuster show that calls for a ticket with an entry time. The
galleries were so packed (a weekend liability) it was nearly
impossible to see. And this exhibition demands more than cursory
attention. It is quite historical for a blockbuster, short on gold
and long on elegant funerary statues. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Disappointed, I fled the crowds and walked through Lacma's
permanent galleries. It was late Sunday afternoon and even on a
crammed weekend you have to know when you're just walking, not
seeing. When I arrived at a gallery filled with teacups and saucers
called ``Art of the Cup,'' I knew I had reached my saturation
point. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I may have been through with art, but I wasn't through with L.A.
In a perfect Hollywood ending, I had dinner with friends in the
enclosed courtyard at Spago Beverly Hills. Some showbiz cliches are
true; Wolfgang Puck's food lived up to its hype. I bypassed
``Wolfgang's Childhood Favorites'' (Wiener schnitzel in Beverly
Hills?), and chose an incredibly light risotto with sweet peas,
shrimp and morels. For the moment, under the stars at Spago, that
devilish New Yorker's voice was nowhere to be heard.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
