<SLUG> BC-L.A.-JANITORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES JANITORS APPROVE NEW CONTRACT 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ending a three-week strike, janitors here voted
overwhelmingly on Monday to accept a new contract that will raise
their wages above the federal poverty level by the time it expires
in three years.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Service Employees International Union Local
1877 said members approved the contract by a vote of 1,747-91.
</P>
<P>
   The three-year deal provides raises of 60 cents an hour in the
second and third years of the contract. Workers in the major office
areas of downtown Los Angeles and Century City will receive raises
of 70 cents an hour in the first year; workers in suburban areas,
who recently received health benefits worth $2 an hour, will
receive 30-cent raises in the first year. The contract also
provides for a $500 bonus for each janitor.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the contract expires, the janitors' wages will be
above the federal poverty level of $16,700 a year for a family of
four.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
