u f BC-AOL-MOVIEFONE-NYT &LR;      04-24 0346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-MOVIEFONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AOL MOVIEFONE TO INTRODUCE VOICE RECOGNITION TECHNOLOGY 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK LYMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Taking its cue from an incident in a ``Seinfeld''
episode, AOL Moviefone will announce Tuesday that it is introducing
voice-recognition capabilities to its telephone service in New York
and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The move will allow callers to buy movie tickets and get
information on show times and theater locations by simply speaking
into the phone rather than wending their way through a labyrinth of
touch-tone menus.
</P>
<P>
   Executives from Moviefone and Lucent Technologies, which
developed the speech recognition technology that will be used, said
the germ of the idea came from a ``Seinfeld'' episode in which
Kramer receives a new phone number that is very similar to the
Moviefone number _ 777-FILM _ and begins to imitate the phone
service when people mistakenly call him. At one point, exasperated
with the touch tones, he tells a caller, ``Why don't you just tell
me the name of the movie you'd like to see?''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Jarecki, Moviefone's chief executive, said that the
service will be available beginning Tuesday in New York and New
Jersey, but will eventually expand to more than 35 markets around
the country. The technology will be able to understand the names of
movies, when spoken by callers, as well as zip codes, credit card
numbers and other information needed to make the service work,
Jarecki said.
</P>
<P>
   The technology, from Lucent's Bell Labs Speech Solutions
division, is able to understand a wide range of voice pitches and
accents, as well as filtering out background noise.
</P>
<P>
   Moviefone, which began offering a telephone movie-ticket service
in 1989, was acquired last May by American Online and is now part
of AOL's Interactive Properties Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the phenomenal growth of our moviefone.com service on
the Web, our phone service still serves the majority of our
audience each week,'' Jarecki said. ``This will save people time
and ultimately drive more traffic to the service.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-00 2054EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
