<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, April 25, 2000, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As a storm that brought abundant clouds and rain to the
Northeast last week moves into eastern Canada, yet another storm
will approach the Middle Atlantic States from the south. Onshore
flow will resume over much of the Eastern Seaboard, promoting cool
readings and rain in some sections. In the mountains of West
Virginia and western Virginia, there may even be some periods of
steady snow.
</P>
<P>
   A strong area of high pressure will remain over the Rocky
Mountains, bringing unseasonable warmth to the region. In the
central Plains, there will be some showers as a weak disturbance
drifts to the east. Meanwhile, the deserts of the Southwest will
turn hot.
</P>
<P>
   A low pressure system will swirl into the Northwest, bringing
valley showers along with mountain snow. Meanwhile, the coast of
southern California will turn a bit milder. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: VERIFYING TORNADOES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Late last week a damage survey confirmed that several tornadoes
had occurred near Louisville, Ky., during Thursday's severe
thunderstorm outbreak. When twisters are large and seen by many
people, the job is easy. In other cases, people sometimes confuse
benign, pendulous clouds with tornadoes. Damage thought to be
caused by a tornado is often a result of straight-line winds
generated when downdrafts of thunderstorms spread rapidly after
hitting the ground. Experts look for spiral patterns in damaged
trees and buildings as evidence of the swirling winds of a
twister. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
