<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6131 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-WNBA-DRAFT25-COX     04-24 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WNBA-DRAFT25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former Texas star Brown's a target, on court and on WNBA's draft
list
 &HT;    By Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Now that Edwina Brown has become an ultra-hot
commodity in WNBA circles, possibly even the top pick in today's
draft, she has discovered that there is no such thing anymore as an
innocent little pickup game at Gregory Gym.
</P>
<P>
   On a Monday evening in late March, Brown, along with four of her
now former University of Texas women's basketball teammates, were
taking on all comers at Gregory Gym. The all comers happened to be
male.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's makeshift team had just defeated one all-male team when
another all-guy squad challenged them.
</P>
<P>
   One male in particular seemed intent on making sure that Brown,
who recently was awarded the Margaret Wade Trophy as the national
women's player of the year, wasn't going to show him up.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy was really upset that his manhood was being
stomped,'' Brown recalled. ``He didn't want to get showed up by a
girl. I posted him up, and he was trying to foul me hard. I knew
it, and so did everybody else. He was trying to strip me (of the
ball). And he used a closed fist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Dude, calm down. Relax.'''
</P>
<P>
   The closed fist came down painfully hard on Brown's right hand.
Thinking she had a jammed knuckle, she persevered through the
pickup game and competed days later in the Women's Basketball
Coaches Association All-Star game in Philadelphia as part of the
women's NCAA Final Four festivities. It wasn't until she got back
to Austin, 10 days after her injury, that she learned her injury
was much more severe than a knuckle jam.
</P>
<P>
   X-rays revealed she had a fractured bone in the middle of her
hand. Her hand was placed in a plastic splint, and the fracture
prevented her from participating in the WNBA draft camp in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   But the injury doesn't seem to have hurt her chances for today's
WNBA draft. Brown, along with four other college seniors, will be
guests of the WNBA for the draft, which starts at 10 a.m. at the
league's New York offices. Brown still will be wearing a splint,
but it's expected to come off within the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, a versatile guard who can play point or shooting guard on
the professional level, has been forecast as the top college player
selected. Depending on whether Olympic standout Teresa Edwards
makes herself available for the draft, Brown could be selected by
the Cleveland Rockers with the first selection. ESPN.com anointed
Brown as the probable top pick last week.
</P>
<P>
   The WNBA draft is unique compared to other pro drafts because of
the talent pool from which it selects. College players such as
Brown and Kansas' Lynn Pride, another top prospect, are available
for the draft, as are foreign professionals. Players such as
Edwards, who played in the now-defunct American Basketball League,
also are eligible for the draft.
</P>
<P>
   The ABL folded in December 1998. The WNBA teams absorbed most of
its top players in last year's draft when only a dozen collegians
were picked. But there were some ABL stars, Edwards among them, who
did not sign a WNBA contract. Edwards is a 35-year-old point guard
and in September will be playing for her fifth Olympic
team.(backslash)
</P>
<P>
   DRAFT HAS GUARDS GALORE
</P>
<P>
   The talent pool for today's draft is not a deep one because most
of this season's college stars were juniors. This draft class is
guard-heavy. Like its NBA counterpart, the WNBA covets centers. But
there are only three truly talented posts in this year's class _
North Carolina State's Summer Erb, UCLA's Maylana Martin and Penn
State's Andrea Garner.
</P>
<P>
   Because Brown can play point guard _ she averaged 6.0 assists
last season despite running the UT offense only half the time _ she
has separated herself from the crowded pack of mostly shooting
guards. Another aspect of Brown's game that makes her so attractive
to scouts is her rebounding. She averaged 8.4 rebounds a game this
season and led the Longhorns in that category for the last two
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care where I play, I just want to be on the floor,''
Brown said. ``I'm one of those types of players who can do
whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   WNBA coaches appreciate that versatility almost as much as her
scoring skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brown is probably the most explosive guard in the draft,''
Seattle Coach Lin Dunn said. ``She is 5-10, very physical and a
great defender. She can hit the jumper and the three-point shot.
She is an exceptional shooting guard.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Nancy Lieberman-Cline, Detroit coach and general manager:
``Going to the shooting guard, Texas' Edwina Brown and (Tulane's
Grace) Daley are clearly the two top collegiate players at that
spot. We have Brown rated as the best and Daley right behind her.''
</P>
<P>
   The Big 12 Conference will have an impact on the draft. Besides
Brown, Pride will vie to be the top pick. The athletic forward did
not participate in the pre-draft camp, which could hurt her stock.
</P>
<P>
   The WNBA, aside from its draft pool, also is unique in that it
has a set pay scale for its draftees. Players who are selected in
the top five of the draft will be paid $52,500 for the season, in
addition to living expenses. Fourth-round picks make $26,000.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said she has no plans to hire an agent and refers all
agents who call her to coach Jody Conradt or Barb Kowal, a UT
assistant athletic director. Brown also is not worried about her
fractured hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe everything happens for a reason,'' she said. ``I
looked at this as a chance to work on my left hand. I know that
this is all part of God's plan and will. I know that there is a
next level for me (after college). This injury could have set me
back if I had a negative attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   WNBA draft
</P>
<P>
   WHEN: 10 a.m. today
</P>
<P>
   WHERE: New York City
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB: For live draft coverage, go to www.wnba.com
</P>
<P>
   LAST YEAR'S TOP PICK: Chamique Holdsclaw (Washington Mystics)
</P>
<P>
   THIS YEAR'S TOP PICK: Depending on whether Olympic standout
Teresa Edwards makes herself available for the draft, former
University of Texas star Edwina Brown has a good shot at being the
No. 1 selection.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
