<DOCNO> NYT20000424.0403 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6133 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-SPLIT-2TAKE     04-24 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-SPLIT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT'S MICROSOFT PROPOSAL SEEKS TO WIDEN COMPETITIVE FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
  (With MICROSOFT-SUIT and related stories and graphic) 
 By STEVE LOHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With its proposal for breaking up Microsoft, the government is
betting that two monopolies, when no longer under the same
corporate roof, would behave very differently than they do today _
and thus create a more open, competitive environment in the
software industry.
</P>
<P>
   The essence of the Justice Department's tentative proposal,
which is expected to be submitted to a federal judge later this
week, would be to force Microsoft Corp. to break off its
industry-standard Windows operating system into one company, and
its Office applications software business and most other Microsoft
operations into a second company.
</P>
<P>
   In the long-running antitrust case, Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson found that Windows had a monopoly with nearly 85 percent of
the market for personal computer operating systems. Its Office
product is a bundle of programs including word processing,
spreadsheet and database software, and analysts estimate that it
holds about 90 percent of the market for such programs for business
use of personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's Office software came up only a few times during the
lengthy trial, which focused mainly on accusations that Microsoft
used its market power to stifle the challenge to Windows posed by
Internet software. Yet throughout the case, the government referred
to Microsoft's arm-in-arm, self-reinforcing linkage between Windows
and Office as being a crucial part of its strategy to defend its
monopoly _ or, in legal terms, raising the ``applications barrier
to entry.'' Jackson, in his ruling earlier this month, embraced the
government's concept of the case.
</P>
<P>
   David Yoffie, a professor at Harvard Business School, explained:
``What the government seems to be trying to do is change the
incentives for both monopoly products, Windows and Office. If they
are split up, you would have more of a duopoly structure with the
same kind of tension that exists between Microsoft and Intel, which
is healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Intel dominates the market for microprocessors, the chips that
power personal computers, almost in the same way that Microsoft
dominates the market for PC operating systems, which control the
basic operations of the machines. The two companies cooperate
closely, but they also have an interest in encouraging competitors
to each other. Intel, for example, wants to make sure the market
for its chips is as broad as possible. So it has invested in
companies developing Linux, an increasingly popular version of the
Unix operating system, which competes with Windows.
</P>
<P>
   By placing Microsoft's Office business in a separate company
from Windows, analysts say, the executives in charge of Office
would have some of the same kinds of incentives as does Intel. At
present, Microsoft does not make a version of Office for Linux. But
in a stand-alone company, the Office managers could well find it in
their interest to develop a version of Office for Linux. Dan
Kusnetzky, an analyst at the research firm International Data
Corp., says that if 2 million of today's 12 million Linux users
bought Office, that could be roughly a $600 million business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because Office has always worked better with Windows, that is
part of the way Microsoft drove people to the Windows operating
system,'' Kusnetzky said. ``But as a separate company, that linkage
should change. Then, people would not care what the underlying
operating system is.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed split-up would address one issue that has been a
frequent complaint from other software companies _ that Microsoft
gives its own applications programmers preferred access to the
inner workings of Windows technology. With Office no longer in the
same company, the Windows team would have no incentive to give it
preferred treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has long maintained that it does not withhold from
rivals the technology inside Windows _ called application program
interfaces, or APIs _ that other programs must have to run smoothly
with the Microsoft operating system.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A Microsoft spokesman, Mark Murray, said that the government
plan, if actually presented to the federal court, would be a ``very
radical and extreme proposal.'' Such a proposal, Murray said, was
in no way justified by the case presented in court, which, he said,
dealt with the allegation that Microsoft illegally tied its
Internet browser to its industry-standard Windows operating system.
Microsoft has denied all the allegations in the suit and plans to
appeal Jackson's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   A breakup is a harsh sanction. But splitting the Windows
business and the Office business into stand-alone companies was not
the most extreme of the remedy proposals that had been considered
by the Justice Department and the 19 states suing Microsoft. The
toughest breakup proposal was to not only split off the Office
applications business, but to give the Windows programming code to
perhaps three different companies to create immediate competition
in the operating system business.
</P>
<P>
   The danger of that approach, analysts said, is that it might
well balkanize the Windows operating system _ a familiar standard
used on 300 million desktop computers worldwide. The prospect of
``fracturing'' the Windows standard concerned many economists,
investors and PC users _ most of whom would not regard three
versions of Windows as a triumph of ``consumer choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Justice Department shunned that approach. Instead,
according to one person close to the proposal, the government's
goals were to craft a remedy package that restrains Microsoft's
behavior, opens the industry to greater competition and yet does
not require the Justice Department to continuously police
Microsoft's actions.
</P>
<P>
   The split-up companies would still be huge and profitable. In
the fiscal year ending in June, the Windows business is expected to
have revenue of $9.5 billion, according to Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter. Revenue for the Office applications business is expected to
be $10.5 billion. And its consumer unit, which includes everything
from its MSN Internet service to Microsoft keyboards and mice, is
projected to have revenue of nearly $3 billion. The consumer
division, a person close to the government's proposal said, would
likely be folded into the company that takes the Office
applications business.
</P>
<P>
   The gross profit margins, before taxes and other expenses, are
an astronomical 95 percent on Microsoft's Windows business,
analysts estimate. On the applications business, the gross profit
margins are more than 80 percent, analysts estimate.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, some analysts have speculated that a breakup of
Microsoft into two monopolies could prove a windfall for investors.
After Standard Oil was split up in 1914 and the AT&AMP;T breakup in
1984, they noted, the pieces were soon worth far more to investors
than the combined companies had been.
</P>
<P>
   That theory apparently provided scant comfort to Microsoft
investors Monday. Microsoft's stock dropped $12.3125 a share, to
$66.625 a share. The main cause of the falloff was a belated
reaction to the company's disappointing quarterly revenue growth,
reported on Thursday after the close of the market but before the
Good Friday holiday.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts also doubted the theory that a breakup would
benefit investors. ``I see it more likely to result in a
destruction of shareholder value, not an unlocking of shareholder
value,'' said David Readerman, an analyst at Thomas Weisel Partners
in San Francisco.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
