u s BC-BKN-BRADLEY-WILKENS25     04-24 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BRADLEY-WILKENS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Orlando's idea right for Hawks
 &HT;    By Mark Bradley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Hawks should send a thank-you card to the Orlando
Magic. By giving Doc Rivers a chance, the Magic cleared a path. All
businesses try to think outside the box, as management jargon has
it, but some company has to be the first to make a beyond-box move.
Orlando did it.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer Orlando made Rivers, who was then 38 and who hadn't
worked even as an assistant, its head coach. The Magic subsequently
overachieved so outrageously that Rivers stands as the new model
for NBA teams seeking a coach. As of Monday, that list officially
includes the Hawks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to put specifics on it,'' said general manager Pete
Babcock, speaking of his criteria. Then he did anyway. ``We're
looking for energy, a specific direction, a commitment to player
development, someone who can relate well to players and at the same
time be demanding.'' In sum, the Hawks are looking for the
anti-Lenny.
</P>
<P>
   Lenny Wilkens isn't the wrong coach for every team, but he was
for the band of fledglings this had become. At the end, even
Wilkens had to know it. He resigned because his other choice was to
get fired. Babcock and Stan Kasten took great pains Monday to speak
no ill of the newly deposed, but it was clear that familiarity had
had its accustomed effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a truism that five years is about the max (for any pro
coach),'' Babcock said. ``It's like a great speech. You can deliver
the speech 100 times and it's still a great speech, but the 100th
time it isn't as impactful.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the Hawks can find a new voice, emphasis on ``new.'' Tubby
Smith would be a splendid candidate, but he isn't apt to leave one
of the three best college jobs for the team that finished with the
NBA's 25th-best record. Isiah Thomas would generate major publicity
but would come with an outsize ego and hasn't been able to divest
himself of the CBA. (Can't coach a major-league team while owning
an entire minor league.)
</P>
<P>
   But the Hawks shouldn't feel a need to make a Big Splash with a
Big Name. As the composition of NBA rosters grow ever younger, it
seems forward-thinking to follow Orlando's example and hire a coach
of tender years and limited seasoning. ``I would never downgrade
head-coaching experience,'' Babcock said, ``(but) Doc's success
opens the door for everyone in the league to be more flexible.''
</P>
<P>
   The hot names among NBA assistants are Byron Scott of Sacramento
and Rick Carlisle of Indiana. The Hawks figure to consider both,
but they should look first at another former player. They should
look first at Nate McMillan.
</P>
<P>
   He's 35, barely two years removed from a career so distinguished
that Seattle was moved to retire the number of a player who never
averaged more than 7.6 points. McMillan has spent this season on
the Sonics' staff. He played under the huckster Jim Valvano at
North Carolina State, played for the canny George Karl as a pro,
played alongside the raging Gary Payton. Presumably this varied
background left McMillan with a feel for motivation, for tactics
and for ego-massaging.
</P>
<P>
   As a player, the resourceful McMillan was heralded as a
coach-in-waiting. He need wait no longer. Orlando has shown the
way. The Hawks should be brave enough to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
