<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-GALA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP EXPECTS TO RAISE $18 MILLION AT GALA HONORING BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also GORE-CLINTONS) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Republican Party expects to raise at least $18
million, the largest sum collected at a fund-raising event by
either major party, at a black-tie dinner on Wednesday night
saluting Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   A month from now, however, that record may be shattered by the
Democratic Party when it holds its annual springtime gala, a
tribute to President Clinton. Unlike the Republicans' event at the
Armory here, to be attended by 1,600 guests in tuxedos and evening
dresses, the Democrats plan to hold a barbecue at the MCI Center
sports arena on May 24 with 15,000 guests encouraged to wear blue
jeans and cowboy boots.
</P>
<P>
   There is another fundamental difference between the parties' two
big-money galas. A majority of the money raised by the Republican
Party for its dinner is soft money, the unlimited, often large,
contributions that Vice President Al Gore has challenged Bush to
eliminate from this year's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   To underscore the vice president's challenge, the Democrats have
tried to transform their annual gala into a small-donor event, with
ticket prices starting at $50. But many contributions will be
soft-money checks of $100,000 or higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our folks are going to come to this event on the Metro, not in
limousines,'' said Terry McAuliffe, the dinner's chairman and the
chief fund-raiser for the Clinton-Gore campaign in 1996. It was the
idea of McAuliffe, who has raised more money than any fund-raiser
in the history of the Democratic Party, to place an emphasis on
collecting small donations at the tribute to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Clifford May, the communications director for the Republican
National Committee, objected to the Democrats' effort to portray
the Republican gala as a dinner for wealthy contributors. ``That is
disingenuous and misleading and they know it,'' May said. ``Our
average donation is lower than theirs. We will tell you what ours
is. Up until now, they have refused to reveal their average
donation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans' average donation is $55, officials said. Jenny
Backus, the Democrats' spokeswoman, said the party did not reveal
its average donation because it viewed the information as
proprietary.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties have spent much of their time soliciting soft-money
contributions during the lull between the primaries and this
summer's nominating convention. On Monday night, Clinton and Gore
and their wives attended a fund-raising dinner in New York that was
expected to raise $2.2 million for the Democratic National
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter, the Democratic National Committee
surprised many fund-raisers by outraising the Republicans, who
traditionally raise more. The Democrats raised $26 million from
January to March, while the Republicans raised $24 million. The
Democratic effort was bolstered by the efforts of Clinton, who
attended 41 fund-raising events.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican event on Wednesday night, called Gala 2000, will
shatter last spring's record of $14 million at a salute to former
President George Bush. The fund-raising for this year's gala was
led by 50 vice chairmen, each of whom raised $250,000 or more, said
Mel Sembler, the finance chairman of the Republican National
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is an enormous amount of enthusiasm out there
for our nominee,'' Sembler said.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Fox, the gala chairman and chief executive of the Harbour
Group, an industrial products manufacturer, said on Monday, ``The
response has been absolutely incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   The gala comes 10 months after George W. Bush, who has already
raised record sums for his own campaign, held his first
presidential fund-raiser in Washington, an event that raised $2
million and was attended by hundreds of lawyers and lobbyists.
Although he is running as a Washington outsider, Bush was embraced
then, and will be feted on Wednesday, by hundreds of this city's
most powerful and influential Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The gala invitation list reads like a who's who of Republican
lobbyists from K Street, the capital's corridor of influence. Some
of the Republicans' biggest contributors are listed on the program,
including Kenneth Lay, the chairman of the Enron Corp. in Houston,
which has given more than $500,000 to past Bush campaigns; Charles
J. Wyly Jr., the Dallas investor whose group, Republicans for Clean
Air, spent $2.5 million on attack advertisements against Sen. John
McCain of Arizona; and Carl H. Lindner, the chairman of American
Financial Group, who personally gave the Republicans $550,000 last
year.
</P>
<P>
   The party's fortunes have also been bolstered by the new
big-money donor club known as the Regents. Each member gives
$250,000 to the party. There are 56 ``Regents,'' and party
officials hope to recruit 44 more by Election Day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
