</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MOORE-WILKENS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Resignation' buys time for Hawks duo
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Not surprisingly, those who run the Hawks still don't
get it. Either that, or they simply wished to save themselves from
the guillotine of their combined bosses at Turner Sports, Time
Warner Inc. and AOL by slicing off the head of Lenny Wilkens and
presenting it as a sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, I'm sorry. Hawks president Stan Kasten and Hawks general
manager Pete Babcock said Monday at Philips Arena during a hastily
called news conference that Wilkens resigned. You know, just like
Richard Nixon resigned.
</P>
<P>
   This is such a joke. This almost is as funny as Kasten and
Babcock hiring the most troubled player in the NBA named Isaiah
Rider before the season, telling the famously meek Wilkens to do
something with him and firing both of them after the Hawks dropped
into purgatory.
</P>
<P>
   I keep forgetting. Wilkens resigned. That's right, he just
happened to decide over the last few days to leave the Hawks, even
though he spent much of the last couple of weeks expressing his
eagerness to coach the team for an eighth season.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever. Wilkens definitely had to go after this season's 28-54
disaster turned Philips Arena into the loneliest place in Atlanta
during Hawks games. The public rebelled against Wilkens' mellow
coaching style of 27 years and a roster of young and boring players
with little athleticism.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to this season, the Hawks continued their yearly meltdown
early in the playoffs with old and boring players with little
athleticism.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkens didn't hire any of those players. Kasten and Babcock
did. That means Wilkens is only the symptom here, and that also
means the problem for the Hawks is elsewhere. Like wherever Kasten
and Babcock have gathered during the past 10 years to make
decisions for this hapless franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Not only isn't Kasten going anywhere as president of the Braves
and Thrashers as well as the Hawks, but neither is Babcock. With
Wilkens' departure, they've bought themselves maybe three more
years of excuses and alibis.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with the NBA draft in June. Since the Hawks finished
brutal enough this season to earn a lottery pick, Kasten and
Babcock will have the chance to suggest during another rocky season
that it will take a while before the new guy meshes with the
previous new guys that Wilkens wouldn't play _ you know, just
because they weren't that good, but so much for the truth.
</P>
<P>
   You'll also have the traditional grace period for a new coach.
That's good for a couple of seasons right there for Kasten and
Babcock. And, as they already like to tell the public, the Hawks
will have all of that money under the salary cap to purchase free
agents. No, not this summer, but the next summer.
</P>
<P>
   And, when the Hawks still are sorry three summers from now,
we'll likely hear the same words from Babcock during a news
conference that we heard after Wilkens, uh, resigned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put a tremendous burden on him with all the changes we
made.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a great deal of responsibility, and an even greater
sense of frustration for not providing the coaching staff with the
atmosphere to allow us to maximize our potential.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As difficult as this is for us, we think the future is
extremely bright. We're excited about this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Yadda, yadda, yadda.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
