<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSING-LAPTOP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT TAKES SECURITY STEPS IN WAKE OF LAPTOP DISAPPEARANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER MARQUIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Decrying ``inexcusable and intolerable'' security
lapses at the State Department, Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright Monday stripped her intelligence office of its right to
police itself, reassigned two diplomats and ordered supervisors to
rethink their security procedures.
</P>
<P>
   The measures came as the FBI led an investigation into the
disappearance more than two months ago of a laptop computer
containing highly sensitive files, including intelligence sources
and methods weapons related to weapons proliferation, senior
diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   Albright, whom aides described as extremely angry, targeted the
department's Bureau of Intelligence and Research for punishment,
transferring a top administrator and an analyst and placing its
overall security under the aegis of the Bureau of Diplomatic
Security, whose tasks including protecting U.S. embassies and
envoys.
</P>
<P>
   Asserting that a series of incidents have ``put our nation's
secrets at risk'' and damaged her department's reputation, Albright
chided every employee under her leadership to make security ``your
top priority in all its aspects all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, security is not a subject in a university
course,'' said Albright in a press briefing. ``Ninety-nine percent
success is a failing grade.''
</P>
<P>
   The missing laptop comes four months after officials discovered
an eavesdropping device in a State Department conference room, and
promptly expelled a Russian diplomat from the country. In 1998, a
man dressed in a tweed sportcoat strolled into the executive
secretary's office, six doors down from Albright's office and
walked out with sheaves of classified documents while two
secretaries worked nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said Monday they have not yet
determined whether the laptop computer, which vanished from a
sixth-floor work area of the Bureau of Intelligence and Research,
was lost or stolen. It not known whether the computer may have been
sought for its hardware or its files, which carried a ``code word''
classification, higher than top secret.
</P>
<P>
   But department officials appeared to proceed under the
assumption that the files _ which drew on material culled from
sensitive human and electronic sources _ were likely to fall into
the hands of adversaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are talking about extremely sensitive information here,''
said James P. Rubin, the department's spokesman. Various agencies
are still examining the implications of losing such files, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Albright ordered the transfer of two employees from Intelligence
and Research, pending the results of the investigation.
Administration sources identified those reassigned as Nancy May,
the acting executive director of the bureau, and Allen Locke,
director of the bureau's office of analysis for strategic,
proliferation and military issues.
</P>
<P>
   Neither official responded to requests for comment. The
temporary transfer was ``not a finding of fault,'' Rubin stressed.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Albright ordered all senior supervisors at the
department to review their security practices and demanded an
intensified program of annual refresher classes for people who
handle classified information. She said, moreover, she would work
with lawmakers to possibly establish a new senior position at the
department to handle security matters.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers from both parties have prodded Albright to better
safeguard U.S. secrets. Rep. Benjamin A. Gilman, the chairman of
the House International Relations Committee, announced he would
hold hearings into security failures at the department.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph R. Biden, Jr., a Delaware Democrat, praised Monday's
steps to ``shake people out of their lethargy.'' But Biden also
blamed steady cutbacks in the State Department's budget, including
a Republican-led move earlier this month to slash international
funding by over 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This reduction will surely harm the State Department's ability
to assure robust information security,'' Biden said.
</P>
<P>
   The laptop incident spotlighted the struggle of a relatively
obscure, often criticized bureau that seeks to provide independent
intelligence to the secretary of state and her deputies, while
functioning in the shadows of the deep-pocketed Central
Intelligence Agency, the Defense Intelligence Agency and the
National Security Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Among the larger intelligence services, the State Department's
bureau _ with shrinking personnel and an antiquated computer system
_ has long been viewed as an institutional stepchild with an
unmotivated staff. The CIA has been known to withhold intelligence
from the bureau, staffers there said. Albright consulted the CIA
chief in announcing her steps Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a place they sent people who weren't making a great
deal of progress in their overseas posts,'' said one former CIA
official of the bureau. ``The general impression at CIA and DIA was
that these were second-raters. They were not considered
top-drawer.''
</P>
<P>
   Toby Gati, the former assistant secretary of the Bureau of
Intelligence and Research, charged that her office had been
neglected by Albright and her top aides. While she said there was
no excuse for the bureau's ``terrible mistakes,'' Gati said its
staff toiled under the constant mantra of ``doing more with less.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither the secretary nor her deputy cared a whit about
Intelligence and Research, nor have they made much use of its full
potential,'' said Gati, who led the bureau from 1993 to 1997. ``If
the department really cared about security, it would have given
Intelligence and Research the resources to do its job.''
</P>
<P>
   Roy Godson, an intelligence specialist who is a professor of
government at Georgetown University, said it is unfair to single
out the State Department for security breaches. It is an easier
target, he said, because it has a more public image and frequently
clashes with Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The State Department has made a number of egregious mistakes,
but it's not the only one,'' said Godson, who served in the White
House during the 1980s. ``To be fair, lots of other services have
made mistakes like that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
