<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    George W. Bush to visit Dayton
 &HT;    By Jim Bebbington
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ A Dayton neighborhood development group is taking
George W. Bush to school today and educating him on the benefits of
individual development accounts.
</P>
<P>
   He may be a willing student.
</P>
<P>
   Bush visits Dayton today for the first time as the presumptive
Republican presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   He is meeting with a small group of local officials who have
used individual development accounts to spur low- and
moderate-income families to save more and buy homes. These accounts
are programs in which banks or other groups match money put into
savings accounts by low- and moderate-income people. The money can
then be used to buy a home or pay for school.
</P>
<P>
   Today's meeting was arranged by OIKOS Community Development
Corporation, which coordinates a local IDA program.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is scheduled to speak with local officials at 12:30 p.m. in
the auditorium of the Corpus Christi Parish Center in Dayton's Five
Oaks neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Bush touched on individual retirement accounts first in an April
11 speech in Cleveland, when he detailed a broad slate of
initiatives to help the working poor. He proposed a federal tax
credit for banks that match up to $300 in savings participants put
aside. The full $600 could be withdrawn tax-free.
</P>
<P>
   OIKOS has 68 people in its program, matching $2 for every $1
saved up to a total of $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the IDA programs are a really good idea and any
candidate worth their salt is going to lock onto this idea,'' said
Bob Beachdell, a VISTA volunteer with OIKOS. ``That is what we
really need. Funding is from both parties. It has a place in both
parties.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
