<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6146 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-WILKENS25-COX     04-24 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WILKENS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wilkens walks away from Hawks
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Hawks actually launched their search for a
new coach last weekend, days before Monday's announcement that
Lenny Wilkens would resign as coach.
</P>
<P>
   Team president Stan Kasten and general manager Pete Babcock knew
they were going to make a change before the season ended and they
had already reached agreement with Wilkens before the announcement
at the team's practice facility at Philips Arena. Wilkens, who was
home in Seattle and did not attend the news conference, is
guaranteed the remaining $10.4 million on the final two years of
his contract.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued through Career Sports Management Inc.,
Wilkens said, ``Atlanta will always hold a special place in my
heart. I have wonderful memories, both personally and
professionally, but it is time to explore new challenges and new
opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Lonnie Cooper, Wilkens' agent, said he expects his client to
land one of the NBA's eight or nine anticipated job openings, and
the salary in the new job will be deducted from the money the Hawks
are obligated to pay him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should Lenny not find a position that he's comfortable with,''
Kasten said, ``we have invited him to join our front office next
season. That tells you how much we think of him.''
</P>
<P>
   The winningest coach in NBA history with a career record of
1,179-981, Wilkens was 310-232 in his seven seasons with the Hawks.
Near the end of this year's dismal 28-54 season, the worst in
franchise history and the worst mark of Wilkens' 27-year coaching
career, he was clearly unhappy about the fortunes of the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a terrible year. Just awful,'' he said. ``Don't
even try to sugar-coat it.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his resignation, Wilkens, 62, plans to coach again and
speculation has him linked to Washington, which announced recently
that interim coach Darrell Walker would not return next season. The
Wizards appear to need a prominent coach for their roster of
high-salaried, veteran players. Wilkens also has been mentioned as
a possibility if jobs open in Portland or Seattle, teams that are
currently in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Hawks, Kasten said he was ``extremely optimistic''
about the search for Wilkens' replacement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had talks with some interesting names over the
weekend,'' he added. ``I'm not going to start naming people, but
there are some impressive people who have an interest in our
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Former NBA All-Star and league executive Isiah Thomas is the
foremost name on the Hawks' list, but a few weeks ago it appeared
Thomas would not sell his interest in the CBA and would remain
ineligible to coach in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever it is, I'm confident that he will join Pete in giving
us an extremely talented team,'' Kasten said. ``Just as Lenny and
Pete were a great team. We had seven good years with Lenny. Even
this season, I must say he worked as hard as he could.''
</P>
<P>
   Kasten said Babcock's job is not in jeopardy; in fact, the team
president gave his general manager a vote of confidence Monday.
Asked whether Babcock had the ability to take the Hawks to the next
level, Kasten responded, ``Absolutely and without reservation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the talent he's brought to our team,'' Kasten
continued. ``Just two years ago we had four All-Stars on our team.
What does that tell you? Look at the record of talent we have
assembled here over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must tell you that I feel much more confident about our team
than our record would indicate. I have no hesitation in saying
that. With a high draft pick in June and the ability to sign a
quality free agent next summer, I feel that our future here is very
bright.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Hawks forward Alan Henderson agreed with Kasten's
assessment of the team, he expressed disappointment over seeing the
only coach in his professional career leave the organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't want to get started next year, even though I'm very
sad to see Lenny leave,'' he said. ``He was good to me. He taught
me a great deal. He and I had a number of conversations about next
season and I felt good about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this is a business. I've seen friends leave and I've
seen a great coach leave. That's on top of the toughest year we've
ever had here. But at the same time I feel real good about our
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
