<DOCNO> NYT20000424.0419 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6165 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT &LR;      04-24 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BREAKUP OF MICROSOFT SEEN AS PART OF U.S. PROPOSAL
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department intends to ask a federal judge this week
to break Microsoft into two companies to bring about competition in
the software industry, officials and others close to the
government's deliberations said.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal comes less than a month after settlement talks
between the government and Microsoft broke down and a federal judge
found Microsoft in wide violation of federal and state antitrust
laws.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, which issued a disappointing earnings report on
Thursday, led stocks lower. The Nasdaq composite index fell 161.40
points, or 4.4 percent, to 3,482.48. The Dow Jones industrial
average closed at 10,906.10, up 62.05 points, or 0.6 percent. The
S&AMP;P 500 edged down 4.68 points, or 0.3 percent, to 1,429.86.
</P>
<P>
   EARNINGS INCREASE 15 PERCENT AT MERCK
</P>
<P>
   Merck, the drug giant, said that its first-quarter profit rose
15 percent as it sold more of the painkiller Vioxx, the cholesterol
reducer Zocor and other medicines. Net income increased to $1.5
billion, or 63 cents a diluted share, compared with $1.3 billion,
or 54 cents a share, in the quarter a year earlier. Revenue rose 17
percent, to $8.85 billion. Analysts had expected the company to
earn 62 cents a share. Shares of Merck rose $2.625, to $71.9375.
</P>
<P>
   GE TO OFFER BANKING ON THE WEB
</P>
<P>
   General Electric, which has been aggressively expanding the list
of products and services that it sells on the Web, plans to offer
online banking on its consumer-oriented financial Web site, the GE
Financial Network.
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINE SUES OVER BAGGAGE SIZERS
</P>
<P>
   Continental Airlines sued United Airlines and the committee that
oversees operations at Washington Dulles International Airport,
contending that baggage-sizing templates at security checkpoints
inhibit competition.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN EXPRESS PROFIT RISES 14 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   American Express, the charge-card issuer and travel agency, said
that its first-quarter profit rose 14 percent, beating Wall Street
forecasts, as it earned more fees from issuing cards and selling
mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   BLAIR DISCUSSES FACTORY WITH FORD
</P>
<P>
   With Britain's troubled auto industry facing severe cutbacks and
job losses, Prime Minister Tony Blair and other government
officials have held talks with Ford Motor as it contemplates
closing a plant near London. Officials said that Blair had met
recently with Jacques A. Nasser, Ford's chief executive, and that
he and other officials were talking with Ford about a review of its
European operations expected to be concluded in mid-May.
</P>
<P>
   MEET MYA, MOTOROLA'S PITCHWOMAN
</P>
<P>
   As the symbol of the new 24-hour talking Internet, Motorola
nominates a virtual woman named Mya, a long-legged blonde, clad in
a silver business suit and displaying spunky hair and a ubiquitous
telephone headset. Her animated figure is showcased in a new
60-second television spot created for Motorola, the cellular
telephone and semiconductor giant that is now trying to sell
software and Internet services and jazz up its image.
</P>
<P>
   REVENUE RISES 41 PERCENT AT AT&AMP;T UNIT
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T said that revenue at its wireless unit, which plans to
issue tracking shares this week, rose 41 percent, to $2.2 billion,
in the first quarter as more customers signed up.
</P>
<P>
   AOL MOVIEFONE TO ADD VOICE OPTION
</P>
<P>
   AOL Moviefone plans to announce Tuesday that it is introducing
voice-recognition capabilities to its service in New York and New
Jersey. The move will allow callers to buy movie tickets and get
information on show times and theaters by simply speaking into the
phone.
</P>
<P>
   OLDSMOBILE GENERAL MANAGER TO QUIT
</P>
<P>
   The Oldsmobile unit of General Motors plans to announce later
this week that its general manager, Karen Francis, has resigned,
auto industry officials said. Francis is the best-known member of a
group of young GM managers hired from consumer products companies
to revitalize GM's brands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
