   (NYT17) MADISON, Wisc. -- April 24, 2000 -- WIS-ALCOHOL --
Scholars say the beer-drinking tradition in Wisconsin traces to the
German heritage of the state. State lawmakers have recently
toughened drunken-driving laws. A liquor store in Madison. (Andy
Manis/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) LIQUICA, East Timor -- April 24, 2000 -- TIMOR-SOLDIERS
-- Former members of the militia, which waged a violent campaign in
East Timor, have come home to try to rebuild their lives. Luis, a
former civil servant who would only give his first name, is now a
fisherman. (Anastasia Vrachnos/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) UNDATED -- April 24, 2000 --
SCI-TRILOBITE-EXTINCTION-B&AMP;W -- A quarter billion years ago, some
90 percent of all animal species, including the trilobites, the
three-lobed predators of the sea seen in this fossil, suddenly
disappeared in the worst of all mass extinctions. The killer's
identity has long been a mystery. But now scientists in Australia
have unearthed evidence that the culprit could have been a speeding
rock from outer space that slammed into the planet, carved out a
huge crater some 75 miles wide, and blasted millions of tons of
rock and dust into the sky, blotting out the sun. (The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) LAWRENCE, Mass. -- April 24, 2000 --
CATHOLIC-CONVERTS-BOS -- Data being collected by the National
Conference of Catholic Bishops indicate the Catholic Church in the
United States this year is experiencing a significant, if somewhat
mysterious, surge in the number of adults joining the church. The
Rev. Jim Seymour of St. Patrick Church in Lawrence, before Catholic
converts during Palm Sunday Mass. (Matthew Lee/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) WASHINGTON -- April 24, 2000 -- GORE-FUERTH -- There is
only one member of Vice President Gore's staff close enough to call
him Al. It is Leon Sigmund Fuerth, Gore's longest-serving aide, who
has acted as his elder consigliere on national security matters for
two decades. Fuerth last week on the balcony outside of his office
in the Old Executive Office Building overlooking the West Wing of
the White House. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) KISII, Kenya -- April 24, 2000 -- AFRICA-MALARIA --
Malaria hurts African economies more than has been recognized but
could be better controlled for relatively little money, according
to a new study to be released on Tuesday by Harvard's Center for
International Development and the London School of Hygiene and
Tropical Medicine. A malaria ward last July was overflowing with
patients to the point that the hospital packed them two or three to
a bed, with others on the floor. (Ian Fisher/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) EAST ISLIP, N.Y. -- April 24, 2000 -- NY-HEROIN-TEENS-2
-- Dennis Fleming is one of a small but slowly growing number of
suburban teen-agers who have become addicted to heroin. Fleming
during a recent talk to a class at East Islip High School about his
addiction. (Vic DeLucia/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) EAST ISLIP, N.Y. -- April 24, 2000 -- NY-HEROIN-TEENS-1
-- Dennis Fleming is one of a small but slowly growing number of
suburban teen-agers who have become addicted to heroin. After a
recent talk to a class at East Islip High School about his
addiction, Fleming hugged his mother. (Vic DeLucia/The New York
Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- April 24, 2000 -- LUCENT-APPOINT -- Still
working to shore up its financial credibility on Wall Street,
Lucent Technologies Inc. on Monday named Deborah C. Hopkins,
previously a senior executive with the Boeing Company, as Lucent's
chief financial officer. Hopkins, 45, seen in this undated photo,
had been Boeing's chief financial officer, a job she assumed when
she joined the aerospace giant in November, 1998. (The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT) WASHINGTON -- April 24, 2000 -- GORE-FUERTH -- There is
only one member of Vice President Gore's staff close enough to call
him Al. It is Leon Sigmund Fuerth, Gore's longest-serving aide, who
has acted as his elder consigliere on national security matters for
two decades. Fuerth last week on the balcony outside of his office
in the Old Executive Office Building overlooking the West Wing of
the White House. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) MIAMI -- April 24, 2000 -- MIAMI-FRESCO-DISPUTE -- In
1984, the artist David Novros found a public space for one of his
huge fresco murals in the old federal courthouse here. But today he
is trying to save his ``Frescos in the Courtyard'' from destruction
by the government in a dispute that is pitting the artist and his
supporters against historic preservationists who want to restore
the old courthouse to its original condition. A mantenance man
cleaned the floor recently in the courtyard where Novros's frescos
are located. (Cindy Karp/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- April 24, 2000 -- LITERARY-OFFSPRING -- The
children of baby-bommer writers are coming of age. Just as the
music and film industries are seeing a burst of activity from
stars' progeny, books are being written by young people with
familiar names and, in some cases, derivative styles. Several
notable authors from left: Molly Jong Fast, Andre Dubus III, Gotham
Chopra and Katie Roiphe. (Ruth Fremson, Michael Quan, Edward
Carreon, Ozier Muhammad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WASHINGTON -- April 24, 2000 -- CUBAN-BOY-RENO -- Taking
a break from the Elian Gonzalez crisis, Attorney General Janet Reno
read a book to children attending the annual White House Easter Egg
Roll. Reno signed autographs Monday after reading to children at
the annual event at the White House. (Stephen Crowley/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) FERNDALE, N.Y. -- April 24, 2000 -- VITAL-SIGNS --
Salmonella is most commonly associated with eating contaminated
food, but federal health officials are now noting other sources:
baby chicks and ducklings. A recent report from the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention warns that merely handling the young
birds, as children sometimes do especially around Easter, can
transmit the disease, which causes diarrhea, vomiting and fever and
can be especially dangerous to children. Ducklings at a farm in the
Catskills. (Joyce Dopkeen/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. -- April 24, 2000 --
SCI-BIO-PROSPECTING -- In a decision that could give a boost to
``bio-prospecting'' in national parks, a federal judge has upheld a
precedent-setting agreement in which a biotechnology company will
pay Yellowstone National Park for the right to search its geysers
and hot springs for commercially valuable microbes. Researchers at
one of the park's hot springs that are seething with heat-loving
microbes. (Yellowstone National Park/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- April 24, 2000 -- SCI-SPIN -- A spinning disk
has inspired a British scientist to delve into the underlying
mathematics, and now he has devised a model to explain how the
rolling speed can accelerate even as the disc is losing energy. The
Euler's disc, in a time lapse photo, that inspired the scientific
study. (Tangent Toy/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- April 24, 2000 -- SCI-MATH-PROBLEM-B&AMP;W -- In
1742, a little-known mathematician named Christian Goldbach, wrote
this letter to Leonhard Euler in which he speculated that every
even number greater than two could be expressed as the sum of two
prime numbers. The first person to submit a correct proof of
Goldbach's conjecture, which has resisted solution for more than
250 years, before March 15, 2002, will receive a check for $1
million. No reasonable mathematician seriously doubts the validity
of Goldbach's conjecture. But mathematical proof is not a matter of
what seems reasonable, but a product of pure reason. (The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- April 24, 2000 -- SCI-NURSE-PRACTITIONERS --
Nurse practitioners were the focus of a study published in January
in The Journal of the American Medical Association, which found no
significant differences in the quality of care received by patients
randomly assigned to either doctors or nurse practitioners.
Patients see advantages in the nurses, who often have much more
time to spend with them and can work on prevention issues. Eileen
Cafasso, a nurse practitioner, with a patient. (Nancy Siesel/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
