<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE-DELAY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH WINDS PROMPT NASA TO DELAY SHUTTLE LAUNCH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ High winds Monday forced at least a
one-day postponement of NASA's bid to launch the shuttle Atlantis
on a repair mission to the fledgling U.S.-led international space
station.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantis and its crew of seven were tentatively re-scheduled for
lift off at 3:52 p.m. EDT Tuesday from NASA's Kennedy Space Center.
</P>
<P>
   However, forecasters placed the prospects of continued high
winds and thunderstorms Tuesday at 80 percent. NASA launch director
Dave King did not rule the possibility that mission managers could
postpone a second attempt until Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The space agency has until Wednesday to begin the mission to the
uninhabited first components of the new station before it faces a
postponement until May 11.
</P>
<P>
   After Wednesday, NASA must give up the use of Air Force
radar-tracking equipment here that is required for every U.S.
rocket launch. A handful of commercial and military rocket launches
have lined up behind Atlantis for the use of the equipment.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the advancing weather system proved more powerful
than originally forecast. As it swept across the southeastern
United States, cross winds at the shuttle's emergency runway kicked
up well above the 17 mph limit.
</P>
<P>
   If problems develop early in the spacecraft's 8 1/2-minute climb
to orbit, the long runway at Kennedy must be prepared for a shuttle
crew to attempt an emergency landing.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's scrub cost $616,000 in lost rocket engine propellants
and labor, NASA said.
</P>
<P>
   The launch bid was called off with nine minutes left in the
Atlantis countdown. Shuttle commander Jim Halsell and his crew had
been strapped aboard the spacecraft for nearly 2 1/2 hours,
successfully satisfying all other launch criteria, hoping the wind
velocities would drop.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand the rationale,'' Halsell said when informed of
the postponement. ``We will wait until the conditions are better.''
</P>
<P>
   The launch period is constrained by the ability of the shuttle
to reach the new international station, which is circling the Earth
at an altitude of about 220 miles.
</P>
<P>
   If Atlantis lifts off Tuesday, NASA plans to extend the shuttle
mission from 10 to 11 days because it will take the shuttle three
days rather than two days to reach the orbital outpost.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlantis visit is intended to set the stage for the arrival
of the station's three-person Russian crew module in July and the
first resident crew this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlantis crew plans to replace failing batteris aboard the
first components of the new orbital outpost and repair the U.S.
communications system. Astronauts Jim Voss and Jeff Williams plan
to re-secure a wobbly cargo crane on the exterior of the outpost
with a lengthy spacewalk.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
