<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JANUARY SPENDING ON CAMPAIGN ADS DOUBLES; COUNTING THE MONEY IN
N.C.; GORE CLOSES GAP IN OREGON 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Candidates for political office spent twice as much on
television advertising in January as in the same month in 1996,
according to the Television Bureau of Advertising. Based on figures
compiled by Competitive Media Reports, a company that tracks
spending for commercials, the bureau reported that political
expenditures on local television stations across the country came
to $12.8 million for January. That was double the $6.4 million
spent four years ago. The rise was attributed in part to a more
competitive primary season and the early scheduling of primaries in
several major states. The bureau, the broadcast television trade
group, forecasts a nearly corresponding rise for the entire
campaign: It predicts that this year, candidates at all levels will
pay $600 million _ $550 million of that on local stations, the rest
on the networks _ for commercials. Four years ago, a total of $400
million was spent on political advertising, the bureau said.
</P>
<P>
   _ PETER MARKS
</P>
<P>
   THE GOVERNORS: CASH COMPETITIVE IN NORTH CAROLINA
</P>
<P>
   With North Carolina's gubernatorial primary only eight days
away, the money and the polls seem to be moving in different
directions in the Democratic race. Attorney General Mike Easley has
had a comfortable lead in recent polls over Lt. Gov. Dennis Wicker,
but Wicker has raised more than Easley. The lieutenant governor has
collected $4.7 million, while the attorney general has raised $3.6
million. On the Republican side, former Mayor Richard Vinroot of
Charlotte holds a modest lead in both the polls and fund raising.
He has raised $2.4 million, compared with $1.6 million for Leo
Daughtry, the state House majority leader. A third candidate, Chuck
Neely, a Raleigh lawyer and former legislator, has raised $1.06
million.
</P>
<P>
   _ KEVIN SACK
</P>
<P>
   THE POLLS: GORE GAINS IN OREGON
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, it appeared that Gov. George W. Bush of Texas was on
his way to being the first Republican presidential candidate to
carry Oregon since Ronald Reagan in 1984. Polls showed him leading
Vice President Al Gore by more than 10 points. Since then Gore has
closed the gap; the latest poll, an April 10-17 survey of 504
likely voters by The Oregonian, has Bush leading by only three
points, 40 percent to 37 percent. The poll, which has a margin of
error of plus or minus four points, also found Ralph Nader, the
Green Party candidate, running best among third-party contenders,
at 7 percent; Patrick J. Buchanan, the likely Reform Party
candidate, had only 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ B. DRUMMOND AYRES JR.
</P>
<P>
   TODAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: New York, Boston, Hartford, Conn.
</P>
</TEXT>
