<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6187 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-US-CUBA-HNS &LR;      04-24 1223
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-CUBA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELIAN DRAMA COULD HELP THAW U.S.-CUBA RELATIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trim) 
 
By DUDLEY ALTHAUS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The Elian Gonzalez affair has painted an all-too-human
face on the 40-year conflict between the United States and Cuba, an
issue that doesn't cross many American minds much anymore.
</P>
<P>
   In his five-month stay in the United States, the bright-eyed and
vulnerable 6-year-old shipwreck survivor has found himself caught
up in a media frenzy and torn by the bitter squabble between his
communist-ruled country and its exiles in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   As efforts move forward to return the boy home, the underlying
question is whether Elian's travail _ for many, the pop culture
event of the moment _ will have any lasting impact on U.S.-Cuba
relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this crisis has done is awaken American public opinion to
the sense, or nonsense, of U.S. policy toward Cuba,'' Julia Sweig,
deputy director for Latin America on the Council on Foreign
Relations in Washington, said Monday. ``It's not going to have any
short-term impact, but it's accelerated a process that started
before Elian: a national rethinking of U.S.-Cuba policy.''
</P>
<P>
   That policy, forged in the 1960s and reinforced in the 1990s
with the Helms-Burton Act and other anti-Castro legislation,
includes a near-total embargo on trade with the island and a tight
restriction on travel there by U.S. citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly anyone expects the embargo to be dropped soon. That would
require more political will than can be mustered for now and might
cause more harm than good in both Cuba and the United States, Sweig
said.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's saga also suggests that the U.S.-Cuba conflict, once a
cornerstone in the Cold War, has largely become a feud among
Cubans.
</P>
<P>
   But the hatred between Castro and his enemies will likely hobble
a steady march toward a more normal relationship between Washington
and Havana, some analysts say. Castro needs his enemies in Miami to
stiffen the resolve of his people. The Miami Cubans have powerful
friends in the U.S. Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Elian drama could help speed the thaw that has been
going on in recent years. What is being contemplated in Washington,
Sweig and others say, is how to ``manage down'' the embargo and
other sanctions in order to ease tensions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't expect anything bold,'' said Shawn Malone, a Cuba
analyst at Georgetown University in Washington. ``But what (the
Elian affair) could lead to, is that most Americans will no longer
actively oppose any opening to Cuba.''
</P>
<P>
   That opening is already under way, helped along by Pope John
Paul II's trip to the island in January 1998, by the evaporation of
U.S. fear of a communist threat from Cuba and by an eagerness by
many U.S. companies to participate in the opening of the Cuban
economy.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration last year began allowing friends and
family in the United States to send money to Cuba. It also approved
food and medical sales to non-governmental agencies on the island,
and gave Cuban-Americans the right to visit there once every 12
months.
</P>
<P>
   The response has been dramatic. Remittances to the island now
run to the hundreds of millions of dollars. And some 150,000 U.S.
citizens will travel to Cuba this year with Washington's
permission, 90 percent of them Cuban-Americans returning to visit
friends and relatives, according to the U.S.-Cuba Trade and
Economic Council, a New York-based lobbying group.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps another 25,000 Americans will go to Cuba illegally,
flying through Mexico, Canada and other third countries.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, as many as 60,000 Cubans will come to the
United States this year, a third of them with the right to settle
here permanently and the remainder with permits for visits that
could stretch into months.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see more contact between Cubans on both sides of the
Florida Straits and that can only be positive,'' said Delvis
Fernandez, director of the Cuban-American Alliance, a
Washington-based coalition seeking to improve ties to the island.
</P>
<P>
   ``After years of separation, you create a lot of myths about one
another,'' Fernandez said. ``We need new schemes of engagement.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. businesses have long been clamoring for the chance to trade
with the island. Nearly 3,000 U.S. executives journeyed to Cuba
last year, hoping to learn the ropes and to make contacts in
expectations that the embargo will end sooner rather than later.
</P>
<P>
   ``To wait for politics to catch up to business means that a
business is behind the curve,'' said John Kavulich of the U.S.-Cuba
Trade and Economic Council. ``Change will be more frequent and more
expansive as time goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   Legislation allowing food and medicine sales directly to the
Cuban government was approved by the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee recently with the tacit consent of Sen. Jesse Helms,
R-N.C., the committee chairman who is an anti-Castro stalwart. But
it was not submitted for a vote by the full Senate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Texas Farm Bureau's 12-person board of directors led a
delegation of farmers and agribusiness executives to the island
this week. It is the group's second visit there since last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the embargo lifted,'' said Mike Barnett, a farm bureau
spokesman in Waco. ``It hasn't changed anything since Castro came
in. The only ones being hurt are the Cuban people.``
</P>
<P>
   Well, almost the only ones. Cuba imports hundreds of millions of
dollars worth of food and other agricultural products, Barnett
noted. ``We'd like a piece of it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Castro in many ways has been helped more than harmed by the
embargo, some analysts say. His revolution has been at least as
much about guarding Cuba's independence from foreign domination as
it has Marxism. And for more than 100 years now, the biggest
foreign threat to the island has been the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The embargo reminds the Cuban people that they have powerful
enemies.
</P>
<P>
   Castro called a ``one-day truce'' Saturday in appreciation of
the Clinton administration's help in returning Elian to his father.
But neither the Cuban regime nor the media it controls have let up
on its attacks of U.S. ``imperialism.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the government media downplayed the affair while
ramping up attacks on the Czech Republic, a former socialist block
ally, for leading the condemnation of Cuba in the United Nations
Commission on Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
   Some 200,000 people marched past the Czech Embassy in Havana,
shouting ``traitors, lackeys, puppets.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the same day a U.S. appeals court ruled that the
boy must stay in the United States pending a May 11 hearing, an
evening television program set up to discuss the saga for two hours
every weeknight instead devoted five hours to lambasting the
perfidy of the Czechs.
</P>
<P>
   Although some 100,000 Cubans attended a rally Thursday to
protest the boy's continued stay in the United States, many in the
crowd drifted away after a few minutes of speeches. Those who
stayed spent more time visiting among themselves, sitting on
Havana's seawall or simply staring into space.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Save Elian'' T-shirts worn by many protesters were faded,
the boy's image bleached by the harsh tropical sun.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
