<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6189 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-DAVIDIANS-HEARING25-C     04-24 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVIDIANS-HEARING25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Expert's opinion of siege supported by evidence, judge says
 &HT;    By Mark England
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ U.S. District Judge Walter S. Smith Jr. said
Monday there is ``corroborative evidence'' to back up the opinion
of the court's expert that no muzzle blasts are seen on the
infrared videotapes taken at Mount Carmel on April 19, 1993, when a
fire broke out that led to the deaths of David Koresh and 75 other
Branch Davidians.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs in the wrongful-death lawsuit against the
government claim FBI gunfire pinned many Davidians inside a burning
Mount Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   Smith stressed that he does not consider the preliminary
analysis by Vector Data Systems, a British firm that conducted a
re-creation of the final day at Mount Carmel, incontrovertible
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is evidence from an expert,'' Smith said. ``That expert's
opinion may be controverted.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith made his comments before the start of a pretrial hearing
on the plaintiffs' request that he sanction the government in the
wrongful-death lawsuit filed by surviving Davidians.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Mike Caddell of Houston, the lead plaintiffs attorney,
said the government dumped more than 100,000 pages of records on
the plaintiffs after a court-ordered deadline. He also accused the
government of tampering with the evidence. The plaintiffs are
seeking $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Before the sanctions hearing, though, Smith told attorneys that
Vector Data detected 57 thermal events or flashes of light on the
government's 1993 infrared tape (which picks up heat signatures).
</P>
<P>
   Vector Data, however, said the flashes are not muzzle blasts,
Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their preliminary opinion is that there were no muzzle blasts
at all on the FLIR (Forward-Looking Infrared) tape,'' Smith said.
``That's not merely expert opinion. It's backed up by corroborative
evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said Vector Data's experts showed him video of the Bureau
of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms breaking the window into Koresh's
bedroom, trying to enter Mount Carmel during the Feb. 28, 1993,
raid that saw four ATF agents and five Davidians killed. Glass from
the shattered window fell on the roof and was pinpointed as the
source of one of the flashes some have identified as a muzzle
blast, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not here to tell you that every type of flash was
identified that specifically,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said Vector Data will turn in a written report to him May
8.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Michael Bradford said he was pleased with Vector
Data's preliminary report.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's consistent with what we've said all along,'' Bradford
said. ``There was no gunfire behind the compound on April 19th.''
</P>
<P>
   Caddell said the test protocol for the re-creation was not
followed. Temperature requirements were not met, and the helicopter
carrying one of the FLIR cameras did not fly at the right altitude,
according to Caddell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not rejecting the report,'' Caddell said. ``I haven't seen
it. We've got five issues in this lawsuit. Gunshots are just one of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   In the sanctions hearing, an FBI pilot testified he thought
there was audio on the FLIR tape that captured the fire at Mount
Carmel. The 1 1/2-hour tape, however, has no sound. Caddell called
the lack of audio ``suspicious.''
</P>
<P>
   The pilot, who was not identified by name, said it was
``standard operating procedure'' to turn on the audio while
operating the FLIR camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised when I heard the tape had no audio on it,''
the pilot said.
</P>
<P>
   Learning the FLIR tape had no audio led him to call the FBI's
Office of General Counsel, the pilot said. During that
conversation, he speculated why there might not have been sound,
the pilot testified.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to think of any plausible reason why there was no
sound on the tape,'' the pilot said.
</P>
<P>
   Either nothing was going on or there might have been
conversation inside the surveillance plane of a ``sensitive''
nature that led someone to turn the audio off, the FBI pilot
testified.
</P>
<P>
   Bradford, who assisted Justice Department attorney Marie Hagen,
noted that the secondary FLIR operator, who was responsible for the
audio, was inexperienced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it possible that an inexperienced operator simply forgot to
turn it back on?'' Bradford asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, sir,'' the pilot said. ``That is possible.''
</P>
<P>
   However, an audio expert tapped by Caddell claimed that his
analysis of the FLIR tape led him to think the audio may have been
erased from the FLIR tape.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Cain, a forensic tape expert who worked for the Secret
Service, testified that the FLIR tape is silent until after the
video image ends. Then there is ``hissing,'' which indicates the
audio had been on, according to Cain.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, the audio has been erased,'' Cain said. ``I
think the evidence is fairly substantive.''
</P>
<P>
   But an expert witness for the government, Bruce Koenig, a former
FBI agent, testified that what Cain was hearing was attributable to
his copying the original FLIR tape and taking it back to his
Wisconsin lab to study. Koenig said the hissing is not heard on the
original FLIR tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had his report saying it was there,'' Koenig said. ``I
checked. There was nothing there.''
</P>
<P>
   Caddell told reporters that the audio might have been stripped
off the FLIR tape to cover up a request to fire military tear gas
canisters, which are flammable. He noted that when the audio was on
during the morning of April 19, it recorded an FBI request to fire
military tear gas canisters at an outlying bunker area at Mount
Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   ``A military tear gas canister might have started the fire in
the kitchen,'' Caddell said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradford, however, scoffed at Caddell's claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no proof presented that anything was destroyed or
withheld,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides also had different viewpoints on an eight-minute gap
in the photographs taken by an FBI aerial photographer, who, like
the pilot, wasn't identified. The photographer, who said his job
was to take photographs of anything significant, didn't take
photographs of a tank collapsing the Davidians' gym, a tank ramming
the corner of Mount Carmel (where the fire first broke out) and the
start of the fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to imagine, sir, with all this activity that there
was nothing going on that you felt warranted a photograph,''
Caddell said.
</P>
<P>
   The photographer said he may have been giving the pilot a
``break,'' since the pilot had to hold open a window for him to
take photographs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once again, I'd have to say the pilot wasn't in a position for
me to take a photograph,'' the FBI photographer said. ``Also, it
looks far worse on the FLIR than it does to the naked eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith did not rule on whether to grant sanctions Monday. He gave
attorneys the week to submit written arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Late Monday, Smith released copies of an order denying the
government's request for a summary judgment in the case. He also
denied the plaintiff's request to reinstate Richard Rogers, the
former commander of the FBI's Hostage Rescue Team, and Jeffrey
Jamar, the FBI special agent in charge during the siege, as
defendants in the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
