<DOCNO> NYT20000424.0432 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6193 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-FORCE-2TAKE     04-24 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-FORCE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBATE ON MIAMI RAID RIDES ON WHETHER DEAL WAS NEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In three minutes on Saturday morning, the national
debate over who should have custody of Elian Gonzalez was replaced
by a much more intense dispute over whether Attorney General Janet
Reno had acted wisely in ordering the 6-year-old boy seized by
armed agents in a pre-dawn raid.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday that dispute was intensified by comments from the
White House and from Congress, and by the release of documents from
both sides in the nightlong negotiations over the child, documents
that hardly differed in words but were separated by a chasm of
conflicting interpretations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The negotiations were proceeding,'' four Miami civic leaders
maintained in a statement issued Monday afternoon. ``They had not
broken down. People were acting in good faith. Progress was finally
happening after the months of stalemate.''
</P>
<P>
   But Reno, interviewed on the NBC News television program
``Monday,'' said, ``We just kept getting mixed signals from a
family that had given us hope and then pulled it back, said they
would comply with the law and then said on several occasions that
we would have to take the child by force.''
</P>
<P>
   And Gregory B. Craig, lawyer for Elian's father, Juan Miguel
Gonzalez, said in an interview, ``We were, as far as I can tell,
never close to an agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing from either side on Monday definitively settled the
question of whether the Justice Department's efforts to broker a
deal between the families Gonzalez could ever have succeeded. And
for all the complaints over the raid's being done in darkness, or
over the arms carried by the agents, that had been the central
question before Reno.
</P>
<P>
   And as Friday night wore on into Saturday morning, the biggest
difference _ untouched as progress was made over times, places and
conditions _ was over trust, and that may have been too broad a gap
to bridge.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday afternoon, Craig said, the attorney general told Juan
Miguel Gonzalez that she did not want to have to send people in to
take Elian out by force. Gonzalez objected, telling her the Miami
relatives would never give in. ``They are never going to give up
the boy voluntarily,'' and every day's delay makes things worse,
Craig quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Miami relatives said they did not believe
that the father and the government would keep their word to have
the boy stay in the country until a judicial appeal decided the
asylum issue surrounding his case.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was the Justice Department completely open with both sides.
While Reno spoke of deadlines to the Miami leaders, especially
Aaron Podhurst, a lawyer she has known well for many years, she did
not let them know a raid was imminent. Podhurst complained Monday
that she had led him to put two of the other civic leaders, Carlos
M. de la Cruz and Carlos Saldriga, ``in harm's way'' by sending
them to the Miami home of Lazaro Gonzalez, where the raid was
nearly at hand.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, when she met with Juan Miguel Gonzalez and Craig on
Friday afternoon, she did not tell them she had been in touch with
the Miamians _ who also included Edward T. Foote II, president of
the University of Miami _ since Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But she did disclose the overture at some point that day,
telling Craig she was going to explore the Miamians' efforts. Craig
says he told her he had no confidence that the Miami relatives had
more in mind ``than a ploy to take us through Easter and into next
week.''
</P>
<P>
   He says he told her that he and Gonzalez were ready to go to
Miami themselves to get the boy (for the Miami relatives' lawyers
had said that was all they needed to do), and she told him not to
do anything rash.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, he asked the attorney general to get him something
in writing if she expected him to take anything from the Miami
relatives seriously. She asked the Miami civic leaders for
something concrete, in a document, and they faxed her a one-page
proposal about 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   That document, which was never given directly to Craig, proposed
that the two families live together ``in a mutually agreed, neutral
site in Miami-Dade County.'' Except for marshals to guard them, the
Gonzalez clans would have no one around other than a neutral
facilitator ``to help the family members get together and do what
is in the best interest of the child.'' Their lawyers would be
barred. This arrangement would be maintained until all legal
proceedings were ended.
</P>
<P>
   That proposal from the Miamians also included this sentence:
``We understand that you have transferred temporary custody of
Elian to his father.'' Podhurst maintained Monday that this had
conceded the custody question. Craig said that it had not done so
satisfactorily and that the open-ended joint living arrangement had
muddled the question of who could legally speak for the boy.
</P>
<P>
   At 7:58 p.m., Craig received a different proposal from the
Justice Department, apparently a product of the department's talks
with the Miami leaders about what might be acceptable to Juan
Miguel Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   This proposal moved the venue for the joint living arrangements
from Florida to Airlie House, a conference center in the Washington
suburbs. But that concession was not enough for Gonzalez, who
returned from dinner to Craig's office, or for Craig, who said he
thought the open-ended joint living arrangements were a mistake. He
also said a provision for the Miami leaders to nominate a new team
of experts to advise on how to deal with Elian was thoroughly
unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal also suggested that there would be conditions on
the father's custody; Craig said there had been no conditions on
Lazaro Gonzalez's temporary custody, so he asked why new ones were
being contemplated.
</P>
<P>
   At 10:53 Justice sent another proposal. It softened the
suggestions of new custody conditions, and made it clear that while
both families would live at Airlie House, they would have separate
living quarters. But the timing was still an issue, and Craig said
none of the joint arrangements should exceed one week.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department kept talking with the Miami leaders, who
kept talking to the family of Lazaro Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   After those talks, at 2:10 a.m., Justice faxed another draft to
Craig. It gave him most of what he had demanded, including a 3:30
a.m. turnover of the boy to U.S. marshals at the federal courthouse
in Miami. It dropped the plan for nomination of a new group of
experts. And most important of all, it limited the joint residence
arrangement to a one-week period of transition in Elian's custody.
</P>
<P>
   Craig complained Monday that the one-week limitation had not
been included in another section, which allowed the attorney
general to direct the conditions of the transition period. He said
Holder had agreed to add it, but not to insert another section that
Craig sought, declaring Juan Miguel Gonzalez's right to ``challenge
the reasonableness of any condition imposed under this agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Holder asked Craig to wake up his client and get him to agree.
Craig said he told Holder to ``sell it to them first.'' But, he
said Monday, he would have tried to persuade his client to agree,
and at about 2:50 a.m., he told Holder to ``proceed as if we had
agreed to it.''
</P>
<P>
   That same draft, with the one-week limitation, was faxed to
Miami at 2:59 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   From here on, the accounts diverge. The Miami group insists that
it was making progress. But Craig says he was told the Miamians
were now changing their minds about letting Elian go to the
Washington area, suggesting instead White Oak Plantation on the
Georgia-Florida border.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said Monday that she told Podhurst ``at about 4 in the
morning that we had run out of time, because we kept getting mixed
signals.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the issues,'' she said ``was where would the families
meet. And the father did not want to come to Miami, because of the
tension and the tense atmosphere in Miami.'' She said Podhurst
``said that was a deal-breaker, and so we agreed that we had tried
our best.''
</P>
<P>
   With immigration agents on their way to raid Lazaro Gonzalez's
home, Reno talked to Podhurst again at 4:21.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of us remember it vividly,'' she said Monday. ``And he
said, `Could I have just five minutes?' And I said, `Five minutes.'
``And he said, `That means 4:26.' And I said, `That's right.' He
continued to keep me on the phone, and I kept on the phone because
I wanted to try to do everything I could. But we did not feel like
we could delay any longer, because the action was carefully timed.
And if it did not go forward at this time, it would be very
difficult in the future to effect a safe extrication of the little
boy.''
</P>
<P>
   The conversation unfinished, she put Podhurst on hold when the
raid began. When she picked up the phone again, he shouted angrily
at her. She cried, according to Podhurst and Holder, who said he
put his arms around her.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday the Miami leaders' statement said, ``We were
completely surprised and astonished that the government would
resort to armed marshals when we were so close to agreement,
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig said: ``The attorney general stretched and pushed and
waited and tried as hard as she possibly could. I thought, prior to
her decision to go in, that she had been paralyzed by the
worst-case scenario. To accuse the attorney general of being
precipitous is, with all due respect, preposterous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-00 2206EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000424.0434 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6195 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-U.N.-U.S.-ARMS-1STLD-     04-24 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-U.S.-ARMS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT DEFENDS U.S. INTENTIONS ON ARMS CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to add four grafs to end of original text.)  
(With RUSSIA-U.S.-ARMS) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Secretary of State Madeleine Albright tried to
convince the world Monday that the United States was not
threatening to undercut a quarter century of progress on
international arms control by developing a new anti-missile defense
system that had drawn criticism from Russia and China.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Clinton administration were bent on sabotaging the ABM
treaty and strategic arms control,'' she told an international arms
control conference, ``we have surely gone about it in a strange way
_ in the open, with care and in consultation not only with
Congress, but after extensive discussions with our allies and other
countries, Russia and China emphatically included.''
</P>
<P>
   In a speech at the opening of an international conference called
to review a treaty banning the spread of nuclear weapons, Albright
also argued that the United States had reduced its nuclear arsenal
by 60 percent since the end of the Cold War, and had joined in
cutting NATO's nuclear stockpile by 85 percent. She spurned calls
for the quicker elimination of nuclear arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, none of us has it within our power to create
overnight the conditions in which complete nuclear disarmament is
possible,'' she said. The speech offered no new initiatives but was
more of an accounting of how the administration wanted to define
its record.
</P>
<P>
   Albright walked into an almost solid wall of criticism of the
United States inside and outside the General Assembly hall because
of what was widely perceived as the slow pace of nuclear
disarmament more than a decade after the end of the Cold War and
because of the fears that the proposed American anti-missile
defense system would start a new international arms race.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the United States _ which last fall saw the Senate
reject another crucial accord, the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty _
is seen as setting a bad example for other countries that can now
cite political pressures for refusing to sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clinton administration's legacy is the re-legitimating of
nuclear weapons after the end of the Cold War,'' said Daniel
Plesch, director of the British American Security Information
Council, an independent research group in Washington and London.
</P>
<P>
   India and Pakistan, which tested nuclear weapons in 1998, and
Israel, which is assumed to have nuclear arms, were also criticized
Monday as some conference delegates demanded they adhere to the
nuclear nonproliferation treaty, the focus of the conference. The
treaty, which came into effect in 1970, has been ratified by 187
countries. Only four _ India, Pakistan, Israel and Cuba _ have
refused to sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nuclear testing has no place on our planet,'' said Brian
Cowen, Ireland's foreign minister. ``The time to rid the world of
these weapons is now.'' Nuclear arms are the only weapons of mass
destruction not banned by international treaties. The United States
and Russia have the majority of the world's nuclear warheads.
</P>
<P>
   Cowen's speech was one of the day's toughest, but his sentiments
were echoed by other governments, independent arms control groups
and former American arms control officials. Republicans in
Congress, including Sen. Jesse Helms of North Carolina, chairman of
the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, have been especially harsh
in attacking international arms control agreements, and independent
experts say they are puzzled by this.
</P>
<P>
   ``What appears anomalous to me is that historically, the
Republican Party has led in the area of arms control
strengthening,'' said Jonathan Granoff, co-chairman of the American
Bar Association's committee on arms control and disarmament, said
in an interview Monday. ``The scuttling of arms control through
ballistic missile defense or through the undermining of the
commitment to nuclear disarmament contained in the nuclear
nonproliferation treaty is against the heritage of the Republican
Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Graham Jr., who was the Clinton administration's special
representative for arms control from 1994 to 1997 and is president
of the independent Lawyers' Alliance for World Security, says that
much of the annoyance with the United States stems from commitments
all nuclear powers made five years ago to work harder on
eliminating nuclear weapons in return for international agreement
to make the nuclear nonproliferation treaty permanent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many non-nuclear weapons states _ particularly nonaligned
countries, but also some Western countries, indeed even some NATO
countries _ believe that the nuclear weapons states have not lived
up to commitments that they made in exchange for everyone else
agreeing'' to make the treaty permanent, Graham said. ``If that
doesn't change over the next few years, it could have a very
negative effect on the long-term viability'' of the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Although the conference here is focused on the treaty to halt
the spread of nuclear weapons, much attention was also given Monday
to the perceived threats to the antimissile accord.
</P>
<P>
   Antonio Monteiro, Portugal's representative, speaking for the
European Union, called the ABM treaty ``one of the pillars of
strategic stability'' and said it must be preserved.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary-General Kofi Annan also joined in voicing concerns
about the disruptive potential of a missile defense system _
without mentioning the United States _ when he said in a speech
opening the conference Monday morning that ``it could well lead to
a new arms race.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
