<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONN-WAGES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT HOUSE APPROVES RAISING MINIMUM WAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ The Connecticut House of Representatives
approved a compromise bill Monday that would raise the state's
minimum wage by 55 cents over two years, to $6.70 an hour by 2002.
The State Senate is likely to vote on the increase later this week.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which passed by a 99-to-45 vote in the
Democratic-controlled House, is a watered-down version of a
Democratic proposal that would have increased the state's minimum
hourly wage to $6.75 beginning Jan. 1, which would have made it the
highest minimum wage in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   In hope of ensuring the bill's approval by the Senate, which has
a slight Democratic majority, and by Gov. John Rowland, a
Republican, House Democrats proposed a less ambitious increase. The
bill passed Monday would raise the state's $6.15 minimum wage by 25
cents an hour on Jan. 1 and 30 cents more in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``Minimum wage does not meet basic needs,'' said Rep.
Christopher G. Donovan, a Democrat from Meriden, who defended the
bill against several Republican attacks on the House floor. ``It's
time to make an adjustment.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington and Oregon have the highest minimum wages _ $6.50 an
hour _ and the Massachusetts minimum will increase to $6.75 in July
2001. In New York and New Jersey, the minimum is the same as that
set by the federal government: $5.15.
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut House also added provisions to its bill
specifying who would be eligible for the increases. Tip-earning
hotel and restaurant workers, who are paid a lower minimum wage of
$4.70 a hour, would not be eligible for the increase. But
Connecticut bartenders, whose minimum wage is $6.15, would be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
