<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6206 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-CASINO-2TAKES-     04-24 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CASINO-2TAKES-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS, QUEENS AND SLOT MACHINES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 30) 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The other gamblers did not look pleased. ``Taking a card with 12
showing, and the dealer's card up is a 5!'' growled the
silver-haired man at the other end of the blackjack table. ``I'd
never, (italics)ever(end italics) do that!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was feeling lucky,'' I explained, trying not to sound
defensive.
</P>
<P>
   Dumb thing to say. The guy at my left shoulder smiled
patronizingly. ``What he's trying to tell you is, if you hadn't
asked for that card, it would have gone to the dealer, and we all
would have won.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh. What I'd done wrong was win at the expense of everyone else.
I drew an 8 on my 12, for a total of 20, often a winning hand in
blackjack, otherwise known as 21. The dealer, it was revealed in
the tense denouement of the hand, had 15, and if I had passed and
the 8 had gone to him, his over-the-limit 23 would have meant a
payoff for the whole table. Instead he drew a 4, for a total of 19,
a victory over my fellow players.
</P>
<P>
   Sheepishly, I scooped up my chips _ a hundred dollars' worth,
the precise amount I had started with an hour and a half earlier _
and backed away from the table in the Grand Pequot Casino, the
poshest of the gambling rooms at Foxwoods, the betting mecca in
Mashantucket, Conn., eight miles north of Exit 92 of the
Connecticut Turnpike and about a two-hour drive from New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Was a card game supposed to be this jaw-clenchingly
intimidating? The man on my right, who wore a large ceramic belt
buckle and a look of utter exasperation, had glanced at me
disdainfully any time I as much as hesitated during a game. ``He
doesn't want to part with his money,'' he announced when I failed
to double my bet on a 6 of clubs and 4 of diamonds I had been
dealt. In another round, he had actually commandeered my hand,
making the cutoff signal to the dealer on my pitiful behalf.
</P>
<P>
   OK I admit it. When it comes to risk, I'm no Evel Knievel, even
when it's to be taken over drinks, on green felt. We had come to
the Mashantucket Pequot Reservation for the kind of weekend we had
never spent: my wife and I were gambling babes-in-the-Foxwoods.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I'd been to Las Vegas a couple of times, and had lost all
of $90 on the slots. As for Val, her idea of a madcap betting
impulse was tickets to a movie we hadn't read about first. Our
chromosomes seemed to be short the gene for blowing large amounts
of money on games of chance. So we had to know: was it possible for
us to find the music that so many others hear, to swing for a
couple of days to the beat of clinking coins?
</P>
<P>
   If ever there was a place to find out, it was Foxwoods, the
impossibly vast, turquoise-roofed casino-resort that rises over the
New England countryside like a multitiered mountain of cash.
Foxwoods is to wagering what San Simeon is to tract houses: simply
overwhelming in scale. ``Oh my God, it's huge,'' Val said, as we
approached the complex on Route 2. Minutes earlier, we had passed a
herd of grazing sheep on the two-lane highway that links the casino
with I-95, just west of the Rhode Island line. Now, a contemporary
palace loomed incongruously in the windshield.
</P>
<P>
   Foxwoods, opened by the tribe in February 1992 and expanded
several times since then, today occupies a total of 4.7 million
square feet. The network of casinos is connected to two hotels,
with 1,136 rooms; a 280-room inn is situated nearby. Threading
through the complex are 24 restaurants, 17 stores, a dance club,
theater and arcades: the betting parlor as mall.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Foxwoods is designed to trigger all sorts of familiar
American spending rituals. There is, after all, almost nothing else
to do there. For if Las Vegas is a neon shrine to glitz, and
Atlantic City a dowdy hybrid of grime and show biz, Foxwoods
represents the suburbanization of casino culture. All it seems to
lack is a Banana Republic.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly doesn't lack crowds. (Foxwoods estimates that
40,000 people visit daily.) When I tried to make a hotel
reservation in early March, I was told no rooms were available
until late April. I went to the Foxwoods Web site and found other
recommended places to stay, including a Hilton in Mystic, a
20-minute drive from the casino.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring that the Mystic Seaport, a popular tourist destination
in its own right, would be an additional diversion, we booked a
room at the Hilton on the ``executive level.'' For a $20 surcharge
we got Continental breakfast, a newspaper at the door, and a few
other amenities.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel, across the street from the Mystic Aquarium, met our
weekender specs: well-run, quiet, comfortable. A staff member
actually called to ask if the room-service breakfast was up to
snuff. The coffee was great, we felt compelled to report. The
Hilton, which is owned by the tribe, also offered shuttle service
to Foxwoods: on the weekend we were there early this month, the
shuttle ran every two hours.
</P>
<P>
   From New York City, we made the trip to Mystic at the tail end
of a Friday evening rush in about three hours, including a stop for
dinner. The drive from Mystic to Foxwoods on Saturday morning,
along a country road lined with ivy-covered trees, was not the
car-clogged nightmare I was imagining, and it was easy to find a
spot in the garage underneath the newest hotel in the complex, the
Grand Pequot Tower.
</P>
<P>
   Up the elevator to the casino level. The wide, coldly appointed
walkways had that unmistakable Mall of America feel. ``It sort of
reminds me of the Orlando Airport,'' Val said. The Indian flavor
was minimal; here and there were reminders of the casino's
proprietorship, as in the booths marked Wampum Club, the casino's
players club. (It reminded us that we really should pay a visit to
the new Mashantucket Pequot Museum and Research Center, just down
the road, to learn something about the tribe.)
</P>
<P>
   The casino attire was retirement-village casual _ the average
age was about 60 _ and everywhere there were men in sweatsuits and
women in sneakers and windbreakers. Some visitors brought their
children, who were scrupulously kept from the casinos by the
security people.
</P>
<P>
   Many gamblers had arrived on the charter buses that pulled in
and out of Foxwoods' own depot in endless rotation. The visitors'
props of choice were little plastic buckets (the better to lug your
quarters in) and cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   What is it about nicotine and slot machines? The place was
bathed in eau d'ashtray. I gazed at the casino map _ you
(italics)needed(end italics) a map _ and noticed a zone marked
``Nonsmoking gaming tables.'' Val charted a course for slots in the
fresher air.
</P>
<P>
   I took a wrong turn at the Food Court and ended up at the doors
of a room that looked as if it were built to hold a fleet of 747s.
But no, it was just the Foxwoods bingo hall, with seating for
3,200. Enough bingo for the entire population of Moonachie, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   My destination, however, was video poker. If baccarat is the
sort of abstract expressionism of casino gambling _ I haven't a
clue how it's played _ the slot machines are finger painting. All
you need is a dollar and a digit. You can sit at a slot for what
feels like days, pressing the maximum-bet button and watching the
dials spin.
</P>
<P>
   Video poker is a step up to gambling kindergarten, requiring
higher-level brain function: you have to press multiple buttons
after deciding whether to hold the cards the machine deals you.
</P>
<P>
   I was prepared to part with $400. I also wanted the money to
last the weekend, and I thought that electronic poker could be an
entertaining and low-pressure introduction. Foxwoods has a normal
Vegas-style assortment of gambling distractions: craps tables,
roulette, keno, betting on the horses. There was even a New England
regional poker tournament. My inclination was to lose my money as
anonymously as possible.
</P>
<P>
   But first, I had to find a slot machine, and on this Saturday
afternoon, that was no safe bet. The 25- and 50-cent slots were
standing room only everywhere I turned. In some instances, single
bettors were hogging two machines. Wheelchairs were maneuvered next
to machines at awkward angles; one man was wandering around with
what looked to be a portable IV drip, a plastic tube protruding
from his arm.
</P>
<P>
   Some players, apparently fearful of forgetting their Wampum Club
cards, inserted them in the machine with plastic cords affixed to
their sweaters, like umbilical cords.
</P>
<P>
   I finally settled into a 25-cent video poker machine in the
middle of a long row, breaking one of the rules passed on to me by
a slots-crazed acquaintance: try for a machine on the end, because
it gets more traffic and thus has more cash to dispense. Stay with
one machine and be patient, she also advised.
</P>
<P>
   I have no idea whether these were wagering facts or fiction, and
I had no chance to try out some of the strategies. End machines
were as hard to come by as summer rentals with ocean views.
</P>
<P>
   The captivating fog of money-lust enveloped me. I looked at my
watch, and an hour had been consumed, then two, along with $125.
I'd been up $25, down $100, down $150, up, down, up, down. The man
and woman next to me deftly balanced cigarettes between their
fingers as they worked the buttons. Four aces flashed on my screen,
and then 45 minutes of nothing. The man irritated me with his
squeals of delight every time he won. The woman's teeth clicked.
Another man walked by, inserted $5 in a machine, quickly lost it,
and left. Ha! Amateur! Somewhere, jackpot bells rang and quarters
dropped like hail. But not for me.
</P>
<P>
   I rendezvoused with Val outside the smoke-free slots area. She
was skipping. ``I won $56,'' she said, sounding so merry I could
spit. ``How nice for you,'' I said, smiling through gritted teeth.
</P>
<P>
   We had a late lunch in the Bistro at Foxwoods, the casino's
designated nonsmoking restaurant. I was grumpy, but the Bistro chef
revived my spirits. Mixed greens doused in a chianti vinaigrette
and stuffed sea bass on a bed of orzo was a dandy consolation. A
shrimp cocktail also arrived, fresh and appetizing, each crustacean
on its own lemon slice, followed by an architecturally ambitious
presentation of beef tournedos. With wine and tip, the meal came to
about $90.
</P>
<P>
   I went back to video poker. We made another vow to get in some
culture; we really should stop by the Indian museum. But first, I
had to play another $50 bill in my wallet that seemed to cry out:
Go ahead. Bet me.
</P>
<P>
   For the evening, Foxwoods was presenting the Charlie Daniels
Band. Pass. (Willie Nelson was to perform the following weekend;
Harvey Korman and Tim Conway, Olivia Newton-John and Kenny Rogers
were scheduled for May.) Foxwoods fatigue was setting in fast. We
got in the car, drove to Mystic and relaxed before dinner.
</P>
<P>
   The historic village is compact and crowded with small
boutiques. In the late afternoon, families were out for strolls and
poking their heads in the children's clothing and toy stores. That
evening, we meandered through a long, leisurely meal down by the
Seaport at the Capt. Daniel Packer Inne on Water Street, around the
corner from Mystic Pizza: littleneck clams baked in boursin cheese,
fresh shrimp with a hot sauce, yellowfin tuna, duck, a dazzling
chocolate cake with ganache and butter cream and a bottle of
chardonnay came to about $110 with tip.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning was overcast. I got dressed quickly and early,
stepped over the fat Sunday paper at our door, and headed for the
car, jacks and kings and aces swimming in my head. Val had had
enough; betting the 401(k)s was not her vice, so she lingered over
the paper on a lounge chair by the hotel's heated pool.
</P>
<P>
   I hardly noticed the cigarettes all around me now, as I located
a machine in the Grand Pequot Casino and started feeding it 50s. In
no time _ well actually, about two and a half hours; I was afraid
to get up for fear of losing my spot _ I was down $180. I would
have stayed longer, but I had run out of cash.
</P>
<P>
   ATMs, of course, were installed for my convenience on the
betting floor. I retrieved a C-note and headed for my date with the
seething denizens of that blackjack table. When I left the table
later that afternoon, with enough money in my pocket for lunch and
gas and tolls on the Triborough Bridge, I felt as if I had made it
through a hazing ritual. I even entertained the idea of a return
trip. After all, we never did get to that Indian museum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
