<HEADLINE>
POLICE SAY SUSPECT SHED CUFFS AND STOLE VAN 
</HEADLINE>
   By C.J. CHIVERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A prostitution suspect who was left unattended in a
police department van managed to slip through handcuffs early
Monday and escape to New Jersey with the van and an officer's
ammunition and bulletproof vest, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities said the suspect, Tacoma Hopps, 35, was wanted
as a parole violator from Georgia and decided to try to escape
rather than being returned to jail.
</P>
<P>
   If that was her plan, it failed. The police said Hopps, who is
also known as Precious or Dimples, was recaptured after she left
the van at a strip mall and set off shoeless down a highway in
Secaucus, N.J., carrying the vest, handcuffs and a magazine of
hollow-point bullets, all inside a green duffel bag.
</P>
<P>
   She was charged in New Jersey with possession of stolen
property, possession of handcuffs, possession of hollow-point
bullets and with being a fugitive. She was ordered held at the
Hudson County Jail and was awaiting extradition to New York to face
charges of prostitution, auto theft and escape.
</P>
<P>
   The police said Hopps' misadventure began at 2:15 a.m. at 10th
Avenue and West 46th Street, when she solicited an undercover
officer. As arrests go, it was routine: Two officers from a
Manhattan South vice enforcement unit handcuffed her wrists behind
her back and placed her in the rear seat of an unmarked Ford van.
</P>
<P>
   But a few minutes later, when the officers stepped from the van
to pick up another suspect, they left the keys in the ignition, the
police said. Hopps climbed into the front seat and drove away,
heading south down Ninth Avenue for the Lincoln Tunnel, they said.
</P>
<P>
   How she slipped from the cuffs remained a mystery. ``It appears
she is very agile with her hands,'' said Sgt. Andrew T. McInnis, a
Police Department spokesman. Hopps was next seen shortly after 3
a.m., walking barefoot along Route 3 in Secaucus, said Lt. John
Buckley, head of detectives at the Secaucus Police Department. She
was arrested after officers saw the police equipment in the bag.
Later, the Secaucus police found the van at a strip mall parking
lot.
</P>
<P>
   Hopps, who told the police that her most recent address was the
Royal Motel in Secaucus, has been arrested repeatedly since the
1980s on drug and prostitution charges, the police said. McInnis
said the circumstances surrounding her arrest Monday were being
reviewed to determine whether the vice officers should face
disciplinary charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prisoners are not to be left alone, barring unique
circumstances,'' he said. ``The officers' actions, and the
incident, are under investigation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
