<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6209 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-STUDENT-SLAYING-HNS &LR;      04-24 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDENT-SLAYING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E-MAIL MYSTERY KEY TO TEXAS A&AMP;M STUDENT'S DEATH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Ill.) 
 
By JOHN WILLIAMS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Local and state authorities are trying to identify the
mysterious ``Kelly'' who assured the parents of a Texas A&AMP;M
University student that their son was fine even after he had been
killed and his body dumped on a Central Texas ranch.
</P>
<P>
   E-mails sent by someone claiming to be Texas A&AMP;M junior Kerry J.
Kujawa said that he would be back in several days. But authorities
believe that Kujawa may have been dead since shortly after he left
College Station on April 7 to go to San Antonio to help Kelly, whom
he met on the Internet. The last several e-mails were sent several
days later. All of the correspondence was sent from Kelly's e-mail
address.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, authorities confiscated the computers of Kujawa, his
parents and others in an effort to find Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   They hope that by locating the individual they can learn who
shot Kujawa once in the back of the head with a small-caliber
weapon, leaving his body without shoes or socks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bizarre and unusual case, very bizarre,'' said
Department of Public Safety spokesman Tom Vingar.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly is said to have self-identified as a girl with boyfriend
problems, said Texas A&AMP;M University police director Bob Wiatt.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Kujawa _ a slender, humorous, 20-year-old
mechanical engineering student from Richmond _ did not have a
girlfriend, said his mother, Lucille Kujawa.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made one bad decision in his life _ and this is it,'' the
mother said. ``He was a very sweet boy. He didn't deserve this.''
</P>
<P>
   When Kujawa didn't return to the Texas A&AMP;M campus, family and
friends weren't concerned because they were receiving e-mails,
supposedly from Kujawa, assuring them that he was all right, Wiatt
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the e-mails usually ended with: ``I'll be back in a few
days, everything is okay. Don't worry, I'm still taking care of
Kelly.''
</P>
<P>
   The e-mails were sent from Kelly's Internet account, Wiatt said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, on April 20, after friends raised concerns, the adviser
at Kujawa's college dormitory filed a missing-person report with
campus police, Wiatt said.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Dr. Elizabeth Peacock of the Travis County Medical
Examiner's Office used dental records to identify a body found on a
ranch just off Pursley Road west of Dripping Springs as that of
Kujawa.
</P>
<P>
   The badly decomposed body was found by someone on the ranch
looking for the cause of a foul odor, Hays County Justice of the
Peace Rex Baker said. Baker and others estimated that the body had
been there for at least a week.
</P>
<P>
   While Kujawa said he was going to San Antonio, it is unclear
whether he got there and, if so, how. Nor can officials explain how
he came to the Central Texas area where his body was found.
</P>
<P>
   Kujawa's 1990 Ford Probe was found at Easterwood Airport in
College Station, having been in the long-term parking lot since
April 10, the Monday he promised to return after a weekend trip to
San Antonio, Wiatt said.
</P>
<P>
   A review of airport records indicates that Kujawa did not take a
flight from the airport during the weekend of April 7, Wiatt said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the investigation includes campus police, the Hays County
Sheriff's Department and the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing that he was going to San Antonio is just part
of what we're looking into,'' said DPS spokesman Vingar. ``We're
looking at other things. This investigation is wide open.''
</P>
<P>
   However, finding Kelly through the e-mail address is a key,
Wiatt said. But that could be easier said than done, a Houston
computer expert said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Lee, who hosts the weekly radio show ``Technology Bytes''
for Pacifica, said law enforcement officials first will match the
computer files of those who received e-mails from Kelly with
Kelly's Internet provider.
</P>
<P>
   If they are lucky, Lee said, that will lead them to the computer
of the so-called Kelly. Lee said a similar effort helped officials
break a child pornography case.
</P>
<P>
   However, it is easy and common for people to mask their
identities on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   First, Lee said, Kelly could have given the Internet provider
incorrect identity and address information.
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, though some computer searches will indicate the
telephone number from which Kelly sent the reassuring e-mails, the
sender could have masked that information or used a different
telephone line, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, it is possible for someone to steal the Internet access of
another, and send e-mails on that account. Proving that the owner
of an e-mail address is the same person who sent an e-mail can be
difficult without corresponding evidence, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone wants to make it hard to be found on the Internet,
that can be done,'' Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   Lucille Kujawa said the family hopes to have a funeral service
Thursday at Sacred Heart Catholic Church in Richmond, where their
son was an usher. He is survived by his parents, John and Lucille
Kujawa of Richmond, and a brother, Kraig Kujawa of Lombard, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lucille Kujawa said her son was the neighborhood's ``fix-it
man'' and could repair almost anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he was 11 years old, he took down a ceiling fan and put
up a new one,'' she said. ``At first, I was upset, because he was
messing with electrical wires. But then, I was amazed because he
could do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kujawa was a national merit scholar who graduated sixth among
more than 500 seniors at Austin High School in 1998. He won the
district junior varsity championship in the 1600 meters as a high
school sophomore.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Lucille Kujawa saw her son was March 19, at the
end of spring break, which he spent putting in the base for a
storage shed the family was building.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had expected to see him again at Easter,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
 &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
