u a BC-VIETNAM-RESISTER-NYT &LR;      04-24 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIETNAM-RESISTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW, AS THEN, WAR RESISTER IS PERSISTING 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLYDE HABERMAN  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Even before climbing the flight of well-worn stairs,
you could tell from a sign in the front window that you were
entering the offices of the War Resisters League. ``End
terrorism,'' it announced to anyone who looked up from Lafayette
Street in Greenwich Village. ``Disarm the Pentagon.''
</P>
<P>
   Some things do not change. That goes for the War Resisters
League, steadfastly finding reasons to condemn American military
policies at a time when dissent is not exactly rife in the land.
</P>
<P>
   Another constant is David McReynolds, who was standing at the
top of the stairs.
</P>
<P>
   McReynolds has been with the league for four decades. During the
long Vietnam War, he was its field secretary, meaning he was a
point man on the protest campaigns of those days. Now, at 70, his
beard steely gray, he is technically retired. The key word seems to
be ``technically.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that we have a title for me,'' he said. ``I'm an
emeritus of some kind. I'll have to ask someone up front what my
title is.''
</P>
<P>
   He never got around to it. Too many distractions got in the way,
including a conversation about why he is running for president as
the candidate of the Socialist Party USA.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he can't win (though he hopes for more than the 6,720
votes that he got the last time he ran, in 1980). Why bother?
Because, McReynolds replied, there's a new generation of students
out there looking for answers that they will never hear from the
major parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want them to feel there is a reason to take part in
political life,'' he said, adding that he had been ``very
well-received'' on his visits to college campuses. ``I sort of keep
waiting to be heckled,'' he said. He figures that his age protects
him.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for calling on McReynolds was to talk less about his
campaign than about Vietnam, which is with us once more as we near
the 25th anniversary of the war's end, on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   No backward glance would be complete without examining the
antiwar movement. And few of its generals, if one may give a
military rank to a devoted pacifist, stood front and center more
than David McReynolds _ at the draft-card burnings and repeated
demonstrations that ultimately helped build a critical mass of
domestic opposition to the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   It bothers him, he admits, that the movement's role is receding
into the mists of history. ``The whole thing has sunk into a memory
hole,'' he said. ``But I accept that. It's 25 years ago. It's
another century. It's farther away from young people than World War
I was when I was a student. But it is important for people to go
back and look at the history and understand what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   In some circles, it is fashionable to dismiss the 60s protests
as the excesses of college students with draft deferments, pampered
kids who were in it for sex, drugs and rock 'n' roll while
unfortunate sons of the poor and the working class had to take
their chances in the rice paddies and jungles.
</P>
<P>
   No question, many back then went to sit-ins and lie-ins and
teach-ins mainly because those -in's were in. And, McReynolds said,
``I'm sure there were some hippies _ who I would have slugged if I
had a chance _ who spit on soldiers.'' He can get equally worked up
about ``the ultra-militants who would so happily throw rocks at the
cops from behind our lines at demonstrations.''
</P>
<P>
   But neither the ``peace, love, dope'' types nor the ``off the
pigs'' screamers formed the core of the antiwar resistance, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who led the movement were very courageous,'' he
said. ``Many of them went to prison. Many did go to Canada because
they had given up on this country. The guys who actually organized
the demonstrations and burned their draft cards et cetera were
taking very substantial risks they didn't need to do.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, McReynolds added, the rest of the country caught up
with the resisters in deciding that America _ that's America with a
C, not a K _ had lost its way in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wore us out,'' he said of that era. ``I was alcoholic
during much of it. I'm not blaming the war for the alcoholism, but
I was an alcoholic.'' He stopped drinking about the time the war
ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``From one point of view,'' McReynolds said, ``it was a
wonderful time _ to feel that you were doing something, or that you
shortened the war by one day, or saved one life on either side. To
some extent, we did that. Some observers don't realize how
important the Vietnam peace movement was in moving this government
to finally negotiate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
