<HEADER>
A6218 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BOX-LEWIS-NYT &LR;      04-24 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-LEWIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWIS IS THE UNDISPUTED, AND UNHERALDED, CHAMPION 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There is no designation in athletics that has the
figurative, almost primal status that comes with being the
undisputed heavyweight champion of the world.
</P>
<P>
   The title belongs to Lennox Lewis, but how he wishes it defined
him. Monday, sitting on the side of a boxing ring at Madison Square
Garden, his feet dangling over the apron like a child on a
playground swing, Lewis conceded that he may be a bit out of place.
</P>
<P>
   Not because he is relentlessly polite, courtly and respectful _
a fighter by vocation _ but because great champions are often
defined by their opponents. And while Lewis may have beaten
everyone he was supposed to beat in the last five years and may be
the recognized king of boxing's mountain, Lewis sighed at one point
as he said: ``I'd like to be fighting the guys from my era, really.
I don't want to box the young guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday at Madison Square Garden, the 34-year-old Lewis boxes
one of the young guys, the 6-foot-7-inch, 250-pound Michael Grant,
who is seven years his junior. Still, it is the specter of fighting
Mike Tyson, or even Evander Holyfield for a third time, that keeps
coming back to Lewis, a haunting that Lewis is powerless to
exorcise. And he knows it.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if there was a potential opponent who excited him, Lewis
answered: ``Yeah, but I don't think he wants to fight me. I'd like
to fight Mike Tyson, but he's a movie star now. He hasn't been
taking it too seriously. What can I do?''
</P>
<P>
   Then, turning his head from side to side as if he were furtively
looking for someone behind him, Lewis added: ``And there's
Holyfield. He's still lurking around somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis is what he is, a champion waiting for the unforgettable
rivalry, a fight or series of fights that could give him greater
star power.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible that Grant, who is undefeated and has immense
size and punching power, can provide the intriguing, entertaining
test that will enhance Lewis' profile _ provided Grant does not win
and launch a new era in the division.
</P>
<P>
   Grant became a credible contender five months ago with a
come-from-behind victory over Andrew Golota. Knocked down twice in
the first round, Grant fought back for a 10th-round knockout.
</P>
<P>
   ``That confirmed to him and everyone that Mike is not just a
tremendous athlete who became a fighter _ it confirmed that he's a
fighter,'' Grant's manager, Craig Hamilton, said. ``He got up off
the canvas and won.''
</P>
<P>
   But Grant has been fighting as a professional only since 1994.
He has been busy in that time, winning 31 fights, including 22 by
knockout, but he has far less experience than Lewis. Lewis, who is
6-5 and usually fights at about 245 pounds, has a &QC; 35-1-1 record in
10 years as a professional after an 82-fight amateur career that
included two Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grant is still a gangly, uncoordinated kid,'' Lewis' trainer,
Emanuel Steward, said Monday. ``People have talked about Grant's
height bothering Lennox, but I've watched tapes of Lennox fighting
tall fighters even as an amateur, and he traditionally fights tall
guys real well.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who worked out for about an hour Monday afternoon before
meeting with reporters, had nothing derogatory to say about Grant.
He even praised him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the No. 1 contender in the people's mind and in my
mind,'' Lewis said. ``He's done the work to get there. He's got
height, reach and strength. But I don't think this fight will go
the distance. He's not been in the ring against a boxer like me.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be the closest Lewis got to stirring up prefight bad
blood.
</P>
<P>
   He may be too amiable for that. He smiled easily Monday, joking
with Steward and the few others who help him train. He entered the
Garden for his workout without fanfare, emerging from a back
entrance, and did his warm-up exercises in a darkened corner. A
businesslike, no-frills session in the ring followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am relaxed,'' Lewis said. ``I've been through this many
times now. I'm not loud, but I know my talents.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Steward offered his own analysis. ``Lennox's strengths,''
the veteran trainer said, ``are unheralded.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything about Lennox Lewis, it seems, is unheralded.
</P>
<P>
   When Lewis was done with his interviews, he left the Garden
through a 33rd Street exit and walked 25 yards to a waiting
limousine. On the busy Manhattan street, no one called out the name
of the undisputed heavyweight champion of the world. No one asked
for his autograph or a picture.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of security guards walked with Lewis, and when the
group reached the curb, Lewis turned and thanked them. Then he
ducked his head and disappeared inside the limousine, which joined
the flow of taxi cabs, cars and buses of Midtown traffic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
