<SLUG> BC-BOEING-HOPKINS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING`S TOP FINANCIAL OFFICER TAKES LUCENT JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A little more than a year after she was wooed away from General
Motors to help turn around The Boeing Co. with a value-oriented
approach to business, Chief Financial Officer Debby Hopkins has
resigned to take the same position at Lucent Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins, 45, became Boeing's highest female executive ever when
she joined the aerospace giant in December 1998, a time when Boeing
was struggling to recover from production problems that had sent
its stock tumbling and had seriously damaged its once-shining Wall
Street reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Even though she was with Boeing for only a short time, Hopkins
is credited with overhauling its antiquated financial system, and
bringing financial discipline to the world's biggest aerospace
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Debby Hopkins was a factor for change in a company that really
needed it,'' said Joe Campbell, aerospace analyst for Lehman
Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was no shrinking violet,'' Campbell said. ``She held her
own ... This was a woman who was a whirlwind of energy and she made
a lot of changes, all of which were positive for Boeing.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Jacobs, analyst with Ragen MacKenzie, said Hopkins
``brought a new openness at the company toward financial
performance, and was a major reason for the restoration of investor
confidence in the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins performed so well that she was considered one of three
candidates to replace Boeing President Harry Stonecipher, who is
planning to retire next April.
</P>
<P>
   But many analysts believe the leading contender for that job now
is Alan Mulally, head of Boeing's commercial operations. Mike
Sears, who runs the company's military aircraft and missiles unit
in St. Louis, is also thought to be in the running.
</P>
<P>
   Knowledgable industry analysts, as well as sources within
Boeing, said there was nothing untoward in the sudden departure of
Hopkins. Lucent had been after her for some time and finally
presented her with a salary and financial package that Boeing could
not match, these people said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Hopkins was attracted to the Lucent job because it meant
returning to her high-tech roots, they said. Before she became vice
president of finance and chief financial officers for General
Motors Europe, Hopkins spent 13 years at the Unisys Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy the passion and velocity of a high-tech company,''
Hopkins said in a statement. ``And Lucent is at the center of one
of the fastest-growing industries today. When I was offered the
opportunity to join Lucent ... I couldn't pass it up.''
</P>
<P>
   She replaces Donald K. Peterson, who has been named chief
executive officer of Lucent's new Enterprise Networks Group, slated
to be spun off later this year. Lucent was spun off from AT&AMP;T Corp.
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Condit said Monday he learned last week that Hopkins was offered
the Lucent job, and he tried to talk her into staying at Boeing. He
declined to say what kind of counter offer was made.
</P>
<P>
   ``She and I talked,'' Condit said in an interview with the
Seattle Post-Intelligencer. ``I'm not going to get much deeper than
that ... We had those conversations.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why Boeing didn't make Hopkins an offer she could not
refuse, Condit had this to say:
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to take into account all the pieces of what any offer
has _ how does it fit with the profile of your industry. The kind
of offer you would make out of a Microsoft is very different than
the kind of offer you make out of Boeing. There are certain things
we can do logically, and things we cannot do.''
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins' appointment at Lucent was effective immediately.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband and two children plan to relocate to Far
Hills, N.J. Lucent is headquartered in nearby Murray Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Skowronski, a former Lockheed Martin executive who was
brought to Boeing by Hopkins about a year ago to be vice president
of finance and treasurer, will be acting chief financial officer
until a replacement is named, Boeing said.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent is the world's largest telecommunications equipment
maker. The company declined to say what it agreed to pay Hopkins.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, Hopkins earned more than either Condit or Stonecipher
at Boeing, according to the annual proxy statement that was
recently mailed to shareholders for the annual meeting on May 1.
She received stock options worth nearly $5 million. Her total
compensation in 1999 was more than $6 million, including a bonus of
$633,600.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins received a signing bonus of $750,000 when Boeing hired
her, according to a filing Boeing made last year with the
Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing shares fell $2.38 to $37.88 Monday on the New York Stock
Exchange, and analysts said it was a reaction to the news about
Hopkins. The stocks of other aerospace and defense companies were
up on Wall Street Monday, and so were Boeing shares before word of
Hopkins' departure became widely known.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the investor standpoint, her absence from Boeing will be
missed,''said Jacobs, the industry analyst. ``One of the question
marks is who will fill those shoes. It will be tough to find a
replacement for her. ... It's probably going to take several weeks
or even months to find a replacement.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jacobs and other analysts said Hopkins has built a strong
financial team at Boeing, and what she started will not be undone
by her leaving.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has put in place new financial controls and a new way of
thinking within the company in terms of financial measures,''
Jacobs said. ``That will still be the guiding force, same as
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Condit, in the interview with the Post-Intelligencer, said the
company is ``headed in the right direction'' and that will not
change, regardless of who ends up replacing Hopkins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have built an incredibly capable team,'' Condit said.
``Debby had a real hand in building that team. We have a lot of
momentum going for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
