<SLUG> BC-HARE-PLAY-LAWSUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAY BY DAVID HARE IS RULED HIS OWN 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal lawsuit charging that David Hare's one-man
play about the Middle East, ``Via Dolorosa,'' misappropriated
elements from another author's one-man play has been dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have read the two plays, and the plays are, beyond the bare
minimum structure of a play addressing contemporary issues
involving the Middle East, the plays are substantially different,''
Judge Denny Chin of U.S. District Court in Manhattan wrote in his
decision, which was released on Friday. ``They are completely
different.''
</P>
<P>
   In a civil complaint filed last May, Steven Greenstein charged
that the Royal Court Theater in London rejected his one-act play,
``Voices From the Holy ... and Not So Holy Land'' in 1997, and then
used its ideas, structure and some dialogue for Hare's play. The
suit named only the Royal Court as the defendant and not Hare.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Hare expressed relief at the decision,
particularly on behalf of the Royal Court, which commissioned him
to write ``Via Dolorosa,'' and because the litigation has delayed
the PBS broadcast of a film version of his play. ``We've been
hamstrung by this litigation,'' he said. ``From this tenuous claim
you can actually hold up a project for 10 months and cost the Royal
Court $40,000 in legal fees, which it doesn't have.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Via Dolorosa,'' which started in September 1998 at the Royal
Court, opened on Broadway at the Booth Theater on March 18, 1999.
In the one-act monologue, the author recounts his trip to Israel
and conversations with people on each side of the Arab-Israeli
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Charles S. Sims, a lawyer at Proskauer Rose LLP, which
represented the Royal Court and its co-defendant, the English Stage
Company, said that such claims were part of a trend. ``Even when
these claims are meritless,'' Sims said, ``it costs money to defend
them, and plaintiffs hope they will get some money to go away.''
</P>
<P>
   In his decision Chin said there were decisive differences
between the two plays. Hare's is told by him, for example, while
Greenstein's is not told from the author's point of view and could
be played by any actor. Hare's play is nonfiction, and Greenstein's
is fiction. And while conceding that the plays have a few things in
common, the judge said that some overlap was to be expected ``with
any treatment of the discussion of the Middle East.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a copyright claim, the lawsuit charged that by
reading Greenstein's play, the Royal Court entered into a contract
that obligated it to compensate the playwright. Chin also rejected
that claim.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Hare _ who said he had not read Greenstein's play
_ expressed concern that such cases would force the Royal Court to
re-evaluate its open submissions policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed,'' Greenstein said. ``I think that my claim
was legitimate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-00 2252EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
