<HEADER>
A6225 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLA     04-24 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTROVERSIAL CALL LEADS TO DODGERS LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; NEW YORK _ The Los Angeles Dodgers paid some respect to four
Mets pitchers who held everyone but Todd Hundley hitless, but they
also spoke of being weary from a rough first month.
</P>
<P>
   The fatigue showed; Hundley had all three of the team's hits.
There were also breakdowns in the field, and a pair of them in the
ninth inning led a 1-0 Mets win Monday at Shea Stadium in a makeup
game the Dodgers weren't happy playing.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have won eight in a row and the Dodgers lost for the
first time in eight road games. After scoring 36 runs on 37 hits in
thrashing the Reds, the Dodgers were shut out for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Having already opened the season with 12 of their first 17 games
on the road, the Dodgers left Cincinnati on Sunday to play this
game, rescheduled from the April 9 snowout. After the loss, the
Dodgers took a charter flight to Atlanta, where they'll begin a
three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got in at a decent hour (Sunday) night, but still you fly,
unpack, you sleep, you pack back up, come the ballpark,'' said
Dodgers starter Darren Dreifort, who pitched six shutout innings.
``So guys are going to be a little sluggish. But the guys played
their (butts) off on defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   A controversial call and missed grounder in the ninth doomed the
Dodgers. Robin Ventura led off the inning with a double against
Terry Adams (1-1), Melvin Mora pinch-ran and Jon Nunnally was
walked.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Payton hit a grounder between shortstop Kevin Elster and
third baseman Adrian Beltre. Elster fielded it and flipped the ball
to Beltre, but Beltre didn't have his foot on the base so he tried
to tag Mora.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew the bag was behind me, but I didn't know exactly where
it was,'' Beltre said. ``I felt it when I touched it, but I wasn't
sure, so that's why I tagged him, too. That's why I was trying to
get him both ways. I got him. Both (ways).''
</P>
<P>
   Third base umpire Gerry Davis disagreed, calling Mora safe.
Dodgers manager Davey Johnson argued and was thrown out for the
first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a pretty good angle, and even though he tried to tag him
it looked to me like his foot was on the bag,'' Johnson said.
``That's what I had a beef with Gerry. . . . I didn't cuss him. I
said, `What in the world are you throwing me for that for?' He said
`I have a right to throw you any time I want to throw you.' I said,
`Thanks. Great call.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, many of the Dodgers thought Mora was out. Mora had
a different idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Beltre) thought I was going to hit him with my spikes,'' Mora
said. ``He tagged me late. I think he was scared.''
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't over. With the infield drawn in, Adams got Rey
Ordonez to ground to Elster, and Mora was forced at home.
Westlake's Matt Franco then grounded a pitch back to the mound, but
Adams couldn't come up with the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it glanced off his glove and behind him, which enabled
Nunnally to score the game's only run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I was too quick in trying to get my glove to
the ball, and then to home plate, but it just went off the top of
my glove,'' Adams said. ``It's play that should be made in that
situation, but I didn't make it. I didn't field my position like I
should have.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the Dodgers had chances to take the lead and failed.
Beltre grounded into a double play with runners on first and third
and one out in the second. In the fifth and sixth, the Dodgers had
runners on second with one out and didn't get a hit.
</P>
<P>
   But the best chance was in the seventh when the Dodgers had
runners on second and third and one out. New York reliever Turk
Wendell struck out Elster. Pinch-hitter Dave Hansen walked and
Devon White popped out to catcher Mike Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those days,'' Hundley said. ``These last couple of
days, it was serious tough travel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
