<HEADLINE>
KARROS IS FINALLY HEALTHY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dodgers first baseman Eric Karros was hobbled the
final days of spring training by a bruised ankle, then he missed a
few games in San Francisco with an ailing back.
</P>
<P>
   And before the road trip began, Karros had an injection into the
back of the shoulder because of an irritation. Karros says he feels
``great,'' but he'd like to be hitting better. He was 0 for 1 in
Monday's 1-0 loss to the Mets at Shea Stadium, but he was on base
three times with two walks and being hit with a pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Karros, a slow starter, is hitting .190, but he has four homers,
12 RBI and a .329 on-base percentage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I where I want to be? No, but it's strictly from an average
standpoint,'' said Karros, who didn't acknowledge the injection.
``We're 11-7 right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Karros had the inflammation at least twice in the past, and on
those occasions it was early in the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gets it from swinging,'' said Dodgers physical therapist
Pat Screnar, who also said Karros is healthy.
</P>
<P>
   __ Park's preference? Dodgers manager Davey Johnson isn't a big
fan of personal catchers for certain pitchers, but he's done it on
a few occasions, most notably in Baltimore with right-hander Scott
Erickson and catcher Lenny Webster.
</P>
<P>
   Though Johnson has tried to steer away from it, he admits
there's something to the way backup catcher Chad Kreuter and
right-hander Chan Ho Park work together. Park's had four starts
this season and Kreuter has caught three of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every since my first year as manager, I have a little (book) I
keep of who caught, so it's easy for me, when I open up that page I
can look and see,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Then he was asked if his book contained anything value about
Park and Kreuter.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some information about it. That is being
considered,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Park went to pieces last season, having mental breakdowns and
looking confused; he was 13-11 but with a 5.23 ERA. Kreuter, who
played at Pepperdine, showed his value during Park's first start
this season in Montreal. Park was wild and reeling and Kreuter
talked to him time and again to ease Park's mind.
</P>
<P>
   In the three games Kreuter has caught, Park is 2-1 with a 3.00
ERA. He's 1-0 with a 4.50 ERA in one start throwing to Todd
Hundley.
</P>
<P>
   Park is questionable for Thursday in Atlanta. He opted not to
throw a bullpen in New York, wanting to give the blister on the
middle finger of his pitching hand another day to heal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to throw a good bullpen,'' Park said. ``That's why I'm
going to wait, to make sure it's a better bullpen. I checked
(Monday) and it felt OK, but I want it to feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: Johnson talked with Jeff Williams on the
flight to New York to tell the lefty reliever he would be sent to
Triple-A Albuquerque to make room for Kevin Brown on the 25-man
roster. . . . Right-hander Gregg Olson threw in the bullpen again
and said his right forearm was ``a lot better than it was,'' but he
said a timetable for his return is not yet set. He was eligible to
come off the disabled list Monday. . . . Hundley went 4 for 40 with
four RBI last season as a right-handed hitter. Against the Mets'
Dennis Cook, Hundley got his fourth hit in 11 at-bats as a righty
this season. He went 3 for 4 in the game and is batting .302.
</P>
</TEXT>
