<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTRICITY-SUMMIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENERGY SECRETARY SAYS THAT THREAT OF BLACKOUTS IS RISING 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ Raising the specter of widespread blackouts, the
United States secretary of energy said Monday that the nation's
electric system might fare worse this summer than it did in 1999
because of a rocky transition to deregulation when demand for power
is booming.
</P>
<P>
   In meetings with government officials, corporate executives and
customer advocates here and in Hartford, Conn., the secretary, Bill
Richardson, called for new steps at the state and federal levels to
line up customers who would be willing to be unplugged on the
hottest summer days in exchange for appropriate payment, and for
identifying the backup generators that some hospitals, factories
and big companies maintain for emergencies and using them on days
when electricity demand peaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're worried as a nation, despite a hugely booming economy,
about problems in our electricity grid,'' Richardson said at a
forum at the New Jersey Institute of Technology Monday afternoon.
Richardson had a similar appearance in Hartford Monday morning and
had scheduled one in New Orleans Monday evening. He plans to hold
another, in Sacramento, on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Taking note of blackouts last summer, he said: ``Fortunately, we
were able to avoid a widespread systems failure, this time. But we
may not be so fortunate in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things may get worse before they get better. That's especially
alarming in light of the National Weather Service prediction of a
long hot summer in 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   But representatives of the region's electricity suppliers _
Consolidated Edison, Public Service Enterprise Group, General
Public Utilities _said they had made extensive investments since
last summer and would be ready for hot weather this year.
</P>
<P>
   And in Hartford, Dean Pagani, a spokesman for Gov. John G.
Rowland, said that state officials expected Connecticut's largest
power generator, the Millstone 3 nuclear plant, to be in service
this summer; last year, it was sidelined because of management
problems.
</P>
<P>
   But Rowland, who was the co-host of the session in Hartford with
Richardson, said the public should be aware that conservation would
be required on peak demand days. And in Newark, E. James Ferland,
the chairman, president and chief executive of PSE&AMP;G, said that New
Jersey could face shortages ``if there are problems in the Midwest
and we are required to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agreed with Richardson's short-term steps.
``Turning on old dirty diesel generators that are the standby
backup generators is going to be an environmental disaster,'' said
Nathaniel Greene, an electricity expert at the Natural Resources
Defense Council, an environmental group, who was one of 19
panelists at the 90-minute session here.
</P>
<P>
   The experts suggested a variety of reasons that the difference
between electric supplies and peak demand had become uncomfortably
small. One is that New England, New York and the Middle Atlantic
states are all in various stages of deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   Under the old system, the monopoly utilities generated power,
transmitted it over their own lines and sold it to their own
customers, but now some utilities have gotten out of the generating
business while dozens of other companies have gotten into it. Under
the deregulated system, electricity is bought and sold wholesale,
hour by hour or minute by minute.
</P>
<P>
   One difficulty, according to several participants, is that the
new system has not provided proper incentives to companies to build
new transmission lines. Scott Weiner, a former head of the New
Jersey Department of Environmental Protection and Energy and now a
senior vice president of Sithe Northeast, an independent power
producer, said that the deregulated system was not ``sending price
signals that allow for the construction of new capacity and shoring
up transmission systems.''
</P>
<P>
   Although New England runs low on spare capacity on peak days, he
said, some companies are taking generators out of that region and
shipping them elsewhere in the country to make larger profits.
</P>
<P>
   The session was moderated by Kurt Yeager, the president and
chief executive of the Electric Power Research Institute, a
nonprofit organization in Palo Alto, Calif., that has complained
recently that deregulation has cut investment in research and
development. In a recent report, the institute said that the
electric system was in the worst condition it had been since the
great northeast blackout of 1965.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
