<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
  
 J.D.'s BITTER SPOONFUL OF CASTRO OIL  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
(PHOENIX) - For the better part of two years it was as if the
entire state of Arizona had only one elected official _ John
McCain.
<TEXT>
<P>
   As far as the national me dia was concerned, we had only one
senator in Washing ton and no elected members of the U.S. House of
Repre sentatives.
</P>
<P>
   Here we are, living in one of the nation's fastest grow ing
states, and the major TV networks and major newspa pers ignored
every official from Arizona except one.
</P>
<P>
   As both a journalist and a longtime resident, I've qui etly
endured this long-stand ing affront. But no more.
</P>
<P>
   Developments in the Elian Gonzalez case have changed all that.
The time has come to look into the eyes of the TV executives who've
spent years snubbing Arizona's other politicians, avoiding them,
dismissing them, and say:
</P>
<P>
   Thank you.
</P>
<P>
   You'd understand why if you'd seen any of the news reports
featuring Arizona Rep. J.D. Hayworth talking about the Gonzalez
case.
</P>
<P>
   Hayworth called the re moval of Elian from the home of his Miami
relatives ``the lowest point of the Clinton presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   He called for the immedi ate resignation of Attorney General
Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   He described what hap pened in Little Havana as ``the raid on
the home of this small boy.'' As if Elian was born and raised in
Miami, rather than Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Hayworth said ``Bill Clin ton and Janet Reno went into that home
prepared to use deadly force to satisfy Fidel Castro.'' As if
Elian's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, didn't even exist.
</P>
<P>
   Hayworth described the action taken by federal agents an
``abduction.'' As if a child can be abducted from his kidnappers.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Hayworth proved why he once was voted No. 1 in
the ``No Rocket Scientist'' category in a Wash ingtonian magazine
survey of Capitol Hill staffers.
</P>
<P>
   He also proved why it is that whenever an Arizona politician
other than McCain is given the national stage, outsiders suggest we
change the name of the state capital to Hooterville.
</P>
<P>
   I asked Hayworth's office why he so easily dismisses the
father-son relationship be tween Juan Miguel and Elian and was sent
a statement from Hayworth saying in part, ``Juan Miguel will never
have custody, in the true sense of the word, of his son as long as
they remain under Castro's thumb.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayworth said he's calling on congressional leaders ``to
immediately bring up legisla tion to give Elian permanent residency
status.''
</P>
<P>
   Most responsible parents don't even let their children decide
what drink they can order with their Happy Meals. Hayworth believes
a 6-year-old is capable of de ciding whether he wants to seek
political asylum.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps Hayworth doesn't believe that, but doesn't care.
Every game played in Washington needs a political football. It
doesn't matter to some if the object getting passed and kicked
happens to be a little boy.
</P>
<P>
   The TV networks and big newspapers go right along. We can't stop
it. With McCain out of the picture, however, us folks out in Green
Acres country might suggest to big-time media types that they
bypass Rep. Hayworth for someone with slightly more humanity.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Ziffel, maybe. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach Montini at Ed.Montini &LR; ArizonaRepublic.com or (602) 444-8978. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
