<SLUG> BC-DOWNTOWN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
5 PHOENIX FIRMS AIM TO ENTICE WORKERS TO LIVE DOWNTOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY CATHERINE REAGOR  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - Workers from a handful of downtown Phoenix's biggest
employers could soon get help to buy a home close to their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 135 people will receive $5,000 in down payment and
closing cost aid through the new Downtown Phoenix Homeownership
Program.
</P>
<P>
   The housing initiative is a $675,000 venture between non-profits
and businesses. It's being unveiled by community leaders today at
Heritage Square.
</P>
<P>
   Employees from Arizona Public Service, The Arizona Republic,
Bank of America, the Downtown Phoenix Partnership's Retail Council
and Wells Fargo Bank are eligible for the housing aid.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown Phoenix has made a comeback from the sea of empty
parking lots it was after quitting time a decade ago. But the area
still lacks 24-hour residents.
</P>
<P>
   Companies are backing the housing incentives to bring more
residents to central Phoenix, cut back on traffic congestion and
pollution and entice new employees.
</P>
<P>
   Other cities have worked with mortgage company Fannie Mae to
entice buyers to blighted or downtown areas to cut traffic
congestion.
</P>
<P>
   Denver's Chamber of Commerce has a program to help its employees
buy in the city. Los Angeles firefighters and police officers are
given assistance to purchase homes in the city instead of the
suburbs. And in Maryland, at least 25 employers are helping workers
with at least $3,000 if they buy houses close to their offices.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix program is believed to be the first of its kind for
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five thousand dollars can mean the difference between becoming
a homeowner or remaining a renter,'' said Elisa de la Vara,
director of Fannie Mae's Phoenix Partnership office.
</P>
<P>
   The boundaries where people can buy and get the interest-free
loans vary by company. The biggest targeted area stretches between
Broadway and Camelback Roads and 19th Avenue and 24th Streets.
</P>
<P>
   Other downtown Phoenix firms are expected to join the effort and
offer their workers incentives to buy homes in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a seed to start a central-Phoenix housing boom,'' Jo
Marie McDonald of Phoenix Community Alliance said.
</P>
<P>
   Fannie Mae, which is the largest source of U.S. home financing,
teamed with Phoenix Community Alliance and Neighborhood Housing
Services to help Phoenix area businesses set up the
employee-housing program.
</P>
<P>
   The four companies involved have all set aside $150,000 to help
their employees buy houses, while Neighborhood Housing Services has
contributed $75,000 to start a pool for small-business workers
covered under Downtown Phoenix Partnership's Retail Council.
</P>
<P>
   APS, BofA and Wells Fargo employees interested in the program
should contact their human resources department. Employees from The
Arizona Republic and Downtown Retail Council can call Neighborhood
Housing at (602) 258-1659. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Catherine.Reagor(at)Arizona Republic.com or
(602) 444-8040. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
