<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CABLEVISION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CABLEVISION MAKES DEAL TO ADD TO ITS NEW YORK CUSTOMERS
</HEADLINE>
  By JAYSON BLAIR   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Cablevision Systems Corp. has obtained an
additional 125,500 customers in the New York metropolitan region in
a $1.1 billion deal that will make it the nation's largest local
cable provider, company officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The move takes the company out of the Boston area and is the
final step in a plan announced last year to consolidate it in and
around New York. It also puts Cablevision's focus on expanding
beyond the bounds of a traditional cable company into Internet and
other types of media, company officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, the company has begun telephone service over
cable lines to customers in parts of Long Island and in Fairfield
County, Conn.; expanded its high-speed Internet service over cable
modems and standardized its channel lineups throughout the region.
</P>
<P>
   Cablevision, which owns Madison Square Garden and Radio City
Music Hall and operates Rainbow Media MetroChannels, a set of
television channels stressing New York programming, has set its
sights on becoming a telecommunications and entertainment company
that provides service and content through several media.
</P>
<P>
   In this latest deal, the company agreed to trade its 357,000
Boston area subscribers to Media One, which is to be acquired by
AT&AMP;T as a division, for 125,500 subscribers in the northern suburbs
of New York City, the officials said. The deal calls for AT&AMP;T to
provide Cablevision with $284 million in cash and $878 million in
stock, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The AT&AMP;T deal was made final last week, company officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The transaction is consolidating the New York market,'' James
L. Dolan, president of Cablevision, said Monday. Time Warner Cable
of New York City has 1.8 million customers in Manhattan, Queens and
parts of Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Cablevision announced a deal to sell its 306,000-subscriber
cable system in the Cleveland area in December to the Adelphia
Communications Corp. for $1.53 billion in cash and stock, and
agreed to sell its 48,500-subscriber cable system in Kalamazoo,
Mich., to Carter Communications in March for $172.5 million in
stock. Cablevision officials say they hope that some of the money
from the three agreements can be applied toward the company's debt.
</P>
<P>
   The deals are all expected to be completed by the end of the
year and would give Cablevision 2.9 million customers in its
remaining regional cluster, which includes New York, New Jersey and
Connecticut.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
