<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CARVER-BANCORP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON BANK SAYS IT HAS WON BOARD SEATS AT CARVER BANCORP 
</HEADLINE>
   By LESLIE EATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Boston bank that has been waging a long-running
battle over Carver Bancorp in Harlem said late Monday that a court
decision had given it two seats on the board of Carver, a
financially troubled institution that is the largest black-run bank
in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Two executives of the Boston Bank of Commerce, a black-owned
bank that is one of Carver's largest shareholders, ran for Carver's
board at a tumultuous shareholder meeting in February; they were
defeated by a narrow margin, 30,000 of the 1.7 million votes cast.
The executives, Kevin Cohee and his wife, Teri Williams, have
challenged the election on several grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the Delaware Chancery Court issued a ruling invalidating
about 86,000 votes that were cast in favor of the incumbent
directors, David R. Jones, the bank's chairman, and David N.
Dinkins, the former mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge ruled that Teri and Kevin are on the board,'' said
Robert Patrick Cooper, general counsel of Boston Bank. ``They look
forward to sitting at the next board meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   But Carver executives believe the ruling is technical in nature
and may appeal it, said Ruth Pachman, a spokeswoman for the bank.
``It does not say they can go on the board,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A trial on the other issues raised by Boston Bank is scheduled
to begin next month in Delaware, where Carver is incorporated. The
main issue in the case is whether Carver improperly sold shares to
friendly Wall Street firms to stuff the ballot box rather than to
strengthen the bank's financial position.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's ruling is the latest twist in what has become a bitter
fight over the future of the bank, which was founded in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   The insurgents have criticized the bank's new president, Deborah
C. Wright, for her lack of banking experience; though she once
worked on Wall Street, she was more recently the president of the
Upper Manhattan Empowerment Zone, an economic development agency.
</P>
<P>
   Wright and her supporters have, in turn, criticized Boston Bank
as an interloper without the community ties that the bank needs.
They note that Cohee has proposed merging Carver with his
institution, a plan that he says he has abandoned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
