<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ELDERLY-CARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE PLUNGE IN HOME HEALTH CARE  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, April 25:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Each year, as the elderly population increases, the number of
older Americans who are in some way disabled grows. Many need help
each day but less than total care. Some have supportive families,
others do not. Some require more help than their families can give.
Few of them want to be in hospitals or nursing homes. None of us
should want them there. The high cost of institutional care
impoverishes families and strains federal and state health care
budgets, and most people prefer to age where they live, at home.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1997, in an attempt to slow the growth of Medicare costs,
Congress tightened up on payments for nursing homes and for the
medical and social services given by home health care agencies to
people who remained at home. Several of the nation's biggest
nursing home chains have since filed for bankruptcy, blaming the
changes in federal payment policy for their plight. New data just
compiled by the Congressional Budget Office show that home health
care has suffered sharp losses too.
</P>
<P>
   The figures are, in fact, alarming. Medicare spending on home
health care has dropped by 45 percent, from $17.5 billion in 1997
to $9.7 billion last year. The result in just one year, from 1997
to 1998, was that the number of people receiving home health care
shrank by 600,000, from 3.6 million to 3 million.
</P>
<P>
   As Robert Pear reported in The New York Times last Friday,
reports from across the country indicate that the most disabled are
being rejected or forced from the rolls. Home health care agencies
are spurning old people whose care may cost them more, they fear,
than they can be reimbursed. Patients are backing up in hospitals
and nursing homes, where their care is more costly, or are going
without any help at all.
</P>
<P>
   If Congress does nothing, home health care payments will be
automatically cut by an additional 15 percent next year. But the
sharp drop in home health care has caught both Republicans and
Democrats by surprise. Sen. Susan Collins, R-Maine, is leading a
bipartisan move in the Senate to cancel the planned reduction, with
support from dozens of senators of both parties. A similar effort
in under way in the House. That is only prudent. The cut should be
dropped, and serious study given to what the payment system ought
to be. Congress had reason to try to rein in ballooning Medicare
costs in 1997. But the nation's oldest and most fragile citizens
should not have to suffer for good intentions that have gone awry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-00 2316EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
