<SLUG> BC-VICTIMS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTIMS SEEK `PART IN THE SYSTEM' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY JUDI VILLA  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - No one phoned Louise Pattison when her son's killer was
released from jail; she didn't find out until she asked four days
later.
</P>
<P>
   And though she was allowed to speak during the court proceedings
that were supposed to bring the justice she sought, Pattison felt
her words had no impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have recited Mary Had a Little Lamb. That's what it
was received as,'' said Pattison, whose son, Brian Seth, 21, was
murdered in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Pattison is among a group of Arizona victims who complain that,
despite having a law on the books for 10 years protecting victims'
rights, they often feel like outsiders in a system that caters to
the rights of defendants.
</P>
<P>
   Today, April 24, as the U.S. Senate debates whether to approve a
federal Constitutional amendment, Pattison and other victims of
crime say Arizona's law has made strides but remains rife with
problems, ranging from failure to force convicts to make financial
amends to failure to inform victims about court dates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Victims overall feel that their rights pale in comparison to
the defendants,'' said Dan Levey, a victims advocate for the state
Attorney General's Office. ``They want to have a part in the
system, but that's hard when you're an afterthought.''
</P>
<P>
   In Pattison's words: ``It's hard to say; who did we matter to?''
</P>
<P>
   The federal amendment, sponsored by Sen. Jon Kyl, R-Ariz., would
amend the Constitution to put victims' rights on equal footing with
the rights of criminal defendants.
</P>
<P>
   It would guarantee such things as the right to be present at
court hearings, the right to speak at sentencing and to have a say
in plea agreements, the right to a speedy resolution of the case
and the right to repayment for losses. It would also force the
courts to weigh the safety of the victim when considering any
release order.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put them (victims) into the fundamental law, and they become
of the same importance as other values of our criminal justice
system, such as the rights of defendants,'' said Steve Twist, a
local victims advocate. ``The balance will be fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona is one of 32 states that currently have some form of
victims' rights, but still, victims say, the promises often ring
hollow.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 75 percent of offenders pay off all the restitution
they are ordered to pay before they're released from probation or
parole, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   And judges tend to be more protective of a defendant's rights,
guaranteed by the Constitution, than they are of a victim's rights,
protected only by the state. They admonish victims that they might
be asked to leave the courtroom if they cry, stare at the
defendant, walk out too often and even cough too loudly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy, it's a whole different world in there,'' said Sue Osolin,
whose son, Ryan, was shot three times in the back of the head and
killed in 1997. ``It's hell in there, but not so bad when you think
of other states where people can't even be in the courtroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys watched Osolin's reactions when they showed
graphic photos and once asked for a mistrial after she bowed her
head and a victims advocate blew her nose, Osolin said. Osolin, who
is nearsighted, learned to take off her glasses when the pictures
came out.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not getting me out of the courtroom,'' she said. ``I
have a right to be here, and God forbid I shed a few tears.''
</P>
<P>
   Levey, whose brother Howard was murdered in 1996, says that, if
nothing else, talk of the federal amendment will raise awareness of
victims' rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal amendment is one way we can scream out to the
country and say victims are important too,'' Levey said. ``The main
thing we're looking for is equity. Being equal and having a part in
the criminal justice system rather than being on the periphery
looking in.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Judi.Villa(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or (602)
444-8048. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
