<HEADER>
A6387 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKNOT-LADN-(SLAN     04-24 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKNOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAQ HAS STERN WARNING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ So Rick Adelman wants to make an issue over
non-foul calls with regard to Shaquille O'Neal. Apparently, the
Sacramento Kings coach does so at his own peril.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fine. He can be an idiot,'' O'Neal said of Adelman's
complaints, which came in the wake of the Lakers' victory over the
Kings in Sunday's first-round playoff opener. ``What Rick Adelman
doesn't want to do is wake me up. (By) crying and whining, he'll
wake me up.''
</P>
<P>
   So, 46 points, 17 rebounds and five blocked shots isn't woken
up?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' O'Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   While O'Neal _ who made just five trips to the foul line _
contends officials miss numerous defensive fouls committed against
him, Adelman contends it is O'Neal who got away with the bullying
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt that Shaquille O'Neal is a great player,''
Adelman said, ``but they do not officiate the game the same for him
with all his strength as they do for everybody else. . . . I just
think we need to find something else (defensively), because they
are not going to call anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Responded O'Neal: ``My game is a game of tai-chi, I'm good
enough to go around people. I don't have to go through them. I've
never had to go through (Kings center) Vlade Divac. Period.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Kings have nothing to complain about?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers coach Phil Jackson had his own postscript on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might talk about the officiating a little bit myself, if I'm
prodded long enough,'' Jackson said. ``I mean, really, (the Kings)
shot 35 foul shots to our (14)? They had 20 more foul shots in the
game. That's a disparity you usually don't see at home. But you
know . . . that's the way the game went, and it looked to me early
like they weren't going to give any simple, cheap fouls to Shaq. .
. .
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it boils down to refereeing as much as it just
boiled down to who wanted the game more and who played with more
intensity.''
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant figured the Kings' ire could work in the Lakers'
favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're thinking more about the officials than they're
thinking about playing us,'' he said, ``I think sure, that can work
to our advantage, because to some extent they're losing focus. But
I think come game time on Thursday, they're not going to be
thinking about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Criticism of officials was all the rage in the Kings locker room
after Game 1. Chris Webber fumed over the pair of offensive fouls
called against him while jostling with Robert Horry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The refs read the papers, just like normal people,'' Horry
said, ``A lot of times, it's just talk to try to get the refs to
(call the game differently).''
</P>
<P>
   __ Waiting, the hardest part: Having handled the Kings Sunday,
the Lakers are eager for more, but they'll have to wait until
Thursday to try to make it a 2-0 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big bummer,'' Horry said. ``To take this many days off,
the competition level drops in practice, and you'll be so anxious
to get out there and play the game, it kind of hurts you at times.
</P>
<P>
   ``But hopefully, the only thing this will do is make us better,
because there's still a lot of stuff that coach is throwing in to
make us a better team, and we're still learning.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal called the delay ``very strange.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good, especially for me, a guy that takes a pounding,''
he said. ``I'm going to chill out today. Then (Tuesday), I'm going
to get a massage, a little steamy-steam-steam, mineral bath-bath.
Wednesday, put my face back on, then Thursday be ready to play. So
it's good for me.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Payday for Shaq: O'Neal had little to say about a New York
Times report that indicated he will sign a contract extension this
offseason. O'Neal, whose contract expires in 2003, is eligible for
a three-year extension worth $83.5 million, starting at $24.75
million in 2003-04.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't been discussed,'' O'Neal said. ``I haven't even
thought about it. You know, it really doesn't matter to me. I make
good money, the organization takes care of me. We'll see.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
