<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALTERNATIVE-SIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Interactions between drugs and alternative remedies
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Medicine and pharmaceutical science have a good understanding of
which drugs interact with each other and which foods interfere with
the actions of drugs. But the question of interactions between
pharmaceuticals and natural remedies _ herbs, minerals and high
doses of vitamins _ is a new one for researchers. Here's a sampling
of what's known so far:
</P>
<P>
   If you take:
</P>
<P>
   St. John's wort for depression.
</P>
<P>
   And also take:
</P>
<P>
   Protease inhibitors to fight HIV.
</P>
<P>
   The interaction could:
</P>
<P>
   Increase metabolism of drugs in liver; make levels of drugs in
blood lower than intended; speed development of the virus'
resistance to drugs.
</P>
<P>
   If you take:
</P>
<P>
   Licorice to reduce inflammation, soothe digestion and regulate
hormones.
</P>
<P>
   And also take:
</P>
<P>
   Nifedipine, enalapril or prazosin to regulate blood pressure and
heart arrhythmia and prevent heart failure.
</P>
<P>
   The interaction could:
</P>
<P>
   Cause the body to retain sodium, increasing blood pressure and
canceling out the drug's intended effects.
</P>
<P>
   If you take:
</P>
<P>
   Valerian for insomnia.
</P>
<P>
   And also take:
</P>
<P>
   Diphenhydramine or other antihistamines sold as over-the-counter
allergy drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The interaction could:
</P>
<P>
   Increase the drug's potential for causing drowsiness.
</P>
<P>
   If you take:
</P>
<P>
   Feverfew for migraines.
</P>
<P>
   And also take:
</P>
<P>
   Warfarin or heparin
</P>
<P>
   as blood thinners.
</P>
<P>
   The interaction could:
</P>
<P>
   Reduce the ability of platelets in the blood to clot; a double
dose of anticoagulants from the drug and herb may cause internal
bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   If you take:
</P>
<P>
   Kava to reduce anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   And also take:
</P>
<P>
   Levodopa or carbidopa to treat Parkinson's disease.
</P>
<P>
   The interaction could:
</P>
<P>
   Drug restores levels of a brain chemical; herb interferes with
the same chemical. The combination could worsen symptoms of
Parkinson's.
</P>
<P>
   If you take:
</P>
<P>
   Milk thistle as a
</P>
<P>
   general detoxification aid or to improve liver function.
</P>
<P>
   And also take:
</P>
<P>
   Oral contraceptives to prevent pregnancy or regulate the
menstrual cycle.
</P>
<P>
   The interaction could:
</P>
<P>
   Disable the action of a particular enzyme; may reduce absorption
and effectiveness of pills.
</P>
<P>
   If you take:
</P>
<P>
   Cascara sagrada
</P>
<P>
   as a laxative.
</P>
<P>
   And also take:
</P>
<P>
   Thiazide diuretics to reduce high blood pressure by helping the
body eliminate salts and water.
</P>
<P>
   The interaction could:
</P>
<P>
   Cause the body to excrete potassium; potassium deficiency
impairs heart function.
</P>
<P>
   Compiled by M.A.J. McKenna / Images courtesy of American
Botanical Council
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
