<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZEDILLO-BUSH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH, ZEDILLO CHRISTEN NEW BORDER BRIDGE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NUEVO LAREDO, Mexico _ With about 3,000 Mexicans cheering them
on, Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo
formally opened a new trucks-only bridge across the Rio Grande on
Monday and proclaimed it a new symbol of globalized commerce and
bilateral friendship.
</P>
<P>
   The new World Trade Bridge is located several miles outside of
town and is expected to alleviate some of the traffic snarls
produced by the North American Free Trade Agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, one more barrier has fallen. One more divide has been
bridged,'' Bush told the crowd of Mexican dignitaries, laborers and
students who assembled under the shade of a giant new customs
station, where goods from the United States are inspected before
being trucked into Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will work to extend the benefits of NAFTA from northernmost
Alaska to the tip of Cape Horn. I will call upon the United States
Congress to give me fast track negotiating authority to
aggressively recruit new trade agreements in our hemisphere,'' Bush
said in an oblique reference to his GOP presidential aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton sought congressional renewal of fast-track
authority two years ago, but withdrew the request when it became
apparent that labor-backed legislators in his own Democratic Party
might help defeat it.
</P>
<P>
   ``As president, I will look south not as an afterthought but as
a fundamental commitment of my presidency,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who takes credit for fostering friendly relations with
Mexico as governor, said the current mood of economic cooperation
wasn't always a given.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, there have been walls and divides between Mexico
and the U.S. We must be committed to raise the bridges of trade and
friendship and freedom,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that half of the $200 billion annual trade between the
two countries passes through Texas, Bush said ``this partnership
may seem inevitable, but it hasn't always been so.'' He said the
neighbor nations are only now emerging from an era of ``distrust,
division ... divided by our history, our culture and our
economics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We now understand our nations share more than a border. We
have common interests,'' Bush said, adding that the two nations
have been building mutual trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we're celebrating today _ not just a bridge of
concrete and steel but a lasting alliance of common hope and
friendship,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo praised Bush for ``understanding our culture'' and
helping improve bilateral relations. The Mexican president, who
leaves office later this year, said the fact that he has christened
six bridges in six years speaks to the improved cooperation.
Zedillo also hailed President Clinton for being a ``great friend''
of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-lane bridge cost $128 million, of which Mexico pitched
in $33 million, mainly from a consortium of private Mexican
investors. Under Mexican law, the bridge can only be used by trucks
and commercial vehicles _ a rule that played havoc with Bush's
travel planners.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Mexican federal authorities refused a Bush campaign
request for Bush's motorcade to use the bridge to enter Mexico for
the dedication. But the federal officials relented Sunday when
Bush's gubernatorial staff made the same request.
</P>
<P>
   The span, which opened April 15, is the fourth to connect the
two Laredos. The first three were clogged from an estimated 1.3
million vehicle crossings a year _ 38 percent of all ground-based
trade between the United States and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   To divert international commercial traffic away from the cities'
connecting downtowns, the Colombia Solidarity &UR;  &LR; bridge was opened 17
miles northwest of Laredo two years ago. It crosses the border
where a small sliver of the Mexican state of Nuevo Leon abuts the
Rio Grande.
</P>
<P>
   But with more and more traffic being generated by the North
American Free Trade Agreement, the fourth bridge _ this one within
Nuevo Laredo's state of Tamualipas _ had been sought for several
years. Since the fourth bridge's recent opening, Laredo's total
truck crossings have quickly increased by 50 percent, hitting a
local record 8,000 crossings on one day last week.
</P>
<P>
   Also on hand for the ceremonies Monday were Tamaulipas Gov.
Tomas Yarrington and U.S. Ambassador Jeffrey Davidow. Bush's
entourage included Texas Secretary of State Elton Bomer and
Railroad Commissioner Tony Garza.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Bush travels to Ohio in the company of four Texas
Democrats _ two current and two former members of the state
Legislature. Aides said Bush and the Democrats, who will visit
Washington, D.C., later in the week, will call for a new bipartisan
tone in the nation's capital, like the one Bush claims to have
established in his home state.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Karen Hughes said among those tentatively set to
make the trip are House Appropriations Chairman Rob Junell, D-San
Angelo; Senate Criminal Justice Committee Chairman Ken Armbrister,
D-Victoria; and former Reps. Mark Stiles, D-Beaumont and Hugo
Berlanga, D-Corpus Christi.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said the Democrats would be on hand to challenge
``unfair'' claims of the Gore campaign that Texas ranks low in
health care, education and other key services. Junell, one of the
state's most influential Democrats and chief overseer of state
spending, endorsed Bush's re-election bid in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
 &QL; 
$$$
</P>
