<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-24 23:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6390 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-CLINTONS-ART-535     04-24 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CLINTONS-ART-535&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE FOURSOME SWITCHES FAMILIAR ROLES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bill Clinton may be president, and Al Gore may be
vice president, but, as Tony Bennett put it, ``the best is yet to
come.''
</P>
<P>
   The song seemed tailor-made for Monday night's fund-raising gala
in midtown Manhattan with political ambition unbound, both for
Gore, who wants to be president, and Hillary Clinton, who aspires
to move on from first ladyship to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Bill and Al and Hillary and Tipper revived their foursome for
the night, chatting and schmoozing with contributors to raise money
for the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   They raised $2.2 million from more than 1,000 people who
attended the mammoth fund-raiser at the Sheraton Towers. This was
less than the $2.8 million that the president and vice president
raised from about 100 contributors two weeks ago in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Tipper Gore introduced Hillary and Hillary introduced Bill and
Bill introduced Al. It was one of the first role reversals of its
kind, where the vice president was given top billing and presented
as the ranking guest of honor and gave the longest speech.
</P>
<P>
   In his tribute to the vice president, Bill Clinton said, ``I
feel absolutely comfortable putting the future of my daughter and
the grandchildren I hope she'll give us in his hands.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee set up two reception rooms at the hotel, one with
Clinton and one with Gore, and guests who had given or raised
$25,000 each shuttled between them before sitting down to a dinner
of filet mignon.
</P>
<P>
   Guests included the actress Lauren Bacall; Jean Kennedy Smith,
sister of President Kennedy; Arthur Schlesinger Jr., the author and
Kennedy confidant; Sam Waterston, the actor; Harvey Weinstein,
co-chairman of the Miramax unit of Walt Disney Co.; Lawrence
Rockefeller, a Republican and New York environmental lawyer; Steve
Rattner, the financier; Martha Stewart, the doyenne of home and
hearth; and Michael Coles, the unsuccessful candidate for the
Senate from Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Also on hand was Rep. Jerrold Nadler, D-N.Y., who was one of the
few establishment politicians to support Gore's primary rival,
former Sen. Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   He was joined by several other New York politicians, including
Carl McCall, the state controller; Rep. Anthony Weiner of Brooklyn;
and Eliot Spitzer, the state attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   The event also drew other long-time major party donors,
including Orin Kramer of New Jersey and Jonathan Tisch, the chief
executive of Loews Corp.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of Clinton and Gore, the party raised $26 million
in the first quarter of this year toward its goal for the year of
$100 million.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Stewart, the comedian, was the master of ceremonies and
began the evening with a few Elian-related comments, saying he
could not ignore the news of federal agents snatching the
6-year-old Cuban boy in a pre-dawn raid. He said Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, Hillary Clinton's opponent in the Senate race, had
complained about ``the use of nonexcessive force'' in the taking of
the boy early Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart also joked that the federal government had no choice but
to conduct the armed raid. ``Any Jewish person will tell you the
terror that they feel when they hear the phrase `Miami
relatives,''' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Seated with Hillary Clinton at dinner was Bernard L. Schwartz,
chairman of Loral Space and Communications Corp., a major
Democratic donor and friend of the Clintons. Loral is the subject
of a Justice Department investigation into whether it violated
export law by giving sophisticated satellite technology to China.
</P>
<P>
   The event caused considerable traffic gridlock across New York.
The Clintons arrived together on Air Force One after their weekend
at Camp David, but left in separate motorcades. Al Gore arrived
later on Air Force Two and Tipper Gore arrived separately. The
foursome posed such a need for heightened security that the
director of the Secret Service traveled with the Clintons on Air
Force One.
</P>
<P>
   The Gores spent the afternoon at the home of their daughter,
Karenna, who arrived late for Monday night's event because, as the
vice president explained it, she had to attend a class at law
school. Her husband, Dr. Drew Schiff, also attended.
</P>
